<HEADLINE>
MAMIIT STAYS HOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For ue by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ Whn Steve Starleaf came up with the idea of
building the Burbank Tennis Center about a decade ago, he
envisioned a venue to showcase local players.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the final day of the second Challenger Series event
there, the center's director and others in the tennis community
found gratification.
</P>
<P>
   Cecil Mamiit, a product of Eagle Rock and USC, beat No. 9-seeded
David Nainkin of South Africa 7-6 (7-5), 7-5 to win the singles
title while the Bryan twins of Camarillo, Bob and Mike, defeated
the Nos. 1- and 2-seeded teams to win the doubles championship
before a crowd of 300 that amounted to a hometown advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Mamiit is the hottest player on the Challenger circuit.
</P>
<P>
   He has made three consecutive finals, winning two. He won on
Sunday even though he had to work overtime: He beat Ville Liukko in
a tough, two-hour semifinal match 7-6 (7-3), 6-3 two hours before
his finals match because rain washed out play Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It had little effect against Nainkin, a six-year tour veteran
who played at UCLA for parts of two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Mamiit, who is generously listed at 5-foot-8, stuck to his
baseline game. He simply traded deep shots, waited for Nainkin to
make mistakes and chased down many of his opponent's best shots, a
style akin to Michael Chang's.
</P>
<P>
   It worked, although he seemed to be in trouble midway through
the first set and late in the second.
</P>
<P>
   He was leading 4-1 when he lost 17 of 22 points as Nainkin took
a 5-4 lead. He looked tired. However, Mamiit, who relies heavily on
his grit, seemed to steal the momentum on sheer determination to
pull out the set.
</P>
<P>
   Then, down 5-4 in the second set and Nainkin serving, he won 12
of the final 13 points _ including two aces _ to win his third
Challenger tournament before dozens of boisterous friends and
family members.
</P>
<P>
   Nainkin attributed the loss in good part to Mamiit's ballooning
confidence and lack of mistakes. And the fans didn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd gave me so much energy,'' Mamitt said. ``I don't
usually get that on the tour in all these different places. It felt
so warm, like a college match. It made me so relaxed, so cool and
calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was huge for me.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't long ago that Mamiit wondered whether he did the right
thing turning pro after winning the NCAA singles in title in 1996.
Now, none of the doubts linger.
</P>
<P>
   He entered the tournament at No. 151 in the world. After Sunday,
he expects to jump about 20 places _ to his highest position _ with
one more tournament to go, in Guadalajara, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Next year? He has dreams of cracking the top 50.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, my short-term goal is top 80. But I'm loose, I'm
confident, I have such a good feel for the game right now. We'll
see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bryans, who also had a large number of supporters here, did
most of their work in the early match: They also played their
semifinal earlier in the day, beating No. 1 Brandon Coupe and Jared
Palmer 7-6 (7-4), 3-6, 7-6 (10-8).
</P>
<P>
   In the final, No. 2 David DiLucia and Michael Sell, veterans who
have played together often, apparently were caught cold in the
dipping temperatures around 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   They warmed up in the second set but couldn't overcome the
rapidly rising 20-year-old rookies, losing 6-0, 7-6 (7-5). It was
the Bryans' second title in five Challenger tournaments as a
doubles team.
</P>
<P>
   And it was a splendid day for local tennis. The Bryans had the
only complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Said Bob Bryan, with a smile: ``I think Cecil had more fans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
