<HEADLINE>
BELANGER BRUINS' HARDEST SHOOTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Everyone knew he could fight. Everyone knew he could
hit. But who knew that forward Ken Belanger could fire a slap shot
more than 100 miles per hour? No one, including Belanger.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' big left wing unseated defenseman Hal Gill during
the annual Skills Competition at the FleetCenter Sunday, blasting
the puck 100.4 m.p.h. Gill won the event last year with 95.4 m.p.h.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the turning point,'' joked Belanger, who was
competing in his first such event. ``I scored on the breakaway
(relay) and won the hardest shot. I was curious what it was. I
never really had it clocked before.''
</P>
<P>
   For a few minutes, it didn't appear as if anyone would know just
how hard he could shoot the puck. His first two shots didn't
register on the radar gun. The first one that did was clocked at
95.4 m.p.h., which bested Joe Thornton's 94.5. Belanger's next one
proved to be the winner. Belanger believes he can do better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can get a little higher with a few more shots,'' he
said. ``It's all about practice. It's like the longest drive in
golf. You have to keep it low and at the middle of the net so the
radar can read it directly.''
</P>
<P>
   Belanger has been with the Bruins since Nov. 7, when he was
acquired from the Islanders for Ted Donato. He then missed two
games as a result of being struck in the face by a puck at
practice. He has played in the last five games and said he feels a
part of things now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a young group of guys, so everyone blends in well,'' he
said. ``Three weeks ago I didn't know anybody, but now I get along
with everybody here.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you first walk in, you get a little bit of an
uncomfortable feeling but it's such a good group of guys and they
make you feel really welcome. It hasn't been a big adjustment. It
was a big move, but they made it really comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Another first-time participant in the competition was forward
Shawn Bates, who has been a healthy scratch the last four games.
</P>
<P>
   Bates edged Sergei Samsonov, last year's winner, for the title
of fastest skater.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun to be out there in front of the home crowd,'' said
Bates, who played at Boston University. ``I was pretty happy with
it. My biggest strength is my skating. I have to give credit to
(conditioning coach) Mike Boyle, who helped me during my college
career and since I've been with the Bruins. You just have to go out
there and give it all you have. I only beat (Samsonov) by two-10ths
of a second.''
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that with injured forward Peter Ferraro out of the
lineup, Bates could get the nod for Tuesday's game against the
Vancouver Canucks at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been practicing with the team for a couple of weeks now
and I'm learning a lot,'' he said. ``Obviously I'd like to play,
but I like where I am right now and all I can do is work hard every
day and maybe I can get another shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Taylor won for the most accurate shooting and Rob Tallas won
the goaltending competition.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro attended the event but his left arm was in a sling to
immobilize the injured muscles in his chest. Ferraro said he
expects to be sidelined for at least a week as a result of a
crushing hit from Montreal defenseman Vladimir Malakhov in the
first period of Friday's matinee against the Canadiens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like I'm going to be out at least a week or two,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I popped my chest out of place and then it popped back
into place, which is good. I knew he was coming really hard and
fast. It was a situation where I got the puck at my blue line, I
saw him coming out of the corner of my eye. I had to get to the red
line in order to dump the puck in. He's a big guy so I knew I was
going to take a pretty good hit, which I did. I just hoped it would
be a better outcome. Unfortunately, it wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro was happy the Bruins won the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found out about it at the hospital, which made it easier to
deal with at the time,'' he said. ``It was a clean hit and it's
just part of the game. It's very disappointing. I'm just going to
try to get back as quick as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Left wing P.J. Axelsson was the only other Bruin who didn't
participate. He is suffering from the flu.
</P>
</TEXT>
