<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE POINTED WAY FOR UMASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE CHARLES, La. _ All season long, the offense has been the
focal point. Quarterback Todd Bankhead, wide receiver Jimmy Moore,
and running back Marcel Shipp have helped rewrite the University of
Massachusetts record book this season in leading the 9-3 Minutemen
to one of the nation's best turnarounds.
</P>
<P>
   They're members of the unit that finished the season ranked
third in the nation in total offense. So impressive were the
efforts of the offense that the defense went virtually unheralded;
even when it shined and the offense struggled, people focused on
the latter unit's woes.
</P>
<P>
   But that may have changed following the Minutemen's 21-19
victory over McNeese State Saturday in the first round of the
Division 1-AA playoffs. When the offense stalled in the second half
after creating a 21-3 halftime lead, the defense withstood several
McNeese State rallies, limiting the Cowboys to one touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   All other times, McNeese State either gave up the ball, lost it
on a turnover, or settled for a field goal attempt. It converted on
four, but missed a 52-yard try with 1:42 left, securing the first
postseason victory for the Minutemen in 10 years. Saturday UMass
hosts unbeaten Lehigh, a 24-23 winner over Richmond, in the second
round.
</P>
<P>
   The other local team in the playoffs, UConn, showed off its
offense Saturday, as senior quarterback Shane Stafford scorched
Hampton's secondary for 294 yards and four touchdowns in a 42-34
victory at Storrs, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Next for the Huskies (10-2) is a trip to Statesboro, Ga., to
face No. 1 seed Georgia Southern (12-0), which defeated Colgate,
49-28.
</P>
<P>
   If UMass wins Saturday, it faces the Appalachian
State-Northwestern State winner; if UConn prevails, it faces the
Florida A&AMP;M-Western Illinois winner. UMass and UConn would not meet
until the championship game.
</P>
<P>
   It was the McNeese State defense that entered the game against
UMass with impressive credentials. The Cowboys unit was third in
Division 1-AA, yielding only 83 yards rushing a game.
</P>
<P>
   But it was upstaged by a UMass unit that held its opposition to
one touchdown for the second consecutive week. The defense's effort
was so exceptional that by the fourth quarter it was evident the
Minutemen had not missed Shipp, who sat out the game with a knee
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked to the defense before the game and we told them they
were going to have to step it up because Marcel wasn't able to
play,'' said UMass coach Mark Whipple.
</P>
<P>
   All season, several players have excelled for the defense,
particularly linebacker Khari Samuel, who led the Minutemen
Saturday with 11 tackles (10 unassisted) and one pass breakup.
Linebacker Kole Ayi had seven tackles, a fumble recovery, and three
pass breakups. Strong safety Brian Smith had 10 tackles and two
pass breakups.
</P>
<P>
   ``These last couple of weeks we've been preaching to each other
to just step it up, and every time we go out on the field play the
best game we can,'' said Samuel. ``When each player sits down and
says he's going to play their best game, or at least try to, we
have good results.''
</P>
<P>
   But as a unit, their efforts have gone unnoticed because UMass
games this season have been point-pouring affairs, with the
Minutemen usually outgunning the opposition for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   But the unit began raising eyebrows Nov. 7 against Rhode Island.
The defense held off the scrappy Rams as the offense struggled,
then secured the victory when Samuel returned an interception for a
touchdown late.
</P>
<P>
   The defense's effort in the regular-season finale against UConn
was arguably its best to that point. It held one of the most potent
Division 1-AA offenses scoreless until the fourth quarter. But the
offense's seven turnovers and the special team's blunders made it a
mere afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore. McNeese State, which returned most of its players
from last year's Division 1-AA runner-up, drove within the UMass 35
four of the five times it had possession in the fourth quarter.
Trailing by 15 points entering the quarter, McNeese State came up
with 13 (two field goals and a touchdown), but it wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   When UMass hosts Lehigh, it will mark the second time the teams
have met in postseason; Lehigh beat UMass, 30-23, in Amherst in the
1977 Division 2 playoffs. Tickets for the game go on sale this
morning at 8:30 at the UMass Athletic Ticket Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense has gained a lot of confidence over the last half
of the season,'' said Whipple.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just came up big. We tried to stay under control and let
our defense win the game, and they were the ones who came up big in
the second half. They played super in our red zone defense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
