<HEADLINE>
ORANGE PERFORM WITH SQUEEZE ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ Give credit to Syracuse. With everything at stake _
primarily a $12 million Bowl Championship Series spot _ the
Orangemen played the way their fans hoped they would all season by
blowing away a good Miami team, 66-13, Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The enigma of Syracuse is that it was good enough to come within
one play of beating Tennessee, but bad enough to lose to North
Carolina State.
</P>
<P>
   That inconsistency is why the Orangemen are 8-3 and heading for
a slot in the Orange or Sugar bowls (most likely the Orange against
Florida State or Ohio State) instead of 11-0 or 10-1 and contending
for a national championship slot in the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In this season, in which no superteam exists, the Orangemen have
proven they are as good as anyone on any given week. And they have
become the power in the Big East, winning or sharing the conference
title the past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Donovan McNabb is arguably the best player in the
country and should have been a real Heisman Trophy contender _
maybe he still is, but it's probably too late _ but he picked a
nationally televised Thursday night game against North Carolina
State to have his worst game, and the voters and media turned him
off.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's effort ``was one of those games we hit on all eight
cylinders,'' said Orangemen coach Paul Pasqualoni, who has turned
even grayer when his team has squandered opportunities as it has
the past three years. ``You can never go into a game like this and
imagine it would turn out this way.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's the perplexing part. With Syracuse you can't. When
the Orangemen are good, they are very good. When they are bad ...
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Notre Dame's 10-0 loss to Southern California Saturday,
pencil the Irish into the Gator Bowl against Georgia Tech. The
Irish obviously missed quarterback  &UR; Jarious Jackson &LR; . Freshman
 &UR; Arnaz Battle &LR; , &UR;  &LR; thrown into the lurch after Jackson suffered a
knee injury on the final play of last week's win over LSU while
taking a safety, did not complete a pass until the third quarter.
The Irish had almost as many turnovers (5) as completions (7) ...
Tennessee's 11-0 record is the best regular-season mark in school
history and its first perfect regular season since 1956. Throw out
some of those losses to Florida the past few years and the Vols
have been pretty much invincible, posting a 48-5 mark in their last
53 games ... Vanderbilt may have finished with a dismal 2-9 record,
but the Commodores can point to their grades. Thirty-seven players
on the roster had a 3.0 average or better during the spring
semester ... There still might be some doubt about who deserves the
Heisman. You can argue that players like Tulane's  &UR; Shawn
King &LR; , &UR;  &LR; Kansas State's  &UR; Michael Bishop &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and McNabb are more
valuable to their teams, and that someone like Kentucky's  &UR; Tim
Couch  &LR; had overwhelming numbers, but so did Texas running back
 &UR; Ricky Williams &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who will win the award in New York in two weeks.
He also is the all-time NCAA collegiate rushing leader, breaking
 &UR; Tony Dorsett's  &LR; record with an eye-popping 259 yards in the
Longhorns' win over Texas A&AMP;M Friday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M can make the BCS muddle clearer if it upsets Kansas
State in the Big 12 championship game in St. Louis Saturday.
Neither Tennessee, which faces Mississippi State in the
Southeastern Conference title game in Atlanta Saturday, nor UCLA,
which plays at Miami Saturday in a makeup game, figures to have as
tough a time as Kansas State ... Poor Arizona. The Wildcats ended a
remarkable 10-1 season (losing only to UCLA) with a 50-42 win over
Arizona State Friday night and the Wildcats still have to wait
until after the UCLA-Miami game to find out if they are going to
the Rose Bowl for the first time. A UCLA loss or a shift in the BCS
standings likely will put the Bruins in the Rose against Wisconsin
and send Arizona to the Holiday Bowl against Nebraska ... Speaking
of remarkable seasons, how about Tulane's? The Green Wave are 11-0
after beating up Louisiana Tech and are going to the Liberty Bowl
to face BYU in what could be one of the most entertaining bowl
games. It could also be coach  &UR; Tommy Bowden's  &LR; last game before
taking a more high-profile job at somewhere like Mississippi,
Oklahoma, or Clemson ... If Boston College can be proud of anything
this season, it is its opening-game win over Georgia Tech. The
Yellow Jackets turned out to be one of the best teams in the
country, as their victory over Georgia Saturday proved. It was
Tech's first win over Georgia since 1990, including losses the last
three years by a combined 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cotton Bowl people must be doing handstands. They are going
to get an Arkansas-Texas rematch of the old Southwest Conference
days, with both teams coming off impressive wins in their last
games, and they'll have the Heisman winner as well ... LSU, the
preseason pick to finish first in the SEC West, finished 4-7, the
first losing season for coach  &UR; Gerry DiNardo  &LR; in four years ... How
important was Nebraska's 16-14 win over Colorado Friday? Oh, it
just prevented the Huskers from having their first four-loss season
since 1968, and marked the 30th consecutive year they have won at
least nine games in a season ... Hawaii made history Saturday
night. The Rainbows' 48-17 loss to Michigan gave them an 0-12 mark,
matching Colorado State in 1981 as the worst record for a season in
college football history ... The UMass and UConn victories in the
Division 1-AA playoffs mean the Minutemen's  &UR; Mark Whipple  &LR; and the
Huskies'  &UR; Skip Holtz  &LR; will move to the forefront of the young
coaches who will be called upon by Division 1-A teams in search of
a makeover. Hello Oklahoma, Iowa, South Carolina, and Clemson, are
you listening?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
