<HEADLINE>
STEELE SHINES IN BC VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Boston College senior center Whitney Steele suffered
through a scoreless first half that included a seat on the bench
when she picked up her third foul against St. Joseph's Sunday at
Conte Forum.
</P>
<P>
   But when the game was on the line, Steele, with a big assist
from freshman guard Nicole Conway, made sure the Eagles' winning
streak remained intact.
</P>
<P>
   The pair combined for 11 points, 6 by Conway, during a 14-8 run
in the final six minutes that broke a 56-all tie and keyed a 72-68
victory that improved the Eagles record to 6-0, the best start in
school history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very frustrating to be on the bench in foul trouble,''
said Steele, who entered the game as her team's leading scorer
(18.2) and rebounder (8.4). ``Especially since two of the calls
were offensive fouls, because I was just trying to be aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Joseph's (1-3) gave BC all it could handle, hitting on 9 of
22 3-pointers, including three by center Jana Lichnerova (19
points) and four by guard Melissa Coursey (12 points). Freshman
forward Susan Moran also gave the Eagles fits with her penetration,
which resulted in 15 trips to the free throw line, where she
converted a dozen times.
</P>
<P>
   Moran made six consecutive freebies during an 8-0 run that gave
the visitors a 56-55 lead with 7:45 to play. A Cal Bouchard free
throw tied it, and Steele finally broke the ice with a banker that
put her team ahead for good.
</P>
<P>
   That hoop was followed by an Alissa Murphy (16 points) free
throw, two foul shots by Conway after an offensive rebound, another
free throw by Steele, and a Conway layup for a 64-56 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But even with Moran (18 points) on the bench after fouling out,
St. Joe's made one last rush. An Angela Zampella 3-pointer closed
it to 64-61, then a Zampella steal and drive to the basket had the
crowd of 458 holding its collective breath. But the Hawks forward
was called for charging into defender Paula Bacso and Steele
followed with a driving layup for a 68-64 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Two St. Joe's turnovers later, a pair of Murphy free throws iced
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had to be patient,'' said Steele, who reentered the
game with 12:23 to play and still wound up with as many rebounds
(five) as Lichnerova.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even think about a win until we had a 4-point lead
with a second to play,'' said Conway. ``In a close game like this,
I just tried to keep my composure.''
</P>
<P>
   BC coach Cathy Inglese said the loss of Steele was softened by a
balanced offense and hard work under the boards. Cocaptain Bouchard
and freshman backcourt mate Brianne Stepherson chipped in with 13
points each, Bacso had 10, while freshman Becky Gottstein had 7
points and a game-best 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the first team that we've played in a long time that
looked more to slow it down and play a quarter-court game,'' said
Inglese, whose team never trailed or led by more than 8 points.
``We talked about that and about hitting the boards and we
responded.''
</P>
<P>
   BC, which outrebounded the Hawks, 41-30, thus ended a
four-games-in-eight-days stretch. The Eagles open their Big East
schedule Saturday at Miami, the first of four road games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
