<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-HARVARD-MISSISSIPPISTATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIMSON FALL SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Mississippi State women's basketball team proved
quicker than Harvard in Sunday's Harvard Invitational final, but
the Crimson went to a 2-3 matchup zone to try to counter that.
</P>
<P>
   There was just one problem _ not enough of Harvard's shots went
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one thought we would play this well,'' said Harvard coach
Kathy Delaney-Smith. ``Everybody I talked to was sort of laughing
at the matchup. I'm very proud, we could have won this game, but
our shots didn't fall.''
</P>
<P>
   The Crimson connected on just 35 percent of their field goals
(19 of 54), while the Lady Bulldogs (4-0) made 44 percent of their
shots (12 of 27) in the second half on their way to a 64-51 win at
Lavietes Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in its 14th Harvard Invitational final in the 18 seasons
the event has been held, Harvard (2-3) couldn't get closer than 7,
that 46-39 margin coming with four minutes remaining on a Sarah
Russell putback.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was close enough for me,'' said Mississippi State coach
Sharon Fanning. ``Winning this tournament was huge for us, the two
days in a row, the travel, it all takes a lot of focus. Plus, we're
a young team, with just one senior and three new starters.
Hopefully, our confidence is coming on.''
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi State promptly pushed its lead back to double
figures when guard Meadow Overstreet flipped in a 3-pointer from
the top of the key, making it 49-39 with 3:35 left.
</P>
<P>
   Junior Nitra Perry had 17 points for Mississippi State while
Overstreet, a sophomore, tossed in 16. Harvard had 13 points from
senior cocaptain Suzie Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're 100 times more athletic,'' said Delaney-Smith. ``I'm
proud of our rebounding effort (Mississippi State had 44 to
Harvard's 34). Player for player, and quickness and jumping
ability, they probably had the edge, but I don't think they
dominated the game with their athletic ability.''
</P>
<P>
   The zone defense served Harvard well. ``It took their inside
game away and their rebounding in the first half, and in the second
half their shots were short, but the rebounds came out high and
they came up with the ball,'' said Delaney-Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi State grabbed its first lead on a Perry 12- footer
with 7:10 before the intermission, and held an 8-point lead at
halftime, 25-17, on an Overstreet 3-point jumper.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard, which had 15 turnovers at halftime but only three more
the second half, didn't get the ball inside to its frontcourt as
much as it wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a good job of running down the clock,'' Delaney-Smith
said. ``This was a hard matchup, but I saw some signs that a month
from now we're going to be a strong team.''
</P>
<P>
   Wofford (1-3) won the consolation game, 70-69, in overtime, over
Ball State (2-3) when Meredith Denton made both ends of a
one-and-one with 25 seconds left.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
