<SLUG> BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KITNA SHINES IN BLEAK WEEK FOR SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ He was addressing the events of Sunday afternoon at
the Kingdome when Jon Kitna unintentionally captured the region's
holiday week from hell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things,'' he said, ``seemed real bleak out there.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to the fact that the Seahawks apparently had
blown yet another game after the Tennessee Oilers went ahead 18-17
with 33 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But after the Anacortes oil refinery explosion, the Aurora
Bridge bus tragedy and the death in his prime of a cherished civic
leader, John Stanford, bleakness was indeed out there, in
exponential numbers. Throw in the wettest November in local weather
history, and Thanksgiving sighs don't get much heavier here.
</P>
<P>
   For most people, what the Seahawks did or did not do Sunday was
utterly irrelevant. By the same token, emotional sunshine would be
taken, in any amount from any source, by a community unaccountably
battered.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna provided.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just the quarterback, of course. The Seahawks' 20-18
victory was one of the broadest multiple-hero games in some time.
But Kitna's improbable story and even more improbable legerdemain
Sunday, replete with an Elway-like comeback for the game-winner,
are so wonderfully corny and warm that they take the dampness right
out of a soul.
</P>
<P>
   From reckless punk to Christian, from Central Washington to the
NFL, from Tacoma to Seattle by way of the World (League), from
third-string to first-string in one week, from the Seahawk 29 to
the Oiler 30 in 27 heart-jolting seconds ...
</P>
<P>
   If it were a script, Hollywood would reject it. Too
unbelievable. Besides, ``The Waterboy'' has been done.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna is such a great kid, and his story so cockamamy, that it
is hard to imagine the saga unfolding in the midst of the Seahawks,
who have been the NFL's dump site of the '90s for toxic stories.
</P>
<P>
   But he is here, coach Dennis Erickson's lone flower in the slag
heap. Even the vanquished opponent had to admit admiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to give Jon Kitna credit for finding a way to win this
ballgame,'' said Oilers coach Jeff Fisher. ``He was obviously the
difference in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   That ordinary sounding observation is nevertheless a stunner. In
a week in which Erickson risked internal problems by benching the
venerable, popular Warren Moon, Kitna came out not as the weak link
in an already crippled offense, but as the guy to fix things.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't to say that Moon, placed into Kitna's identical field
circumstances, wouldn't have done as well. But he has been in
similar situations this season, and he hasn't often delivered.
</P>
<P>
   It might be as simple as what Erickson said: ``Maybe Jon just
doesn't know enough to be rattled.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's a little more complex, like the Seahawks emphasizing
pass plays for Kitna to the running back and tight end that are
lower risk and more easily blocked.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe there's something bigger at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got an aura about him in the huddle,'' said wide receiver
Mike Pritchard.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's cosmic or strategic or psychic, Kitna outdid a
superlative pair of Oilers, superstars-in-waiting Steve McNair and
Eddie George, and overcame the Seahawk offense's propensity for
self-destruction.
</P>
<P>
   In his second career start. After 10 of the season's 11 weeks on
the practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   That just doesn't happen in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   But it did.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to say if it will continue. He threw a bad pass to the goal
line that was intercepted, fumbled a snap, and nearly blew the game
when in the final drive he failed to get off a play in time,
costing a critical five yards on a delay penalty.
</P>
<P>
   But each time, he ignored his inexperience as well as the Oiler
defense, to find an answer. The last recovery was the most vital
and impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a third-and-five at the Tennessee 33-yard line with 12
seconds left, Kitna's delay penalty was followed by a false start
on guard Pete Kendall, preposterously hurling the Seahawks out of
field-goal range.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed as if a season of foolish errors was spasming into a
single perfect moment of imperfection.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna then turned his back on the gloomy expectations of a
two-thirds-filled Kingdome. He delivered, taking a shotgun snap and
finding Pritchard alone up the right side for the yardage necessary
to give kicker Todd Peterson a 48-yard field goal to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been saying that he reminds me of a young Brett Favre,''
said Pritchard, a teammate of the Packer great when both were in
Atlanta. ``His demeanor is the same. The confidence he has in
himself is the same.''
</P>
<P>
   A Favre successor, in Seattle? The elephant's graveyard of
quarterbacks? Given the club history at the position, and the
disappointment of this season, Kitna's remarkable 298-yard passing
day makes it easy to get carried away.
</P>
<P>
   He's not Brett Favre. But he is a wonderful story in a place
desperately short of them.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
