</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-OILERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KITNA RESCUES SEAHAWKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Seahawks did more than win a game that appeared
lost Sunday. They also rediscovered their offense.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the right arm of Jon Kitna, who completed 24 of 39
passes for 298 yards and two touchdowns in his first start of the
season and only the second of his NFL career.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the hands of James McKnight, the drop-prone wide
receiver who caught five passes for a career-high 113 yards,
including a dazzling 59-yard TD pass play, exactly the kind of play
that had been missing from the dormant offense that struggled so
badly as the Seahawks lost six of their previous eight games.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the hands and feet of Ricky Watters, who had 123 yards
rushing and receiving.
</P>
<P>
   And ultimately, it was in the right leg of Todd Peterson, who
kicked a 48-yard field goal with one second remaining on the
Kingdome clock to give the Seahawks an improbable 20-18 victory
over the Tennessee Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   As Peterson's game-winner sailed through the uprights, Kitna
dropped to his knees and pointed heaven-ward; embattled coach
Dennis Erickson bounded onto the field, hugging anyone and everyone
in his path; the at-times docile crowd of 59,048 roared its
approval; and Oilers coach Jeff Fisher couldn't believe his team
had its playoff hopes crumpled for the third straight season by
losing to the Seahawks in the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very disappointing loss for our club,'' Fisher said.
``We're running out of games. The walls are closing in on us.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Seahawks, it was only one win in a still-disappointing
season. But the victory over the now 6-6 Oilers was just the second
against a winning team in the past 27 games, and it also evened
Seattle's record at 6-6 entering next week's game against the New
York Jets in the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of playoffs in the locker room? Hardly. But there wasn't
the morgue-like silence that followed recent losses to the Oakland
Raiders at home and the Raiders and Dallas Cowboys on the road,
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never been out of a game all year. We just haven't found
ways to win enough of them,'' guard Pete Kendall said. ``To finally
win one, we've still got a pulse. As much as people may want to
write us off, the vultures are still going to have to circle us.
We've still got a pulse in our carcass.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna was the most obvious jump-start for an offense that had
scored just seven TDs in six losses and had converted only nine
third downs in the previous five games.
</P>
<P>
   Switching quarterbacks last Monday meant benching future Hall of
Famer Warren Moon and giving the impression the coaches were giving
up on the season.
</P>
<P>
   But after the way Kitna performed Sunday, perhaps this season is
just getting started for a team that possesses so much talent but
has done so little with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jon gets an A-plus from me for everything he did today,'' said
Watters, who ran 14 times for 63 yards and matched that total on
seven receptions. ``He was very poised in pressure situations. He
was very excited. He came into the huddle and told us, `Hey, we're
going to score here.' That's contagious. That's the way to be.''
</P>
<P>
   After Del Greco had kicked his fourth field goal of the game _ a
42-yarder that put the Oilers up 18-17 with 33 seconds left to play
_ the Seahawks made the kind of mistakes that have been their
undoing in other close games, twice drawing penalties. But Kitna
was unflappable.
</P>
<P>
   The undrafted, second-year quarterback from Central Washington
University and Tacoma's Lincoln High School made the kind of
impromptu plays that seem to be his specialty:
</P>
<P>
   -- On the first play of the ensuing series, Kitna passed to
McKnight for 19 yards and gained another 15 yards when Oilers
defensive end Kenny Holmes was penalized for hitting Kitna in the
head after he threw. First down at the Oilers' 38-yard line with 20
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   -- Kitna then passed to Watters for 5 yards. Second-and-5 from
the Oilers' 33 with 16 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   -- Kitna went to McKnight along the sideline, but McKnight was
out of bounds as he made the grab. Third-and-5 with 12 seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   -- Then came a delay-of-game penalty and a false start charged
on Kendall. Third-and-15 from the Oilers' 44.
</P>
<P>
   -- Kitna went to Mike Pritchard, who lunged out of bounds at the
Oilers' 30-yard line with six seconds left. After a timeout by each
team, Peterson coolly kicked the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the way the game was going there was a chance I might
get a kick to win it,'' said Peterson, who hit a 50-yarder in the
second quarter and also supplied the winning kick in the Seahawks'
win at Oakland last season in Kitna's only other start. ``Guys rose
to the occasion. That was the difference. We believed we would win
today, instead of just thinking we can't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks needed everything Kitna, Peterson, McKnight,
Watters and Joey Galloway could supply because the defense had a
dickens of a time containing the Oilers' 1-2 punch of quarterback
Steve McNair and running back Eddie George.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-2, 225-pound McNair completed 18 of 34 passes for 199
yards and ran eight times for 64 yards, including a 3-yarder for
the Oilers' only TD. The 6-3, 240-pound George ran for 76 yards and
caught five passes for another 64 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't tell if McNair was Eddie or Eddie was McNair,''
said defensive end Michael Sinclair, who had two sacks of McNair to
regain the AFC lead with 14. ``It's tough for one guy to bring
McNair down. You've got to rally to him. We bent a little bit
today, but we didn't break.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair and George _ or George and McNair, if you will _ were the
main reasons the Seahawks had to scratch back from deficits of 6-0
and 18-17.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, unlike so many other times this season, the
Seahawks fought back and did it by leading with their offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things seemed real bleak out there,'' Kitna said. ``You'd love
to run away with a 21-point win. But things just don't happen like
that in this league very often. We'll take them how we can get
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
