<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONCOS TURN BACK THE CLOCK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ That '70s Show wound down Sunday in San Diego in
time for us to catch the start of the television sitcom by the same
name.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, you say that wasn't Don Shula standing on the Qualcomm
Stadium sidelines, Paul Warfield streaking for the end zone, Marv
Fleming sacrificing his body to catch a third-down pass from Bob
Griese or Earl Morrall, and Nick Buoniconti stuffing Chargers
runners?
</P>
<P>
   Well, you could have fooled us. The Denver Broncos of 1998, with
Mike Shanahan at the helm, John Elway and Bubby Brister (Bubby
Brister???) at the controls, Terrell Davis and Shannon Sharpe at
his disposal and Bill Romanowski and John Mobley at their defense,
resemble the Miami Dolphins of 1972 enough to be their progeny in
history's family tree.
</P>
<P>
   On the same field where they won their first Super Bowl
championship in January, the Broncos defeated a charged-up San
Diego squad 31-16 to extend their winning streak to 17 games and
become the fourth NFL team in history to start a season 12-0 (the
others were the 1934 Chicago Bears, the 1972 Dolphins and the 1985
Bears).
</P>
<P>
   To put the Broncos' winning ways in perspective, consider: Doug
Flutie was the crown prince of the Canadian Football League the
last time the Broncos lost, on Dec. 15, 1997 against the San
Francisco 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie, now appearing as the savior of the Buffalo Bills, is as
heartening a story as has been written in the NFL this year. The
fairy-tale season, though, is being authored by the Broncos, who
clinched the AFC West title over San Diego linebacker Junior Seau's
dogged body.
</P>
<P>
   After winning a Super Bowl, it's hard to write an epilogue. And
yet the only ones at a loss for words so far are those trying to
find suitable superlatives to describe a team with a kicker who
doesn't miss, a quarterback who doesn't quit, a running back who
doesn't slacken, a defense that doesn't waver and a coach who
doesn't let up.
</P>
<P>
   How about place kicker Jason Elam? With two-thirds of the season
gone he has yet to miss a field goal or a PAT. His 18 field goals
have included a 63-yarder against Jacksonville last month that tied
Tom Dempsey's 28-year-old record.
</P>
<P>
   And is there a finer running back right now than Davis, a San
Diego native and the Most Valuable Player in Super Bowl XXXII? On
Sunday he became only the second player in NFL history (after
Detroit's Barry Sanders) to surpass the 1,500-yard rushing mark in
three consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   He is on pace to finish with 2,086 yards. That would make him
only the third running back to crack the 2,000-yard milestone,
after O.J. Simpson and Eric Dickerson. This despite sitting out
snaps in the late going of one-sided games, of which Denver's had a
few; the Broncos have outscored their opponents 401-206. (This
Denver team is so dominant, it has spent only 29 minutes, 11
seconds of its season playing catch-up.)
</P>
<P>
   If Dickerson's 14-year-old single-season record of 2,105 yards
is the destination, Davis comes across as an accidental tourist.
``It's really not something that's on my mind,'' Davis said
recently. ``If I wanted it, I could have easily convinced
(Shanahan) to keep me in a couple of games this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway, a one-time Granada Hills High standout, has sat out 2{
games with nagging aches and pains, thus delaying the inevitable _
and incredible. Finally, on Nov. 22 he joined Miami's Dan Marino as
the only players to throw for over 50,000 yards in the first
quarter of a 40-14 win over Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   This is shaping up as Elway's worst season statistically since
his rookie campaign. As if he cares.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Elway had better individual numbers in his other
Super Bowl appearances but no more fulfilling moment than when he
held the Super Bowl trophy aloft in his fourth stab at the NFL's
grand prize.
</P>
<P>
   In the early going against the Chargers, Elway was
uncharacteristically sloppy, fumbling away the snap on the Broncos'
first play from scrimmage and throwing three interceptions in the
first half. But he also passed for three of his four scores in that
span. That and San Diego quarterback Craig Whelihan's three
misfires went a long way toward explaining Denver's 21-10 lead at
intermission.
</P>
<P>
   As Whelihan readily can attest, the Broncos are, to borrow a
phrase used to describe the 1972 Dolphins, ``an acquisitive bunch
of opportunists.''
</P>
<P>
   That Miami team faced only two teams with winning records in the
regular season and struggled in the playoffs to beat Cleveland
(20-14) and Pittsburgh (21-17). The Dolphins' 17th game was at the
L.A. Coliseum, against a Washington Redskins team that went 11-3 in
the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Are these Broncos better than those Dolphins? Are you kidding?
Time has been kind to the Dolphins, who weren't even considered the
best team on the Coliseum field until the final whistle sounded on
their 14-7 Super Bowl victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington should win by at least 10 points,'' opined one
scribe beforehand, ``and perhaps by as many as 21.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the Broncos' four remaining regular-season opponents, only
Miami has a winning record. Something tells us the champagne
bottles the members of the 1972 Dolphins team uncork each season
when the last of the undefeated teams is beaten might be good and
chilled by the time they reach their lips.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
