</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER LATE BLEDSOE TD LIFTS PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Doug Flutie couldn't wait to give the quote
of the day:
</P>
<P>
   ``Want the quote? Want to hear what these guys had to say on
that fourth-down play?'' said Flutie, calling over the first
reporter into the Buffalo locker room. He was referring to a Shawn
Jefferson ``catch'' on the Patriots' last drive that appeared to be
out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, it wasn't a catch. And one official called it
that way. No catch. Then the second official came over with a dumb
look on his face. He made no call. Then another official says `Just
give it to them.' Imagine that. He says, `Just give it to them.'''
</P>
<P>
   And that's precisely what the officials did to the Patriots
Sunday, they just gave it to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an embarrassment to the league and football,'' said
fuming Bills general manager John Butler outside the locker room 15
minutes after his team had a victory it deserved taken out of its
hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something like this is disgusting. They (officials) are
ruining the game. They are taking all of the fun out of it. The
level of incompetence is getting worse each year.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo coach Wade Phillips wasn't as animated as Flutie or
Butler. But he was right to the point when asked why he didn't send
his team back out for the final point-after attempt at the end of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point didn't make any differnce. They had already given
them the game,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   This was a bountiful week for New England as it enjoyed ``home
cooking'' three times. Home cooking is an expression used in the
NFL, and all pro sports, to describe game officials who appear not
to have the courage to make a call against the home team when the
game is on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night against Miami, the Patriots drove for the winning
touchdown in the final seconds, much as they did Sunday, passing
the ball down the field, and not a single holding call was made
when the Miami pass rushers were being mauled.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, as Drew Bledsoe courageously took his team down the
field for another fantastic finish with all passes, again there
were no holding calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where were the officials when I was being mugged by some of
their linemen?'' asked Buffalo defensive lineman Marcellus Wiley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We outplayed them,'' said Phillips, ``and we should have won.
We deserved to win. We made big plays to come back and they took
the game away from us.''
</P>
<P>
   Two plays drove the Bills nuts and will have them berating chief
of officials Jerry Seeman at NFL headquarters in New York Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo led, 21-17. New England had the ball on the Buffalo 36
with 11 seconds to play, and the Patriots had no timeouts. The
Patriots had a fourth and 9. Anything less than 10 yards and the
game was over.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe went back to pass and threw to Jefferson in front of the
Buffalo bench. Jefferson caught the ball and appeared to be out of
bounds. Not only that, but he also appeared to be short of the
first down. Either way, the Bills would have won.
</P>
<P>
   Here's Flutie's first-hand view of the conversation once again:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was no catch. The guy closest said no catch. Then a second
guy came in and he said he didn't know. Then another guy comes in
and says, `Just give it to them.' I mean, what is that? Why did it
happen? Because the place is filled. There's a lot of money on the
line. Why did that happen?''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots were still alive. But there were only six seconds
left. Time for one play.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe threw a Hail Mary into the left side of the Buffalo end
zone.
</P>
<P>
   There was a gang of players from both sides in the area, pushing
and shoving for position. This always happens on this play, and
after watching hundreds of Hail Mary passes in 38 years, this
reporter can't recall a pass interference call.
</P>
<P>
   When the pass is in the air like that, it is a given that
players are going to jockey for position, crawling all over each
other trying to make the play. Unbelievably, Glenn, in the middle
of this mass of humanity, jumped, had the ball in his hands, and
dropped it. Game over.
</P>
<P>
   But wait, out came another flag against Buffalo. Pass
interference. New England got one more play, from the 1, and
Bledsoe threw a perfect touch pass to the back of the end zone to
Ben Coates for the winning score.
</P>
<P>
   To call interference on a play like that is simply absurd. No
official with any common sense would make that call. Players on
both sides could have been called for pass interference, and then
maneuvered into position, and when Glenn had a clean shot to catch
the ball, and simply dropped it, then it was doubly ridiculous to
make the call.
</P>
<P>
   The officiating marred another terrific football game.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe and Flutie gave all that one could ask for. Bledsoe once
again carried his team to victory.
</P>
<P>
   He had 246 passing yards, including three touchdowns, while the
New England running game produced just 44 yards. He had to go to
the air, and again, Coates and Glenn with 18 catches between them,
saved the day.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo outplayed the Patriots and deserved to win. After a
sluggish first half, Flutie played superbly down the stretch. He
threw for 339 yards, almost 100 more than Bledsoe, with four fewer
attempts. The Bills outrushed the Patriots, 99 yards to those 44.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots blitzed Flutie throughout, and in the second half
he showed why he is playing so well right now. There were a
half-dozen times he threw to receivers who were covered, but
somehow completed these passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their cornerbacks cover (man to man) with the backs to the
line of scrimmage a lot, so I threw the ball in there, giving my
guys a chance to make plays and they did,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After Bledsoe hung a ball up early for an interception, he threw
underneath and got rid of the ball more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   On both sides, it became a game of catch-and-throw.
</P>
<P>
   All of the big plays came in the air. Bledsoe and Flutie passes.
And the officials' flags.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
