<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3991 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS-CHARGERS-     11-30 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-CHARGERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
SAN DIEGO _ The Denver Broncos almost proved nobody's perfect, but
they overcame four first-half turnovers Sunday night to become only
the fourth 12-0 team in NFL history and the first since the 1985
Chicago Bears.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Broncos mauled the San Diego Chargers 31-16 to clinch the
AFC West title. They earned their 17th consecutive victory dating
to last season, when they won Super Bowl XXXII.
</P>
<P>
   Denver moved one step closer to achieving its goal of becoming
the NFL's first 19-0 team and joining the 1972 Miami Dolphins as
the league's only unbeaten and untied champions.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos survived John Elway's three interceptions and
fumbled snap in the first half to beat the Chargers for the second
time this season. It was the first time since 1995 Elway had been
intercepted three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when we're bad, we're good,'' Broncos guard David
Diaz-Infante said.
</P>
<P>
   The teams combined for eight turnovers in the first half. The
first two quarters at Qualcomm Stadium showed how good and bad the
Broncos can be. They played their worst half of the season but led
by 11 points at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   How could the Broncos commit four turnovers and still lead
21-10? Because Elway threw three touchdown passes, including two
after Denver interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not bad when you can throw three interceptions and fumble
once and still be up 21-10,'' Elway said.
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers, who had won their past two games after quarterback
Craig Whelihan replaced No. 1 pick Ryan Leaf, also committed four
turnovers, including three interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were playing our worst, and they were playing their best,
and we still won,'' Broncos receiver Rod Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Before this game, Denver had committed only nine turnovers,
including two fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the night to beat them,'' San Diego general manager
Bobby Beathard said.
</P>
<P>
   Elway and Tom Nalen mishandled the snap on the first play, and
linebacker Junior Seau recovered at the Broncos' 25. That led to
John Carney's 27-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   If not for San Diego's turnovers, the Broncos would have had
little to show for the first half because the Chargers' No.
1-ranked run defense threw a blanket over running back Terrell
Davis, who carried nine times for 32 yards in the first two
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Elway and Davis needed help from the defense to jump-start the
offense. When cornerback Darrien Gordon intercepted Whelihan and
returned it 17 yards to the San Diego 22, the Broncos scored for
the first time. Elway found receiver Ed McCaffrey for a 15-yard
touchdown. Jason Elam made it 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   Denver's best drive came midway through the first quarter when
it covered 66 yards in five plays. Elway and McCaffrey combined for
the touchdown, this one going for 37 yards with 6:43 left in the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared another Denver rout was on, but the Chargers
regained their composure, thanks to Whelihan. On an 81-yard drive,
he completed four passes for 56 yards. Running back Terrell
Fletcher scored on a 13-yard run to make it 14-10.
</P>
<P>
   On their next series, the Chargers looked as if they were going
to take the lead. They reached Denver's seven, but reserve running
back Kenny Bynum fumbled at the five. That was it for San Diego's
offense. From there, it became a comedy of errors with Elway and
Whelihan the featured performers.
</P>
<P>
   First, Elway was intercepted by cornerback Charles Dimry, who
returned it 30 yards to the Denver 41. The scoring chance was
squandered when Whelihan was intercepted by cornerback Darrius
Johnson at Denver's 49.
</P>
<P>
   On the first play of that Denver series, Dimry intercepted Elway
again, but the Chargers could do nothing with it.
</P>
<P>
   Elway was intercepted on a third consecutive series when safety
Greg Johnson picked off a long pass at the San Diego two. Two plays
later, linebacker John Mobley intercepted Whelihan, and a San Diego
facemask penalty gave the Broncos a first down at San Diego's 19.
</P>
<P>
   Elway didn't waste this opportunity. On the second play, he
threw a perfect pass to the corner of the end zone, where Smith
caught the 13-yard touchdown, giving Denver a 21-10 lead with 49
seconds left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were fortunate to be ahead 21-10,'' coach Mike Shanahan
said. ``I've got to credit our defense for hanging tough and John
for keeping his poise.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos opened the second half with a drive becoming of the
defending Super Bowl champions. After stopping the Chargers on
three downs, Denver got the ball at its five. Fourteen plays, 95
yards and eight minutes, 20 seconds later, the Broncos had a 28-10
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Elway completed five passes on the drive. Offsetting penalties
rubbed out his 18-yard touchdown pass to Smith on third-and-seven.
No problem. On the next play, the Chargers rushed only three
linemen, and Elway had enough time to throw an 18-yard TD pass to
tight end Shannon Sharpe.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe broke off his route and headed for the end zone when he
saw Elway scrambling and looking for a receiver. Sharpe caught the
ball in the back of the end zone with 4:34 left in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers scored their last touchdown when Whelihan threw a
47-yard pass to Bryan Still with 4:55 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing the Chargers did surprised us,'' Shanahan said.
``They're No. 1 in defense, and we knew going in it was going to be
a dogfight, and it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy to be 12-0, but that was our goal. Now, our goal
is to be 13-0.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
