<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3994 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BILLS-BO     11-30 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BILLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER LATE BLEDSOE TD LIFTS PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ It was a Flutie Finish.
</P>
<P>
   Starring Drew Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   Once again Sunday, Bledsoe had his finger on the pulse of the
Patriots' life support. It wasn't enough that he worked a Doug
Flutie-like miracle in a dramatic victory over the Dolphins last
Monday night after breaking his right index finger in two places.
</P>
<P>
   This time he won the game and saved the season again, with no
time remaining in regulation, snatching the spotlight and a chapter
from Flutie folklore right out from under Flutie's nose with a
1-yard touchdown pass to Ben Coates that produced a 25-21 victory
over the Buffalo Bills. This came right after the Patriots received
what may have been a gift interference call charged to safety Henry
Jones on a Hail Mary pass from Bledsoe to Terry Glenn in the end
zone that ate up the final six seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I've never had anything good happen on a Hail Mary
pass,'' said Bledsoe. ``I've tried about eight of those things and
six of them have been intercepted.''
</P>
<P>
   On the play before the pass interference call, the Patriots
threw to Shawn Jefferson on a fourth and 9 from the Bills 36 with
11 seconds left. He caught the ball, but appeared to be out of
bounds, however the officials gave him the call.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, several Bills said they heard one official say
to another, ``Just give it to them.'' And so the play stood,
setting the stage for the next questionable call.
</P>
<P>
   Of the interference call made before the winning play, Bledsoe
said, ``They hit (Terry), and so it's pass interference. It was a
good call.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn said he should have caught the pass, as he turned back
toward the ball and saw it go right between his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got hit right before the ball arrived,'' said Glenn. ``But I
should have caught the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Ty Law, the victim of two pass interference calls in what was a
tough performance by the Patriots' secondary (and perhaps a tougher
day for the officials), saw it differently and sympathized with the
Bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see anything,'' said Law. ``That was one for the
boys. Everybody's jumping on those Hail Marys. They have a right to
be pissed. With all the bad calls we got, I think we deserved one.
But we can't make miracles happen every week. We've got to get our
act together on defense. We're better than what we're showing.''
</P>
<P>
   Referee Walt Coleman confirmed that the call was on Jones and
explained: ``The receiver went up to catch the ball. (Jones) just
went through the receiver and he was not playing the ball. He made
contact with the receiver and that's interference.''
</P>
<P>
   There were 21 penalties called, 12 on the Bills and nine on the
Patriots. But the one at the end sent Bills owner Ralph Wilson
through the roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the worst officiating I've ever seen,'' said Wilson.
``I'll take the fine. I don't care what it is. It's embarrassing to
the league. Don't get me wrong, the Patriots have a hell of a team,
but we got robbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen football for six decades,'' Wilson continued, ``I've
never seen anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The win improved the Patriots' record to 7-5, 4-3 in the AFC
East, and they are tied for third place with the Bills, a game
behind the New York Jets and Miami, who share the top spot at 8-4.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pete Carroll said he let offensive coordinator Ernie
Zampese call the final play. The Patriots lined up in a running
formation (and some Bills thought the Patriots were going to run
it) at the goal line, but Bledsoe stepped back and lofted the
winning pass to Coates, alone in the back of the end zone to the
right side, leaving linebacker Marlo Perry behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the play we would normally call if we're going to throw
it there,'' said Zampese. ``It was made to order. Drew and Ben have
developed this great rapport over the years, so when it comes to
crunch time like that, that's what we do. Ben really got himself
wide open and Drew ... this guy just amazes me week to week. He's
playing hurt. He's showed so much heart and soul the last two
weeks. It was an emotional win. It's an emotional situation for our
football team. To win two games like this has to do a lot for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Coates and fullback Tony Carter were Bledsoe's only two options
on the play, Carter along the goal line and Coates deeper.
</P>
<P>
   The game ended with Adam Vinatieri running in for a 2-point
conversion after officials called both teams back on the field to
complete the scoring. But the Bills didn't come back, and holder
Tom Tupa pitched to Vinatieri, who padded his scoring totals.
</P>
<P>
   That ended an afternoon that looked as if it might end the way
so many envisioned it, with Flutie leading the Bills to a win in
his hometown. He had been 10-0 here before Sunday. He threw for 339
yards, an NFL career high, completing 21 of 39 passes with two
touchdowns. He had brought the Bills back from a 14-0 deficit to
within 14-12 in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots put distance between them and the Bills on
Vinatieri's 44-yard field goal with 5:06 remaining in the third
quarter, ending the Bills' string of 12 unanswered points.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bills got the ball back and Flutie drove them from their
33 to the Patriots' 4 before Steve Christie booted a field goal
from 22 yards to pull the Bills to within 17-15.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots did a three-and-out as the third quarter ended and
the final period began. And then, Buffalo went on one of the
strangest drives, which consumed 8:28. It featured two critical
third-down penalties, one to Law for defensive holding and one on
rookie Tebucky Jones for illegal use of hands, and one big
second-down penalty on Steve Israel that put Buffalo on the New
England 5.
</P>
<P>
   On third and 4 at the 4, Flutie looped one over Jones's head to
Andre Reed, and the Bills had taken their first lead of the game,
21-17, with 6:14 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots made a couple of first downs on the ensuing drive,
with Glenn catching a 23-yard pass along the way. The drive stalled
at the Bills' 29 when Glenn dropped a slant, on which he was about
to get demolished, but the news got worse when Vinatieri missed a
47-yard attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills got the ball back at their 37 and tried to eat up the
clock. After Antowain Smith made a first down on runs of 8 and 3
yards, the Patriots' defense began to tighten. Flutie attempted a
keeper on third and 8 at midfield that was stuffed by rookie
defensive end Greg Spires.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills punted back to the Patriots after the two-minute
warning to the Patriots' 18, where the final drive began with 1:52
remaining. Bledsoe went 8 for 12 for 52 yards on the final drive,
connecting with Coates four times, but no pass went for more than
12 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drew played a great game,'' said Flutie. ``He played with a
lot of heart. In the past two weeks he's won over a lot of
naysayers with his approach to the game. We played with the same
heart, but the officials had way too much control of the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 0135EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
