u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     11-30 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG PREACHES CAUTION AMIDST EUPHORIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Bruce Armstrong sat alone amidst the
rubble of the passing parade Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   His team had just pulled out a most improbable victory for the
second straight game and there was chaos around him. Young players
who didn't know any better were uplifted, voices rising in
excitement at what they had just won, which Armstrong understood
was nothing but a game unless better games followed it.
</P>
<P>
   Older hands, who maybe should have known better, were uplifted
as well, their gear lying in piles around the locker room as they
slapped hands, slapped backs, slapped anything they could think of
in the pure joy of unexpected victory.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was uplifted as well. After 12 years of NFL warfare,
he knew better than most how joyful the feeling was Sunday night
after Drew Bledsoe threw a touchdown pass to Ben Coates with no
time on the clock to beat the Buffalo Bills and keep the Patriots'
playoff hopes alive. But he also knew something had to be said to
his frolicking teammates right then, before the partying spun out
of control.
</P>
<P>
   What had to be said had to be said at that moment, in the midst
of the elation of victory, but how it was said might be as
important as that it was said at all, and Armstrong understood
that, too.
</P>
<P>
   So the six-time Pro Bowl tackle gently reminded his younger
teammates that, yes, this was a stirring 25-21 victory and yes, it
was nothing short of marvelous to have won in this fashion two
weeks in a row, but ... there's always a but in a circumstance such
as the Patriots are in now ... it would be unwise to continue to do
things in this manner much longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a great victory, but the fact is we're pretty much
all out of miracles,'' Armstrong explained, an hour after another
one had lifted his team to 7-5 and into a third-place tie with
Buffalo behind the Jets and Dolphins, who both won Sunday to remain
tied atop the AFC East at 8-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not here just to win a few games and make some money. I'm
doing this for an opportunity to win the championship. It feels
good to win a game like this because I've been here a long time and
been on the wrong end of a lot of these kind of finishes, but we
know we've got to play better than this.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to go out and make that play (the 1-yard touchdown pass
to Coates with no time left and the 25-yard pass to Shawn Jefferson
a week ago with 25 seconds to play that beat Miami) is important.
It shows we've got a bunch of guys in here with a lot of heart, but
we can play better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made plays lately and it's given us a chance to win, but
we don't want to keep putting ourselves in position to have to win
this way. If you do, one day you don't win. That's indicative of
where we're at at the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Where the Patriots are at this moment is back in the race with a
month to go, back in a place where it did not look likely these
Patriots could reach two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   As they say in pool, there is still a lot of green between the
balls they have to knock into the pockets and their cue, but at
least they are alive again, which, frankly, did not seem likely
after they lost four out of five games before miracles started
happening as if they were playing on 34th Street this holiday
season.
</P>
<P>
   Now they must go to a most difficult place next Sunday and do it
again. They must go to Pittsburgh, where they have lost six
straight dating back to 1986 and face the Steelers, to whom they
have lost seven of the last eight games, and they must win. If they
are wise, Armstrong knows, they will not go to Pittsburgh expecting
to have eight penalties called on the Steelers in the final two
drives of the day, as happened Sunday night to the Bills.
</P>
<P>
   If they are wise, they will not wait for the final seconds,
needing a miracle to stay alive. If they end up winning in as
dramatic a fashion as they did Sunday _ when they drove 82 yards to
victory in the final minute and 52 seconds to win _ Armstrong will
take it, but he is the ultimate realist and so he knows these are
not the Lourdes Patriots. This is not a team of constant miracle
workers _ no team can be.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years in the NFL, half ending with him drinking fresh
pineapple juice at the Pro Bowl, have taught Bruce Armstrong. He
understands pro football is a game in which the fantastic may
happen, but to rely on it is to court disaster.
</P>
<P>
   So Sunday night, as gently as he could, Armstrong reminded his
young teammates that drama sells, but too much drama can turn a
good story bad. Too much reliance on drama leads you not to the
championship game in January but to the golf course, and so he took
this win for what it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sitting here appreciating this, but the realist in me
knows we can't keep going out and doing this,'' Armstrong said. ``I
don't want to spoil the atmosphere or rain on anyone's parade, but
we have to play better to win the championship. That was addressed
as soon as we came in this locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was worried a lot a few weeks ago about where we were
headed. If you looked at all the numbers, it didn't look good. We'd
created a situation for ourselves that brought everything else into
play, like tiebreakers, instead of taking care of our own business,
but now we got a chance again if we realize what these last two
games did for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't win us anything. If we lost this game we would
have just been playing football games the rest of the year. We need
to understand that. This was a great win for us, but all it gave us
is a chance to make next week mean something.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win there, then the next week could mean something. And
if we keep doing that and not making it so hard on ourselves, when
we get to the end we could really win something. That's what we
have to remember.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, miracles are fine as long as you don't need one
too many.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
