<SLUG> BC-FBN-BILLS-FLUTIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ONCE, FLUTIE ON SHORT SIDE OF SCORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The postgame attire was black. In fashion,
as in football, Doug Flutie is ever on target. The humor, too,
matched the attire.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie isn't usually the one who has to explain the
inexplainable defeat. He's the one who invites the superlatives.
He's the one who singularly turned ``Hail Mary'' into something
other than a prayer. He's the miracle worker, not the spurned
suitor.
</P>
<P>
   On this particular occasion, however, Flutie was on the losing
end. In 10 previous starts at Bob Kraft's Xanadu on Route 1, Flutie
had won 10 times. No. 11 seemed to be a formality after a
career-best 339-yard, two-TD performance against the Patriots. His
team led, 21-17, until the Patriots scored on the final play, with
no time left, beneficiaries of some truly controversial, bizarre,
and, in Flutie's view, gutless calls by the officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game was worth the price of admission, wasn't it?'' he
deadpanned to a sea of minicams. He then went on to say that
several Bills had overheard the officials discussing a critical
fourth-down play that kept New England's drive going.
</P>
<P>
   One official didn't know. The other wasn't sure. So, Flutie
said, one turned to the other and said, ``Just give it to them.''
They did. ``I'm not going to get fined for this, am I?'' Flutie
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's a judgment call, make a decision and live with it,''
he said. ``It's frustrating. We missed a big opportunity. We played
well enough to win and it's frustrating to lose it the way we did
at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   It was hard, almost impossible, to get Flutie to talk about The
Day. The Game. The Return. It all seemed so irrelevant to him. He
was his usual, accommodating self afterward, going so far as to
suggest the best possible backdrop for a television interview. (It
was the end zone.)
</P>
<P>
   It had been a decade since he last passed through here, soon to
be exiled to the Canadian Football League. There was a huge buildup
for his one and only appearance at Kraft's Shangri-La and he didn't
disappoint.
</P>
<P>
   He completed 21 of 39 passes with no interceptions. Two passes
went for touchdowns; an 84-yarder to Eric Moulds (great catch and
great run) and the erstwhile game-winning toss of 4 yards to Andre
Reed to cap a drive that took more time than the director's cut of
``Dances With Wolves.''
</P>
<P>
   There were also the obligatory escapes (five rushes for 30
yards) and, until the bitter end, the satisfaction of seemingly
winning a big division game, on the road, in front of many, many
closet Flutie fans, some of whom were brave enough to wear Flutie's
old No. 2 Patriot jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Flutie shrugged when told of the gaudy numbers. ``It's
not that satisfying, though. You want to put enough points on the
board and we didn't do it. I thought I played well. I played my
heart out. I'm not disappointed with that. I'm disappointed the way
it ended.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted the fans were supportive at the beginning, but as the
game wore on, they turned hostile. He said he expected that. ``Once
the game starts, they forget about all that other stuff and root
for their team,'' he said. But he also noted these were fans who
needed no convincing of his worth or ability. He may have had to do
it elsewhere, but not here.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the people who knew,'' he said. ``I didn't have to
prove anything to them.''
</P>
<P>
   These also were the people accustomed to watching Flutie win
games like this. They saw him direct the Bills on that interminable
fourth-quarter drive, abetted by some similarly controversial calls
against the Patriots. They saw Flutie connect with Reed on a must
third-down timing play to give Buffalo its first lead of the game.
</P>
<P>
   But they also saw Flutie fail to get that final first down that
would never have given the Patriots _ or the officials _ another
chance. He still regretted not making a cut that might have got the
necessary yardage.
</P>
<P>
   And he was like so many others in that final 1:52, a helpless
bystander. He has been on both sides of miracle wins, from his
``Hail Mary'' toss to beat Miami in 1984 to a Grey Cup loss when
his brother, Darren, made the winning catch.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, there was some brief family time with his wife,
mother-in-law, and sister-in-law. There was some family pride in
knowing that his nephew, Billy, won the Punt, Pass &AMP; Kick
Competition. But there also was the sense of opportunity lost,
something Flutie and those who have watched him over the years
simply aren't used to seeing.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Laurie, probably summed it up best.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was typical Doug,'' she said. ``It was unbelievable. He
played really well. He just couldn't do any more than he did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
