<SLUG> BC-FBN-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE'S FINGER BROKEN, BUT SPIRIT INTACT 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Larry Bird.
</P>
<P>
   These are the words that best describe what Drew Bledsoe in the
last seven days has done for his team, our region, and his own good
name.
</P>
<P>
   It took a broken bone, and a couple of impossible last-second
comebacks against Miami and Buffalo, but after what we saw in
Sunday's 25-21 win over the Bills, it's clear that Bledsoe is
finally ready to take his place in the pantheon of local sports
greats. In his sixth full season, already the greatest Patriot
ever, Bledsoe is poised to join Ted Williams, Carl Yastrzemski,
Bobby Orr, and yes ... Larry Bird.
</P>
<P>
   He'll need a championship or two to finish the job, but that
suddenly seems like part of his future now that we know Drew's got
the same stuff that drove Larry to dive on the floor and take the
last shot.
</P>
<P>
   It took a broken index finger and back-to-back miracles to bring
local fans and media critics on board. Bledsoe knew all along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to be arrogant, but I haven't been surprised by any of
this,'' he said after throwing a 1-yard TD strike to Ben Coates
with no time on the clock. ``I've always enjoyed these situations.
It's the situation you live for when you play sports, from the time
you're playing ball at recess in grade school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the guy I've seen all along,'' said Pete Carroll, the
cheerleader/coach who has been pulled from the fire by his heroic
quarterback. ``I've seen the intensity. I've seen the
competitiveness. This is what he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently. But cynical/impatient/passionate/angry New
Englanders have been reluctant to fully embrace their young star
who passed for 20,000 yards quicker than any quarterback not
</P>
<P>
   named Marino. It's bothered us that he can appear so calm before
going into battle. We've decided that he doesn't have enough fire
and, like Roger Clemens before him, he can't win the big game.
</P>
<P>
   These last two games were practically franchise-savers. Since
owner Bob Kraft announced his intention to move the team to
Chernobyl-by-the-Connecticut in Hartford, the Patriots twice played
knowing that a loss almost certainly would eliminate them from
playoff competition. In both contests, Bledsoe drove them the
length of the field in the closing seconds despite playing with a
broken bone in his passing hand.
</P>
<P>
   Tough enough for you?
</P>
<P>
   Downright Larry-esque. That's what it was.
</P>
<P>
   This is what the great ones do. Against Miami Monday night,
Bledsoe was like a weary Luis Tiant, refusing to come out of the
game and throwing strikes from every angle to beat the Cincinnati
Reds in the fourth game of the 1975 World Series. Against the Bills
Sunday, he was like Bird in the 1991 playoffs, coming out of the
trainer's room in the second half to beat the Indiana Pacers after
smashing his face on the Garden parquet.
</P>
<P>
   Proof that there is a sports god with a fine sense of symmetry,
Bledsoe's finest hour came while local icon Doug Flutie _ who never
had lost at Foxboro Stadium _ stood on the sideline, unable to
perform any more miracles.
</P>
<P>
   When the Buffalo offense left the field for the last time, the
Bills led, 21-17, and the Patriots were stuck on their own 18 with
1:52 showing on the clock, no timeouts remaining, and a QB with a
broken finger.
</P>
<P>
   Then Bledsoe did what Flutie has done so many times. He took his
team down the field. And then he beat the Bills with ... a Hail
Mary pass. Beating Doug Flutie's team with a Hail Mary is like
beating Mark McGwire in Home Run Derby. Flutie copyrighted the
prayer pass against the University of Miami in 1984, but Sunday he
watched helplessly hoping as Bledsoe's 26-yard heave came down
under Terry Glenn. The pass was incomplete, but a pass interference
call gave the Patriots a final play from the 1 with no time
remaining in the game. Bledsoe made it count, finding Coates in the
back of the end zone near the far right corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the Hail Marys I've thrown in my career, going back to the
eighth grade, I've never had anything good come out of any of
them,'' said Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   Something good happened this time (though in Buffalo the play is
likely to be remembered as something akin to grand theft). And then
Bledsoe was able to finish the job with no time for consultation
from the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   And so the Patriot season is saved. For now. And 6-foot-5-inch
Drew is finally bigger than 5-9 Doug.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Drew is tired of hearing all that Flutie stuff,'' said
Bledsoe's backup, Scott Zolak. ``I think this is rather tasty for
him. I think maybe he's Massachusetts' top quarterback tonight,
instead of that other guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. On this night Drew was Larry. And Doug never had a
prayer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
