<SLUG> BC-FBN-BILLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLS OWNER RIPS OFFICIATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Buffalo Bills owner Ralph Wilson was already
wound up. He had stood livid Sunday in the visitors' locker room _
where the Bills thought they had been robbed of a game they had won
_ and railed about the officiating.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the locker room, he ran into quarterback Doug Flutie.
They talked for a minute and Flutie passed on the word that besides
the pass interference call in the end zone that led to the winning
Patriot touchdown, and a Shawn Jefferson catch along the sideline
that the Bills thought was clearly out of bounds, there was more.
</P>
<P>
   Even on the remote chance that Jefferson did make the catch
inbounds, Flutie was reporting, it looked like he didn't have
enough yardage to make the first down on fourth and 9. In other
words, the game should have ended a play earlier and the pass
interference play never should have happened.
</P>
<P>
   None of this changed Wilson's assessment of what he had seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the worst officiating I've ever seen,'' Wilson said.
``I'll take the fine. I don't care. I don't know what can be done
about it, but it was awful. It's embarrassing to the league. Don't
get me wrong. The Patriots have a heck of a team. But we got
robbed.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the prevailing sentiment in an angry, irate locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen football for six decades and I've never seen
anything like that,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm obviously upset about the outcome of the game, I think
it's ridiculous,'' said Buffalo coach Wade Phillips. ``A guy
catches the ball on the sideline, I think it's over then, and I've
never seen a pass interference call on a Hail Mary play.''
</P>
<P>
   Fullback Sam Gash, once a Patriot and now a Bill, watched it
from the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (things) that happened at the end was ridiculous,'' Gash
said. ``Two calls back to back. Ridiculous. Yeah, I feel like we
were robbed. That's the worst end of a game I've ever been involved
with in terms of officiating. The worst.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive backs Henry Jones and Thomas Smith and the rest of the
Bills defenders watched it all up close _ too close _ in the left
corner of the end zone. ``It was a mess out there,'' they said.
Smith said he heard someone say the pass interference call was on
No. 20 _ Jones. Jones said he still didn't know if the call had
been against him (it was).
</P>
<P>
   Smith's job was to jump and try to knock the ball away. Jones
was supposed to hang back and keep an eye out for deflections.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said his arms were being held down as he got ready to jump
and there came Terry Glenn across and going up.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always contact,'' Smith said. ``It's in the end zone,
it's a Hail Mary, people are jockeying for position. There are
about six people there in what is a little amount of space.''
</P>
<P>
   Contact? Oh yeah. Pass interference? No way, they all felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you supposed to do?,'' Smith said. ``How can you
cover anybody? How can you call it pass interference? I don't
understand it. I don't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was crazy out there,'' he said. ``I don't think referees
should ever decide a game like that. It was unbelievable. I had
contact with somebody. I had contact with a couple of people.''
</P>
<P>
   But pass interference? Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave them the ball at the 1-yard line,'' Jones said. ``I
don't know what to say. I could see it if someone pulled someone
down, or if they tackled him, or if they were holding him down and
he couldn't jump. That's one thing.''
</P>
<P>
   This, they could not understand.
</P>
<P>
   But, Wilson said, he did see it coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``On that interference play, right before it, I turned to my
daughter and said they're going to throw it into the end zone and
the officials are going to call interference,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   To his horror, the play unfolded exactly as he had predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could play the stock market like that,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
