r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CASSTEVENS-CARDIN     11-30 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CASSTEVENS-CARDINALS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERIC, TELL US HOW YOU'RE FEELING NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ Dear Eric:
</P>
<P>
   If you missed it, and you did, the Cardinals lost to the Kansas
City Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, the Chiefs. The Chiefs who had lost six in a row.
The Chiefs who lead the league in fumbles and penalties.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs who couldn't remember the last time they rushed for
100 yards might as well have worn a sign on their back Sunday that
read, ``Beat Us, Please.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Cardinals couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Without its best player, the defense couldn't make a stop when
it needed to, when it had to, with the game on the line.
</P>
<P>
   With six minutes left and the Cardinals trailing by a touchdown,
Dave McGinnis paced the sideline, frantic, hands cupped to his
mouth. What was your coach shouting? Defensive signals or
encouragement?
</P>
<P>
   ``Both,'' McGinnis said later.
</P>
<P>
   The pleas were snatched from his lips, the words swept away by a
gusting prairie wind.
</P>
<P>
   Your teammates ``had'' to make a stand. But there was Rich
Gannon rolling out and tossing another pass for a first down. There
was Bam Morris bamming through the line. Fourteen yards. Six more
to the Cardinals' 1.
</P>
<P>
   Did you watch the game on TV?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he _ ``you'' _ did,'' Lomas Brown said, not unkindly.
The Cardinals tackle felt compelled to say what McGinnis can't say.
What he won't say. In the code of coaches citing injuries after a
loss is a cop-out. A crutch.
</P>
<P>
   So Brown said it. ``We need him. We need ``everybody.'' We're
fighting for the playoffs.'' The 14-year veteran buttoned his dress
shirt, knotted his tie. ``I don't think I'm saying anything out of
place.''
</P>
<P>
   No one blames this loss on you.
</P>
<P>
   To do so is unfair.
</P>
<P>
   It is as unfair as those who wonder if you're ``really''
hurting. ``I can't be in his body,'' Lomas said in the emptying
locker room. Only you can feel the soreness in your right knee.
Only one other person, our president, feels your pain.
</P>
<P>
   But it must hurt terribly.
</P>
<P>
   The pain must be excruciating for you to submit to another
operation _ the same procedure you had in October _ and miss the
Cardinals' playoff drive. It must hurt like hell.
</P>
<P>
   Redd Foxx as TV's Fred Sanford called it ``arthur-i-tis,'' but
it's not a laughing matter to those who are afflicted, and many
are.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got it in my wrist,'' said Michael Bidwill, the owner's
son, bending the joint. Bidwill feels stiffness and pain. But he
can't feel ``your'' pain.
</P>
<P>
   So team management relies on the expertise of its doctors. They
say you're suffering from arthritis in both knees. They say last
month's surgery _ a cleaning-out procedure called an arthroscopic
flush _ was successful. They contend you don't need another
surgery, that you're looking for ``a silver bullet'' _ a cure that
will make the pain go away. They are hoping before you have surgery
that you'll get a third opinion.
</P>
<P>
   How much pain can a player endure? That depends upon the
individual. At times during his Hall of Fame career, Larry Wilson
played with broken fingers on both hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always able not to think about it,'' Wilson once said.
``I can't tell you why.''
</P>
<P>
   It must be a heavy burden weighing your physical well-being
against the desire to compete and the obligation to your teammates.
You signed a five-year, $25 million contract. You're earning more
this season than seven or eight other defensive starters combined.
</P>
<P>
   Of course the coaches and players wanted you in the lineup
Sunday. Even though the Cards have won three of their last five
games, the defense obviously isn't the same without you.
</P>
<P>
   You are Eric Swann, 6 feet 5, 313 pounds, a Pro Bowl player, the
best defensive player on the team. You can dominate the middle. You
draw double-teams, freeing others to make plays.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Tobin downplays your absence. ``You hope one player
wouldn't be the breaking point of a whole defensive football
team,'' the coach said after this loss.
</P>
<P>
   But Lomas Brown is right. The Cardinals need you. Whatever you
can give.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not coming back,'' Jamir Miller said dismissively as he
left the locker room. ``He's done for the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it true?
</P>
<P>
   If it is, and if your decision is as painful as your aching
knee, here is some advice, not that you asked for it. Say what's in
your heart. Tell your teammates how much you regret not being there
with them, for them. Tell the public, too. Everyone would feel a
little better. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
