<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-CHIEFS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEFS MAKE CASE AGAINST CARDINALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Out of the kindness of his heart, Kansas City
Chiefs Coach Marty Schottenheimer had quarterback Rich Gannon take
a knee three straight times to end Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   It was the only way the Cardinals' defense was going to make a
stop.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals allowed 282 yards and 20 points in the second half
to fall, 34-24, before 69,613 fans at Arrowhead Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Just when their offense finally gets going _ they've averaged 30
points in their past four games _ the defense goes into retreat.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardinals (6-6) fail to reach the playoffs, they can
blame their defense, which has been mauled the past three weeks.
They've given up 1,151 yards and 111 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything has flipped on this team,'' outside linebacker
Jamir Miller said. ``The momentum has gone to the offense and we've
just stalled. Any time an offense scores (24) points, you should
win 85 percent of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Three times in the second half, the Cardinals came within a
touchdown of the Chiefs but couldn't stop them, including the final
six minutes after Mario Bates' 1-yard touchdown run cut the lead to
31-24.
</P>
<P>
   On the ensuing kickoff, Bates was penalized for being offsides,
kicker Joe Nedney suffered a torn anterior cruciate ligament in his
left knee that will end his season and punter Scott Player was
forced into action when the Cardinals had to kick again.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs, who broke a six-game skid, went 66 yards in 10 plays
to put the game away on Pete Stoyanovich's 18-yard field goal with
1:57 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not dominating like we used to,'' rookie defensive end
Andre Wadsworth said in the understatement of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In second halves the past two weeks, the Cardinals have allowed
seven touchdowns and two field goals and scores on 9 of 12 drives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It completely baffles me after (Sunday's) first half,''
defensive coordinator Dave McGinnis said. ``How many yards did they
have? What did they do? The first half, we got this thing going.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs led, 14-10, at halftime, but both of their touchdowns
came on short drives. They took over on the Cardinals' 4 after
quarterback Jake Plummer was intercepted by cornerback James Hasty
in the first quarter. They started their next drive on the Arizona
37 thanks to a 62-yard kickoff return by Tamarick Vanover.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked into the locker room at halftime and saw that (the
Chiefs) had about 12 carries for 30 yards,'' Miller said of a first
half in which the Cardinals allowed only 37 rushing yards on 13
carries. ``I looked up (at the scoreboard) again in the third
quarter, and three carries later, they had 15 for about 75 yards.
You can't do that and be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs gained 20, 15 and 16 yards on their first three runs
of the second half. They had 91 rushing yards in the second half
and finished with 128, their first 100-yard game in seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an early scouting report from Cardinals defensive back
J.J. McCleskey on next week's opponent, the New York Giants. He
didn't have to be reminded that the Giants have rushed for 577
yards in beating the Cardinals by a combined score of 80-30 the
past three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll come back at us in their regular old offense and try
to do what they did to us to beat us the last three times, just run
the ball at us,'' McCleskey said.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, the Chiefs took a page out of Giants Coach
Jim Fassel's game plan and ran at the team's smallish right side of
the defense. They kept going at end Simeon Rice (260 pounds) and
outside linebacker Tony McCombs (246). That opened up the passing
game, and the Cardinals put little pressure on Gannon, who
completed 21 of 28 for 231 yards. Wide receiver Derrick Alexander
had six catches for 116 yards and two scores.
</P>
<P>
   The dreadful defensive performance ruined another big day by the
offense, which threw for 250 yards and rushed for 124.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer led the Cardinals on a four-play, 80-yard drive in the
third quarter that cut the lead to 24-17.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the game wears on, we feel we can't be stopped,'' center
Aaron Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was, the Cardinals also couldn't stop the Chiefs,
who then went 76 yards on 11 plays to extend their lead to 14
points, the touchdown coming on a 15-yard pass from Gannon to
Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' offense again wasn't going to be denied. Plummer
directed it on an 80-yard, 10-play score.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Cardinals scored twice. A 37-yard touchdown pass
from Plummer to Rob Moore with 8:33 left was wiped out when the
officials ruled that Moore landed out of bounds. Replays showed it
was a legal catch. Six plays later, Bates scored, but the Cardinals
couldn't stop the Chiefs from getting the clinching field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't get them turned away coming down the stretch, and
that is very disappointing,'' Coach Vince Tobin said. ``Good
football teams find a way to make plays when they have to make
them. We were close to making plays but didn't make them. We had
chances to knock passes down. We had chances to get sacks, and we
didn't do either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very concerned that we're not playing well in the second
half and shutting the door on teams.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
