</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-JOHNSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL  JOHNSON SELECT DIAMONDBACKS TODAY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It appears to be close to a photo finish between the
Diamondbacks and Anaheim Angels in the four-horse race to capture
prize free-agent left-hander Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The long wait will end at mid-morning today, when the
35-year-old Johnson announces his choice from his Valley home.
</P>
<P>
   If Diamondbacks Managing General Partner Jerry Colangelo already
knew the result, he wasn't tipping his hand Sunday night. But after
speaking earlier in the day with Johnson and his two agents, Alan
Nero and Barry Meister, Colangelo said, ``I feel very upbeat, very
positive. I feel pretty confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Four clubs, including the Los Angeles Dodgers and Texas Rangers,
had offered Johnson four-year deals in the $50 million range.
</P>
<P>
   During the past week, the Dodgers were said to have the highest
offer at around $52 million, but Arizona apparently raised its ante
from $51 million to about $54 million. Combine that with the fact
that Johnson would be able to remain at home year-round, and the
Diamondbacks might have the edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Diamondbacks are showing that they want to win now, and
that has made Randy's decision tougher,'' Nero told the`` Los
Angeles Times.''
</P>
<P>
   The signing of Johnson would enable Arizona to become an
immediate contender in the National League West Division. Last
week, the team signed right-handed starters Todd Stottlemyre and
Armando Reynoso and previously signed veteran left-handed middle
reliever Greg Swindell. The Diamondbacks already had a solid
pitching nucleus with right-hander Andy Benes, left-handers Brian
Anderson and Omar Daal and right-handed closer Gregg Olson.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels also made a recent bold move of their own when they
signed slugging first baseman Mo Vaughn to a six-year, $80 million
deal. Shortly after signing, Vaughn contacted Johnson in a
recruiting attempt, but recent calls apparently have gone
unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   Angels Manager Terry Collins, Dodgers General Manager Kevin
Malone and Texas General Manager Doug Melvin remained optimistic
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson began the 1998 season with Seattle and was 9-10 before
being traded to Houston on July 31. He was 10-1 with the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has a career record of 143-79. He won the American
League Cy Young Award in 1995, is a five-time All-Star and has led
the AL in strikeouts four times. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
