<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-FRAUENHEIM-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON NEAR HIS MOMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A final piece to one very strange trip could be in place later
this week when Mike Tyson's comeback bout on Jan. 16 against Frans
Botha is officially announced in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In the past several months, Tyson has appeared at more hearings
than a Clinton lawyer. Psychiatrists poked, prodded and then
published their evaluation of Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder Tyson appears to be content, if not relieved, to
be at Phoenix's gritty Madison Square Garden. There's nothing
pretty about the place, but there is some hard-edged honesty in
knowing that the surroundings are ruled by a well-placed punch
instead of parliamentary procedure.
</P>
<P>
   It's anybody's guess as to whether Tyson's new-found home will
help him rebuild his life and career. He says it will.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just thankful to be alive, to be here and not be in the
penitentiary'' he said last week. ``A lot of people would have died
if they had lived my life. You know what I mean? I've abused my
life, sometimes. But, right now, I'm pretty much happy.''
</P>
<P>
   You only can speculate at what all the trouble has done to
Tyson's instincts. As history's youngest heavyweight champion more
than 10 years ago, he was without a hint of self-doubt. He went
about his business in a way that was both frightening and
fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   But a prison stretch, followed by the humiliation of biting
Evander Holyfield's ears and public disclosure of his psychiatric
report, are elements that have had to alter the single-minded
purpose that characterizes great fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Distractions often defeat the best ones long before the first
punch ever lands.
</P>
<P>
   At 32, this looms as Tyson's last chance at redeeming his
career. And redemption is another mark of greatness. The defining
moment can come in the ring when a fallen fighter climbs off the
canvas and wins. Or, in the larger sense, it can come in a career
that appears finished. Tyson has met his moment.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the first hurdle is Botha. He's slow. He figures to be
there when Tyson stages one of his trademark assaults. But Botha is
in no Peter McNeeley, Tyson's first foe out of prison. Botha has
faced ranked heavyweights, including former World Boxing
Association champ Michael Moorer. What's more significant about
Botha, however, is an evident lack of fear. He will fight back. A
willingness to do so was the start to Holyfield's two victories
over Tyson. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Briefly . .  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dueling news conferences: Two are scheduled for Thursday in Los
Angeles. One, for Botha-Tyson, is supposed to be at the Century
Plaza Hotel. On Sunday, Don King, Tyson's ex-promoter, decided to
stage one at the Grand Olympic Auditorium to announce
Holyfield-Lennox Lewis on March 13.
</P>
<P>
   A sparring partner, Salvador Jasso, for both Oscar De La Hoya
and Ike Quartey has this to say about their welterweight clash on
Feb. 13: ``Ike will knock you out with two or three punches, but
Oscar, he's fast and turns his hands at the last second so it
hurts. Oscar surprises you and then explodes in your face.''
</P>
<P>
   A Valley card is scheduled for Dec. 8 at Midnight Rodeo, a
west-side nightclub. A possibility is a 12-rounder between Mexican
bantamweight Oscar Calzada and American Francisco Rodriquez for a
minor title.
</P>
<P>
   Home Box Office did a nice bit on Michael Carbajal Saturday
night during a telecast of Kosta Tyszu's victory over Diobelys
Hurtado. The cable network said Carbajal did more for the lightest
weight classes than anyone ever has. It's no coincidence that
attention and purses for 108-to-122-pound fighters have shrunk
since the retirement of Carbajal, whose comeback is in limbo. He
had hoped to fight in late October, but the date has been delayed
repeatedly. &QL; 
Norm Frauenheim can be reahed at norm.frauenheim(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 0202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
