<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-NOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REF'S CALLS NEVER SEEM TO GO IN MOORE'S FAVOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Once again, the replay showed Rob Moore being
victimized by a bad call on a pass play in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals receiver seemingly had sliced between Kansas City
Chiefs cornerback Dale Carter and free safety Jerome Woods for a
37-yard touchdown reception from Jake Plummer that would have cut
the Chiefs' lead to 31-24 with 8:33 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   One member of the officiating crew, standing in front of the
play, raised his arms. After a huddle with his crew, referee Larry
Nemmers ruled that Moore was out of bounds and declared the pass
incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   Replays showed that Moore was inbounds. The Cardinals eventually
scored on the drive, but it took an additional 2:26 to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Two games earlier, with the Cardinals rallying from a 28-0
deficit against Dallas, Moore appeared to have been interfered with
in the end zone by cornerback Kevin Smith on the game's final play.
The replay confirmed it then, too. But there was no call. Instead
of getting one play from the 1-yard line to try to send it to
overtime, the Cardinals lost, 35-28.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told that Rob landed out of bounds,'' Cardinals Coach
Vince Tobin said. ``That's not what people are telling me who saw
it on the replay. Obviously, we would have liked to have had that
2{ minutes back at the end of the ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to score. If it truly was a score and you get it
taken away from you, you have to expend that much more energy to
score again. It just seems to be a series of plays the past few
weeks that have been very, very close _ and most of them have gone
against us.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore, who banged up a shoulder and will have it x-rayed this
morning, didn't want to join in the ref-bashing. After making seven
catches for 75 yards and a touchdown in another losing effort, he
was drained.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any question that I caught it
inbounds,'' Moore said. ``The first thing I did was look down at my
feet. They were in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the coach I'm not going to complain, I'll let him do
it. I don't want them (the refs) to hate me any more than they
already do.''
</P>
<P>
   Streak intact &QL;  &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have only one more chance to beat an AFC West team
this season.
</P>
<P>
   They dropped to 0-3 against the AFC West after their 10-point
loss to the Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   In September, they were routed, 33-14, by Seattle and beaten,
23-20, by Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals end the regular season at home against San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Streak intact II &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the victory over the Cardinals, the Chiefs extended their
winning streak over NFC teams to 10 consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   Their last loss to an NFC team was on Thanksgiving Day 1995 at
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Short shots &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Ronnie Anderson, activated for the second
consecutive week, had his first career reception, an 8-yard grab
late in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Kwamie Lassiter, who made his first start of the season at free
safety, forced a fumble. He has four interceptions, four forced
fumbles and one fumble recovery this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs' five sacks was their most since 10 against Oakland
in the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Steve Schoenfeld also contributed to this
article. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
