<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-INJURIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEDNEY'S LOSS A KICK IN CARDS' TEETH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ It's fourth and 4 and the Cardinals need a
45-yard field goal for a win that puts them into the playoffs for
the first time in 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   Who's going to kick it?
</P>
<P>
   It won't be Joe Nedney, who helped launch their midseason
turnaround with game-winning field goals at Detroit and against
Washington. Nedney on Sunday suffered what is believed to be a
season-ending torn anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee in
the loss to Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was blocked and I just got twisted up,'' Nedney said. ``My
foot was planted, I got hit and my body went the other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel a snap. It was more like paper crumpling. I can
put weight on it. It doesn't feel bad. They're saying it's worse
than it feels.''
</P>
<P>
   Nedney will have a magnetic resonance imaging performed on his
knee today to confirm the diagnosis by Cardinals orthopedist
Russell Chick.
</P>
<P>
   So who will be the Cardinals kicker?
</P>
<P>
   It could be Pete Elezovic, the former Michigan kicker who was in
Tampa Bay's preseason camp before being released.
</P>
<P>
   Or Scott Blanton, who was released by the Redskins early this
season. He owns a career-long 53-yard field goal. Or Scott Bentley,
who was in the Cardinals training camp in 1997 and also spent time
with the Braoncos and Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Or veteran Eddie Murray, 42, who has big-game experience but
clearly is on the downside of his career. Murray was on the Dallas
Cowboys' 1993 Super Bowl team and Detroit's 1991 squad that played
in the NFC championship game. His weakness is distance on kickoffs.
There isn't anyone else on the roster who could perform kickoff
duties effectively. The new kicker will have to be able to do all
the placement kicks as well as kickoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Nedney's is the latest in a growing list of critical setbacks
for the team during the stretch drive. Middle linebacker Ron
McKinnon, who is having the best season of his short career with
five pass interceptions, suffered a strained right knee. It won't
be known for a few days whether he will be able to suit up Sunday
when the Cardinals try once again to beat their former offensive
coordinator, Jim Fassell, and his New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon's backup, Mark Maddox, did not suit up for the second
straight week (knee). A weakness at middle linebacker wouldn't
escape the attention of Fassell, whose club has pounded the
Cardinals three straight times.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Rob Moore will have a shoulder x-rayed this
morning. His injury is not believed to be serious.
</P>
<P>
   And then there remains the question regarding defensive tackle
Eric Swann, who is contemplating another knee surgery that would
shelve him for the remainder of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Nedney, a left-footed kicker who made a 37-yard field goal
Sunday and then missed from 50 into a swirling wind, suffered his
injury on a kickoff after his extra point with 6:07 left cut the
Chiefs' lead to 31-24.
</P>
<P>
   An offside call against the Cardinals on the play forced them to
rekick. Scott Player, their punter who kicks ``five to 10 balls a
week'' to be ready for such emergencies, got the call. He squibbed
the kickoff down the middle of the field. The Chiefs fell on it at
their 33-yard line, then drove for a touchdown that iced the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was real quick,'' Player said of the turn of events.
``That's the first time I'd ever done it in a game at any level.
But they ended up with the ball where they'd been getting it all
day. It just functioned as a squib that took them out of a big
return.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardinals' defense had made the stop, and if their
offense had scored to make it a one-point game, Player would have
gotten the call for the extra-point try to send it to overtime,
according to Coach Vince Tobin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never done that, either,'' Player said. ``But I think I
could have made an extra point. A field goal, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6-6, the Cardinals can afford no more than one more loss in
their quest for the playoffs. Given their wild finishes in the past
five games, they well could be in a pressure-cooker, late-game
situation that calls for a field-goal, or a kickoff to pin a foe
deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a huge loss,'' special teams coach Al Everest said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 0207EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
