<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4019 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-DEFENSE     11-30 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-DEFENSE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIXED BAG AT CORNERBACK  
 CHAVOUS INTERCEPTS PASS IN DEBUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Cardinals' defense offered non-stop
service to yet another destination on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Corey Chavous was given his first pro start at cornerback
in hopes of shoring up a secondary that was riddled the week
before. While Chavous' third-quarter interception against the
Kansas City Chiefs stopped a threat deep in Cardinals territory, it
was the Cardinals' only defensive stop of the closing half. The
Chiefs scored on four of their first five possessions to secure a
34-24 win.
</P>
<P>
   A week earlier, right cornerback J.B. Brown was the fall guy
when the Cardinals let Washington score on six successive
possessions that wiped out a 31-0 lead. The Cardinals survived,
45-42, but in the wake of the scare, Brown was out. Since Tom
Knight was not ready to play on his sore hamstring, Chavous, a
second-round draft pick, was in.
</P>
<P>
   Chavous described his debut as uneven.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had chances to make plays late in the game, but we didn't
step to the plate defensively,'' Chavous said. ``We couldn't get
the ball back. I gave up a touchdown pass in a critical situation.
Playing corner here is a lot different than playing it in college,
but when you cover Frank Sanders and Rob Moore every day in
practice, you're going to be ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``As members of the defense, we're all accountable. The last
couple of weeks, we have not done the job sustaining and finishing.
Unfortunately, we're giving up too many big plays in critical
situations. We've got to do a better job getting off the field on
third down. We had trouble stopping the run, so that made the
play-action pass available to them the whole second half. We never
did stop that.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Chiefs' second possession of the third quarter, Chavous
ended a scoring threat when he stepped in front of wide receiver
Andre Rison and picked off Rich Gannon's pass at the Arizona 4.
Chavous fell as he tried to return the interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish he could have gotten up quicker, because it looked like
he had a lot of room to run,'' Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardinals, who fell to 6-6 with the loss, are going to
challenge for an NFC wild-card playoff spot, the defense has to
regain the dominance it showed earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin said he saw enough flashes in Chavous' play to make him
believe there are good days ahead for the Vanderbilt product.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made an excellent play on that interception,'' Tobin said.
``He released under the wide receiver and made the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got beat a couple of times, but anybody is going to get
beat at that position. For his first game there, he played well.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Chavous was in position to tackle Chiefs receiver
Derrick Alexander early in the fourth quarter. Instead, Alexander
faked Chavous and ran past him for a 15-yard touchdown pass play
from Gannon.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Alexander became the Chiefs' first receiver in four
years to have more than 100 yards in back-to-back games (six
catches, 116 yards, two touchdowns).
</P>
<P>
   Chavous wasn't entirely at fault. For the second straight week,
Pro Bowl left corner Aeneas Williams shared in the roast on several
occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Chavous, a second-round draft pick, played cornerback in
college, but his duty with the Cardinals had been at safety until
he was moved last week. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
