<HEADLINE>
GEORGIA EDGES LONGHORNS IN LAST SECONDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ These days at Texas, progress on the basketball
court is measured by the degree of a loss.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns, off to their worst start since opening 0-6 in
1974, failed to get off a decent shot in the waning seconds last
night and fell to once-beaten Georgia, 78-77, before 6,024 fans at
the Erwin Center.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Texas (0-4) lost at No. 11 Arizona by 16 on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a great effort for Georgia to beat us tonight,'' UT
coach Rick Barnes said. ``I really feel for these guys. They're
working hard and they're starting to understand. We've gotten
better the last two weeks. It's amazing. We're going to be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Short-handed Texas might not turn the corner as quick as Barnes
hopes. Forward Kris Clack, who suffered through a 3-for-18 shooting
performance, scored Texas' last two baskets, but dislocated his
right shoulder during the game's final sequence and will be
examined today.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Clack's bad night and the fact that 7-foot sophomore
center Chris Mihm continues to struggle, Texas had the ball and a
shot at winning after Georgia guard G.G. Smith sank two free throws
for the one-point lead with 9.3 seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   Gabe Muoneke, who scored a game-high 23 points, threw the
inbounds pass after Smith's second free throw to point guard Ivan
Wagner. He brought the ball downcourt and passed off to Clack as
designed. But Georgia, wary of the 6-5 senior after he twice gave
the 'Horns a one-point lead in the last minute with baskets in the
paint, quickly closed with three players.
</P>
<P>
   Clack dished back to Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cut backdoor and felt like I had an easy layup _ until my
\Rleft\S shoe came off,'' Wagner said. ``I lost my balance and
couldn't regain it, so I just threw it up.''
</P>
<P>
   His desperate offering never cleared the rim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a crusher,'' said Muoneke, whose 19.7-point average leads
Texas through four games. ``I love this team's performance. We've
worked extremely hard and we're starting to see the benefits. It
takes time to get acquainted to a new system where it becomes
second nature. But no one has his head down.''
</P>
<P>
   Mihm left the game with 3:22 with severe leg cramps after
scoring 12 points, but eight of those came from the free-throw
line. He had five rebounds _ but seven turnovers _ and Texas
actually played better with seldom-used Marlon Drakes, who made all
four of his shots.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore center Robb Dryden led Georgia with 22 points. Smith,
son of former Bulldogs and now Kentucky coach Tubby Smith, scored
16. Muoneke's defense helped limit star sophomore forward Jumaine
Jones to three points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think Texas is about to bust out and I told our
players that before the game,'' Georgia coach Ron Jirsa said.
``They played well enough to beat us tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
