<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HORSE-FUTURITY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUMONT COUPLE EYE `QUIET' TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ When Carl Schrontz and his wife, Laurel,
entered their first horse in the NCHA Futurity last year, they
thought they would quietly maneuver through the cutting horse show.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't happen. Their mare, Some Kinda Memories, ridden by
Mike Mowery of Millsap, won the open division title in dramatic
fashion at the National Cutting Horse Association's premier show.
</P>
<P>
   The Shrontzes, of Beaumont, may not quietly leave the 1998
Futurity. During the first go-round last night at Will Rogers
Memorial Coliseum, Mowery, turned in an above-average score of 216
aboard Ravishing Ruby, the second horse that the Schrontzes have
entered in the Futurity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize that lightning doesn't strike twice, so we want to
progress through this show quietly,'' Laurel Schrontz said.
</P>
<P>
   The 216 `quietly' will advance Mowery and Ravishing Ruby to the
second round after the first round ends tonight. The second round
is scheduled tomorrow and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to be solid,'' Mowery said of his first-round
run. ``I was trying to build confidence in my mare.''
</P>
<P>
   Mowery must advance Ravishing Ruby through two more rounds in
order to gain the final _ the second round and the Dec. 12
semifinal. With that in mind, Carl Schrontz said he isn't looking
too far ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just glad to get every step of the way,'' he said.
``Every step is a milestone. Every point of elimination is big to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he has never owned a horse that was eliminated at the
Futurity, Schrontz said competing in the show can build character.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very humbling event,'' Schrontz said of the open
division, which features 499 horses. ``If you don't believe in
humility, cutting will teach it to you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Schrontzes said they began investing in the cutting horse
business four years ago with the intention of competing in the
Futurity. But they declined to enter the show after they could not
find a suitable horse.
</P>
<P>
   When they shopped for a horse for last year's Futurity, Mowery
recommended Some Kinda Memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It indeed was some kind of memory,'' Carl Schronz said of
winning the Futurity and watching the mare earn approximately
$185,000 during the 1997-98 season. ``We came as the underdogs.''
</P>
<P>
   With NCHA Hall of Fame member Mowery on their 1998 Futurity
horse and their name in among the list of champions, the Schrontzes
have nowhere to hide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
