<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4031 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-WINNINGD     11-30 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-WINNING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICE DAY FOR A DRIVE 
</HEADLINE>
 DRIVE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ When New England offensive coordinator Ernie
Zampese sent the perfect play down from the press box, and when it
was radioed to Drew Bledsoe in the huddle, and when the words
calling that final play came out of Bledsoe's mouth, Bruce
Armstrong felt good. As good as he's felt in six days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that one play, and I know it's designed to roll to the
right and get a couple of people open to the right,'' said the
Patriot tackle. ``And one of those two is Ben ... and I'm always
feeling pretty good if it's going to go anywhere near Ben, because
Ben is going to make the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm betting my paycheck on a play, Ben's the guy I'm
betting on.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an exquisite call, as Bledsoe tried to pull off his
second straight Drive. The numbers on the scoreboard clock were
down to ``:00'' and all was riding on one play to transform the
drive into The Drive. Chaos was everywhere but in the New England
huddle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were thinking run,'' said Patriots back Robert Edwards of
the Patriots' lining up in a strong run formation with two backs,
three tight ends, and no wide receivers. ``It was a strong run
formation and I knew it was a great call, because I knew they were
thinking run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had used the same play against New Orleans, when Ben scored
there, too, and when I heard the call I knew it was a great call.
Ben was wide open in the back of the end zone in New Orleans,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very composed in that huddle, sort of just like
practice,'' said fullback Tony Carter, the other Patriot who would
roll out to the right, along with Coates, as a potential receiver.
``You could tell by looking in everybody's eyes; everybody was
ready. And it happened ... just like practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Smith was one of the many Bills who was thinking ``run''
and Edwards was so determined to make his run fake look good ``that
I did it almost too good because I was trying to make it look like
a run so much their guy almost got by me, the guy I was blocking,
and he slid by me and he got to Drew's feet. But Drew had gotten
rid of the ball and ... ''
</P>
<P>
   And it was floating toward a wide open Coates in the deep right
corner of the end zone, yards clear of Buffalo linebacker Marlo
Perry. As usual, the Patriots' tight end said little after the
game, little to explain how he got open, but what he said was so
typical of the way he plays.
</P>
<P>
   Was he surprised at the call?
</P>
<P>
   ``Kind of .... sort of,'' said Coates. ``But (Bledsoe) called
it, it worked, and now it's time for me to go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Patriots were explaining, Coates was told, that the play
was designed to go to two Patriots, Carter or Coates.
</P>
<P>
   Coates raised an eyebrow and responded, ``There's only one
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was one of the few, the very few, who never saw Coates
catch that final pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just knew there was one guy who wasn't going to get to Drew
on that play and I was locked up pretty good with that guy (Bruce
Smith) on the play,'' said the tackle. ``But ... I heard. I heard
that roar.''
</P>
<P>
   Coates's reception was preceded by what seemed to be the
Patriots' final play of the game. A Hail Mary pass from Bledsoe
toward three Patriot receivers in the left corner of the end zone,
26 yards between the end zone and the line of scrimmage. Terry
Glenn went up for the pass, it bounced off his pads, and the game _
briefly _ seemed over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know what happened, except I should have had
the ball,'' said Glenn. ``It was an open shot, an open opportunity
to make the play and I should have made it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry made a great effort to go up for that ball and I know he
wishes it was a play he would have made,'' said Bledsoe. ``So that
we wouldn't have had to have the last play.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Terry go up for the ball,'' said Armstrong, some 30
yards from the play. ``And when he went for the ball, I saw Terry
get hit, and when he got hit, the hit changed his body position. He
was ready to catch it and when he got hit, the ball ricocheted off
his pads. No, I never saw the flag; I'm just thinking, `Damn, he
should have caught the ball.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Bills owner Ralph Wilson saw the flag. Just before that pass
to Glenn, said a furious Wilson, ``I told my daughter `They're
going to throw it in the end zone and the (officials) are going to
call pass interference.' I wish I could play the stock market like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn said he was aware that pass interference had been called
but he was too angry at himself to be happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I said, I should have had that ball,'' said the receiver.
``I was happy they called that penalty but I should have made that
play.''
</P>
<P>
   So, back-to-back plays ending back-to-back-weeks with
last-minute game-winning drives have raised appreciation of Bledsoe
in New England. And this victory with a broken finger, this one
with Doug Flutie the miracle-maker on the other side, and now it
was Bledsoe, not Flutie, who had pulled out the miracle. Just as
last week it had been Bledsoe, and not Miami's Dan Marino, who had
signed onto the signature drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without sounding arrogant, no, I haven't surprised myself the
last two weeks,'' said Bledsoe. ``This is a situation that I've
always enjoyed and always loved and I expect to win games in these
situations. And when it doesn't happen, that's when it's a shock to
me. Talk about the Pittsburgh game in the playoffs last year, when
we didn't win that game, that was a shock to me.''
</P>
<P>
   And that it came with Flutie on the opposite sideline?
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the way Doug is appreciated around here and he
deserves it. And I'm not jealous of his popularity one bit,'' said
the Patriot QB. ``He's a legend here and he deserves that but, at
the same time, I'm the quarterback of the New England Patriots and
people who come to these games hopefully will cheer for our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, none of this could have happened without yet another
Shawn Jefferson fourth-down catch, this time it was unclear whether
Jefferson (a) actually had caught the pass inbounds on the right
sideline and (b) whether he had traveled far enough for a first
down. Flutie said several Bills heard the officials on the sideline
say, ``Just give it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   But, now, after back-to-back winning drives, nothing may have to
be given to Bledsoe in the final moments of games that have to be
won. If a new aura surrounds him, he has earned it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
