<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 08:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4274 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-BIGBOOKS-KAN &LR;      11-30 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-BIGBOOKS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATCH FOR THESE GREAT COFFEE TABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Book publishers seem unable to keep from printing more and more
coffee table books about less and less. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Years ago you'd get big books called something like ``An
Illustrated History of the World'' that would pretty much describe
everything important from Piltdown Man to the Great Society. (Oh, I
know Piltdown Man was a fraud, but much the same has been argued
about the Great Society. And what is history if not a recounting of
how humans have defrauded one another?) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But nowadays no topic is too small to be excluded from being the
subject of a book all by itself. Thus for holiday giving this year
we can find such books as ``The Year of Liberty: The Great Irish
Rebellion of 1798.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm not saying this late 18th century uprising of Irish
Catholics wasn't an important landmark in the history of human
miscalculation and violence and not worth recounting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All I'm saying is that this new book by Thomas Pakenham (which I
haven't read and may never) is more proof that the focus of more
books is getting narrower. In the case of this Irish rebellion, the
focus is one year, though no doubt in the book Pakenham goes back
to, say, 1795 and the founding of the Orange Society and such. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, given this funneling trend, I think it's possible to
predict some of the coffee table books we may see offered the
future. Here are some of the titles I expect to see next year: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Irish Elk Fossils: What They Say About Antler Size.'' This
richly illustrated $49 volume will answer for all time nearly every
still-unresolved question about genus Megaloceros. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A Comprehensive Atlas of Kamloops Maps.'' Here for the first
time _ and for just $75 _ the editors have collected the historical
maps showing the development of the city of Kamloops in southern
British Columbia, from 1813 to 1862. Volume II, covering 1863 to
1946, is expected within a year. Publication of Volume III, from
1947 to the present, is dependent on the sales of the first two
volumes (which should be high, given this vital plug). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Diabetic Dogs of Bernardo Alberto Houssay.'' The world
has long been waiting for details of the dogs this Argentine
physiologist turned diabetic by excision of their pancreases in
experiments from 1924 to 1937. This $125 volume reveals the entire
story. Also available on tape and CD. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Compleat Book of Pickerelweed.'' Although this aquatic
plant of the Pontederiaceae family is common in the eastern part of
North America, not until publication of this $45 scratch-and-sniff
volume has such an exhaustive look been offered. It contains an
accurate and up-to-date list of pickerelweed-related Web sites. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Oxpeckers: Africa's Yellow- and Red-Billed Tickbirds.''
Haven't we all admired how oxpeckers cling to large African animals
and remove ticks and maggots from their hides? Here, for only $89,
is a graphically pleasing volume describing what makes them tick
(and, for that matter, what makes them tickbirds). Some proceeds
from each sale will go to the International Oxpecker Preservation
Society. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Inspector General Years of Jean-Gaspard-Felix Lacher
Ravaisson-Mollien.'' Finally we get the details of the time this
19th century French philosopher spent as France's inspector general
of higher education. The book includes the 1892 self-portrait of
Ravaisson-Mollien that hangs in the Louvre and the very short list
of people who have both seen it and known who he is. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
