<SLUG> BC-R-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Nov. 27, moved Saturday and are repeated Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Moved in `a' category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-REVIEW (Undated) _ The problem with the $206 billion
tobacco settlement, say economists and legal experts (as opposed to
anti-smoking advocates), is that 99 percent of the $206 billion is
a disguised tax hike. Taxing cigarettes more heavily may be a good
idea, but labeling a tax on consumers as ``damages'' being paid by
Big Tobacco is fraudulent. The deal forces citizens of modest means
to subsidize well-heeled lawyers and wealthy owners of cigarette
companies. By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-REVIEW (Washington) _ The upcoming effort by Congress and
the Clinton administration to reform Social Security could as
easily end in partisan gridlock as in the historic achievement both
parties are hoping for. The debate encapsulates fundamental
tradeoffs: between individual and collective responsibility, market
forces and government, and maximizing rewards and minimizing risks.
By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRIC-CARS-REVIEW (Washington) _ Once upon a time, 1998 was
going to be the year of the electric car. But now it seems an idea
whose time has been put on hold. The technology behind electric
cars improves yearly, but the cars themselves fail to attract
buyers. Experts say the reason is they are not as flexible as
gasoline cars, and policy-makers have become reconciled to gasoline
as engines have become cleaner and oil cheaper. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH-BOOKS-REVIEW (Undated) _ At the height of its global
ascendancy, supposedly optimistic and youth-obsessed America is
also fixated on death. A sampling of recent books on death and
bereavement.
</P>
<P>
   RENO-COUNSELS-REVIEW (Washington) _ The independent counsel law,
enacted to keep politics out of high-level corruption cases, has
been a constant source of political trouble for Attorney General
Janet Reno, but it has probably helped her keep her job. By David
Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   EXPECTATIONS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Wherever a plan is hatched based
on rational expectations of other people's expectations, it rears
its head, decreeing that the very result that the plan is designed
to prevent will in fact come to pass, quickly and inevitably. Put
more scientifically, expectation of an expectation alters the
expected expectation. By David Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   INTERVIEWERS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The recent batch of electronic
interviewers and celebrity subjects drawn together by the Lewinsky
affair sometimes seems like a parody of Spy magazine's gallery of
improbable doppelgangers, ``Separated at Birth'' By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Moved in `i' category
</P>
<P>
   DICTATORS-REVIEW (United Nations) _ The arrest of Chile's
Augusto Pinochet and the British ruling upholding it may have
opened a new era in the practice of international human rights law.
The decision falls into what had been almost a legal vacuum, making
it all the more interesting to human rights specialists.
International norms have been laid down broadly in human rights
conventions, but there have been no universally agreed definitions
and procedures. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-MIDEAST-REVIEW (United Nations) _ Diplomats watching for
Saddam Hussein's next move sense something profoundly different in
the Iraqi air. Some Arab and Western experts now see signs that he
is more isolated in the region than at any time since his 1990
invasion of Kuwait, which drove fellow Arab nations into backing
the U.S.-led coalition in the Gulf war. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-GUILT-REVIEW (Berlin) _ A fierce debate has erupted
about the place of memory and the shame, if any, that young Germans
should feel for the crimes of their forebears. Germany has broached
such issues before; but in its scope, openness and vitriol, the
current discussion appears to be without precedent. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINIANS-AID-REVIEW (Jerusalem) _ Monday's opening of a
U.S.-sponsored conference of international aid donors to the
Palestinians is a reminder of just how far they have to go before
achieving economic independence. By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-EUROPE-REVIEW (Istanbul) _ For generations, even for
centuries, Turks have debated how to relate to Europe and, by
extension, the Western world. In recent weeks the issue has been
brought to the fore again, this time by an extradition dispute over
a fugitive Kurdish rebel leader. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
