<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 09:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4295 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN02-CO     11-30 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Democracy, at a snail's pace, wavers
 &HT;    (For release Dec. 2, 1998.)
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is obvious that democracy doesn't work everywhere, not
quickly, anyway. And not without a lot of help from the outside.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a poll showed that 51 percent of Romanians feel life
was better under their previous Communist government _ a government
so harsh that one of the first things Romanians did after gaining
their freedom from communism was to try and execute their former
Soviet-buttressed dictator Nicolae Ceausescu.
</P>
<P>
   Only 43 percent of the Romanians questioned said life was better
since communism was torn down in the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   This example is not unique. A host of former Communist nations
of Eastern Europe are struggling with their new lives, embroiled in
ethnic clashes and economic quicksand.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the days after the close of World War II when the United
States rushed in with a humanitarian Marshall Plan to rebuild the
destruction and rejump the economy of a battered Germany, but only
the Western Sector, the former Communist states are more left on
their own to restructure.
</P>
<P>
   This is not so much because of a change of economic heart by the
U.S., but because there are so many of them. Switching overnight
from a Communist to free-market economy is like learning to eat
with your right hand after eating with the left all your life.
</P>
<P>
   The dissatisfaction with instant democracy is not confined to
Romania. A dismembered Yugoslavia, no longer under the benevolent
dictatorship of Tito, rips itself into ethnic pieces that are
incapable yet of understanding the formula that a good economy can
cure almost all that ails you; just ask Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The states of the former Soviet Union, particularly Russia, are
reeling under democracy. Russia's economy is unstable and the
Russians who see prices skyrocket with each sunrise begin longing
for the days when bread was plentiful, prices paltry and the only
real price you had to pay was to stay clear of the KGB.
</P>
<P>
   I recall a person I met in what then still was East Germany just
several weeks prior to the rejoining of the two Germanys. She was
frightened of the future. She was going to lose her stipend as a
teacher under the Communist system and her salary was going to be
lowered. Yet, her rent was about to be doubled and food prices
increased.
</P>
<P>
   The denominator of life for her was economy. How would she
survive?
</P>
<P>
   I will presume she has because she was a bright woman, but would
she be one of those who longs for a return to a life that was no
better than spartan but at least dependable?
</P>
<P>
   This week Romania celebrates, under duress, 80 years of
unification, although much of that history was served under the
Soviet heel. There is a question as to what to celebrate. Reforms
are slow, privatization of industry is undergoing a reluctant
metamorphosis.
</P>
<P>
   Emil Constantinescu, the democratically elected president, has
not been able to deliver what he promised: speedy reform. And
because he has not, there is grumbling _ and a longing for the bad
old days of Ceausescu, on the premise that a loaf of bread in the
hand is a decent price to pay for loss of freedom.
</P>
<P>
   It is a growing concern among the struggling nations of Eastern
Europe, not insignificantly in Russia, where parades of red banners
are becoming larger and more frequent these days.
</P>
<P>
   The American economy may be sailing along in a spacious suite,
but well to the east and to the south, things are hardly as rosy.
An Eastern Europe, economically stagnant for close to half a
century, is beginning to look backward. And to the south,
particularly since the vast destruction caused by Hurricane Mitch,
the economic needs of impoverished people are overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   How can we help all of them? That's a good question. We, as a
nation, need to sit back and look at our new surpluses and wonder
if it does better for us to keep them in our hands or use them to
brace and vitalize wavering democracies that still are teething on
the system.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
