<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer questions
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where exactly is the Oval Office in the White House complex?
I believe it is now on the first floor of the West Wing, not in the
main house. It used to be on the second floor of the main building,
overlooking the South Lawn. When and why was it moved? _J.C.B.
</P>
<P>
   A: Southeast corner, West Wing office building.
</P>
<P>
   The Oval Office was never in the White House per se, notes
William Bushong,historian at the White House Historical
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The Oval Office was built in 1909 in the West Wing office
building, in the center of the southern extension. The only office
the president occupied previously was on the second floor of the
White House (a rectangle, not an oval room). The West Wing offices
were constructed when Teddy Roosevelt came into office complete
with a large family. The shape of the new office was based on the
tradition of oval walls _ suitable for formal introductions.
</P>
<P>
   As the presidency grew, so did the need for more space. In 1934,
during President Franklin Roosevelt's administration, the West Wing
office building was expanded and the Oval Office moved to the
southeast corner.Q: Osama bin Laden is always referred to as a
``multi-billionaire.'' What is the source of these riches? _Olin D.
</P>
<P>
   A: Bin Laden is a construction engineer whose father gave him a
starter bankroll _ part of a $5 billion inheritance he shares with
his siblings. Bin Laden is one of 52(count 'em) children of a Saudi
construction and oil billionaire.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the shelf life of those little ketchup and mustard
packets you get at fast-food joints? We have got tubs of them here
at work, and some must be ancient. _Steve B.
</P>
<P>
   A: According to the Heinz consumer line at (412) 237-5740, most
of these packets should probably go. The ketchup package has a
shelf life of six months; mustard, eight. No date is on the packet;
it is on the packet box. Doesn't do much for the fast-food muncher.
</P>
<P>
   Condiment king Henry Heinz began with bottled horseradish while
still keeping his day job as a brickmaker. According to ``So Who
the Heck was Oscar Mayer,'' Heinz developed his famous ``57
Varieties'' slogan after seeing an advertisement on a New York
elevated train for ``21 styles'' of shoes.Q: In which years was
Eddie LeBaron the quarterback for the Dallas Cowboys?
</P>
<P>
   _J. Jones
</P>
<P>
   A: (No, J. Jones is not Jerry Jones.) Edward Wayne LeBaron Jr.
attended high school in Oakdale, Calif., and college at the
University of the Pacific. The diminutive (5' 9'', 168 lbs.) passer
led the Cowboys from their inaugural year, 1960, through 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In June the television show ``Interior Motives'' featured
slipcovers. This was for seasonal changes using bedsheets without
the expense of re-covering furniture. The decorators used
innovative techniques including tools to tuck and pleat material.
Is there any written information available from that show? Where
can I purchase tools to re-cover a couple of old chairs I have? _L.
Rebstock
</P>
<P>
   A: Slipcover instructions are not available from ``Interior
Motives.'' But I did find a simple set of instructions from Nancy's
Notions to share with you and readers. (Send a stamped,
self-addressed envelope to Nancy's Notions, P.O. Box 683, Beaver
Dam, Wis. 53916, attention: slipcover instructions.) The
instructions advise using sheets or wide-width fabrics and include
illustrations for all-thumbs girls like me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When the District of Columbia was created as the home of the
federal government, it was a perfect square, roughly half given by
Maryland on the north side of the Potomac and the southern part
donated by Virginia. At some point Virginia reclaimed its part (now
Fairfax County), leaving what we have now. When and why did
Virginia take its land back? _J.C.B.
</P>
<P>
   A: The site for the 10-mile square District of Columbia was
selected by George Washington and donated by Virginia and Maryland.
The Virginia portion remained part of the District for more than 50
years, according to the Virginia Historical Society. In 1846,
Congress retroceded (gave back) the Virginia portion, returning
Alexandria _ both the city and county _ to the state of Virginia.
District residents living south of the Potomac River voted in favor
of the change. Historians note there was concern over the
abolitionist movement gaining strength in the nation's capital as
well as the Old Dominion's need to finance construction of the
Alexandria Canal, says Becky Ballou of the Perry Castaneda Library
reference desk.
</P>
<P>
   Q: On the news last spring I heard about a local lady who had
very old stocks that turned out to be worth a good sum of money. My
grandmother passed away and left many old stock certificates I
would like to find out about. Could you help?
</P>
<P>
   _A.R.
</P>
<P>
   A: Many stockbrokers could help you. But it sounds like you need
a stock search company like R.M. Smythe. Send a photocopy of the
front of the certificate and a check for $75 per issuing company
(not per stock) or a credit card number to 26 Broadway, Suite 271,
New York, N.Y. 10004, Attn.: Caleb. There is a 20 percent discount
for five or more companies. In about a week you will have an
answer. Even if the stock is no longer valid, they may have value
as collectibles. In either case you will know. Good luck!Q: I am
trying to locate a movie, ``The Egg and I,'' with Fred MacMurray
and Claudette Colbert. I want to get it as a Christmas present for
my sister. _Peggy L.
</P>
<P>
   A: Colbert and MacMurray star as the MacDonalds in this 1947
version of the same old sordid tale of woe: Husband buys abandoned
chicken ranch in the country; wife hates country life. Pick up a
copy from Reel at (888) 707-7335.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have three American Airlines tickets issued in July 1996.
The tickets are in three different names and state ``no
refund/change fee of $50 plus fare difference.'' Are these tickets
still exchangeable according to the above restrictions? Can anyone
use them or only the people whose names are listed on the tickets?
Can another family member use them? Or combine all three for a
single, higher priced ticket? _K.T.R.
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Most of our non-refundable tickets are reusable and have
been since 1992,'' says spokesman Tim Smith. The value of the
ticket may be applied to a future itinerary minus the change fee
(presently $75). Smith said if the change fee American Airlines
placed on the ticket is $50, it will be honored. No, you may not
change the name on the ticket, nor can one person combine the three
and go to Europe.Q: I would like to have an address for director
Lynda Obst, who lives in Fredericksburg. I have a World War II
story I would like to send to her. _C.H.
</P>
<P>
   A: The executive producer of ``Sleepless in Seattle'' and
producer of ``One Fine Day'' vacations in the Hill Country and has
many friends in Fredericksburg. Write to her, however, in care of
Lynda Obst Productions, 10201 W. Pico Blvd., Building 43, Los
Angeles, Calif. 90035. Proceed with caution regarding any idea you
plan to share. Many producers do not accept unsolicited ideas.
Document anything you send (certified letter) for your own
records.Pet stain guru Jane Fish of Source Menagerie says one of
the best tools for blotting up Fido/Garfield misses and messes is
bed underpads, like the ones made by Depends. Pick up a box in the
incontinence section of the store. This is absorbent material.
Makes sense. Keep some sort of absorbent material at the ready _
perhaps under a chair cushion in every room. Cloth diapers work
well. These are handy to attack a spill or accident as soon as it
happens.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane S. Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, Texas 78767;
(512) 445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512)
445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   For copies of Jane's book, ``Thanks for Asking!'' _ a
compilation of more than 600 favorite questions and answers _ call
(800) 424-6291.
</P>
