<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wrestling world may be fake, but it's so much fun to watch
 &HT;    By Ana Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The mattresses had been pulled off my son's bunk bed and placed
strategically on the floor. A chair was stationed a few feet away.
</P>
<P>
   The television was blaring.
</P>
<P>
   There was a wrestling match on the screen and one in his
bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the world of Nitro. There's Monday Nitro, Thursday
Nitro and Saturday Nitro. Joaquin, who is 12, tells me we could
have even more if we'd only upgrade our cable service.
</P>
<P>
   We used to call it ``rasslin'' back when it was on TV only on
Saturday night after the news or when a tour materialized at the
high school gym.
</P>
<P>
   They've prettied it up a lot. Now it's diversified, modernized
and glamorized.
</P>
<P>
   Aficionados can cheer wrestlers aligned with WWF, NWO, NWO Black
and White and NWO Wolf Pack.
</P>
<P>
   My son and his buddies are diehard fans. The summer evening when
I discovered the mattresses on the floor, he and Ryan were
practicing their leaps from the chair onto the mattresses.
Telephone conversations between the two do not concern girls, but
big sweaty guys with names like Goldberg, Sting and Disco Inferno.
</P>
<P>
   They have their own moves. A fellow called The Raven uses ``DDT
The Evenflow.'' You place your opponent in a headlock and then fall
backward and, Joaquin said, ``it kind of crunches their neck.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch. Makes Fritz von Erich's Sleeper Hold seem pretty lame.
</P>
<P>
   Wrestlers may also fall victim to moves such as Outsider's Edge,
Scorpion Deathlock, the Pile Driver and the Diamond Cutter.
</P>
<P>
   Many girls disdain wrestling. Joaquin says his female classmates
waste their time watching music videos. His sisters rag on him.
``Why do you watch this? It's fake.''
</P>
<P>
   His elucidating response: ``So?''
</P>
<P>
   His comments to his mom's gentler questioning: ``It looks like
it's real sometimes, and sometimes it really looks fake.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, it's apparently entertaining teen-age boys and adult
males as well. Though few care to admit it, the signs are there.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's dad seems awfully willing to host the boys for
Pay-Per-View matches. Another dad consented to drive a group to a
wrestling exhibition in Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   And Joaquin's dad has participated in tag team watching.
</P>
<P>
   Because Joaquin and Ryan both love wrestling and also have
parents who demand homework be done, they have discerned a watching
strategy since school started.
</P>
<P>
   TV wrestling is like a soap opera. If you miss one match, you
might miss the beginning of a new feud or the reconciliation of
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The other night, I asked if Joaquin's reading was complete, and
he informed me he would finish it at 8.
</P>
<P>
   Why not now?
</P>
<P>
   Because Joaquin's wrestling watch was from 7 to 8 while Ryan
finished his homework, I was informed. Then, Ryan's watch was from
8 to 9 while Joaquin finished his.
</P>
<P>
   A shower had to be taken before 8, though, and Joaquin assigned
his dad to watch and make sure that The Warrior, a newcomer and
probably future star, didn't make his entrance while he was in the
shower. Instructions were to call him immediately if the
trench-coated Warrior showed up.
</P>
<P>
   Next thing I heard was a commotion. ``Something's happening,
Joaquin!''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, the television crowd was in an uproar, as was the
crowd at my home.
</P>
<P>
   The Warrior had appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Ana Walker is managing editor of the Longview (Texas)
News-Journal. E-mail: awalker(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
