<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Checkbook a symbol against complexity
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At some point, our heads are just going to explode. We
will reach a point where we will have to remember so many
passwords, phone numbers, deadlines and e-mail addresses that our
skulls won't have any room left. We'll try to cram in one last Web
site address and our brains will blow up.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this is not medically possible, but I can't think of any
other outcome. The pace of human evolution cannot keep up with our
need for more brainpower. A cranial eruption seems more likely than
an awakening in the corporate world, which refuses to see that
consumers can't absorb any more complexities.
</P>
<P>
   Our nervous systems were built to deal with the pressures of
finding bananas and hiding from big animals in the prehistoric
wilderness. We were not wired to spend hour after hour trying to
comprehend the details of natural-gas utility deregulation to
choose the cheapest provider.
</P>
<P>
   But here we are, wandering through an economy that demands far
too much of us. Increasingly, we are running up our white flags.
For example, millions of Americans have given up preparing their
own taxes, or even changing the oil in their cars.
</P>
<P>
   We don't understand our computers or video recorders, and now
our phones require elaborate owners manuals. The formerly simple
task of paying the phone bill has turned into an IQ test. I have a
local bill, a long-distance bill and a cell-phone bill. I study
them each month to determine whether I'm getting ripped off _ and I
never really know.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few weeks, the Georgia Public Service Commission
will rule on a rate case that may lower electric bills and lay the
groundwork for deregulation of the industry. If competition comes,
rates will go even lower. That will be good for my purse. But for
my overworked brain, deregulation will bring another bewildering
array of choices.
</P>
<P>
   When I first started working, paying bills took maybe five
minutes once a month. I'd pay the rent (which included utilities)
and the phone bill. Now, a blizzard of bills blows at me
constantly, with white envelopes and six-page billing explanations
piling against the back of my desk like snowdrifts. The typical
middle-class family has bills for cable TV, Internet access,
pagers, cell phones, two or three vehicles, insurance, the
mortgage, the mortgage insurance and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   Last week The Wall Street Journal wrote about growing consumer
resistance to this billing complexity. The banks would like for us
to begin paying for goods and services with online banking, smart
cards, debit cards and other electronic devices. The story noted
that 15 years ago, the Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta published an
article entitled ``Displacing the Check.'' The report predicted
that check writing would virtually disappear in the 1990s as
consumers switched to electronic payments.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of disappearing, checks are growing in number. This
year, 65 billion checks will be written, twice as many as 20 years
ago. I believe people write checks because checks make sense: You
write down the name of the person who gets the money and fill in
the amount. You don't have to remember more passwords or use new
technology.
</P>
<P>
   For a while longer, we may cling to our checkbooks as a protest
against complexity. But in the end, we won't win. Banks will boost
checking fees so high that eventually, we'll switch to
electronic-payment vouchers. And the deregulation of electricity,
natural gas, phone service and cable will bring more bills to pay
with these more sophisticated devices.
</P>
<P>
   Our only hope may be duct tape. Maybe if we can wrap the tape
tight enough, our heads won't burst.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mgeewax(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax is a member of The Atlanta Constitution editorial
board.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
