 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No 2503 - November 30, 1998   NEWS AND
FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2503 -- Nov. 30, 1998 We are offering the
following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. THE EXECUTIONER'S TRAIL For five years Michael McQueen tried
to uncover sufficient evidence to bring to trial Aleksandras
Lileikis, head of the Lithuanian security police in the Vilnius
province under the Nazis. Lileikis, a retired printer now living in
Massachusetts, was one of the worst mass murderers of World War II.
Finally, on a 1993 trip to Lithuania, McQueen found the
incriminating documents he was seeking. Steven Levingston tells the
tale of the relentless efforts of MacQueen and others to bring
Lileikis, who is standing trial in Massachusetts this month, to
justice. From The Boston Globe Magazine. Full-length (4,900 words)
+ edited article available.
_______________________________________________________________ 2.
TAKING THE STARCH OUT OF STATUS Status used to be all about
exclusion. Not any more. Most notably, there has been a decline in
the once-all-important element of WASP reserve. By Charles McGrath.
From The New York Times Magazine. 1,000 words. 3. HOLLYWOOD, D.C.
With the Clinton glitzkrieg, status has a new calling card in the
nation's capital. By R. W. Apple Jr. From The New York Times
Magazine. 1,500 words. 4. RYTHM AND IRON A popular new
weight-training program, BodyPUMP, is fun, high-energy and set to
music. It's aerobic dancing with weights. The program was developed
in New Zealand and introduced in U.S. fitness clubs this year. By
Andrea Billups. 500 words + photos.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
FROM MEDICAL TRIBUNE NEWS SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   A. Tips For Fighting Computer Strain In Older Eyes As eyes grow
older, they become less tolerant of the computer-screen stare, but
optometrists say some easy steps can ease the problem. 350 words.
B. How To Make Sure This Holiday Season Is A Happy One If this is
the season to be jolly, why are so many people unhappy?
Psychologist Gayle R. Berg explains how to beat holiday depression.
500 words. C. Tips For Fighting Wintertime Colds and Flu Several
steps can help people avoid catching a cold or flu, ease symptoms
and speed recovery time. 300 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
IDEAS FOR INEXPENSIVE, EASY-TO-MAKE HOLIDAY GIFTS Gift-giving is
one of the most enjoyable parts of the holiday season, but choosing
presents for everyone on your list can be a considerable challenge
to a budget. One solution is the assembly-line gift : The basics
are the same for each package, but you can personalize the details
for its recipient. By Martha Stewart. 1,000 words + photo. 7.
DICTATORS DON'T SIMPLY WALK INTO THE SUN The arrest and detention
of Augusto Pinochet is serving a purpose, far beyond warming the
hearts of the thousands of friends, relatives, and colleagues of
his victims. Beyond its ethical and legal implications, the
dictator's detention reveals many of the contradictions and deeper
truths about how societies move from authoritarian to democratic
rule, and how they settle scores with a past that never should have
existed. By Jorge G. Castaneda. 1,000 words. 8. From THE NEW YORK
TIMES BOOK REVIEW A. Engineering An Icon : A biography of Marilyn
