<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Society needs better handle on pharmaceutical fixes for
childhood
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Another day at Apothecary Elementary. Jason,
George, Alex, Samantha and Sandy are on Ritalin. Mary is on
lithium. Thomas is on Welbutrin. Horace is on Luvox.
</P>
<P>
   An observer is left to wonder if the harried school nurse is the
one who needs medication the most.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar tells his teacher, ``I need my medicine to control
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry gets frantic at noon one day when it's time for his
Ritalin and the nurse, who's tending to a playground wound, hasn't
a free hand to get into the locked medicine cabinet. Jerry's state
of anxiety is not due to chemical withdrawal but the fact that his
parents have convinced him that without his pill he will be a mess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how many times I have heard a student
desperate to take his or her medication at the exact time it has
been prescribed because if it is late, 'I won't be able to be
good,' or 'I won't be able to keep myself from doing bad things,'''
related a Waco educator.
</P>
<P>
   There's no sense jumping to any conclusion about Jerry or any
students like him. The clinical consensus is that some children
need medication to deal with severe behavior problems. For some
children with attention deficit-hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) and
other clinical problems, medicine is a godsend. For others
misdiagnosed or mildly afflicted, however, a pill may doing a poor
job of what counseling, parental discipline or, maybe, decent
nutrition, basic nurturing and stability at home would.
</P>
<P>
   Hooked on Ritalin
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, unlike the popularity of breakthrough remedies that
assure more people get treated for medical conditions and fewer
suffer, the escalating number of American children on Ritalin is
cause for concern rather than for relief.
</P>
<P>
   The global breakdown of Ritalin use may be the most telling flag
raised on this issue. Ninety percent of the Ritalin prescribed on
the planet is used in this country. That's whole continents that
deal with the same problems American parents face in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   Experts who gathered in Bethesda, Md., to discuss Ritalin use
came away with the consensus that Ritalin does work.
</P>
<P>
   But the real issue is the difficulty of diagnosing the problem
for which Ritalin is the answer. Parents are urged to seek multiple
opinions from physicians before turning to medication to solve a
child's behavior problems.
</P>
<P>
   Too often underlying events are society's quick-fix penchant:
the pining for a magic pill to make things better.
</P>
<P>
   Making the medication fit the need is only one challenge within
the scope of the uniquely American condition, highlighted on the
cover of last week's Time magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Let's talk
</P>
<P>
   The other issue is informing and involving parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents and children need to be educated about the 'power' of
mood-altering medication,'' said the educator to whom I spoke.
</P>
<P>
   She suggested that as a prerequisite for a school nurse assuming
responsibility for medicating their children on a daily basis,
parents be required to attend a workshop featuring a medical expert
or, at minimum, a talk by the school nurse.
</P>
<P>
   The key purpose of such a workshop would be to convince the
parents that medication alone can't be the cure-all for behavior
problems.
</P>
<P>
   A talk from a professional would be a useful experience for the
parents who participated. Those who didn't would have to come to
school to medicate their children. So doing, they would get an
eye-opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``A visit to the nurse's office in any elementary school around
noon would give an idea of the huge number of children lining up,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
