<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Auto-related gifts can fit the individual
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ready, set, CHARGE!
</P>
<P>
   It's here at last, the biggest shopping season of the year.
Millions of people will embrace the thrill of holiday gridlock
traffic, followed by the chance to implement their keenest
mall-parking-lot battle strategies. Whether you choose to be a
player or an observer of this seasonal American sport, no one has
been granted immunity from the pregame hype that has been around
since Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   While I make it a rule never to pass a Salvation Army pot
without leaving a contribution, the seasonal bell ringer at the
membership warehouse caught me by surprise last week.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the store, the aisles displayed this year's solutions to
gift-giving dilemmas. Amid the talking wreaths and dancing Santas,
automotive accessories (after all, nearly everyone has a car, don't
they?) made a prominent showing.
</P>
<P>
   I browsed through the prepackaged car gifts section thinking how
generic they all seemed. If I were going to give a car gift, I
would want it to be practical yet personal, fitting the needs of
the individual. Here are some suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   For those with vehicles having altered suspensions, either
raised or lowered, a set of tires is nice. These vehicles cannot be
correctly aligned, so they wear out tires. Of course wheel bearings
and axle (CV) joints tend to self-destruct at an equally rapid
rate, but the repair of these items normally requires professional
intervention. Let them pay for the repairs. Tires can be
gift-wrapped.
</P>
<P>
   Add-on accessories, including high-output sound systems or light
kits, keep a vehicle's original equipment electrical system living
on the edge. Their insatiable electrical appetites _ added to
normal winter use of wipers, heater, rear window defroster and
headlights _ inevitably will turn on the little red ``Bat'' or
``Alt'' light on the dash.
</P>
<P>
   When this electrical collapse occurs, wouldn't it be nice to
have the parts handy to make the repairs (until the next time)?
Some of the discount parts places sell lifetime alternators. These
come in an easy-to-wrap box, and when it quits again, it can be
exchanged for a new one. (Be sure to include the receipt.)
</P>
<P>
   Auto parts stores also sell batteries, cables and repair manuals
with instructions on how to change the parts. This thoughtful gift
will be remembered year-round.
</P>
<P>
   Do you know someone whose vehicle leaves a fluid-leak calling
card whenever it is in your driveway? How about giving them a drip
pan? These large, shallow pans also are available at auto parts
stores. Insist that they carry it in the trunk and use it when
visiting.
</P>
<P>
   Some of my personal favorites are wiper blade inserts, a bottle
of Rain-X, pocket magnets and pocket screwdrivers.
</P>
<P>
   So you really don't need prepackaged car gifts. Use your
imagination. Match the gift to the personality. Besides, you have a
much better chance of finding a parking space at the auto parts
store.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter, who has 26 years of experience in the auto repair
industry, is an automotive instructor at DeKalb Technical Institute
and an ASE master automobile technician/L-1. Write her in care of
Wheels, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta,
GA 30302. Or send comments online to
nora(at)admin2.dekalb.tec.ga.us or 2wrenchs(at) bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
