u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD01-COX     11-30 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woodworking and the Internet
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I get regular messages from readers who want to know
what this rec.woodworking thing from which I'm always quoting is,
where to find it and how to participate in it.
</P>
<P>
   So this column will not be about woodworking, but about
computers.
</P>
<P>
   First, the basics. The newsgroup, or usegroup, called
rec.woodworking is part of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Within that vast, chaotic sea of information and misinformation
called the Internet, rec.woodworking is part of the Usenet. It has
nothing to do with the World Wide Web. Nor is it a chat group.
</P>
<P>
   It is a newsgroup where people interested in woodworking post
messages, sort of like a bulletin board. Let's say you're a novice
and you want to get a new router. You might go to rec.woodworking
to seek the advice of the old hands.
</P>
<P>
   You would do that by posting a message containing your question.
Everybody who visits the newsgroup will see your question. Those
who wish to give you the benefit of their wisdom, or lack of it,
will post replies. Their replies may engender responses from other
visitors who agree with them, or who think they're full of sanding
dust.
</P>
<P>
   This exchange of messages in response to an original post is
called a thread. But I'm getting ahead of myself. Most of my
correspondents on this matter appear to be on the Internet, but
they have apparently never heard of the Usenet.
</P>
<P>
   If you can access the World Wide Web, you should be able to look
at any newsgroup.
</P>
<P>
   If you are browsing the Web with Netscape or Microsoft Explorer,
you can use either of them to get into newsgroups.
</P>
<P>
   Neither is optimal, but they'll certainly work, and a lot of
people use them for that purpose. If you have a dedicated
newsreader such as Eudora, use it.
</P>
<P>
   I am not going to tell you how to do this with Explorer, because
I do not use that program. It is an excellent program, to be sure,
but I have an involuntary reaction to have something thrust down my
throat, which is what Microsoft is trying to do with Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   So I use Netscape, and I expect Explorer will work much the
same.
</P>
<P>
   First, the program must be set up properly. If you pull down the
Options menu in Netscape, you will see a choice labeled Mail and
News Preferences.
</P>
<P>
   Select that, which will bring up a tabbed box. Pick the Servers
tab.
</P>
<P>
   Here you tell Netscape where to go to get your e-mail, if you
wish it to do that, and, more to the point here, where to go to
find newsgroups.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, I can't tell you what to put in these blanks.
Your Internet service provider _ the outfit to which you pay money
every month in order to reach the Internet _ can tell you that.
Call its help line.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've got that done, close Netscape and then reopen it. Go
to the the Window menu and select Netscape News.
</P>
<P>
   This will bring up a window that looks a lot like the original
Netscape window, but it's the one you'll use to access
rec.woodworking.
</P>
<P>
   If you pull down the file menu, you'll see a choice called Add
newsgroup. If this is grayed out, look in the subwindow
(windowpane?) titled News Server, and highlight the selection that
has the same name that you entered as the server in preferences.
Now the Add Newsgroup selection under the File menu should be
available.
</P>
<P>
   Select it, and you'll get a dialogue box. Into this box, type
``rec.woodworking'' _ without the quotes. In a few moments, the
current messages in the group should appear in the upper right
pane. Select one, and it will appear in the wide bottom pane.
</P>
<P>
   Newsgroups are an amazing source of information, but try not to
ask people for stuff you can find out just as easily for yourself.
You can ``subscribe'' to rec.woodworking. All you need do is
right-click on the newsgroup's name, and select subscribe. Then
every time you ask for a newsgroup window, rec.woodworking will be
there.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find a lot of kindred souls hanging out there.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
