<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Help available for handling holiday traffic
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like many metropolitan areas, Atlanta's roads and
freeways are often filled to the point of gridlock. And now that
the holiday season is beginning, travel is even more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, the Web can help. In some cases, you'll be
able to avoid a trip altogether by visiting a store or organization
using your computer. Other Web sites can give you traffic and
weather information that will make your trip less stressful.
</P>
<P>
   One of the complications of getting around a large city is
locating your destination. Even people who have lived in Atlanta
for years occasionally need a map or driving directions. One of the
best ways to find almost any address is by going to Yahoo!'s
excellent map site at http://maps.yahoo.com/py/maps.py. You will
get a small but usable map, and you can also get turn-by-turn
driving directions.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing how to get there is just part of the equation. If
traffic is heavy, you may decide to postpone the trip or take
another route. One way to check traffic is to blunder forth
blindly, listening to the traffic reports on the radio as you go.
Then, when you get stuck in an impossible traffic jam, you will
have the rich satisfaction of knowing why you aren't moving. Or,
before you leave home or work, you can check one of the traffic
cameras that update every minute or so and provide a live view of
traffic conditions at several locations. One good one is maintained
by WSB-TV at
</P>
<P>
   http://www.accessatlanta.com/wsbtv/trafficcams.html.
</P>
<P>
   One little slip or extra push of the gas pedal can earn you an
unexpected meeting with the Atlanta police, which maintain a page
at http://www.atlantapd
</P>
<P>
   .org/. You'll find telephone numbers for various units of the
police and contact information. Or, if you're just nosy, you can
click on the link called Busted and find the names of people
arrested for drug- and sex-related offenses. The theory here,
according to the Web page, is ``the age-old method of public
embarrassment. The message is simple: Anyone caught buying or
selling drugs or sex in Atlanta risks seeing their name here.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most frustrating trips in town can be attempting to
drive to Hartsfield International Airport and then find a parking
space. You'll get some help at the airport's official site,
</P>
<P>
   http://www.atlanta-airport.com/index2.html. Not only will you
find information about parking conditions, you'll also be able to
get a live camera view of traffic around the airport. And if you
are planning a trip by air, or picking up a traveler, you can use
the link on the Hartsfield page to get the latest flight
information, or you can go directly to the page at
</P>
<P>
   http://www.infaxinc.com/WebFIDS/ATL/.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, it's easy to take the train, whether you're going to
the airport or just to one of the shopping malls. You'll be able to
get schedule and route information from the official page of MARTA,
the Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority at
http://www.itsmarta.com/. You'll find an excellent system map as
well as all you'll ever need to know about the rail system.
</P>
<P>
   If all else fails, you can always walk. If you'd like to learn
about a few short hikes in and around Atlanta, check out the
Gorp.Com Web site at
</P>
<P>
   http://www.gorp.com/gorp/location/ga/ruatlan.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
