<HEADER>
A4365 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-MEDIA01-COX     11-30 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MEDIA01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mac experts pick CDs suitable for giving
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ What's a good Macintosh CD to give as a gift? The
December issue of MacWorld has some ideas. This issue contains the
magazine's annual holiday roundup of the best reference and
entertainment software for the Mac. Among its recommendations is
the Complete MasterCook Suite, an interactive cookbook. Another
pick is Kid Pix Studio Deluxe, the venerable computer art program.
And, for young kids, MacWorld recommends ``Pajama Sam 2: Thunder
and Lightning Aren't So Frightening.'' This is a learning game from
Humongous Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   The holiday season is a hot time for new computer CDs. Companies
tend to issue lots of new titles to take advantage of the big
buying season. Not all, however, are games. Nor are all of them on
CDs. This year you'll be seeing more DVDs _ the trendy new digital
versatile disc format that holds much more data than a CD. Because
these discs can store more than twice the amount of data, it's
possible for them to do a better job with multimedia functions.
Among the new DVD titles are IBM's ``World Book Discoveries: The
Student's Multimedia Guide to World History.'' It features 5,400
images, seven hours of sound and more than 900 animations. The disc
lets you search, copy, export and print text and images. ``World
Book Discoveries'' is designed as a homework aide for kids. It's
available only for PCs running either Windows 95 or Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   In the game department, Microprose is releasing another ``Top
Gun'' title, ``Hornet's Nest.'' This is a combat flight simulator.
You play a maverick young navy pilot flying an F/A-18 fighter jet.
There are 30 missions and three overall campaigns. Play against the
computer or others online. ``Hornet's Nest'' is available only for
PCs running Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   Parents, are you looking for a kid site not driven by one of the
big entertainment companies? Then check out Kids On-Line America,
or the KOLA Network. It's commercial but directed toward kids,
education and teachers. The site's content is screened carefully.
You'll find all kinds of stuff here, including chat rooms, bulletin
boards and e-mail features. The site is divided into six
communities: junior, kids, teen, senior, parents and teachers.
You'll find KOLA Network at http://www.kola.net.
</P>
