<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A fitting room just like home
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You're caught in the middle: You hate holiday season
mall traffic but you like even less the idea of buying clothes you
haven't tried on. If that describes you, a Web site that belongs to
Lands' End might have your answer.
</P>
<P>
   New to the site at http://www.landsend.com this year is a
feature called Your Personal Model, which lets women create a model
somewhat tailored to their body size. You can use the virtual model
to ``try on'' clothes, seeing how they lay across a body type
similar to yours.
</P>
<P>
   The option is only available to women, because Lands' End found
women were more likely than men to want to see how something fits.
Return shoppers can store their personal model dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   For men, there is a feature called Oxford Express, which lets
men sort through hundreds of dress shirt options. They can
customize their search based on size, color, fabric, collar and
style.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lands' End, most of the people who buy from the
company's online site do so while at work. The peak time is
Wednesday. The top shopping day for catalog shoppers is Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A site that examines interest
</P>
<P>
   They do it for Beanie Babies, so why not mortgages?
</P>
<P>
   MortgageAuction.com is a site where you can see if you can get a
better mortgage rate than the banks are offering, at least
according to the folks who run the site. Interest rates are the
lowest they have been in years, so there is a lot of interest in
interest these days.
</P>
<P>
   It takes about 10 minutes to fill out the forms on this site.
Then you are notified within 48 hours if your application is
accepted. Little pain, some potential gain.
</P>
<P>
   Call up http://www.mortgageauction.com and the site walks you
through five steps, including filling out a mortgage profile, a
personal financial information form, property and loan information,
and your monthly expenses. Then the information is sent off for
competitive bidding among mortgage lenders.
</P>
<P>
   The site is free. All information is protected with encryption.
</P>
<P>
   Some hot tips on e-mail
</P>
<P>
   Hotmail, a free Web-based e-mail company, is offering a few tips
for sending and getting safer e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   Tips include:
</P>
<P>
   Change your e-mail password often. Using a combination of
letters and numbers is best.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds obvious enough, but they recommend not sharing your
password. Most system administrators will not ask for your
password, nor should you give it to anyone who asks over the phone
or via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Don't open attachments from people you don't know. Attachments
can bear computer viruses.
</P>
<P>
   Remember to log out when you're done. Do not reply to spam
e-mail. The folks at Hotmail recommend you take it one step further
and forward the unsolicited e-mail to the customer service
department of the sender's Internet access provider. This name is
usually in the domain part of the e-mail address. Most Web-based
e-mail services offer ways to weed out unwanted e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Use an up-to-date browser. Newer versions include security
features.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, they suggest using common sense. Be careful not to
reveal personal information, such as your home address or phone
number.
</P>
<P>
   The pointers can be seen online at http://www.hotmail.com.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing online
</P>
<P>
   You've seen the college kid order one from his dorm room on the
television ad. Now, the Fall 1998 issue of Money.com offers tips on
how to make sure you get a good deal on a car you buy on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The article says 25 percent of all new-car buyers use the Web to
gather information during the shopping process. Internet car buying
sites only account for 1 percent of all new-car purchases. General
Motors is expected to have a Web site up in 1999 that will let
customers get price quotes and check inventories. Sites for online
car shopping include http://carsmart.com,
http://www.carpoint.msn.com and http://www.autobytel.com.
</P>
<P>
   To help guide your purchase, Money.com offers these tips:
</P>
<P>
   Check the manufacturer's site. It saves time and lets you gather
information you normally would have to go to a dealership to find.
</P>
<P>
   Look at consumer guide sites, such as http://www.edmunds
</P>
<P>
   .com or http://www.kbb.com.
</P>
<P>
   Decide how many options you want, look for rebates and pick your
target price.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the magazine suggests getting financing approved first.
It helps you stick to your target price.
</P>
