<HEADER>
A4370 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHARP-DRIVING01-COX     11-30 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A little pressure goes a long way
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The weekend after Thanksgiving is often filled with
football, shopping and leftovers. You may not think it the best
time to worry about tire pressure, but this is the time when the
last thing you need is tire failure or an accident. Either will put
a significant dent in your holiday budget.
</P>
<P>
   During two days of torrential rains recently, I made a trip to
Nashville. The vehicle I was driving had the same brand and model
tires I have on my personal vehicle. When I found the tires were
more than willing to hydroplane on a moment's notice, I made a
mental note to check tire pressures at my next stop, knowing this
was not the norm with these tires. A quick look led me to believe
they were a bit on the low side, and the tire gauge proved me
right.
</P>
<P>
   Most drivers don't know what an enormous impact just seven
pounds of air pressure can make in a vehicle's performance. Aside
from the tendency to hydroplane, the car started to push or
understeer out of one corner. This should never happen at
reasonable speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, to get a car to understeer as much as the one I was
driving would require a speed in triple digits. The other major
effect of under-inflated tires is a loss in braking capability.
With much standing water, I found that under moderate-to-heavy
braking, my vehicle actually felt like it was floating forward.
</P>
<P>
   What caused all these problems? Just a few pounds of air
pressure. When you combine low pressure with heavy rain and a
surface that is well oiled from traffic, much less than seven
pounds will make a big difference.
</P>
<P>
   When a tire is under-inflated, the tread _ whose main purpose is
to disperse water _ is pushed up off the road by water pressure.
This makes the tires' contact area, the part that actually rests on
the pavement, more concave than flat, so the car is riding on a
small stream. When the contact patch is pushed up, the treads are
pushed together like when you clamp your fingers together. This
provides a broad, flat area for the water to run under and greatly
accelerates hydroplaning action. This is also why under braking, my
car felt as if it were floating. It pretty much was.
</P>
<P>
   When tire pressures are set on the high side, it spreads the
tread apart like stretching your fingers apart. The larger space
between the treads results in increased water dispersion.
</P>
<P>
   Proper air pressure also establishes the correct sidewall
strength. Under heavy cornering, a soft sidewall will roll under,
which results in push or understeer. Look at the sidewalls of a
police car. They will be almost vertical, and the contact patch is
a bit crowned. That is because law enforcement vehicles usually
increase the recommended pressure by as much as 10 pounds to reduce
understeer in high-speed situations.
</P>
<P>
   Your owner's manual will suggest the proper tire inflation for
your vehicle usually in a range, say 32-36 psi. The higher psi will
give you a slightly more harsh ride, but it will improve your car's
steering and reduce the risk of hydroplaning.
</P>
<P>
   I adjusted the air pressure in the vehicle I was driving to two
psi over the recommended amount. The result was an entirely new
vehicle. No hydroplaning, no understeer and perfectly straight and
narrow braking. There is a small downside, however. Moderate
over-inflation can cause tires to wear prematurely in the center.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, your tires are the instruments through which all
communications between your vehicle and the road surface take
place. One of the best gifts you can give yourself and your family
is safety. Proper tire pressures only take a second and can help
save a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp is a training consultant to auto manufacturers. Her
column is written exclusively for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
Write her in care of Wheels, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Or send comments online to
sharpdriver(at)worldnet.att.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
