<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bad hair days go beyond teen-age years
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ It's 7:30 _ much too early in the morning and
too late in my life to have to put up with the foolishness a bunch
of 13-year-olds lay on me five days a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``OOO! Gross!'' Cindy giggles and points to my head. ``Ms.
Schuett, your hair is sticking out!'' She appears to be amazed when
I don't head for the nearest mirror and leap into corrective
action. ``Aren't you going to fix it?'' I ask what she has in mind
short of half-a-day at the Beauty Bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dunno,'' she allows, ``but if my hair stuck out like that, I
wouldn't come to school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why they pay me the big bucks,'' I remind her, ``so I
have to show up no matter what's sticking out.'' She gapes, so I
add, ``...within reason of course.''
</P>
<P>
   Now would be one of those ``teaching moments'' that educators
who educate educators love to extol. It would be an ideal time to
do the lecture thing about values, but it's too early in the
morning and I have too much to do. The parable will have to wait.
Instead I tell her to relax and suggest that maybe ``sticking out
hair'' is not the end of the world as we know it. Of course, that
doesn't mean I can't remember when I thought it was.
</P>
<P>
   As I go about responding to a brace of irrelevant memos the
office can't seem to live without, and hastily scratch a regrets
note to the organizers of a pot luck lunch informing them that the
last time I took a dish to such a function, the school suffered the
highest faculty absence rate in its history, I can't help
chuckling. This kid doesn't know from bad hair. I grew up in Bad
Hair City, USA - Miami, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Picture this: It's bedtime, 1948, and a scrawny, wild-maned
13-year-old sits cross-legged on her bed peering into a mirror she
has propped against the pillow. It's decision time - homework or
hair. No contest. She begins fiddling with her hair. Up? Down? Over
one ear? One eye (it works for Veronica Lake)? Both eyes?
</P>
<P>
   She has no recourse. It's either the Dippity-Do (gelatinous pink
hair setting glop) and pincurl routine or social ruin. She drips.
She slathers. She twists and pins. The whole time she prays to the
god of teenage hair. ``Oh please, Lana
</P>
<P>
   Turner, make my hair look just like yours when Clark Gable saved
you from the enemy tank in `Homecoming.' And if you can't do that,
please make it last at least until after second period when I have
algebra with that gorgeous guy in the red shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Every night it was the same routine. Every morning, the same
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   The best I could hope for was twenty minutes of curls - and that
was on a good day in the winter when the humidity unpegged itself
from the total saturation point. Before I could walk the two blocks
to the bus stop, my hair would have returned to the wild. I would
slouch onto the bus, pretending to be a woman of mystery,
self-absorbed and other worldly. Anything was better than admitting
I was a kid with stupid hair.
</P>
<P>
   For as long as I could remember, all I asked of life was a
portable phonograph for slumber parties, and some curls. My mother
had curls. My father had curls. Even the neighbor's dog had curls.
WHY NOT ME?
</P>
<P>
   ``Bug out,'' I tell the giggling adolescent hanging over my
desk, ``I have more
</P>
<P>
   important stuff to do than put up with your foolishness.'' I
waggle my hand in the direction of the door and can't hide the
chuckle welling in my throat. The kid I'm picking on thinks exactly
the way I did 50 years ago - only now there's no excuse for it.
</P>
<P>
   When I was her age, girls were supposed to be all curly and cute
and you could definitely tell the sexes apart by the length and
style of the hair. Today, there's so much latitude in hair styles
that girls can keep their cool whether they choose long and lank,
or a '90s version of Crewy Lou in the old Dick Tracy comic strips.
I was born half-a-century too soon.
</P>
<P>
   My diminutive tormentor scoots out to the hall to find a few
friends before the bell rings. Probably to share a good giggle
about the condition of the teacher's hair. A quick glance around
the room ensures me I'm alone. I whip open the bottom desk drawer,
prop a little mirror against my Riverside Shakespeare, and reach
for the standard tools of the trade - a spray bottle of water and a
hairbrush.
</P>
<P>
   Squirt. Brush. I can hardly believe it. Fifty years later, and
I'm still going ten rounds with the bad hair beast.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett, a writer and teacher in Gibsonburg, writes
for Cox News
</P>
<P>
   Service. Her address: 320 West Madison, Gibsonburg, Ohio 43431
or e-mail to eschuett(at)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
