<HEADER>
A4422 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVOR-JANE-HORROCKS-AR     11-30 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-JANE-HORROCKS-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JANE HORROCKS: 'LITTLE VOICE,' BIG TALENT 
</HEADLINE>
  World rights except Great Britain and Australia 
 Color slides and black and white photos of Jane Horrocks in
``Little Voice.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It was such a plum role that the ultra-hot Gwyneth Paltrow had
her eye on it. But British actress Jane Horrocks _ a virtual
unknown in Hollywood _ beat her to the punch.
 &HT;    As a result Horrocks has become a dark-horse Best Actress Oscar
contender for ``Little Voice,'' a British-made fable in which the
spotlight falls directly on the 34-year-old actress, best known for
her role as the ditzy Bubble in TV's U.K. comedy import
``Absolutely Fabulous.''
 &HT;    ``They were going to switch the film from England to America
with Gwyneth Paltrow, but it didn't work out,'' Horrocks said, her
voice brimming with happiness, in a telephone interview from New
York. ``So suddenly the part came back to me.''
 &HT;    In ``Little Voice,'' (opening Dec. 4 in New York, San Francisco
and Los Angeles, and on Christmas Day elsewhere) Horrocks is the
shy daughter of Brenda Blethyn (nominated for an Oscar for
``Secrets and Lies''), fearful of leaving the safety of her room
and her precious record collection. They call her Little Voice but
the girl packs a big talent. She can belt out a song and sound
exactly like Judy Garland, Marilyn Monroe, Shirley Bassey or
Marlene Dietrich _ to name a few.
 &HT;    It's a miraculous feat: Before your eyes Miss Meek is
transformed into a series of charismatic nightclub singers.
 &HT;    ``They had other people in mind for the lead,'' says Horrocks,
``but Jim Cartwright, who wrote the play, insisted he wanted me.''
In fact, she notes, Cartwright penned the play from which the movie
is drawn with her in mind.
 &HT;    ``I was in another play by him and we became friends,'' she
recalls. ``We were in my back garden one day and the subject of
impersonations came up. So I did a few for him. He said he would
write a play around me _ and two years later he did. I was
horrified and frightened to death to do the voices on stage. At the
time I hoped some disaster would come and take it away. But I did
the play for eight months, first at the National Theater then in
the West End.''
 &HT;    In the movie, Little Voice has to contend with her crude, rude
and hard-drinking mother (Blethyn), and with Michael Caine as the
sleazy agent who wants to exploit her talent. Ewan McGregor plays
her telephone repairman boyfriend.
 &HT;    What will astonish moviegoers is that Horrocks actually sings in
the voices of the legendary ladies; no tricks or miming are used.
``It was important to me and Mark Herman (the
screenwriter-director) that I actually sang because if the audience
thinks for a moment that the character is miming then you've lost
them.''
 &HT;    While she was impressive as an anorexic teenager in Mike Leigh's
``Life Is Sweet'' (1991) and has had roles in ``Memphis Belle''
(1990), ``The Witches'' and a slew of TV including her own British
comedy show ``Never Mind the Horrocks,'' the tiny Jane first caught
everyone's attention as the flaky PR girl in ``Ab-Fab.''
 &HT;    She auditioned first for the role of one of the character's
daughter but because she was too old for that part they hired her
to play Bubble. The show featuring the addled antics of a pair of
dipsomaniacs, quickly became a cult hit, and when it came to the
end of its run its devoted fans mourned. Of its future Jane says,
``Maybe they'll do a one-off special,'' using the British term for
a one-time TV presentation. ``The shows work well for 30 minutes
but I think they'd die in a two-hour movie.''
 &HT;    Her part as the dumb Bubble has had a considerable impact on her
career. ``It's made me more of a semi-household name, and given me
a lot of attention. But I'm not massively famous in the U.K. People
sometimes come up to me in the street and say, 'Oh, you're
So-and-so.' But it's not out of control. It's at a very nice
level.''
 &HT;    Unlike Bubble, Jane is no airhead. She lives in suburban London
with writer Nick Vivian and is expecting their second child. She's
not in favor of marriage, explaining: ``It doesn't appeal to me.
I'm happy as I am and feel if it ain't broke why fix it.''
 &HT;    She seems astonishingly natural on- and off-screen, but it
doesn't come as easily as all that. ``Like my character in the film
I'm a sort of reticent performer,'' she says. ``I don't feel
comfortable doing it. I don't consider myself an impersonator. I'm
an actress really. I began doing impersonations when I was about 9.
My parents had all these Shirley Bassey and Cilla Black records and
I was able to imitate them. Friends thought it was amazing so I
became this little party act. Garland and Monroe and Dietrich came
much later. ''
 &HT;    Now almost five months pregnant, (Dylan, her son with Vivian is
l8 months old) she says: ``I don't enjoy working as much as I used
to. I'd like to have more time for the momhood than the work. I'm
very fortunate because at home I've been able to do supermarket TV
commercials which doesn't take me away from home and pays the
bills. I'd love to retire.''
 &HT;    She says that however much she's been praised for her
impersonation, her son Dylan is often less than impressed. ``When I
did a Judy Garland for him he screamed his head off. He much
prefers my Julie Andrews.''
 &HT;    
 c.1998 Ivor Davis  (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter.)  
