<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4511 &Cx1f; tad-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITEHOUSE-HOLIDAY-$A     11-30 1341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITEHOUSE-HOLIDAY-$ADV05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PLANNING CHRISTMAS AT THE WHITE HOUSE IS A YEAR-ROUND JOB
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories for
release Saturday, Dec. 5.
 &HT;    Cox photos for this story have been placed in the National
folder on the Cox server.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a cramped hallway, about eight tiny reindeer
lengths from the Diplomatic Room fireplace, White House cooks were
merrily stamping out gingerbread men on an autumn afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every slow day is a day we use for Christmas preparation,''
explained pastry chef Roland Mesnier, guiding a visitor past this
culinary assembly line. ``If there is an empty corner in the White
House, you will find somebody rolling cookies there.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Santa's elves, some White House staffers regard Christmas
preparation as a never-ending job.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday (Dec. 7), First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton will
unveil the 1998 Christmas theme and decorations at the White House,
beginning a traditional round of seasonal tours and parties at the
presidential home.
</P>
<P>
   During the following three weeks, about 15,000 guests will
marvel at Christmas trees laden with 50,000 lights and handmade
ornaments from across America, hear seasonal songs of musicians
from every state, and consume 50,000 cookies, half a ton of
fruitcake and 250 gallons of eggnog.
</P>
<P>
   Such festivities take a tad of forethought. The fruitcake, for
instance, was baked in June and stacked in refrigerators in
two-pound blocks to await the holiday parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truthfully, right now I'm making mental notes for next year of
what didn't work very well this year,'' said Nancy Clarke, head
florist at the tiny flower shop beneath the North Portico. ``When
Christmas decorations are still up, we start talking as a group
about next Christmas because that's the best time to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly a year-long project,'' agreed Capricia
Marshall, the social secretary in charge of all White House events.
``We start in early January thinking about the theme for that
year's Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   The tradition of a theme for the official Christmas tree in the
Blue Room was begun by Jacqueline Kennedy in 1961. The first theme
was the ``Nutcracker Suite.'' Last year's theme was ``Santa's
Workshop,'' and ornament designer Christopher Radko served as an
artist coordinator to carry the theme throughout the White House.
</P>
<P>
   This year's theme is a secret, but Marshall hinted that it was
``super sweet'' and noted that New York cake designer Colette
Peters is the coordinating artist.
</P>
<P>
   The theme was chosen in February after a series of meetings
between White House staffers and Mrs. Clinton. Mesnier was
consulted on how to portray the theme in the gingerbread house he
makes each Christmas. Clarke envisioned ornaments for the Blue Room
tree. Mrs. Clinton had the final say.
</P>
<P>
   Then the White House enlisted creative people from around the
country _ everything from glass blowers to fashion designers to
needlepoint artists _ to come up with ornaments and decorations.
Governor's spouses helped select artists from their state.
</P>
<P>
   By early summer, Mesnier had begun to prepare the Christmas
party fare. Fruitcake is first because it keeps well in
refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a fruitcake recipe that was designed for the White
House,'' said Mesnier, who was born in France and was working at
the Greenbrier resort in West Virginia when he was hired by
Rosalynn Carter in 1980. ``It has been changed every year since
I've been here. We always try to make it more earthier, if you
will, by reducing the sugar content, the calories and all that. ...
We use naturally dried fruit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people have come to me who swear that they hate
fruitcake. They detest it. But when they taste this one, they
absolutely love it,'' said Mesnier.
</P>
<P>
   Also months ahead of time, an assortment of unbaked Christmas
cookies is cut out and frozen raw. During the party season, ``we
bake them as we go along to serve fresh,'' the chef explained.
</P>
<P>
   Other traditional White House Christmas treats are completed
months ahead and put in freezers. Yule logs are made of coffee
mousse with walnuts and coated with chocolate. There are Christmas
cakes _ a raspberry and chocolate combination, pumpkin cake, double
applesauce cake, and an orange cake similar to pound cake.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all, there will be 120,000 cookies or pieces of cake
served,'' Mesnier estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for this year's gingerbread house were finished in August.
The sheets of gingerbread were baked in mid-November.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gingerbread must be very dry,'' said Mesnier. ``I do not
use any support that is not food. Many people use cardboard or
plastic to support the house. This house is totally food _
gingerbread, chocolate, sugar icing. It weighs close to 150
pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Florist Nancy Clarke can't freeze her creations for later
presentation, but plans decorations down to the last red bow and
poinsettia.
</P>
<P>
   Months ago, she focused her digital camera on all the public
White House rooms. The digital images were converted into
computerized stage sets where the virtual furniture could be moved
around and would-be decorations inserted or removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the easiest way to do it. We have an instant visual,''
she explained. Then she and Marshall, the social secretary, made a
presentation to Mrs. Clinton on proposed Christmas decorations for
each room.
</P>
<P>
   The First Lady ``is very hands-on in the entire process,'' said
Marshall. Once the presentation is made, Mrs. Clinton ``starts
tweaking it. She has wonderful ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Clarke oversees a staff of four fulltime floral designers and 11
part-timers. They are reinforced by 60 volunteers to decorate the
White House for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The volunteers come in the Monday after Thanksgiving. They go
to our warehouse in Riverdale, Md., and start working on bows and
all of the arrangements and getting everything prepared,'' said
Clarke, who was a White House volunteer herself for several years
before being hired by Nancy Reagan in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Everything is readied to move into the White House on the Friday
before the Kennedy Center Honors feting prominent artists, which
are always held on a Sunday (this year on Dec. 6). The decorating
is finished on Saturday night, and the next afternoon the First
Family welcomes the Kennedy Center honorees to a White House
freshly decked out in holiday finery.
</P>
<P>
   This busy weekend requires some precision. Wreaths are ordered
from a company in Oregon _ 168 small wreaths, 92 larger ones. Last
year, 486 feet of garland were draped inside the White House and
another 862 feet on the grounds. The official Christmas tree in the
