<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LASER-POINTERS (San Francisco) _ To prepubescent boys, they're
the coolest gadgets on the market. To school teachers, they're a
vexatious distraction. To unsuspecting drivers, they're a hazard.
And to cops on the street, they are a serious threat. The battle
over laser pointers _ which can beam a red light as far as 1,500
feet _ is no longer child's play. By DIANA WALSH.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-CLEMENCY (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Although California
Gov.-elect Gray Davis would invoke former Gov. Pat Brown's
legendary name on the campaign trail, it's unlikely Davis will
follow Brown's path on one critical issue: clemency for death row
inmates. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COFFEE-TABLE-BOOKS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Coffee-table books are
hardly ever read cover-to-cover, but nonetheless, even though they
are dust collectors or sometimes conveniently hide a table scar,
they can add a touch of class to any room in the house. By FRANCES
INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   NORMAN-ROCKWELL (Stockbridge, Mass.) _ Ye denizens of uber-cool
galleries and jiggy art happenings, admit it you like Norman
Rockwell. It's OK. Rockwell is no longer a guilty pleasure of the
art cognescenti. The time has come when his pictures, the best of
which possess an authenticity and insight comparable to the Old
Masters, are being accepted as fine art. By TIMOTHY CAHILL,
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUYBACKS (San Francisco) _ Aiming to boost their stock
performance, hundreds of corporations continue to buy back their
shares at a torrid, record pace, as investors wonder whether the
repurchase plans are worth it. By EDWARD IWATA.
</P>
<P>
   BENETTON-CATALOG (San Francisco) _ Cover model Hildegard, age 6,
has spiked hair, Down's syndrome and a wonderful blue turtleneck
that bears the message, LOVE. In another brilliant photograph,
Florian, a 9-year-old with cerebral palsy, wears a beautiful brown
sweater as he communicates with his teacher Tanja. Is this 98-page
catalog, showing the fall/winter line for Benetton, the Italian
apparel retailer, cynicism and exploitation run amok? By GEORGE
RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HIP-HOP (San Francisco) _ More white kids may buy rap records,
but the phenomenon of hip-hop culture has created a black urban
economy in the form of jobs for the first post-soul generation. And
hip-hop is not going to die any time soon, according to Nelson
George _ hip-hop's prolific chronicler _ despite wishes by some
adults. By GREGORY LEWIS.
</P>
<P>
   INCA-GOLD (San Francisco) _ If David Ultan and Adam Ballachey
had known two years ago that their lives would be turned upside
down by filming a documentary about cursed Inca treasure, would
they still have done it? ``Absolutely,'' says Ultan. ``It was
tough, and it cost us dearly, but it was worth it.'' By JANE
GANAHL.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-AERATION (San Francisco) _ I think I'd rather play a course
that had its greens aerated two or three weeks ago rather than one
that was aerated four days ago. By SUSAN FORNOFF.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ On the summit of my favorite
Bay Area mountain, Montara Mountain, I kept thinking about how
beautiful, diverse and engaging this region is, even compared to
the Himalayas _ with the Bay, coast and ocean circled by a
greenbelt and a mountain rim featuring a series of peaks that is
accessible to nearly everybody. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CALIF (Long Beach, Calif.) _ Los Angeles, Santa Monica,
Beverly Hills, Disneyland, Long Beach. Long Beach? Until recently,
few people thought of Long Beach among the LA-area's vacation
destinations. But it's now a place with many diverse attractions.
By MARTY RACINE.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ A new miniature museum in
Fredericksburg, Texas, showcases a lifetime's labor of love. By
HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Every time I hear another
Republican echo the Bush brothers and speak of the GOP becoming the
party of ``compassionate conservatism,'' the same image comes to
mind: A group of white folks (wearing very nice clothes and pained
looks on their faces) stand on a sidewalk around a dirty,
disheveled homeless family and chant: ``We really feel sorry for
you _ but it wouldn't be prudent to help.'' By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   GARY-HART (Berkeley, Calif.) _ OK, I know we're all tired of the
subject, but has it occurred to anyone else that this whole
business of the Starrship Lewinsky is the fault of Gary Hart? By
GENE MARINE.
</P>
