<DOCNO> NYT19981130.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 12:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4622 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LASER-POINTERS-HNS &LR;      11-30 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LASER-POINTERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHORITIES SEE RED OVER LASER-POINTER MISCHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DIANA WALSH  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ To young boys, they are the coolest gadgets on
the market. To school teachers, they are a vexatious distraction.
To unsuspecting drivers, they are a hazard. And to police officers,
they are a threat.
</P>
<P>
   Laser pointers _ the pen-sized devices that can beam an intense
red light as far as 1,500 feet _ are no longer child's play.
Several jurisdictions on the East Coast have already restricted the
sale of laser pointers and now the mayor of San Ramon, Calif.,
hopes his town will be the first on the West Coast to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Byron Athan said several drivers have complained recently
about being the target of red-dotting, a not-so-funny game in which
youngsters aim the laser pointers at passing cars, often focusing
on the driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are getting to be a nuisance,'' Athan said. ``We want to
do something before we have any problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Athan has asked the city attorney to draft legislation making it
illegal for children under 18 to use the laser pointers unless an
adult is present. The full City Council is expected to review the
proposal sometime this month.
</P>
<P>
   Such restrictions have already been passed in Westchester
County, N.Y., Ocean City, Md., and Chicago Ridge, Ill. Proposed
restrictions are under review in New York City and before the New
Jersey Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Some restrictions have made it illegal for children to possess a
laser, even if their parents gave it to them, while others have
banned the sale of the devices to minors.
</P>
<P>
   Pen-sized laser pointers, invented as a visual aid for
boardrooms and classrooms, became a toy of choice for adolescents
as the price of the devices dropped from $300 to as low as $8.
Manufacturers have targeted the preteen market by designing
interchangeable attachments that beam red hearts, basketballs, or
naked girls.
</P>
<P>
   Youngsters who own lasers say they are just having a little fun
aiming the lights at the ceilings of their darkened bedrooms or at
outside walls after dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``The light kind of amazes us that it goes so far,'' said Jake
Cohen, 12, of San Francisco, who received a laser pointer as a
birthday present earlier this month. ``We shine it outside and see
how far it can go on buildings. It can go at least three or four
blocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Cohen limits his aim to trees and other inanimate
objects, red dots are showing up on movie screens, at football
games, school dances, on women's breasts, younger siblings and
occasionally the eye of teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have one in my desk drawer right now,'' said Judy Dong,
assistant principal at Hoover Middle School in San Francisco, when
asked whether students take them to school. ``When we see them, we
confiscate them.''
</P>
<P>
   While many red-dot antics are harmless, some are not.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration and the American Academy of
Ophthalmology have issued alerts to parents and school officials
about the risk to eyesight from laser light.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it is unlikely that anyone would be injured by a brief
flash from a laser pointer, it is apparent that children may misuse
them. It is important that parents and school officials realize
that pointers are not toys,'' said Dr. Martin Mainster of the
American Academy of Ophthalmology. ``Adults need to take laser
pointers seriously and not allow children to play with them.''
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen school bus drivers in Florida filed complaints
after being hit directly in the eye by lasers while driving
students.
</P>
<P>
   In Alameda County, Calif., several truck drivers, motorists and
a deputy sheriff reported being unsettled by someone who flashed a
laser onto their cars and sometimes into their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a dazzling effect on the pupil. You get these flashing
lights in your head and it blinds you,'' said Lt. Dave Hoig of the
Alameda County Sheriff's Department. ``If someone gets it in their
eyes and they are operating a two-ton vehicle and can't see ... the
likelihood of an accident or near-accident is great.''
</P>
<P>
   The police say they are unnerved when they are targeted by a red
dot because the dot is identical to the aiming devices attached to
rifles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dean DeJesus, who owns a retail kiosk in San Francisco, stopped
carrying the lasers earlier this month despite brisk sales. He said
he has many friends who are police officers who told him they were
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the decision not to carry them so that my (police)
friends wouldn't fear for their lives,'' he said, ``and because I
couldn't have it on my conscience, as remote as the possibility may
be, that a cop sees the beam and retaliates against a (kid) who was
just out having fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seemed to me that the fun factor was outweighed by the
safety factor,'' DeJesus said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
