<HEADER>
A4633 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COFFEE-TABLE-BOOKS-HN     11-30 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COFFEE-TABLE-BOOKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS CAN BE DECORATIVE EVEN IF THEY'RE NOT READ ALL OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Coffee-table books are hardly ever read
cover-to-cover, but nonetheless, even though they are dust
collectors or sometimes conveniently hide a table scar, they can
add a touch of class to any room in the house.
</P>
<P>
   The size of a coffee-table book is tantamount to seeing a movie
on the big screen. The pictures are bigger and more lush than in
the average-sized hardcover book.
</P>
<P>
   Meals always look more appealing in a coffee-table book. Art
books are sometimes the next best thing to owning the actual works
of art that are beautifully captured between the covers. You almost
can smell the fresh paint and feel the fabrics in interior design
books and see what's outside the windows in architectural books.
Photography books keep you mesmerized for hours on end.
</P>
<P>
   And animal books warm your heart.
</P>
<P>
   There's a coffee-table book on just about every subject or fad
with prices ranging from $25 to $100.
</P>
<P>
   Coffee-table books also come in oversized softcover, which is
the fastest-growing segment of publishing's quality paperback
market, according to one bookseller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coffee-table books add an aesthetic touch to a room,'' said
Susan Novotny, owner of the Bookhouse in Guilderland, N.Y.. ``They
are also a kind of status thing, especially if they are
out-of-print. Print runs on coffee-table books are often low, with
as few as 6,000 published for the whole country, so that publishing
houses, especially the smaller ones, are not stuck with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Coffee-table book sales soar like Santa's sleigh around the
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make great, lasting holiday gifts, because they often
reflect what the buyer perceives as the recipients' tastes,''
Novotny said. ``If someone is global, they might get `National
Geographic Windows on the World' featuring fabulously curious
pictures. If they collect ephemeral things such as posters, they
might receive a copy of `The Milk Book,' which is a collection of
all the milk ads with famous people wearing the white milk
mustache. Last year, it was `The Vodka Book,' with all of the vodka
ads. A very popular book among the Generation X-ers.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Tannenbaum, owner of The Bookstore in Lenox, Mass., said
people often will save up to buy a coffee-table book.
</P>
<P>
   ``They often justify the expense, because they do buy it as a
Christmas gift,'' Tannenbaum said. ``Coffee-table books aren't
usually a spur-of-the-moment purchase. It's something people think
about buying, especially if it's connected to an historical event,
happening or great art exhibit. The anniversary collectors book of
`Gone with the Wind' came in a slip case. Art exhibit catalogs in
hard cover, like those held at major museums, look great on the
coffee table and can be appreciated for generations to come.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no set rule-of-thumb when it comes to giving a
coffee-table book, but etiquette guru Peggy Post, the great
granddaughter-in-law of the late Emily Post, offered her personal
feeling on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to give coffee-tables books if they are on a subject
that someone I know either has an interest in or something they
like to do, such as gardening, travel, decorating, dance or other
artistic expression,'' Post said from her home in Connecticut.
``Coffee-table books make a lovely keepsake gift, because it's
often something that most people don't go out and buy for
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Interior designers also love coffee-table books. They like to
use them as room accessories, which either speak to the owners
intellectual taste or color scheme of the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all for them,'' said interior designer George W. Orton
III, owner of Orton &AMP; Orton in Lee, Mass. ``Coffee-table books are
very decorative and interesting on a coffee table. Two or three
books will do the trick. They can be informative or decorative.
Nothing looks as good on a coffee table as oversized colorful
and/or picturesque books.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
