<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4674 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AGING-HOLOCAUST-SURVI     11-30 1432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGING-HOLOCAUST-SURVIVORS01-CO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Memories of Holocaust survivors combine with aging in painful
process
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The boy Tibor Farkas remembers was as
skinny as a stick. Skinny for a 12-year-old and skinnier still
because Nazi guards didn't feed Jews too well in Austrian work
camps.
</P>
<P>
   They called him ``Beanpole,'' Farkas remembers. One day,
Beanpole asked to take Farkas' place on the next day's trip to
fetch milk for the camp commander, and Farkas hesitated. Whoever
made the trip got a slice of bread and glass of milk from the owner
of the store.
</P>
<P>
   The skinny boy died of starvation before Farkas made up his
mind. And Farkas _ 15, tubercular, lice-ridden and emaciated _
walked out of a Viennese detention center at the end of the war and
into a state of psychological repression that would last through
his entire professional life. In more than 50 years as a scientist
studying the behavior of the brain, he virtually never thought
about the war, or Beanpole, or how he died.
</P>
<P>
   But now Farkas is retired, and like thousands of survivors, he
is finding that the past and present are colliding. With time on
his hands and absent distractions, Beanpole, the guards and the
torture have invaded his days and taken over his nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my life, I never dreamt about any of it,'' Farkas, 68,
said recently in his North Palm Beach apartment. ``Now, I wake up
in the middle of the night and I remember details down to the names
of guards. More and more each day the past wells up. You think
about it and one memory triggers another one until you have almost
total recall ... It alters the present, it turns the days into
nightmares.''
</P>
<P>
   The natural process of aging, difficult for the most
well-adjusted, is often debilitating for Holocaust survivors who
equate the ability to work with survival, counselors who work with
survivors say. The phenomena is especially true for
concentration-camp victims who lived through the ordeal as
children, before they developed mature psychological defenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``For these people, when they retire, all hell breaks loose,''
said Dr. Marvin Lipkowitz, who chairs the psychiatry department at
Maimonides Medical Center in Brooklyn, where hundreds of Holocaust
survivors have been treated. ``They work in order to avoid dealing
with things and when they no longer can, it can be devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon has not been studied closely in the United
States, where mental-health facilities and even most Jewish homes
for the aged don't track survivors among their residents. But it is
the subject of growing research in Israel, where Holocaust
survivors number about 300,000 _ almost 10 percent of the country's
Jewish population.
</P>
<P>
   There, sociologists and mental health professionals have found
that the population of patients in mental health facilities is
nearly double what would be expected given their proportion of the
Israeli population.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly any survivors suffered mental breakdowns directly after
the war, according to John Lemberger, the executive director of
Amcha, an Israeli organization that cares for survivors. ``Today,
however, what we are seeing is the recurring trauma (or
post-trauma) relating to their Holocaust experiences, coming
together with the normal and difficult process of aging.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 20 percent of survivors in Israel, Lemberger said, have
shown signs of mental deterioration related to their wartime
trauma.
</P>
<P>
   Farkas said he felt virtually immune from the effects of the war
throughout his life. He consistently worked 14- and 15-hour days,
and that obsession paid dividends: He ultimately won international
acclaim for his work pioneering brain scans. And even when he
underwent psychoanalysis as part of his early training, delving
deep into his subconscious, his experiences in the war almost never
surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   Today, this slightly stooped, gentle man who still keeps his
papers in the precise stacks of a scientist lives in what he calls
a social Siberia: Too sick to visit friends in other parts of the
country, he knows almost no one in Florida. The combination of
isolation and depression has become agonizing.
</P>
<P>
   Eva Weiss, a counseler who works with survivors in Palm Beach
County, has seen the sudden transformation before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for most (survivors) it's like a film playing in the
back of their minds,'' Weiss said. ``It was always there but they
didn't have to focus in on it and they had other things to think
about. But when those things are gone, it comes back into focus.''
</P>
<P>
   In the vast field of Holocaust research, delayed mental
breakdowns among survivors has altered thinking about the survivors
themselves. Once it was believed that those who survived the camps
persevered because they were stronger then those who perished. It
helped explain the high achievement of many of the victims after
the war and helped a growing Israel build its image as a strong
country populated by tough Jews.
</P>
<P>
   But the trauma, it is now understood, was often internalized and
hidden until the anchors of everyday life are removed, as they are
in old age, said John Garfinkel, a psychologist with Jewish Family
and Children Services in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The most stark portrayal is found in those who suffer from
dementia, when they mentally return to their days in the camps and
endlessly repeat a 50-year-old nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Helthgot remembers walking to his mother's house in South
Florida when she was suffering the early stages of Alzheimer's
disease. The table was set for 12. Behind each plate was a
photograph of a relative, most of whom had died in the war. On each
plate was a bowl of steaming soup.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was having a dinner party,'' said Helthgot, from his home
in Los Angeles. ``And when I walked in and asked her who was
invited, she pointed to all the pictures. When she got to me (a
picture of Helthgot as a small boy) I said `But I'm Joseph.' She
just sort of looked at me.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Helthgot said, his mother would spend hours crying
and occasionally fly into violent rages, cursing the Nazis who
killed two of her children. Ultimately she had to be taken out of a
Boca Raton nursing home because she became dangerous to other
patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of it is the fixation. The other part is that you don't
have the resources anymore to stave off the bad feelings,''
Helthgot said. When you're young ``you can't think about your kids
getting killed because you have to go on. You have to be able to
put that on a shelf somewhere and compartmentalize. Once you get
older you lose that ability, you can't keep it on a shelf and it
invades your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Institutions such as nursing homes and hospitals can be daunting
triggers for even the most well-adjusted survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any feeling that they're being held against their will will
bring back these memories,'' Lipkowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year in West Palm Beach, an 81-year-old woman suffering
from Alzheimer's was so convinced she was back in the camps she
scaled an eight-foot fence to escape a nursing home. She took a bus
to Boston before she was found.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a survivor and she thought we were trying to kill
her,'' said Carol Stevens, a nurse at the Four Seasons Nursing Home
at the time. ``She was just a little, itty bitty woman. She stacked
boxes up against the fence to get out. I can't imagine how she did
it, except that she must have been very desperate.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no cure-all, no balm, caretakers say. But
institutionalized survivors tend to feel more comfortable when
being taken care of by Jews, said Michael Brodie, the director of
assisted living care at the Miami Jewish Home and Hospital, which
has 600 residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very often, when they're being cared for by someone not in
their own racial or ethnic group they don't respond well,'' Brodie
said. ``There is some paranoia, and some feeling of being
threatened.''
</P>
<P>
   Often, Weiss said, the best treatment is to create situations
where survivors can be around other survivors _ not necessarily to
talk about their experiences, but just to share their company.
</P>
<P>
   As educated as he is, Farkas has yet to take that step. And
though he knows the guilt he harbors about Beanpole makes no sense,
he also knows logic doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's irrational to think a piece of bread and a glass of milk
would have made a difference,'' Farkas said. ``He was already
dying. But guilt is irrational. The whole war was irrational.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
