<HEADLINE>
PINOCHET IN EXILE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Tomas Eloy Martinez'
biweekly column. To publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must
be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New
York Times Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By TOMAS ELOY MARTINEZ  
 c.1998 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   These past weeks I've been trying to step into Agosto Pinochet's
shoes, trying to figure out what must be going on inside him.
</P>
<P>
   The former Chilean dictator, of course, has now been denied
immunity from prosecution, and faces possible extradition from
London to Spain for trial.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet had arrived in London in September, taking residence in
a five-star hotel in the posh district of Mayfair, not far from the
gardens of Buckingham Palace.
</P>
<P>
   London had always been the city of his dreams,``the ideal city
to live in'' _ as he had said publicly more than once. But the need
for back surgery necessitated a change in his routine during this
last trip.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, since 1990 when he stepped down from the presidency of
Chile, Pinochet has traveled to London at least once a year. His
visits were discreet and private. Each time Margaret Thatcher _ a
woman he devoutly admires _ invited him to tea. He usually went
shopping in the morning _ his favorite store is Burberry's _ and
then had lunch with friends in Fortnum &AMP; Mason.
</P>
<P>
   One of his most unchanging rituals was a visit to the Army
National Museum, and another to Madame Tussaud's wax museum, where,
deep in thought, he would spend hours in front of Napoleon
Bonaparte's figure.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet is deeply moved by everything related to Napoleon.
During this last visit he bought half a dozen books about the
emperor and was planning to go to Paris again to visit the tomb in
Invalides.
</P>
<P>
   But the Spanish judge Baltasar Garzon put an end to those happy
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   It seems the notion of empires was always in Pinochet's mind. As
have other dictators of his kind, Pinochet thinks of himself as an
envoy of Providence, someone who is Goodness incarnate and has been
destined to exterminate Evil, whatever that means. It's the same
feeling of omnipotence felt by the ayatollahs, Pol Pot and hundreds
of fanatical fundamentalists at large in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But Pinochet's case is more pathetic because once out of Chile,
and away from the glow of his wealthy Latin American supporters, he
suddenly looks like a tainted mortal.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving for London, Pinochet agreed to talk in Santiago
with a correspondent for The New Yorker magazine, Jon Lee Anderson,
author of a much-praised biography of Che Guevara. The interview
was arranged through the efforts of Pinochet's daughter Lucia. She
thought that if an honest and well-meaning journalist talked with
her father, it might put to rest the malicious talk about his old
regime.
</P>
<P>
   A great deal of what Pinochet told Anderson allows us to really
understand him for the first time. Pinochet, for instance, is still
seeing Marxists everywhere, as did the brutal commandants of the
Argentinean military juntas.
</P>
<P>
   For Pinochet, the world is divided into two irreconcilable
halves, the Marxists and the Christians, a notion that presupposes
that a war between them is unavoidable. For Pinochet, this is a
matter of life and death, and anything goes. You don't defeat the
enemy: You destroy him. The only possible way to deal with the
enemy is extermination: concentration camps, slavery, torture.
</P>
<P>
   I expect that the nastiest thing Pinochet must be feeling right
now is his total incomprehension of why he was arrested. To his way
of thinking, he didn't do anything wrong: the blood, the exiles,
the brute force, all those were ``necessary actions.''
</P>
<P>
   I wonder how he reconciles this with the fact that the great
newspapers of the Christian nations say it's unthinkable that his
crimes should go unpunished merely because he was chief of an
illegitimate government, or because he enjoys a diplomatic immunity
conquered at bayonet's point. No doubt he thinks the world is in
the hands of the Devil.
</P>
<P>
   Up until the time Pinochet seized power in 1973, he hadn't done
anything, either brilliant or terrible. He was a mediocre man, very
conservative, never noticed by anybody anywhere. But like Francisco
Franco, his most admired leader, after Napoleon and Thatcher, he
gained absolute power. Now, to his surprise, Pinochet has found out
that another power, a lot less absolute _ that of justice _ wants
to seize him. He must think this is an inexplicably sarcastic act
of God.
</P>
<P>
   At 83 years old, Pinochet has stopped wearing dark glasses, like
he did in his violent years. But it's as though he has kept on
using them. In his later years in Chile he would rarely look people
in the eye. His blue pupils would appear to be fixed on the beyond,
which for him maybe is empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never was a dictator, only an aspirant to dictator,'' he
told Anderson. ``As every man interested in history knows, I've
learned that dictators never end well.''
</P>
<P>
   What does Pinochet think then of this twist of life, this fate
that keeps him locked in a hospital room, waiting for the sort of
democratic institutions he never trusted _ chambers of
representatives, stewards of the law _ to decide his fate? If he
returns to Chile _ and he will, no doubt about it, dead or alive _
he won't be able to leave his country again.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet failed to learn that exile is no longer what it was in
the 1970s, during the heyday of Latin American dictatorships. Today
the exile of dictators is of a singular kind: They are condemned
not to leave the country they so tormented. The moment they go out
into the world, the world traps them. It's a laughable destiny, but
not unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Soon Pinochet will have his last glimpse of London, but his
victims will keep on seeing him, endlessly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Tomas Eloy Martinez is the distinguished author of ``The Peron
Novel'' and ``Santa Evita.'' He is chairman of the Latin American
studies department at Rutgers University and travels widely as an
editor and journalist.) &LR;
</P>
