A4684 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PINOCHET-DONT-PUNISH-     11-30 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-DONT-PUNISH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUNISHING PINOCHET MAY NOT BE THE ANSWER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By FLORA LEWIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    PARIS _ The instinctive reaction to word that Chile's Augusto
Pinochet has been denied immunity in London and faces extradition
to Spain is: Good, at least one bloody dictator can be held to
account.
 &HT;    But it isn't a simple issue, and the simple answer can have very
bad consequences.
 &HT;    It is no accident that the French government congratulated
itself on having foreseen possible embarrassment and refused
Pinochet a visa before his ill-fated London trip. Nor is it
surprising that Spain's Prime Minister Jose-Maria Aznar initially
commented that ``the best outcome would be if the government
doesn't even have to decide.''
 &HT;    A jumble of issues is now provoked by the collision of demands
for pure justice and the demands of politics, the demands of peace,
the demands of reconciliation. Further, the new emphasis on the
international right to judge certain crimes complicates the
question of who is to be the judge of whether circumstance or
unyielding moral dictates should prevail.
 &HT;    It has been pointed out that the peaceful, constructive
transition of Spain from a fascist dictatorship to a sturdy
democracy was achieved, despite ominous predictions of another
civil war, by refusing to judge the past. South Africa found relief
from intolerable prospects of confrontation and revenge in its
Truth and Reconciliation Commission.
 &HT;    Many countries _ El Salvador, Guatemala, Argentina, and
ex-communist countries of eastern Europe as well as Chile _ have
sought to transcend ferocious or deeply wounding civil strife by
trying to tell the truth instead of by insisting on punishment. Is
their choice to be overruled on the grounds that crimes committed
were crimes against all of humanity, not just their own nation?
 &HT;    The Spanish judge, Baltasar Garzon, who initiated the warrant
for Pinochet's arrest, has been working on testimony collected by
victims of the regime for several years. He is a man of rigor, who
pushed corruption and drug cases and tracked the ``dirty war''
against Basque terrorists.
 &HT;    Garzon's document calling for Pinochet's arrest and listing 91
people kidnapped, tortured or killed also lists a long series of
international declarations and agreements which Britain has signed
proscribing genocide, war crimes and torture. There is no question
about the straightforward legal sincerity of Garzon or of the fact
that crimes were committed.
 &HT;    There has been a tendency of late, particularly in connection
with the atrocities in former Yugoslavia, to proclaim the
inevitability of eventual punishment as a kind of consolation for
not being able to stop the terror and not being able to catch the
perpetrators. The Pinochet arrest gives the satisfaction of being
able to feel that some day evildoers everywhere will get their due.
 &HT;    Indeed, the new treaty on establishing a permanent international
tribunal, which the United States has refused to sign, has been
hailed as a signal advance that will deter future criminal
monsters. But this is fantasy. If anything, an advance, locked-in
provision for punishment makes it harder to end a conflict short of
total victory. It leaves no room for negotiation or compromise.
 &HT;    Of course, a possible answer is that there never should be
compromise with evil. Justice must be complete, there must be no
escaping the highest law.
 &HT;    That leaves the underlying question of what we really hope to
achieve and what standards are to be applied. Even today in Chile,
there are people who consider Pinochet a savior rather than a
murderer. He was able to make his deal for lifetime immunity there
because he still had considerable support when he turned power over
to a freely elected president.
 &HT;    It isn't just a matter of who is to decide. It is whether the
desired outcome should be punishment, revenge, blind justice
regardless of its consequences or removal of civil conflict and a
better chance of peaceful life.
 &HT;    When, as was the case at Nuremberg after World War II, it is
possible to achieve all at once, so much the better. But the best
in moral terms must not destroy the chances of improving how people
live.
 &HT;     (Flora Lewis is the former foreign-affairs columnist for The
New York Times.) 
 &HT;     c.1998 Flora Lewis 
