<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YELTSIN-CHAOS-MURDER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN MAY BE SICK BUT RUSSIA IS OK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By LYUDMILA TELEN  
 c.1998 Moscow News  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Again Boris Yeltsin has been hospitalized with pneumonia. In a
normal situation in a normal society this news ought to have evoked
just one kind of feeling: compassion for an elderly man who must
discharge far-from-easy duties. In Russia, however, circumstances
do not allow one to indulge exclusively in these emotions.
</P>
<P>
   The assassination of Galina Starovoitova; the uproar around the
Federal Security Service following Boris Berezovsky's accusations
of a plot to kill him; the escape of six dangerous criminals from a
Moscow jail; the triumphant victory by the anti-Semitic
``Fatherland'' political bloc in a Krasnodar election _ this is far
from being a complete list of events that have occurred merely in
the course of the past week.
</P>
<P>
   And this amid mounting hysteria, when even a person's death is
used as an excuse for settling political accounts. The president is
sick, but are we all right?
</P>
<P>
   In this situation, Boris Yeltsin's hospitalization could indeed
aggravate the situation even more. The radicals will, with even
greater enthusiasm, start harping on the need to remove the
president from office. Kremlin officials will, with fresh vigor,
continue the search for a new boss. Bandits can breathe a sigh of
relief: They will be forgotten in the political turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   All this points to an obvious conclusion: Today there are
powerful social groups in Russia that, judging by the logic of
their life, will continue to rock the boat.
</P>
<P>
   But let's keep a clear head. What has actually changed in the
country since the president fell ill? Has he only now stopped
running the state? The condition of his health has long forced him
to take it easy. Has he only now left the country unattended? For
sure, Russia has a prime minister who was approved by parliament.
Is there now reason to believe that the premier has illegally
usurped power? But under the Constitution, the head of cabinet
performs presidential duties in the event that the president is
unable to do so himself.
</P>
<P>
   The only tricky point is the formal transfer of powers from the
president to the prime minister through an edict, something for
which Boris Yeltsin is apparently not ready. Yet, should we be so
upset over this given that it is only the ``nuclear briefcase''
that is ever transferred by edict? Hardly anyone seriously believes
that this is one of the trappings of power over which Russia can be
paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   The situation with the political powers that be is more or less
clear, but what about those who are going to take over? Is anyone,
except for the chronically feverish radicals, interested in the
idea of the president being relieved of his duties ahead of term
and, for that matter, in early elections?
</P>
<P>
   Although the election campaign began a long time ago, none of
its favorites are as yet ready for a showdown. The party of power
has not as yet decided on its single leader. Today this role is
being claimed by both Yuri Luzhkov and Viktor Chernomyrdin. Yevgeny
Primakov does not aspire to it but others are claiming it on his
behalf. Representatives of the ruling establishment refer to him as
a possible ``common nomenklatura'' candidate. This group is
obviously not ready for a forced presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are others particularly well prepared. Gennady Zyuganov has
unexpectedly acquired a rival in the person of the Moscow mayor,
who has recently managed to bite off a hefty bit of support from
the leftist electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the government, formed with the participation of the
Communists, has not achieved overnight success. Nor is the famous
Gen. Alexander Lebed in particularly good shape. To date Boris
Berezovsky, his main image maker and sponsor (who has also fallen
on hard times), has not yet found a way to make up for Lebed's
mistakes in Krasnoyarsk, of which he is the elected governor.
Neither does Grigory Yavlinsky seem to be rapidly gaining
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, amid the ongoing crisis, no one has enough funds
for the elections. In short, all the indications are that no one is
going to force presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   But what if the worst comes to the worst and early elections do
become inevitable? Even then a sociopolitical catastrophe is not a
foregone conclusion. The country has a prime minister who is in a
good position to lead the country to a nationwide ballot. So no
matter what, there is indeed a safety factor. Let us understand
this and not give way to panic.
</P>
<P>
   Neither politicians nor special services nor psychics, even if
they really want this, will be able to cause an era of chaos
against our will. The country will calm down as soon as its
citizens calm down. And then the president's pneumonia will remain
nothing more than a sad page in his medical history. Not in the
history of the country.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Lyudmila Telen is deputy editor in chief of Moscow News.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------ &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
