<HEADER>
A4735 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-PATRICKDILLON-     11-30 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-PATRICK </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORM OF TRAGEDY ENGULFS ANACORTES IN `LOST AT SEA' 
</HEADLINE>
 DILLON-SPI   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (Photo available through Wieck Photo Database)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patrick Dillon was at his newspaper job in San Jose, Calif., in
1983 when the Americus, a crab boat from Anacortes, capsized in the
Bering Sea. Then came reports that a sister vessel, the Altair, had
disappeared, too.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen young men vanished with the ``A-boats.'' Some were
related through marriage, but all had become kin through the tribal
rites of a small town: playing high school football, sharing beers
at the Anchor Inn, bidding farewell to wives and tiny babies as
they headed north for another fishing season.
</P>
<P>
   ``My initial gut reaction was it has to rip the heart out of
that town,'' Dillon said. ``With the loss of those 14 lives, the
linkages that are ripped off the face of the earth are just hard to
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dillon knew more about fishing and small-town life than
most. He grew up on Bainbridge Island. On summer nights, he could
hear the diesel engines of the boats and the voices of the
fishermen. They cursed on bad nights and laughed on nights when
salmon filled their purse seines.
</P>
<P>
   The A-boats' story was one that Dillon, now 53, wanted to tell
and would 15 years later. His ``Lost at Sea: An American Tragedy''
(The Dial Press, 264 pages, $23.95) details the lives, work and
deaths of the 14. It also explores the aftermath: the families'
grief, the search to answer why the pride of the crab fleet sank
and the drive to bring safety regulation to a renegade industry.
</P>
<P>
   In the intervening years, of course, there have been other
American tragedies in the fishing industry. But the story of the
Americus and the Altair stayed with Dillon as he edited newspapers,
wrote novels and raised children.
</P>
<P>
   Dillon waited 10 years to put the story on paper. What finally
moved him, he said, was reading the late Norman McLean's ``Young
Men and Fire,'' which told of 12 smoke jumpers killed in a Montana
forest fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a great story there,'' he said of the A-boats. ``It
wasn't just a story how 14 kids came to die. It was also a story of
repressed grief and how a village manages grief.''
</P>
<P>
   He would have to wait to tell his story for business reasons.
``The Perfect Storm,'' which focuses on the loss of a fishing boat
in a horrendous storm in 1991, became a best seller in 1997.
Dillon's publisher decided to wait on his book, hoping ``The
Perfect Storm'' would create a market for similar stories.
</P>
<P>
   The writer's research for ``Lost at Sea'' ranged from dull to
dangerous. He studied the nuances of marine engineering and the
record of Coast Guard investigations. And he learned the power of
the sea as he slid on all fours on the olive oil-coated galley
floor of the crab boat Provider in bucking seas. He signed on as a
cook on the vessel to experience working on a crab boat, and spent
part of one memorable day on that floor as the contents of the
pantry fell on him.
</P>
<P>
   The heart and the tears of the story, however, are in Anacortes.
He moved into the town for four months. ``I tried from the very
beginning to become a neighbor instead of a reporter,'' Dillon
said.
</P>
<P>
   He ran into the players in his story at the gas station and
supermarket. He drew out people whom reporters had spooked 10 years
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Dillon said, what those left behind in Anacortes
didn't say was as important as what they did say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who did they really blame?'' Dillon said, was a question that
wouldn't be answered. Then again, the question perhaps shouldn't be
asked in a town where the vessel owner, crews of other boats and
the widows of the Altair and Americus rub shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not people who could just pack up and move to Santa
Fe. Anacortes is essentially an island. You can't escape each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   And they lived the story. They went to school with the crew.
They heard the church sermons that tried to make sense of it all
after the Valentine's Day sinkings.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people know the story a lot better than I do,'' Dillon
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although some may read otherwise, Dillon said his intent was to
finger no one for the loss of the 14 lives. ``To say any one person
is to blame would be wrong,'' he said. The blame trickles down from
the boats' design to their construction to their operation, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good man can sink a ship. A remorseful man can sink a ship.
A forgiving community can sink a ship. That is the story of the
book.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason the two boats sank died with the 14 young men.
</P>
<P>
   Dillon believes similar American tragedies can be prevented
through tougher policing of fishing. Boats should be built to
exacting standards and skippers and crewmen should have to pass
tests, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, since the A-boats went down, fishing in Alaska _ an
occupation 20 times more deadly than a normal American job _ has
become safer.
</P>
<P>
   Congress passed a safety law for fishing in 1988. Fishermen must
carry survival suits, life rafts and know how to use them.
</P>
<P>
   Today, more and more fishermen are surviving disasters at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many of the conditions that sent the Altair and Americus out
to sea still exist. Crab fishing remains a race among boats and
their crews to set pots and haul them back no matter how high the
seas or how strong the winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible,'' Dillon said, ``to take away from the
inherent danger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
