<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4738 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELECTION-2000-BOS &LR;      11-30 1348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTION-2000-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY DECISION TO DRIVE POTENTIAL CANDIDATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ During the next five weeks, prospective
presidential candidates will be scrambling to decide whether to run
for the White House, with some preparing to burst out of the
starting gates shortly after Jan. 1, the first day contributions
can be matched with federal money.
</P>
<P>
   While Texas Governor George W. Bush and Vice President Al Gore
have enough financial clout to put off an announcement for months,
most of the dozen other top prospects have no such luxury, with
analysts figuring that a viable candidate needs to raise $22
million in 1999, an amount requiring a daunting daily average of
$60,000 in contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the biggest overhaul of the primary system in 30 years
is under way, resulting in a bunched-up early round of primaries
that could determine the nominee for both parties in a period of
three to six weeks starting in February 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process becomes much more difficult if you wait too long''
to decide to run for president, said Senator John F. Kerry, who
expects to make his plans known in late January or early February.
Most other prospective candidates surveyed by the Globe laid out a
similar or speedier timetable.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Jardin, political director for Senator Bob Kerrey of
Nebraska, agreed: ``If you are going to do it and take on a sitting
vice president, there is no reason to wait. The money situation and
the truncated primary system mean you need a lot more money
early.'' Kerrey plans to make his decision by Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates who decide to run are expected to begin forming
campaign committees early next year. That is considered tantamount
to announcing a candidacy, although the formal announcements and
the accompanying cross-country tours might come later.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic race boils down to who might be able to mount an
aggressive challenge to Gore. House minority leader Richard
Gephardt, who may drop plans to run for president in order to
concentrate on trying to become House speaker, is expected to make
his announcement soon, thus helping other Democrats decide whether
to jump into the race.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, meanwhile, a series of subplots is
developing, among them the possibility that former vice president
Dan Quayle will try to be the consensus anti-Bush candidate, an
unlikely role for the man who shared the White House with the Texas
governor's father, President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Prospective candidates must raise money from only a limited pool
of contributors, according to Stan Huckaby, a financial consultant
to eight possible Republican presidential candidates. For example,
Huckaby said, about 45,000 Republicans are likely to donate $1,000
each to a presidential campaign, the maximum allowed in each
election cycle. To be a viable candidate, Huckaby said, it is
necessary to get contributions from about 19,000 of the 45,000.
Thus, only two or three candidates could have enough contributors.
</P>
<P>
   The key to getting those contributions, Huckaby said, is to
start collecting money in January. The financial requirements are
likely to narrow the field from the start, although some long-shot
prospects, including Republican Senator Bob Smith of New Hampshire
and GOP Representative John Kasich of Ohio, have said they might
run anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John McCain, the Arizona Republican, once said he would
rather bang his head against the wall than spend so much time
raising money. But asked last week if he is willing to embark on
such an effort, McCain displayed little hesitation, saying he is
``more inclined'' to run than before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am keenly aware the odds are not in my favor and the
difficulty of it,'' McCain said in an interview. ``My view is I am
62 years old, I am confident that a Republican would win the White
House, and this is the only time the opportunity would come up.''
While he has ``no doubt'' Bush will run, McCain said he shares some
of the Texan's strengths, including an ability to appeal to
Hispanic voters.
</P>
<P>
   Many candidates also plan to announce early because they are
mindful of the lesson learned by California Governor Pete Wilson,
who waited until June 1995 to announce his presidential candidacy
and found many financial sources had already dried up.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, early money is not a guarantee of success. Senator
Phil Gramm, the Texas Republican, raised $10 million in the first
quarter of 1995 but wound up pulling out of the campaign before the
New Hampshire primary in February 1996. The lack of big money,
however, hurt other Republicans. For example, Lamar Alexander did
reasonably well in fund-raising, but he didn't have enough money
after his third-place finish in New Hampshire to run a credible
national campaign and soon dropped out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   An exception is a candidate like multimillionaire publisher
Steve Forbes, who can afford to delay his announcement because he
can finance his own campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Several GOP prospects have been running de facto campaigns.
Alexander has spent this year collecting funds for several
political action committees, including one called ``We the
Parents,'' which is running ads featuring Alexander that look and
sound like campaign commercials. Forbes has gathered contributions
for a nonprofit company that also runs campaign-style ads.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle has spent much of 1998 raising $6 million for his
political action committee, Campaign America, which boosts Quayle
and distributes some funds to state and local candidates. For now,
though, the GOP field is focused on Bush, described as the
``Republican rock star'' of the moment by Wilson's press secretary,
Sean Walsh. Bush has said he will send a ``signal'' in the spring
about whether he will run. But Walsh said the scrutiny of Bush will
be intense and stars can fade.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Bush could face a challenge from the right, with
Quayle or Senator John Ashcroft of Missouri hoping to win over the
party's social conservative wing.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, meanwhile, have a smaller field of prospects and one
very well-placed, well-financed front-runner, Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Gephardt, four other Democrats have said they
might run. Senator Paul Wellstone of Minnesota is viewed as a
long-shot liberal candidate. Former senator Bill Bradley of New
Jersey, who is winding up a successful tour for his new book,
``Values of the Game,'' has said he will make his decision in
December.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey of Nebraska, whose Senate term expires in 2000, has ruled
out running for the presidency and reelection at the same time.
That would turn a presidential bid into an all-or-nothing
proposition. Moreover, Kerrey last week told his hometown newspaper
that he doesn't want to be ``an anti-Gore spoiler ... I don't
intend to enter the race to cause anybody any difficulty.'' He told
the Omaha World-Herald that he will decide within weeks, saying,
``I won't enter 1999 with `maybe' on my lips... There is no
torment. There is not a skull in my hand saying, `To be or not to
be?'''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry &UR;  &LR; of Massachusetts, who held a $650,000 fund-raiser last
week in an effort to wipe out his 1996 Senate campaign debt, said
he is ``very inclined'' to form his first political action
committee. That could be a sign that he plans to run for the White
House because such PACs can pay many campaign-related expenses for
a presidential aspirant. In addition, Kerry is considering dropping
his much-touted ban on accepting money from various PACs, another
sign he is thinking ahead about the difficulty of raising money for
a presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, meanwhile, is moving rapidly toward consolidating support,
starting with what aides are calling a campaign-style speech on
Wednesday at the Democratic Leadership Council, home to many of the
party's moderates and conservatives. Gore and his aides said they
hope the speech will be ``visionary,'' distinguishing himself from
President Clinton and setting the stage for his own presidential
campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
