<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-SST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SST EMERGES FROM ITS LONG SLEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At an evangelical church not far from Disney World, services
were held in the shadow of its massive variable-sweep wings and
five-story tail.
</P>
<P>
   Several times it was nearly sold for scrap metal.
</P>
<P>
   And for the past eight years, it deteriorated in the rain and
Florida humidity at a junkyard near Cape Canaveral, covered by
weeds and all but forgotten. It was the last artifact of America's
efforts to build a supersonic passenger plane that promised to be
an aviation tour de force that would have profoundly changed the
face of aviation.
</P>
<P>
   The full-scale, $11 million mock-up of The Boeing Co.'s
supersonic transport has had a vagabond existence since it was sold
to a Nebraska millionaire and transported in seven railroad cars
from Seattle to Florida after Congress killed the SST project in
1971.
</P>
<P>
   Now, most of it has finally found a permanent home, thanks to a
California aviation pioneer who had help from friends at Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the highly publicized saga of the old ferry Kalakala,
which was rescued from mudflats in Alaska and recently returned to
Seattle for restoration, the effort to save this piece of aviation
history has played out without public notice.
</P>
<P>
   A 100-foot section of the fuselage, including the cockpit and
the plane's ``droop snoot'' needle nose, was rescued from the space
center junkyard, shipped cross-country in trucks and is being
restored at the recently opened Hiller Aviation Museum near San
Francisco. Eventually, visitors will be able to sit in the
first-class cabin and even operate from the cockpit the droop
snoot, which was designed to be lowered to give pilots better
visibility during takeoffs and landings.
</P>
<P>
   The mock-up will be as close as anyone gets to a Boeing-built
SST until well into the next century. Boeing recently decided to
delay until at least 2020 developing a new generation passenger jet
that would fly several times faster than the speed of sound,
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes for quite a display. We feel very fortunate to have
it,'' said Stanley Hiller Jr., a longtime member of Boeing's board
of directors who spent two decades trying to turn his dream of an
educational aviation museum into a reality. The Northern California
museum that bears his name opened this past May.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we finish the restoration,'' he said of the SST mock-up,
``it will look like a flyable aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   The fuselage section acquired by the museum already is on
display with some 75 other airplanes, and its needle nose was
recently mated again to the cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   It is far from being restored, however. As Hiller said, ``If you
saw it now, it looks a little like it's been in a very long sleep.
It was just lying in the weeds and rain for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   The blue and white Boeing paint job has faded and the fuselage
has been consumed by rust and streaked with years of grime since
that day on Sept. 29, 1966, when the sleek mock-up, only a dozen
feet shorter than a football field, was unveiled to the media,
airline representatives and other VIPs at Boeing's Developmental
Center off East Marginal Way in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``Legend &AMP; Legacy: The Story of Boeing and Its
People,'' Robert Sterling wrote of that moment:
</P>
<P>
   ``The visitors were gathered on a balcony in the Developmental
Center; a bridge connected the balcony to the mock-up, which was
bathed in darkness until the moment of unveiling. A series of
spotlights came on one by one, illuminating the immense needle-nose
blue-and-white plane in sections. The last spotlight threw its beam
at the large `USA' on the tail, as a voice intoned over a
loudspeaker: `This ... is the Boeing supersonic transport!'''
</P>
<P>
   As the plane's nose was raised and lowered, guests were escorted
across the bridge into the model's interior, which Sterling wrote
was ``as spectacular as the exterior.'' The carpeting was a rich
but pleasing blue. Each of the seats, which alternated deep reds
and purples with splashes of orange, contained its own television
screen, a personal touch that would become available only when
Boeing introduced the 777 nearly 30 years later.
</P>
<P>
   The mock-up was not just for show. It was built to test
engineering designs for two prototypes of a Boeing SST that would
carry 250 passengers at Mach 2.7, or about 1,800 miles per hour.
That's faster than today's jet fighters can fly.
</P>
<P>
   The mock-up had the same section breaks and critical dimensions
as the planned prototypes, including wings that could be swept back
after takeoff to provide a more efficient angle for supersonic
flight.
</P>
<P>
   Although the prototypes were to be made of titanium, the mock-up
was built of wood, steel and aluminum. Fifty tons of steel, 42,800
linear feet of lumber and 3,500 sheets of plywood went into the
mock-up.
</P>
<P>
   It was the only SST Boeing would build.
</P>
<P>
   Painted by critics as a white elephant and by environmentalists
as a destroyer of the Earth's ozone, the project ended abruptly
shortly after midnight on May 20, 1971, when the U.S. Senate killed
further funding.
</P>
<P>
   More than $1 billion already had been spent on developing the
SST.
</P>
<P>
   The 288-foot mock-up was put up for sale, but initial bids came
from companies that wanted Boeing to pay them to haul it away as
junk. Finally, it was sold by sealed bid to Marks O. Morrison for
$31,119. Morrison was a pilot, aviation buff and millionaire from
Nebraska who wanted the model as the centerpiece for an aviation
museum he planned in Central Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1973, with the help of Boeing engineers, it was taken
apart, loaded on to seven railroad cars and hauled to Kissimmee,
Fla. There it was reassembled on a concrete slab the size of a
football field that had been poured in a cow pasture about 15 miles
east of Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison's transportation bill was $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   The aviation museum, which opened July 4 that year, was
literally built around the mock-up, with the plane's tail _ the tip
of which rose 50 feet _ sticking through the roof.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, the museum drew crowds, but visitors eventually
stopped coming and the museum closed in 1981. It would have cost
too much to take the plane apart and move it elsewhere, so it
remained when the property was sold to Faith World.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentecostal church held services under the wings until 1988.
Two years later, the building was sold to another church group, the
Osceola New Assembly of God. And it wanted the SST out.
</P>
<P>
   The story quickly attracted attention. Time magazine sent a
reporter. A CBS crew showed up.
</P>
<P>
   At a Sunday service, church pastor Ernie DeLoach told his
congregation that he hoped the plane could be saved rather than
hacked into bits, but it had to go so the church could expand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know some of you are going to miss this plane, and that some
of you will shed tears,' he said. ``Some churches have steeples.
Ours has an airplane tail sticking through the roof.''
</P>
<P>
   The mock-up was nearly sold for $10,000 to a scrap dealer, but
the deal fell through just days before the plane was to have been
chopped up.
</P>
<P>
   That's when a retired NASA engineer named Charlie Bell came
calling on the Osceola New Assembly of God.
</P>
<P>
   Bell liked to collect space-age artifacts and had restored a
couple of Redstone and Atlas rockets. At the request of the Puerto
Rican government, he had even built a rocket park near San Juan.
</P>
<P>
   After reading in a newspaper that the SST mock-up might end up
on the scrap heap, Bell bought it in late 1990 for an undisclosed
amount and, with the help of friends, took it apart in seven
sections and transported them to a former steel plant he owned on
Merritt Island, just outside one of the gates to the Kennedy Space
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Bell removed valuable instruments from the mockup and took them
inside the plant to protect them from the weather, but the seven
pieces of fuselage, nose, wings and tail were left outside.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, aviation buffs from around the world who knew
about Boeing's SST project and the history of the mock-up would
track Bell down and visit the old steel plant just across the
highway from the Shuttle Bar &AMP; Grill.
</P>
<P>
   ``All it needs is a good high-pressure washing ... and some
tender loving care,'' Bell told a Post-Intelligencer reporter who
visited the mock-up late last year.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Bell said he was talking to someone interested in
buying the mock-up and putting it in a museum. The buyer turned out
to be Stanley Hiller Jr.
</P>
<P>
   A native of San Francisco, Hiller pioneered many of the
vertical-lift concepts that led to the modern helicopter. He built
his first helicopter, which he named the XH-44, in a friend's
garage at age 16. It was the first helicopter ever to fly on the
West Coast, hovering over the football field at Berkeley Memorial
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In 1942, at age 18, he founded the Hiller Aircraft Co. It would
produce more than 2,000 helicopters for military and commercial
use.
</P>
<P>
   Hiller's $25 million museum opened in May on land leased from
San Mateo County near the San Carlos Airport. It features 100
exhibits and 75 aircraft, including some built by Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Hiller, now 73, has a fondness for Boeing planes. He was on the
company's board for 22 years. Although it was his ties with Boeing
that led him to the SST mock-up, Hiller understood the plane's
importance in aviation history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It fit the theme of our museum, which is not only to look back
but to look ahead in aviation to the next 100 years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing helped Hiller locate the mock-up and sent engineers to
Florida to examine its condition. Hiller hoped to bring all of the
mock-up back to his museum, but it would have taken up too much
space.
</P>
<P>
   The fuselage section, cockpit and nose were taken from Florida
to California on two flat-bed trucks. Boeing coordinated the
difficult wide-load transport task with the various states along
the way.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also is providing expertise to ensure the mock-up is
restored to its original condition, including the cabin interior
and cockpit instruments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our being able to do this is a real credit to Boeing,'' Hiller
said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Bell nor Hiller will say how much the museum paid for
the mock-up. Bell said he didn't make money on the deal; he just
got back what he paid the Osceola New Assembly of God.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I could help find a home for it,'' Bell said. ``It
could easily have ended up as scrap metal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 1325EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
