<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARY-HART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAME THE WHITE HOUSE SCANDAL ON GARY HART 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE MARINE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ OK, I know we're all tired of the subject,
but has it occurred to anyone else that this whole business of the
Starrship Lewinsky is the fault of Gary Hart?
</P>
<P>
   If you're too young, you may not remember the senator from
Colorado, a bright Democratic hopeful who had his eye on the White
House. Unlike the lackluster Walter Mondale and Michael Dukakis of
his time, he was a forceful and charismatic campaigner who offered
a specific program of opposition to the Republican policies of the
day.
</P>
<P>
   He was doing pretty well on the march through the 1988 primaries
when Miami reporters caught him spending late-night hours in a
townhouse with a woman not his wife. Magazines and newspapers also
printed stories about Hart's being off on a boat called Monkey
Business _ without his wife but in the company of a couple of women
described, whether or not accurately, as bimbos.
</P>
<P>
   What Hart did _ perhaps nobly from his own point of view but
disastrously both for American politics and for American journalism
_ was to concede that the revelation about his private life was
important, and to withdraw from the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   What Hart could have done _ and by doing so could have set a
precedent that politicians of every conviction, from Wilbur Mills
to Henry Hyde, could have relied on _ was to say simply, ``My
private life is none of your bloody business, and has nothing to do
in any way with my competence to be president of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Had he done so and stayed in the race, he might not have won the
nomination, but we would not have had to wait this long to learn
that Americans are sanely capable of separating serious government
from salacious gossip.
</P>
<P>
   Of course Bill Clinton, regardless of Gary Hart, could have done
the same thing (in 1992 he did, and it worked).
</P>
<P>
   The accusation by Paula Jones was different. Whatever its truth,
it was about sexual harassment _ an act that, not being consensual,
cannot be private, and therefore must be dealt with publicly. But
the business about the adventurous and far-from-innocent Beverly
Hills chippy who wrote about earning her ``presidential kneepads''
(and who has never been cross-examined) is something else again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never had sexual relations with that woman.'' That's
what Clinton said. What he could and should have said was: ``My
personal sex life is none of your business; it was never any of
your business, and it will never be any of your business. Do you
have any questions about Northern Ireland?''
</P>
<P>
   Because, you see, that has to be the point. When the jinni of
your dreams promises you three wishes, you're always dutiful enough
to make the first wish for ``world peace'' _ and since the fall of
the Berlin Wall, the three biggest threats to world peace have been
the conflicts in Northern Ireland, in the Middle East and in the
former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   During the six years of Clinton's presidency, all parties agree
that his administration was a major force in bringing about a peace
agreement in Northern Ireland; it brought about the Wye accords, in
which an Israeli prime minister actually signed an agreement with
Yasser Arafat; and, tenuous though it is, the world press routinely
refers to the ``U.S.-brokered'' cease-fire agreement in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland may blow up again; it may be that neither side really
wants peace in the Middle East; and I confess to understanding the
Balkans no better than do most Americans. But surely some
distinction must be made between this sort of diplomatic heroism
and a private life perhaps three miracles short of sainthood.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nixon was specifically ordered by the Congress not to
extend the war in Vietnam beyond that country's borders. In
deliberate (and admitted) violation of that limitation, Nixon
personally ordered the bombing of neutral Cambodia _ with reports
of 3,000 civilian deaths. The House Judiciary Committee chose not
to include that war crime in its impeachment investigation, because
(as one committee member wrote to me personally), ``We have enough
without it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's potential impeachment, even without the bombing of
Cambodia, was about something that had to do with the presidency.
Clinton's troubles are about, to use the usual weasel phrase, oral
sex. If he had had the good sense to tell the first investigators,
and all who came after, that it was none of their business, he'd
have made an important contribution both to politics and to
journalism, and would have found himself where most of us have been
all the time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
