A4753 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-30 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDS STILL RAGES, AND DRASTIC MEASURES ARE NEEDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You thought the AIDS epidemic was tailing off? Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   An American dies from this plague-for-which-there-is-no-vaccine
every 15 minutes. Another American is infected every 13 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   You thought today's young people have been educated about safe
sex? Wrong; worldwide, half of all HIV-AIDS infections come in
those age 15 to 19.
</P>
<P>
   Despite wonderful medical gains, colossal investment of reseach
money, and vastly improved knowledge about how to not only prevent
but treat this plague, ``HIV-AIDS remains the most dangerous public
health threat of our time,'' said Robert Wakefield, director of
Boston's Lemuel Shattuck Hospital. The Shattuck and the
Massachusetts Medical Society sponsored an ``AIDS at the
Millennium'' conference Nov. 18 at the Kennedy Library.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday is World AIDS Day. Despite the discovery of
protease-inhibitors drug cocktails, nine out of 10 of the 40
million people infected worldwide have no shot at getting those
drugs, whose US cost per patient can range from $25,000 to $40,000
a year. Nearly half of America's AIDS cases are black _ 43 percent
_ but blacks are only 12 percent of the population. Among infected
females, 60 percent are black, typically sex partners of men who
may use dirty needles to inject drugs. AIDS is the number one cause
of death among 16- to 24-year-old women.
</P>
<P>
   But the infernal viruses surprise other demographic groups. In
Florida, 15 percent of AIDS cases are in people over 50, primarily
heterosexuals. But overall, here as in the rest of the world, AIDS
is becoming a disease of women, the poor, minorities, and gay men
engaging in unprotected sex.
</P>
<P>
   While the disease spreads among the vulnerable here, in the
Third World the epidemic rampages. Asia, India, Latin America, and
worst of all, Africa, suffer a plague of biblical scale. Scientists
and bureaucrats are in the oldest race of all: against time. In
broad swaths of sub-Saharan Africa, one out out of every three
people between 15 and 55 are already infected. Life expectancy in
Botswana, where one in four adults are already infected, has fallen
from 61 years to 45, and a decade from now could drop to 33, warns
Harvard's Dr. Daniel Tarantola.
</P>
<P>
   Within 11 years, 40 million children worldwide will have been
orphaned by AIDS. ``We have never before in the history of man had
children losing their family at this rate,'' said Loretta
McLaughlin, a Fellow of the Harvard AIDS Institute. ``In Africa,
and soon in India, there is a fall-off in skilled manpower because
in a lot of these places the skills run only one person deep. A lot
of Third World countries don't want to talk about this.''
</P>
<P>
   By June, the Christian Science Monitor calculates, the planet's
population will be 6 billion, double what it was in 1960, the year
JFK was elected. One out of three humans today is under age 15.
Those hormones are kicking in. The right-wing foes of abortion and
family planning in Congress this year blocked the US from
contributing even its usual pittance to the UN Population Fund.
</P>
<P>
   It takes 2.1 children per woman to maintain population at a
steady level. The United States and most European countries have
fertility rates lower than that; our population increase (2.3
million a year) comes mostly from immigration. By the year 2050,
India will have more people than China, the United Nations
projects. We'll be the number three country, but there'll be about
as many Pakistanis as Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia and Nigeria combined will be double our population
now. Ethiopia and Congo combined will equal the US population then.
Africa will have three times the population of Europe and Russia in
51 years. Without question poverty and population pressure in Third
World countries will spur migration _ legal or illegal _ to the
developed world. Immigrants cannot come without bringing their
diseases with them.
</P>
<P>
   Just as it is tragic and stupid for young gay males to engage in
promiscuous and unprotected sex, it is folly on a grand scale for
politicians to refuse to fund needle exchange programs, condom
distribution, and aggressive sex education programs for
schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rate of infection is still going up in Massachusetts among
the urban poor,'' points out McLaughlin, despite the demonstrable
reduction possible with bolder efforts to meet the crisis.
Conservatives elected to office on the ``just say no'' theme about
teen sex tell voters they are being moral and good. But the May 20
issue of the Journal of the American Medical Association
editorialized that the abstinence-only approach the Republican
Congress funded for $50 million is woefully misguided and
incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching safe sex has to be part of the effort, but the
conservatives block money for that. The editorial concludes:
``Public health policy should be empirically driven, not
ideologically motivated. Ideologically motivated policy decisions
may inadvertently cause a grave disservice to our youth, many of
whom are ill-equipped with the knowledge and the skills necessary
to reduce high-risk sexual behaviors. In the end, we risk
jeopardizing the health and well-being of a generation of youth.''
</P>
<P>
   To halt the AIDS epidemic, we need drastic measures. That
includes overriding the well-intentioned but misguided conservative
politicians who are disarming the doctors and teachers we need in
the front lines for this battle. If HIV-AIDS strikes down someone
you care about, who might have been spared by sterner measures, you
can't say no one ever told you.
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
