<HEADLINE>
A HOLIDAY OF MIXED BLESSINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a guinea pig in our freezer, his shoe box coffin wedged
between Ziploc bags of turkey meat and Tupperware containers of
creamed onions, an incongruous presence among the Thanksgiving
leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   Death came without warning. No sooner had 8-year-old Katie
pronounced herself especially thankful for Fritz the dog,
Marshmallow the rabbit, and Zachary-Christine, the guinea pig of
indeterminate gender, than the smallest of our family pets keeled
over in its cage and died.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways the simplest of American holidays, Thanksgiving is
also our most ambiguous. There is no pressure to produce a perfect
gift, no demand in this informal age to appear at the table in a
velvet dress or a bow tie. The most that is asked of us is to bake
a pie, help with the dishes, and hold our tongue when one or
another of our distant relatives makes an especially asinine
remark.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no family measures up to Norman Rockwell's idealized
image of domestic harmony and few can wholly embrace the
Wampanoags' view of the holiday as a national day of mourning for
the loss of Native American land and culture.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden demise of Zac-Chris, as he/she was informally known,
is something of a metaphor for the mixed blessing that was
Thanksgiving in our house this year, that the holiday probably is
in most houses most years.
</P>
<P>
   We gathered around a bountiful table, at once grateful for one
another's company and awkward about how _ or even whether _ to
acknowledge the fresh absence of the family matriarch we lost last
spring. Every chair in the newly refurbished dining room was
occupied, but an empty space remained. Each member of a
reconfigured family was working out a new role. The unspoken aim of
a clan known for its emotional reserve was to concede, but not
dwell upon, the changed domestic landscape. A dampness around the
eyes might be appropriate; an abundance of tears, a little over the
top.
</P>
<P>
   It's never that easy, however, especially for those for whom the
finality of death is not yet entirely comprehensible and for whom
little distinction is made between the loss of a favored pet and a
beloved grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't Santa Claus please bring Grandma and Zac back for
Christmas?, Katie asked between sobs.
</P>
<P>
   No, we told her gently, that's just not possible.
</P>
<P>
   The genuineness of her plea made it easy to suppress the smile
prompted by the image of my mother seated beneath a Douglas fir,
tucked between a pair of Roller Blades and a Beanie Baby, holding
the guinea pig that, out of Katie's earshot, she was known to
sneeringly refer to as ``that filthy rodent.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an unfair characterization. Zac kept himself clean enough
and he was a distinctive-looking rodent, as rodents go. A streak of
red fur over his left ear made him look either rakish or punkish,
depending on your age. His otherwise black-and-white fur stood
straight up along his back, Mohawk-style.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to know what his expectations were, of course, but by
our own measure he had a good life for a guinea pig. His bedding of
fresh wood shavings was changed daily rather than mixed with the
cedar chips that eliminated odor but irritated his nose. He had
fresh water and nutritionally balanced food.
</P>
<P>
   It's true he didn't do very much. He cared little for the great
outdoors. If Katie put him in the yard, she could be sure he'd be
in the same spot an hour later. If she let him loose in the
playroom, though, he would soon be lost behind the television set
or among the stuffed animals.
</P>
<P>
   The guinea pig's squeak was louder than the dog's bark. It
reverberated off the walls of the basement playroom whenever we
descended the stairs. Zac was not signaling pleasure at our
presence; rather, he was issuing demands for fresh carrot peels.
Such was the racket he made that we felt compelled to exile him to
the laundry room during the children's sleepovers.
</P>
<P>
   We are full of grief and penitence now for our annoyance with
the guinea pig. When there is no time for goodbyes, there is an
abundance for recrimination. Did we feed him enough? Too much? Did
we ignore a warning sign that might have saved him?
</P>
<P>
   Katie has picked the spot for Zac-Chris's interment, between the
flowering crab apple and the lace-cap hydrangea in an area of the
backyard we have designated as Grandma's garden. ``So Grandma can
look after Zac-Chris in heaven,'' Katie said. It's a prospect I
know my mother will welcome with all the ambivalence of a typical
Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   (Eileen McNamara is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
