<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORK TELEVISION'S NIGHTMARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five years ago, Marc Andreessen was a student at the University
of Illinois, tinkering with software that enabled people to access
the Internet with ease. Five days ago, the company he founded after
graduating from college _ Netscape _ was sold to America Online for
$4 billion. In the course of five short years, Andreessen changed
the face of computing forever. He is now involved in a venture that
may do something similar to broadcast television.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, it was announced that Andreessen had made a
significant investment in a small Silicon Valley start-up called
Replay Networks Inc., and that he would take a seat on the
company's board. Replay Networks will soon bring to market a
digital television recording system, similar to a videocassette
recorder, that will initially retail for $999.
</P>
<P>
   The system is called ReplayTV and in the words of New York Times
technology correspondent John Markoff, it will ``enable users to
record a complete program that is already in progress, to
automatically record programs that meet a predetermined criterion _
for example, movies featuring a particular actor _ and to
intelligently skip commercials.''
</P>
<P>
   The ReplayTV system houses a 7-Gigabyte hard-disk drive similar
to a personal computer's hard drive. According to Daily Variety,
``cable or satellite TV programming signals coming into the house
are sent into the unit, where they're compressed and recorded on
the disk drive. Software inside the device enables the user to
easily select programs up to two weeks in the future to record on
the disk drive for later viewing, as well as pause, fast forward
and review programming that they're currently watching and that's
still being recorded.''
</P>
<P>
   This technology represents a potentially lethal threat to the
broadcast television business. Broadcasters break even (or lose
money) on network programming and make a killing on their
owned-and-operated affiliates (O&AMP;Os). This arrangement allows
broadcasters to present themselves as competitively disadvantaged
(we can't make a buck in this business) while their O&AMP;Os mint money
for shareholders (we've just had another record year).
</P>
<P>
   Everything depends on a huge advertising revenue stream to cover
(or almost cover) the costs of network programming and fatten the
profit margins at the owned affiliates. To keep that revenue stream
flowing, broadcasters must convince advertising agencies that
spending vast sums of money on television commercials is the
``only'' way to reach a mass audience. This they have done with
considerable success for the last 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   But what if consumers adapt to digital television recording
systems as quickly as they did to videocassette recorders? The
first thing that happens is that Microsoft and everybody else will
get into the business of manufacturing digital television recording
systems and the price of said systems will plummet to a commodity
rate of about $199 per unit. The second thing that will happen is
that viewers will have complete control over content. If they don't
want to watch television commercials, they won't have to. The third
thing that will happen is that the network schedule (``ER'' at 10
p.m.) becomes fungible. Someone can watch the news from 9:45 to
10:07 (minus all commercials) and then watch ER in 50 minutes
(minus all commercials). Should they be interrupted for any reason,
they would simply ``pause'' the programming and return to it at
their convenience.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine for a moment that you run an advertising agency. Would
you tell your clients to sign a long-term advertising deal with NBC
or CBS, knowing that in five years as many as 60 percent of all
households might be hooked up to digital television recording
systems? The only thing you might urge your clients to buy would be
``live'' events, such as breaking news stories or sports. You
wouldn't touch the rest of it, because you would know that anyone
with a digital television recording system can ``intelligently
skip'' commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Without this river of advertising revenue, the network equation
falls apart. Network programming goes broke. The owned-and-operated
affiliates also go broke. Cable television maintains its
subscription fees, but it also takes a huge hit on the revenue
side. Only HBO, Showtime and other premium television services
would be unaffected by the new technology.
</P>
<P>
   According to people who have used ReplayTV, it is a quantum leap
ahead of the videocassette recorder and is remarkably
user-friendly. ``The adaption rate is likely to be much faster than
VCRs,'' says one industry analyst, ``partly because it's like a VCR
and partly because it's so much easier to use.''
</P>
<P>
   If ReplayTV connects with consumers, then network television and
cable television will have to completely rethink their business
models, Hollywood television production companies will have to
rethink their distribution, and syndicators will have to
re-negotiate their contracts. Without advertising, television as we
know it is unsustainable. ReplayTV is a harbinger of the end of
television advertising.
</P>
<P>
   (John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
