<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADY-LOOPHOLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOPHOLE IN BRADY LAW ALLOWS FOR UNCHECKED PURCHASES  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Fla.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PUNTA GORDA, Fla. _ Hassle-free sales and the bounty of choice _
Tec-9s, MAC-10s, double-action Berettas, and 9mm Glocks _ made
competition tough for the man wearing a ``for sale'' sign around
his neck and peddling a single rifle at the recent Suncoast Gun
Show &UR;  &LR; in this steamy Gulf Coast town.
</P>
<P>
   At any of the 5,000 gun shows around the country every year, an
individual claiming to be a private collector can sell firearms to
anyone who wants them. And private owners and collectors do not
have to record the transaction or subject the buyer to the
background check mandated by the 1993 Brady law.
</P>
<P>
   This means that people barred from buying guns at retail stores
_ fugitives, convicted felons, wife-beaters, illegal immigrants _
can slip under the Brady law radar by making purchases through
private owners and collectors at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no federal law whatsoever regulating gun shows,''
said BJ Zapor, a special agent of the federal Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco, and Firearms in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, law enforcement officials say these shows attract a
strong criminal element, along with hunters, collectors, and other
law-abiding citizens. Gun-control advocates say a loophole in the
law has transformed these shows into a legally sanctioned ``gray
market.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is not the gun shows themselves, it's the
unregulated sales that take place,'' said Sarah Brady, chairwoman
of Handgun Control Inc., a national advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control supporters like Brady are calling for change. This
month, President Clinton directed the administration to recommend
ways to close the loophole, and Representative Rod Blagojevich, an
Illinois Democrat, introduced a bill to crack down on off-the-book
firearms sales.
</P>
<P>
   The first stage of the Brady law expires Nov. 30. Henceforth,
the Justice Department will implement a system of instant
background checks to replace a five-day waiting period for gun
purchases. Like the previous system, the instant checks pertain
only to gun retailers, not hobbyists who sell at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Many collectors say the fears that gun shows attract criminals
are exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crooks don't come to gun shows. They steal guns or get them on
the street,'' said a retired collector at the Punta Gorda show who
said he sells guns ``on the side.'' He requested that his name not
be used.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association also rejects the idea and opposes
efforts to close the loophole.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a dealer, you need a permit, and if you are a
hobbyist or a collector, you don't,'' said Wayne LaPierre, the
NRA's executive vice president. ``This is the law and we support
it. I don't support the notion that criminals are getting guns at
shows. ... I don't believe more regulation is the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   But ATF agents said licensed dealers have long complained about
private sellers. In a 1993 letter to a congressional subcommittee
considering amending the law, Bill Bridgewater, executive director
of the National Alliance of Stocking Gun Dealers, wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``Do something about gun shows. Either shut them down or
regulate them and restrict their activities to legal transactions
in firearms. ... Every pugnacious child with a grudge to settle and
every other form of human predator has easy access to all the
firearms that they might desire.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun control advocates say the history of gun shows demonstrates
the need for more regulation:
</P>
<P>
   _David Koresh acquired hundreds of weapons at shows and
stockpiled them in the Branch Davidian compound at Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   _Timothy McVeigh and Terry Nichols bought and sold stolen
weapons at shows across the Midwest before the bombing of the
federal building in Oklahoma City, according to court documents.
</P>
<P>
   _Sam Dillon, a convicted Illinois serial killer who pleaded
guilty to five homicides, repeatedly bought, sold, and traded
weapons at gun shows, sometimes within hours of commiting crimes,
according to an investigation by the Chicago Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 Justice Department study found that an estimated 40
percent of all gun transfers are made in unregulated secondary
markets, including gun shows, flea markets, swap meets, and
classified ads.
</P>
<P>
   At the state and county level, a patchwork of laws regulate
gun-show sales. California and New Jersey have essentially outlawed
them. In Massachusetts, gun shows are legal, but both buyer and
seller are required to have a permit. Earlier this month, Florida
amended its constitution to let counties regulate gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a gun-loving state, but people don't feel no questions
should be asked when someone buys a gun,'' said Edward Griffith,
assistant to the Miami-Dade County state attorney. ``They feel they
should know who it's being sold to.'' The state attorney's office
pushed the amendment, which passed with 70 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Repeated attempts to interview gun show promoters, including
Suncoast's, were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the lack of regulation, ATF agents said it is
extremely difficult to draw the line between legitimate commerce
and a gray market.
</P>
<P>
   An ATF agent who asked not to be named said: ``I have yet to
encounter an unlicensed dealer who didn't say they were selling
from their `collection' that they just happened to have acquired
last week and want to get rid of this week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
