<HEADER>
A4764 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TISSUE-ENGINEERING-BO     11-30 1566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TISSUE-ENGINEERING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICINE: REMAKING OURSELVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems like the stuff of fiction, or a horror film plot line,
with mad scientists creating human body parts in laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a fact: Yard upon yard of human skin is being grown in
laboratories to help repair burns and leg ulcers. Tissue from pig
intestines is used to replace knee ligaments, and then stimulates
new human cell growth so that pig gut turns into human ligament.
And body pieces, from chest bone to thumbs, are being grown in
laboratories and then surgically attached to humans.
</P>
<P>
   Tissue engineering _ an amalgam of biology, chemistry and
engineering _ is producing stunning results, including the
manufacture and testing of everything from nipples to heart valves
to liver cells. In less than 20 years, the tissue engineering field
has grown from a few scientists to more than 2,400.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the future, the whole question of worrying about body parts
wearing out will cause no more concern than whether your carburetor
wears out,'' says Dr. Michael Sefton at the University of Toronto.
Last summer, Sefton _ echoing the kind of bold challenge made by
President Kennedy a generation ago that man would walk on the moon
_ set the goal of growing a human heart in the laboratory in 10
years. With the help of scientists around the world, he says, that
goal is achievable.
</P>
<P>
   Such pioneering efforts in tissue engineering are backed by more
than $3 billion in investments _ 90 percent of it private.
Virtually all of the investors are betting heavily that tissue
engineering will result in profound changes in medicine. And
virtually everyone is calling that a pretty safe bet.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, some skeptics doubt the industry can, say, produce a
complete off-the-shelf heart in 10 or even 20 years. And many in
medicine discount the idea that doctors will remove a diseased
heart or liver and plop in a new factory-made replacement organ
anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   But when doctors talked 15 or 20 years ago about putting new
body parts in patients, they talked of synthetics, of metal and
plastic. Now, the talk is of human tissue. And many doctors believe
that pieces of heart or liver may someday be grown and used to
replace diseased portions of those organs.
</P>
<P>
   But while there is general consensus, even among skeptics, that
tissue engineering holds great promise, there is not much agreement
on how best to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until last year that a group to formulate testing and
materials standards for tissue engineering was created. And there
is debate on the best way to stimulate tissue growth.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, doctors and scientists, such as brothers
Charles and Jay Vacanti and MIT chemical engineering professor
Robert Langer, use biodegradable scaffolds made of artificial
polymers to plant cells, which are then given growth factors to
produce a variety of body parts. Organogenesis, a Canton-based
company, is one of a handful of companies that have received FDA
approval to market human skin made in a lab, using a collagen-based
scaffold.
</P>
<P>
   This week, scientists from around the world, who use a
decellularized kind of pig intestine known as SIS (for
small-intestinal submucosa) will gather in Orlando to discuss SIS
as a scaffold for tissue regeneration in everything from a knee
ligament to abdominal hernia repair to small bowel regeneration.
The FDA this year approved first-stage clinical trials in humans
for regeneration of the knee ligament known as the anterior
cruciate.
</P>
<P>
   Developed by Purdue University researchers led by Dr. Stephen F.
Badylak, the paper-thin and maleable SIS is inserted at a wound
site. In lab tests, it seems to stimulate growth of blood vessels
in the area, which not only speeds healing, but also rebuilds the
tissue that was destroyed or removed. Eventually, all that is left
is new tissue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our approach, at least for some applications, gets very good
results and the body seems to return to a more fetal wound-healing
when the SIS matrix is used,'' Badylak says. ``We don't understand
all the reasons why this happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are more like pigs than we would like to admit and this is
just further proof of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Because SIS, at least in animal trials, tends to seed whatever
type of cells it is placed near, its supporters say it offers a
simple, inexpensive way to grow new cells because the manufacture
occurs in the body, not a laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Growing new cells may well prove to be a more desirable way to
repair a knee than the technique most often used now, which
involves taking ligament from another part of the body to repair
the damaged area. That results in a second wound and a leg that is
less strong overall than it once was.
</P>
<P>
   Growing new knee ligament has none of those disadvantages _ and
the first rounds of testing shows that the results are generally
positive. Dr. Robert Hunter in Aspen, Colo., has put SIS in five
knee patients, the first one last January. Of the five, four are
doing ``very well'' and one operation was a ``complete failure,''
Hunter says. He believes the failure was the result of a mechanical
problem in the installation of the SIS (the ligament is attached
with titanium screws). The FDA, he said, last week concurred and
allowed the trials to resume. Surgeons in Baltimore will soon
perform six such operations.
</P>
<P>
   SIS is also being tested to repair skin wounds and bladder
problems. Badylak is hopeful that SIS will be able to help with
so-called orphan diseases, those so rare that neither research
companies nor medical facilities spend much time studying them
because the demand is so low. ``It could be used for cleft palate
repair, which is a horrific problem, but not the sort of thing a
company will ever get rich over,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Companies do hope to get rich with tissue engineering. In June,
the FDA approved the sale of Organogenesis's Apligraf skin tissue.
Since then, orders have been received by 200 medical centers around
the country, according to Carol Hausner, director of investor and
public relations for Organogenesis. The market for this type of
artificial skin, she notes, includes the 1 million people in the
United States who suffer from leg ulcers each year.
</P>
<P>
   And Reprogenesis, a Cambridge, Mass. company that uses
technology invented by Langer and Jay Vacanti, takes cartilage from
the ear, isolates the cells, combines it with a polymer, and
injects the substance in a patient to narrow the opening of the
bladder near the ureter, to prevent urine backflowing to the
kidneys _ a dangerous condition that affects thousands of children
each year and can require major surgery to correct.
</P>
<P>
   Late-stage clinical trials, says Reprogenesis CEO Daniel
Omstead, have shown a majority of patients to be ``clinically
cured.'' The company is also working on creating tissue-engineered
answers to the problems women face after breast surgery, including
mastectomies.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lysaght, a Brown University biomedical engineer, found
that the capital value of the companies in the field today is $3.5
billion and growing at a rate of 21 percent a year. He reported his
findings in Tissue Engineering (yes, the field has its own
journal.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, tissue engineering is like a lot of biotech and the
money is in the investment rather than sales. There has not yet
been a really significant revenue-producing product, so it is a
huge act of faith,'' Lysaght said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is an awfully good bet. In general, the potential
clearly justifies the investment that people are putting into it.
If you look at the first generation of high-tech medical devices,
pacemakers, heart valves, none of those things existed in 1960.
They now account for something like $200 billion of the $3 trillion
spent on health care around the world. Tissue engineering is the
next generation of those kinds of products. ... It is one thing to
invest in a second- generation pacemaker, but the really gutsy move
is the first-generation pacemaker. And that's where people are
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Announcements earlier this month that researchers at the
University of Wisconsin and Johns Hopkins University had tamed a
human embryonic stem cell, which has the potential to form any of
the 210 kinds of cells in the human body, only further excites
people who believe tissue engineering will do for medicine in the
21st century what drug therapies did for medicine in this century.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the potential to design human tissue to meet the
shortage needs for organs,'' says Dr. Peter C. Johnson, president
of the Pittsburgh Tissue Engineering Initiative. ``In the meantime,
tissue can be generated in real time _ in the next few years _ to
meet the need for reconstructive surgery, cartilage, tendon, skin
and bone. And the component tissue will take up the blood supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``What tissues do is, they allow you to provide `smart therapy'
to a diseased state.'' Johnson said. ``At some point in the future,
you will give the drug one time, in this case tissue. If a person's
face is paralyzed, you will put muscle in the face, they will smile
again and won't need drugs. You will put an organ in and they don't
need dialysis. How long in the future we will have to wait is not
known.''
</P>
<P>
   (Matthew Brelis is the Globe's Focus writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
