<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY DO KIDS HEAR AND SEE BETTER? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Why do kids see and hear better than adults?
</P>
<P>
   J.S., Peabody, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. One on one, any adult with good vision can see as well as any
kid with good vision; 20-20 is 20-20, whether you're 10, 20, 40, or
80. But across the population, more adults will need help to see
well, from glasses and contacts to surgery. The reason lies in the
way cells behave in the lens of the eye.
</P>
<P>
   The lens sits behind the iris, which lies behind the
liquid-filled aqueous humor compartment, which is under the cornea,
the outer layer of the eye. By changing shape from rounder to more
oval and back again, the lens helps us focus and adjust for the
distance of what we see. The lens is the size and shape of a
smallish button with a rounded top.
</P>
<P>
   Only cells on the surface of the lens have the ability to
replicate. As new cells grow on the surface, the older cells get
pushed farther back into the middle, which gradually becomes denser
and stiffer. The muscles that pull the lens into a more oval shape
to focus on things farther away can still do their job. But the
less-elastic lens doesn't spring back to the rounder shape it needs
to be in for seeing things closer up.
</P>
<P>
   That creates presbyopia, a common condition in people over 45,
in which the lens can no longer focus accurately on close things
and we need glasses to read.
</P>
<P>
   The aging lens causes another eye problem more typical in
adults. As those older cells are pushed into the middle of the
lens, it goes from clear to opaque, blocking some of the light.
That condition is called a cataract.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing is like vision. Any adult who can hear well, hears as
well as any kid. But more adults have trouble hearing than kids,
because with age hair cells and nerves in the cochlea, the inner
ear, break down and don't regenerate.
</P>
<P>
   The cochlea is a spiral, fluid-filled duct lined with sensitive
hairs. Incoming sound waves create pressure on the fluid and cause
it to move. That makes the hairs wiggle. They're connected to nerve
cells that translate the movement of the hairs into signals that
the brain ultimately translates as sound.
</P>
<P>
   Chronic exposure to high levels of sound can cause these
delicate hairs and nerves to deteriorate. (Short-term exposure
generally results in only short-term hearing loss.
</P>
<P>
   Aging commonly causes the same breakdown. This kind of hearing
loss in the elderly is called presbycussis. It affects different
people at different ages, depending on the kinds of sounds they've
been exposed to over their lifetimes, their general health, and
their genetic predisposition.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it only affects how well someone can hear ... the
volume. Hearing aids can help restore most of that loss. Sometimes
presbycussis also affects how well someone understands what they
hear ... clarity. Sounds come in garbled instead of clear. Hearing
aids are only just now being developed to deal with that kind of
problem.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 1339EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981130.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4766 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-DIET-BOS &LR;      11-30 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DIET-BOS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rachel Gray picked at her bagel and cream cheese as she sipped a
bottle of Chillers juice in her school cafeteria. Almost every day,
that's what she eats for lunch. Nothing more. Most of the time, she
leaves off the cream cheese.
</P>
<P>
   At 5-foot-5 and 120 pounds, she's slim in her size 3 jeans. Yet,
she says, ``I wish my thighs were a lot smaller.''
</P>
<P>
   Her age? Twelve.
</P>
<P>
   Many of her classmates at Brown Middle School in Newton, Mass.
eat just as little, and some even skip lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of girls say they're fat, but they're not at all,'' said
Naomi Rotstein, 12, sipping low-fat chocolate milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``At lunch, look around and you'll see girls who don't eat. They
just drink something,'' said Marie Iagulli, 11.
</P>
<P>
   For those who thought dieting and obsessing about weight and fat
grams was something that begins in high school, guess again. Recent
studies show that diet-ing _ and associated eating disorders _ have
crept into childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very scary. They're bombarded by this culture of thinness
and their parents are gearing them in that direction,'' said Dr.
Cyndi Koch, director of the Renfrew Center in New Jersey, a women's
health center, where she treats an increasing number of
grade-school girls who have eating disorders.
</P>
<P>
   Koch said parents call her, sometimes alarmed that their
daughters are gaining weight just before puberty _ something that's
natural and helps girls develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the culture of thinness, people are getting their
kids to eat low-fat,'' Koch said. ``So you see girls, 8 and 9, who
are dissatisfied with their bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   Janet Bode, a book author, was curious. She had been hearing
stories of young girls who were dieting but wanted to get a better
idea of how bad the situation was. So she surveyed 100 eighth
graders on Long Island, asking them about their eating habits.
</P>
<P>
   Half of them had been on a diet at least once, she found, and 12
percent had forced themselves to vomit, a symptom of bulimia.
</P>
<P>
   Her findings led to her 1997 book, ``Food Fight: A Guide to
Eating Disorders for Pre-Teens and Their Parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Bode said she also visited schools across the country. ``I asked
students to try (to write) about what they would change about
themselves,'' Bode said. ``They wrote things like, `I look like
Shamu the whale,' `I hate my body.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's shocking, isn't it?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Timothy Brewerton, professor of psychiatry and behavioral
sciences and the director of the Eating Disorders Program at
Medical University of South Carolina, said America is just waking
up to this fact because researchers haven't studied younger
populations until recent years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Brewerton and two colleagues conducted one of the first
studies on eating habits of grade-school children.
</P>
<P>
   They surveyed 3,175 students in grades five to eight and found
that 42 percent wanted to lose weight, 31.4 percent had dieted, 4.8
percent had induced vomiting, and 2.4 percent had taken diet pills.
Three percent had used either laxatives or diuretics to lose
weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no indication that it's getting any better,''
Brewerton said. ``Other studies have looked at young-er kids and
found simliar results. Some studies of preschool children have
indicated they have negative attitudes about overweight people.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the same messages that brainwash adults _ advertisements
flaunting the physiques of slender models _ have seeped into the
subconscious of younger girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They also see it in their mothers who are pretty preoccupied
with their weight,'' Brewerton said. ``This can't help but affect
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Although pediatricians are seeing an increase in the number of
children with eating disorders, American children _ like adults _
are becoming heavier. That's because of a lack of exercise and
diets heavy on junk foods that are fatty, high in calories, and not
very nutritious.
</P>
<P>
   For grade-school girls who diet there are obvious health
concerns. If girls don't get enough vitamins, protein, and even fat
in their diet, they may not fully develop. But Brewerton says even
more dangerous are mental health concerns.
</P>
<P>
   He said white girls are more likely to report a dissatisfaction
with their bodies than girls who are African-American, Latino, or
Asian, but that doesn't mean girls of color are less likely to
obsess about weight.
</P>
<P>
   Students peer into the cafeteria kitchen at Brown Middle School
in Newton, a randomly chosen school that a reporter visited on a
recent day. Many students, especially the girls, passed up the
lasagna, vegetable, and garlic bread entree. Instead, many reached
for bagels _ the most popular lunch item on the menu, according to
Principal Judith Malone-Neville.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girls are more label conscious,'' Malone-Neville said. ``They
like salads and ask for yogurt.''
</P>
<P>
   She said a family and consumer science class, which is a
modern-day version of health and home economics rolled into one,
includes lessons on nutrition and proper eating habits. All
students take the course by the time they graduate, which she hopes
will keep students away from junk food and incomplete meals.
</P>
<P>
   But the lesson girls seem to be getting is that they have to eat
skimpy meals so they can lose weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``For breakfast, I have a banana or a NutriGrain bar,'' says
Rachel Gray, 12. ``For lunch, I'll have a berry bagel, plain, and
an iced tea. I'm a vegetarian. For dinner, I usually have fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Margo Mosher, 13, eats one slice of toast or a half-bagel for
breakfast with water or apple juice. For lunch, she eats a peanut
butter and jelly sandwich and has pasta for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Sherman, 13, eats cereal with skim milk for breakfast.
For lunch, she usually eats nonfat key lime yogurt with a cup of
dry Cheerios, a piece of fruit, juice and ``sometimes an Oreo. ...
I can't eat more than one.'' But, she says, she eats a big dinner:
tacos, pizza, pasta _ whatever her parents make.
</P>
<P>
   While Sherman says she's never dieted, she believes most of her
female classmates are concerned with their weight. ``I'd say 90
percent are very conscious and would, if they could, lose some
weight. But they don't have eating disorders,'' Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Iagulli, 11, agrees: ``They think guys would like them
more if they were skinnier.''
</P>
<P>
   While eating a bagel and cream cheese for lunch, Iagulli said
she takes calcium, iron, and vitamin supplements because she knows
she's not getting enough in her vegetarian diet. Her mother, Sharon
Iagulli, said she spoke to Marie's pediatrician before getting the
supplements.
</P>
<P>
   Iagulli said she took a soy cooking class so she could make
dishes for Marie with lots of protein. But Marie didn't care for
soy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her if she gets sick, this is not going to continue,''
Iagulli said. ``She looks and seems pretty healthy. She has plenty
of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman, who is a size 1, said, ``I'm pretty happy with how I
look but if I could change something I'd make my stomach smaller.''
But her mother says Sherman wouldn't have said that if the topic
wasn't on weight and dieting.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Sherman, a psychologist, said her daugher isn't body
conscious, just health conscious.
</P>
<P>
   ``She loves key lime yogurt. She would definitely eat it if it
had fat in it,'' Sherman said. ``She's not too thin. I think she's
pretty perfect, but of course she's my daughter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 1341EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981130.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4769 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CITIES-2TAKES-BOS     11-30 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CITIES-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW VIEW OF ORIGIN OF CITIES 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The old view of how cities and civilizations began _ and the
one that's still being taught in many schools _ was simple and
straightforward. Sometime around 5,000 to 6,000 years ago or
earlier, the story went, humans learned to grow crops and
domesticate animals, and almost immediately this led to an
explosion of developments: Cities were built, complex social
organization arose, and advanced civilizations grew and flourished.
</P>
<P>
   It was an appealing and reasonable story. But as a variety of
archeological sites around the world are making increasingly clear,
it's a story that simply doesn't hold up. The emergence of
agriculture, animal domestication, cities, and civilizations are
all intertwined, to be sure, but in ways far more complex and
varied than the old cause-and-effect view.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that in many places, people lived in large
settlements for centuries, or even millenia, before developing the
agricultural base that was thought to have made such settlements
possible. In other places, agriculture developed for millenia
without giving rise to cities or civilizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so simple,'' said Guillermo Algaze, a professor of
anthropology at the University of California, Berkeley, in an
interview last week. ``What has become clear now is that
agriculture and sedentism'' _ meaning settled life in permanent
villages _ ``are no longer so closely related. It used to be
thought that they were two sides of the same coin. Now, especially
in the Near East, it's clear that there was sedentism long before
agriculture.''
</P>
<P>
   And, conversely, at some sites _ especially in South and Central
America _ it is becoming clear that at least some kinds of
agriculture were being practiced for thousands of years before
permanent settlements began to appear. Rather than developing
quickly and bringing social and economic changes in its wake, the
domestication of plants and animals was a long, slow process full
of fits and starts and occasional blind alleys. And rather than a
single pattern, it appears to have procee-ded very differently in
different regions, with major variations around the world in the
kinds of plants and animals that were used by early populations.
</P>
<P>
   It was only when the process of taming and controlling nature
had been so fully mastered that there were substantial surpluses of
food that large settlements usually followed, Algaze said.
</P>
<P>
   The key to this emerging understanding is to ``separate
agriculture, as the underpinning of civilization, from the early
stages of the domestication of plants,'' said Deborah Pearsall, an
archeologist at the University of Missouri who studies the earliest
evidence of plant domestication in the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   Most earlier archeologists, she said, assumed that the origins
of agriculture would be found in and around the sites of the
earliest great cities. Not so, it turns out. In most cases,
agriculture had been developing slowly for many centuries and in
many locations before it led to the establishment of such cities.
</P>
<P>
   Domestication of plants and animals is ``an evolutionary
process,'' Pearsall said. ``It's a process, not just an event.''
</P>
<P>
   This changing view, still unfolding as several important sites
are going through more detailed excavations and analysis, was
highlighted in a series of articles in the Nov. 22 issue of the
journal Science.
</P>
<P>
   This reassessment has come from a combination of factors. New
excavations are underway in regions that have been little studied.
Many significant sites in the Near East, for example, were long
closed to research because of wars and political tensions, such as
the Kurdish regions of Turkey, but they are now accessible and
being studied again. And advances in scientific tools permit a
better analysis of existing sites, including more-precise dating of
small samples, and improved ways to find and identify small remains
of plants and animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, archeologists had a limited amount of information
to work with,'' said Bruce Smith, director of archeobiology at the
Smithsonian's National Museum of Natural History in Washington.
``Now, there is so much more information, we're getting the
details. It's getting more complex and interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who wrote a book called ``Emergence of Agriculture'' that
has just been published in paperback, said that some of the key
contributions to the new understanding have emerged from research
in Central and South America. Clear evidence is turning up there,
through microscopic analysis of ancient plant remains, that shows
squash, tubers, and beans were being planted and harvested for as
long as 6,000 years before any signs of settlements and large-scale
agriculture show up.
</P>
<P>
   During that long interval, Smith said, ``domesticated plants
filled a relatively small role in their economy,'' which continued
to be based on a largely hunter-gatherer lifestyle. ``So, it's not
exactly a rapid expressway of development leading from
domestication of plants to a full agricultural economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The flip-side of that coin are some large settlements in Turkey,
such as Catalhoyuk, which dates back about 9,000 years. When first
excavated in the 1950s and 60s by British archeologist James
Mellaart, it was by far the earliest known large settlement, nearly
a third of a mile across and supporting a population of perhaps
10,000 people at its peak. It contained cattle bones as well as
depictions of the animals in murals and sculpture _ evidence, in
the prevailing view at the time, that the site may have been one of
the first places where cattle were domesticated.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
