<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4771 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INCA-GOLD-HNS &LR;      11-30 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INCA-GOLD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR YOUNG PRODUCERS, `INCA GOLD' A TREASURE IN THE MAKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE GANAHL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If David Ultan and Adam Ballachey had known two
years ago that their lives would be turned upside down by filming a
documentary about Inca treasure, would they still have done it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Ultan said. ``It was tough, and it cost us
dearly, but it was worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the two-year process of making ``The Search for Inca Gold,''
which aired Sunday on the A&AMP;E network, the 31-year-old producers
endured endless delays, exhaustion, lack of funding leading to
personal debt and even a sudden death within the group. But never
once did they think about quitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell, how could we have?'' Ballachey said with a laugh. ``This
thing became a force of nature, with a life of its own. We couldn't
have gotten off that bus if we'd wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides,'' he said, ``It was a great story. We wanted to see
how it would end.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, ``Inca Gold,'' part of the Peabody Award-winning series
``The New Explorers,'' is nothing if not a ripping yarn. Filmed in
the rugged Ecuadorean Andes, ``Inca Gold'' has history, villainy,
derring-do, genius scientists and charismatic treasure hunters.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-minute documentary involves a high-tech goose chase for
archaeological remains and buried treasure, about $3 billion worth
of gold, reportedly hidden from the marauding Spaniards 400 years
ago by the dying Inca nation. Innumerable treasure hunters have
died seeking the treasure in the treacherous Llanganati region of
the Andes. But while their search was always ground-level, this one
was in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Using ground-penetrating radar technology developed by a team at
the Stanford Research Institute headed by Dr. Roger Vickers, the
documentarians flew over the region in a twin-engine plane. After
gathering data, the plan was to return to the Stanford Research
Institute and process the results, looking for irregularities that
would indicate Inca roads or ruins.
</P>
<P>
   It's fair to say that the results yielded both good and bad
news. The Llanganati _ the area presumed to be the resting place
for the tons of gold _ proved too rugged a terrain for the radar to
take proper readings. But a nearby site, flatter and more open,
which was surveyed to test the equipment, showed conclusive
evidence of Inca ruins.
</P>
<P>
   Vickers, 60, points to a computer screen at the Stanford
Research Institute. ``You see remnants here of a road, a wall,
possibly a farmhouse. And these other dots, they're probably
farmhouses.'' He grinned broadly. ``So at least we know the
technology works.''
</P>
<P>
   Better news still, which was unreported in ``Inca Gold,'' is
that Dr. John Rick, the Stanford archaeologist who plays a major
role in the documentary, has made a discovery of his own using
similar technology in Peru.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say too much about it,'' he said, noting that if he
gave the location, treasure hunters would be swarming the area.
``But it's an already-explored area of ruins that predate the Inca
by perhaps two or three thousand years. We have found something
inside the ruins using radar that is a 3-meter by 3-meter cube.
Possibly an undiscovered tomb, which could give us important
information about who these people were.''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe treasure? Rick smiled indulgently. After all, he is a
scientist, not a gold-crazy explorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   The group, perhaps knowing they were there for the ``right''
reasons, was undaunted by the legend of an Inca curse surrounding
the treasure, despite gruesome true stories that abounded of
veteran explorers who would become disoriented and plunge to their
deaths off cliffs, become impaled on sharp branches, kill
themselves when the disappointment proved too much.
</P>
<P>
   And although Ultan is shown in the film nearly taking a header
over a cliff during the grueling ground exploration of the area,
everyone survived the filming process. All but one.
</P>
<P>
   Diego Arias, perhaps the most famous treasure hunter in Ecuador,
who had been into the Llanganati some 70 times, died suddenly in a
freak car accident between the two filming trips. In perhaps the
film's most poignant moment, Arias is heard muttering to himself as
he peers through his binoculars: ``I love these mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was a moment when I wasn't sure I could go on, it was
when we lost Diego,'' Ultan said. ``He was an amazing guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballachey already has three new proposals in the chute for ``The
New Explorers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``David and I are emblematic of the new opportunities out there
for documentary filmmaking,'' he said, noting the breakthrough
success of nonfiction series like ``The Civil War'' and programs
like A&AMP;E's popular ``Biography.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge is to keep working, more independently all the
time. And someday, maybe documentaries will be funded the way
Hollywood features are. They bring so much more to people's
lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
