<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4773 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KERRY-GRANITE-BOS &LR;      11-30 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KERRY-GRANITE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GO WEST, MR. KERRY, NOT NORTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For a presidential hopeful from Massachusetts, neighboring New
Hampshire's first-in-the-nation primary is seductive indeed.
</P>
<P>
   The Granite State has shown a decided preference for Bay Staters
_ and the national media has treated the results not as a
predictable back-yard benediction, but as a legitimate national
victory.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Massachusetts Governor Michael Dukakis's win in New
Hampshire's presidential primary catapulted him on his way to the
Democratic nomination. In 1992, former US senator Paul Tsongas's
laurels there transformed him from an underfinanced long shot to
Bill Clinton's chief rival for the Democratic nomination. No wonder
US Senator John F. Kerry _ who last week sent out fresh signals
that he'll seek the Democratic presidential nomination _ thinks he
may see gold when he looks toward the White Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the glint could just as easily be fool's gold _ which
is why Kerry must stake a claim in Iowa if he hopes to strike it
rich in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   And he must realize that, New Hampshire toehold notwithstanding,
1998 promises to be a very different year from either 1988 or 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In those years, there was no heir apparent for the Democratic
nomination. Thus the Democratic primary resembled a sorting process
among newcomers, where any of a number of lesser-known candidates
had a credible shot at winning. In such an environment, being known
in New Hampshire was valuable indeed.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1998, Vice President Al Gore will be running as the that
heir, campaigning with the power of two-time incumbency. A race
that involves such a candidate, particularly an incumbent, usually
has room for only two serious candidates: The front-runner whoever
emerges as his principal challenger.
</P>
<P>
   That means the first fight Kerry faces is not so much with Gore
as with the rest of the field so as to emerge as the challenger
best able to take on Gore. And that, in turn, suggests the Iowa
caucuses, the first real contest in the nominating process, will be
particularly important this time around.
</P>
<P>
   Remember 1984? It was US Senator Gary Hart's distant second
there against former Vice President Walter Mondale (16 percent to
Mondale's 48 percent) that separated the Coloradan from the rest of
the field. Even that showing was good enough to establish Hart _
not, as many had expected, Ohio Senator John Glenn _ as the most
credible alternative to Mondale.
</P>
<P>
   Positioned that way, Hart rode a riptide effect to victory in
New Hampshire and across New England and then into the South before
Mondale finally battled back.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa played a less dramatic role in 1988, but only because the
dynamic was different. With no established front-runner, the
caucuses were viewed as much more a first cut, culling a field of
little-knowns _ ``the seven dwarfs,'' the Democrats were derisively
called _ than as a contest that selected the chief challenger to
another two-time incumbent vice president, George Bush, who also
was a heavy favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Still, veterans of Dukakis's campaign say that had he not
managed to stay viable with a third-place finish in Iowa
(collecting 21 percent of the caucus vote to 27 percent for Dick
Gephardt, the congressman from Missouri, and 24 percent for Paul
Simon, the Illinois senator), his support in New Hampshire likely
would have eroded.
</P>
<P>
   The early presidential primaries are essentially a process of
serial elimination. Jack Corrigan, Dukakis's deputy campaign
manager, compares it to the old joke about the two campers charged
by a bear.
</P>
<P>
   When one frantically ties his shoes, scrambles to his feet, and
dashes off, the second yells: ``It's no use. You can't outrun that
bear.'' ``I don't have to outrun the bear,'' the first replies. ``I
just have to outrun you.''
</P>
<P>
   That, says Corrigan, is the reality of the early going: ``If the
bear eats you in Iowa, there is nothing left for New Hampshire. You
have to maintain your viability coming out of Iowa.''
</P>
<P>
   As it was, Gephardt emerged as Dukakis's early rival, despite a
neo-protectionist message that had little to offer booming New
England.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly US Senator Edward M. Kennedy could tell Kerry that
popularity in New Hampshire can neither make nor save a
presidential candidacy. In September 1979, Kennedy led President
Carter by an astounding 48 points, 68 percent to 20 in New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before the Iranian hostage crisis created a
patriotic push that rallied Americans to the theretofore
beleaguered Carter's cause. With Kennedy slipping nationally, New
Hampshire voters declined to rescue him; Kennedy fell to Carter 47
percent to 37, completing his transformation from formidable foe to
injured challenger.
</P>
<P>
   After the campaign, Kennedy acknowledged the Iowa results had
probably doomed his campaign from the start. ``Iowa was probably
the most significant one,'' he said. ``After that, our chances for
success were remote.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Iowa didn't matter because home-state US Senator Tom
Harkin was a candidate, rendering the caucuses there meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   But without Harkin, it's hard to imagine that Tsongas, for all
his grit and determination, would have done as well as he did. His
underfinanced campaign had little traction outside of New England.
And though he had held a solid lead in New Hampshire the previous
fall, when New Hampshire voters started to focus on the choice they
faced, Clinton, then the governor of Arkansas, pulled even and then
passed Tsongas in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in late January, came the allegations that Clinton had
carried on a long-time liaison with Gennifer Flowers, followed
shortly thereafter by the controversy over his efforts to avoid the
draft.
</P>
<P>
   Those controveries sent Clinton tumbling in the polls. Scared
off their first choice, New Hampshire voters retreated back to the
well-known and reassuringly mature Tsongas, who won a 33 to 25
percent victory over Clinton in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Still, had Clinton never faced the Flowers controversy, it's
hard to avoid the conclusion he would have beaten Tsongas in New
Hampshire and ended his before it ever left New England.
</P>
<P>
   So as Kerry ponders his future _ he says he will announce his
decision ``by the turn of the year'' _ what lesson should he take
from history?
</P>
<P>
   First, popularity in New Hampshire alone is unlikely to be
enough to launch a campaign. If a Massachusetts candidate wants to
pitch his presidential tent there, he'd best guy it off with a
solid showing in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Second, a fellow New Englander's New Hampshire advantage is
hardly immune to national trends sweeping the country.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, best to keep the sneakers tied in Iowa: When the
bear charges, a candidate must outrun his rivals if he's to stay
alive in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   (Scot Lehigh is a member of the Globe staff.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 1344EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
