<DOCNO> NYT19981130.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4777 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CITIES-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     11-30 1855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CITIES-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... were domesticated.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But now, using methods developed since the first excavations, a
large team has been back at the site for three years _ and expects
to be there at least another 25 years. Led by British archeologist
Ian Hodder, now at the University of California, Berkeley, team
members are making a much slower, more methodical analysis of the
site than would have been possible before. Where Mellaart and his
team excavated more than 200 houses in four years, Hodder's team of
90 specialists are unearthing just one or two a year.
</P>
<P>
   Mellaart acknowledged the difference in the approach in an
interview last week. ``In those days, we got the experts to come at
the end of the season'' to spend a few days looking over bones,
seeds, and other significant pieces found during a season of
digging. The idea of having botanists, anatomists, and other
specialists right on the site throughout the digging was out of the
question, at a time when there were only a handful of specialists
in the world in identifying such remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays, they do things with such precision,'' he said. But
one result of that painstaking methodology is that it may take a
very long time to build up enough evidence to make a convincing
case about exactly how these early dwellers in a large settlement
lived.
</P>
<P>
   But the preliminary evidence suggests that Catalhoyuk, far from
being a textbook example of the domestication of animals leading to
large settlements, may be quite the opposite. New analysis suggests
that most of the animal bones were from sheep and goats, not
cattle, and that the animals may have been wild, rather than
domesticated. &UR;  &LR; And microscopic examination of human teeth from the
site shows no sign that they were yet eating grains, at least not
in significant amounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in the early days, as for as making any good
conclusions,'' says Nerissa Russell, an archeologist at Cornell
University taking part in the Catalhoyuk dig who specializes in
interpreting animal bones. ``The cattle could be wild or
domestic,'' but there is no sign of the usual reduction in size
that occurs when a species is domesticated.
</P>
<P>
   This characteristic reduction in size _ perhaps a result of
human selection because smaller animals were easier to control, or
perhaps an unintended result of limited diet and mobility _ has
been used as one of the few ways of distinguishing wild from
domesticated animals in old sites. Recently, an additional method
has come into use: Looking at the ratios of old and young animals,
and males to females. Hunters tend to take full-grown animals,
while herders tend to kill most young males and keep a majority of
females for breeding, the theory goes, leading to differences in
the animal populations that can be determined statistically by
studying large numbers of bones.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that may eventually help to clear up the questions in
Catalhoyuk is the extensive artwork. Many houses had elaborate
murals painted on the mud-brick walls, most of them depicting
humans and animals together. Interpreting these scenes may help to
unravel the practices of that early society _ but that may not be
easy. Most of the paintings excavated in the 1960s have crumbled or
been lost, and can be studied only from photographs or drawings,
and no substantial murals have yet been found in the new round of
digging.
</P>
<P>
   The old murals remain hard to figure out. Humans cavort around
large animals, in some cases actually pulling their tails or
tongues. No obvious weapons are seen. ``Are they hunting scenes,
sacrifice scenes, or scenes from dreams or myths?'' Russell
wonders. ``It's hard to know exactly what's going on.... We hope to
have answers in the next few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Other, even earlier large settlements _ though not nearly as
large as Catalhoyuk _ provide clearer evidence, she said. At a
Turkish site called Asaclahoyuk, ``it looks like things are
basically wild,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   These and several other big sites in the Near East and China,
says Hodder, ``appear without any trace of agriculture. You have
large numbers of houses, buildings, temples, all in a society which
is still using wild resources in terms of animals and plants.''
</P>
<P>
   In places like Catalhoyuk and Abu Hureyra, also in Turkey,
Hodder says &UR; , &LR;  ``Agriculture really comes in fairly late in the
process, 1,000 or 2,000 years later, depending on where you are.
There are a whole series of cultural changes that take place before
you get farming.''
</P>
<P>
   One consequence of the recent research, Hodder said, is that
``this is causing a reconsideration of what we call agriculture and
domestication.'' It is becoming clear that these are not practices
that emerge quickly and simply, but that there is usually a long
transitional period where humans exert more and more control over
their plant and animal resources _ and become more dependent on a
few species.
</P>
<P>
   Research in the Near East, as well as in China and Central
America, could provide significant evidence over the next few years
about this intermediate stage _ a stage that Richard MacNeish, an
archeologist based in Andover who pioneered much of the study of
early plant use, dubbed ``incipient agriculture.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said that ``people have tended to focus on evidence for
domestication, and for agricultural economies, and not much on
what's in between.'' But continuing research around the world is
likely to come up with more details about this critical stage of
development _ and its many variations around the world.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-SCI-CITIES-2ND &LR;   &UR; TAKE-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: ... were domesticated. &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But now, using methods developed since the first excavations, a
