</P>
<P>
   One consequence of the recent research, Hodder said, is that
``this is causing a reconsideration of what we call agriculture and
domestication.'' It is becoming clear that these are not practices
that emerge quickly and simply, but that there is usually a long
transitional period where humans exert more and more control over
their plant and animal resources _ and become more dependent on a
few species.
</P>
<P>
   Research in the Near East, as well as in China and Central
America, could provide significant evidence over the next few years
about this intermediate stage _ a stage that Richard MacNeish, an
archeologist based in Andover who pioneered much of the study of
early plant use, dubbed ``incipient agriculture.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said that ``people have tended to focus on evidence for
domestication, and for agricultural economies, and not much on
what's in between.'' But continuing research around the world is
likely to come up with more details about this critical stage of
development _ and its many variations around the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
