<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNISEX JOHNS WON'T WASH WITH WOMEN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   The New York Times reports that a metal distribution company in
Bristol, Conn., is installing a unisex ``Ally McBeal'' style
bathroom in its new facility. Craig Yarde, president of Yarde
Metals, told the Times, ``It started off as a little bit of a joke,
but we think it sends a message that we're all in this together.''
</P>
<P>
   All in what together? What is he talking about?
</P>
<P>
   OK, we may all be in this together in the larger, cosmic,
universal, lashed-to-the-great-wheel-of-being sense. But does that
mean we all have to go into the same company bathroom and do it
together? Is this what sexual equality in the workplace has come
down to?
</P>
<P>
   I don't know if men are thrilled about the concept of unisex
company bathrooms, although I doubt many are. But I do know that
virtually any woman you ask will tell you that it's difficult
enough to share a bathroom with friends and loved ones of the
opposite sex. And now to share with male co-workers? Some of whom
you don't even know?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you might get to know them in a hurry, and better
than you might like, if they were occupying stalls next to yours.
Maybe the water closet will replace the water cooler as the hub of
office gossip, as it seems to have in Ally McBeal's law firm, where
people of both sexes gather to exchange maddeningly fey dialogue.
Does anybody ever actually, you know, go in those scenes? Or do
they just meet there to chat?
</P>
<P>
   Before we go any further, let's pause for a moment to let the
following sink in, once and for all, because I'm getting tired of
repeating myself: ``Ally McBeal'' is fiction.
</P>
<P>
   One of the classic indications of sanity _ as I understand it,
at least _ is the ability to differentiate between reality and
fantasy. Does Craig Yarde honestly think his real live employees
are going to take to his unisex bathroom the way Ally and her
fictional colleagues have taken to theirs?
</P>
<P>
   The Times suggests McBealish bathrooms may be a trend. They
managed to dig up an expert, industrial psychologist Andrew DuBrin,
who claims that unisex facilities are ``increasingly popular among
workers.'' Which workers? Where? If anybody knows, please get in
touch. Meanwhile, pardon me if I refuse to believe these people
exist.
</P>
<P>
   DuBrin also told the Times there was ``one possible benefit'' to
the unisex facilities: ``Bathroom hand-washing among men has
declined quite a bit in recent decades. Maybe this would get them
to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Really, working women don't have enough to do already. Besides,
when it comes to bathroom hand-washing, women are almost as bad as
men. According to a survey of 7,000 Americans, conducted last year
for the American Society of Microbiology, 98 percent of those
interviewed said they always washed their hands after they went to
the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   That's what they said. This is what they did: Researchers
stationed in public restrooms found that only 68 percent actually
wash up afterward. They observed that women are more likely to wash
than men _ 74 percent compared to 61 percent _ but I think it's
fair to say that neither sex has any reason to feel smug about
these figures.
</P>
<P>
   Your mother was right. All sorts of diseases are spread by
people who don't wash their hands after they use the bathroom. It's
not just disgusting, it's unhealthy. If men are more lax about it
than women, well, that's a good reason to resist the unisex
bathroom trend, if there is such a trend, which I doubt, Yarde and
DuBrin not-with-standing.
</P>
<P>
   There are so many other reasons to can the idea, so to speak,
not the least of which is that bathroom gossip would never be the
same. We might all end up sounding as ditsy as the characters on
``Ally McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
