<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SEXUAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DERSHOWITZ FINDS STARR HARD TO DEFEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT L. TURNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
SEXUAL McCARTHYISM 
Clinton, Starr, and the Emerging Constitutional Crisis 
By Alan M. Dershowitz 
Basic Books, 275 pp., $23 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even a novelist would find it hard to conjure up a character
better equipped to sail past the dangers of the Lewinsky affair
than Bill Clinton. His legal background is considerable _ Yale Law
School, attorney general of Arkansas _ and his political deftness
is unmatched. Yet the nexus of politics and the law is what snared
him and spun the nation into a constitutional crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Few probably are surprised that Clinton lacked the moral sense
to avoid a squalid affair with Monica Lewinsky. But it is shocking
that he lacked the political sense to sidestep danger when a
partisan special prosecutor was already out gunning for him, and
that he also lacked the legal sense to stay away from a sworn
deposition and grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   This historic lapse gains occasional perspective from ``Sexual
McCarthyism,'' by Alan M. Dershowitz, the local sage who has proved
himself unavoidable for comment on all things legal and
sensational.
</P>
<P>
   Dershowitz is hard on Clinton, not so much for his infidelity as
for his bad judgment in hitching up with a ``young blabbermouth.''
The Harvard law professor also faults him for a series of legal
blunders that not only threatens his presidency but has created
precedents that will hurt his successors. The affair, however
smutty, never should have produced the damage it did, Dershowitz
argues persuasively.
</P>
<P>
   As the title would suggest, however, Dershowitz is most critical
of Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel. He says Starr is also
obsessed with forbidden sex and has abused his office far more than
Clinton did.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely does a short book like this require the reader to
dispense with so much dross to find so few nuggets. One reason has
to do with time pressure: The book is current through September,
and even contains one short chapter, dated October, speculating
about a possible deal to end the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But the price is heavy. Collected between these hard covers is
nothing more than an assortment of columns and opinion pieces that
are poorly connected, repetitive (four different articles say the
president should not be above or below the law), and often
embarrassingly self-serving _ why, exactly, do we need to hear
Der-sho-witz's contention that he do-nates half his professional
time to pro bono work? A 36-page overview plows much of the same
ground. The writing is festooned with cliches, and some of the
arguments run in contrary directions.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Dershowitz argues that some form of independent
counsel is necessary in our system, but the appointing authority
should not be the judges who now have that role. Sitting judges, he
says, ``should not be in the business of appointing independent
counsel.'' Elsewhere, however, he makes a more dubious argument for
a permanent Independent Office of Public Prosecution within the
Justice Department, headed by someone ``selected on a nonpartisan
basis by a panel of judges or others outside the political
process.''
</P>
<P>
   All that said, the book makes some interesting points, several
of which are articulated with refreshing precision and clarity.
</P>
<P>
   Already well-publicized is Dershowitz's contention that Clinton
should have tried harder to settle the Paula Jones case and,
lacking an agreement, should have simply defaulted rather than
submit to a deposition. Even if this strategy were given the
consideration in January that Dershowitz says it was denied, it
might not have seemed so attractive then. Only in hindsight does it
seem obvious that the political and financial costs to Clinton
would have been far less if he had defaulted.
</P>
<P>
   Of more immediate interest, Dershowitz offers sharp views on key
issues. If Starr had no intention of seeking criminal indictments
against the president, Dershowitz says, he should not have been
able to use a grand jury as an investigative tool.
</P>
<P>
   And on defining proper grounds for impeachment, Dershowitz
summons history and legal logic to argue that personal failings,
even serious ones, should be dealt with separately and that only
governmental misconduct deserves the fundamentally political
sanction of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   For Lewinsky scandal buffs, there is enough here to stimulate
and refine consideration of the moral, legal, political, and
constitutional questions that have combined to threaten a
presidency. With more work, this book could have been a fine
magazine piece.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
