<HEADLINE>
COSTLY CATALOG ITEMS: SHIPPING &AMP; HANDLING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding; includes shipping and handling text table)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN AND BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've ever been skeptical about catalog merchants saying
their pricey ``shipping and handling'' charges barely cover costs,
you might be interested in a new survey on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study in the upcoming Catalog Age, a trade
publication for the mail-order industry, 48 percent of catalog
businesses this year admitted they made a profit from shipping and
handling charges, up from 44 percent the year before. About 41
percent said they broke even, and 11 percent said they lost money.
</P>
<P>
   These findings come as no surprise to many shoppers who say
they're drawn to the time-saving advantages of catalog shopping,
especially during the hectic holiday season, but can't bear the
delivery fees. On a typical $60 order, mail-order companies charge
anywhere from $5.50 to $16.95 for shipping and handling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fees bother me,'' said Mary Johnson, a mother browsing
last week at the Cambridgeside Galleria, which was already heavily
adorned with holiday lights and decorations. ``You're throwing
money away.''
</P>
<P>
   While consumers may be outraged by the fees, the catalog
industry may feel little pressure to change as more Americans get
hooked on the convenience. Catalog sales are projected to total
more than $87 billion this year, a 7.7 percent increase over last
year, according to the Direct Marketing Association in New York, a
mail-order trade group.
</P>
<P>
   The group also reported that more than two-thirds of Americans
last year made a purchase by mail, phone, or computer.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some companies are responding to customer complaints.
Victoria's Secret, an intimate-apparel shop for women, offers free
shipping for orders over $100 until the end of the year. If you
order from certain L.L. Bean catalogs, you can get free regular
FedEx delivery until the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Catalog consultant Jack Schmid of Kansas City, Kan., said the
industry is beginning to wake up to the consumer outcry. He said he
has found more companies experimenting with early-bird promotions,
flat-rate fees, or loyalty programs that give breaks on shipping
and handling charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are showing more sensitivity to customers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even with some discounts, anyone who wants the convenience of
catalog shopping faces hefty shipping and handling fees, usually
based on the total bill, and a sales tax that may have to be paid
to the state where the item is being sent.
</P>
<P>
   A federal rule requires that companies shipping items out of
state must impose that state's sales tax if they have a store or
other business presence there. Therefore, Massachusetts residents
sending clothing as a gift may lose this state's tax exemption on
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Why can't catalog companies base the shipping fee on weight, as
the post office does?
</P>
<P>
   While some do, the growing trend is to assess fees based on the
total bill. Bettye Kahn, spokeswoman for Crate &AMP; Barrel, based in
Wheeling, Ill., said it gets too complicated for businesses to
assess each shipping order based on weight.
</P>
<P>
   At Crate &AMP; Barrel, the shipping and handling fees range from $5
for a $15 order (a 33 percent fee) to $15 for a $150 order (10
percent fee). A more typical $60 order would incur a $10.50
shipping and handling fee _ 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be a few people that we treat unfairly so we can
treat thousands of people fairly,'' she said. ``Hopefully, it evens
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Kahn points out that stores such as Crate &AMP; Barrel that sell
many fragile dishware items are also providing the service of
packaging the items safely for delivery. The thick boxes, tissue
paper, and other packaging materials are costly, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The highest delivery fees appear to be from the food companies.
At Harry and David, the specialty food catalog business, a $60
order costs $16.95 to deliver.
</P>
<P>
   But even some firms sending nonfragile items have high fees. At
Hingham-based Talbots, a women's clothing store, delivery charges
are similar to Crate &AMP; Barrel. A typical $60 order would cost $10
in shipping and handling.
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Thompson, spokeswoman for Talbots, said she believes they
are in the ``middle ground'' of their competitors and that they
also offer such perks as free gift boxes when they deliver.
</P>
<P>
   For those interested in catalog shopping, the best way to reduce
costs is to buy in bulk so that shipping and handling fees are a
lower percentage of the total bill.
</P>
<P>
   Even with price breaks, Kathleen Seiders, marketing professor at
Babson College in Wellesley, Mass., said the catalog industry will
probably flourish because so many people hate shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``People this time of year are looking for ways to not have to
deal with the store or deal with the post office,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Playpen danger.  &LR; This warning came out in the middle of last
week, but we thought it worth mentioning again that the US Consumer
Product Safety Commission has recalled 9.6 million play yards and
playpens with protruding rivets because they can strangle children.
The commission knows of eight cases of toddlers strangling in these
products when their pacifier strings or clothing caught on rivets.
For more information, call the CPSC hotline at 800-638-2772.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a consumer tip, e-mail mohl(at)globe.com or
wen(at)globe.com, or write Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
MAIL-ORDER CONVENIENCE HAS A PRICE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Factors you may want to consider if you are deciding whether to
be a catalog shopper or a do-it-yourself shopper. In the example
below, a Boston resident picks a $68 fleece jacket from Talbots and
wants the gift shipped to someone in Chicago. The item weighs about
1.5 pounds. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CATALOG SELF  &QL; 
Item $68 $68  &QL; 
Shipping &AMP; handling charge(1)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $10 $3  &QL; 
Tax $4.25(2) $0  &QL; 
Total $82.25 $71.00  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Difference  &QL; 
By catalog, the shopper pays $11.25 or 16 percent more than
do-it-yourself shopping and mailing.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Other issues  &QL; 
You can shop from home at any hour, and you're spared a trip to the
mall and post office.  &QL; 
You can handle the item you select, which may reduce the chances
that you'll have to go through the trouble of returning an item.  &QL; 
(1) Talbots uses the US Postal Service for its regular shipping
services, but sets fees based on the customer's total bill. We had
our do-it-yourself shopper also mail by US Postal Service, where
fees were based on the item's weight. &QL; 
(2) Based on a federal ruling, the company must impose sales tax if
it is shipping a package to a state where it has a store or other
business presence. The customer pays the sales tax rate of the
state where the package is being sent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOURCE: Store and Postal Service &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
