<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAZDA CELEBRATES ON PEARL HARBOR DAY: YULE GIFT IDEAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R. WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Auto companies do strange things to promote the corporate image,
brand awareness, or a car. Mazda has, it seems to me, gone the
corporate equivalent of bonkers.
</P>
<P>
   I have been receiving a series of fancy, four-color invitations
that open with the question: ``Pondering your news options for
December 7th?'' Below that, next to a rendering of Rodin's famous
sculpture, The Thinker, is the admonition: ``It's time to think ...
'' and inside it continues: ``out of the box.''
</P>
<P>
   Now we get to the heart of it. It informs that more than 3,000
``creative, intelligent, dare-to-be different personalities'' vied
for the title of ``Out-Of-The-Box Individual'' and the list has
been pared to ``five'' finalists: Marisa Tomei, actress; Jane
Krakowski, actress; Dennis Rodman, hoopster; Judge Mills Lane,
boxing referee; Eric Fogel, creator of MTV's Celebrity Deathmatch
(I'm not making this up); Mother Love, TV talk show host who
specializes in prompting embarrassing confessions. You have noticed
that six people are listed? Anybody who would hold Rodman up as an
intelligent, creative candidate for public honors couldn't be
expected to be good with numbers.
</P>
<P>
   One of these will be named to receive the Mazda Protege
Out-Of-The-Box Award. Protege is the car they're promoting.
</P>
<P>
   Come join them for this ``break-from-the-herd media event'' Dec.
7 in New York, Mazda implores.
</P>
<P>
   Putting aside the tastelessness of asking an American journalist
to celebrate Dec. 7 with a Japanese company (I know the war's long
over but would Ford invite Japanese to celebrate Aug. 6, the
anniversary of the Hiroshima bombing?), why would any journalist
consider that choosing the head idiot from among this gang is a
news event. OK, I'll give the actresses the benefit of the doubt;
acting is an honorable calling and if they do anything strange
offstage, I don't know about it nor do I care, either.
</P>
<P>
   I know the Protege _ it's a nice car scheduled for review here _
and everybody knows Bad Boy Rodman, but why would a corporation
concerned for its image be throwing a party to honor a jerk like
that?
</P>
<P>
   The sad thing is there will be some journalists in New York on
Monday, Dec. 7, with not much else to do, and there is the usual
long list of professional guests pretending to credentials who will
go to the opening of an envelope if free food is involved, who can
be counted upon to fill the hall. Auto companies desperately in
search of good words for bad cars depend on these people and public
relations firms seem to bill according to the head count at the
event. Since Mazda isn't making bad cars, why this desperate bid
for notoriety?
</P>
<P>
   Mazda, this gets my vote for Most Tasteless Event of Decade.
Mazda should can the PR genius who dreamed this up; PR agents are
supposed to get a company talked about, not laughed at. And just
how does this sell Proteges?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Christman looms, so, in the spirit of the season, we offer our
annual shopping suggestions for the difficult person on your list
who owns a car. Buy for the car or buy car-related.
</P>
<P>
   A decent flashlight, especially one that plugs into a cigar
lighter or auxiliary socket, can make a welcome gift. Totes, the
umbrella maker, offers an interesting two-fer this year, a brolly
with a flashlight in the handle, about $20. The light is slightly
offset so that it illuminates the ground ahead of you while using
the bumbershoot on a rainy night, but it doubles as a handy light,
if you leave the umbrella in the car _ it's a compact that will fit
quite nicely in most door bins. One drawback: You need a small
phillips-head screwdriver to replace the two AA batteries in the
handle.
</P>
<P>
   Maps are always welcome. Delorme offers road atlases for Maine,
Vermont, New Hamphire and a few other states. There are also good
volumes of city/town street maps for eastern and western sections
of Massachusetts and all of New Hampshire's various municipalities
_ all this stuff is available in bookstores for reasonable money.
For the heavy-duty traveler, check the map supplies at interstate
truck stops where you can find a complete United States road atlas
with all the pages laminated in plastic for 20 bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Books are always a good thought and the world abounds with
specialty books based on certain cars, books about the business
(such as ``Glory Days,'' reviewed here last week, from Robert
Bentley Publisher, 800-423-4595). For less reading and more photos,
something like ``Sixties American Cars,'' written and photographed
by journalist Dan Lyons, published by Motorbooks (800-826-6600,
$12.95). Lavishly illustrated, Lyons's tome captures the spirit and
iron of the decade that was the heyday of the muscle car.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons is also noted for his car calendar photography on
BrownTrout calendar editions and some of Hemmings Motor News
offerings. Brown Trout lists a slew of motor calendars showcasing
Mustangs, Camaros, Porsche, Corvette, Cadillac, Chevrolet, Ford,
Jaguar, and convertibles and exotics ($10.99 each, telephone
800-777-7812). Hemmings offers its '99 edition of the classic
old-cars-abandoned series that it initiated showing derelicts in
various scenic locales. In addition, Hemmings offers calendars
dedicated to antique pickup trucks, cars of the '50s and muscle
cars ($9.95 each, telephone 800-227-4373, ext. 550.
</P>
<P>
   Hemmings also offers various automobilia and is becoming well
known for its series of collector truck banks _ for a catalogue,
should this intrigue you, telephone 800-442-3100.
</P>
<P>
   Auto retailers have hopped on the automobilia bandwagon and
these days many showrooms offer a boutique of marque-related stuff
from pricey pewter sculptures and key chains to models of the
individual cars.
</P>
<P>
   A decent tire pressure gauge _ some electronic models are
currently available _ is a handy stocking stuffer and, if you're
really stumped, a book of tickets to a car wash is a very good
idea.
</P>
<P>
   If you've got a few hundred in spare cash, you might also
consider the young driver in your family for a gift of training in
an advanced driving school _ Skip Barber in Lakeville, Conn.
(telephone 860-435-1300) or Sandy Stevens in New Hampshire
(800-594-4193) are the closest to the Boston area. Hey, a gift of
advanced driver training could be a gift of life as well as the
gift of a lifetime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
