<HEADER>
A4789 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANIMALS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-30 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMALS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO-STEPPING WITH FOUR PAWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've done it before, admit it. We've all done it. But we had
the decency to do it in the privacy of our own homes. However, in
today's permissive society, in which anything goes, people are
doing it right out in public.
</P>
<P>
   Dancing with dogs, that is.
</P>
<P>
   It is the latest competitive ``sport'' that's sweeping the
country, or maybe just whisk-brooming the country..
</P>
<P>
   It's not the kind of dog dancing most of us remember from
childhood, when you would pick up your dog's front paws and in a
moment of exuberance, dance around the living room until the dog
gnawed at your hands or your mother yelled, ``Leave the poor dog
alone!''
</P>
<P>
   In ``musical canine freestyle,'' owners and dogs perform
``dance-oriented footwork in time to the music.'' And the rules
specify that you can't do anything to endanger the dog, so ixnay on
grabbing those front paws. Basically, you dance to the music and
the dog sticks close. Each routine is supposed to tell a story.
</P>
<P>
   Patie Ventre is the national guru of the freestyle competition.
She is the force behind creating the World Canine Freestyle
Organization, which is so newly minted that it doesn't have
membership dues set or even a membership list yet. But there is a
mailing list of 8,000 people worldwide. There are freestylers in
Australia, Switzerland, Greece, Turkey, and in African countries.
Ventre and her group's doggie Rockettes have recently been featured
on NBC and CNN (the reporter from the latter network compared the
virile energy of a golden retriever named Lookie to that of John
Travolta).
</P>
<P>
   If you want to trip the paw fantastic, to merengue with your
mutt, polka with your puli, or cha-cha with your chow chow, the
group says don't be intimidated. ``Being a dancer is not
necessary,'' the Pup-Peroni freestyle brochure reassures, though
``some sense of rhythm is helpful.'' Your dog should be
``accomplished in heeling.'' Ventre estimates that it should take
about three to six months to work up a routine. Part of the process
is finding out ``which music your dog responds to best.'' Foxtrot,
perhaps? That's easy for some of us _ it's the sound of kibble
hitting the dish, but it just doesn't have a beat.
</P>
<P>
   As for musical ideas, Ventre says that at the recent ``Nature's
Recipe Footloose Fantasy Freestyle Event'' in Houston, the waltz
``God Bless Texas,'' performed by a Chihuahua mix, brought tears to
the eyes of the crowd. (An encore of ``The Yellow Rose of Texas''
might have put the audience on stretchers.) Donna Duford and her
fuzzy little petit basset griffon vendeen will be doing Judy
Garland (not to mention Toto) proud with ``Get Happy'' at Bayside.
</P>
<P>
   But besides a catchy tune, you need a snappy outfit. Performers
``must costume up,'' according to Ventre. Unfortunately, that other
great tradition, making your long-suffering dog wear clothes, is
not allowed, though the dog's collar must match the handler's
attire.
</P>
<P>
   Do certain breeds dominate the field? Of course a Border collie,
the thinking dog's athlete, will often do well, but Ventre says
there are many mixed breeds and surprising entries, such as
bloodhounds and Newfoundlands.
</P>
<P>
   The competition is divided into three levels: novice,
intermediate, and advanced. There are competitions for one person,
one dog; two handlers, two dogs; and team, three or more handlers,
each with a dog. Judging, Ventre points out, is like the Olympics,
with scores from 1.0 to 10 on technical merit and artistic
impression.
</P>
<P>
   Freestyle has been around since the early '90s and Ventre says
she has been overwhelmed with the amount of media attention the
``sport'' has received. Now if only Kevin Costner had changed his
film's title to ``Dances With Pugs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
