Tuesday on the consequences of perjury. Judiciary staff takes
deposition of Nathan Landow. Also: the special investigator probing
accusations that Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's office leaked
grand jury material could report to a federal judge today.
Meanwhile, reports indicate that Starr is considering stepping down
in about four months. (Carr, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TJOFLAT _ One of the witnesses the Republicans on the
Judiciary Committee are calling Tuesday to discuss the importance
of perjury is Gerald Tjoflat, the chief judge of the Atlanta-based
11th Circuit Court. (Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TV _ WASHINGTON _ In the midst of an impeachment threat,
President Clinton has found that television news has been
friendlier to him than to his chief foe. A private media watchdog
group found that, aside from the scandal, 80 percent of the network
news TV ``sound bites'' on his job performance were positive.
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's coverage has been only 15
percent positive, only slightly better than Saddam Hussein fared on
the evening news programs during the Persian Gulf war. For the
White House, powerful pictures and a TV-savvy president have been
crucial to scandal management, experts say. (Malone, Cox News
Service)
</P>
