<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
!! 1/2 ``Babe: Pig in the City''  There's more city than story in
this sequel, as the talking pig, on a mission to save the farm,
journeys to an American city as it might be reproduced in a Vegas
theme park. What he saves are a bunch of dogs and primates facing
cruel and menacing dangers that might be too dark for younger
viewers' comfort levels. (G)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (FR) &LR; !!! &UR; 1/2 ``A Bug's Life'' &LR;  The ``Toy Story'' creators move
outside, into a luminously green natural world, beautifully
detailed. Their story of a misfit ant who redeems himself by saving
the colony from rapacious grasshoppers doesn't have the wit of the
similarly themed ``Antz,'' but exceeds it in all other respects.
(G)
</P>
<P>
   !!! &UR; ``Destiny''  &LR; Egypt's Youssef Chahine bends Hollywood's
old-fashioned way of filming historical epics to the service of a
biofilm about the 12th-century Islamic philosopher Averroes, whose
books were burned, but whose teachings survive. It's heartfelt and
enlightening on the achievements of Islamic civilization and on its
history of being menaced by fundamentalists, with a solid centering
performance by Nour el-Cherif as the wise, humane teacher. But it's
also tongue-in-cheek enough to throw in a little song and dance
when needed. (Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   ! &UR; 1/2 ``Very Bad Things''  &LR; Actor Peter Berg's filmmaking debut
isn't a very bad movie, just a relentlessly tiring one about a
bachelor party that goes murderously wrong. The one bright spot is
Cameron Diaz's maniacal bride-to-be, who is determined to let
nothing interfere with her wedding. (R) (Renee Graham)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe movie critic Jay Carr's entire archive of reviews may be
retrieved from Boston.com, the Globe's on-line service on the
Internet's World Wide Web; key words ``movie reviews.'')
</P>
