<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND RECOMMENDED RECENTLY REVIEWED BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ``The Love of a Good Woman'' &LR;  by Alice Munro (Knopf, $24).
Eight new stories by the Canadian master of the form.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``The Hours''  &LR; by Michael Cunningham (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$22). A lovely triumph, both a re-imagining of the story of
Virginia Woolf's modernist classic ``Mrs. Dalloway'' and an homage
to the original.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Samuel Johnson: The Life of an Author'' &LR;  by Lawrence Lipking
(Harvard University Press, $35). A biography that concentrates on
Dr. Johnson the writer, not the wit or ``character.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``The Life of Thomas More'' &LR;  by Peter Ackroyd (Nan A. Talese/
</P>
<P>
   Doubleday, $30). A scrupulous treatment of the ``man for all
seasons,'' and of the passing of the Middle Ages in England.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``A Man in Full'' &LR;  by Tom Wolfe (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$28.95). A sweeping novel of power, wealth, and the New South.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Mary Baker Eddy'' &LR;  by Gillian Gill (Perseus, $35). The story
of the founder of Christian Science, from hardscrabble farm to
international triumph, seems to exemplify the principle that the
Lord helps those who help themselves.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Bech at Bay,'' &LR;  by John Updike (Knopf, $23). Henry Bech, the
novelist's alter ego, sallies forth to confront his own mortality.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Evening'' &LR;  by Susan Minot (Knopf, $23). Written as the
recollections of a woman on her death- bed, this novel casts a
clear light on a long life and a lost love.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``The Story of American Freedom'' &LR;  by Eric Foner (Norton,
$27.95). A thoughtful, readable history of the most highly esteemed
and least well-understood of American virtues.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Like Never Before'' &LR;  by Ehud Havazelet (Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux, $23). Lyrical, tender, bitter stories about three
generations of a Jewish American family.
</P>
</TEXT>
