<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4798 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MANHUNT-RUDOLPH-BOS &LR;      11-30 1775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANHUNT-RUDOLPH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HUNT FOR RANDOLPH, G-MEN FIND SOUTHERN DISCOMFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANDREWS, N.C. _ The hunt begins with breakfast at the Huddle
House, an island of biscuits and gravy in the predawn darkness.
</P>
<P>
   At tables just feet apart, two separate groups of men talk about
the weather, the news, everything but their prey. They speak only
to one another, never to the men across the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   As light breaks over the maddeningly dense forest that surrounds
and beckons them, they move quickly to pay their separate bills,
then exit to their separate cars, and that is when the first of
many deep-rooted differences reveals itself.
</P>
<P>
   One group piles into a pickup truck carrying caged hounds, the
signature vehicle for country-bred bear hunters. The other group
slides into a gray Crown Victoria, the signature car for city-bred
G-men on a manhunt. They leave in opposite directions.
</P>
<P>
   As that scene played out last week, 293 days had passed since
the start of authorities' search for Eric Robert Rudolph, the man
accused in fatal bombings at a Birmingham, Ala., abortion clinic
and at the Atlanta Olympics. The day began and ended like every
other since Rudolph disappeared in the woods near this western
North Carolina town on Jan. 30.
</P>
<P>
   What happened in between revealed in a hundred small ways why
the shotgun marriage between federal agencies and a mountain hamlet
has become badly strained. Pieced together, those elements offered
a possible explanation for why the search has taken so long with so
little apparent progress.
</P>
<P>
   Among the locals, at least, much of the blame is placed on
federal agents' textbook approach _ in the town as well as in the
wild _ and how it has succeeded only in alienating the natives
while leaving Rudolph running free.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one area of the country where, regardless of the
badge, you don't come in riding buckshot and pushing people around,
which is what they've done,'' said Darren McCullough of nearby
Murphy. ``I don't know about the abortion bombs, but I believe
they're using him as a scapegoat on the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also widespread disdain for the outsiders' search
methods. Nathan Curtis, a 14-year-old, fourth-generation bear
hunter, said city-bred agents would have better luck ``if they put
out a couple girls and a six-pack and just waited.''
</P>
<P>
   Before taking her 7-year-old daughter to school, Cathy Cottrell
of Andrews laughed as she told a story about an FBI dog falling to
its death. ``They brought in a dog from California and it chases a
scent right off a mountain. They should put mountain dogs rather
than flatland dogs out there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal authorities are doing their best to ignore the
pressure and act as though they are welcome guests here. Some
accomplish that by simply turning on their heels at the approach of
a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have consistently said that we are here solely to locate
and apprehend Eric Rudolph,'' Woody Enderson, an FBI inspector who
heads the search effort, said in a statement. ``We are not going
anywhere before our job is done.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, warming the hearts of many locals, he promised: ``While we
have deeply appreciated the hospitality of the people in this
community, we have no desire nor plans to remain here after our
mission is complete.''
</P>
<P>
   While the action and the tension are here, the implications
extend far beyond the half-million acres of search area in the
Great Smoky Mountains of western North Carolina. The Rudolph
manhunt has become a test of two elite law enforcement agencies,
the FBI and the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, the
primary players in the Southeast Bomb Task Force that is conducting
the search under Enderson's direction.
</P>
<P>
   The shine was rubbed off federal agents' shoes at two previous
standoffs with antigovernment separatists _ the Branch Davidians at
Waco, Texas, and the Weaver family at Ruby Ridge, Idaho. Further
damaging the FBI's image was its initial insistence that the
Olympics bomber was security guard Richard A. Jewell, followed by
revelations that the FBI's vaunted crime lab was a petri dish for
faulty science.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the FBI and ATF have invested resources and prestige in two
beliefs: They have the right man and they know where to find him.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes have risen markedly in recent weeks as the task force
has grown to roughly 200 agents _ after falling to about 80 earlier
in the fall. Justice Department officials say more searchers were
added because the FBI believes Rudolph will be easier to find now
that leaves that gave him cover have fallen from the trees.
High-tech motion and heat-sensing devices also should have a better
chance of finding a moving man or a heat source, a necessity on
cold mountain nights, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Ratcheting up the intensity further was an incident two weeks
ago in which someone fired several shots across a soccer field and
into the task force headquarters, a former textile manufacturing
plant in a residential neighborhood. One round brushed the hair of
one agent and just missed another. The police chief said last week
he has no suspects.
</P>
<P>
   A wide place on N.C. Highway 19 with just 1,674 people,
sustained by a Lee jeans factory with more than 400 workers,
Andrews bills itself as ``The Little Town With a Big Heart.''
Despite the deaths blamed on him and a $1 million bounty on his
head, Rudolph apparently has found a place in that heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real distrust of central authority here. It might
go back to the moonshine days. Not helping the feds isn't
necessarily looked on as a bad thing,'' said Frederick Hawley, a
criminal justice professor at Western Carolina University.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old Rudolph learned these forested mountains while
spending part of his youth here, and old connections run deep.
Already, he has been immortalized in at least two country-western
songs. One, written by the owner of a pizza parlor in nearby Bryson
City, opines: ``Now the folks around the town of Andrews said they
wouldn't turn him in; Not even for a million dollars ... that would
surely be a sin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a romantic legend building here,'' Hawley said, ``and
the FBI needs to drag it into the courts and show it for what it
is, warts and all.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be an uphill battle with at least some locals. Bear
hunter Mike Curtis, who moves mobile homes when he is not in the
woods, said he thinks Rudolph might be a scapegoat. He has no
interest in the reward: ``It's really not that important. It's not
worth killing somebody over.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's sure making the FBI look bad,'' added Curtis, who said he
knew Rudolph casually years back. ``That don't bother me a bit. If
they knew what they were doing, they'd have caught him by now. They
would have had him in the first two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The search and bear hunt take place in the beautiful but hostile
Nantahala National Forest, a seemingly endless expanse bisected by
the Appalachian Trail. It is a world of ragged rock cliffs, steep
hills, old gem mines, laurel thickets, and huge rhododendrons.
Rattlesnakes are numerous, big, and fearsome, and the recent dry
weather was a boon to stinging yellow jackets.
</P>
<P>
   Proof of the forest's density came this month: A single-engine
plane piloted by the father of an FBI agent went down in the woods
on the way to Andrews; despite a beeping signal beacon, weeks of
searching proved fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible to get lost only a hundred yards from a main
road, and bear hunters warn a novice in the woods: ``If you lose
your way, follow a creek.'' Then, they joke, ``Or follow an agent.
There'll be plenty of them, and they'll be lost, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The task force agents enter the woods in groups of four to
eight, with one or two rifle-toting marksmen assigned to ensure the
team's safety. Authorities consider Rudolph armed and dangerous,
willing to kill to preserve his freedom. Some teams use tracking
dogs, and some use sophisticated electronic gear.
</P>
<P>
   If they are frustrated, none admit it to a reporter. ``Morale's
real high. Everybody's here to do a job, and we're confident of
getting it done,'' said one ATF agent from Atlanta. Citing task
force rules, he insisted on anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Among the locals, it is a widely held belief that if Rudolph is
still in these woods _ and there is doubt about that _ he must be
getting help. But not everyone is a supporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not out there all this time. He couldn't survive it. He's
in somebody's basement, watching CNN,'' said David Hall, a
carpenter who said he briefly knew and disliked Rudolph. ``He's a
smart aleck, arrogant, a guy with a chip on his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I saw him, I'd hit him in the head with a stick. I ain't
above that. I'd be dragging him in for the bounty,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Suspicions of sympathetic helpers stem from a July 7 incident in
which Rudolph contacted Andrews shopkeeper George Nordmann, a
longtime acquaintance. Two days later, Rudolph went to Nordmann's
empty house and took a large amount of food and a pickup truck,
leaving five hundred-dollar bills as payment. Nordmann did not
report the theft for two more days, and on July 13 investigators
found the truck at a nearby campground.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Nordmann refused to talk about the meeting. At his
health food store, The Better Way, he responded to a reporter's
questions with hands held high in a pose of surrender. ``No
comment, no comment, no comment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There has been little sign of Rudolph, other than some buried
trash that bore his fingerprint. Yet, there have been alleged
sightings far from here, including several in West Virginia of a
pizza-eating, foul-smelling mountain man who left the woods to buy
a phone card.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the FBI, the ATF, and other task force members are
convinced Rudolph remains somewhere in these mountains. They are
not predicting when they will find him.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews Mayor Jim Daily said he is in no rush to see the search
end. ``This has helped the town. It's been good for business. All
the restaurants and B&AMP;Bs are full,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When night falls, there is little to do in Andrews. Dinner might
be a ``Rudolph Burger with FBI Curly Fries'' at the Cherokee Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Then, one of the few options is the Civic Cinema. But on this
night the main feature does not appeal to many locals, and there
are no agents in sight, either. Starring Denzel Washington, it is
``The Siege.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected them all to come look at it,'' manager Sharon Ray
said of the task force searchers. ``A lot more came to see
`Something About Mary.' They liked that one a lot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
