<HEADLINE>
A NEW LOOK AT OLD GROWTH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRINCETON, Mass. _ They are stunted and, some would say, ugly
trees, clinging to the rocky slope with bare roots like talons. The
19th-century farmers who cleared the land at the foot of Mount
Wachusett didn't bother to cut down these old birches because the
trees were so spindly and the footing around them so treacherous.
</P>
<P>
   Until three years ago, they were just unheralded trees along the
mountain road. But, today, ecologists know that homeliness was the
secret to centuries of success. These birches are part of the
largest known old-growth forest in Massachusetts, about 200 acres
of woodland that was never cut because no one thought the timber
was worth the trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Forest researchers have doubled their estimate of the remaining
old-growth forests in the East over the past four years, as marvels
like the Wachusett woods prove that far more of the pre-European
landscape somehow escaped the woodsman's ax than they had thought
possible.
</P>
<P>
   The expanding acreage of confirmed or suspected old-growth
forest _ now estimated at 2 million acres in the eastern half of
the country by leading researcher Robert T. Leverett _ is a boon
for scientists who get an unexpected chance to learn what Eastern
forests were like before Europeans cut them.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, these trees may possess genetic secrets to
long life that foresters would love to know. The yellow birches on
Wachusett are older than many ecologists believed, enduring
centuries of winter cold and ice that sheared off limbs and left
some with up to a dozen knobby scars.
</P>
<P>
   But, for the scientists, activists, and amateur old-growth
``detectives'' who gathered at Harvard Forest in Petersham for a
conference on Eastern old growth this month, the main virtue is
more intangible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us really have a feeling somewhere inside of us that
these places are important and we shouldn't let them slip away,''
said Leverett, a computer specialist in Holyoke who has developed a
knack for finding old-growth forests.
</P>
<P>
   The ``new'' old growth looks nothing like the ancient,
awe-inspiring Douglas firs in the Pacific Northwest, whose majesty
defines virgin forests in the public mind. Instead, Eastern old
growth is likely to be waterlogged black gum swamps, a prairie-edge
forest just 25 feet tall, or stunted birches on the windswept side
of Wachusett Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people have this idea of big, cathedral-like trees as the
old ones and not these harsh, exposed sites,'' said Harvard
University forest ecologist David Orwig, pointing out a
370-year-old, lichen-covered birch at Wachusett. ``This hillside
probably looks a lot like it used to'' when permanent white
settlers came in 1791.
</P>
<P>
   In no small part because Eastern old growth is not widely
recognized, it is largely unprotected. Some of the oldest red oak
trees in New England were slated to be knocked down for a ski slope
at Wachusett Mountain State Reservation before an amateur
naturalist identified them.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Massachusetts has a policy to save old growth on public
land, but other forests have no such protection. For instance,
large areas of suspected old growth on federal land in North
Carolina are not protected from logging, while Oklahoma developers
clear ancient forests for houses without even knowing what they've
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sin of it is that, because we do not widely appreciate
that fragments of original America still survive, we continue to
cut them down,'' said David Stahle, director of the Tree-Ring
Laboratory at the University of Arkansas and an authority on the
Oklahoma old growth. ``They're part of an ecosystem that has been
held together for 6,000 years, and we are bulldozing them and
replacing them with ornamental pear trees.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the early 1980s, most researchers assumed that almost
every acre of forest east of Oklahoma had been subjected to logging
or other human disturbance in more than three centuries of European
settlement. Farming had denuded the landscape in great waves as it
spread westward, and even now spectacular woods such as the White
Mountains in New Hampshire have had to grow back from stumps at the
turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, except for national treasures such as the
150-foot-tall trees in the Great Smoky National Forest in Tennessee
and Adirondack Park in New York, ecologists assumed there were few
old-growth forests in the East worth looking at.
</P>
<P>
   Even Stahle, known as ``the Lord of the Rings'' for his skill at
estimating tree ages, said he expected to learn about Eastern old
growth by studying log cabins rather than live trees because ``I
had the notion ... that it's all been chopped down.''
</P>
<P>
   But enthusiasts such as Leverett, who stalks old growth on
weekends, kept finding forests that somehow escaped logging, often
because they were inaccessible or the trees of low commercial
value. By 1994, Leverett and Vermont naturalist Mary Byrd Davis
identified 750,000 to 1 million acres of old growth in the 34
states from Maine to Florida to Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Davis's guidebook, ``Old Growth in the East,'' lists 23 stands
of old growth even in densely populated Massachusetts, two-thirds
of it on state land in the western part of the state. Though almost
all of the sites, such as land on Mount Greylock, were known to
state officials, the guide brought many of the sites to public
attention for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and Leverett's estimates are not scientific _ most sites
have not been thoroughly surveyed, and ecologists differ on what
should be counted as ``old growth'' _ but the report inspired
others to follow in their footsteps, spurring today's boom of
interest.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Rob Messick of the environmental group Western
North Carolina Alliance was so inspired that he trekked far from
the trails in North Carolina's Pisgah National Forest to find an
astonishing 38,900 acres of old-growth forests amid the gorges and
rocky outcroppings that warded off 19th-century loggers.
</P>
<P>
   Messick's discoveries underscored how little forest researchers
had focused on the ancient woods of the East: The Forest Service
had never tried to determine if the woods were old growth, leaving
the work to an amateur researcher.
</P>
<P>
   In Oklahoma, meanwhile, Stahle of the University of Arkansas
discovered that tens of thousands of acres in the Cross Timbers
forest at the edge of the Oklahoma prairie had never been logged.
He found post and blackjack oaks more than 300 years old despite
the fact that few were more than 25 feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   The ``new'' old growth in New England contained relatively few
acres, but researchers were surprised to find any new sites after
all the human disturbances. Despite the widespread belief that the
White Mountains had been so heavily logged that it was reduced to
``smoldering ruins,'' University of New Hampshire graduate student
Christine Goodale found a stand of never-logged trees just off
Route 16 by reviewing historic maps.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there was the Wachusett old growth, which put the brakes
on expansion at Wachusett Mountain ski area in 1995. The trees run
in a narrow band around the mountain, representing the land that
neither the farmers below nor the resort hotel operator above
wanted. Leverett learned why loggers left them alone, breaking an
ankle while climbing the slope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within 5 minutes, I knew that we had the discovery of the
decade,'' said Leverett of the day when he saw the Wachusett trees
for the first time. When the field work is done, Leverett believes
researchers will have identified at least 200 acres of old growth
at Wachusett.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the old growth of the East has to battle for respect.
Unlike the Pacific Northwest, field biologists have not found
animals, such as the spotted owl of northern California, that
depend on these virgin forests for survival. The best they can do
so far are several types of rare lichen that grow much more readily
on old trees than young ones.
</P>
<P>
   But Harvard's Orwig said the old-growth forests deserve respect
simply because they survived, and are one of the few places that
looks much as it did when the Pilgrims stepped ashore in 1620.
``It's the portion of the landscape that's remaining from earlier
times,'' he said. ``It's what we have left.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
