<DOCNO> NYT19981130.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4803 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOREA-REFORMER-BOS &LR;      11-30 1489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-REFORMER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUSADER TARGETS CORRUPTION IN SOUTH KOREA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL _ Call it Korea's tale of David and Goliath.
</P>
<P>
   Jang Ha Sung, a bespectacled, mild-mannered professor of
finance, has taken on the corporate giants of South Korea. And
shockingly, in a country where the chaebol, or family-run
conglomerates, control almost every aspect of life, Jang has
achieved victories that no one dreamed possible.
</P>
<P>
   With his conservative maroon tie and briefcase full of financial
documents, Jang is no Che Guevara. But that might be why he and his
band of progressive lawyers and professionals _ People's Solidarity
for Participatory Democracy _ could be the most effective
revolutionary group that tradition-bound South Korea has seen in
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, we'd march and yell. But when you're dealing
with the chaebol, that doesn't work. It has to be pressure within
the system,'' said Jang, a former student activist and Wharton
School of Management graduate.
</P>
<P>
   By persuading average Korean shareholders and large American
investment funds to sign over voting rights to him, Jang has
pressured chaebol to clean up management, cut corruption, and open
their often-doctored accounts to public view. In cases where
pressure hasn't worked, Jang and his crew have resorted to the
American-style response: Sue the guys in charge.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Jang and his band of anti-establishment
establishmentarians is a lesson in how the mood of even a
conservative nation can shift when people become fed up with crony
capitalism. The response here has not been violent as in Indonesia,
where people rioted and brought down a government. For that reason,
Jang's crusade to clean up Korean corporations may prove far more
effective in overhauling this economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see him as a quixotic figure. One man tilting at the
corporate windmills is not going to knock them down or make them
salute him,'' Hank Morris, director of the Seoul-based Industrial
Research and Consulting Ltd., said of Jang. ``It'll probably be
years before his work has great impact.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And yet,'' Morris conceded, ``there are signs that he has had
some initial success. I have to take my hat off to him, because
what he is doing is quite courageous.''
</P>
<P>
   Courageous because the chaebol mostly control life here. They
dominate business, from electronics and cars to real estate and
advertising. They own newspapers and television stations and run
foundations that set the cultural agenda. They own schools,
universities, and hospitals. And they have also controlled many
politicians and banks through bribery and collusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You name it, they own it,'' said Jang, sitting behind his desk
at Korea University, piled high with papers documenting
illegalities in top conglomerates. ``If we want to make this
country more efficient, cleaner, more open, less corrupt, we have
to reform the chaebol and cut their relations with politics. Right
now, they are stronger than the government. Presidents come and go
every five years, but the chaebol never change.''
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, the denizens of industry have not been amused
by the 45-year-old upstart. Jang, whose father was a businessman
and whose uncles are a top politician and the president of Korea
Electric Power Co., says being from the same background as many
chaebol elite has made his crusade harder.
</P>
<P>
   Managers first lobbied him through family and friends to drop
his campaign. Then came phone calls to his home and efforts to dig
up dirt from his past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these top managers are my school and college
classmates, and we are talking about issues that nobody's
comfortable with,'' Jang said. ``But in their hearts, they know
that if not all, at least part of what I am doing is good and
correct.''
</P>
<P>
   Koreans had long chalked up the roaring growth of the last three
decades to state-directed capitalism that featured cozy ties among
government, banks, and chaebol. But average folk now blame
conglomerates burdened by staggering debts for the crisis that
forced Seoul to accept a $57 billion bailout last year, the largest
ever granted by the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting recession has been one of the worst in Asia _ the
economy is expected to contract 7 percent this year, and about 2
million people are jobless. And although average laborers have
taken a bite by accepting layoffs and pay cuts, everyone from
Korean President Kim Dae Jung to President Clinton complains that
the biggest chaebol have refused to accept reforms that would allow
the whole economy to recover. The top five chaebol, including
Hyundai, Samsung, and Daewoo, account for 40 percent of economic
activity here.
</P>
<P>
   At the root of the problem are years of government pressure on
banks to lend to chaebol, which in turn were given the right to
overborrow and expand into every kind of business _ in exchange for
donations to politicians. In the process, conglomerates did as they
pleased _ using funds from flush companies to subsidize failing
subsidiaries, selling products to sister companies at inflated
prices, and issuing discounted shares to the chairman's family.
</P>
<P>
   Jang's aim is to prevent such practices and reform corporate
governance by speaking out for minority shareholders. His movement
began in 1994, but gained steam last year when the economy began to
show signs of wear. In January 1997, the Hanbo Steel conglomerate
went bust, bringing down with it Korea First Bank, which had made
more than $805 million in loans to Hanbo.
</P>
<P>
   Jang and his friends went onto the streets with placards asking
shareholders to sign over their voting rights in a campaign to
reform the bank. About 150 disgruntled stockholders _ from rich
individuals to janitors saving for retirement _ did so. Soon they
had 1 percent of First Bank's shares, the magic number to propose
an agenda, open a company's books, or sue executives.
</P>
<P>
   Jang's group suggested a plan to cut the labor force, sell off
bad assets and affiliates, form an independent appraisal company,
and fire top executives. First Bank rejected the plan, so the
minority shareholders sued, seeking $30 million compensation for
illegal loans to Hanbo and illegal political contributions. In
July, they won, Jang said.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1997, Jang's group filed suit to stop Samsung
Electronics from issuing a convertible bond to the chairman's son
at a discounted price. They won an injunction, but Samsung was
allowed to issue the bond, though they were barred from selling it
on the Korea Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Jang's group attended the Samsung Electronics'
shareholders' meeting, an affair that was reportedly packed with
employees who were urged to jeer at Jang and fill seats to prevent
other minority shareholders from attending. The usually cursory
agenda dragged on 13 1/2 hours as Jang's group interrogated
management about allegedly illegal transactions and a shell company
in Ireland. Jang also protested the appointment as auditor of a
former government official who had been convicted of taking bribes
from Samsung.
</P>
<P>
   But 1 percent of votes was not enough, and in the end, ``they
did what they wanted,'' Jang said, shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   Jang's most successful campaign was targeting SK Telecom Co.
Joining forces with Koreans and big American institutional
investors _ Scudder Kemper, Tiger, Oppenheimer and Emerging Markets
Investors _ Jang's alliance amassed 18 percent of shares, enough to
force SK Telecom to accept three independent board directors to
represent minority shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman's family also reimbursed the company $23 million,
which Jang said they took in illegal profits. And SK Telecom _ the
cash cow of SK Group's 45 companies _ was reimbursed $270
million &UR;  &LR; that its managers had drained away to ailing affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   Jang calls SK Telecom his group's one victory. Even though they
won a lawsuit against Korea First Bank, the bank is still on the
verge of collapse. ``Our purpose is to make the companies better,''
Jang said. ``Unless we turn it around and make a company a success,
I wouldn't say we won.''
</P>
<P>
   Jang has attracted the attention of US diplomats, who invited
him as one of six guests last week at a roundtable with Clinton,
and the admiration of several institutional investors who have made
him their proxy. Jang has asked two Boston-based investment funds _
Putnam Investments and Wellington Management _ to join forces with
him, and a Wellington representative is expected to meet Jang here
in a few days to discuss his work.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Jarvis, Korea analyst for the Arlington, Va.-based Emerging
Markets Investors Corp., recounted that largely because of the
efforts of Jang, ``corporate governance is in the vocabulary of
every chaebol I meet these days. It remains to be seen if their
deeds will match their words.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 1358EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981130.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4804 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUYBACKS-HNS &LR;      11-30 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUYBACKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS COMPANIES RUSH TO REPURCHASE SHARES, SOME INVESTORS ARE WARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a bid to boost stock performance, hundreds of
corporations are buying back their shares at a torrid pace, while
investors wonder whether the repurchase plans are worth it.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities Data Co. of Newark, N.J., reports that companies
are heading toward another record year, with 1,768 saying they'll
buy $203 billion of their shares. That tops the 1,300 companies
that announced buybacks worth $181 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a rash of announcements, and we won't be
surprised if we continue to see more,'' said Michael Mauboussin, an
analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But the stock repurchases are sending mixed messages to
investors and Wall Street analysts. Some companies enjoy dramatic
rises in their share prices, while others see their stock sink like
a rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buybacks aren't automatic,'' said David Fried, editor of ``The
Buyback Letter'' and president of Fried Asset Management, an
investment management company in Malibu, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that love buybacks span all sectors and products. In
banking, Citigroup has announced plans to snap up $2 billion of its
stock. Intel Corp. has said it will repurchase $7.6 billion worth
of shares. McDonald's plans a $3.5 billion buyback. And Philip
Morris Cos. has unveiled an $8 billion buyback plan _ the largest
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The prosperous stock market, scores of mergers and the growth of
employee stock option plans have filled corporate coffers with
extra cash and billions of shares. Rather than use the surplus cash
or equity to pay off debt or feed business growth, companies are
buying their own shares.
</P>
<P>
   Since buybacks are unregulated by the securities industry, the
process is quick: Corporate officers and boards simply sign off on
the repurchase plans, then make it public to investors.
</P>
<P>
   One big reason companies do buybacks is to jump-start flat or
sinking stock prices. When a company repurchases millions of common
shares, it shrinks the total number of shares in the market. With
fewer shares claiming a piece of a company's profits, its
earnings-per-share ratio often gets a big boost. This can lead to
greater demand and higher stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   One good example is The Gap Inc. in San Francisco. After the
company announced Oct. 29 it would buy back $1.6 billion, or 30
million shares, of its outstanding stock, its shares rose from
$55.13 to $59 on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Buybacks seem to help the long-term stock performance of
companies that repurchase at least 5 percent of their shares,
according to Melissa Brown, an analyst at Prudential Securities in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   From 1978 to 1996, big companies that bought back their shares
gained 21 percent a year, compared to 15.5 percent for comparable
companies that did not. Medium-sized companies that repurchased
shares gained 26 percent yearly, compared to 16 percent for others.
And for smaller companies, the gap was 22.6 percent to 15.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Another appeal of buybacks: It signals a company's faith in its
share performance and the overall stock market.
</P>
<P>
   One dramatic example came last year in October, when the Dow
Jones index plunged 554 points or 7 percent, in one day _ the worst
one-day percentage drop since the Black Monday market crash of
October 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The market rallied swiftly the next day, and many credited IBM's
move to repurchase $3.5 billion of its shares. That vote of
confidence encouraged many investors to plunge back into the
market, market experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Buybacks also create tax advantages for shareholders. If a
company rewards its investors by paying dividends, the dividends
are taxable at an individual's tax rate of up to 39.6 percent. In
contrast, money returned through buybacks would be taxed when a
shareholder sells stock at the lower capital gains rates of 35
percent for corporations and 20 percent for individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you pay out in dividends, it would be taxable
immediately,'' Fried said. ``With buybacks, you get to choose when
you cash out.''
</P>
<P>
   But buyback plans don't always work out, market experts said.
</P>
<P>
   One danger to small investors, who rarely have a say in the
matter: Some corporate officers and board directors don't follow
through completely with their buyback plans after announcing them.
</P>
<P>
   A study last August by James Westphal, a management professor at
the University of Texas, found that one-third of 412 major
companies that announced buybacks from 1985 to 1991 failed to
repurchase their stock, and they are not legally required to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Companies also may halt or postpone buybacks if they are heading
into a merger or acquisition paid for by stock. If the proposed
merger uses the popular ``pooling of interests'' accounting method,
in which the exchange of stock to pay for the deal is not taxable,
companies must halt their buyback plans to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, stock buybacks are used by strong, profitable companies
with healthy cash flows. But market pros advise investors that
financially weak companies may announce buybacks in a last-gasp
attempt to boost their share prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``History is littered with companies that repurchased
`undervalued' shares, only to see business prospects sour and the
stocks go down,'' Mauboussin said. ``An announced buyback program _
even an aggressive one _ is not an automatic signal of value.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 1359EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
