u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-30 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVE THANKS TO GORE FOR TAKING ON MAHATHIR MOHAMAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- As lying, racist, anti-Semitic crooks go, Mahathir
Mohamad is small potatoes, except for the fact that any time a
lying, racist, anti-Semitic crook is actually running a country
it's wise to beware, at least out of respect for history.
</P>
<P>
   That goes double when the slime in question has been running the
place for more than 17 years, jails his deputy and has him beaten,
thumbs his nose at the world by placing controls on capital flows,
and blames his country's economic woes repeatedly on Jews and then
tries to deny having said it.
</P>
<P>
   Look on the prime minister of Malaysia, in short, as Louis
Farrakhan with a government, and be thankful that the likes of Al
Gore have decided to take him on now that he has become a threat
not only to human rights but also to a gradual return to economic
stability in turbulent Asia.
</P>
<P>
   It has barely been two weeks since Gore identified the United
States with the forces of reform _ political and economic _ in
Malaysia, obviously too soon for sweeping judgments about the
aftermath, but not too soon to notice some hopeful signs.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Prime Minister Mohamad himself has shied away
from any response to Gore's direct, tough criticism of his brutal
treatment of a prominent former government leader and protege, his
dangerous challenge to economic reform principles, and his related
suppression of political reformers whose peaceful agitation for
real democracy threatens his grip on power.
</P>
<P>
   For another, the visible signs of democratic activism _ protest
gatherings each Saturday _ not only continue, but are attracting
more participants. Less visible is a vibrant democracy movement
that is gaining strength and followers via a uniquely vigorous use
of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   And for a third, the increase in the world press's attention to
Malaysia has been huge, and may be the most important, short-term
consequence of Gore's well-timed intervention. It may be the most
important because the signal being sent by the increased scrutiny
is that Malaysia may not be the island of ``stability,'' the safe
investment haven it has long been assumed to be, that perhaps
international businesses and financial organizations need to
seriously rethink their assumptions. That prospect is delightfully
subversive.
</P>
<P>
   In the foreign policy priesthood, Gore's explicit words in Kuala
Lumpur produced some classic tsk-tsking _ rude to the host,
distracting at an Asian economic summit, counterproductive, and all
the other realpolitik cliches that post-Cold War reality is
rendering intellectually silly.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, however, the tsk-tsking has missed the point
factually as well as strategically, particularly in two areas:
</P>
<P>
   _Gore didn't simply blurt out a few phrases about free people
and free markets and single out for praise the ``reformasi''
activists in Malaysia. His comments were the culmination of weeks
of escalating alarm in the Clinton administration, and would have
been delivered by the president himself had Saddam Hussein's latest
outrages not intervened.
</P>
<P>
   _The bulk of his speech to the summit concerned the vital
importance of economic reforms in extricating the region and the
world from financial danger _ more disclosure of basic economic
information, more open markets for capital as well as goods and
services, and less crony capitalism and corruption. That was just
as tough a slam at current, kleptomaniacal practices in Malaysia as
his remarks on political freedom, but the foreign policy priesthood
(with economic interests at stake) somehow found that not only
excusable but even praiseworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Until last year, Malaysia was an economic success story in the
main, though tarnished by a prime minister who gloated more than
most regional autocrats over the superiority of ``Asian values'' of
conformity over Western democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The financial crisis, however, produced a unique lurch in Prime
Minister Mohamad's behavior. To shield his country in the short run
and promote his reelection next year, he slapped currency and other
anti-market controls on the economy, and began blaming outsiders in
general and Jews in particular for his problems.
</P>
<P>
   And because this kind of dictatorial economics and bigoted blame
game is usually accompanied by political misdeeds, he also went
after his longtime deputy, Anwar Ibrahim _ a free-market democracy
advocate well known in international circles as well as to Al Gore
personally. Ibrahim was arrested on trumped-up corruption and sex
charges and beaten.
</P>
<P>
   The post-arrest photos of his bruises and his ex-boss's virulent
anti-Semitism galvanized the administration and Gore weeks ago to
public criticism, and the vice president's speech was preceded by a
highly publicized visit to Ibrahim's wife by Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Gore did not act rashly, in short. His words had both context
and careful timing, and the world needs more of them, not less.
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
