<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4812 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-SUBSIDIES-BOS &LR;      11-30 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-SUBSIDIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICANS CHAFE UNDER BELT TIGHTENING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ It's the tortilla, stupid!
</P>
<P>
   That's the message President Ernesto Zedillo and his top
officials are hearing these days from nearly every corner of Mexico
in response to proposed government cuts of basic _ and
traditionally subsidized _ staples.
</P>
<P>
   With crucial elections next year quickly approaching and a
presidential vote less than two years away, critics and political
observers are warning the Zedillo administration that many of the
cuts and tax increases they're seeking might anger Mexicans enough
to end the ruling party's 70-year hold on the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   This year's budget debate has been unusually combative, due
mostly to an opposition-led Congress and because of several
controversial measures in the government plan. Among them: a 30
percent increase in gasoline, already about $1.65 a gallon; a 15
percent tax increase on phone calls; and increases in water,
electricity, and the sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Zedillo government has proposed ending tortilla
subsidies for 3 million low-income residents, a move that would
probably result in a price hike in the country's most important
staple from roughly 14 cents a pound to about 18 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will affect me and my family a lot,'' Guadalupe Macias, a
47-year-old housekeeper, said Friday afternoon while holding 2
kilos of fresh corn tortillas she had just bought at a factory in
the southern neighborhood of Coyoacan. ``You can tell people to buy
less gasoline, but how can you tell us to eat less?''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials say the cuts and price increases are
necessary to offset shortages caused by record-low oil prices this
year _ and free up more money for initiatives to fight crime,
widely viewed at Mexicans' foremost concern. About a third of the
federal government's revenues come from petroleum-related
operations, mostly through its monopoly, Pemex.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo's budget chief, Jose Angel Gurria, also said that
without tighter spending, the country's deficit could balloon next
year from 1.25 percent of gross domestic product to nearly 3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Another hot-button issue in the Zedillo budget is a $55 billion
expense to rescue a bankrupt, government-run bank known as Fobaproa
that many Mexicans see as a taxpayer bailout for wealthy bankers
and political cronies.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, budget season in Mexico has been one of quiet
handshakes and rubber stamps. The executive branch would propose
the plan, and a majority of Congress _ usually members of the same
party _ would approve it.
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, both the government and the budget have
drawn an unprecedented level of criticism from all sides, including
conservative business leaders, the Roman Catholic Church, and
progressive community activists. Even members of Zedillo's
Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as PRI, have lashed out at
parts of the budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally think that if there are exaggerated increases ...
the people who manage the government's budgets are in a different
galaxy from the one we live in,'' said Bishop Abelardo Alvarado,
secretary general of the Mexican Episcopal Conference.
</P>
<P>
   A major labor union leader last week called for national strikes
unless wages are raised to compensate for the higher prices. And
several members of the lower house heckled Gurria with refrains of
``It won't pass!'' during a budget presentation last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intensity, variety, and solidity of the criticism that the
administration has received on its handling of the budget will
bring reforms to the process that could qualify _ without
exaggeration _ as revolutionary,'' Sergio Aguayo Quezada, a
political scientist at Colegio de Mexico, wrote in the Reforma
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The bailout plan prompted protests at a bankers' meeting
Saturday, with one demonstrator putting a severed pig's head in
front of a leading government economic official and shouting, ``You
all should pay, not the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress has until Dec. 15 to decide the budget. The Mexican
Constitution allows it to create a modified version that the
president could not veto.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their anger, though, some Mexicans wonder whether
legislators can or will do much to change the government's
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear them talking and yelling about the budget, but I don't
hear them saying what they're going to do about it,'' said Dolores
Cantu Cortez, 33, another customer at the tortilla store. ``Maybe
it's all a show, because they get their salaries from the budget,
too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
