<HEADER>
A4817 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WILSON-BOS &LR;      11-30 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WILSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILSON'S HUMOR BROKE BARRIERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the outsize personalities who popped out of the TV screen
in the late 1960s and early 1970s, few were more vivid than Flip
Wilson, and none pulled a more decisive disappearing act.
</P>
<P>
   By creating characters like the exuberant Geraldine and coining
such catch phrases as ``The devil made me do it!,'' Wilson
imprinted himself on the national imagination so quickly that in
1970, its first year on the air, ``The Flip Wilson Show'' was the
second-highest-rated TV program in the country. It was a remarkable
feat that he promptly repeated the next year.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the country had embraced a television
variety show headlined by a black performer, after shunning earlier
programs hosted by Sammy Davis Jr. and Nat King Cole. Wilson was on
top of the entertainment world.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1974 he decided to get off the weekly TV carousel. Even
though it was still popular, Wilson left his show. From then until
his death Wednesday night of liver cancer at the age of 64, the
comedian was seldom in the public eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made virtually a complete disappearance from television,''
remarked TV historian Alex McNeil yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's appetite for any kind of spotlight seemed to disappear
as well. McNeil recalled attending a performance by Richard Pryor
in the mid-1970s at the old Paul's Mall in Boston. Spotting Wilson
in the audience, Pryor introduced him and asked him to come onstage
and take a bow. Wilson declined.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's withdrawal from the public arena was prompted, he told
interviewers, by his desire to spend more time with his five
children, to ``make sure they don't go through what I did.''
Abandoned by his mother at age 7, he had bounced among foster homes
and reform school while growing up _ hardscrabble origins that make
his later success even more impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson was no Pryor; his comedy nestled within the mainstream
and seldom ventured toward the cutting edge. There were those who
accused him of stereotyping or of not being confrontational enough.
</P>
<P>
   But others saw Wilson as a gifted sketch comic who was simply
doing what comedians of other ethnic groups have done from time
immemorial: mining his own background for material, creating
exaggerated characters in a quest for laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Wilson benefited from arriving on television at a time
when new opportunities were opening up for black performers. The
racial antagonism that had undermined Cole's variety show in the
1950s and Davis's first show in the 1960s was beginning to ebb.
Wilson's apolitical hi-jinks found a ready audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying he wasn't talented and he wasn't funny, but the
time was right,'' said McNeil. ``He came in on the right wave.''
</P>
<P>
   Relatively brief though it may have been, Flip Wilson's time at
the TV pinnacle was memorable. One of his most popular characters
was Reverend Leroy of the Church of What's Happening Now; in an era
that consecrated the ``now,'' Wilson was what was happening.
</P>
<P>
   He was not the first man to wear a dress on network television _
that was Milton Berle _ but Wilson was probably the first one to
wear miniskirts, hot pants, and go-go boots. The sheer energy he
brought to the character of Geraldine made her over-the-top funny.
Pretty soon, the whole country was repeating Geraldine's pet
phrases: ``When you're hot, you're hot; when you're not, you're
not,'' ``What you see is what you get,'' and of course, ``The devil
made me do it!''
</P>
<P>
   That alibi would be employed by a fallen tel-evan-ge-list or two
in years to come, but could Wilson also have sown the seeds for
Dana Carvey's Church Lady on ``Saturday Night Live''? Not only did
Carvey wear a dress, but the Church Lady blamed everything on
Satan.
</P>
<P>
   Like innumerable other comics, Wilson had gotten his big break
on ``The Tonight Show,'' in 1965. He also appeared on that other
pillar of the comedy establishment, ``The Ed Sullivan Show,'' but
his reputation was really made on the counterculture classic,
``Rowan &AMP; Martin's Laugh-In.'' Even among the riotous goings-on of
``Laugh-In,'' Wilson stood out, especially when he declaimed,
``Here come the judge.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving ``The Flip Wilson Show,'' Wilson resurfaced
occasionally in films or network specials, plus a short-lived
sitcom called ``Charlie and Company,'' and an equally short-lived
revival of ``People Are Funny.''
</P>
<P>
   But he seemed determined to prove there is life after
television. Having shucked the role of celebrity, he seemed content
with the off-camera role of father. And when he died, his daughter
Michelle was at his side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
