<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4818 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-JOEL-BOS &LR;      11-30 1307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-JOEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ENTERTAINER IS READY FOR A REST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No artist wants to be a parody of himself. Think of Elvis
Presley in his twilight years and the shuddering image of an
immobile, embarrassing burnout. That's not what Billy Joel has in
mind for his career, so he's taking himself out of the running.
He's now on one of the longest unofficial farewell tours in memory,
but he expects to end it before his 50th birthday, on May 9 of next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting to that time _ and, yeah, I don't want to be a
parody,'' says Joel.
</P>
<P>
   ``My ability to do these rock 'n' roll shows is beginning to
leave,'' says Joel, who is confronting the inevitable. ``And I'm
aware of that. I'm more acutely aware of that than anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   His soul-searching comes at a time when the demand to see him
has never been higher. His shows are selling out briskly and new
ones are being added daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``The audiences are fantastic,'' he admits. ``They are really
enthusiastic. They're made up of a lot of younger people, too.
College-aged kids. And even little kids. They're just screaming
their heads off. And I'm thinking, gee, the audience is in better
shape than we are these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel, who still plans to record classical music after this tour,
has had to overcome some serious physical ailments this year.
During the summer he suffered an upper respiratory infection that
forced him to cancel a European tour with Elton John. ``I
completely lost my voice, which was really bizarre,'' he says.
``That never happened to me before.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, he had a heavy bout with the flu that caused him to
postpone a Pittsburgh show for the second time, though he's since
recovered and declares that his more recent shows have been among
the best on the tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't want to be up on stage if I can't do it well,''
Joel says from a tour stop in Chicago, before citing an analogy to
former baseball star Joe DiMaggio. ``You know, Joe took himself out
of the game when he felt he couldn't swing like he had before. And
I always thought, well, that took a lot of class. He removed
himself from the lineup. It's getting to be that time for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get up on a stage now and it's like going on some kind of
terrifying amusement park ride,'' Joel says. ``The lights come on
and there is this huge roar coming out of the audience, so you're
immediately thrown into this broiler rotisserie with a lot of
lights, and this hugely loud PA system is blasting. Your head is
ringing and there you go, you're on this roller-coaster ride as you
go from song to song. I talked about this with the drummer (Liberty
DeVito), who has been with me a long time and is only a year
younger than me. It's now difficult for him to finish a two-plus
hour show banging the drums as hard as he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at each other by the end of the show and we say, `Hey,
we're getting too old for this.' You walk off the stage, your head
is ringing from the noise, your heart's pumping, you're sweating
like crazy, you're kind of dizzy from it, you're blinded by the
lights and then you go from sensory overload to sensory
deprivation. After the show, you get into this real quiet car and
you're sitting there and hearing all your systems pounding and
pumping. And I'm thinking, man, I'm definitely not as young as I
used to be. But that's not bad, as long as you're not trying to
make believe you are.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Joel has never done that. He has always espoused honesty in
his music _ and it's been enough to earn him a recent appointment
to the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame, which he'll enter in March with
Bruce Springsteen, Paul McCartney, and Curtis Mayfield, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   That's select company, but Joel, the pride and joy of
Hicksville, Long Island, has earned his slot with richly colorful
story songs such as ``Scenes from an Italian Restaurant,'' ``Piano
Man,'' and ``Only the Good Die Young.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking out on the audience and seeing college-age kids
who weren't even born when I wrote most of this stuff,'' he says.
``They're singing every lyric and I'm thinking, gee, this is the
stuff they want to hear, so they're getting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, this has been a ``greatest hits'' tour for Joel, who
hasn't had any new studio music out since 1993. ``That's a long
time in the music business. That's five years ago. And I realized
if I'm not going to put out new songs and new rock 'n' roll music,
then the day is coming that I will be a parody of myself.''
</P>
<P>
   It was about a year ago that Joel made a commitment to tour
again. ``It's actually a commitment I made to the band and the crew
that I would tour. And then I got sick and couldn't tour the whole
middle of the year. So I'm touring at the end of this year and the
beginning of next. I don't want to call it a farewell tour, but
it's saying goodbye to fans who have been coming to see us for many
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying I'll never perform again. And I'm not saying I
won't pop up here and there from time to time in a different kind
of production. But right now, this is a kind of payback and a way
of saying thanks. We're also trying to keep the ticket price
down.'' (Joel's tickets are $39.50 _ not bad for an arena headliner
of his longevity.)
</P>
<P>
   The last pop song Joel even attempted to write was in 1995. It
had the working title ``Champs-Elysees.'' ``I said, OK, I'll write
about Paris. I love Paris. I'll just write about visions I've had
in Paris and the sort of serene consciousness of seeing the
carnival in Paris as I head toward the lights, and the ghosts of my
past, and just real pretentious crap. It was a bad lyric. Lyrics
were no longer expressing what music was expressing for me at that
point. But the song came to me as I walked along the
Champs-Elysees.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my guitar player, Tommy Burns, he's a tough kid from Long
Island, said, `You wrote a song called the `Champ's Eyelashes'? And
I cracked up and everybody else in the band cracked up. And I
realized no matter what I do, no matter what the lyric ends up
being, it will forever have to be known as the `Champ's Eyelashes.'
I might as well have been writing about the Champ's Eyelashes for
all the meaning the lyric had. And that was it. I just said, `This
stinks.'''
</P>
<P>
   Thus began Joel's more serious foray into classical music
writing, which is where he feels his future lies. ``I'm getting
better at it,'' he says. ``I've got about eight or nine pieces now.
They are mostly piano pieces. Some pieces are for piano and
orchestra and there are some fragments of purely orchestral pieces
which are part of this work I've been doing called `The Scrimshaw
Pieces,' which is based on the history of Long Island and its
relationship to America and the settling of it.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not as confident, though, that critics will like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what would happen in the classical world if I tried to
present this as my attempt at classical music. They'd carve it to
bits because it is in no way late-20th-century atonal modern music.
It's very derivative of Chopin and Rachmaninoff and all of the
Romantic composers. And I'm not shy about saying that it is. That's
what I like, and that's how I write. I think even when I was
writing pop songs, I was coming from that ultra-melodic
Romanticism. And I think for it to be performed, for it to be
presented, I would prefer to have a classical virtuoso who's
trained to present this music to really do it justice. I can barely
play rudimentary classical music because my left hand is a waste
and I don't sight-read like I used to. And even though I have a
good knowledge of classical music, my hands don't do what they
could have done had I continued with my lessons when I was a
teenager.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the moment, I can write better than I can play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
