<P>
   SCI-ALZHEIMERS (New York) _ Scientists at New York University
Medical Center spent three days exploring the brain of the writer
in search for clues about what destroyed the brain of her mother at
a very early age. By Marion Roach. (1725 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SCIENTISTS-FILM (Los Angeles) _ Hollywood's treatment of
scientists is out of sync with that of the press, which generally
presents scientists as articulate people making important
discoveries. So now, efforts are being mounted to get Hollywood to
portray scientists in a more realistic light, as people with more
complex drives and emotions. These efforts also aim at getting
Hollywood to portray the process of scientific inquiry itself. But,
it's a hard sell. By Andrew Pollack. (1880 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NEANDERTHAL-DIET (Undated) _ In a study already provoking
controversy, an American geographer has pointed out evidence
suggesting, in his view, that little more than the amount of iodine
in their diets may have been responsible for the physical
differences between Neanderthals and modern humans and that this
might solve the mystery of what happened to the Neanderthals. By
John Noble Wilford. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EMBRYOS-COMPETE (Undated) _ Evolutionary theorists are
scratching their heads over a new experiment on the breeding
characteristics of a rare species of monogamous mice. The
experiment has cast surprising doubt on a controversial, but highly
successful idea, namely that of a competition between embryos in
the womb and their mother, fueled by a kind of molecular arms race
between the sexes. By Gina Kolata. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions answered: Do the terms
snake, viper and serpent have scientific differences? (300 words)
</P>
