<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981130.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4848 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-30 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG OBSESSION TURNS INTO TINY MUSEUM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREDERICKSBURG, Texas _ A few weeks ago in this space, I wrote
about how travel can help make our world seem smaller.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie and Joe Red take that philosophy to an extreme.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds purchased their first piece of miniature furniture 26
years ago. Bonnie explains, ``What started as a hobby turned into
an addiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon they were designing and building a doll house. Equipping it
with personal mementos and gifts from friends. Making it the
centerpiece of their Arlington home.
</P>
<P>
   That was merely the beginning. They scoured North America for
other tiny treasures. Europe, too. As their collection grew to tens
of thousands of pieces, Joe designed miniature buildings _ a
schoolhouse, pharmacy, old-time barbershop, bakery, meat market _
to house them. He added paint, wallpaper, flooring and lighting.
Bonnie provided furnishings and landscaping.
</P>
<P>
   Through their travels, Bonnie and Joe met others who cherish
miniatures, and they began purchasing rare finished displays _ a
Guatemalan monastery; a replica of Anne Hathaway's cottage near
Stratford-on-Avon, England; an entire European mini-village _ to
supplement their collection.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Bonnie says, ``We ran out of room.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No labor involved &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lucky for us. The Reds moved to Fredericksburg, and last month
they opened A World of Miniatures, a fascinating small museum that
allows them to share this labor of love with others.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we don't use that word `labor,' '' Joe corrects. ``That
implies work. And we don't consider this work. It's fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe's fun filled his spare time; only recently did he retire
from a full-time job as a computer engineer, a vocation whose
graphics elements helped provide perspective in creating an
environment one-twelfth the world's normal size.
</P>
<P>
   A visitor is hard-pressed to determine which is more impressive:
the Reds' meticulous precision or their imagination and creativity.
</P>
<P>
   The Nicholas Pharmacy and Fountain (named for Bonnie's father),
for instance, contains more than 450 medication and perfume bottles
and other miniatures. And that doesn't include hundreds of
pint-size candies that were glued together piece by piece.
</P>
<P>
   The produce section at Greene's Grocery features berries, grapes
and mushrooms. Shelves are stocked with tiny containers of
Campbell's soups, Kellogg's Corn Flakes, Ritz Crackers and dozens
more products. Entire flounders and haddocks could be devoured in
one bite at Captain Jack's Fish Shack. Mark's Meat Market is
equipped with working scales. And no two cakes are alike at the
Bluebonnet Bakery.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide search &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the Allman Art Gallery, 15 of 20 paintings are reproductions
of famous works copied in miniature _ a remarkable accomplishment _
by U.S. and European artists. Soft lighting and mirrors create a
haunting effect.
</P>
<P>
   Where in the world do the Reds find all these itty-bitty
objects? Just about everywhere. ``We attend miniature shows in
Houston each March and in Dallas in May,'' Joe says. ``We've
traveled to almost every state. We've been to England, Scotland,
France, Italy, Switzerland, Canada. We're always looking.''
</P>
<P>
   Improvisation is essential. For salt-and-pepper shakers, Bonnie
and Joe use the backs of pierced earrings. A minuscule flowerpot is
a nut from Joe's toolbox. Beads are ideal for making perfume
bottles. Wax candles become cakes. Tongue depressors are shaped to
form furniture.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if you take the top off a tube of toothpaste and turn it
upside down, you've got a perfect wastebasket,'' says Joe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thatching'' the roof of one building in the European village
took Bonnie 40 hours. ``I can't tell you how many brooms I used to
get enough straw,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Even more challenging was finding sufficient leaves for trees in
the village setting. ``But when I was shopping at Winn-Dixie, I
noticed them cleaning out the meat market, and I said, `Can I have
all that greenery?' They were throwing it out. And it was just what
we needed.''
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece for a wedding-reception room also came from
Winn-Dixie. ``We needed a nice painting,'' says Bonnie, ``and when
I was looking for a sympathy card, I saw one with a pretty floral
arrangement on the front. I cut it out, and Joe framed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie and Joe credit hundreds of other miniaturists and
craftspeople with contributing to their displays. Exhibits range
from a Bavarian inn to a replica of the Vereins Kirche, a
Fredericksburg landmark directly across the street from the museum;
from a Roman colonnade to an ice-fishing shanty modeled on one in
the movie ``Grumpy Old Men;'' from an English castle to a rock shop
complete with workshop for cutting, grinding and polishing.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds aren't finished, either. They're hard at work building
the choir for an African-American church setting. For Christmas,
says Bonnie, ``We'll decorate the doll house, put in trees and hide
presents.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum is housed in a Texas historical landmark, the
100-year-old F.W. Arhelger building at 109 N. Adams St., less than
a block from Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   Hours are 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays. Admission is $4,
$3.50 for senior citizens, $3 for students, free for preschoolers
accompanied by an adult. Group rates are available. For more
information, call 830-990-8833 or call the Fredericksburg
Convention and Visitors Bureau at 830-997-6523 or access
www.fredericksburg-texas.com on the Internet. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
