<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-GERMANY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPE'S SPECIAL RELATIONSHIP: RUSSIA AND GERMANY 
</HEADLINE>
   News Analysis  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's visit to Moscow
last month underscored the special relationship _ sometimes
friendly, often bitterly antagonistic _ that has bound Russia and
Germany together for three centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Geography links them in a way that cannot be undone. Just as the
Russians recognize that the United States is the world's
superpower, they know that Germany is by far their strongest
European neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship has gone through many phases. The Russians
first entered the mainstream of European history by taking part in
the coalition that waged war against a German king, Frederick the
Great of Prussia, in the conflict called the Seven Years War
(1756-1763) in Europe and the French and Indian War in colonial
America.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Russia's greatest sovereign, Catherine the Great, was
originally a German princess who came to that country as consort to
the czar. She later usurped the crown.
</P>
<P>
   It is now almost forgotten that in the late 19th century, the
then emperors of Germany and Russia formed an alliance to control
eastern Europe between them. Their alliance ended when Berlin chose
to support the territorial ambitions of its other ally,
Austria-Hungary, in the Balkans. It was a step that deeply offended
all Slavs, including the Russians, and eventually led to World War
I when Slavs murdered the heir to the Austro-Hungarian throne.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout history, the Germans have been attracted to the vast
space and natural resources of the land to their east, which is
part of Europe but somehow quite different. For Germans, Russia
will always be an enigma.
</P>
<P>
   And the Russians, even though they defeated Hitler's invading
legions in World War II, today fear and respect Germany as they do
no other nation, including their other great neighbor, China. They
are envious of Germany's industrial prowess and efficiency, which
they know they'll never be able to match.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, Germans have abandoned their old dream of conquering
Russia and are content now to be simply its biggest foreign
investor, outstripping America and other industrial powers.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, this is a return to the past. Traditionally, the
Germans were the leading merchants and traders of eastern Europe
long before they became jackbooted conquerors.
</P>
<P>
   It was the risk to German investments brought about by Russia's
financial turmoil that gave a sense of urgency to Schroeder's visit
and hour-long meeting with the fading Russian president, Boris
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   However, the big German banks that are the primary investors
seem prepared to ride out the storm. For them, Russia is a good but
extremely long-term bet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 1422EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
