<HEADER>
A4856 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CALIF-3TAKES-H     11-30 1415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CALIF-3TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Onetime glamour town of California resurges with urban renewal 
 
By MARTY RACINE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Hollywood. Beverly Hills. Palm Springs.
Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach?
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Age of Celebrity the glamour capital of Southern
California was a resort town on a bay south of Los Angeles. Back in
the 1920s Long Beach had the largest motion picture studio in the
world, a boardwalk, mansions full of silent-film stars and, well, a
long beach.
</P>
<P>
   But the plot thinned. Hollywood became the leading man in
movies, Beverly Hills and Palm Springs attracted the stars, and
Long Beach returned to the real world. Long Beach discovered oil
under its skin. It built a Navy base and a commercial port. And for
half a century the second-largest city in the metropolitan Los
Angeles area was just too working-class, too secondary to be much
of a destination.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1975 the city embarked on a multibillion-dollar urban
renewal program to continue through the year 2000. It built a
sparkling Convention &AMP; Entertainment Center. It created a village,
marina and park along its shoreline and undertook the largest
waterfront redevelopment project in California history. It carved
out trails for biking, jogging and skating. It landed an aquarium,
installed nightlife downtown and rediscovered history in its parks,
ranches, canals and seaside neighborhoods. Gourmet coffee shops
filtered in from Seattle. Then came the requisite galleries,
bistros, antiques stores and museums.
</P>
<P>
   The refinery became a boutique. Long Beach became a destination.
</P>
<P>
   Now it ranks among the municipalities across America emerging
bleary-eyed from the agrarian and industrial ages knowing the old
economies don't work. Farming communities dried up. The grunt jobs
in the cities were exported to sweatshop republics that high school
seniors couldn't locate on a map. The new economies are based on
tourism _ sports, concerts, gambling, shopping, festivals, scenic
development and restoration.
</P>
<P>
   The Visitor is the new commodity. To compete, all a destination
requires is a big enough Wow Factor to blast the kids' attention
spans for more than three seconds, or long enough for Mom and Dad
to hit the casinos. Soon enough we will be the United States of
Disney, one clamoring theme park stretching from coast to coast,
with security around every corner, ushers in every doorway and
lengthy waits for the privilege.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the carnival and the boosterism, some cities evoke a
sense of place. Long Beach is still a real city _ the size of Fort
Worth, it's too big to be otherwise. And as you drive down Ocean
Boulevard lined with palms and whitewashed bungalows, or fan out
across tidy rose-hedged neighborhoods or find lovers strolling down
its shores, you can't help but be charmed by its daily rhythms. For
there is, apart from the hype and headlines, a timeless California,
where the fog rolls in and by late morning surely burns off, where
desert and sea meet in a ritual pounding of the waves.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the real Long Beach presents itself as a community secured
in time. Its population peaked after World War II, and half a
century later, having battled urban decay, there is a genteel
maturity about the city that contrasts with the tragically hip,
tongue-pierced parades up the coast in Venice and Santa Monica.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it has its rough spots: The shoeshine man on Pine Avenue
will warn you about the ``interior,'' and the air at the Port of
Long Beach feels a little oily, and the freeways are choked half
the time. But on the whole, when the overcast lifts to reveal a
golden go-West-young-man afternoon, as yachts drift in the Pacific
Basin and Lester Young blows wild free-form jazz on local radio
station KLON, Long Beach appears stately, even sophisticated. It's
a role any actor would covet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aquarium of the Pacific &UR;  &LR; (310 Goldenshore; call 562-590-3100;
access www.aquariumofpacific.org on the Internet; open 10 a.m.-6
p.m. daily except Christmas Day; adults, $13.95; children, $6.96;
seniors, $11.95).
</P>
<P>
   Opened this past June at a cost of $117 million, the AOP is the
latest gem to grace the crown of the downtown/harbor Queensway Bay
redevelopment project. The only aquarium anywhere to focus solely
on the world's largest ocean, its huge glass-walled tanks are home
to 10,000 specimens from three major regions: the temperate waters
of Southern and Baja California, the frigid waters of the northern
Pacific and the brilliant coral reefs of the tropics.
</P>
<P>
   Aquariums are lovely to look at, to be sure, but you can't just
jump in and go snorkeling. You can't bait a hook and cast away. For
a visceral experience aquariums rely on virtual reality. For
children of all ages there's Kid's Cove, a hands-on experience. And
suspended above the building's entry is a full-scale replica of a
blue whale, the world's largest mammal. If it were to swim away,
its tongue would weigh 5 tons, more than the body of an African
elephant.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Queen Mary (1126 Queens Highway; 562-435-3511;
www.queenmary.com; open 365 days a year; tours are 9 a.m.-9 p.m.
daily; adults, $13; children, $8; seniors, $11).
</P>
<P>
   The most luxurious ocean liner ever built, the Queen Mary once
ferried the likes of the Duke and Duchess of Windsor, Fred Astaire,
Spencer Tracy, Lionel Barrymore, Clark Gable, David Niven, Greta
Garbo, Bob Hope and Marlene Dietrich.
</P>
<P>
   Longer than the Titanic by 136 feet, the Queen embarked on her
first voyage from Southhampton, England, to New York City in 1936,
with, it is said, more art onboard than is stashed in most major
museums. During World War II it was refitted for battle and
conscripted into service. It participated in numerous allied
campaigns, and Winston Churchill made the Queen Mary his seaborne
headquarters. Nicknamed the Grey Ghost, Hitler put a bounty on it,
offering the equivalent of $50,000 to any submarine that could sink
it. But the liner was so swift it couldn't be caught, and it never
had to fire any of its guns in anger.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967 the city of Long Beach purchased the Queen Mary and
docked it in Long Beach Harbor for use as a tourist attraction and
hotel. Its first-class cabins were converted into hotel rooms (many
with lovely porthole views of downtown Long Beach). Meeting rooms
were turned into catering and banquet rooms, and a wedding chapel
was added, which hosts hundreds of nuptial ceremonies a year.
</P>
<P>
   The restoration of the Queen Mary parallels the Southern
California economy. In the recession of the early 1990s the hotel
closed, and pigeons roosted in the hallways. When it reopened in
1992 the operation lost $4.2 million. By July 1994, expenses no
longer exceeded income. In 1995, the ship made a little money, and
last year it raked in $26 million in tours and hotel stays.
</P>
<P>
   All right, the Queen Mary didn't hit an iceberg, and if you must
gawk at a disaster there's a Titanic exhibit near the front
entrance. But for tourists and hotel guests alike, the Queen
presents a living history. There are authentic replications of such
cruiseline amenities as a barber shop, gymnasium and pharmacy, and
table settings for dining passengers are re-created.
</P>
<P>
   Elegance still reigns in the Queen's Salon, which presents
ballroom dancing on Tuesdays; in Sir Winston's restaurant, which
requires proper attire and offers ocean vistas; and at the Art Deco
Observation Bar, formerly the first class lounge, which recalls a
classy, bygone era. Order a martini or something, not Fizz Lite
beer.
</P>
<P>
   There are airy, wood-planked decks, dim stairwells and romantic,
somewhat musty hallways _ just the odors and the lighting exude
character.
</P>
<P>
   True believers among hotel guests might chance a late-night
stroll, for ghosts are rumored to roam the decks. Famous psychics
have even claimed to hear them. ``Some of my staff said they saw a
woman dressed in black walk into my office and thought I'd come to
work, because I wear black a lot,'' said Lovetta Kramer, director
of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they walked in, and no one was there. I said, `See, I'm
always watching you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Scorpion (1126 Queens Highway).
</P>
<P>
   This 300-foot diesel ``Foxtrot-Class'' submarine served in the
Soviet Navy from 1972 to 1994 and carried 22 torpedoes. Berthed
next to the Queen Mary in a ``wealth and stealth'' tour package,
the Scorpion will be here for the next five years. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 1424EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
