<HEADER>
A4859 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CALIF-2NDTAKE-     11-30 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CALIF-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL-CALIF-2NDTAKE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  LONG BEACH, Calif.: five years. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's referred to by its code name, Scorpion, because its
official moniker, Povodnaya Lodka B-427, which is, well _ imagine
Dad saying to the family, ``Hey, guys let's go visit the Puv ...
odd ... Pavarotti Vodka Before!''
</P>
<P>
   Visitors are first advised to consult their claustro-meters. The
Scorpion is a closet-size, gizmo-crammed chamber through which one
negotiates using pull bars and nimble leg-work. If you feel
trapped, just remind yourself it's only a visit. And you're not
underwater. At one time, 78 Russian sardines coexisted in this tin
can.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rancho Los Alamitos Historic Ranch and Gardens &UR;  &LR; (6400 Bixby Hill
Road; 562-431-3541; tours are1-5 p.m. Wednesdays-Sundays. Admission
is free. Group reservations should be made two weeks in advance).
</P>
<P>
   This ranch echoes with the history of Native America and Spanish
and Mexican California.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning there was the arid, wind-swept mesa and the
American Indian village of Puvungna, a sacred place that existed
around A.D. 500. In 1790 it comprised the largest land grant ever
from the Spanish crown, 300,000 acres given to soldier Manuel
Nieto.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, property disputes with nearby missions and the
concept of eminent domain by Cal State-Long Beach and other
institutions reduced the Alamitos site to 7 { acres. In 1968 the
parcel was donated to the city of Long Beach. Today it is operated
by a nonprofit foundation, with 130 volunteers and a paid staff of
nine.
</P>
<P>
   The grounds are kept as historically correct as possible _ down
to the rose hybrids from the 1920s. Even a damaged sundial was
rebuilt with the help of computer generated graphics.
</P>
<P>
   The guided tour features the rustic adobe ranch house with its
sturdy walls and old-fashioned furniture and appliances. One of the
few remaining two-story adobes in Southern California, it began as
a rudimentary outpost shelter for the ``vaqueros'' working Nieto's
open range and evolved into a home and Long Beach social center.
Behind the hacienda are the working-ranch barns, stables, bunks and
blacksmith shop standing from the ownership of cattleman Fred Bixby
in the early 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   Self-guided tours free you to wander the four acres of famous
gardens developed by Bixby's wife, Florence. Created in an era of
flamboyant regional horticulture, her gardens are instead prized
for their cool, restrained beauty. They were not planted for show
but for repose, for use by friends and family. And at every turn a
new garden envelopes you, such as the geranium walk, rose garden,
olive patio, rock waterway, cactus garden and the oleander walk.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the hacienda or out in the garden, one senses the
continuum of history. With that, it's easy to beam yourself back to
a more serene, if hardscrabble, environment. ``Teeming with people,
it still feels like a special place,'' says C.J. Derby, director of
public relations. ``You can have 2,000 people on the site, and you
still feel like you have your own space.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   El Dorado Nature Center &UR;  &LR; (7550 E. Spring St.; 562-570-1771;
trail tours are 8 a.m.-5 p.m. Tuesdays-Sundays; the museum and
bookstore are open 10 a.m.-4 p.m. Tuesdays-Fridays and 8:30 a.m.-4
p.m. Saturdays and Sundays. Entrance to the nature center is free,
but vehicle entry into the surrounding El Dorado East Regional Park
is $3 weekdays and $5 weekends and holidays).
</P>
<P>
   Alert to stressed-out residents of the modern world: This is
high-trek, not high-tech.
</P>
<P>
   Set amid the urban sprawl is a Long Beach retreat: El Dorado
East Regional Park and its 102-acre centerpiece, the El Dorado
Nature Center. The complex is so massive it shouldn't be in a city.
But this is where it is needed. The nature center sponsors numerous
educational outreach programs. The park participates in Discover
Long Beach Parks, an adopt-a-park program designed for
third-graders that has been credited with reducing vandalism,
graffiti and gang activity.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a former flood plain of the San Gabriel River, the
nature center has walking trails winding around two lakes and a
stream in a dense forest of oak, pine, sycamore and redwood. Keen
observance might yield foxes, weasels, herons, egrets, hawks,
rabbits, possums and turtles.
</P>
<P>
   The two-mile dirt trail has an optional switchback that cuts it
in half. For even shorter jaunts there is a paved quarter-mile
trail that brushes against an open butterfly garden; recovering
stroke patients frequently take their daily constitutionals here.
</P>
<P>
   To begin your walk, stop. Take a deep breath. Take another. It
will calm the mind and clear your senses, senses that have been
dulled by tailgating through life on a treadmill. Here, the ears
are critical, for the brush rustles with critters, and the eyes
follow. Not to worry, though; unlike refuges in Texas, there are no
alligators or venomous serpents.
</P>
<P>
   Don't strive for absolute silence, however, or you'll notice the
high-tension lines humming and the jets roaring at Long Beach
International.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe we can't completely go back to the garden. But we
try, for we deny nature at our peril. The woods hone our survival
instincts, sharpening our entire being. You can achieve that by
walking in a bad part of town, but this is prettier.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Belmont Shore.
</P>
<P>
   Once an expanse of ocean wetlands, Belmont Shore was still a
marsh when real estate agents got in the act in the 1920s. But it
grew into a quintessential Southern California seaside community,
with sandy beaches, boardwalks, apartments named La Contessa and
Ocean Bliss, and immaculately maintained bungalows. There are rose
gardens, white picket fences, archways, red-tiled roofs _ lovely
stuccoed homes built prior to the new architectural behemoths that
scream, ``I'm rich, and you're not!''
</P>
<P>
   Today's Belmont Shore and its main thoroughfare of Second Street
are lined with boutiques, cafes and upscale emporiums _ the
proverbial shopper's paradise in a bastion of breezy
intellectualism, like the Rice Village with a nautical flair. The
people watching isn't bad, either, because Californians don't age.
There is a shoe store named Runner's High, a restaurant that serves
lobster burritos and a Mexican grill that advertises, ``No
microwaves, no can openers, no lard, no freezers, no MSG.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Shore is not above whimsy. If you see a parking meter
casting a ``shadow'' in the form of a pelican don't rub your eyes;
it's only part of a public art project.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shoreline Village.
</P>
<P>
   Located near downtown and on the water, Shoreline Village is a
contrived ``New England-style'' shopping and dining complex.
Despite the affectations, the location is attractive and the dining
excellent. Check out the Yard House, with over 250 brands of beer
on tap and an inventive menu. Parker's Lighthouse is famed for its
seafood.
</P>
<P>
   For families, there's a concentration of the keep-busys: a
virtual reality booth in the EcoPark educational center, outdoor
food vendors, harbor cruises and surrey tours of the coastline.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pine Avenue (downtown).
</P>
<P>
   It's not the French Quarter or Greenwich Village. Pine Avenue,
which slices through the heart of downtown, is more trendy than
bohemian. But it's hip enough, with nightclubs, delis, sidewalk
cafes and art galleries, to qualify as a magnet for
action-seekers. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 1424EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
