<DOCNO> NYT19981130.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4861 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CALIF-3RDTAKE-     11-30 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CALIF-3RDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL-CALIF-3RDTAKE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  LONG BEACH, Calif.: action-seekers. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is only being faithful to its history. For decades Pine was
the city's premier business and social district, linking downtown
shopping with the famous Pike Amusement Park on the water. Grand
hotels, like the Virginia, drew world travelers, and on New Year's
Eve 1961 the Beach Boys made their first public appearance at the
foot of Pine in Municipal Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   But the street deteriorated as business fled to the suburbs, and
the amusement park lost its lure to Disneyland. In the 1960s, '70s
and '80s, the area was dead. Then the city stepped in with a
revitalization plan. Recently it has paid dividends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago, winos were sleeping in the doorway,'' said
shoeshine man Jimmie Brown working Pine between 2nd and 3rd
streets. ``It was full of panhandlers, dope addicts and homeless.
It was real sad in the '80s. This was a Navy town. The city had to
transform it from a Navy town into something else. So they started
by cleaning up these two blocks _ reclaimed them, that is.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't stray too far, he cautioned, waving his arm in a
direction opposite the sea.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gondola Getaway (5437 E. Ocean Blvd. behind Leeway Sailing;
562-433-9595; rides are $55 a couple and $10 for each additional
person and include a complementary basket of bread, salami, cheese,
wine glasses and an ice bucket. Tours are 11 a.m.-11 p.m. daily and
are conducted year-round. Reservations are advised.)
</P>
<P>
   It's not Venice (Italy), but there can be few more romantic
European-like excursions in the New World than the Gondola Getaway,
a one-hour glide through the canals of picturesque Naples Island.
</P>
<P>
   Bring a bottle of your favorite (California) wine and relax as
the gondola drifts around three islands connected by automobile
bridges and adorned with some of Long Beach's most interesting
homes. One, the Hershey House, was built in 1921, about the time
the canals were dredged.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-year-old operation owns a fleet of eight gondolas, some
designed for groups. But this is best appreciated by lovers and
other strangers; many wedding proposals have been issued in these
gondolas.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed, some gondoliers will even croon Italian love
songs. ``People kept on asking me if I'd sing,'' said one. ``I said
`I'm sorry.' Finally I went out and bought some sheet music.''
</P>
<P>
   Though tours are offered throughout the day, the best cruising
hours are at dusk, when the fading sunlight splinters over the
water, the imagination stirs and island residents are likely to be
at home. Some might be swimming in the canal, others might shout
greetings _ in Italian, of course.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach Museum of Art Summer Concert Series (2300 E. Ocean
Blvd.; 562-439-2119; 7 p.m. Wednesdays during the summer; $9 for
members, $12 for nonmembers.)
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it, the appreciation of art can get a little stuffy.
In the summer check the breeze in the Museum of Art's sculpture
garden atop a knoll overlooking the Pacific. On Wednesday evenings
the museum presents concerts that will appeal to anybody but snobs.
This year, the series' 14th, the eclectic list of invitees included
Tex-Mex legend Little Joe, Kansas City bluesman Jimmy Cheatham, big
band leader Eddie Reed, alternative country band the Derailers,
funkster Leo Necentelli, Afro-Cuban group Charanga Cubana and
roots-rocker Dave Alvin.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the down-home mix, this is a first-class BYOB. The
ladies and gentlemen arrive balancing armloads of the essentials
for a true concert experience: short-legged lawn chairs, picnic
baskets and bottles of chardonnay and cabernet sauvignon. To be
imbibed from long-stemmed glasses, natch.
</P>
<P>
   On the evening of Charanga Cubana, a couple of guys are sitting
on the lawn playing chess. A woman is yakking on the phone even as
the cha-cha-cha beat dances past her. Little children are drawing
in coloring books, doing their own thing. And when one couple
unfolds the linen tablecloth and spreads the basil dip, bread
sticks and broccoli florets, you know you've arrived at the end of
the continent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For brochures and general information, call the Long Beach Area
Convention and Visitors Bureau at 800-452-7829. Access
www.golongbeach.org on the Internet. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
