<HEADER>
A4863 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-30 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOV. BUSH STILL DEFINING `COMPASSIONATE?' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Politicians, it seems, are constantly in search of the
perfect buzz word or memorable phrase that will keep them near and
dear to the hearts, minds or whatever else prompts voters to put
and keep them in public office.
</P>
<P>
   Former President George Bush advocated a ``kinder, gentler''
America.
</P>
<P>
   Now, his eldest son, George W. Bush, the hugely popular governor
of Texas who is being effusively touted in the Texas and national
media as the next president, is eagerly embracing the
``compassionate conservative'' label.
</P>
<P>
   As with all labels, we should be wary of this one until we see
how the governor continues to define it through his actions in his
second term. Of particular importance will be his role as the state
continues to grapple with welfare reform, an area that needs a
large dose of compassion in the true meaning of the word.
</P>
<P>
   Bush didn't invent the ``compassionate conservative'' phrase. A
long string of other Republicans with varying reputations have been
laying claim to it for years.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dole called himself a ``compassionate conservative'' in the
months before he lost the 1988 Republican presidential nomination
to the Texas governor's father.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Wilson won the governorship of California in 1990,
campaigning as a ``compassionate conservative,'' and then, a few
years later, adopted a hard line against impoverished immigrants
seeking a better life _ but overwhelming the financial resources _
in his state.
</P>
<P>
   Even Newt Gingrich has tried to wear the label.
</P>
<P>
   Bush apparently is trying to distinguish himself from the
``take-no-prisoners,'' social conservative agenda that has
dominated so much of Republican Party politics in recent years
before sputtering in the recent congressional elections, resulting
in Gingrich's downfall.
</P>
<P>
   Bush occasionally tosses a bone to that wing of the party,
which, he knows, can help scuttle a race for the GOP nomination for
the White House. He opposes abortion rights, for example, and will
even say so if someone asks him. But he has never been very
comfortable with the far right.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Bush has been enormously successful. He was re-elected
with 69 percent of the Texas vote and helped Republicans capture
every statewide office for the first time in modern history. His
message of lower taxes, welfare reform and improved educational
opportunities clearly appealed to a wide mainstream of Texas
voters, including many minority Texans who usually don't vote for
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republican governors and gubernatorial candidates in other
states enjoyed similar, if less spectacular, successes while their
more obviously partisan GOP colleagues in Congress were suffering
setbacks on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP governors believe their electoral successes were derived
from their pragmatic, businesslike approach to tackling the same
``mainstream'' issues that Bush has identified. At least that was
the message they delivered at their recent national conference in
New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   One could argue that Bush and other Republican governors have
been seeking ``moderate'' solutions to crucial pocketbook issues
that are of far more importance to the average American than any
amount of ideological ranting or hot button-pushing.
</P>
<P>
   Bush could be classified as a ``moderate'' Republican. But the
Texas governor quickly spit out that adjective when a reporter
suggested it at the New Orleans meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Being labeled a ``moderate'' is only slightly less distasteful
for a potential Republican presidential candidate than being called
a ``bleeding heart.''
</P>
<P>
   By calling himself a ``compassionate conservative'' instead,
Bush is trying to appeal to all stripes of Republicans,
independents and even some Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But it is difficult to reconcile the ``compassionate'' part of
Bush's self-proclaimed label with some of the new welfare reforms
the governor proposed during his re-election campaign. Particularly
disturbing is his proposal to cut off welfare payments to children
if their parents refuse to work, as required by state and federal
laws.
</P>
<P>
   Bush insists the sanction, designed to help end the welfare
cycle, would prove more ``compassionate'' in the long run. And, he
says, the children would still be eligible for food stamps and
Medicaid benefits.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that poor people must be moved from the
welfare rolls to jobs. But making a child, whose existence is
already pretty close to hand-to-mouth, suffer for the sins of a
wayward parent is hardly ``compassionate.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
