<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4879 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BENETTON-CATALOG-HNS &LR;      11-30 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BENETTON-CATALOG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETAILER'S CATALOG TACKLES NEW SOCIAL ISSUE: DISABILITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The young cover model has spiked hair, Down
syndrome and a wonderful blue turtleneck emblazoned with the word
LOVE. In another brilliant photograph, a boy with cerebral palsy
wears a beautiful brown sweater as he communicates with his
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Is this 98-page catalog, showing the fall/winter line for
Benetton, the Italian apparel retailer, cynicism and exploitation
run amok? Or is it the liberation of stereotypes about the
developmentally disabled?
</P>
<P>
   This much is true: Raising questions, social conscience and
emotions is the way of Benetton's unusual and provocative branding
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1982, the company has used the photography and art
direction of Oliviero Toscani to create a sociopolitical brand
image that denounces intolerance. Many images have struck many
people as gratuitously offensive. Examples: a man dying of AIDS, a
nun and priest kissing, a condom placed over the Obelisk in Paris,
a black horse mounting a white horse.
</P>
<P>
   Toscani explains that the horses ``oblige us to reflect on a
principle we often forget: that which is natural is never vulgar.''
</P>
<P>
   Criticism notwithstanding, Benetton's revenues and net profits
have grown steadily through the decade in the 120 countries where
it has a presence. It had $2 billion in sales in 1997, a 13 percent
increase in Europe, up 11 percent in the Americas and down 11
percent in Asia and the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Its strategy in the United States has been to reduce the number
of stores from 600 _ when the company went public in 1986 _ to 200
today, but increasing their size.
</P>
<P>
   In those stores, consumers will find the new fall/winter
catalog, which, in fact, is not a catalog: There are no prices, no
codes, no way to order any of the clothes worn by the children
photographed with their families and teachers and staff at their
school, St. Valentin Institute in the Bavarian Alps of Germany.
Benetton calls it ``an image booklet'' that is free and has been
extremely popular at Benetton stores since it was released last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Toscani is not on Benetton's executive staff but is given
artistic license through a contract with Luciano Benetton,
president of the Benetton Group. Benetton founded the company with
brothers Gilberto and Carlo, and sister Giuliana in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   The faces of the children in Toscani's photographs reflect the
same joy and curiosity and melancholy of any child, and lead people
to ``not pity but respect'' others who are different, said Millie
Olson of Amazon Advertising in San Francisco. She found the book a
bold detour from advertising's overworked and often narrow
boundaries of beauty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company is willing to do the socially responsible thing,''
said Lynda Pearson, Olson's Amazon colleague, ``and thank God for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The children of St. Valentin are the centerpiece of an $82
million worldwide fall/winter advertising campaign, including U.S.
fashion magazines. There's no question that selling goods has a
role in the campaign. But is this campaign righteous?
</P>
<P>
   ``They are pictures that speak of a world with no defenses, no
limits, no preconceptions,'' said Toscani, who, in the 1970s and
1980s, did conventional fashion photography and catalog work. ``I
chose these children, these young people, these families, because
they are beautiful in the purest sense of the word.''
</P>
<P>
   Toscani long ago broadened his definition of beauty. Last year's
Benetton image booklet was titled ``Enemies,'' in which friendly
Israelis and Palestinians _ some of them lovers _ were photographed
in colorful Benetton clothes. On the cover, a Bedouin and an
Israeli kissed.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1991, Toscani has assembled provocative ads and placed
them within the covers of the Benetton magazine ``Colors,'' which
contains no ads for the retailer but is devoted to stories about
race, war, AIDS and a host of other social issues. It is published
six times a year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This year's Benetton booklet, called ``the Sunflowers,'' has
resonance among parents of disabled children.
</P>
<P>
   Geneva Peare of Lafayette, Calif., whose son, Garrison, 6, has
Down syndrome, said she saw only love in the 98 pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tells about the children and their families and you get a
sense of the individual versus the disability, and that is what we
all strive for,'' Peare said. ``A lot of times people will say,
`Oh, you have a kid with Down's, and they are so loving.' They just
give a generalization and they do not try to get to know my son as
a person who has his own likes and dislikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Including disabled children in society, advertising included, is
good for all of us, said Dr. William Cohen, director of the Child
Development Unit and Down Syndrome Center at Children's Hospital of
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important issue is that if we make believe that people
with differences do not exist, it certainly makes it harder for
them to live their lives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ```Sesame Street' recognized this 20 years ago and began
including children with a whole variety of differences. Believe me,
parents of children with learning problems and physical
disabilities want their children in the community,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Disabled children, said Salt Lake City pediatrician Louis
Borgenicht, are not like every other child. ``The degree to which
they are set apart depends on the individual who is perceiving what
they are doing,'' he said. As he looked at the catalog, he said he
thought not about what the children wore, ``but who these kids are
and how we view them socially.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Borgenicht added, ``I flip-flop on thinking it's
exploitative. I'm torn a little. It raises questions I'm not
prepared to answer. But that's good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
