<HEADER>
A4897 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      11-30 1481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of TUESDAY, Dec.
1.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ALZHEIMERS (New York) _ Scientists at New York University
Medical Center spent three days exploring the brain of the writer
in search for clues about what destroyed the brain of her mother at
a very early age. By Marion Roach. (1725 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SCIENTISTS-FILM (Los Angeles) _ Hollywood's treatment of
scientists is out of sync with that of the press, which generally
presents scientists as articulate people making important
discoveries. So now, efforts are being mounted to get Hollywood to
portray scientists in a more realistic light, as people with more
complex drives and emotions. These efforts also aim at getting
Hollywood to portray the process of scientific inquiry itself. But,
it's a hard sell. By Andrew Pollack. (1880 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NEANDERTHAL-DIET (Undated) _ In a study already drawing the
fire of controversy, an American geographer has pointed out
evidence suggesting, in his view, that little more than the amount
of iodine in their diets may have been responsible for the physical
differences between Neanderthals and modern humans and that this
might solve the mystery of what happened to the Neanderthals. By
John Noble Wilford. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EMBRYOS-COMPETE (Undated) _ Evolutionary theorists are
scratching their heads over a new experiment on the breeding
characteristics of a rare species of monogamous mice. The
experiment has cast surprising doubt on a controversial, but highly
successful idea, namely that of a competition between embryos in
the womb and their mother, fueled by a kind of molecular arms race
between the sexes. By Gina Kolata. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions answered: Do the terms
snake, viper and serpent have scientific differences? (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ION-PROPULSION (Undated) _ After more than a month of
lurching through space in fits and starts, an experimental
spacecraft crammed with new technologies has begun to cruise away
from Earth, driven by a recently revived ion propulsion engine
taken from science fiction. By Warren E. Leary. (980 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SHUTTLE (Undated) _ People in the eastern third of the
United States will be able to see the space shuttle within a few
minutes of its launching. By Joe Rao. (680 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SAGAN-LEGACY (Undated) _ When Dr. Carl Sagan died two years
ago this month at age 62, most eulogies focused on his career in
popularizing science and conveying the wonders of the universe to
millions of people. But in addition to his celebrity, or perhaps
even despite it, Dr. Sagan was a serious and gifted researcher who
pushed back the frontiers of planetary science, molded a number of
gifted students and wielded great influence behind the scenes in
Washington. By William J. Broad. (2150 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on a new
test to tell if old pottery held milk; ways of dating earthquakes
with cosmic rays; sniffing out termites because they smell like
moth balls; dead and dying salamanders. (666 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-UMBILICAL-BLOOD (Undated) _ Should parents pay a blood bank
to store the blood from their newborn baby's umbilical cord and
placenta, in case that child or another family member ever needs it
to treat cancer or leukemia? Expectant parents are being urged to
do so by companies that have sprung up during the past few years to
sell cord-blood banking as a form of ``biological insurance''
against such dreaded diseases. By Denise Grady. (1150 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Fitness and Health &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Diet plays an important role in the
prevention of cancer, including breast cancer. The American Cancer
Society estimates that diet is a primary factor in a third of
cancer deaths. But pop science that holds that fish oils, for
example, ``prevent'' cancer just doesn't hold up under scrutiny. By
Jane E. Brody. (1150 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SOCCER-RISK (Undated) _ The risk of injury in soccer may
have been downplayed, at least at the professional level, a study
published in the current issue of the British Journal of Sports
Medicine reveals. Players, the researchers found, had a 12 percent
chance of injury per game. By Paul Gains. (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MAMMOGRAPHY (Undated) _ After a long delay, the Food and
Drug Administration is on the verge of issuing revised guidelines
that could enable a new generation of mammography devices to come
to the market. The devices rely on digital imaging, a technique
experts say offers clearer, more detailed pictures of some breast
tissue than traditional X-ray film. By Anne Eisenberg. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FITNESS-TREADMILL (Undated) _ The success of Spinning has
spawned a new concept in exercise: Group classes are moving out of
the aerobics studio and on to the cardiovascular machines found on
the gym floor. Treadmill classes in particular are beginning to
appear on aerobics schedules all across the country. (575 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ Shorts on health:
</P>
<P>
   _ According to a researcher at Harvard, in any 24-hour period,
married women are 50 percent more likely to complain of being in a
bad mood than they Y-chromosomed counterparts. The reason, he
theorizes, is that married women juggle several roles, so they
encounter more opportunities for things to go wrong in their lives.
(275 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ The Lung Health Study, which tracked 5,887 smokers, found that
those who quit put on substantially more weight in the years after
they kicked the habit _ 17 pounds for men and 19 pounds for women _
than earlier, shorter studies had indicated. (245 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Until recently, these utterances like `uh' and `oh' were
considered garbage that hindered communication. But a study due to
appear in the Journal of Memory and Language argues that the word
``oh,'' when used in the middle of a sentence, is not a bad habit,
but in fact plays a pivotal role in comprehension. (350 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ When doctors put down their pens and typed prescriptions into
a terminal, serious medication errors dropped by half, researchers
at Brigham and Women's Hospital have found. (325 words)
</P>
