<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORDERLY HOUSE, ORDERLY MIND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A friend returned a book I'd lent her three years ago. It was
``The Messies Manual,'' one of a series Sandra Felton does so well,
the verbal equivalent of a week in boot camp for bad housekeepers.
I tried to stick it back on the shelf, but it clung to my fingers
for dear life and was grunting, ``Read me, read me,'' as it
wrestled me onto the couch.
</P>
<P>
   I'd already completed my entire fall cleaning. I'd finally
gotten rid of the pantry moths that spent an entire summer in my
house. I'd moved my winter clothes into my closet and organized the
upstairs hall closet. I was ready to move on with my life, when
that darn book started whispering, ``little minutes, little
minutes,'' like I really cared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little minutes'' is Felton's technique for breaking the habit
of making messes. It sounds simple. Placing something in a cabinet?
Wipe off the fingerprints. Brushing your teeth? Clean off the
counter. Putting away the laundry? Take a few ``little minutes'' to
straighten the drawers.
</P>
<P>
   Voila! No need for a cleaning marathon. None of this
it's-such-a-mess-I-don't-know-where-to-start. Everything that was
once neat and clean stays that way. No more lost checkbooks or
jumbled papers, dirty dishes in the sink, or clothes on the floor.
You just tidy up as you go along and before you know it, your house
is manageable and, even better, your life is in order at last.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe that, I have a bridge in Brooklyn I'd like to
sell you ...
</P>
<P>
   But I did believe Sandra Felton, who confesses to having once
been a major messie herself. I loved how orderly my house felt and
I wanted to reform. I didn't want to wake up in a day or two and
find that Hurricane Linda had struck again, dirtied things and
failed to clean them, taken things out and not put them back, used
things and left them where they didn't belong and couldn't be
found. Could my housekeeping actually be turned around in just a
few ``little minutes'' a day?
</P>
<P>
   A week later: The house is still neat, but I'm a wreck. Constant
straightening does the trick, but I'm finding that Felton's little
minutes stretch out like hours for someone who's used to leaping
ahead to the next thing on her mind. I'm usually ready to head off
to aerobics class right after breakfast, but like a fly in
molasses, now I'm stuck. I can't leave until the dishes are in the
dishwasher, the milk is in the refrigerator, and the oatmeal and
brown sugar are back on the shelf. Clean-up feels endless when I'm
raring to go and there are still a few malicious crumbs on the
counter, thumbing their nose at me.
</P>
<P>
   There are moments I doubt I'll ever get out the door again.
</P>
<P>
   There's another problem. One little minute leads to a myriad
others, at least at the beginning. For example, for most of my life
I've simply gotten out of my car, taking a few things with me.
Inside the house I usually drop them on the counter in the hall and
tend to whatever task is before me. Now I carefully clean out the
car and when I get inside, I concentrate on putting everything
away.
</P>
<P>
   This is what happened one day. First I put the Scotch tape I'd
bought up in my office. I took a few little minutes to organize the
basket that holds Scotch tape and stuff. Then I filed the papers
I'd photocopied, taking more little minutes to straighten out the
papers in that one file. When I went to put away a shirt I'd
purchased, I took quite a few little minutes to hang all my
turtlenecks next to each other. I was putting away groceries, using
up more precious minutes wiping refrigerator shelves, when my
husband showed up, expecting to eat dinner.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't believe his nerve.
</P>
<P>
   Felton says it gets easier. I believe her, even though she's
never set foot in our attic or Jack's workroom, two domestic black
holes that have been accepting everything and disgorging nothing
for 30 years. When I have organized the life out of every drawer,
every closet, every shelf, and every cabinet in this house, she
promises my little minutes will shrink to almost nothing, my
extraordinary capacity to create a mess a minute will diminish, and
beauty, dignity, and harmony will reign in my home and in my soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere. Sometime,'' as Maria sings in ``West Side Story.''
</P>
<P>
   If you believe that, I have some waterfront property to sell you
in Bangladesh ...
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's website is at www.shore.net(tilde)weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
