<DOCNO> NYT19981130.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4940 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-30 1581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING THE FAMILY IN BALANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whenever Gary Slate of Stoughton, Mass. comes home from school
and sees yet another thick envelope in the mail for his sister, he
writes off dinner that night. Conversation is bound to focus again
on the pros and cons of yet another college that Rachel is
considering. Boring, boring, boring.
</P>
<P>
   Gary, 14, tries to be stoic. Nonetheless, he says, ``It starts
to make you feel bad.'' Bad as in jealous, left out, and worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts things in my mind that I wish weren't there and that
makes me feel weird,'' says Gary. ``Like, even though college is
far away for me, I wonder, `Am I gonna make it?''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Gary has felt that special events in
his sister's life are unfairly setting the agenda for the family.
Take her bat mitzvah. ``Nobody had time to do regular family
things, like throw a ball around,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   What Gary is experiencing is a disequilibrium in the family, a
natural occurrence when one child gets more than a normal share of
parental attention. It doesn't have to be monthslong preparations
for a bar mitzvah; for some children, attention that comes and goes
even in a week in the wake of a one-time award is too much to
handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family balance is out of whack,'' says psychologist Mark
L. Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
   That it's out of whack for something exciting, something worthy
of pride and joy, is a nuance lost on them. A child can only bring
a child's perspective to bear, after all, and it can best be summed
up in three words: What about me?
</P>
<P>
   The sooner parents realize and accept that, the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any child who feels left out is going to be hurt. That's human
nature,'' says Michigan clinical psychologist Daniel Blake, who
specializes in sibling relationships.
</P>
<P>
   How the hurt manifests itself varies by developmental stage:
</P>
<P>
   _A 3- to 5-year-old typically blames herself: ``It's my fault
I'm left out because I had bad thoughts about Daddy.''
</P>
<P>
   _A 6- to 8-year-old sees things as right or wrong, thus he's
angry at you for being ``unfair'' and allowing the balance of
attention in the family to shift.
</P>
<P>
   _A child 9 or older knows he should be happy for a sibling but
he can't help his jealous feelings. ``That makes him feel bad: `I
must be a bad person if I can't be more generous and loving to my
sister,''' says pediatric psychologist Peter Goldenthal, director
of child and family therapy at Children's Seashore House of
Children's Hospital of Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   At any age, the behavior you see can run a gamut, from lashing
out to withdrawing. The young child, for instance, could be angry
with Daddy for making her have the bad thoughts to begin with or
she could refuse to get caught up in the event because she reasons
she's too bad to share in it.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest mistake we make is insisting a sibling be
happy for the sister. When you force a child to act other than the
way he feels, it creates dissonance, says Blake: ``It makes you
question your feelings _ `Are they real?' _ and makes you think
there is something wrong with you for having them.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting aggravated at what looks like a selfish attitude doesn't
help either. ``Asking, `Can't you be happy for your sister?' or
telling her that her turn will come doesn't compute for her,'' says
Goldstein, a Northbrook, Ill., therapist who specializes in family
relations. Children under 12 are generally too egocentric to take
another person's perspective, he says. They also have a hard time
looking into the future.
</P>
<P>
   While it's true many children look at a brother's presents or
praise and whine, ``I want some, too,'' Goldenthal tells parents
not to assume a child is only feeling petty jealousy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be very anxiety-provoking to see your older sibling go
through something you know you, too, will have to go through,
especially if the sib is struggling,'' he says. ``There's a lot of
anticipatory anxiety: `I don't want to go through that. It'll be
even harder for me!'''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Fran Slate says that for her daughter's bat mitzvah,
Gary was more nervous than Rachel. It wasn't out of empathy,
however. Not only was he nervous for himself, says Fran, but he
worried his parents would run out of money by the time it was his
turn. ``He wanted the same benefits as Rachel,'' says their mother.
``When it was time to plan his bar mitzvah, he wanted the exact
celebration she had.''
</P>
<P>
   Wisely, Fran and husband Arthur never tried to disavow Gary's
jealous feelings and engaged him in conversations about his fears.
Goldenthal urges all parents to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can almost be certain that every child worries about his
turn,'' he says. In families where there is only one child, the
comparison could be made to an older cousin.
</P>
<P>
   Bring up the issue even if a child doesn't: ``I know you've
noticed how hard this is/how much work this is. When it's your
turn, we'll get you all the help you need.'' This simple statement
of support, especially for a child who feels less capable, is
surprisingly calming, Goldenthal says.
</P>
<P>
   He also tells parents to let a child know that you know the
balance is out of whack. For instance: ``This college stuff is
taking more time than I expected and it may seem unfair to you. If
you notice I'm going overboard with it, tell me, as long as you are
polite about it.'' Then, says Goldenthal, ``When he says at dinner,
`Dad, you asked me to remind you,' thank him and switch gears.
Don't say, `Yeah, but this is important.'''
</P>
<P>
   While some siblings' anger will be directed toward the older
sibling, some may be directed toward you. ``It's as if she's
saying, `You're not taking good care of me!''' says Blake.
</P>
<P>
   Don't compromise your limit-setting, even if you feel guilty for
neglecting a child. Instead of making him feel special, it feels
like you aren't paying attention or don't care enough to set the
limits. In addition, you push him to seek negative attention:
``What will make Mom pay attention to me?''
</P>
<P>
   Not all children look at a big event in an older sibling's life
and dread it. Some can't wait for their turn, especially for
graduation or a driver's license. Validate that these are
reasonable feelings to have, suggests Blake: ```It does seem like
it will be forever, doesn't it,''' rather than, ```Stop griping,
it'll be your turn soon enough.' That puts you on his side,'' says
Blake: ```You aren't going through it alone.'''
</P>
<P>
   On occassion, the table gets turned and it's an older sibling
who is jealous of a younger's achievement. Just because he's older
and developmentally more capable of understanding how these things
can happen, the hurt is no less.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many parents have no tolerance for comments like, `She doesn't
deserve it,''' says Blake. He says a good response is to
acknowledge the reality in a gentle way: `There are some painful
moments in life and this may be one of them for you, to see your
sister do something better than you did. It hurts.''' Find a time
later to talk about his strengths.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Slate wishes there was a way for parents to protect younger
siblings from all the plans and discussions. ``Maybe the
conversations can be when the younger person isn't around, or after
he's gone to bed,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that parents have to forget about the college
applications, or whatever,'' adds Gary. ``I know it's a big deal in
a family, but the rest of us still have our life, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Look for ways to include younger siblings in the event.
</P>
<P>
   Siblings who exhibit no signs of jealousy or anger may or may
not be fine. Try to draw them out by talking about yourself or a
third party: ``I remember when my sister ...''
</P>
<P>
   It's better to help a child work through feelings of resentment
than to buy the feelings away with a gift; when the gift's novelty
wears off, the feelings will still be there. On the other hand,
it's OK to talk about his upcoming birthday and what he wants as a
way to remind him that he, too, is worthy.
</P>
<P>
   If you're spending less time with a younger child, be pointed in
your adjustment: ``I've been so busy with Jen's recital that you
and I haven't had any time together. How about if we shut ourselves
in your bedroom Saturday morning to play?''
</P>
<P>
   If you can't afford to do the same thing you did for your
first-born, or your values have changed, say so: ``We gave your
brother a car when he got his license. It was a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Give credit to a sibling for his help, even if the help is
simply not complaining: ``I know it must be hard to listen to all
these conversations. Thanks for being such a good sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Deal with brattiness between siblings as you always would, but
afterwards look for an opening to get feelings out: ``I bet it's
hard to see your brother getting so much attention ...''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ Before a new baby and just after, two good books:
For a preschooler, ``Waiting for Baby'' by Harriet Ziefert; for 4-
to 7-year-olds, ``frog face, my little sister &AMP; me'' by John
Schindel (both Henry Holt).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Barbara Meltz's e-mail address is meltz(at)nws.globe.com. Her
columns are now on line at Boston.Com, keyword ``parenting.'' For
photocopies of past columns, send a self-addressed, stamped
envelope to Barbara F. Meltz, The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston,
MA 02107-2378. Please specify the column.)
</P>
</TEXT>
