<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4974 &Cx1f; taf-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PICKING-THE-PERFECT-G     11-30 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PICKING-THE-PERFECT-GUITAR-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PICKING THE PERFECT GUITAR  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., DATE, 1998)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By MICK HAMER  
 Copyright 1998 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What makes a good classical guitar? Researchers in Mexico have
discovered that a guitar's quality can be assessed by measuring its
tuning accuracy and its acoustic efficiency. Their findings could
take much of the guesswork out of buying a guitar.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, led by Ricardo Boullosa from the National
Autonomous University of Mexico in Mexico City, tested four
classical guitars, ranging in price from $50 to $500. They asked a
mixture of people, from nonmusicians to professional guitarists, to
rate the sound quality.
</P>
<P>
   The team then tried to link its results with the physical
characteristics of the instruments. ``As far as we know, this is
the first attempt to correlate the tuning properties and radiation
efficiency of guitars with their subjective musical quality,'' the
researchers say in the current edition of Applied Acoustics.
</P>
<P>
   Two separate tests were carried out. First, the team asked a
small audience, including professional guitarists, to listen to
snatches of music. The audience could not see which of the four
guitars was being played. The most expensive guitar won three times
as many votes as the cheapest. Then a small group of guitarists,
including amateurs and professionals, was asked to rate the
instruments. They too rated the most expensive guitar the highest.
</P>
<P>
   Guitarists sound different notes by holding down the guitar's
strings against ``frets'' _ thin raised metal bands mounted on the
wooden ``neck'' of the instrument. The team measured the tuning
accuracy of these frets. In a perfectly tuned guitar, each fret
would be exactly a semitone apart _ known in acoustics as 100 cents
(one cent is one hundredth of a semitone).
</P>
<P>
   But the team found that the mean tuning error of the four
guitars varied from 7 cents in the $500 guitar to 20 cents in one
of the midrange guitars.
</P>
<P>
   The team then tested the radiation efficiency of the
instruments, which is a measure of how effective they are at
turning the mechanical energy from plucking a string into sound.
They found that for frequencies below 1 kilohertz, the $500 guitar
had an efficiency of nearly 15 percent, while the cheapest guitar
was less than 10 per cent.
</P>
<P>
   David Whiteman, who teaches guitar-making at London Guildhall
University's department of design and technology, says that the
tuning and radiation efficiency are unlikely to be the whole story.
Players also look for the guitar's tonal quality, how long notes
take to die away and the sound balance between the different
strings, he says.
</P>
<P>
   He adds that the guitars used in the test were relatively cheap,
and components such as the fretboard were probably factory-made.
``In the United States a handmade concert instrument would cost
between $3,000 and $6,000,'' he says. He doubts whether the results
from these tests would apply to top-of-the-range models. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
