<TEXT>
<P>
   COLORADO -- CENSUS. Colorado stands to gain millions of dollars
in federal aid because of its burgeoning minority population if
President Clinton prevails over congressional Republicans in the
court battle over how to conduct the next census. The Supreme Court
began hearing arguments in the case Monday. With tabular material.
Davant
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA -- CENSUS. U.S. Rep. Dan Miller, R-Bradenton, still may
have a say in the controversy over whether statistical sampling is
used in the next census, even though the issue has landed in the
Supreme Court. (Sidebar.) Williams
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA -- STEEL. A Senate panel held hearings from members of
the U.S. industry and Clinton administration officials on whether
foreign countries are illegally dumping cheap steel on the American
market. Wolfberg
</P>
<P>
   MASSACHUSETTS -- HUD. The Worcester area will receive more than
$2.5 million in federal aid this year to help subsidize elderly
housing, President Clinton announced Saturday. (Note - Story moved
at 12:10) Preston
</P>
<P>
   OHIO -- STEEL-DEWINE -- U.S. Se . Mike Dewine warned a Senate
panel Monday that the flood of foreign steel imports are
threatening Ohio's economy. Gorman
</P>
<P>
   -- MANSFIELD-CAP. A federal district judge ruled late last week
that the Mansfield Community Action Program cannot temporarily
retain control over the Head Start program. Claiming that CAP is
not likely to succeed in its efforts to sue the U.S. Department of
Health and Human Services for taking away its Head Start grant,
Judge Colleen Kolar-Kotelly denied CAP's request for a preliminary
injunction against Akron-Summit Community Action Inc.'s scheduled
takeover of the local Head Start on Dec. 7. Hurt
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA. STEEL - Sens. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., Senate steel
caucus chair, held a caucus hearing to examine remedies for the
steel import crisis. Among those testifying, Curtis Barnette,
chairman and CEO of Bethlehem Steel Corp. Developing from 2 p.m.
caucus hearing. Fine
</P>
