<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NSYNC-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'N SYNC'S A CAPPELLA FELLAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _If your teen-age daughters won't stop talking about
'N Sync, don't go running to the kitchen in a panic. That's not the
Sync they're excited about.
</P>
<P>
   This 'N Sync is Justin Timberlake, JC Chasez, Lance Bass, Joey
Fatone and Chris Kirkpatrick, five good-looking boys-next-door from
Orlando, Fla., who specialize in smooth r&AMP;b-style harmonies, tight
soul-brother choreography and more hooks than you'll find in a
fisherman's tackle box.
</P>
<P>
   The group, which has been compared to fellow Orlando heartthrobs
the Backstreet Boys and New Kids on the Block, is this week's pop
sensation. Last month, they were opening for Janet Jackson. Today,
they're in the midst of a headlining tour of theaters that comes to
the Universal Amphitheatre on Jan. 5 and 8 for shows that sold out
in 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't hurt that 'N Sync had two albums in the Top 10 last
week _ their self-titled debut and the holiday-themed ``Home for
Christmas,'' both on RCA Records. Plus, there was that high-profile
appearance last week on the Macy's Thanksgiving Parade telecast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't changed _ our schedules have changed, that's about
it,'' said Timberlake, 17, the youngest member of the group. ``We
have ourselves to keep us humble. We're a gathering of friends who
really wanted to do this particular kind of music. We knew we
wanted to sing a lot of a cappella harmony.''
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, Timberlake and his pals formed the group in Orlando
but became an overnight success in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Chasez, originally from Washington, D.C., met Memphis-born
Timberlake on the set of the Disney Channel's ``Mickey Mouse Club''
in the mid-'90s. After the show ended, the two singers found
themselves in Nashville working with the same vocal coach and
writers on separate solo projects.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Timberlake returned to Orlando, where he hooked up
with Kirkpatrick. The trio met New York native Fatone at a local
club, later adding Bass.
</P>
<P>
   'N Sync's debut album was first issued in Germany, where the
pop-soul workout ``I Want You Back'' became a chart smash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's a learning experience,'' Timberlake said from
home. ```The Mickey Mouse Club' was a great way for me to learn
about acting and sound stages and studios. You get to see how the
machinery works, how everything comes into play.''
</P>
<P>
   The group appears Saturday in the premiere of the Disney
Channel's ``Holidays in Concert'' cable special and as presenters
on Monday's on Fox's Billboard Music Awards. Christmas Day, you can
get in sync with 'N Sync on ABC's ``Walt Disney World's Very Merry
Christmas Parade.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Bell, music buyer for the Wherehouse chain, called the
quintet ``unstoppable'' a few days before an April 16 date at the
17,500-seat Forum sold out in 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be heard by all age groups,'' Timberlake said. ``We
came out first on the radio. If people were into the song, then
they were into the group. Shortly after that, they matched the
faces with the song.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the group has captivated the teen and preteen market with
high-energy teen music made by teens, just like Hanson and Brandy.
</P>
<P>
   A typical fan is Tina Mathew, 15, a Maryland high schooler who
started an 'N Sync site on the Web in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their music is so upbeat, and they seem like the type of
people you want to talk to,'' she said. ``They're not stuck up
about their success or anything. They differ from the Backstreet
Boys musically, too. A lot of people just hear the dance beat and
assume they're the same, but really they're not. There's
differences in lyrics, beats and singing styles.''
</P>
<P>
   There's that B-word again _ Backstreet. 'N Sync not only share
the same manager and home base, but both groups have a cute young
blond as their object of female devotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being compared to others is just something that comes along
with being in a group,'' says Timberlake, 'N Sync's teen-age poster
boy in question. ``Things will change. When Toni Braxton first came
out, she had to deal with being compared to Mariah Carey and
Whitney Houston. It's not a big deal with us. I think people
recognize the difference when they come see our show. Personally, I
think our harmonies sound a lot different. We have a little more of
an r&AMP;b sound.''
</P>
<P>
   The members of 'N Sync insist there's no competition, even when
their debut album overtook Backstreet in the Top 200 after a savvy
Disney Channel concert special aired in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't come into this business to beat anybody out,''
Timberlake said. ``We weren't thinking about anybody except
ourselves when we started. We're not here to knock anybody off
their platform _ we want to make a platform of our own. We're just
all about 'N Sync. It's a big country, and there's room for
everybody. I'm not worried about what anyone has to say about us or
what other groups might think of us. We're just here to be the
first 'N Sync, not the second anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite a packed schedule that will see 'N Sync on TV and
in concert throughout the new year, Timberlake says it's all
business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Even as far as girlfriends are concerned?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't get close to anybody,'' he laughingly moans, then gets
serious. ``I'm trying. It's a hard thing to do being in a different
city every day. Personally, I'm not good over the phone. I've
tried, but it doesn't work for me. I'm just trying to keep my
options open for when things maybe settle down.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we're at home, we go out on dates if we meet someone.
We'll definitely ask them out if time permits, but we're all really
focused on what we're doing right now. Everything else is just kind
of secondary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
