<HEADER>
A5070 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ESSAY:RADIO-REEKS-150     11-30 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESSAY:RADIO-REEKS-1500(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORPORATE OWNERS AND FAINTHEARTED PROGRAMMERS ARE KILLING RADIO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although this is an essay about radio, it's appropriate that it
follows the reissue of a certain older movie. Because every time I
turn on a commercial music radio station these days, I feel my own
big chill.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1983, when ``The Big Chill'' was first in theaters, I
was part of a group of broadcasting students who _ like the movie's
characters when they were in college _ were idealistic, precocious
and ambitious. And, like the movie's characters, few of us followed
through on our promise, at least not in the way we expected to.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen of us staffed a campus radio station that was
piped directly into the dorms. We followed few rules; although the
station had some sort of playlist, most of us played what we wanted
to. It made for a lively mix of early hip-hop, small-label punk,
deep-cut classic rock and mainstream music.
</P>
<P>
   The station was called KVOF, the last three letters
optimistically standing for Voice of the Future. We were hardly the
voice of the future; only one person from that group still works in
radio. We were hardly the voice of the present; I used to joke that
the transmitter was made up of a shoe box, a couple of soda cans, a
double-A battery and a coat hanger. But it's precisely because we
didn't believe anyone was listening that we were so adventurous.
</P>
<P>
   Before and since, I've followed radio with an equal mix of
fascination and disgust. But it's not fair to assign the blame to
local radio _ it stinks all over, and I'm not the only one who
thinks that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody I talk to in every city in America thinks that radio
in their town sucks,'' said Dan Halyburton, marketing manager for
Susquehanna Radio, which owns four Fort Worth-Dallas stations.
``You go to New York City or San Francisco, and they think they've
got the worst radio anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   If people everywhere think radio is lame, why doesn't someone do
something to fix it? Radio-industry suits blame a raft of factors.
Car-radio presets and scan buttons come in high on the list, as do
the quarterly Arbitron ratings, which the stations use to set
advertising rates. Record-label pressure to play certain songs
comes up, as does FCC deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to sympathize. Since the passage of the
Telecommunications Act of 1996, which allowed corporations to own
eight stations in a single market and hundreds nationwide, the
radio dial has turned into a Monopoly board. Companies such as
Irving, Texas-based Chancellor Media Corp. _ which owns six
Metroplex radio stations and nearly 465 nationwide _ have spent
millions and even billions on mergers and package buys. No wonder
they're playing it safe, with this much money being thrown around.
</P>
<P>
   And no wonder they're playing it safe, with so much competition.
In the dial-busting Metroplex market, KHKS/106.1 FM (a k a KISS)
ruled the third-quarter Arbitrons with a 7.7 share _ less than 8
percent of the potential audience. Thomas Mocarsky, vice president
of communication for Arbitron, says that even a 2-share station can
make money.
</P>
<P>
   With everyone after such tiny pieces of the pie, stations are
taking the tack that familiarity breeds attraction. Abby Goldstein,
assistant program director for KKZN/93.3 FM (the Zone), explains
the reasoning this way: Most people listen to the radio in their
cars, during their commutes to and from work _ an average of three
to six songs (and that's if the DJs are unusually reticent).
Therefore, those songs had better be ones that keep people from
hitting the scan button. Which is why you hear the same songs over
and over.
</P>
<P>
   The people I know who are disenchanted with radio see it
differently; it's precisely because they hear the same songs over
and over that they're playing radio roulette, or that they've given
up altogether and turned to their car CD players. Their main
complaint is that they're not exposed to enough variety or novelty.
In other words, they're bored.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
