<HEADLINE>
EASTERN THIRD OF U.S. CAN CATCH THE SHUTTLE'S GLOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOE RAO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Space fans who have always yearned to see a rocket launching but
could never venture to Cape Canaveral will get a great chance, of
sorts, early Thursday morning, when the space shuttle Endeavour is
scheduled to blast off with the second component of the space
station.
</P>
<P>
   Because of unusual circumstances _ the tilt of Endeavour's
orbit, the direction of the launching and a rare nighttime takeoff
_ observers in the eastern third of the United States will be able
to see the shuttle's glow as it bores up into a 245-mile-high
orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Around New York, it should be visible about seven minutes after
the launching, set for 3:59 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, shuttles are launched into orbits inclined at 28.5
degrees to the Equator, or straight to the east from Cape
Canaveral. But the International Space Station is to have an orbit
inclined at 51.6 degrees so that it can be reached from the Russian
launching pads in Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
   The first piece of the space station, a module called Zarya, was
launched from there on Nov. 20. To connect with the nascent
station, Endeavour, with a six-member crew aboard for an 11-day
flight, will be launched to the northeast, adjacent to the Eastern
Seaboard of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Given good weather, people within a radius of 475 miles of the
Kennedy Space Center will be able to see the opening 128 seconds of
the mission. Then, the shuttle will be visible because of its two
solid booster rockets, whose brilliant orange-yellow plumes shine
roughly half as bright as the sun. For Florida communities near the
launch site, the night will briefly be turned into day as Endeavour
rises into space.
</P>
<P>
   According to the flight plan, the solid rocket boosters will
shut down and be discarded two minutes into the flight, but the
shuttle should continue to be visible, though not as bright, by
virtue of the light from the three main engines on the orbiter
itself.
</P>
<P>
   The main engines will fire for about 8.5 minutes after liftoff,
and will be cut off when the shuttle reaches an altitude of about
70 miles, roughly 200 miles east of Atlantic City. Then, racing at
about 17,000 miles an hour, the shuttle should be visible within a
900-mile radius as the main engines are shut down.
</P>
<P>
   In the New York area, observers should concentrate on the
southeast horizon beginning about seven minutes after the shuttle
lifts off from Florida. It should become visible as a bright,
pulsating yellow-orange star that will appear to race rapidly
toward the east. The shuttle's altitude will be rather low, only
about 10 to 15 degrees above the horizon at maximum.
</P>
<P>
   Shuttle launchings have been visible from the New York region
before. On Feb. 28, 1990, the shuttle Atlantis was visible along
much of the Atlantic Seaboard soon after it lifted off with a spy
satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Covault, an editor at Aviation Week and Space Technology,
saw the vehicle from Washington and described it as ``a bright,
V-shaped rocket plume moving northward at high velocity.'' At this
point, about 8 minutes into the flight, Atlantis was 60 miles high
and moving at a velocity of Mach 25, or 25 times the speed of
sound.
</P>
<P>
   When the main engine cut off, the plume disappeared, but the
thruster firings to move the orbiter away from the large external
fuel tank were visible, Covault said.
</P>
<P>
   Total darkness is not always necessary to see the shuttle. The
Discovery was launched in bright twilight on Sept. 12, 1991. Then,
people as far north as New York reported seeing both the glow of
the main engines and sunlight reflected off the shuttle itself.
</P>
<P>
   In the magazine Sky &AMP; Telescope, John Bortle, a contributing
editor, described seeing the shuttle from his home in Dutchess
County, N.Y. ``The shuttle showed the most amazing structure,'' he
wrote, ``looking like a bright star with multiple gas jets trailing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking to Thursday's launching, a NASA spokesman, Bruce
Buckingham, said: ``If you see it, it will look like a large star
moving fast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
