<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-AND-FAMIIES-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW COMPUTERS CONNECT FAMILIES
</HEADLINE>
  By BRONWYN FRYER 
 c.1998 Child magazine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When 6-year-old Derek Fearon, who lives in a New York City
suburb, lost his first tooth, he longed to show his stubby white
prize to his grandmother, ``Bubbe.'' It hardly mattered that she
lived in Boca Raton, Fla. His mother simply turned on the computer
and clicked on an icon. In seconds, Derek could see and hear his
grandma as if she were in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed it to me and said, 'Look, Bubbe!''' recalls Derek's
grandmother, Judith Levy. 'What's better than seeing the face of my
grandchild?'''
</P>
<P>
   Barely a century ago, the telephone began to alter forever the
way human beings communicate. Today, the Internet is retracing the
telephone's path, not only changing the way we go about our
business but also transforming the way we keep in touch with our
loved ones. Electronic mail, videophones and family web pages are
allowing us to maintain close contact at a minimal cost, regardless
of distance.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Videophones: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Levy's thrice-weekly conversations with grandson Derek are
hardly the stuff of science fiction. They come courtesy of
videophone technology _ in this case, Intel's Create &AMP; Share Camera
Pack. The camera pack, which ranges in price from $149 to $300
(each party must have one), provides everything a computer-equipped
family needs for those virtual family get-togethers. Kodak's DVC
323 ($169) is another good choice.
</P>
<P>
   For Marcy Fearon, mother of Derek and 3-year-old Dylan, the
videophone has already transformed the family. ``Grandmother is no
longer someone the children hear about once in a while,'' she says.
``It's like she's actually in the house. It's a real blessing for
the children, who don't get to be with their grandparents very
often.''
</P>
<P>
   Videophone technology typically consists of a camera that mounts
on a computer monitor, a video capture card that is inserted in a
slot inside the computer, and software that places calls and
transmits video images over a regular telephone fine.
</P>
<P>
   On the downside, the quality of the sound and picture can be
iffy. Also, the person on the other end has to be compatibly
equipped, and the telephone line must be working well. Some
technical novices find the installation and setup daunting. (Levy
had a technician install hers.) And the technical requirements are
generally too stiff for anything less than a fully equipped
multimedia computer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Family websites: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   When Steve and Leslie C. brought their new baby boy to their San
Francisco home, Steve's coworkers gave him a gift that keeps on
giving: a family website. ``I got the baby shower, and Steve got
the site,'' Leslie says proudly.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Steve and Leslie's site boasts regularly updated pictures
of their son, Sam, who now 1 1/2. As the child has grown from
infancy to toddlerhood, Leslie's brother in Massachusetts and
sister in Southern California have been able to see how he's
filling out and to share milestones _ like Sam's finally surpassing
the size of the family cat!
</P>
<P>
   It's not hard to set up a website. With software like IBM's
deluxe version of the 1999 World Book Multimedia Encyclopedia
($70), families can employ easy-to-use templates to create their
own individual, group, or newsletter-style pages. The software also
helps families research information from the World Book to include
on their sites, like facts about the breed of the family dog, and
create links to other, related sites.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Scanners: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   To get your snapshots up on a site, the best way to go would be
to use a desktop scanner; these are now priced at $200 or less and
produce crisp color reproductions of ordinary photos. Just plug the
scanner into your computer and load the companion software. Place a
photo on the scanner, close the lid, click a button on your
computer screen, and voila: Your photo is digitized, suitable for
electronic use.
</P>
<P>
   Good scanners include the HP ScanJet 5100C ($299) and the AGFA
SnapScan EZ ($129). Once you have your digital pictures, you can
post them to your site.
</P>
<P>
   Many Internet service providers offer free website service.
America Online, for one, gives its members free space for a site
and a simple, easy-to-use tool with which to build it. The effort
is worth it. Compared with the cost of developing, copying and
mailing photos, posting to a site is a real bargain.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; E-mail: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Most families with home computers have discovered that
electronic mail is an inexpensive alternative to the telephone.
Kelly and Kevin Jones of West Jordan, Utah, have discovered that
it's also a great way to send quick pictures of their three small
children _ Bryson, 3, Addisen, 2, and Corbin, 7 months _ without
having to pay for film, processing and postage.
</P>
<P>
   The Joneses, who use a free e-mail service called theglobe.com,
regularly send text messages to the children's great-grandmother in
Springfield, Ore., and to their maternal grandparents in Portland.
``Today I sent my in-laws a message telling them how Bryson was
putting Addisen to bed,'' says their father. When he's finished
with his own message, he places Bryson on his lap and allows the
little boy to add a few lines of keyboard gobbledygook.
</P>
<P>
   When the text message is complete, Jones can attach a picture to
it. For this purpose he uses a tool from Play Inc. called Snappy
Video Snapshot, a $99 video grabber that plugs into the computer's
printer port. Jones plugs the family's video camera into a jack on
the computer; then he and his wife pose with the kids in front of
the camera. When they see an image they like, ``we just click the
mouse and the frame gets saved on the computer,'' he explains. Then
he selects the ``attach file'' option in his e-mail software,
clicks on the ``send'' button, and the photo arrives on
grandmother's desktop in minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Jones notes that e-mail is an ideal communication tool for
young, budget-conscious families like his. ``It's a quick, easy,
inexpensive way to keep up with our family,'' he says. ``And that's
really been wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Bronwyn Fryer is a wife and mother who lives in Santa Cruz,
Calif.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS at (800) 972-3550 or fax
her at (212) 499-3382.
</P>
</TEXT>
