<HEADLINE>
FOREVER MISS PICKLES
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color photo of the author and her potbellied pig, Presten.
Also a sidebar with address of L'il Orphan Hammies. 
 By LISA TRYTKO 
 c.1998 WE magazine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   My name is Lisa Trytko, and I am 18 years old and live in Mount
Morris, Mich. I was born with cerebral palsy and epilepsy. Not long
after potbellied pigs were introduced into the United States, I
knew that this was the pet for me. My father, however, was not so
easily convinced, and as time passed I gave up all hope of ever
receiving my wish.
</P>
<P>
   Then while I was away at summer camp, I received a letter from
my mother that said she was caring for the cutest baby girl. I
thought it strange my mother would take up baby-sitting. As I read
further, she elaborated: She was, in fact, caring for a 6-month-old
potbellied piglet. Best of all, she said it was my piglet. I was
overjoyed!
</P>
<P>
   On the morning after I arrived home, I had the privilege of the
very first visit with Miss Pickles, named by my mother, who had
noticed that her body formed the shape of a marinated cucumber.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Pickles grew fond of me and I of her, and we became the
best of friends. One of her favorite pastimes, naturally, was
eating, during which her unique personality came into play. When
she got her dinner, she made such a careful effort not to make a
mess, and she especially loved when I dropped spare watermelons and
cucumbers into her pen.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, her all-time favorite treat was mine as well. I
visited the pen of Miss Pickles as often as I could, bringing along
an enormous bag of marshmallows. As I offered them to her, she
would take them tenderly from my hands. Then, she gently licked off
the little sticky bits remaining on my fingers.
</P>
<P>
   She also had one odd trait: She despised getting her trotters
muddy. Whenever she did, her face twisted into an expression of
disgust. Then she carefully picked up a foot as she attempted to
clean it. Every time my mother cleaned her pen, she ran around it
oinking, as if to say, ``You missed this spot. And that one!''
</P>
<P>
   At about this time, I was in junior high school and my grades
were slipping because of kids who saw nothing in me but my
disability. They would tease me relentlessly and I would become
extremely stressed, which, in turn, caused me to go into seizures.
My constant comfort throughout the seventh and eighth grades was
Miss Pickles. I would confess my crisis of the day while she and I
munched on marshmallows. As I poured my heart out, her tall swished
and she oinked, as if attempting to give me counsel.
</P>
<P>
   I thought my guiding light would be with me all my life, but
life had other things in store.
</P>
<P>
   One day my mother had the vet come out for Miss Pickles' first
health examination and shots. The vet had to sedate her in order to
complete the examination, then gave her a clean bill of health. The
forecast was cold for the night, so the vet recommended we bring
her inside until the anesthetic wore off and then return her to her
pen.
</P>
<P>
   Just as I was opening my eyes the next morning, I heard mumbling
voices, then a cry, and, slowly, my mother entered my room to tell
me Miss Pickles had died in the night. As I heard those words, the
walls of security and happiness that had surrounded me shattered.
Grief entered my world.
</P>
<P>
   Mom had bookmarked a website where owners of potbellied pigs
from around the world share stories about their pets. She posted my
story, and then e-mails of condolence poured in.
</P>
<P>
   Among all the generous offers of new pigs was one from Sue
Parkinson of L'il Orphan Hammies, a nonprofit, potbellied pig
sanctuary in Solvang, Calif., where her lifework is caring for
abandoned and disabled potbellied pigs. She said her own beloved
PJ, short for Pete junior, had died recently, and I could have not
one but two piglets!
</P>
<P>
   Once again, after many months of being pigless, I arrived home
from camp, this time to two special bundles, Presten and Westen.
Presten, on hearing the word ``circle'' as he's handed a treat, is
a downright showoff, spinning in circles like a tornado. Westen is
endearing but shy. The Boys, as we call them, recently learned to
swim in a kiddy pool in their pen.
</P>
<P>
   Caring for Presten and Westen brings me joy now and enables most
of the void within my heart to be filled. Part of it will never be,
and it is there that my cherished memories of Miss Pickles will
always rest in peace.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR:
</P>
<P>
   L'il Orphan Hammies:
</P>
<P>
   P.O. Box 924
</P>
<P>
   Solvang CA 93464
</P>
<P>
   email: parky &LR; silcom.com
</P>
