<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN AS A SECOND LANGUAGE
</HEADLINE>
  By NORMA BLAIR 
 c.1998 Ann Normansell 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the problems with moving to a foreign country is learning
the language. After nearly 30 years in the U.S. I still find myself
using expressions that produce blank stares from my listeners.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent example of this came when I pronounced myself
``a little peckish,'' and saw the familiar glazed expression
appear. When I appealed to a bystander he was able to provide a
translation, but the experience brought home to me the fact that
the English and the Americans are more divided than united by their
common language.
</P>
<P>
   In self-defense one has to adopt certain terms for use in
everyday life. Thus I wash my windshield, not my windscreen, and
stash stuff in the trunk rather than the boot. I also check my
``skedule'' rather than my ``shed-yule'' if asked to do something,
which may be the reason that I am accused of ``talking American''
when I visit England, even though I am immediately tabbed as a
foreigner over here.
</P>
<P>
   One thing I have yet to understand, though, is why I am
sometimes called ``veddy British.'' Is that really how the English
``very'' is heard? Shortly after we came to Virginia, I was
chatting with the mailman (not the postman!) and happened to
mention that we were from England.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that's where you're from, is it?'' he replied. ``I thought
you were from one of those Northern states.''
</P>
<P>
   In England I had similar problems. While in college I got a
summer job at the seaside with a family who had a 12-year-old boy
and a 6-year-old girl. Being from the north of England, I build
sand castles (short ``a'') rather than cahstles.
</P>
<P>
   One day we were discussing home towns and, when the fact of my
northern origin emerged, the 6-year-old said, ``Oh, is that why you
don't speak English?''
</P>
<P>
   My acclimatization began on the day that we arrived in
Charlottesville, when we were welcomed into a colleague's home and
our children were offered ``peanut butter and jelly.'' Since jelly
is a gelatine dessert in England, and no mention was made of
``sandwich,'' I had a very strange vision of what was being
offered.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterwards I realized that my English might be more
archaic than the local norm. I told one of the children in that
same household not to ``tread'' on something (not a snake!) and got
the soon-to-be-familiar blank stare. Her mother, a Tennessean who
became a good friend, recommended that I use ``step'' or ``walk''
instead.
</P>
<P>
   She was the person who said ``You have to be kidding!'' when I
said ``aluminium'' instead of ``aluminum.'' Yes, there really is an
extra ``i'' in the word in England, and it is one of the few words
I have learned to pronounce differently. Others, like ``tomayto,''
``vite-amin,'' and the Greek letters ``bayta,'' ``thayta,'' etc.
have been more difficult to adopt.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise slurring ``t's'' into ``d's.'' When our daughter went
to nursery school, she brought home tales of a child named
``Doddy,'' which seemed an unusual name for a girl. I knew it as
the nickname of the English comedian Ken Dodd, he of the buck teeth
and electric shock hair, who was popular then. It was not until I
met ``Marty,'' pronounced ``Mardy,'' that I made the connection and
realized that I had been hearing about ``Dottie.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, I was totally confounded when I met another ``Marty''
whose name turned out to be ``Mardie.''
</P>
<P>
   Shopping can also be an interesting experience. When I asked
where I might find a ``Thermos flask'' in K-Mart, I got a very odd
look until the assistant divined that I might be looking for a
``Thermos bottle.'' And I would love to have been there when a
fellow alien asked for batteries for her ``torch'' _ it wasn't even
Olympic season!
</P>
<P>
   I have learned to avoid the obvious pitfalls, like abbreviating
pussycat, but I still goof at times when talking about waking
people up in the mornings. Long before alarm clocks and telephone
wake-up calls, there was a person in the north of England who
walked the streets in the predawn hours, carrying a long pole with
which he tapped on upper storey windows. His official title was
``the Knocker-up.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Norma Blair is a free-lance writer based in Charlottesville,
Va.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS at (800) 972-3550 or fax
her at (212) 499-3382.
</P>
