 FOREVER MISS PICKLES (WITH ART) 
 800 words. Includes color photo of the author and her potbellied
pig, Presten. 
 By LISA TRYTKO 
 c.1998 WE magazine 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   It's an old story _ girl gets pet, girl loses pet, girl gets two
more pets _ but told in this case by a handicapped teenager who
found (via the Internet) an unexpected source of comfort and joy.
Told in her own words, this piece lacks polish, but there's a vein
of feeling here your readers will find and cherish.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged: BC-PIGLETS-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF, priority code r,
category code l) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TIMELESS ADVICE ON AGING &QL; 
 &UR; 1000 words, with Internet address of Cicero website) &QL; 
 &UR; By HERBERT STEIN &QL; 
 &UR; c.1998 Slate &QL; 
 &UR; World rights &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An eminent American economist rereads Cicero for advice on how
to ``invest'' for old age. It just doesn't get any sager than this.
With a cool website for readers who want more Cicero in their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged: BC-AGE-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF, priority code r, category code
l) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW COMPUTERS CONNECT FAMILIES &QL; 
 &UR; 1000 words &QL; 
 &UR; By BRONWYN FRYER &QL; 
 &UR; c.1998 Child magazine &QL; 
 &UR; World rights &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is retracing the telephone's path, transforming the
way we keep in touch with our loved ones. Here is practical advice
on using electronic mail, videophones and family web pages to
maintain close contact at a minimal cost.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged: BC-COMPUTERS-AND-FAMIIES-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF, priority code
r, category code l) &QL;
