<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BAPTISTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESSAY ON CLINTON PROMPTS ANGRY RESPONSE FROM BAPTISTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do President Clinton's sexual sins have a connection with his
Baptist upbringing? Newsweek religion correspondent Kenneth L.
Woodward posed that question Nov. 2 in an essay, ``Sex, Sin and
Salvation,'' that brought a flood of responses.
</P>
<P>
   ``To understand Clinton the president, you have to meet Bill the
Baptist, a believer whose faith leaves plenty of license,'' a
subheadline declared.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward theorizes that the Baptist doctrine of ``soul
competency'' that Clinton was taught as an adolescent _ combined
with the belief ``once saved, always saved'' _ could be interpreted
as almost a libertarian doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth of the matter is that having a doctrine like soul
competency _ saying I can interpret the Bible for myself _ combined
with the radical individualism of the Baptist faith can be
translated into a kind of immunity'' from sinful behavior, Woodward
said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward's essay was fiercely criticized by many Baptists,
including Toby Druin, editor of the Baptist Standard, the Texas
Baptist news journal.
</P>
<P>
   Druin especially objected to Woodward's statement that moderate
Southern Baptists view Clinton as ``both a flawed follower of
Christ and an exemplary Baptist president.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know of no Baptist, moderate or otherwise, who would say he
has been an `exemplary' Baptist president,'' Druin wrote in a Nov.
11 editorial. ``Most I know are embarrassed to share the name
`Baptist' with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Baptists are known for bans on alcohol, gambling and other
worldly activities. Some still see dancing as a sin. A Baptist
program, ``True Love Waits,'' asks young people to sign pledges
promising they won't have sex before marriage.
</P>
<P>
   But Woodward says Baptist doctrines of freedom of conscience
leave room for immature Christians to think they are free to
indulge in all kinds of behavior, including sexual experimentation.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward said in an interview that many who become Christians
before reaching puberty _ including Baptists, Catholics, Lutherans
and members of other faiths _ have trouble reconciling what they
are taught in church with the sexual urges they have later.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made a profession of faith as a 7-year-old in a Hot
Springs Baptist church. He was taught that individuals have the
final say in how they interpret the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus seemed to be telling imaginative Baptist teen-agers that
they could work out their own personal rules, permitting some forms
of sexual experimentation without feeling guilty,'' Woodward wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I looked at specifically was how these doctrines related
to Bill Clinton growing up as an adolescent Baptist,'' Woodward
said. ``When Clinton said `I didn't go all the way,' I learned that
many Baptists, as adolescents, went through similar kinds of
experiences. But the difference is, Clinton gave those same kinds
of explanations when he got caught as an adult.''
</P>
<P>
   Newsweek received more that 200 E-mail responses to the ``Bill
the Baptist'' essay, much more than the responses to the cover
story. Most were critical, Woodward admitted.
</P>
<P>
   But one Philadelphia woman, the daughter of a Baptist minister
who said she was of the same generation as Clinton, wrote that
Woodward's essay made sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found your article right on and can wholeheartedly confirm
your explanation behind our president's rationalizing of his `lies'
regarding his sexual activity of late,'' Bonnie Bergey said in a
letter published Nov. 23. ``From the get-go, many honest Baptists,
or former Baptists, saw in Bill's `fudging' the tactics employed in
our Baptist adolescence. That, plus the inability to lose one's
salvation, makes temptation more tempting.''
</P>
<P>
   A letter from a Southern Baptist executive, Robert E. Reccord,
complained to Newsweek of Woodward's ``cavalier'' portrayal of
Baptist doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Woodward suggests that Baptist doctrine somehow legitimizes
extramarital sexual conduct by providing `considerable room for
maneuvering' to full-blooded youth like the adolescent Clinton,''
wrote Reccord, president of the Southern Baptist North American
Mission Board.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward's provocative article won't convince many Southern
Baptists that their doctrine about soul freedom is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Caldwell Giles of Raleigh, N.C., reminded Newsweek
editors that former President Jimmy Carter, also a Southern
Baptist, confessed to Playboy magazine that he had lusted after
women, thereby committing the sin of adultery in his heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the version of adultery I remember being taught as a
Baptist teen-ager,'' Giles said. ``Not the
fill-in-the-blank-to-define-your-sin variety that you seem to feel
most Baptists espouse.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
He can be reached at jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) .MDBR/.MDNM/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
