A5131 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX     11-30 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECALLING THE UNKNOWNS OF THE SPACE PROGRAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six men and one woman stood before the world that October day,
decked out in their impressive NASA flight suits, prepared to be
thrust into the heavens with an unwavering confidence in man and
machine that most people are hard pressed to understand.
</P>
<P>
   Most people are also hard pressed, despite the overwhelming
media coverage, to name six of the seven astronauts who were aboard
the space shuttle Discovery last month as it circled the globe on
its 3.6 million-mile mission. Sure, everyone knows John Glenn. Even
youngsters who were born decades after his historic 1962 orbit of
the Earth in Friendship 7 know the name John Glenn. He's a true
American hero, right up there with Abe Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   But were it not for the inclusion of the 77-year-old senator
from Ohio, the activities in southern Florida as Discovery lifted
off on Oct. 29 would have garnered scant attention, and few would
have been so enthralled with daily updates on the crew's progress
before and after its Nov. 7 return to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   This is nothing new for pioneers and innovators _ they are used
to working in anonymity. The nameless, faceless men who risked
their lives as Cold War test pilots in the pursuit of science and
military might for the United States were no exception _ yet they
were exceptional people.
</P>
<P>
   America paid little attention to the activities at Edwards Air
Force Base in Southern California decades ago, when experimental
flights were making possible what would one day be Glenn's first
trip into space. The men toiled in obscurity, their actions known
by few outside their families and the controlled circle of the
military.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1950s, the United States didn't want the rest of the
world to know what was going on in the deserts of California and
New Mexico. As the Cold War simmered in the international
spotlight, engineers and scientists worked in secret to develop the
next generation of flying machines that could deliver lethal cargo
if need be.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of what America would do if forced into a position of
defense was backed up by real weapons. The world is just now
finding out that much of the Soviet threat during those years was
little more than theatrics and facades.
</P>
<P>
   Away from the scrutiny of America's media, young test pilots
daily stepped into massive pieces of machinery, great hunks of
steel veined with miles of complicated wiring that intricately
coursed through reinforcement joints and instrument panels. These
military men (at that time, all test pilots were male) sat in
cockpits and revved up engines that aerospace manufacturers hoped
would carry them skyward.
</P>
<P>
   When one of these flights failed _ as did the one that in 1958
claimed the life of my father, Boyd Lee Grubaugh _ there were no
public memorials, no scholarship funds for the children left
behind, no national outcries of sorrow. Unlike the televised
disaster that was Challenger, the ill-fated shuttle with an
adventurous schoolteacher named Christa McAuliffe on board, many
men died without a nation's recognition of their important work.
Their widows drew what strength they could from knowing that their
pilot husbands were doing what they loved to do: pushing the
envelope, testing the unknown, ``flying.''
</P>
<P>
   The world is now poised for the next great experiment in space:
the International Space Station. The first piece of the flying
laboratory was launched into the ether this month by the Russians.
It will take scores of such launches to complete the station's
assembly. Another countdown began this week.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds so matter-of-fact, even routine. But in a survey
released in April, NASA concluded that ``it clearly needs to be
recognized and understood that there is a high likelihood that one
or more failures, including catastrophic failures, will occur over
the span of 93 launches.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the technology is more sophisticated, the computers and
materials used to manufacture the parts more exact. But it is still
flesh and blood that sits behind the controls; those are men and
women strapped inside these behemoths made of plastics and
composites, electronics and robotics.
</P>
<P>
   Take a minute to at least remember their names.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Her e-mail address is
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com and her phone number is (817)
390-7599. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
