<SLUG> BC-GATES-BOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MICROSOFT EMPEROR HAS NEW CLOTHES, IN COMEDIAN'S BOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY BINGHAM 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is Bill Gates as you've never seen him.
</P>
<P>
   Uncovered!
</P>
<P>
   Uncensored!
</P>
<P>
   Dressed as Janet Reno!
</P>
<P>
   That's right, the richest man in America has a thing for the
attorney general's clothes. Turns out the Microsoft billionaire
likes to wear pantyhose after a long day fighting the Justice
Department over antitrust charges.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's how comedian Chris Alpine sees it. Alpine and
illustrator Peter Georgeson have brought us Bill just the way we
want him: as a paper doll.
</P>
<P>
   Their new book, ``Bill Gates 99,'' takes on every aspect of
Gates and his computer software empire. Nothing is sacred, from
computer nerds to pocket protectors.
</P>
<P>
   Tired of Bill in Reno's purple suit and black flats? Strip him
down to his boxers and socks and go from there.
</P>
<P>
   There's Bill the Big Man on Campus, and Bill the prison warden;
Bill the computer dork in plaid pants, or Bill as Hugh Hefner in a
bathrobe and fuzzy slippers. The joke: He's carrying a dogeared
copy of ``Pentiumhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Bill the ``Internet Explorer'' in safari clothes,
and Bill dressed as Charlton Heston playing God in socks and
Birkenstocks, holding 10 Commandments (''Thou Shalt Make Money''
tops the list.)
</P>
<P>
   Alpine and Georgeson make fun of Gates' haircut, his glasses,
his money, and they even throw in a fictional biography with the
details we really want to know. Bill's turn-ons: pulling
all-nighters, Pentium chips. His turnoffs: power surges, Macs. And
his nickname? What else but Bill-ionaire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Gates 99'' costs $9.99.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 1640EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
