 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Tuesday, Dec. 1. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   QUEBEC-ELECT (Quebec) _ Quebec votes in a legislative election
expected to determine the future of separatism in the province.
Polls close 8 p.m. Eastern time. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ARAFAT (Washington) _ The United States Monday pledged
an additional $400 million in aid to the Palestinians over the next
five years, nearly doubling its annual economic assistance to the
Palestinians in hopes of bolstering the peace process with Israel.
By Philip Shenon. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-AID (Undated) _ The Clinton administration initially
opposed it, and the Colombian government was taken by surprise. But
a recent congressional initiative, spurred by a growing link
between conservative Republicans and the Colombian National Police,
has more than doubled anti-drug money to Colombia, and made the
country a top recipient of American foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-CENSUS (Washington) _ Members of the Supreme Court
expressed considerable doubt Monday about whether they should
resolve the legal and constitutional issues surrounding the Clinton
administration's plan to use statistical sampling to make the 2000
Census more accurate. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ The House Judiciary Committee will vote
on Tuesday to subpoena two new witnesses and additional documents,
even as the White House made clear that President Clinton would not
appear to defend himself, committee aides said Monday. The
committee was expected to identify the documents and witnesses
later this afternoon. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-DEMS _ The White House said Monday that President
Clinton will decline the Judiciary Committee's invitation to appear
before them to answer questions and defend his actions. The
president is under no obligation to help those who are trying to do
him in, said Joe Lockhart, the White House press secretary. By John
M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   EMERGENCY-CARE (Washington) _ The Clinton administration told
hospitals Monday that they must provide emergency medical care to
all patients who need it and may not delay services while they seek
approval from a health maintenance organization or other insurer.
By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MARINES (Washington) _ On Tuesday, Republicans leading
the House's impeachment inquiry plan to call two retired officers
to testify about the corrosive effect on military discipline of
having a commander-in-chief who has admitted misleading the nation.
But in an interview, Gen. Charles C. Krulak, commandant of the
Marine Corps, suggested that the scandal's impact on the armed
forces has been far less than Clinton's critics say. By Steven Lee
Myers.
</P>
<P>
   RENO-ICKES (Washington) _ After three months of deliberations,
Attorney General Janet Reno on Monday put off a decision on whether
to ask an independent counsel to investigate the statements of
Harold Ickes, a former top presidential aide, about his efforts on
behalf of the teamsters union. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL-GENERAL &LR;  (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO-MAYOR (San Francisco) _ In a recent poll, voters
said Mayor Willie L. Brown Jr.'s greatest asset was charisma. But
after three years, the voters here seem tired of Brown, a Democrat
and one of two or three mayors in the country with widespread name
recognition. By Evelyn Nieves. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BANKERS-TRUST-DEUTSCHE (Frankfurt, Germany) _ In the most
ambitious attempt yet by a European bank to compete on Wall Street,
Deutsche Bank AG announced Monday its plan for a $10.1-billion
takeover of Bankers Trust. The bank announced plans to eliminate
5,500 jobs, mostly in New York and London. By Edmund L. Andrews.
With graphic.
</P>
