<HEADER>
A5139 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTMAS-CDS-2000(3T     11-30 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMAS-CDS-2000(3TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YULETIDE CDS THAT MAKE NOT-SO-SQUARE STOCKING STUFFERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is it just us, or are there more Christmas CDs out this year
than ever before? The only thing missing is ``A Metallica Christmas
_ Thrashin' the Favorites,'' but there's a good chance that's
coming in the mail today. Until then, here's a look at the top
holiday CD offerings:
</P>
<P>
   (Reviews are on a five-star scale).
</P>
<P>
   POP
</P>
<P>
   CELINE DION, ``These Are Special Times,'' 550 Music: This is the
big one, the Christmas offering by the woman who ruled pop music in
1998. And it's ... well, pretty good, in no small part because the
sugary and sometimes schmaltzy Big Pop that Dion traffics in is far
more acceptable during the ultrasentimental holiday season. This
gauzy, string-laden 16-song offering is a nicely eclectic mix of
standards such as ``O Holy Night'' and a few originals, one of
which, ``Don't Save It All for Christmas Day,'' scores points for
reminding us that we shouldn't just be nice to our loved ones
between Thanksgiving and Christmas morning. Dion tries a bit too
hard to be all things to all listeners _ ``Ave Maria'' and a
warmed-over John Lennon's ``Happy Xmas (War Is Over)'' on the same
CD? _ but she gets away with it more often than not.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SHAWN COLVIN, ``Holiday Songs and Lullabies,'' Columbia: Colvin
follows ``A Few Small Repairs,'' her darkest and best album, with
her sweetest and lightest CD. Unsurprisingly, it's a quiet affair,
although the best numbers are the ones in which Colvin's band gets
a bit of a ``Wichita Skyline'' groove going. Some of the Christmas
songs, especially ``Silent Night,'' challenge Colvin's waifish
range, but she acquits herself well on ``In the Bleak Mid-Winter''
and ``All Through the Night.'' The lullabies don't have much
staying power for anyone older than 18 months, but Colvin has
better sleepy-song taste than Linda Ronstadt, who tried to turn
Queen's soccer-game chant ``We Will Rock You'' into a bedtime song.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Robert Philpot
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BABYFACE, ``Christmas With Babyface,'' Epic Records: Christmas
with the megapopular performer and producer sounds as though it
would be pleasant and a bit quiet. Mellow grooves and saxophones
are the cornerstones of this 10-track collection, nine of which are
standards such as ``Rudolph the Red Nosed Reindeer.'' It's all
``nice,'' yeah, but hardly ever are his arrangements or vocal
interpretations of these songs memorable. The last track, his own
``You Were There,'' has little, if anything, to do with Christmas.
Sounds like he just had to get one of his own songs on there.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VARIOUS ARTISTS, ``Celebrate the Season: The 1998 T.J. Martell
Foundation Christmas Album,'' PolyMedia: The T.J. Martell
Foundation supports leukemia, cancer and AIDS research, and this
all-star CD is a worthy purchase if for no other reason than that.
A complete hodgepodge, it includes everything from Elton John's
``Step Into Christmas'' to Bing Crosby's ``White Christmas'' to the
all-time classic ``You're a Mean One, Mr. Grinch'' from the ``How
the Grinch Stole Christmas'' soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHUCK LEAVELL, ``What's in That Bag?,'' Capricorn Records:
Leavell is a Georgia keyboardist who has recorded and/or toured
with the Allman Brothers (in the '70s), Eric Clapton (in the '80s)
and the Rolling Stones (every tour since 1982). His first Christmas
CD is a down-home blast of soul and boogie-woogie piano licks.
Aside from Leavell's voice not being as strong as his playing, it's
one of the season's best. Recorded with esteemed session players
such as Roger Hawkins, ``Bag'' is a solid, Southern-flavored
collection of, mainly, seasonal favorites like Charles Brown's
``Merry Christmas Baby.'' Leavell's solo piano interpretations of
``God Rest Ye Merry Gentlemen'' and ``O Holy Night'' are lovely,
and his duet with Stones vocalist Lisa Fischer on ``Please Come
Home for Christmas'' is as cool as it gets.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CYNDI LAUPER, ``Merry Christmas ... Have a Nice Life!'' Sony:
Big fun, this first yuletide offering from Lauper. Most of the
songs are originals, and most of those are winners: ``Home on
Christmas Day'' is both sad and hopeful, ``Minnie and Santa'' is
the story of a waitress planning to seduce the fat man, and
``Christmas Conga'' is the perfect dance song for that inebriated
office/block/whatever party you know you'll go to. Unlike many
people who do Christmas CDs, Lauper sounds like she really loves
the season, the kind of old-fashioned gal who would put up a big,
real tree, invite everyone in the neighborhood, and lead the
caroling until way past midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   MORE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   'N SYNC, ``Home for Christmas,'' RCA: Millions of teen-age girls
would love to wake up Christmas morning and find this under their
tree _ well, forget the CD, they want 'N Sync under their tree. The
quintet's Christmas disc is, of course, nothing more than
disposable pop fluff, another example of a record company
pressuring a trendy act to spit out as much stuff as possible
before fans grow up and wake up. All the songs are typical 'N Sync:
syrupy, harmony-driven ballads that make schoolyard promises _
``I'll always love you,'' ``You're the only one for me'' _ that
turn 13-year-old girls into goo-goo dolls. It'll sell anyway, and
Justin, Chris, JC, Lance and Joey will become that much richer. And
tomorrow, it'll all be gone.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 star
</P>
<P>
   _ Malcolm Mayhew
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VARIOUS ARTISTS, JERMAINE DUPRI PRESENTS 12 SOULFUL NIGHTS OF
CHRISTMAS, Sony: Unlike other Christmas compilations, this one
isn't filled with someone else's remix or rehash of ``Jingle
Bells.'' Compiled and produced by Jermaine Dupri (a young
R&AMP;B/hip-hop producer whose credits include true talents like Brian
McKnight and true embarrassments like Kris Kross), ``Soulful
Nights'' is made up of original material from R&AMP;B stalwarts such as
McKnight, K-Ci and JoJo, Gerald Levert and Chaka Khan. The sultry
songs follow a similar making-out-by-the-fireplace path, and it
does get old after awhile. At least there's honesty and originality
here, though, not just some crooner belching out more Christmas
carols for more Christmas cash.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Malcolm Mayhew
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SQUIRREL NUT ZIPPERS, ``Christmas Caravan,'' Mammoth Records:
Elmo and Patsy and Robert Earl Keen have had their silly holiday
songs, but leave it to the Zippers to offer an entire Christmas
album that's fun. There's the occasional spurt of looniness, such
as ``Indian Giver,'' but this effort is mainly kept alive through
the band's mix of calypso, Delta blues and ragtime. Katherine
Whalen does her lovely Billie Holiday warble on ``Winter Weather,''
the traditional ``Sleigh Ride'' gets a New Orleans-style makeover,
while ``Hanging Up My Stockings'' changes moods many times, going
from big band to an ominous dirge to vinyl-cracking crooning. A
definite stocking-stuffer.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Mark Lowry
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   VINCE GILL, ``Breath of Heaven,'' MCA Nashville: Beware, the
first couple of cuts are strictly Vince Gill-as-Bob Goulet,
complete with stilted orchestral arrangements and ``ooo-ahhh''
background vocals, but the album does warm up as it goes along. ``A
Cradle in Bethlehem'' and ``Breath of Heaven'' are forthright and
beautiful, and here's a listening tip: Don't have any holiday
glassware nearby when ``O Holy Night'' comes on.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Shirley Jinkins
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MARTINA McBRIDE, ``White Christmas,'' RCA Records: Since all the
songs on McBride's CD are traditional carols, some of the cuts here
are the same overdone choices as on Gill's offering (example: ``Let
It Snow, Let It Snow, Let It Snow.'' But McBride's selections have
richer orchestral arrangements and background vocals. And there's
her own joyful voice. The deep strings and her bell-like lead on
``Away in a Manger'' is warm as a comforting fire.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Shirley Jinkins
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TAMMY WYNETTE, ``Christmas With Tammy Wynette,'' Sony/Nashville:
The late queen of country music released this holiday classic album
in 1970, and it hasn't been commercially available since the
mid-1980s. Fans will rejoice again at the Tammy touch on her
ethereal ``Silent Night'' and steel-guitar paced ``O Little Town of
Bethlehem.'' ``White Christmas'' gets that Wynette catch in the
voice, and a guitar chord intro reminiscent of ``Stand by Your
Man.'' But the most memorable song is ``(Merry Christmas) We Must
Be Having One,'' an untypical country song of holiday love gone
right.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Shirley Jinkins
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CONTEMPORARY CHRISTIAN
</P>
<P>
   MICHAEL W. SMITH, ``Christmastime,'' Reunion Records: It would
have been so easy to turn out a generic traditional/spiritual
Christmas album, but Michael W. Smith has managed to make a lush
production with new arrangements of original and traditional
material. His New Age piano instrumental on ``Hope of Israel'' is
just plain gorgeous. It's followed up with a beautiful vocal
performance by the American Boychoir, which starts the medley
``Sing We Now of Christmas''/''O Com O Com Emmanuel''/''Emmanuel.''
The album's first song, ``The Happiest Christmas,'' is the only bit
of cheap sentimentality, but hey, what do you expect from Christmas
music?
</P>
<P>
   No rating
</P>
<P>
   _ Mark Lowry
</P>
<P>
   MORE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICAL
</P>
<P>
   LEONARD BERNSTEIN, conductor; New York Philharmonic; Westminster
Choir. Handel's ``Messiah'' Sony Bernstein Century Collection: For
some, the newly re-mastered version of Leonard Bernstein's
performance of Handel's ``Messiah'' with the New York Philharmonic,
from a studio recording of 1956, will be a fascinating document of
one musical genius interpreting another. For others, it will be a
bizarre distortion of a masterpiece. Bernstein liberally
re-arranged the movements, sometimes with breathtaking effect. For
better or worse, he makes the Overture sound like Mahler _ and no
other conductor who has ever lived could have made the counterpoint
so lively and energetic. And there are definite drawbacks besides
Bernstein's fast-and-loose approach to the score: the standards for
symphonic choirs were not as high in the 1950s as they are today
and the soloists are a mixed lot. While this is a must-buy item for
connoisseurs of Bernstein or ``Messiah,'' typical buyers looking
for one good ``Messiah'' should go to the star-studded, mainstream
version with the Toronto Symphony and conductor Andrew Davis on
EMI.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Wayne Lee Gay
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLACIDO DOMINGO, tenor; other vocalists; Vienna Symphony; Steven
Mercurio, conductor. ``A Gala Christmas in Vienna,'' Sony
Classical: While fans of Bernstein and Handel will want to add the
Bernstein version of ``Messiah'' to their collection, fans of tenor
Placido Domingo should avoid this year's ``A Gala Christmas in
Vienna'' disc, a cheesy sellout featuring Domingo in collaboration
with Broadway-pop-classical soprano Sarah Brightman, Belgian
pop-classical singer Helmut Lotti and Italian pop singer Riccardo
Cocciante. Out-of-tune singing, generally bad recorded sound and a
program that vacillates between Vegas and Westminster Abbey makes
for an unpleasant listening experience, epitomizing crass holiday
commercialism.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 star
</P>
<P>
   _ Wayne Lee Gay
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MORMON TABERNACLE CHOIR; Canadian Brass. ``A Christmas Gloria,''
BWE Classics: A much more pleasant combination of traditional
Christmas music and serious works comes from two of America's
premier ensembles; John Rutter and J.S. Bach mix comfortably with
``Silent Night,'' other old favorites and, of course, a brass
medley. Here's a chance to get in the Christmas spirit without
wallowing.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Wayne Lee Gay
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
