<HEADLINE>
SNAKES AND VIPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By C. CLAIBORNE RAY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Do the terms snake, viper and serpent have
scientific differences?(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. Especially large or poisonous snakes are commonly called
serpents, and biblical tradition calls the shape Satan assumed to
tempt Eve a serpent, but technically speaking, all snakes can be
called serpents, from the Latin serpere, meaning to creep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snake'' and ``serpent'' are overall terms for any of the
members of the suborder Serpentes in the order Squamata. They lack
limbs, shoulder girdle and external ear openings and have immovable
eyelids and a braincase that is completely bony in the back. There
are nearly 3,000 species in 414 genera.
</P>
<P>
   Vipers, a subgroup of snakes, are another matter, and the term
is derived from fuzzy medieval science. The scientific name of the
family Viperidae, which includes many poisonous species commonly
called vipers or adders, comes from the Latin vivipara, meaning
bearing live young, on the assumption that they all did so.
</P>
<P>
   In truth some are live bearers, some are egg layers and some are
ovoviviparous, meaning that they carry eggs that hatch just before
they give birth. The genus vipera, six species of Eurasian adders
or true vipers, are all ovoviviparous.
</P>
<P>
   The puff adder and pit vipers are usually referred to as vipers.
Pit vipers include the familiar rattlesnakes, cottonmouths and
copperheads, and are so called because they have two characteristic
pits right between the snout and the mouth, which pick up infrared
heat signals to identify approaching creatures.
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions by postal mail to
Questions, Science Times, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd Street,
New York, N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to: Question(AT)nytimes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
