<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-CENSUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT HEARS ARGUMENTS CONCERNING STATISTICAL ESTIMATES TO
COMPLEMENT CENSUS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday heard arguments
concerning the legality of President Clinton's plan to use
statistical estimates to complement the 2000 Census and indicated
strongly that opponents of the proposal lack legal standing to
mount a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   But the justices, in a 90-minute oral-argument session, appeared
just as critical of the president's plan, noting that it would be a
departure from the way the Census has traditionally been taken.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-controlled House of Representatives and 16
private individuals are suing the Clinton administration, seeking a
court order that the president abandon his proposal to use
statistics in addition to the traditional head count of the U.S.
population. Clinton says the estimate is necessary to get a more
accurate number, but House Republicans and the individuals counter
that federal law and the U.S. Constitution permit only a head count
for the Census.
</P>
<P>
   The Census, which the government takes every 10 years, tabulates
not only the U.S. population but determines how the 435 House seats
will be apportioned among the 50 states. The Clinton
administration, saying the last Census in 1990 failed to count 8
million people, including 66,745 in Houston, argues that a
statistical estimate is needed to achieve a more accurate
population count.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Attorney General Dan Morales filed a legal brief with the
Supreme Court in support of the Clinton administration. Morales
noted the large number of state residents, mostly minorities and
poor people, not counted in 1990 and said he feared ``history
repeating itself'' unless statistical estimates are included in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a growing population of those that are traditionally
undercounted, the loss of federal funds and equal representation
would easily eclipse the losses of the last decade,'' Morales
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   However, House Republicans argue that anything but a traditional
head count would be unlawful and result in an illegitimate
apportionment of House seats. The 16 individuals say the
president's illegal plan would also render congressional districts
within states invalid because they also are calculated based on the
Census results.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, in comments and questions directed at lawyers for
the Republicans and the individuals, seemed skeptical of whether
the opponents had adequately shown they would be harmed if
statistics were used to supplement the Census results.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia was especially critical of the House
Republicans' argument, saying their dispute with Clinton's plan was
political, not legal, and, therefore, did not belong before the
Supreme Court. Courts do not get involved in political disputes,
opting instead to let Congress and the president ``duke it out,''
Scalia said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg joined Scalia in saying that
Congress, if it does not like the president's proposal, can simply
refuse to appropriate money for the controversial plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 900 ways Congress (can) stymie the president, if it
has the political will,'' Scalia said. ``All you have to do is not
pass legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice David H. Souter expressed concern that the Supreme Court
would be ``opening up a very large door'' if it permitted Congress
to sue any time the president did something a majority of the
lawmakers did not like.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the justices, the Republicans' lawyer said the
dispute concerns the constitution, not policy. Congress has a legal
right to ensure that the distribution of the 435 seats is based on
a legally sound Census, added the attorney, Maureen Mahoney of
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution's call for an ``actual enumeration'' of the
U.S. population requires a head count and prohibits the use of
statistical estimates, she said. ``They (census takers) can't
guess,'' Mahoney argued.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, who usually reserve only one hour for arguments,
also questioned whether the individuals have suffered as a result
of Clinton's plan to use statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Michael Carvin, pressing the individuals' case,
responded that the federal government uses Census figures not only
to apportion congressional seats but to determine where federal
funds will be distributed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Federal agencies will use the census figure to distribute
funds, and that will cost us money,'' said Carvin of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans' and individuals' arguments have succeeded so
far. U.S. district courts in Washington, D.C., and eastern Virginia
have ruled that the opponents have standing and the president's
proposal runs afoul of the federal Census Act.
</P>
<P>
   The courts, which did not resolve whether the Constitution
requires a head count, said the law prohibits the use of statistics
in calculating the decennial Census.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Solicitor General Seth Waxman, representing the Clinton
administration, urged the justices to overrule the district courts'
decisions. He called the president's plan ``a good-faith empirical
effort to determine the number of persons in each state.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the president's proposal, up to 90 percent of the U.S.
population would be counted by traditional Census methods,
including mail-in questionnaires and visits by U.S. Census Bureau
personnel to residents who did not respond to the national survey.
The other 10 percent, held in reserve to make the statistical
calculation more sound, would be counted using a series of
statistical estimates, Waxman said.
</P>
<P>
   However, several justices appeared critical of the president's
proposal, questioning why the Census Bureau was suddenly choosing
to rely so heavily on estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't do 100 percent,'' Scalia said, noting the
president's plan to actually count only 90 percent. ``You don't
even try to do 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist predicted that a
statistically enhanced Census would breed more litigation. ``Some
court will decide what the population of the United States was in
2000,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The justices are expected to render their decision by July. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
