<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5216 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-MAMMOGRAPHY-635&AMP;A     11-30 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MAMMOGRAPHY-635&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEARER MAMMOGRAMS MAY BE NEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(lb) 
 By ANNE EISENBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a long delay, the Food and Drug Administration is on the
verge of issuing revised guidelines that could enable a new
generation of mammography devices to come to the market. The
devices rely on digital imaging, a technique experts say offers
clearer, more detailed pictures of some breast tissue than
traditional X-ray film.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of digital mammography say that it is particularly
effective in viewing dense portions of the breast. Dense breast
tissue occurs in women of all ages but is more frequent in younger
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a digital image, you can magnify an area and adjust the
contrast at a computer workstation so that dense tissue that
appears virtually white on film reveals more detail,'' said Dr.
Robert Smith, director of cancer screening for the American Cancer
Society.
</P>
<P>
   But companies seeking to market the devices that X-ray the
entire breast have been delayed by a bottleneck in the Food and
Drug Administration, which has not approved any digital mammography
systems even though it issued an initial set of guidelines to the
manufacturers in July 1996. Manufacturers must comply with the
guidelines in order to receive the agency's approval to market
their devices.
</P>
<P>
   Some are critical of the way the agency is handling the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have moved excessively slowly, dampening enthusiasm for a
development that could be helpful to women,'' said Dr. Martin
Yaffe, a professor of medical biophysics and medical imaging at the
University of Toronto and an expert in new techniques for breast
imaging. Yaffe's research has contributed to the development of the
new systems, but he says he has no financial connection to any
manufacturers of the devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a mammogram _ not a vastly new procedure,'' Yaffe
said. ``The new systems just replace film with an electronic
detector.''
</P>
<P>
   In August, the agency conceded that its original guidelines were
flawed. ``The FDA's guidance did not take into account the
variability in the way radiologists read mammograms,'' said Brian
Casey, editor of Scan, a medical-imaging industry newsletter. ``It
wasn't possible for manufacturers to comply, as the agency more or
less admitted when it decided to revise the criteria in August.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Doyle, a reviewer at the agency, said officials there
were responding to critics and hoped to release new guidelines in
about a month.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Susan Alpert, director of the FDA's office of device
evaluation, did not agree that the agency had been slow to act.
``This is a high-impact decision,'' she said. ``It divides the
women who go away for a year from the women who need follow-up. We
have to be sure digital mammography provides a reliable assessment
before we let those women leave for 12 months.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alpert said she is particularly concerned about the skills
of those who will read the digital mammograms. ``How do we train
people to use this new information so we don't lose the gain we
have from film-screen mammograms?'' she said. ``As a woman,
patient, doctor and regulator, I think this question is critically
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Edward Sickles, a professor of radiology at the University
of California School of Medicine in San Francisco, who participated
in the August panel convened by the agency to discuss guideline
revisions, disputed Dr. Alpert's contention. ``Radiologists know
what mammograms look like, and they can learn to read new ones,''
he said. ``The problem is not radiologists; it's the FDA. They are
dragging their heels.''
</P>
<P>
   Breast cancer is the most commonly diagnosed cancer in women in
the United States. About 180,000 new cases have been discovered
this year, said Smith of the cancer society. Though he would like
to see digital mammography approved, he said he believed that the
agency was being appropriately cautious.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The FDA needs to satisfy itself that the accuracy of the new
method is as good as conventional methods,'' Smith said. ``Based on
conversations I've had, I suspect that the FDA and manufacturers
will soon sort out their differences, and that companies will then
be able to bring products to market.'' He predicted that several
systems would come out in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Smith also cautioned that although the new technology offers
many benefits, the devices are not revolutionary: ``It's still
mammography, however improved.''
</P>
<P>
   Fran Visco, president of the National Breast Cancer Coalition, a
patient-advocate group in Washington, expressed reservations about
the new systems' costs, expected to be about four times those of
traditional mammography units. ``We think they are a step
forward,'' Ms. Visco said, ``but we'd prefer an inexpensive global
alternative _ a low-tech, low-cost blood test that all women could
use.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
