<HEADLINE>
GOLF COURSES SHOULD OFFER DISCOUNTS DURING ROUTINE UPKEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN FORNOFF  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Here's some evidence that the advice ``Buyer,
beware'' applies to the business of golf as much as any other.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, I was just an anonymous golfer, calling a few
courses I hadn't played in a while, looking for a tee-time. I was
all set at one of them, when I asked, ``Oh, by the way, how's the
course? Have you been doing any work on it at all?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, yes, we aerated all the greens Monday,'' the starter
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But everyone in Northern California is doing that right now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, maybe so,'' I said, ``but I think I'd rather play a
course that aerated two or three weeks ago than one that aerated
four days ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Greens that have just been aerated tend to be bumpy, sandy and
generally unputtable for the better part of two weeks. Yet, the man
was clearly indignant that I would prefer to spend my money, not to
mention a precious day off, at a course in playable condition than
at his.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, then, you'll have to go someplace else,'' he huffed.
</P>
<P>
   You bet I did, and without a shred of regret. Buy a shirt that's
missing a couple of buttons, you get a discount. Buy a house that's
in shambles, you get a ``fixer-upper'' deal. If you make a tee-time
at a golf course that's aerating its greens, you get a coverup! A
snow job!
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real dilemma for the operators, because if they tell
callers the truth, they're going to lose money,'' said Bob Higgins,
director of golf at Poppy Hills Golf Course, home of the Northern
California Golf Association. ``We tell people. We put it on our
reservation system 30 days in advance, and we hang signs on the
door. Some places don't want to tell anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that they wake up one day and decide to aerate the
greens or punch the fairways. Most courses make their maintenance
schedule at least a year in advance, trying to work around their
biggest tournaments. And if you have a smaller tournament and you
care about this, it's a valid scheduling question.
</P>
<P>
   Courses that understand that great customer services means
repeat business will tell you the truth. Or, they'll search for
compromises _ one course, for instance, will aerate nine holes this
week, nine holes next. Higgins said he played another course where
half of each green was aerated at a time.
</P>
<P>
   We bargain hunters would get a big thrill out of a discount, or
maybe a two-for-one coupon for a future round. Ha, fat chance of
the fat cat golf courses sharing the dish. For the moment, there
are still too many of us and not enough of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
