<HEADLINE>
COUNTDOWN BEGINS FOR ENDEAVOUR LAUNCH TO DELIVER SPACE STATION
COMPONENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ With marginal weather forecast, NASA on
Monday began the countdown for this week's launch of the shuttle
Endeavour with the second major component of the international
space station.
</P>
<P>
   Endeavour and its crew of six astronauts are to blast off from
Kennedy Space Center on Thursday at 3:56 a.m., EST. The precise
moment will be recalculated shortly before liftoff to enable a
rendezvous with the first component of the new station, already
circling at an altitude of 240 miles.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle carries the $300 million Unity module, a
33-foot-long component equipped with a half-dozen docking ports to
which future station compartments and hardware will be attached.
Using the shuttle's robot arm and spacewalks, the astronauts plan
to attach Unity to the $240 million, Russian-built Zarya module.
The station's first component, Zarya was successfully launched from
Central Asia on Nov. 20 to furnish the station's earliest
propulsion, electrical power and communications requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Endeavour's launching has been delayed a year by Russian
financial difficulties. The problems have held up production of the
service module, the station's first habitable component and a
crucial factor in the pacing of the six-year station construction.
</P>
<P>
   As the countdown got under way on Monday, forecasters offered
the prospect of additional delays. The weather outlook included a
chance of low clouds and rain showers.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Priselac, NASA's shuttle weather officer, placed the chance
of favorable conditions at 40 percent. The outlook was not expected
to improve until the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Endeavour mission has reserved the use of U.S. Air Force
ground tracking radar here through Dec. 8, said NASA test director
Doug Lyons, one of the officials supervising countdown activities.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the use of the tracking equipment would be
redirected toward the Dec. 10 liftoff of NASA's Mars Climate
Orbiter aboard a Delta rocket. That orbiter is the first of two
unmanned probes slated for launching to the Red Planet this month
and next.
</P>
<P>
   Officials reported that Endeavour's countdown was unfolding
routinely on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Added to the mission were two Russian electronics boxes for
possible use aboard Zarya. One of the half-dozen power storage
batteries aboard Zarya has not discharged power properly since its
launching 11 days ago. Mission managers may assign the shuttle crew
to repair the problem using the new boxes or to simply leave the
gear for a future repair effort.
</P>
<P>
   After two years of training, the Endeavour crew was clearly
eager to begin its mission as they arrived in Florida from Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a long time in coming,'' said Endeavour
commander Bob Cabana. ``This flight coming up is just the
beginning. I can't tell you how excited we are to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Endeavour links up with Zarya, the astronauts will use the
shuttle's 50-foot robot arm and at least three spacewalks to join
the two modules.
</P>
<P>
   The station's construction will require three dozen shuttle
flights and nine unmanned Russian rockets. An equal number of
Russian Progress cargo and Soyuz crew capsule missions will be
required as well. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
