<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-TEENS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE-THIRD OF TEXAS MIDDLE SCHOOL STUDENTS, 43 PERCENT OF HIGH
SCHOOLERS REPORT TOBACCO USE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ A survey showing that nearly one-third of Texas middle
school students and 43 percent of high school students use tobacco
suggests the enormity of the state's teen smoking problem, which is
worse than state health officials expected.
</P>
<P>
   The figures include roughly 1 in every 4 sixth-graders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tobacco is addictive and deadly, and everyone should be
shocked that more than one-fourth of all sixth-graders in Texas are
using it,'' said Philip Huang, chief of the Texas Department of
Health's disease and injury prevention bureau.
</P>
<P>
   In the survey, believed to be the most comprehensive of its kind
conducted in the state, students were classified as current tobacco
users if they had used tobacco at least once in the previous 30
days.
</P>
<P>
   When students were asked if they had merely tried cigarettes _
as opposed to all forms of tobacco _ the numbers shot up to 53
percent for middle school students and 75 percent for those in high
school.
</P>
<P>
   Other key findings include:
</P>
<P>
   Smoking generally increases with grade level, topping out at 47
percent of high school seniors.
</P>
<P>
   As a group, black students showed the lowest tobacco use in high
school (33 percent) but the greatest in middle school (37 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Huang considered it particularly ``worrisome'' that a larger
percentage of black students are smoking in middle school than in
high school. He said he feared that may stem from cigarette
advertising targeted to African-Americans and noted that black
people have been depicted in several ads for menthol cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Some 51 percent of high school boys and 35 percent of high
school girls use tobacco. But the gender gap narrows in middle
school, where 33 percent of the boys and 28 percent of the girls
use tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Some 19 percent of Texas high-schoolers and 14 percent of middle
school students smoke cigars and 8 percent of both age groups smoke
pipes.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, sponsored by the Texas Department of Health,
included an 87-item questionnaire completed by 13,029 students in
181 public schools last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Students and schools were selected to reflect the statewide and
regional demographic makeup of Texas' student population, the
health department said.
</P>
<P>
   Health experts say most people who become addicted to tobacco
begin smoking as children.
</P>
<P>
   State law prohibits the sale of tobacco to anyone younger than
18, and it also is illegal for anyone younger than 18 to buy or
possess cigarettes or other tobacco products.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature last year attempted to crack down on teen
smoking with a new law that means a fine up to $250 or the
six-month suspension of a driver's license for any minor caught
smoking or possessing tobacco. Violators also can be required to
take a tobacco education course.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Attorney General Dan Morales sued the tobacco industry in
1996 to recoup public health care costs associated with smoking and
to end what he said were industry marketing practices that targeted
young people.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the $17.3 billion settlement that Morales negotiated
with cigarette makers earlier this year, the tobacco companies
agreed to some advertising restrictions, including an end to
billboard ads.
</P>
<P>
   But Huang said cigarette companies had increased their
advertising at convenience stores, which is still allowed under the
settlement. In Texas alone, the tobacco industry has been spending
$360 million a year on advertising _ at least before the state
settled its suit against cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Huang said, the health department only has about
$1.5 million, including federal funds, to spend this year on
anti-smoking programs.
</P>
<P>
   Morales, who will leave office next month, has asked the
Legislature to use $200 million of the state's first-year tobacco
settlement payments to beef up the educational effort against
smoking.
</P>
<P>
   A task force of state agencies and health care providers has
developed a proposal for spending that money over the next four
years, Huang said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the survey will help health officials evaluate the
potential effectiveness of new anti-smoking programs.
</P>
<P>
   According to the study, 47 percent of whites, 41 percent of
Hispanics and 33 percent of black high school students use tobacco.
Users among middle school students include 37 percent of blacks, 35
percent of Hispanics and 27 percent of whites. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
