<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF BUSH CAN'T SAVE THE GOP, WHO CAN?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a question that is occurring to more and more people these
days. U.S. News &AMP; World Report posed it on the cover of its Nov. 16
issue: ``Can Bush Save the GOP?''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine cover featured a photograph of a smiling George W.
Bush, newly re-elected governor of Texas and hands-down
front-runner for the Republican presidential nomination in 2000 _
the picture leaving no doubt as to which member of the Bush family
has been anointed as potential savior of the Grand Old Party.
</P>
<P>
   With the governor's father just six years out of the Oval
Office, his wife winning acclaim as first lady of Texas, his
brother soon to be inaugurated as governor of Florida, and his
mother ... well, with his mother still one of the most admired
women on the planet, it would not be outrageous to imagine that a
casual reader might wonder which Bush was being touted to lead a
Republican rescue mission.
</P>
<P>
   If you didn't know before, you know now: George W. Bush, the
``compassionate conservative,'' is the Republicans' best hope for
the future.
</P>
<P>
   Bush won re-election with darn near 70 percent of the vote _ and
those votes came from Texans in just about every voter category.
U.S. News described the Bush phenomenon:
</P>
<P>
   ``In winning a second term and sweeping the rest of the
statewide Republican ticket into office with him, he carried key
voting blocs that could be the basis for a new Republican
presidential coalition in 2000. Bush won not only more than two
thirds of female voters but 70 percent of independents, 60 percent
of moderates, and nearly one third of Democratic liberals. Perhaps
his most impressive achievement was snagging 49 percent of
Hispanics, a group he made a special effort to court.''
</P>
<P>
   That adds up to the sort of across-the-board appeal that
Republicans have only dreamed about in recent years while
consistently finding themselves on the short end of the gender gap,
the ethnic gap, the race gap and the ``Which candidate cares most
about people like us?'' gap.
</P>
<P>
   Party strategists can hardly be blamed if they are tempted to
overlook other would-be nominees as they rub their hands in
excitement at the prospect of a Bush-led ticket in November 2000.
</P>
<P>
   We should not ignore the possibility, of course, that Bush will
pre-empt the ``Bush saves GOP'' scenario by taking a pass on the
presidential election. He has said again and again that he will not
run if he has serious misgivings about the effect of a national
campaign on his family _ and when he says it, he means it.
</P>
<P>
   What some people don't understand about Bush is that he is not a
politician who wins an election and immediately starts fantasizing
about higher office. He ran for governor because he had a vision
for the state's future and believed that he could turn that vision
into reality; he did not see the Governor's Mansion as a launching
pad to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush runs for president, it will be because he believes that
he can play a role in making the greatest nation on earth even
greater. He's been to the White House; he harbors no irresistible
yearning to live there.
</P>
<P>
   Back to the question: Can Bush save the GOP?
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely. If he decides to run for the Republican presidential
nomination, he will be the nominee. If he is the nominee, he will
win the election _ over Vice President Al Gore or any other
opponent that the Democrats can conjure up.
</P>
<P>
   Why will he win? For the same reasons that he won two elections
for governor. He explained it in his victory speech on Nov. 3:
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight's resounding victory says my compassionate
conservative philosophy is making Texas a better place. But today's
election says something more. It says that a leader who is
compassionate and conservative can erase the gender gap, can open
the doors of the Republican Party to new faces and new voices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says someone who is conservative and compassionate can win
without sacrificing principle. I have set and will continue to set
a tone that seeks to unify, not divide. I will work to include, not
exclude.''
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't just election-night rhetoric. It's what Bush
believes _ it's what he does and who he is.
</P>
<P>
   If George W. Bush can't save the GOP, nobody can.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
