<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-ICKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO POSTPONES DECISION ON ICKES INVESTIGATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno postponed a decision
Monday on whether to seek an independent counsel to investigate
allegations that a former top aide to President Clinton lied under
oath during an inquiry into 1996 campaign fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, who has been reviewing the case involving Harold Ickes for
the past three months, asked for another 60 days to determine
whether an independent counsel was needed to investigate the
perjury allegations against the former deputy White House chief of
staff.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's request was approved by a special three-judge panel of
the U.S. Court of Appeals that oversees the independent counsel
law. The court late Monday said the attorney general had ``shown
good cause for the requested extension.''
</P>
<P>
   The submission by Reno, which included her reasons for seeking
more time, was not released by the court. Sources said Reno asked
that the documents be kept confidential by the court.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two years, Reno has resisted a push, mostly from
Republicans, to turn over to an independent counsel the campaign
fund-raising investigation being run by a Justice Department task
force. The team of 120 prosecutors and investigators has produced
charges against 14 people, including key Democratic contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Reno a week ago decided against seeking an independent counsel
to investigate whether Vice President Al Gore, a likely candidate
for president in 2000, lied under oath during an inquiry into his
1996 campaign fund-raising practices.
</P>
<P>
   Calling evidence of wrong-doing ``insubstantial,'' Reno said
there ``are no reasonable grounds'' for further examination of
whether Gore lied to FBI agents about his effort to solicit
campaign funds by telephone from his government office.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; By Monday, the attorney general must decide whether an outside
prosecutor should look into whether Clinton and his aides violated
federal law when they set up a multimillion-dollar advertising
campaign financed by the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Both Clinton and Ickes have denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The Ickes case grew out of his testimony last year during a
Senate investigation into Democratic fund-raising in the 1996
campaign. Ickes, who coordinated the president's re-election
efforts with the Democratic Party, was asked about the White House
siding with the Teamsters, a major Democratic Party donor, to
settle a California labor dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Ickes said he knew of no assistance from the administration, a
claim contradicted by other evidence gathered by investigators for
the Senate Committee on Government Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Committee investigators found that Ickes had asked then-U.S.
Trade Representative Mickey Kantor to urge Diamond Walnut Growers
to settle a dispute with the Teamsters in 1995. A company executive
testified there was no explicit threat but Kantor's call was viewed
at Diamond Walnut as part of the Teamsters' effort.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has turned to six independent prosecutors to investigate
allegations against Clinton administration officials. They include
current or former Cabinet members Alexis Herman, Bruce Babbitt,
Henry Cisneros, Mike Espy and Ron Brown.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Clinton's business dealings in Arkansas and
his affair with Monica Lewinsky, plus alleged misuse of FBI files
and firings at the White House travel office have been under
investigation by independent counsel Kenneth Starr. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
