A5294 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TV01-COX     11-30 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TV01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON WHITE HOUSE MAKES BEST OF BAD NEWS
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the midst of an impeachment struggle that has
put excruciating details of his personal conduct on display,
President Clinton has nonetheless found the evening TV news much
kinder to him than to his adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the scandal discussion that has dominated the news
programs, comments on Clinton's job performance were 80 percent
positive, according to a study made by the Center for Media and
Public Affairs. The private, non-partisan group rated comments on
the evening news programs of ABC, NBC and CBS from midsummer until
Nov. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the daily barrage of ethics and sex scandal coverage,
Clinton's aides and supporters were successful in airing their
views. Among comments made on the controversy, 25 percent were
rated as ``positive'' for Clinton, according to the same study.
</P>
<P>
   That's much better than for the man who led the investigation of
Clinton. Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr fared about as well on
the evening news as did Iraq's President Saddam Hussein in the
depths of the Persian Gulf war, said Robert Lichter, president of
the media center, which has been monitoring TV news trends for more
than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Starr received only 12 percent ``positive''
comments on news programs, according to the center's count. That's
about the same as the wartime coverage of Saddam. In the past few
weeks, Starr's positive percentage has bumped up to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the Clinton controversy, the president has a big advantage
over his critics, Lichter said. ``The White House defends the
president and it attacks the attackers. So he gets mixed coverage,
but his opponents get the worst.'' Lichter said that accusers such
as Starr, former White House intern Monica Lewinsky, and Linda
Tripp, who taped her phone conversations with Lewinsky, have gotten
much more negative news coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Starr could not publicly defend himself, so that
nearly all the remarks about him came from his critics.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond sound bites, the White House also had the advantage in
providing favorable pictures and backdrops for Clinton, Lichter
said. ``This has been true ever since Ronald Reagan discovered that
he was going to get terrible press but great pictures by setting up
photo opportunities,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the depths of the controversy over whether Clinton
perjured himself about his affair with Lewinsky, Lichter said that
the White House has succeeded in providing positive TV images.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 21, the day the Starr report hit the streets of
Washington, Clinton was addressing the United Nations and receiving
a standing ovation. As the impeachment hearings were opening in
Congress last week, Clinton was touring Asia aboard Air Force One
and cheering the U.S. troops guarding the South Korean border. And
as the House Judiciary Committee holds a hearing Tuesday on the
significance of Clinton's alleged perjury, the cameras will also be
focused on the president's planned appearance at an AIDS event.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Clinton has proven that he can make the most of such
events. ``I describe Bill Clinton as the almost perfect television
president,'' said Bruce Gronbeck, professor of political
communication at the University of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton has the ability to use television's great power, which
is to present emotions or feelings up close and personal,''
Gronbeck continued. ``Clinton's obviously extremely good at face
work. He can express a phenomenal range of emotions by very small
adjustments in his facial features. It's utterly amazing how good
he is at it, as good as any television actor.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the president's conversational style creates ``a
near-intimate relationship with the viewer'' that has been
essential in helping Clinton generate public sympathy, the
communications expert added.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
