<SLUG> BC-SANDLER-MOVIE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POST-`WATERBOY' DEAL MEANS MEGABUCKS FOR SANDLER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``The Waterboy'' has proved to be a watershed
moment for Adam Sandler, not to mention his accountants.
</P>
<P>
   Cashing in on the phenomenal success of ``The Waterboy'' (the
film has already grossed $123 million), Sandler has signed a
two-picture deal with New Line Cinema that will pay him nearly $20
million for the first picture and possibly as much as $25 million
for the second film. Sandler will also receive a substantial gross
participation fee for both movies.
</P>
<P>
   With the deal, Sandler joins the elite circle of actors,
including Jim Carrey, Tom Hanks, Mel Gibson, Harrison Ford and Tom
Cruise, who can command a $20 million payday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When `The Waterboy' grossed $39 million in its opening week,
everyone knew it was just a matter of time before Adam Sandler
would get this kind of contract,'' says Paul Dergarabedian,
president of the box-office tracking service Exhibitor Relations
Co., Inc.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be the first time Sandler and New Line have joined
forces. Earlier this year, the studio released the comedian's
breakthrough film, ``The Wedding Singer,'' which broadened
Sandler's audience appeal to the tune of $80 million. The former
``Saturday Night Live'' star had earlier enjoyed modest box-office
successes with his first two films, ``Billy Madison'' and ``Happy
Gilmore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are thrilled that Adam has committed his next two films to
us,'' said New Line president Michael De Luca. ``With `The Wedding
Singer,' Adam knows how hard New Line worked to develop, market and
distribute a romantic comedy that expanded his fan base. We have
every intention of being a part of his success for a long time to
come.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the immediate future, Sandler is currently shooting ``Big
Daddy,'' about a man who adopts a little boy to keep his girlfriend
from leaving him. Sony Pictures will release the movie in June.
</P>
<P>
   Sandler will then segue into his New Line deal with ``Little
Nicky,'' a father-and-son comedy that has Sandler playing a guy
who's next in line to take over the family business. He has his
reservations, about joining, though, because his father is the
devil. Sandler will write the movie along with longtime
collaborator Tim Herlihy. New Line hopes to begin production this
spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
