A5298 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-30 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET THIS OVER WITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's impeachment nightmare is
turning into a congressional tummy ache. As the showdown with the
lying lecher in the White House at last nears a close, the
sanctimonious Congress is losing.
</P>
<P>
   What began as a gripping morality play has become a silly
political farce, for all its potentially serious consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The sooner the Republican-controlled House Judiciary Committee
gives it to President Clinton, as expected, next week and the House
votes on whether to recommend his impeachment, the better off we
will all be.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment follies have become redundant, filled with a
strange, otherworldly quality that seems isolated from the rest of
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Political unreality characterizes the partisan congressional
crusade to persuade the public that the president should be thrown
out of office. The whole performance comes as an afterthought. Most
minds are already made up.
</P>
<P>
   The same members of Congress appear on television saying the
same things over and over, solemnly arguing with one another over
constitutional issues they describe as inarguable. The same pundits
repeat the comments they have been making all along. Nobody
influences anybody else.
</P>
<P>
   Help. Where is a theatrical deus ex machina when we need one?
</P>
<P>
   A majority of voters long ago decided that Clinton is a naughty
boy but did not abuse his official power in ways that deserve the
impeachment so piously advocated by Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr. The only charge Starr substantiated is that Clinton lied
about illicit sex under oath in a civil suit. This is too much ado
about too little.
</P>
<P>
   For all the contradictory public posturing of its members, the
House committee's anti-Clinton verdict is preordained. But that
will not finish off the president. The Senate is certain to reject
his ouster if the full House recommends a trial. With only 55 GOP
senators, the numbers are simply not there to reach the two-thirds
majority of those present required to send Clinton packing.
</P>
<P>
   The only question is how determined House Republicans are to
betray their own long-term interests by overreaching in their
campaign to humiliate a president who has no shame. They seem
genuinely divided on whether to recommend impeachment, even though
it would be truly stupid to force the GOP-controlled Senate to
waste months debating presidential punishment instead of dealing
with issues that voters really care about.
</P>
<P>
   Such a distraction would interfere with Senate consideration of
serious legislation, leaving the Republicans looking as though they
cannot govern. The image of an impeachment-obsessed Congress hurt
the Republicans in last month's election. Extending that impression
into the new Congress is surely a bad idea for year 2000
presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee is flopping around aimlessly,
making no serious effort to turn up new information and producing
nothing of substance to affect the outcome. This is a bad joke, a
far cry from the serious, bipartisan House committee that
recommended impeachment for President Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Why are members bothering with these nonsensical hearings? Why
are they calling, behind closed doors, minor witnesses who they
know will take the Fifth Amendment? Why don't they call the one
person who could be enlightening, Monica Lewinsky?
</P>
<P>
   Sending 81 juvenile questions to the president created an
illusion of professional activity but was really a foolish test of
wills that the committee could not win. The GOP majority professed
to be outraged at the president's legalistic answers in which he
failed to confess major crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing would have satisfied them but an admission of guilt.
Underestimating him for the umpteenth time, they actually thought
he was stupid enough to voluntarily incriminate himself.
</P>
<P>
   The committee underestimated the rest of us, as well. A day
spent discussing the meaning of perjury is a day wasted, a sorry
attempt to lecture Americans from a moral pedestal that is
inappropriate for a Congress with its own credibility shortfall.
Americans already know the difference between right and wrong. And
they know the difference between a dangerous, corrupt president and
a self-indulgent, horny one.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde also cynically invited Clinton to appear before the
committee to defend his behavior. How generous of Hyde. How
transparent. Not surprisingly, the White House promptly rejected
this feeble legislative trap to force Clinton to grovel in person.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, momentum grows, although mostly underground, for
the alternative penalty of censure. It would scar Clinton for
history's purposes but leave him in office.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans are opposed because they are determined to
destroy Clinton, even though the lengthy impeachment process is not
in the best interest of either their party or the country. But
cooler heads will hopefully prevail. Short of a Clinton
resignation, censure is the only sensible way out. Congress can do
no more. And it should not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
