<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5301 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-ISRAEL-1STLEDE     11-30 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ISRAEL-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSH FINDS BACKERS AT WESTERN WALL
 &HT;    EDS: Clarifies name of ``Jewish voice'' group in 8th graf
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM Amid the religious fervor and history of the holy
Western Wall, travel agent Manola Noon of Austin got to give her
governor the two-fingered ``Hook' em horns'' signal.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush answered the University of Texas fan
with a thumbs up, and his second day in Israel sidetracked into a
few minutes of handshakes and photos with other Americans who
happened to be sightseeing there.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush and Noon were on their first visits to Israel, but
Bush has been hosted as the GOP presidential frontrunner he denies
being.
</P>
<P>
   His day started with a reception with Jerusalem Mayor Ehud
Olmert, who said with a grin that he hoped to someday visit the
governor ``in Texas or Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   He then met with several top Israeli politicians, culminating
with a dinner with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is accompanied by Republican governors from Utah, Montana
and Massachusetts. But, aside for an awkward digression in which he
asked whether Montana borders Canada, Netanyahu focused his toast
on Bush and his potential as a ``world leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he has not made up his mind about whether he will
run for president, but the prospect has focused early attention on
him.
</P>
<P>
   The trip is organized by a group of Republican supporters, the
National Jewish Coalition, which calls itself the ``Jewish voice''
of the Republican Party and supports the policies of the Israeli
government. Bush aides have said he will reimburse the group for
the trip from leftover campaign money. He was re-elected governor
in November.
</P>
<P>
   Trip organizers have refused to disclose the governors'
schedules and Bush has refused to answer most questions from
reporters, saying that he will hold his comments about the trip for
a press conference in Austin on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   There have been questions here about whether the last day of the
trip, Tuesday, will include a visit to any of the controversial
Jewish settlements in the West Bank, land Israel captured in the
1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
   An initial schedule released by the Israeli government indicated
that a helicopter tour for the governors might include a brief stop
at a settlement, if only to use it as an observation point for the
area. The idea concerned a Palestinian spokesman who worried the
Israelis might use the visit to legitimize settlements that much of
the world has condemned.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers also would not say whether Bush would meet any
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush's father was president, he sometimes clashed with
Israel's government at the time over its plan to expand Jewish
settlements in the West Bank. President Bush asserted that
expanding the settlements was an obstacle to peace.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and the other governors heard Monday from members of
Netanyahu's right-wing government as well as leaders of the
opposition Labor Party. Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai reviewed
for them the threats Israel faces from Iran and Iraq and Foreign
Minister Ariel Sharon briefed them on security and the region's
water shortage.
</P>
<P>
   The governors visited the grave of slain Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin, the holocaust museum and the Israeli parliament building.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told local reporters that he has been impressed by the
``warmth'' of the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   In his dinner toast, he said Israel was the ``best hope for
democracy in the Middle East'' and said, ``Long may Israel live and
long may America and Israel's ties be as close as they possibly can
be.''
</P>
<P>
   (Austin American-Statesman reporter Ken Herman contributed to
this story).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
