   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   AUS-DEATH-ROW-ESCAPE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ As prison authorities
spend their fourth day looking for an escaped death row inmate, we
look at the anatomy of a manhunt, spelling out how law enforcement
tracks an escaped convict, examining the effectiveness of
everything from the low-tech bloodhounds and their role to the
high-tech infared detectors on helicopters. We also look at how
much this costs and why, if prison officials, suspect the escapee
remains nearby, he has been able to elude this massive search
effort? (Harmon, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ Profiling the new Georgia Legislature and how it
will differ from the 1998 edition. (Baxter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PBP_PIRO MURDER _ RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. _ Update on the murder of
Janette Piro and her missing husband, Chris Benedetto. Expect
explanation on why Piro's autopsy has been delayed. Also, Riviera
Beach police may take case to America's Most Wanted TV show to get
more publicity. And why is the FBI involved? (Brogan, Palm Beach
Post)
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Tuesday is World AIDS Day.
</P>
<P>
   AIDSVAX _ ATLANTA _ Dan Flinchum doesn't much like needles, but
he is about to become the first volunteer in Atlanta to be
inoculated with AIDSVAX, the first vaccine for the AIDS virus to be
widely tested in the United States. He watches calmly as nurse Gail
Kropf prepares a syringe from an innocuous vial the size of her
thumb. He rolls up his left sleeve. This is not the end of AIDS,
not even close. The vaccine may not work. Even if it does, it will
take years of further testing and tweaking before it is approved
for widespread use. Flinchum knows this, and Kropf knows this, and
they try not to attach too much significance to the tiny vial
marked VAX004. (Kim , Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   AIDSVAX-TESTS _ Perhaps Dr. Edward Jenner swallowed hard when he
steadied the syringe containing the deadly virus smallpox, just
before he injected the contents into 8-year-old James Phipps.
Jenner must have been acutely aware that he was deliberately
imperiling the boy's life. The date was July 1, 1796, and Jenner
was performing a daring experiment that, if reproduced today, would
shock and outrage our 1990s sensibilities. Jenner was lucky. HIV
vaccine researchers know they will need luck, too, if they are to
meet President Clinton's goal of developing a working HIV vaccine
by 2007 _ a goal some believe is impossible, or at least highly
implausible. (Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH GRAPHIC
</P>
<P>
   AIDSVAX-CRITERIA _ Who qualifies for the study.
</P>
