<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT ENTERS BATTLE OVER 2000 CENSUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration asked the Supreme Court
Monday to allow it to use a new method to conduct the 2000 census
that would likely benefit the Democrats by lowering an expected
undercount of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The new method would employ statistical sampling to help
determine the number of people in the United States rather than
relying completely on the traditional system of mailing out
questionnaires and then dispatching thousands of enumerators to
hunt down those who don't respond.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republican-led House of Representatives and a group of
private citizens who claim they would be hurt by the new method
have challenged the use of sampling, saying that it violates the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   In his arguments before the Supreme Court, Solicitor General
Seth Waxman, representing the administration, said that no census
in the history of the United States has ever been able to track
down every person in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The sampling plan would ``best achieve the Constitution's goal
of determining the number of persons in each state,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Waxman added: ``It is in effect a quality check'' on the initial
head count to be conducted starting April 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   A 1992 study by the National Academy of Sciences showed that the
1990 census missed 8.4 million people, mostly of whom were
minorities and recent immigrants living in urban or rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   Michael A. Carvin, representing the group of 16 citizens, told
the court that the Constitution calls for an ``actual enumeration''
of the population. ``The only process it contemplates is
counting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Several justices appeared to agree with Carvin.
</P>
<P>
   Interrupting Waxman during his arguments, Justice Sandra Day
O'Connor said, ``Most people would think an actual enumeration
means an actual count. How do you get around that?''
</P>
<P>
   Waxman answered that someone looking for the number of people
attending a baseball game wouldn't count every person but would,
instead, estimate the size of the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia snapped back, ``You would call that an
enumeration?''
</P>
<P>
   But other justices questioned the accuracy of a census that used
the traditional methods of counting the population.
</P>
<P>
   Justice John Paul Stevens asked Maureen E. Mahoney, representing
the House, what would happen if nobody in a large apartment
building that was known to house illegal aliens responded to census
questionnaires.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a census enumerator couldn't get anybody to say that they
lived there, would he write down that the number of people in that
apartment building was zero?'' Stevens asked.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Mahoney answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if the lights go on and off in the evening?'' added
Justice Stephen G. Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   The court is expected to rule on the case in the spring. Because
the census is used to determine the makeup of the House of
Representatives and state legislatures and to decide where federal
funds should go, the court's decision could have tremendous
political and financial impact across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Strategists from both political parties say that sampling would
turn up increases in the number of people living in historically
Democratic areas, giving the party an advantage when new boundaries
for congressional, state and local legislative districts are drawn
after the 2000 census has been completed.
</P>
<P>
   These strategists also say that since sampling would find
increases in the number of poor people counted in urban and rural
areas, cities and agricultural counties would receive extra federal
dollars at the expense of suburban communities.
</P>
<P>
   Under the administration's sampling plan, the Census Bureau
would use traditional methods to count everyone living in 90
percent of U.S. households and then use the data gathered to
estimate the remaining 10 percent of the population who haven't
been located.
</P>
<P>
   Following that count, the bureau would conduct another, more
intensive census of 750,000 specially selected households.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau then would compare the results of the second census
with those of the original 90-percent census. In areas where the
two counts differ, the bureau would use the figures from the second
census to adjust the original census.
</P>
<P>
   During his argument, Waxman urged the justices to throw out the
case. He contended that the plaintiffs _ the congressional
Republicans in one lawsuit and the 16 individuals living in six
states plus officials from Cobb County, Ga., in another _ have no
right to file the motions. He argued that since the census has yet
to take place, the plaintiffs have not been hurt by it and
therefore cannot say it is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way they can claim that something that hasn't
happened could have injured them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist appeared unconvinced by
the argument, asking, ``What good would waiting until after the
census is taken to figure out if there was a mistake? Would we
re-do the census?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In September, a three-judge federal district court in Richmond,
Va., unanimously ruled, in the case of the 16 individuals and Cobb
County, Ga., that federal law bars the use of sampling for the
purpose of apportioning congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   That court said the six states where the 16 people live are
``substantially likely'' to lose seats in the House if the national
head count is determined partly by sampling. As a result, the lower
court found, the 16 can legitimately claim that they would be hurt
by prospective ``vote dilution'' of the sort that the Supreme Court
has recognized in the past as a basis for challenging an
apportionment plan.
</P>
<P>
   The six states are Connecticut, Massachusetts, Minnesota,
Missouri, Pennsylvania and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, in August, a separate three-judge district court panel
here in Washington, D.C., issued a unanimous ruling in the suit by
House Republicans, saying sampling violated federal law.
</P>
<P>
   The D.C. court ruled that the lawmakers did have the right to
file the suit. It said sampling threatens the ``institutional
interests'' of the House because it could alter that body's
composition.
</P>
</TEXT>
