<HEADLINE>
CUSTOMS SEIZES FAKE NEW JERSEY TAX STAMPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ The U.S. Customs Service said Monday that agents
recovered 86,000 counterfeit New Jersey cigarette tax stamps that a
woman tried to smuggle into the United States from Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The thumb-nail size stickers were hidden in gift-wrapped
packages carried by the woman as she crossed the border from Nuevo
Laredo in a taxi, Customs spokesman Rick Pauza said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, who was stopped during the holiday weekend, had told
inspectors at the international bridge here that the brightly
wrapped packages contained pajamas.
</P>
<P>
   The stamps were seized, but the woman was not charged and later
was fined $34,000 and released. Pauza said she must pay the fine if
she becomes a legal resident of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very rare,'' Pauza said of finding the black-and-red
stickers with an outline of the state of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The bogus stamps, printed in sheets of 100 to look as if they
were issued by New Jersey, have an estimated street value of
$68,800, a New Jersey official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bootlegging in a way,'' said Dan Emmer, a spokesman for
the New Jersey Treasury Department. ``If you get your own or
counterfeit tax stamps, you can undercharge the price of
cigarettes.''
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's tax is 80 cents on a pack of cigarettes, and stamps
are affixed to packs by distributors to show the tax has been paid,
he said. It is the third highest state cigarette tax in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey investigators will examine the stamps, said Joe
Flynn, a criminal investigator with the state treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Among the questions is whether there is a relationship between
the stamps seized here and a New York City operation that was
caught during the summer counterfeiting tax stamps for
Massachusetts, New York and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll try to track down the source and destination,'' Flynn
said. ``If they're counterfeiting New Jersey stamps, I'm sure
they're counterfeiting other things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
