A5343 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKUBE-COLUMN01-COX     11-30 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The world is far larger than outcome of a game
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Naked hatred is an ugly sight, as senseless as a rabid
dog.
</P>
<P>
   You have only to turn on the radio. ``I hate Tech!'' someone
whose name I think was Phil screamed into his telephone. On the
other end, the program's host ministered to his caller like a
kindly pastor in his hour of grief. It occurred to neither host nor
caller to focus the fury more precisely, much less explain it.
</P>
<P>
   This was hatred for someone, or something, that did not even
exist in the flesh. ``Tech''? Who exactly was that? It was an
abstraction, like ``society'' and ``liberals'' and
``conservatives'' and ``the media.'' The impulse to hate creates
its own object, real or not.
</P>
<P>
   So it was on Saturday afternoon as my son and I were driving
from Athens(Ga.) back to Atlanta. We had witnessed one of the best
college football games you'll ever see. A year ago, we had seen one
just like it, this one in Atlanta, this one also involving the
University of Georgia and Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   The two games were mirror images of each other, the outcomes
decided in the closing seconds. The difference _ as all know by now
_ was that Georgia won last year and Tech won this year.
</P>
<P>
   What goes around comes around. At least sometimes _ and that was
what made both games autumn afternoons that won't be forgotten by
anyone who was present. On one side there was jubilation, on the
other disappointment. Anyone could understand that, and the games
could be appreciated for that alone.
</P>
<P>
   It's not always easy to make the case for big-time college
athletics. But last Saturday you could think better of the players
than of the fans. Many of them, anyway. If you were careless enough
to tune into a sports call-in show, you realized that the real
goons were not in the locker room. They were on the air.
</P>
<P>
   It was a station broadcasting from Athens, 95.5 on the AM dial.
As we headed west on U.S. 78, it began as nothing more than
post-game patter. The Bulldogs' offensive coordinator was fielding
dumb questions, returning the dumb answers they deserved, and
sometimes no answer at all.
</P>
<P>
   If I'd been alone I'd have put in a CD or simply enjoyed the
silence. There were other things on my mind. Driving into a sunset
that became more beautiful by the mile, I knew I would be attending
a funeral the next day in Gwinnett County(Ga.). A friend and her
husband would be burying their youngest child, killed a few days
earlier in a car wreck. It was easy enough to enjoy the game, and
just as easy to leave it at Sanford Stadium. Nothing like life or
death was happening between the hedges.
</P>
<P>
   But these were my own thoughts, and there was no reason to dwell
on them with my son. Noah is 11, and you would have thought most of
the callers weren't much older.
</P>
<P>
   When you're 11, the outcome of a game between 20-year-olds can
be all-consuming. I knew that from experience, and tried to be
consoling. The truth is that it didn't matter much to me who won,
the Bulldogs or the Yellow Jackets. But Tech was the underdog and
anyone with any feeling for the game had to thrill seeing
quarterback Joe Hamilton and tailback Charlie Rogers cut upfield
for big gains.
</P>
<P>
   More than any of this, though, I know that Noah enjoys a benign
competition with his old man. When the football rankings come out
each Monday morning, his oatmeal sits cold as he pores over the
latest calibrations in the polls. This fall, every week that
Georgia inched up a notch was a week off to a good start.
</P>
<P>
   How he ever got to be such a Bulldog fan, I have no idea. It's
OK with me, but I'm trusting he'll realize in time that the world
is larger than just Clarke County(Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   The people I wonder about are the ones oblivious of anything
beyond the hedges. The spectacle of grown-ups waiting on hold to
ask a football coach to fill them in on where high school students
plan to attend college is as silly in its own way as the calls Dr.
Laura gets.
</P>
<P>
   But if it's a bit juvenile, at least it's not abusively fanatic.
It was other callers, venting blind hatred, you wanted no part of.
Whatever world they live in, I want to live somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, at a graveside service in Gwinnett County, I thought
about them again, and thought how paltry their passion was, how
small their world. I almost pitied them.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
