<SLUG> BC-TV-SCHRODER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    That's Mr. Schroder: Actor strong in `NYPD'
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time has passed, although apparently not quite enough time for
some of New York's 15th Precinct. Bobby Simone is dead and buried,
but still a living memory for his wife and fellow officers.
</P>
<P>
   Then in walks Bobby's replacement, and it's that little Ricky
Schroder from ``Silver Spoons,'' except now he's Rick (no
diminutive) Schroder, all grown up with what may be the toughest
dual job on television at the moment: convincing his resentful
co-workers he's not some fresh punk trying to do a man's job _ and
convincing ``NYPD Blue'' viewers of the same.
</P>
<P>
   And Schroder is convincing. The acting chops that producer
Steven Bochco and co-star Dennis Franz saw when Schroder tried out
for the new role are abundant. He may look like a high schooler _ a
running thread on tonight's episode _ but he has an impressive
authority as rookie Detective Danny Sorensen.
</P>
<P>
   It ain't easy being the new guy, though, especially when you're
still getting carded in bars. Danny is partnered with Sipowicz
(Franz), who's his usual cuddly self: ``So that's what 14-year-olds
are wearin' now?'' he growls at Danny, who's wearing a leather
jacket. (Sipowicz, never exactly on the cutting edge of fashion,
should realize the leather jacket is now the garment of choice for
45-year-old men nationwide.)
</P>
<P>
   But young Danny's real shoe-squeezer is Diane Russell (Kim
Delaney), Bobby's widow, who's still fragile and unwilling to
accept anybody as Bobby's replacement.
</P>
<P>
   (Maybe it's method acting for the cast, since Schroder
leap-frogged right into second-spot billing, after Franz but ahead
of the rest.)
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Danny is no boy. Although he's only recently gotten his
gold detective's shield, he's an Army vet and former beat cop. When
he hits the streets, he's in his element, with a good cop sense of
when to play rough with a suspect and when to play nice.
</P>
<P>
   The more you watch him, the more he's reminiscent of a younger
Sipowicz we never saw, a guy with a little attitude, a lot of heart
and a healthy amount of lip. ``Yeah, why don't you write that up
for Reader's Digest,'' he snaps at a whiny perp in a line that
could have been written for Andy.
</P>
<P>
   So ``NYPD'' comes out very well in the Smits-for-Schroder swap.
And the sobriquet ``icky Ricky'' is hereby officially retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``NYPD Blue''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   10 E.S.T. tonight on ABC
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
