<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SUN WITNESS TO MOVE MICROSOFT TRIAL INTO KEY PHASE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Microsoft antitrust trial will shift into high
gear again this week when the government calls Java creator James
Gosling to the witness stand.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 pages of direct testimony from Gosling, a
vice-president of Sun Microsystems Inc., is expected to be made
public after the court recesses Tuesday, to be followed by an
intense cross-examination by Microsoft's lawyers for the rest of
the week.
</P>
<P>
   The key issue in this phase of the case will be Microsoft's
purported misuse of the Java programming language. The trustbusters
contend that Microsoft willfully ``broke'' Java by grafting a
Windows-only version of the language onto what Sun's intended
``write-once, use-many'' universal standard.
</P>
<P>
   Gosling has also been a witness in a private lawsuit that Sun
brought against Microsoft. In that case, Gosling told a federal
district court in California why Microsoft supposedly saw Java as a
threat to its operating system, and how it then allegedly wrote a
``polluted'' version of Java for its products in a bid to derail
Sun's competitive efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Sun won a preliminary injunction in that case,
which in turn forced Microsoft to make changes to its Java products
to bring them into line with Sun's compatibility standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although Microsoft is always trying to change the subject,
this case has always been about the market for personal computer
operating systems _ a market that Microsoft monopolizes,'' David
Boies, the government's chief litigator, said in a brief interview
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Microsoft placed an ad in several newspapers
congratulating three companies that have attacked the software
giant in court _ America Online Inc., Netscape Communications Corp.
and Sun _ for having cut a merger deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``A healthy and vibrant high tech economy is creating powerful
new alliances and competitors. It isn't occurring in court and it
doesn't take years of litigation,'' the ad said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always interesting when a monopolist spends its money to
tell people it is not a monopolist,'' Boies said.
</P>
<P>
   Although in view of the AOL-Netscape merger Microsoft has
publicly called on the government to drop its case, no such request
has been filed with either the federal court or with Attorney
General Janet Reno, who has the discretion to halt the civil
prosecution, a Microsoft spokesmen said.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the trial entered its seventh week with no end in
sight. Both sides had initially predicted a six- to eight-week
battle. Boies now believes the trial will run at least until March,
one assertion that Microsoft's defenders, the Wall Street firm of
Sullivan &AMP; Cromwell, won't challenge.
</P>
<P>
   However, over four days in court, attorney Michael Lacovara has
challenged nearly every aspect of the testimony offered by
Frederick Warren-Boulton, a top economist in the Justice
Department's antitrust division during the Reagan administration.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Lacovara noted that one of the many internal
documents Warren-Boulton has cited came from Christian Wildfeuer,
who conducts focus groups for Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think monopolists have an incentive'' to invest in
focus groups? Lacovara asked the witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing about monopoly power that indicates that a
profit-maximizing monopolist has any incentive not to listen to its
customers,'' Warren-Boulton replied.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
