<HEADER>
A5351 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDSVAX-COX     11-30 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDSVAX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taking their best shot; AIDS vaccine trials begin in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dan Flinchum doesn't much like needles, but he is
about to become the first volunteer in Atlanta to be inoculated
with AIDSVAX, the first vaccine for the AIDS virus to be widely
tested in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He watches calmly as nurse Gail Kropf prepares a syringe from an
innocuous vial the size of her thumb. He rolls up his left sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   One would think this would be a solemn moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never, never get a tattoo of your lover's name,'' Flinchum
quips ruefully, looking at the inscription ``ROGER'' _ an
ex-boyfriend _ on his upper arm, just below where the needle should
go.
</P>
<P>
   When everyone stops laughing, Kropf gives him the shot.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the end of AIDS, not even close. The vaccine may not
work. Even if it does, it will take years of further testing and
tweaking before it is approved for widespread use.
</P>
<P>
   Other vaccines must be created and tested, in a winnowing
process that could take more than a decade. In that time, tens of
millions of people will become infected with HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Flinchum knows this, and Kropf knows this, and they try not to
attach too much significance to the tiny vial marked VAX004.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a step in the long march toward eliminating one of the
worst diseases the world has seen, a disease with no cure. As of
today, the 11th annual World AIDS Day, 33.4 million people
worldwide are living with HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Flinchum nor any of the other 149 Atlantans who will be
inoculated eventually as part of the AIDSVAX study are in any
danger from the vaccine. Unlike some other types of vaccines that
carry a small risk of infecting people with the diseases they are
meant to prevent, AIDSVAX is harmless. It doesn't contain the virus
itself, only a copy of the viral shell.
</P>
<P>
   Still, AIDSVAX recipients are at risk for HIV _ researchers are
specifically choosing test subjects with sexual habits that put
them at risk.
</P>
<P>
   It may sound callous, but it is the only way to find out whether
a vaccine works. To prove that an HIV vaccine is effective,
scientists must test it in humans who are exposed to the virus.
</P>
<P>
   But because AIDS is a killer, researchers have a moral
responsibility to do everything possible to prevent people from
risking infection.
</P>
<P>
   It is a dilemma worthy of Solomon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that we would want or encourage infections to happen
in a trial to determine whether or not a vaccine works is
ludicrous,'' said Dr. William Heyward, who heads HIV vaccine
research at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   How, then, is a vaccine to be thoroughly tried?
</P>
<P>
   As the first large-scale trial of an experimental HIV vaccine
gets under way in Atlanta and the United States, researchers must
grapple with this question and other social and scientific issues.
</P>
<P>
   During the next four years, 5,000 people in North America and
2,500 in Thailand will be inoculated with either the AIDSVAX
vaccine or a placebo, an inactive shot. AIDSVAX is the creation of
VaxGen Inc., based near San Francisco and headed by veteran AIDS
researcher Dr. Don Francis.
</P>
<P>
   The AIDS Research Consortium of Atlanta is seeking 150
volunteers for the AIDSVAX trials here. Altruism is appreciated,
but the primary criterion is rigid: Participants must be
HIV-negative but at high risk for infection because of their sexual
behavior. Flinchum, for instance, is dating an HIV-positive man.
</P>
<P>
   The Thai arm of the study will focus on injection drug users.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the study criteria, volunteers will risk being
stigmatized. And because of their own risky behavior, some of the
test subjects will become infected.
</P>
<P>
   They will join the 16,000 people who become infected with HIV
each day.
</P>
<P>
   Francis is optimistic about AIDSVAX, but grimly realistic about
HIV.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bloody dangerous virus,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately before Flinchum's inoculation last week, ARCA nurses
gave him a head-to-toe physical examination as well as a
heart-to-heart conversation about HIV risks and prevention. Test
subjects must undergo risk counseling before every time they are
inoculated _ seven times in all, over three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very excited about it,'' said Flinchum, who works in human
resources for Rich's at Perimeter Mall. ``It gives me a chance to
be involved in something worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   Flinchum, who is 42 and gay, has spent most of his adulthood in
the shadow of the AIDS epidemic, yet has escaped its worst ravages.
He is HIV-negative and has never lost a partner to AIDS, although
friends have died from the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm lucky,'' he says. ``The majority of the people I
know are still around.''
</P>
<P>
   He is seeing a man with HIV, but they are always careful, he
assures. That won't change despite the inoculation _ he knows
there's a 1-in-3 chance the syringe was full of nothing but saline.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Flinchum did receive AIDSVAX, he'll probably never have
reason to question its preventative powers. ARCA researchers will
be proud of him for practicing safe sex, though he won't be a good
test of whether AIDSVAX is effective.
</P>
<P>
   Other test subjects will not be so wise. Despite repeated,
earnest counseling, they will have unprotected oral or anal sex.
Some will ignore constant reminders that they may have received the
placebo and that the vaccine may not be effective. Thinking
themselves protected, they will abandon caution.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mark Feinberg of Emory University(Ga.) recalls a 1994 HIV
vaccine study in San Francisco, in which a number of people were
infected with HIV although testers warned them against relying on
the vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   ``That message seems to be a difficult one to get through,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors are obligated to thoroughly educate study participants,
but it is entirely up to individuals to determine their own
actions, Heyward said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fully recognize that our ability to change people's
behavior and prevent them from engaging in risk behavior, whether
it's sexual activity or drug use, is limited,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the infection rates among the trial's participants may be
lower than among the general population _ yet people will be
infected. Through them, researchers will learn about AIDSVAX as
well as gain insight into the human body's defenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a really incomplete understanding of the immune
system,'' said Dr. Melanie Thompson, ARCA's principal researcher.
</P>
<P>
   The AIDSVAX trial also will be something of a study in human
nature. It will reveal how test subjects behave during an HIV
vaccine trial and whether they acquire a false sense of immunity or
a greater degree of caution.
</P>
<P>
   The concern over complacency is a valid one, as research
indicates faith in new HIV drugs has led some people to engage in
risky behavior.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is that treatment options are far from perfect,
and more people than ever are living with HIV. Half of all new
infections occur among 15- to 24-year-olds, and 11 people are
infected every minute worldwide. Clearly, prevention without a
vaccine is limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Therapy will have a miniscule impact globally,'' Heyward said.
``The only way we're going to get out of this is a preventative
vaccine.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
