<HEADER>
A5352 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN     11-30 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEP OPEN MIND WHEN WRONG PERSON IS PROMOTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Ken Lloyd _ a specialist in organizational behavior _ is a
columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News. His column moves Mondays
in the ``f'' financial news file. Send your questions to P.O. Box
260057, Encino, Calif. 91426 or by electronic mail to
LloydOnJobaol.com. Names will be withheld upon request.) 
By KEN LLOYD  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Q. I cannot believe who our company put into a
vice president position over our area. He has been with the company
for several years, but he does not have the skills or experience to
handle this job, nor does he have the respect of those of us who
are supposed to report to him. It's not as if I should have been
promoted, but any of us would have been better. What should we do?
E.F. &QL; 
A. At this point, you have to play the cards that you have been
dealt, even if you feel that this new vice president is not exactly
an ace. The best approach is to give this whole matter some time.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, if you maintain the belief that he is weak, this
is going to affect the way that you work with him to the point that
your working relationship is going to be undermined before it
starts. Although you do not need to greet this new vice president
with open arms, an open mind will help.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it is possible that your perceptions of this person
are inaccurate, and he may have more skills than may be apparent.
There are certainly cases where people move into positions that are
seemingly over their heads only to perform with distinction.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, if your perceptions about this individual's
competencies are accurate, there is a good chance that top
management will recognize its mistake and correct it. However, if
management is literally or figuratively wedded to this type of
person, then it is time for you to think about how long you want to
be wedded to this type of company. &QL; 
Q. A few weeks ago, I hired a new employee in our department. Right
from the start, he has acted like he is in charge. He tells other
people what to do and answers questions that are beyond his
expertise. I have met with him to discuss the problem, but he has
not changed. What can you suggest I do? K.B. &QL; 
A. Employers often state that they want employees who will take
charge, but sometimes this approach leads to an employee who wants
to take over. On the one hand, you do not want to undercut his
initiative and energy. But at the same time, you do not want to let
him undercut the initiative and energy of your entire department.
</P>
<P>
   Since you have met with him to discuss the problem, now is the
time to meet with him to discuss solutions. Let him know that you
expect employees to demonstrate independence, creativity and
leadership, but the No. 1 priority is for employees to carry out
the responsibilities for which they were hired in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Ask him to discuss what he regards as the primary
responsibilities of his position, along with his views of the way
in which he is carrying them out. If there are a few gaps in these
areas, you should fill them in. Both of you should then jointly
establish some near-term and longer-term objectives, along with
plans and strategies to meet them. The meeting should end with a
commitment from him to focus his energy on these objectives. He
should also understand that if he cannot keep his commitment, it
may be difficult to keep him. &QL; 
Q. One of my close friends reports to me, and she made a monumental
error. There's no question that I have to reprimand her, but,
honestly, I fear what that will do to our friendship. What's the
best way to handle this? T.G. &QL; 
A. In your question, you indicated that you honestly fear what will
happen to your friendship, but your question has the answer implied
in it. The best way to handle this matter is to deal honestly with
her. However, rather than opting for a reprimand, which generates
little more than defensiveness and ill will, you should approach
this from the standpoint of providing performance-based feedback,
coaching and guidance.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that this employee is your friend should have no
bearing whatsoever. You should approach her in the same way that
you would any other employee: Be friendly, fair and businesslike,
and avoid criticizing, berating or labeling. The objective is to
discuss what happened and then develop a strategy to prevent it
from occurring again.
</P>
<P>
   As her manager, you should also honestly ask yourself if there
was anything that you could have done to help prevent the
monumental error in the first place. This type of approach, based
on trust and respect, is an important part of the manager-employee
relationship, and it is an important part of the friendship as
well. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
