<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Toys, our picks of the season's best
 &HT;    By Shelia Poole
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   They fly. They talk and sing. They spurt water, use robotics and
speak a strange new language called ``Furbish.''
</P>
<P>
   Toys and games for the new holiday season do a little bit of
everything. Most of all, they bring you fun. News for Kids has
looked at dozens of new toys and games. Here's a look at some our
picks. Happy wishing, happy shopping!
</P>
<P>
   A Bug's Life Deluxe Moving &AMP; Talking Ant (Mattel, ages 6 &AMP; up,
$29.99) Bugs alive! This 12-inch action figure from the new movie
``A Bug's Life'' says 30 different things and moves.
</P>
<P>
   Air Hogs (Spin Master, ages 8 &AMP; up, $29.99) These planes are a
parent's dream come true because they require no gas, batteries or
assembly. Just use an air-pressure pump, toss them in the air and
watch them soar.
</P>
<P>
   Brain Shift (Tiger Electronics, ages 5 &AMP; up, $24.99) Players
must follow commands on this tabletop game. The computer calls out
colors or sounds and players must memorize the patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Hydro Zap! (Pressman, ages 8 &AMP; up, $27) Test your memory and
reflexes, but watch out! If you forget or are too slow you get
splashed.
</P>
<P>
   Lego Insectoids Celestial Stinger (Lego, ages 8 &AMP; up, $49.99)
Build several species of insectoids that use light and sound.
</P>
<P>
   Lego Mindstorms Robotics Invention System (Lego, ages 12 &AMP; up,
$200) Lego creations come to life with this robotics invention
system. Build your own robot, then use computer software to program
it to follow your commands.
</P>
<P>
   Furby (Tiger Electronics,
</P>
<P>
   ages 6 &AMP; up, $29.99) This 5-inch furry critter that burps and
snores is the latest in high-tech toys. With more than 300
combinations of ear, eye and mouth movements, the animated Furbys
speak ``Furbish'' and English.
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon Rugrats Talking
</P>
<P>
   Alarm Clock (Long Hall Technologies, ages 4 &AMP; up, $24.99) Wake
up to Tommy, Chuckie and Angelica with this talking alarm clock.
Includes four wake up calls from the Rugrats crew, each introduced
by the series theme song.
</P>
<P>
   Totally Twister (Hasbro, ages 8 &AMP; up, $24.99). A new take on the
Twister game uses a handheld format. A Twister cube tells players
to twist, turn and touch the colored buttons in three games. The
challenge is to push the correct buttons in whatever positions
you're in.
</P>
<P>
   Pro Drag Racing (Hasbro, ages 8 &AMP; up, $19.99) Players need a
keen eye and hand coordination to race down the speedway by
shifting through five gears without blowing an engine. You hear
life-like sounds and feel the vibration as your dragster peels out
and heads down the track.
</P>
<P>
   Super
</P>
<P>
   Singing Tommy (Mattel, ages 4 &AMP; up, $32.99) Really for younger
tykes, but NFK knows how much big kids love Nickelodeon 'rats! Rub
his tummy and Tommy tells stories, squeeze his hand and his sings.
Also available at same price: Stop My Hiccups Dil doll.
</P>
<P>
   Mars 2020
</P>
<P>
   (Aristoplay, 8 &AMP; up, $30) A cool multi-level space exploration
board game. While dealing with challenges along the way, players
assume roles and try to be the first to get to Mars.
</P>
<P>
   BREAKOUT
</P>
<P>
   Cheap and cool
</P>
<P>
   Need to get your best bud a little something? Some suggestions
for under $10:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Yo-yos have made a comeback and are sold everywhere _ in hot
new colors. Prices start around $3
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Yak Wakky (for $10) is a little gadget that warps your voice.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Crazy Bones, by Go-Go's, are a series of 60 different
``bones'' that come in packages of four ($1.99 a package). Crazy
Bones can be collected and used to play games. Accessories, which
range from $1.99 to $5, include coffins, key chain cages and bone
bags.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Beads are hot right now. There are dozens of bead kits
available so pals can make jewelry, key chains and more; kits start
at $2.99.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rugrats watches are just $1.99 with meal purchase at Burger
King this month. Four models available. The ``Tommy'' watch says,
``A baby's gotta do what a baby's gotta do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``A Bug's Life Life'' action figures come in many styles, with
prices starting at $6.99.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Meanies ($6-$7) from the Idea Factory, are goofy critters to
give those friends who make fun of your Beanie Babies. New Meanies
include Splat in the Hat (squished by Santa and reindeer) and
Slushy the Snowman (melted by El Nino). The same company is about
to introduce Spice Girls beanbag dolls ($8.99 each).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
