<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Dec. 1, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another round of heavy rain will spread onto the northwest coast
on Tuesday, as the latest in a parade of moist Pacific disturbances
marches onshore. Strong winds will buffet the coast, with gusts
past 60 mph likely along exposed beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Snow, some heavy, will fall in the Cascades. Snow levels will
fall Tuesday night, after temporarily rising Tuesday afternoon.
Farther south, patches of lighter rain will affect northern
California, with snow falling above 4,000 feet in the Sierra.
</P>
<P>
   A potent jet-stream disturbance will spiral into the Southwest.
The associated surface low-pressure system will lead to showers
across parts of southern Nevada, interior southern California, Utah
and Arizona. Snow will fall in the higher elevations. Precipitation
will reach New Mexico and Colorado on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   A complex frontal system will move through the Plains states.
Patchy light snow or freezing drizzle is possible near the Canadian
border, but will mostly be confined to southern parts of Manitoba
and Saskatchewan.
</P>
<P>
   A weak cold front will move away from the northeastern states.
In its wake, brisk winds from the northwest will direct cooler air
into New England. Some clouds and patchy light showers will
accompany the southern end of the front in the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, abnormal warmth will extend from the Front Range of
the Rockies to the Eastern Seaboard. Afternoon highs will be 10 to
20 degrees above normal. A few places in the western High Plains
will have readings nearly 25 degrees above normal. There are no
signs that arctic chill will enter the contiguous states in the
next several days.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Warmth at Night
</P>
<P>
   At 12:01 a.m. Monday, a new record high temperature for Nov. 30
was set in Madison, Wis., where the mercury stood at 63 degrees.
The record-setting nighttime warmth was repeated at several other
locations across the upper Middle West. While record high
temperatures under cover of darkness are uncommon, they are more
apt to occur around the winter season. The contribution of solar
energy to the daily cycle of temperature is limited when sun angles
are low. At the same time, the weather systems that can draw warm
air northward are at their strongest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
