<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Tenn., Calif.)  (The Science Times) 
(Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a Bad Mood _ for a Good Reason
</P>
<P>
   According to a researcher at Harvard University, in any 24-hour
period, married women are 50 percent more likely to complain of
being in a bad mood than their Y-chromosomed counterparts. The
reason, he theorizes, is that married women juggle several roles,
so they encounter more opportunities for things to go wrong in
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ronald Kessler, a sociologist in the department of
health-care policy at Harvard Medical School, and a colleague
studied 166 middle-class couples who kept a diary of their emotions
for six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Women, Kessler said, ``tend to the home, the plumber, their
husband's career, their jobs, and, oh yes, the kids.'' By contrast,
he said, men operate with a narrower focus. ``For men it's `How are
things at work? The end,''' said Kessler.
</P>
<P>
   The study was reported in a recent issue of the Journal of
Personality and Social Psychology.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler said women also pay more attention to the problems of
friends, co-workers and distant relatives, while men tend to limit
their ``range of caring'' to their spouses and children. ``Men's
emotional antennae are not spread as wide,'' he said, adding, ``Men
get to participate in the good stuff, like parties, while their
wives pay the price for maintaining social networks.''
</P>
<P>
   The research challenges the idea that women are unhappy more
often because they ``hold onto bad feelings more,'' Kessler said.
Women appear no more likely than men to remain in a foul mood.
Wives have more bad days than husbands, said the report, simply
``because they experience more frequent daily stressors.''
</P>
<P>
   _ NANCY STEDMAN
</P>
<P>
   After the Addiction, a Matter of Weight
</P>
<P>
   The longest large study to date on weight gain after quitting
smoking has underscored what many researchers consider one of the
toughest obstacles facing smokers who want to stop.
</P>
<P>
   The Lung Health Study, which tracked 5,887 smokers, found that
those who quit put on substantially more weight in the years after
they kicked the habit _ 17 pounds for men and 19 pounds for women _
than earlier, shorter studies had indicated. The results were
published last month in the American Journal of Epidemiology.
</P>
<P>
   The first year is the worst. Of those who quit and stayed off
tobacco, the average weight gain was 10.7 pounds for men and 11.4
pounds for women.
</P>
<P>
   The heaviest smokers had the biggest weight gains, the
researchers found.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peggy O'Hare, a professor of public health and education at
Middle Tennessee State University in Murfreesboro and the lead
researcher, said in an interview that she did not view the results
as simply more bad news about the difficulties of quitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smokers already know this. Ex-smokers know this. I'm an
ex-smoker, and I know this,'' she said. ``I see the point as a
message to physicians and agencies that work with smoking cessation
about the need for a total approach to quitting, for a plan that
includes physical activity and diet control.''
</P>
<P>
   _ JOHN O'NEIL
</P>
<P>
   And, Oh, It Means `Go Back to Topic A'
</P>
<P>
   Most people _ linguists included _ ignore 10 percent of all
conversation, the ums, likes, false starts and repetitions that
litter spontaneous speech.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, these utterances were considered garbage that
hindered communication.
</P>
<P>
   But a study due to appear in the Journal of Memory and Language
argues that the word ``oh,'' when used in the middle of a sentence,
is not a bad habit but in fact plays a pivotal role in
comprehension.
</P>
<P>
   ```Oh' subconsciously alerts the listener to remember a
previously mentioned, but then abandoned, idea,'' said the study's
author, Dr. Jean Fox Tree, an assistant professor in the department
of psychology at the University of California at Santa Cruz. ``It
helps the listener piece together the concepts in the
conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Fox in her study asked 180 male and female students at Santa
Cruz to listen to tapes of unrehearsed speech. In one experiment,
subjects were told to push a button when they heard the name
``Roosevelt.'' They then listened to a speaker first discuss past
presidents and then switch to another topic.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker later returned to his original thought and then
said, ``Oh and Roosevelt,'' the prompt the subjects were told to
listen for. The second group heard only a pause _ the ``oh'' had
been digitally removed _ and then ``Roosevelt.''
</P>
<P>
   The group hearing the ``oh'' responded to ``Roosevelt'' more
quickly than the group that did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were writing and realized you had forgotten something,
you would just go back and insert it,'' Dr. Fox Tree explained.
``But you can't do that in speaking, so you say `oh,' to remind
your listener.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Fox Tree, who is also studying ``um'' and ``uh,'' said there
is a downside to her choice of research.
</P>
<P>
   ``My students tease me whenever I say `oh,''' she said. She
added, ``I don't understand why language presented to us by news
anchors or actors _ with this great enunciation and no disfluencies
_ is considered good, and the way we talk considered bad.''
</P>
<P>
   _WENDY MARSTON
</P>
<P>
   A Prescription Pad That Computes
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a cure for doctors' bad handwriting: the computer. When
doctors put down their pens and typed prescriptions into a
terminal, serious medication errors dropped by half, researchers at
Brigham and Women's Hospital have found.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of the drug reactions of almost 7,000 patients before
and after a $1.9 million computer system was installed at the
Boston hospital, researchers discovered a 55 percent drop in errors
after doctors ordered prescriptions online. The study was published
in a recent issue of the Journal of the American Medical
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Serious drug errors were those that injured, or had the
potential to injure, patients, the researchers explained. And drug
reactions are the most common cause of injury to hospitalized
patients, accounting for about 19 percent of the 1.3 million
injuries annually to those hospitalized, studies have shown.
</P>
<P>
   However, only about 5 percent of hospitals across the United
States have a computerized ordering system for doctors, the
researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years ago, nobody used ATMs, and now it's the routine
method of obtaining cash,'' said Dr. David Bates, an internist at
Brigham and Women's and a co-author of the study. ``My hope is that
this will increase the demand, and the hospitals will begin to
routinely adopt these systems.''
</P>
<P>
   The improvement can be credited to the efficiency of the system,
which was designed to provide a menu selection of medicines and
dosages and also to check patients' medical histories, drug
interactions and allergy problems.
</P>
<P>
   Getting rid of the doctors' illegible scribbling, Bates said,
had its benefits. ``When doctors wrote orders on paper, a high
percentage were logged as written by `doctor unknown' because the
pharmacy couldn't read the doctors' signatures,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``After implementing the computer system,'' Bates added, ``that
problem was eliminated.''
</P>
<P>
   _ CARLOS BRICENO
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
