<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5376 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-CLEMENCY-HNS &LR;      11-30 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-CLEMENCY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT CALIFORNIA GOVERNOR FACES SLEW OF DEATH-ROW DECISIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Although Gov.-elect Gray Davis would invoke
former Gov. Pat Brown's legendary name on the campaign trail, it's
unlikely Davis will follow Brown's path on one critical issue:
clemency for inmates on death row.
</P>
<P>
   Clemency was a decision so painful, Brown once wrote, that it
``took something out of me that nothing ... has ever been able to
replace.'' During his tenure, from 1959 to 1966, Brown commuted a
state record of 23 death sentences, including that of a man who was
released on parole and went on to kill again.
</P>
<P>
   As one of his first tasks in office, Davis could face a clemency
decision in the case of Jaturun Siripongs, convicted of killing an
Orange County store owner and a clerk. A hearing on Thursday may
decide whether Gov. Pete Wilson unfairly denied Siripongs clemency,
and the court's action could push the case past Jan. 4, when Davis
will be inaugurated.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens later this week, the notoriously slow appeal
process for death penalty cases is speeding up for the state's 517
death-row cases. Davis will undoubtedly have to consider more
capital cases than any other governor in more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   But in California and across the nation, the long-held
constitutional right of chief executives to bestow mercy through
clemency has died its own death, the victim of a political lethal
injection and a public that overwhelmingly supports the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 69 people set for execution so far this year in the
United States, only one was granted clemency, a Texas man who
confessed to 600 murders but was found to be in Florida during the
one killing for which he received the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   In this decade in the United States, one to three death-row
inmates have been granted clemency every year, out of as many as 80
executions each year.
</P>
<P>
   This is a dramatic shift from three decades ago, when governors
granted clemency in at least 20 percent of the death penalty cases
they reviewed, according to a 1993 University of Richmond study.
The study found, for example, that Florida governors had commuted
23 percent of death sentences between 1924 and 1966. No Florida
death penalty sentences have been commuted in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In California, death penalty attorneys say it is unlikely Davis
will change the modern trend set by Wilson. Wilson has denied all
five clemency requests that have reached his desk. A sixth killer,
David Edwin Mason, who was executed in 1993, did not ask for
clemency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea of clemency no longer exists in California,''
said Robert R. Bryan, a San Francisco attorney who has handled more
than 100 death-row cases. ``They give lip service to it, but it's a
joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Siripongs believed that they had a strong case for
clemency, but the Wilson administration declined to let them
present evidence that Siripongs had had an accomplice and had not
committed the actual murder.
</P>
<P>
   They did present evidence that Siripongs, 43, was remorseful and
was an exemplary prisoner of deep Buddhist faith. They noted that
the families of the victims, as well as a former San Quentin warden
and the Thai government, believed the death penalty was
inappropriate for Siripongs.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing Thursday, U.S. District Judge Maxine Chesney may
compel Wilson to reconsider his decision denying Siripongs
clemency, prompting the process to begin again and perhaps forcing
Davis to make the ultimate decision.
</P>
<P>
   In denying clemency, Wilson said Siripongs' reasons were not
enough: His ``remorse is infrequent, his callous crimes
unmitigated, his justifications nonexistent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His principal grounds for clemency _ an unfortunate childhood,
his good behavior while in confinement _ are inadequate and could
be invoked for nearly every death sentence,'' said Wilson, who is
retiring after two terms as governor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
