<HEADER>
A5384 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      11-30 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY DRANK THEIR MILK  
 ISOTOPE DATES QUAKES  
 SNIFFING OUT TERMITES  
 SALAMANDER MYSTERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Got milk?
</P>
<P>
   Researchers in Britain have figured out a way to tell if ancient
people got it, too.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, archeologists have had to rely on indirect evidence _
largely pictorial or written records _ that ancient cultures milked
domesticated cows or goats. Ceramic vessels found in excavations
often have a residue of animal fat, but because the fat has
degraded there has been no way to tell whether it had come from
meat or milk.
</P>
<P>
   But using gas chromatography, the scientists have shown that
degraded animal and milk fats have distinctive signatures related
to the relative abundance of a particular carbon isotope. The
researchers, reporting in a recent issue of Science, said they
found evidence of milk fat in pottery shards from an Iron Age Roman
site at Stanwick, England. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another group of scientists is using an isotope to delve into
history. But in this case the isotope is of chlorine, not carbon,
and the history is of the earth's surface, not its civilizations.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists, from the University of Arizona and Vanderbilt
University, have developed a method of dating earthquakes by
measuring trace amounts of chlorine-36 isotope on exposed rock in a
fault zone.
</P>
<P>
   Chlorine-36 is produced when the subatomic particles in cosmic
rays react with surface elements on the rock. The longer the rock
has been exposed, the more chlorine-36 will be produced. And
because the rate of cosmic ray bombardment is predictable for any
spot on earth, the approximate date that the rock was first exposed
by an earthquake can be calculated.
</P>
<P>
   The technique, described in a recent issue of Science, works
only in faults where the rock slips vertically in a quake, not
horizontally (as is the case with the San Andreas fault in
California).
</P>
<P>
   But applying the method to a vertical fault in Montana, the
researchers discovered evidence of six earthquakes, and dated them
as occurring about 400, 1,700, 2600, 7,000, 20,300 and 23,800 years
ago. They hope the technique can be used to provide information to
help predict quakes. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Termites, the scourge of wood-frame houses, are usually
discovered through inspection, and only after they have feasted
unnoticed on a beam here, a stud there, often for months or years.
</P>
<P>
   But scientists at Louisiana State University have come up with a
way to detect their presence early on, before they cause too much
structural damage. The detector makes use of a fact the researchers
recently discovered about termites: they smell like moth balls.
</P>
<P>
   More precisely, the scientists discovered that termites produce
naphthalene, an aromatic hydrocarbon that is the major component of
moth balls. (Apparently the termites use the chemical for much the
same reason humans do: as a defense against bugs.)
</P>
<P>
   The detector, now being developed, samples and analyzes the air
in building walls. When it senses naphthalene, it signals the
possible presence of termites. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The deaths of large numbers of salamanders in Utah, Maine and
North Dakota since summer have prompted United States Geological
Survey officials to issue an alert asking biologists to report
unusual observations of mortality or disease in the amphibians.
</P>
<P>
   The latest event occurred in September at a lake east of Salt
Lake City, where 200 dead tiger salamanders were found. Like
earlier die offs, a virus was believed responsible.
</P>
<P>
   The die offs are a concern because of recent sharp population
declines among many species of amphibians around the world. Among
the theories for the declines are a rise in viral, bacterial or
fungal infections, increased ultraviolet exposure because of a
thinning of the ozone layer and rising global temperatures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
