<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 1820EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981130.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5387 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDSVAX-TESTS-COX     11-30 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDSVAX-TESTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Researchers may have to skip goal of complete cure
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps Dr. Edward Jenner swallowed hard when he steadied the
syringe containing the deadly virus smallpox, just before he
injected the contents into 8-year-old James Phipps.
</P>
<P>
   Jenner must have been acutely aware that he was deliberately
imperiling the boy's life.
</P>
<P>
   The date was July 1, 1796, and Jenner was performing a daring
experiment that, if reproduced today, would shock and outrage our
1990s sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks previously, Jenner, a British surgeon, had
inoculated Phipps with fluid from the sores on a milkmaid's hand.
The sores were cowpox, a harmless disease in humans. Jenner had
noted that milkmaids and others who had cowpox did not suffer
smallpox.
</P>
<P>
   Neither did James Phipps.
</P>
<P>
   Jenner was lucky. HIV vaccine researchers know they will need
luck, too, if they are to meet President Clinton's goal of
developing a working HIV vaccine by 2007 _ a goal some think is
impossible or at least highly implausible.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 experimental HIV vaccines are being developed, but only
one, AIDSVAX, has entered Phase III, in which thousands of people
are being tested. In Phase I, a few dozen people are tested; in
Phase II, hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   Only one other HIV vaccine, based on the canarypox virus, is
expected to enter Phase III testing within the next year or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I very much believe that for the vaccine effort to succeed,
we're going to need a lot of vaccine concepts tested
systematically, in both primates and in people,'' said Sam Avrett,
executive director of the AIDS Vaccine Advocacy Coalition, based in
Washington. ``The question we should be asking is, `Why are there
not more products?'''
</P>
<P>
   Vaccine process costly
</P>
<P>
   Part of the answer has to do with economics, say researchers and
government health officials.
</P>
<P>
   Vaccines generally take longer and cost more to develop than
drugs, making them a high-risk venture for pharmaceutical
companies. The International AIDS Vaccine Initiative estimates that
developing and testing an experimental HIV vaccine will take seven
to eight years and cost more than $25 million. VaxGen Inc. expects
to spend ``tens of millions'' on its Phase III AIDSVAX trials, said
Dr. Don Francis, its president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't blame the companies for not doing more,'' said
Margaret Johnston, assistant director for AIDS vaccines at the
National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases in Bethesda,
Md. ``They're doing what they can, based on what they see as the
cost and benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   New HIV drugs are guaranteed instant demand, especially as drug
resistance forces people with HIV to frequently switch medicines.
And they are profitable: A year's worth of combination drug therapy
averages $10,000 to $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, such treatments are available only to people in
wealthy, industrialized countries. By contrast, the greatest need
for an HIV vaccine is in the Third World, where more than 90
percent of new infections occur.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't all about money. In pursuing HIV treatment advances,
pharmaceutical firms can use knowledge gleaned from the successes
and failures of existing HIV drugs, of which there are now 13.
</P>
<P>
   Vaccine research just isn't as advanced, and no clear
developmental path has been established.
</P>
<P>
   The rapidity of the epidemic's spread is so fearsome, though,
that most scientists would support an HIV vaccine that is only
partially effective. A 30 percent efficacy rate would mean at least
fewer new infections, they reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are used to the concept of vaccines that protect to a very
high level, but that may not work here,'' said Dr. Mark Feinberg,
associate director of AIDS research at Emory University's Rollins
School of Public Health(Ga.). Emory's newly built vaccine center
will open in March.
</P>
<P>
   But the real root of the lack of HIV vaccine research, lament
researchers, is that society still emphasizes treatment over
prevention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will pay tens, hundreds of thousands of dollars to treat
people once a disease hits, but we don't value prevention as
much,'' Johnston said. ``It's a societal thing. You can get people
treated for cancer, but having them change their diet or do things
to prevent cancer in the first place is very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Learning from failure
</P>
<P>
   Francis says he won't be satisfied ``until we have close to 100
percent (efficacy),'' but he realizes that the Phase III AIDSVAX
trial is probably an interim step toward that goal. He hopes the
tests will provide enough information to tweak the vaccine and
resolve any weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going under the presumption that we can spin the
technology around to fill the holes in the sieve,'' Francis said.
</P>
<P>
   Feinberg isn't as hopeful for AIDSVAX, because it generates only
one type of immune system response: antibodies that kill the virus
itself. Many vaccine researchers advocate a two-pronged approach
that also would eliminate infected human cells. Such a vaccine
would have to generate killer T-cells, immune system warriors that
recognize and destroy infected human cells.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Francis says he thinks AIDSVAX will work, based on studies
in chimpanzees and humans. An earlier version of AIDSVAX has been
given to 1,200 people, with some infections, but the new version is
expected to have greater success, since it is designed to resist
two different subtypes of HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Within the next year, 150 Atlanta volunteers will begin a series
of seven shots, the first two within a month of each other and the
remainder spaced at six-month intervals. Two out of every three
volunteers will receive AIDSVAX; the rest will get a placebo, an
inactive substitute.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many vaccines for diseases such as polio, measles and
rubella, AIDSVAX does not contain live, weakened virus. Instead, it
contains only a protein called gp120 that forms a key part of HIV's
outer envelope, or coat. The protein fools the body into believing
the virus itself is present, and the body's immune system
manufactures millions of antibodies.
</P>
<P>
   Even if AIDSVAX fails completely, researchers will have learned
something. But more likely the vaccine will work to at least some
extent. That is a necessary beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone shows that a vaccine is even partially effective,
that will do more to stimulate interest than any other activity,''
Johnston said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing that breeds success like success.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information
</P>
<P>
   These Internet sites have regularly updated information about
HIV vaccine research and trials:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  AIDS Vaccine Advocacy Coalition: http://www.avac.org
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  International AIDS Vaccine Initiative: http://www.iavi.org
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases,
Division of AIDS:
http://www.niaid.nih.gov/daids/vaccine/default.htm
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Vaccine Advocates: http://www.vactup.org
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
