<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-REPORTCARD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDS ADVOCATES GIVE U.S. A MIXED REPORT CARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal government scores high marks for
bankrolling AIDS research but rates poorly when it comes to pushing
prevention programs and helping developing nations battle the
deadly disease, the advocacy group AIDS Action reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years into the epidemic, America's record on AIDS
remain uneven,'' said Daniel Zingale, executive director of AIDS
Action. He said Africa is experiencing ``an AIDS holocaust because
of our failure to address prevention and international efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   A panel of AIDS advocates and health-care policy experts
including former U.S. Surgeon General Joycelyn Elders, former U.S.
Rep. Steve Gunderson, R-Wis., and Jeanne White, president of the
Ryan White Foundation, graded the federal government in four areas.
Gunderson is openly gay and the Ryan White Foundation is named
after a hemophiliac who died of AIDS after receiving an infected
blood transfusion.
</P>
<P>
   The panel gave the government an ``A-'' for AIDS research, a
``B'' for the care and treatment of people with AIDS, a ``D'' for
AIDS prevention and education efforts, and an ``F'' in the
international arena.
</P>
<P>
   The good news in the battle against AIDS is that the U.S. death
rate has dramatically plummeted because government- and
industry-sponsored research have produced effective new anti-viral
drugs and an entire new class of AIDS treatments known as protease
inhibitors.
</P>
<P>
   According to the federal Centers for Disease Control, the number
of U.S. deaths from AIDS fell 29 percent in 1996 from the previous
year and 47 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS fell from the eighth leading cause of death in the nation
in 1996 to the 14th in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But because most developing nations cannot afford the costly
drugs, the death rate from the disease is spiralling upward in the
Third World.
</P>
<P>
   According to a separate study released last week by the United
Nations, 2 million Africans will die from AIDS this year, four
times the total for the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   About two-thirds of the 33 million people around the globe who
are infected with HIV, the virus that causes AIDS, reside in
sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Botswana, Namibia, Swaziland and Zimbabwe, current
estimates show that between 20 percent and 25 percent of people
aged 15-49 are living with HIV or AIDS,'' said the U.N. report.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS Actions also charged that the U.S. government is doing
little domestically to halt the spread of HIV infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Official Washington has flat-funded domestic prevention and
has failed to launch new initiatives around HIV prevention and
education,'' Zingale said.
</P>
<P>
   Federally funded AIDS research receives about $1.5 billion
annually, while AIDS prevention programs receive approximately $657
million.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials acknowledge that prevention and education
efforts have lagged.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has not been the same focus on prevention as there is on
treatments,'' said Dr. Helene Gayle, director of the Center for
Prevention Services, part of the Centers for Disease Control.
</P>
<P>
   An ironic result of the highly effective new drug treatments is
that Americans are beginning to relax safe-sex behavior, Gayle
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People see folks with HIV living more normal lives and some
are saying, `I'd rather have my fun and worry about the
consequences later,''' Gayle said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
