<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HBOC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WebMD lands GilbertsonBy Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Less than two weeks after his high-profile departure
from HBO &AMP; Co., Jay Gilbertson was named Monday to a top slot at a
company part-owned by HBO &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbertson, who had been co-president, co-chief operating
officer and chief financial officer of HBO &AMP; Co., will be president
and chief operating officer of WebMD, a tiny but ambitious company
that aims to use the Internet to connect medical professionals and
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   During his decade with HBO &AMP; Co., which sells software and
services for the healthcare industry, Gilbertson saw the company
boom. Well-respected in the industry, he surprised analysts by not
resurfacing at an established company.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like hunting squirrel with an elephant gun,'' said
Charles Trafton of Adams Harkness. ``This is a guy who could write
his own ticket, so you have to believe (he thinks) this is the best
match for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilbertson said Monday that he looked at about 60 possible
employers, including some outside the area, before settling on
WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted a company that would give me the opportunity to lead
versus a company where I'd probably just run a division and not
have as big an impact,'' he said. ``WebMD could be very large very
quickly. I don't think there's a company out there that can touch
them.''
</P>
<P>
   While offering some consumer services, WebMD's Net site focuses
on doctors, who can verify patients' insurance coverage, read test
results, process claims, communicate with hospitals and order
supplies online.
</P>
<P>
   The Nov. 17 announcement of Gilbertson's split from HBO &AMP; Co.
was somewhat awkward because it came in the aftermath of word that
HBO &AMP; Co. had a $12.1 billion agreement to sell itself to McKesson
Corp., the nation's largest drug wholesaler. The deal seemed to
close out the chance of Gilbertson rising to the chief executive's
job. News of his exit sent HBO &AMP; Co. stock into a one-day slide.
But the stock price quickly recovered after Gilbertson _ and the
company _ reassured investors that his leaving was not a reflection
on HBO &AMP; Co.'s health.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbertson said Monday he harbors no ill will toward HBO &AMP;Co. A
good working relationship is important, since HBO &AMP;Co. has invested
$10 million in WebMD, owns 5 percent of the company and holds one
seat on the WebMD board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbertson said he took the WebMD post on the condition that the
current management team remain. However, with his arrival, Blake
Whitney will shift from president of WebMD to executive vice
president, specializing in new business applications. Whitney will
report to Gilbertson, said Jeff Arnold, WebMD's founder, chairman
and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD filed for an initial public offering of stock in the
spring, retreating when the market turned sour. Arnold, in New York
Monday to speak to analysts and potential investors, said an IPO
early next year is possible _ but not necessary. ``I like working
with strategic partners because they bring so much more than cash.
I am leaning in that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
