<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5406 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPACE-STATION-COX     11-30 1501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-STATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Assembly required: Hard-hats take on the final frontier
 &HT;    By Mike Toner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The space shuttle Endeavour is packed. The toolboxes are on
board. The first of a new generation of astronaut hard-hats are
ready to go to work. And 242 miles above the Earth, a Russian space
module called Zarya _ Sunrise _ awaits the dawn this week of the
most ambitious construction project in history.
</P>
<P>
   After 14 years of engineering, a half-dozen major redesigns and
a spiral of escalating costs, the assembly of the International
Space Station is about to begin.
</P>
<P>
   It's time, NASA Administrator Daniel Goldin says, to begin
``laying the foundation for a multinational permanent human
presence in space.'' Well past time, say critics in the scientific
community and in Congress, who have watched the station's
capabilities shrink as costs and delays have mounted. Completion is
now expected no earlier than 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the U.S. share of the new place in space is expected
to total at least $24.7 billion. Adding shuttle flights and
operational costs, the final tab is expected to reach $100 billion.
</P>
<P>
   For NASA, the start of space station assembly is a political as
well as a technological milestone. The presence of real hardware in
space will provide the agency new leverage in wresting money for
the project from a reluctant Congress. It's too late to turn back
now.
</P>
<P>
   This week, however, the focus is on the immediate challenge _
tool time in space. The final countdown began Monday. Liftoff of
the shuttle Endeavour from the Kennedy Space Center is set for 3:59
a.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Endeavour's six-person crew, commanded by veteran shuttle
astronaut Robert Cabana, will spend 12 days in space, assembling
the initial pieces of what will, over the next several years,
become a sprawling patchwork of modules and metal trusses that will
span the length of two football fields. Up close it will look a
little like a large hamster habitat. Completed, it will be large
enough to easily be visible from Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This flight will demonstrate the unique capabilities of the
space shuttle and of astronauts and cosmonauts to assemble large
structures in space,'' says George Abbey, the director of NASA's
Johnson Space Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The first hints of just how demanding the task will be will come
early next week, when Endeavor reaches the orbiting Russian module,
launched late last month, and the assembly work begins.
</P>
<P>
   Three demanding six-hour spacewalks will be required to attach
the waiting Russian module, which contains fuel and power for the
protostation, to the six-sided connecting node, called Unity, which
the shuttle will carry into space. Like the hub of a giant
Tinker-toy, the 13-ton node will serve as the connecting point for
future station modules.
</P>
<P>
   NASA visionaries weren't the first to imagine a permanently
manned outpost in space. That distinction goes to 19th century
clergyman and author, Edward Everett Hale, whose fictional ``brick
moon'' was populated by people who communicated with Earth by
jumping up and down in Morse code.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to preflight publicity about ``humankind's first
permanent extraterrestrial colony of orbiting pioneers,'' NASA
wasn't the first to build a space station either. Russia's Mir has
been circling the Earth 16 times a day since 1986 _ long enough to
outlast the nation, the former Soviet Union, that launched it.
</P>
<P>
   For well into the new millennium, however, both American and
Russian space programs will be, for better or worse, inextricably
wedded to the fate of the International Space Station.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes as planned, the crew, including Russian cosmonaut
Sergei Krikalev, will be home for the holidays, and the newly
joined Zarya and Unity modules will form the nucleus of a new era
in space.
</P>
<P>
   The upcoming mission, however, could be a cakewalk compared with
the challenges _ political as well as technical _ that the
station's 16 international partners will confront in the coming
years.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next six years, nearly a million pounds of hardware _
100 major components in all and countless nuts, bolts and
connecting cables _ must be delivered to the construction site in
the sky on time and in perfect condition.
</P>
<P>
   At least 45 U.S. and Russian launches, including 34 shuttle
flights, will be required to carry the building material and
supplies into orbit. Eighty percent of all shuttle flights between
now and 2005 will be devoted to station logistics. Any launch
failure, whether American or Russian, could be disastrous. For most
major parts, there are no spares.
</P>
<P>
   Some assembly will be required. Current estimates are that it
will require 1,800 hours of spacewalks _ as much as Russian and
American astronauts combined have logged outside the protection of
their capsules in the previous 40 years of human space travel.
</P>
<P>
   In the airless environment of space, where temperatures can vary
by 500 degrees from the shade to the sunlight, 30-ton pieces of
structural aluminum will have to be fitted together with
submillimeter precision - all while hardware, human work crews and
their tools hurtle around the Earth at 17,000 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The station is expected to be ready for limited occupancy, by a
crew of three, early in the year 2000. But the human presence
aboard the station will bring new risks.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Johnson Space Center analysis concludes that the
station is such a large target that damage from orbital debris or
meteoroids is inevitable. The same analysis concludes that there is
a one in 71 chance of losing the station over the course of its
10-year design life.
</P>
<P>
   Back on planet Earth, however, other problems must be resolved
if construction is going to proceed according to NASA's plan.
</P>
<P>
   The next major piece of hardware needed for the space station is
a Russian-built service module, which provides the navigation,
propulsion, communications and limited living space during the
construction phase. The module, two years behind schedule, is now
set for launch in July 1999, but the bankrupt Russian Space Agency
isn't expected to have it ready in time.
</P>
<P>
   NASA, which has paid $235 million for Zarya, has crafted a $1.2
billion program designed to complete the work on time. Growing
doubts about Russia's ability to deliver vital parts on time have
forced NASA to begin work on a temporary service module of its own.
It won't be ready by July either. Major delays could send the newly
linked Zarya and Unity plunging back into the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Sensenbrenner (R-Wis.), chairman of the House Science
Committee and an outspoken critic of Russia's failings, has fumed
that NASA is, in effect, paying ransom for components that were
supposed to be ``contributed'' by its major partner.
</P>
<P>
   But Russian space analyst James Oberg says NASA itself is
holding the station hostage with its ``foolhardy'' decision to
start assembly without assurances that the hardware for subsequent
missions would be ready on time. Some U.S.-built components,
including those made by prime contractor Boeing, also are behind
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   With the first pieces of the space station now in orbit,
however, Congress is likely to have trouble refusing expanded
station funding. The ante will be upped early next year when NASA
seeks an additional $1.2 billion for cost overruns _ on top of the
$2.1 billion now earmarked for the program.
</P>
<P>
   Even as station costs have soared, however, its capabilities
have been steadily downsized. Initial plans for the station to be a
staging area for missions to the moon and planets have long since
been abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, NASA now envisions the completed station as a permanent
base for the study of human adaptation to the space environment _
as well as a place for basic research on astronomy, microgravity
and materials science.
</P>
<P>
   But as the station's share of NASA's budget has grown, it has
had a devastating effect on the agency's other programs. A study by
the National Academy of Sciences has found an ``alarming'' decline
in NASA's basic space science research in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Many researchers contend that the station has cannibalized funds
that could have been used far more productively.
</P>
<P>
   The 40,000-member American Physical Society, a persistent critic
of the station, points out that the highly successful Pathfinder
mission to Mars in 1997 cost less than a single shuttle flight.
</P>
<P>
   After 14 years in the planning stages, however, NASA sees the
International Space Station as a triumph of politics as well as
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The International Space Station will be a world community
living and working together in space, improving life on Earth and
expanding humanity's horizons for the 21st century,'' says Goldin.
</P>
<P>
   ``In doing so, we will truly open the space frontier.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Toner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
