<HEADER>
A5408 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPACE-STATION-MISSION     11-30 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-STATION-MISSION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tool time in space: Job description daunting
 &HT;    By Mike Toner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If laying the cornerstone of the International Space Station can
be considered the act of any one person, the distinction probably
belongs to 39-year-old Nancy Currie, one of the six astronauts who
will be aboard the space shuttle Endeavour when it thunders into
space early Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   As a mission specialist for the flight, it will be Currie, at
the controls of the shuttle's mechanical arm, who first joins the
12.8-ton American-made connecting node, Unity, with the
Russian-built module that is in orbit. That union will mark the
formal start of a construction project expected to span at least
six years.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle's rendezvous with the Russian module Zarya, is
scheduled for Sunday, the third day of the mission. Sometime on
Saturday, Currie, who is on her third shuttle mission, will set the
stage for the crucial moment when she uses the remote manipulator
arm to upend the cylindrical connecting node in the shuttle's open
cargo bay.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, shuttle Commander Robert Cabana will guide the
Endeavour to within a few feet of the Russian module. Currie will
reach out with the 50-foot arm and grab the Russian module, pulling
it gently into position over Unity's docking ring.
</P>
<P>
   Cabana will then tweak the shuttle's thrusters, providing enough
of a push to firmly join the first two elements of the space
station.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next six days, mission specialists Jerry Ross and James
Newman will don their spacesuits and make three separate, six-hour
spacewalks to finish connecting the two modules to make them work
as a single unit _ the core of the new station.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule for the workweek in space goes like this:
</P>
<P>
   Monday: Ross and Newman go into the shuttle's cargo bay to
connect safety cables and electrical umbilical cables from Unity to
the space tunnel that will enable humans to pass from one module to
the other.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 8: The rest of the crew, including pilot Frederick Sturckow
and Russian cosmonaut Sergei Krikalev, conduct communications and
pressure checks on the docking system.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 9: Ross and Newman go back outside to install handrails and
antennae on the station modules and a sunshade for an external
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 10: Astronauts enter Unity and Zarya for the first time
through the tunnel connecting them to the shuttle. They install
fans, lights and communications equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 11: The crew again enters the protostation to check the
previous day's work and get it ready for the arrival next year of
the next major station element, the Russian service module.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 12: Ross and Newman perform a final spacewalk,
disconnecting all unnecessary cables and testing a spacesuit jet
backpack which failed on an earlier mission. A fully functioning
backpack system will be needed on future assembly flights.
</P>
<P>
   After disengaging from the station, Endeavour's crew will launch
several secondary payloads and perform a number of experiments
before returning to Earth on Dec. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Toner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
