<SLUG> BC-SCHRODER-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW NO-LONGER-A-KID ON THE BLOCK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Rick Schroder begins his run on ``NYPD Blue''
tonight, and you might as well check your misgivings at the door.
</P>
<P>
   Schroder, who made his name as a kid in ``The Champ'' and on
``Silver Spoons,'' shows up at the 15th Precinct as the third
partner of detective Andy Sipowicz (Dennis Franz) since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Mere mentions of his name in the same sentence as ``NYPD Blue''
often evoke panic or ridicule from fans of the series, who fear the
worst. But any doubts that Schroder can make the leap into grown-up
acting are erased moments after his character Danny Sorenson walks
into the squad room.
</P>
<P>
   An early scene in which Sorenson makes the acquaintance of Lt.
Arthur Fancy (James McDaniel) while the rest of the squad room
reacts is especially telling.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenson's first day coincides with detective Diane Russell's
(Kim Delaney) first day back after grieving over the loss of her
husband, detective Bobby Simone (Jimmy Smits). Sorenson is
transferred from the narcotics squad to replace Simone, who died
from an infection he contracted after receiving a heart transplant.
</P>
<P>
   In his first hour, Sorenson, a 28-year-old veteran of Operation
Desert Storm, has to walk the fine line of succeeding at his new
job and not offending his new co-workers still devastated by the
loss of Simone.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenson is a complex character who seems to get as annoyed when
a guy rides his bike on a sidewalk as he does when a gunshot victim
holds out information on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a lot going for him,'' Schroder said of Sorenson.
``He's a smart guy. He and Sipowicz have a different way of
approaching their job, but they are also very similar in a way.
They are both very committed to their job.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorenson is further from a strait-laced, by-the-book cop than
his crystal blue eyes and close-cropped military haircut would
indicate. He is savvy to the ways of the streets, has his own
contacts and wants to make the collar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who comes into the pokey tries to use a different
angle on him,'' Schroder said. ``Sometimes he's as sweet as honey,
and sometimes he's an absolute badass who is in their face.
Everyone wants to give it up a different way. The trick is to find
out how the guy in front of you is going to break.''
</P>
<P>
   If tonight's show is any indication, the addition of Sorenson
should help pump new life into a series that was showing its age
last season.
</P>
<P>
   So far, thanks to a compelling story arc revolving around
Simone's tragic demise, ``NYPD Blue'' already seems back in the
groove.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after spending four weeks in a vacuum (he has already
filmed four episodes that no one has seen), Schroder finally gets
his shot tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has seen anything I've done yet,'' he said. ``I can't
wait to see the reaction. Depending on the reaction, maybe I can
wait.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't have anything to worry about.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
