<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETANYAHU STOPS SHORT OF UNCONDITIONALLY WITHDRAWING TROOPS FROM
LEBANESE SOIL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said
Monday that he felt the pain of every mother whose son had died
fighting in Lebanon, but stopped short of siding with those who
would withdraw troops from Lebanese soil unconditionally now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our heart is with every mother and every person who has
suffered,'' Netanyahu told Israel Radio. ``(But) we have the
responsibility to do the right thing for the state of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   The deaths of seven young soldiers in Lebanon in the past two
weeks have added urgency to an on-going debate here: Should Israel
unilaterally withdraw troops from a self-declared ``security zone''
set up in southern Lebanon in 1985 or should it stay put until an
agreement is reached with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Israel's parliamentary defense and foreign affairs
committee met Monday to discuss that question and, in the meantime,
how Israel should respond to the upsurge in casualties from
roadside bombs placed by the Hezbollah, Iranian-backed guerrillas
who want to force Israel to withdraw from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   During what turned into a stormy meeting, Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai ruled out moving troops from the 10-mile-wide
zone without some kind of negotiated settlement that would
guarantee the security of Israel's northern border.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the opinion of security officials after they examined
all the possibilities,'' Mordechai said after convening top army
officers for an emergency meeting late Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai's statement prompted a sharp response from Yossi
Beilin, an opposition Labor member of the parliamentary committee
who has been pushing for unilateral withdrawal from Lebanon for
more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Beilin walked out of the committee meeting slamming the door and
called Mordechai a ``liar'' and Israel's policy in Lebanon a
``death trap.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nonsense,'' Beilin huffed. ``There are many (Israeli)
generals who believe we must leave this area and I'm sure the
minister (Mordechai) knows it.''
</P>
<P>
   Every time Israel sustains heavy casualties in Lebanon, a nation
weary of what seems like a costly no-win situation reexamines the
possibility of a quick exit from its northern neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, a growing number of Israelis seem to be siding
with Beilin in favor of unilateral withdrawal. An opinion polls
published by the daily newspaper Maariv found that 40 percent want
to leave Lebanon now, up from just 22 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
   These Israelis are willing to take a calculated risk: by
withdrawing from Lebanon without an agreement on security
arrangements, they are betting that the Hezbollah will have reached
its objective and will not launch rockets into northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, superhawk Ariel Sharon, Israel's foreign
minister, has moved toward this camp. He wants to implement a
unilateral troop withdrawal, but in stages. If there is peace after
an initial withdrawal , he says, more troops will leave. If not,
the gradual pullout will not proceed. And if, after the withdrawal
is complete, Hezbollah strikes Israel's northern border, Israel
will respond with a heavy attack.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli analysts say both Beilin's and Sharon's calls for
unilateral withdrawal might win over the public, but they fail to
address the underlying cause of Israel's recurrent problems in
Lebanon: Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Until Israel is willing to return the Golan Heights, a grass and
snow-capped mountainous plateau captured from Syria in 1967, it can
expect Syrian President Hafez Asad to pressure Israel by unleashing
the Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows is that the address, the solution, the key, is
Damascus and the price is the Golan Heights,'' said Moshe Maoz, a
political analyst at the Moshe Dayan Center for Middle Eastern and
African Studies and a leading Israeli expert on Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can overlook this very hard reality,'' said Maoz. ``But
the government tries to overlook this because it is unpopular to
talk about negotiating the Golan Heights. There is no military
solution, only a political solution.''
</P>
<P>
   By adopting a phased withdrawal, Sharon said he hopes to isolate
the conflict with Lebanon from the Israeli-Syrian negotiating
track. The negotiations have been at a standstill for three years
over whether to resume talks based on verbal understandings reached
with Israel's previous Labor-led government or to restart them
without preconditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel wants peace negotiations with Syria ... but we cannot
link negotiations with Syria with what is happening with Lebanon,''
Sharon said on Sunday. ``The two issues must be separated.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, other Israeli ministers backed limited
airstrikes against Lebanon's infrastructure, including its power
and water supplies, if that government failed to reign in
Hezbollah. Such a task is not likely, analysts say, with 35,000
Syrian troops based in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Netanyahu said only that Israel's priority would be
to ensure the safety of Israeli soldiers and its ally, the South
Lebanon Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we don't have a way of leaving Lebanon in an
arrangement that will guarantee the safety of northern Israel, our
main objective is to protect Israeli soldiers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's Army Radio reported Monday that Asad had reiterated his
call to pick up negotiations with Israel where they left off three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The radio, citing U.S. officials, said President Clinton was
working to revive the moribund talks and had sent a message to Asad
asking whether the Syrian leader was willing to resume
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu denied knowledge of any message and said again that he
would not start negotiations based on verbal understandings or
proposals for territorial compromise and for security arrangements
that were made by his predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are prepared to enter into renewed negotiations with Syria
but we are not prepared to accept dictation of terms that in fact
empty the negotiations of all content,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Horan is a free-lance journalist based in Jerusalem. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
