<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON TOP OF THE WORLD IN THE SAN FRANCISCO BAY AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Lately I've been reading ``Into Thin Air,'' the
wrenching first-person account of an expedition that takes the
reader to Mount Everest and back, with a stream of bodies left
behind along the way.
</P>
<P>
   In the San Francisco Bay area, up on the summit of my favorite
mountain, Montara Mountain, I kept thinking about how beautiful,
diverse and engaging this region is (even compared to the
Himalayas) with the Bay, coast and ocean circled by a greenbelt and
a mountain rim featuring a series of peaks that is accessible to
nearly everybody.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody ever says Everest is fun. In the Bay area, hitting all
the peaks is fun.
</P>
<P>
   At Mount Everest, what is called the ``Death Zone'' starts at
25,000 feet, where the air is so thin that the capillaries in your
retinas can explode without warning. In the Bay area, the most
dangerous part of the trip is the drive to the trail head, and the
only things that are eye-popping are the views.
</P>
<P>
   Everest, at 29,028 feet, is called the Roof of the World, and it
can only be climbed with a degree of hope during a few days in
spring and fall, when a 100-knot jet stream and procession of
storms shift away from the peak. The weather in the Bay area, on
the other hand, makes it one of the few regions anywhere in North
America where you can reach your choice of several summits 365 days
a year.
</P>
<P>
   It can cost $75,000 for a guided trip on Everest. It costs $4 to
try Montara Mountain (from San Pedro Valley County Park), $5 for
Mount Tam, and Mount Hamilton is free.
</P>
<P>
   Here are my ratings of the best of them, 1 to 5, considering
views, scope of adventure, and fun, along with five honorable
mentions, rated 6 to 10:
</P>
<P>
   1. Mount Tamalpais, 2,571 feet.
</P>
<P>
   At dawn or dusk, the Bay Area looks like the Land of Oz from the
East Peak, one of the top lookouts in North America; from here, you
can see why so many call San Francisco ``The Emerald City,'' a
phantasmal vision of lights. To the east, the Bay looks like a calm
azure pool sprinkled with islands, and Mount Diablo beyond seems so
massive that it's as if you could take a flying leap across the Bay
and land on its top. Though people pray for clear sunsets, it is
often even prettier when a sea of fog is layered over the Pacific
to the west, where the orange light can filter through the stratus.
Oz? ``Pay no attention to that man standing behind the curtain.''
Hiking demands: A 15-minute walk, with a climb of 330 feet to a
lookout station perched on rock. (For information, call
415-388-2070 or 415-893-1580).
</P>
<P>
   2. Montara Mountain, 1,894 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The next time you think the Bay area is jammed full, make the
trip to San Pedro Valley County Park in south Pacifica, then relish
the 7-mile round trip to the Montara Mountain summit and back. In
the process, you will pass Brooks Falls, a thin, three-tiered
waterfall (a wisp most of the time), a nearby lookout of the coast
(from an obvious rock outcrop, looking north), then the tromp to
the top for a long-distance view of the Farallon Islands out to
sea, the south coast, and an adjoining 100,000 acres of wildlands,
including the off-limits San Francisco Fish and Game Refuge. Note
that the hike is far more demanding from the opposite flank, with
access from McNee Ranch State Park. Hiking demands: 7-mile round
trip, moderate grade, sea level to summit. (650-355-8289).
</P>
<P>
   3. Castle Rock, 3,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   For a fresh perspective across familiar territory, try the view
from the top of Goat Rock. You scan across miles of Douglas fir and
redwoods, Big Basin and beyond to Monterey Bay, one of the region's
most beautiful landscapes. This is the highlight at Castle Rock
State Park, located on Skyline Boulevard (Highway 35), just south
of the junction with Highway 9. Unlike the other top summits, you
hike down, not up, past a waterfall (quite dramatic after a big
rain), then loop up to the top of Goat Rock, a honeycombed
sandstone formation popular among rock climbers, and the best
picnic spot in the Bay area. Hiking demands: 5 1/2-mile round trip,
easy, out on Saratoga Gap Trail, return on Ridge Trail.
(408-867-2952 or 831-429-2851).
</P>
<P>
   4. Mount Hamilton, 4,209 feet.
</P>
<P>
   This is the highest drive-to point in the Bay area. The Mount
Hamilton Observatory is at the top, and the views are unique and
spectacular. To one side, you look down and across the Santa Clara
Valley and its wall-to-wall congestion. To the other side is
country so remote and wild that herds of wild goats and elk are
sometimes spotted. Getting here is a great driving tour, providing
you don't mind the twisties. From Alum Rock in San Jose, the road
winds all over the foothills in its climb to the Mount Hamilton
summit, a route originally designed when the observatory was
selected in order to ease the effort required for horses towing
supply wagons. The road continues down the east flank into
wilderness, and eventually links to Mines Road and continues all
the way to Livermore. Hiking demands: None. (408-274-5061).
</P>
<P>
   5. Mount Diablo, 3,849 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The time to go to Mount Diablo is in the winter after a fresh
storm, when the air is crystal clear. That is when you get
unlimited visibility: a clear view of the Sierra Crest to the east,
and the Farallon Islands to the west. The actual area _ in square
miles _ visible from this lookout is greater than from any other in
Northern California, but the best views are distant, ruined by much
haze. The visitor center perched on the exact summit is one of the
best anywhere. Hiking demands: None required (but a good trail head
to Diablo's sub-peak is available about a quarter-mile below the
parking area). (925-837-2525).
</P>
<P>
   Honorable mentions: 6. Mission Peak, Fremont, 2,517 feet,
(510-635-0135, ext. 2200); 7. Wildcat Peak, Berkeley hills, 1,211
feet (510-635-0135, ext. 2200); 8. Mount Umunhum (Bald Mountain),
Los Gatos, 3,486 feet, (650-691-1200); 8. Monument Peak, Milpitas,
2,594 feet, (408-262-6980); 10. San Bruno Mountain, (true summit is
off limits), 1,314 feet (415-587-7511).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
