<HEADLINE>
TEXAS GOV. BUSH PRAISES ISRAEL AS `COUNTRY OF GENIUS' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Sounding more like a presidential candidate than
he's willing to admit, Texas Gov. George W. Bush Monday praised
Israel as a ``country of genius'' and avoided a brewing controversy
by canceling a planned trip to a West Bank Jewish settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been wonderful to see first hand not only the challenges
facing Israel, but also the opportunities,'' Bush said at a dinner
hosted by Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel is a country of genius, Israel's got tremendous
talent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His comments capped a day of meetings with Israeli government
officials, including Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon and Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, on his second day of a three-day visit
to Israel. He also held talks with opposition Labor leader Ehud
Barak and former Prime Minister Shimon Peres.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, Bush visited Jerusalem Mayor Ehud Olmert, laid a
wreath at the grave site of the late Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin
and visited Israel's Holocaust museum, Yad Vashem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very powerful,'' Bush said after seeing the museum dedicated
to the 6 million Jews who perished during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   He also visited Jerusalem's walled Old City, where he toured the
Church of the Holy Sepulchre, built over the site where most
Christians believe Jesus was buried, and the Western, or Wailing,
Wall, Judaism's holiest site.
</P>
<P>
   At the Wall, Bush was greeted by a crowd of U.S. tourists,
including several from Texas, who waved, snapped pictures and shook
his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little surprised to see him at the Wailing Wall,''
said Dwight Burgess, a travel agent from Dallas who was wearing a
Rangers baseball cap. Bush formerly had a financial interest in the
Dallas team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised at all the warmth he got from the people,
Israelis and Americans alike,'' Burgess said, adding that he hoped
Bush would run for president.
</P>
<P>
   Bush continued to remain tight-lipped about whether he would
seek the GOP presidential nomination. He also sidestepped questions
that might shed light on what his policy in the Middle East would
be if he were to win the White House in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relationship between Israel and the U.S. is a very special
relationship,'' was all he would say. ``It will always be that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's father, former President George Bush, was often at odds
with Israel over the issue of Israeli settlements in the West Bank
and Gaza, one of the most difficult issues facing Israelis and
Palestinians in their quest to make peace.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials said privately that they had hoped that the
younger Bush would offer a glimpse into whether he would follow his
father's policy.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, traveling with other governors from Massachusetts, Utah
and Montana, was invited by the National Jewish Coalition, a
Republican lobby group that holds views on the peace process
similar to Netanyahu's conservative government.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the group had been scheduled to visit two West Bank
settlements, Alfei Menashe in the northern West Bank and Kochav
Hashachar in the Jordan Valley. The plans were canceled, apparently
at the urging of the Clinton administration after Palestinians
objected, according to an Israeli official in the foreign ministry.
</P>
<P>
   The itinerary, organized by the NJC, did not include a visit
with any Palestinian official. An NJC member said the group had
tried but failed to fix a meeting with Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat, who is in Washington this week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Horan is a free-lance journalist based in Jerusalem. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
