<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: Georgia GOP have trouble with direction
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a sense, the identity crisis in which the Georgia
Republican Party finds itself this holiday season has been made
worse by political science.
</P>
<P>
   By now there are textbooks full of graphs showing the steady
rise of Republican influence in the state and the region, lending
to an assumption of inevitability that took a hard rapping in the
past election.
</P>
<P>
   The party lost with Guy Millner leading the ticket for a third
time, but this time the margin of defeat widened considerably. For
the first time in the decade it lost seats in the Legislature: one
in the House and probably one in the Senate, depending on the
outcome in the 38th District, whose weary voters trudge to the
polls again today in another effort to sort out that confusing
situation, and pending legal action in the disputed 53rd Senate
district
</P>
<P>
   While nothing disastrous in terms of the statistical curve,
these setbacks, in combination with Newt Gingrich's surprise
departure, leave the Republicans contemplating a future not
forecast in the graphs. With the Democrats positioned to control
the next redistricting, the uncertainty suddenly extends into the
next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans looked forward to having one of their own as
the governor's floor leader in the Senate. But few would ever have
guessed that the Republican, Sen. Charlie Tanksley of Cobb County,
would be handling legislation for a Democrat _ his law partner,
Gov.-elect Roy Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   Tanksley said Monday his new post gives him an opportunity to be
involved in policy-making that a Republican wouldn't otherwise
have.
</P>
<P>
   Tanksley said Barnes's position on issues such as property tax
relief and giving businesses a moratorium on paying unemployment
taxes are ``consistent with what a lot of Republicans think should
be done.''
</P>
<P>
   While this may bode well for the next administration, it
underscores the difficulty the Republicans, so confident of their
direction throughout most of this decade, currently have in finding
their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The direction of the party is really up in the air, and I'm
not sure we really understand what the problem really was in the
past election,'' Tanksley said. One subject on which Tanksley has
differed with others in his party is affirmative action, sure to be
a prime topic in the soul-searching.
</P>
<P>
   It's a time for the party to re-evaluate its leadership ``from
top to bottom,'' departing state chairman Rusty Paul said Monday.
Paul, who has signed on with Steve Forbes' presidential campaign,
is supporting Florida chairman Tom Slade's bid to unseat Republican
national chairman Jim Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   Paul's decision not to seek another term next May helps the
soul-searching along in Georgia by throwing open the state
chairmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Several names already are being tossed around as possibilities,
including three refugees from this year's lieutenant governor's
race: Sen. Chuck Clay, Rockdale Commission Chairman Randy Poynter
and former Sen. Clint Day. Fulton GOP chairman Ron Jackson and
party vice chair Linda Herren have also been mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter is a political editor for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
