A5444 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENSUS-COX     11-30 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2000 census creates dissention between Clinton administration,
House GOP, firm
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An Atlanta public interest law firm and House
Republicans asked the U. S. Supreme Court Monday to bar the Census
Bureau from using certain estimates in the 2000 census even if they
prove to be more accurate than a traditional head count.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration wants to use scientific sampling to
get a better count of minorities and other hard-to-reach groups,
which could boost the population totals for Atlanta and other big
cities that claimed to have been shortchanged in the 1990 census.
</P>
<P>
   The once-a-decade census helps determine each state's
representation in Congress, the drawing of electoral boundaries and
the distribution of more than $175 billion in federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   Solicitor General Seth Waxman, arguing on behalf of the
administration, told the justices that every census since 1790 has
been an estimate of the population since no census has physically
reached every person in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Sampling, the use of a randomly selected cross-section of the
population to estimate the entire population, would be a ``quality
check'' on the accuracy of the Census Bureau's more traditional
methods of trying to count every American household through
mailings and follow-up visits, Waxman said.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing the Census Bureau to use sampling ``will best achieve
the Constitution's goal of determining the number of persons in
each state,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the House of Representatives and a group of
individuals that includes Matthew Glavin, president of the
Southeastern Legal Foundation, and Rep. Bob Barr agreed that no
census is likely to count everyone.
</P>
<P>
   But, they argued, the Court should uphold lower court rulings
that blocked the sampling plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of accuracy, it is both illegal and
unconstitutional,'' said Michael Carvin, who represents Glavin and
Barr in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 100 percent head count is the only permissible means of
apportioning the population,'' Carvin said.
</P>
<P>
   The census will begin April 1, 2000, in traditional fashion with
the mailing of census forms to every known household in America.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau expects about two-thirds of those households
to respond. Intensive follow-up efforts are intended to bring the
response rate up to 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The sampling plan would estimate the population of the remaining
10 percent of the households based on the characteristics of
similar households that did fill out census forms.
</P>
<P>
   A second rigorous survey of 750,000 households across the
country would allow the Census Bureau to adjust the population
totals.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's rationale perplexed several justices.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you know what the 'true number' is,'' if the Census
Bureau is producing an estimate of the population, Chief Justice
William Rehnquist asked Waxman.
</P>
<P>
   When Waxman sought to assure him that the bureau's estimates
would be very accurate, Rehnquist responded, ``Why do we have a
census then?''
</P>
<P>
   He knew the answer: the Constitution requires one.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Mahoney, who represents the House of Representatives,
found herself arguing against counting the residents of an
apartment who did not fill out a census form and never answered a
knock on the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can put down zero?'' Justice John Paul Stevens asked.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney replied, ``That's right.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Stephen Breyer provoked laughter in the august courtroom
when he chimed in, ``You mean even if the lights go on and off each
evening?''
</P>
<P>
   While both sides passionately argued the merits of their case,
they also spent a good deal of time on a more technical issue that
could prove decisive for the court.
</P>
<P>
   Waxman argued that neither the House nor Glavin and his group
has the right, or standing, to sue at this point because the census
has yet to be taken and no damage has yet been done that could give
rise to a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared to find some support among the justices, including
Justice Antonin Scalia, who expressed his distaste for mediating a
dispute between the executive and legislative branches of
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 900 ways to stymie the president if the House has
the political will to do it,'' including cutting off funding for
the Census or other programs that are important to the White House,
Scalia said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers on both sides said they hope to receive a ruling by late
winter, which would give the Census Bureau barely a year to make
its final preparations for the census.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision, however, is unlikely to be the final act
in the census dispute.
</P>
<P>
   While expressing confidence his side would win, Glavin said that
if the court rules for the administration, ``We'll be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
