<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5445 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUBRIANT-COLUMN29-COX     11-30 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUBRIANT-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A tour of Southern backroads finds downhome cooking alive and
well
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, scholars have been telling us that the South is
becoming as homogenized as the rest of the country because of
television and cookie-cutter malls.
</P>
<P>
   Well, there are Wal-Marts and McDonald's in every town big
enough to have two traffic lights, but regional cuisine is still as
distinctive as fingerprints or biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't believe that, then you haven't eaten the Cajun
peppered shrimp at the Blue Desert Cafe in Cedar Key, Fla., or the
roast beef and ``debris'' po-boys at Mother's in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention the chitlins and fried fatback at the Toot-N-Tell
in Garner, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Like others who rarely leave the interstates when traveling, I
didn't realize how much the food varies from state to state until I
embarked on a 25,000-mile tour of the South to write ``Backroad
Buffets and Country Cafes,'' a guidebook to meat-and-threes and
other places where the local folks eat.
</P>
<P>
   I was looking for restaurants where conscientious cooks still
peeled and mashed real potatoes and pan-fried chicken, where banana
pudding was a
</P>
<P>
   staple and the meringue on the homemade pies was as high as the
waitresses' hairdos.
</P>
<P>
   What I discovered was as eye-opening as it was mouthwatering.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, there is an explosion of all-you-can-eat
catfish-and-chicken restaurants and seafood buffets where you can
gorge yourself for $10 or so. Southerners _ and apparently
Northerners, too _ love to get their money's worth. The closest
thing I have seen to these gatherings is a shark feeding frenzy on
the Discovery Channel.
</P>
<P>
   For noonday meals, fried chicken and country fried steak are
still the mainstays in most meat-and-threes, but several restaurant
owners insist that turkey or baked chicken and corn bread dressing
are their most popular offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Hush puppies are a mystery and vary from state to state. Some,
particularly in North Carolina, are sweet and yeasty and the shape
of an index finger, while others in the South are round lumps with
lots of onion bits and no sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Tamales are another enigma. I mistakenly thought you had to go
to Texas or the Southwest to get tamales, but these Mexican
delicacies are regularly eaten in Mississippi and Arkansas. At
Doe's Eat Place, a disreputable-looking establishment in
Greenville, Miss., they are served by the dozens, along with
28-ounce steaks, to a clientele that includes senators and
congressmen as well as construction workers.
</P>
<P>
   And at McClard's Bar-B-Q in Hot Springs, Ark., they offer
tamales as a side dish to their spicy ribs. Bill Clinton, by the
way, used to eat at McClard's frequently when he was in elementary
school.
</P>
<P>
   Why tamales? Marcia Schnedler, a food critic in Arkansas, says
they are the result of Italian and Mexican grandpas and grandmas
trading recipes while working on a Mississippi Delta farm in the
early 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   Besides serving good local cuisine, many of these establishments
provide colorful glimpses into Southern culture. The Bell Buckle
Cafe in Bell Buckle, Tenn., for example, features a live radio show
every Saturday night with local country and blues singers. And at
the Lantern Inn in Cumming, Ga., Mike Jones does triple duty as a
garbage collector by day and an Elvis impersonator and cook by
night.
</P>
<P>
   After frying up a batch of catfish and chicken, Jones dons black
leather for the early show and performs an act from the early Elvis
days, before too many fried peanut-butter-and-mashed-banana
sandwiches went to his love handles. After an intermission, Jones
returns as the Vegas Elvis in a white sequined jumpsuit singing,
``I can cook a hunka, hunka burning catfish.''
</P>
<P>
   You can't find that kind of combination of food and
entertainment just anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But there were some sad notes. Cracklin' corn bread, that
Southern delicacy laced with bits of fried hog fat, is practically
extinct. (Harold's Barbecue in Atlanta still has it, but few others
do.) Lard is not used nearly as frequently as it used to be, and
sweet tea is not universally available in every restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that in a region once beset with racial
turmoil, I discovered that food, among other things, has helped
break down barriers. In Carrboro, N.C., for example, there's a
little restaurant called Country Junction where the owners and
cooks are Chinese and the customers are a melting pot of
socioeconomic and ethnic groups. The one thing they have in common
is a taste for Southern vegetables at a cheap price.
</P>
<P>
   In Wilson, N.C., Ed Mitchell, a successful African-American
barbecue entrepreneur, explained that when blacks and whites,
Democrats and Republicans come into his restaurant, they break
bread together and forget their differences for at least an hour,
maybe longer. ``All the titles and pedigrees are left at the
door,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   I think he's onto something. It's hard to be angry with someone
from another race or political party when you're both sitting in a
cafe eating barbecue that practically melts in your mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
