<SLUG> BC-SPACE-STATION-ASSEMBLY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A place in space: Some facts about the International Space
Station
 &HT;    By Mike Toner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPACE STATION FACTS:
</P>
<P>
   _ The space station will circle the Earth once every 92 minutes.
As it is expanded, it will be visible from the ground _ reflecting
enough sunlight to be visible as a bright point of light moving
across the night sky.
</P>
<P>
   _ A crew of three hopes to occupy the partially completed
station in the year 2000. Later, the station will be able to
accommodate up to seven people. NASA's emergency escape, the X-38,
won't be ready until at least 2003. In the meantime, crews will
keep a Russian Soyuz capsule on hand as a standby ``lifeboat.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Upon completion, the station will have a mass of 470 tons,
nearly one million pounds. The solar panels will cover an area of
more than a half-acre. The interior living space will be the
equivalent of a 747 jumbo jet.
</P>
<P>
   _ More than 100,000 people have been involved in planning and
building the space station. Several key components, including two
connecting nodes and the U.S. laboratory module and the joint
airlock, were manufactured at the Marshall Space Flight Center in
Huntsville, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   _ The space station is the largest international program ever
undertaken in space. The U.S. partners are Belgium, Brazil, Canada,
Denmark, France, Germany, Italy, Japan, Netherlands, Norway,
Russia, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland and the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   _ The station's electrical power system contains eight miles of
wiring. There will be 52 computers to control power, flight
orientation, heat, light, and other critical concerns. And there
are four windows, at least one of which will always afford a view
of the Earth below.
</P>
<P>
   _ Starting this month, two flight control rooms _ one at NASA's
Johnson Space Center in Houston and one outside Moscow _ will be in
contact with the space station 24 hours a day for as long as it
remains in orbit.
</P>
<P>
   More about the Space Station on the Internet:
</P>
<P>
   The Space Station's current location right now:
</P>
<P>
   http://liftoff.msfc.nasa.gov/temp/StationLoc.html
</P>
<P>
   The International Space Station (NASA):
</P>
<P>
   http://www.shuttlepresskit.com/ISSOVR/index.htm
</P>
<P>
   The Space Station (Boeing):
</P>
<P>
   http://www.boeing.com/defense-space/space/spacestation/
</P>
<P>
   Space Station photo gallery:
http://station.nasa.gov/gallery/index.html
</P>
<P>
   Video of Space Station processing room at the Kennedy Space
Center:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.ksc.nasa.gov/payload/missions/station/sspf-video.html
</P>
<P>
   Mike Toner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
