<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5453 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ARAFAT-HNS &LR;      11-30 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ARAFAT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON BOLSTERS MIDEAST PEACE PROCESS WITH $400 MILLION AID
PACKAGE TO PALESTINIANS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton sought to bolster the Middle East
peace process Monday as he proposed a U.S. aid package of $400
million to Palestinians and downplayed renewed strains between
Chairman Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been bumps in the road, to be sure, but the
agreement is on track, and we must keep it on track,'' Clinton told
representatives of 50 nations and organizations convened at the
State Department. The U.S.-led conference generated $3 billion in
pledges to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Clinton met in the Oval Office with Arafat who enraged
Israelis this weekend by again voicing hopes for creating a
Palestinian state next year. Netanyahu dismissed Arafat's statehood
comments as ``serious and insufferable.''
</P>
<P>
   Talks between the two sides were called off after Israel balked
at releasing more Palestinian prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will fly to the Middle East Dec. 12 to urge the
Palestinian National Council to revoke language in its charter
calling for Israel's destruction. Clinton will be the first
president to visit the Gaza Strip and the West Bank territories now
partially controlled by Arafat's forces.
</P>
<P>
   The donors conference here comes on the heels of the Wye River
Memorandum reached after marathon negotiations between Clinton,
Arafat and Netanyahu at the Maryland conference center last month.
The accord revived stalled Middle East peace talks as Israel agreed
to cede more territory to the Palestinians in return for crackdowns
on terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chairman Arafat reaffirmed his pledge to uphold his side of
the agreement and to work with Israeli authorities to promote
Israel's security. I promised the continuing support of the United
States as we move ahead in the next phase of the peace process.
That phase begins today with this conference,'' Clinton said.
``Today, our purpose is to send a clear signal that this peace is
more than a piece of paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he will work with Congress to craft a $400 million
package to help Palestinians create jobs, to improve education, to
improve access to water and to support the rule of law. The amount
will be in addition to the annual $100 million in support from the
United States, Clinton said. The United States currently provides
more than $3 billion a year to Israel and pledged an increase to
help with security needs.
</P>
<P>
   The donors' conference netted $3 billion in pledges from the
representatives of other nations and organizations for development
in the Palestinian controlled territories.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said this was ``the
beginning of a process which will turn words on paper into
contracts, construction sites and commerce in the West Bank and
Gaza, and throughout the Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the initial 1993 peace accord, international commitments
have totaled $4 billion but only half the amount has actually been
disbursed.
</P>
<P>
   ``No peace stands a chance of lasting if it does not deliver
real results to ordinary people. Our challenge today, therefore, is
to do more to deliver these results and to do it sooner rather than
later,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the first peace accord was signed in 1993, there has been
``too little tangible improvement'' for Palestinians, Clinton said,
noting income is down and unemployment is up. ``Living conditions
are extremely difficult,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton encouraged the representatives to also do their part to
make contributions to economic development in the region.
Palestinians also are working to construct several industrial parks
as well as a seaport at Gaza. An airport opened there several weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters were allowed to attend the conference and listen to
Clinton speak, but were forced to leave before Arafat made his
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   According to a draft copy of Arafat's speech, he told the
potential donors that Israel bears much of the blame for the poor
Palestinian economy because of its ``continued siege and frequent
closure'' of borders into Gaza and the West Bank. Israel repeatedly
has closed its borders following terrorists attacks, a move that
also bars Palestinian workers from their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israeli closure policy is the primary and direct cause for
the dangerous decline in the performance of the Palestinian economy
over the past five years,'' Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Arafat spoke to the Arab-American Institute, inviting
guests to the region in celebration of Christmas and the upcoming
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also hope that this year will be the year of the
independent Palestinian state. On the fourth of May, 1999, the
interim (peace) period will end. And we should by that time be
prepared to declare our independent Palestinian State,'' Arafat
said through a translator whom he corrected repeatedly during his
speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's capital, Jerusalem, the Holy City,'' Arafat said,
adding that ``western Jerusalem could be the capital of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials sought to downplay Arafat's remarks
although the Palestinian leader in recent weeks has repeatedly
suggested he would declare Palestine an independent state by next
May.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position has been clear, as we have stated many times; and
we believe that statehood is an issue for final-status talks, an
issue to be negotiated between the parties, and not unilaterally
decided,'' said Joe Lockhart, Clinton's press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   The final status talks include the most divisive and sensitive
issues left unresolved. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
