<SLUG> BC-PUTNAM-MARKETING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    PUTNAM CREATES CORPORATE MARKETING JOB 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   BOSTON _ Putnam Investments, already one of the strongest
marketing forces in the mutual fund business, is going one step
further by consolidating and centralizing the ways it peddles its
products.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam has named Louise R. Kuo to the new position of head of
corporate marketing. The appointment Monday reflects two trends at
the nation's fourth largest fund house. Recognizing that fund
performance is not enough, Putnam is seeking greater influence over
the various channels through which it sells its investment
products. Secondly, Putnam had worried that the recent retirement
of top executive William N. Shiebler, who turned Putnam into a
marketing machine this decade, might leave a hole in the firm's
ability to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Kuo, 35, comes from Prudential Investments, where she was a
senior vice president in charge of marketing and strategy. She
reports to Thomas J. Lucey, who heads the business side of Putnam's
retail and institutional funds. Starting in January, Kuo will
consolidate marketing in Putnam's four core units _ mutual funds,
institutional money management, defined contribution pension
schemes, and international businesses. Previously, the groups had
their own marketing units, each with slightly different messages
and approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to unify the message across all channels,'' Lucey
said. No layoffs are planned, he said, although some marketing
staffers will be redeployed within the company.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam does not sell its mutual funds directly to consumers or
through ``supermarkets,'' such as Charles Schwab's OneSource.
Instead, it vends funds through banks, brokers, and financial
advisers. Shiebler _ whose successor, former Merrill Lynch
executive Richard A. Monaghan, had his first day on the job Monday
_ cultivated enviable relationships in those three channels as head
of fund sales to individual investors.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam, with $275 billion in assets under management and over 10
million fund shareholders, burst onto the investment scene in the
1990s with high performing funds and strong marketing. The firm, a
unit of insurance broker Marsh &AMP; McLennan Cos., drew in $21.7
billion in new cash last year, about 25 percent more than Fidelity
Investments, the nation's largest fund house and Putnam's crosstown
rival, according to Financial Research Corp. So far this year,
Putnam is second in sales only to The Vanguard Group.
</P>
<P>
   With those numbers, some might ask what needs to be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to beef up an area that had been well taken
care of but never had one person handling it,'' said fund marketing
consultant Geoff Bobroff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 1900EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981130.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5475 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ARAFAT     11-30 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ARAFAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON PLEDGES $400 MILLION TO HELP PALESTINIANS
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON Hoping to nurture the seeds of Mideast peace,
President Clinton on Monday pledged $400 million to help
Palestinians build a working economy in the West Bank and Gaza,
saying jobs and growth can lead a new generation away from violence
in the troubled region.
</P>
<P>
   His pledge kicked off an international donors' conference here
that raised some $3 billion in promised aid meant to help
Palestinians build roads, water systems, schools, clinics and other
facilities deemed essential to their social well being and economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who plans to visit Israel and the Palestinian
territories in two weeks, stopped short of calling for a
Palestinian state. He said, however, that building a viable
Palestinian society is essential to lasting peace in the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
   ''Palestinians have a right to the same things all people aspire
to,'' Clinton said, ''to be part of a normal, even happy, society,
where children receive a decent education, where there are jobs to
go around and decent health care, where people's memories are
reconciled with their hopes for the future, and there is no fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's pledge is subject to congressional approval. It would
come on top of existing U.S. aid to Palestinians, which is
scheduled to hit $100 million next year.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. aid to Palestinians would still be dwarfed by the roughly
$3 billion in assistance, mostly security oriented, that Washington
provides to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who helped broker a set of Israeli-Palestinian accords
in October that breathed life into a Mideast peace process that had
been stalled for 18 months, is traveling on Dec. 12 to Israel and
Palestinian territories to try to build on the momentum toward a
comprehensive peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Central to an overall peace treaty would be the disputed issues
of Palestinian statehood and the future of the city of Jerusalem.
It is now Israel's capital, but the Palestinians claim part of it
as their own.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has taken no public position on either issue, saying
both are to be decided in so-called final status talks.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian Authority leader Yasser Arafat, who met with Clinton
on Monday, has threatened to unilaterally declare a Palestinian
state unless final status talks are completed by May. That is the
deadline set under the Oslo peace process agreed upon in 1993 by
Israel and Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   While U.S. officials have repeatedly cautioned Arafat against
reiterating the threat, he alluded to it again on Monday. He
thanked donors for their assistance and said, through an
interpreter, that the money has ''enabled us to continue with our
efforts to advance the peace process, develop our economy and
proceed towards realizing our independence.''
</P>
<P>
   In Jerusalem, Israeli government officials have said in recent
days that such talk threatens the peace process and government
officials have reiterated their own position that Jerusalem is to
remain in Israeli hands.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat contended on Monday that part of the ancient city, what
Palestinians call ''Holy Jerusalem,'' is territory Israelis
occupied in the 1967 war and should be returned to Palestinian
control.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Jerusalem issue remains the number one issue,'' said
Arafat. ''Jerusalem will remain the item number one on the agenda
of the permanent status talks.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS.
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even as Israelis and Palestinians appeared to harden their
battle lines, Clinton said that economic growth could go a long way
toward building public support for the hard choices needed to forge
a final peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Public and private money will be needed, he said, to jump start
growth, spur investment and demonstrate the benefits of peace to
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ''For too long, too many young people have turned to terrorism
and old hatreds, partly because they had nothing better to do,''
Clinton said. ''We must give them a different future to believe in.
Every step toward opportunity is a step away from violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made his pledge during opening remarks at a donors'
conference held at the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from more than 40 countries attended the
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do not have exact pledges, but it appears that delegations
pledged more than $3 billion today,'' Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright told reporters after the conference ended.
</P>
<P>
   That, she said, was well above the $2.3 billion pledged by the
world community at a similar conference in Paris five years ago,
just after the breakthrough Oslo peace accords inked on the White
House lawn between Israel and the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly half of the money pledged has been disbursed. While
privately some critics have accused donors of not ponying up their
pledged amounts, others contend that the hold-up is implementation.
Starting from nearly scratch, these analysts say, the Palestinian
territories are absorbing the money as quickly as can be done
without rampant waste or ineffectual spending.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the causes, the Palestinian economy has been
backsliding for several years, with per capita income falling and
job growth stymied.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, Clinton said, the momentum of the Oslo accords has
bogged down, in part because ''There has been too little tangible
improvement in the lives of the Palestinian people,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   '''We must convince those who have invested so much in this
process that it was a sound investment,'' said Clinton. ''We must
look at Gaza and the West Bank in a new light, not as
battlegrounds, but as energetic places at the crossroads of the
Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright said Monday's donor conference was aimed at helping to
realize those aims.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is also the beginning of a process which will turn words on
paper into contracts, construction sites and commerce in the West
Bank and Gaza and throughout the Middle East,'' said Albright.
''And the dividends of peace will become increasingly tangible and
enduring in the lives of the Palestinian people.''
</P>
<P>
   EDIT
</P>
