<SLUG> BC-GOLF-TEED-OFF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACUSHNET IRED BY PROPOSED BALL-TESTING RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A proposed change in the required testing of all golf balls
before they hit the market has at least one manufacturer more than
a little teed off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough is enough,'' said Wally Uihlein, president and chief
economic officer of Acushnet Co. of Fairhaven, Mass., who blasted
the US Golf Association's plan to change a 57-year-old test for
golf balls, just weeks after adopting a new measurement for the
so-called spring-like effect of clubs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Supported by a cash-rich balance sheet, the Executive
Committee of the USGA is abusing its power and engaging in action
which it has yet to prove is wanted or asked for by the 25 million
golfers and 10,000 member clubs they profess to represent,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, the USGA has battled with golf
manufacturers over concerns that technology is out-distancing human
skill as a key to success in the game. &UR;  &LR; The USGA sets national
rules for playing the game that govern professionals on the tour,
which are generally respected worldwide, even by casual players.
</P>
<P>
   The manfacturers assert the USGA is intent on stifling
improvements in the design and performance of the equipment, major
factors in driving new sales.
</P>
<P>
   Among the industry leaders, Acushnet _ including the
ball-manufacturer Titleist, the club manufacturer Cobra, and the
footware manufacturer FootJoy Worldwide _ had $911 million in sales
in 1997. But observers of the sporting goods industry say the
market for golf equipment is flat, with many manufacturers showing
large inventories, and at least one company, Callaway, of Carlsbad,
Calif., announcing layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 2, the USGA adopted a proposal to measure the
``spring-like effect'' of clubs over the near unanimous objection
of manufacturers, who spend millions of dollars every year for
research to develop new products and expand their markets.
</P>
<P>
   The USGA now wants to address the technology of balls, proposing
new tests last week to update the current ``overall distance
standard,'' and to substantially upgrade its ``initial velocity
test.''
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, testing of the distance standard would be brought
indoors and would measure the speed, launch angle, and spin of the
ball, as opposed to merely the distance. And the USGA would
increase the striking velocity from 143 feet per second to 180 feet
per second, to better replicate today's stronger players.
</P>
<P>
   The USGA is seeking comment on the proposed ball regulations
this winter, with an eye toward adopting new rules on balls in the
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Uihlein is concerned in part that the USGA adopted the new
regulations on clubs despite vehement, unified protests from the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spite of repeated requests to document where the game is
experiencing some technological Armageddon,'' he said, ``the USGA,
under the pretense of changes to its test procedures, continues to
march forward with plans to modify the Rules of Golf concerning
equipment without serious input from those affected.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
