w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOM-HANKS-IN-YOUVE-GO     11-30 1400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOM-HANKS-IN-YOUVE-GOT-MAIL-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ROMANCE IS BACK FOR TOM HANKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Tom Hanks with Meg Ryan in a scene from
``You've Got Mail.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    He may be one of America's favorite romantic-comedy stars, but
Tom Hanks doesn't believe in destiny, love at first sight or
kindred spirits. Never did, he says.
 &HT;    ``Before I got married _ jeez, man, I just wanted to get laid,''
Hanks says playfully. ``If somebody said, `What were your dreams
and hopes while you were in high school?' I'd say, `To get laid at
some point in my life, to have sex with a woman.'
 &HT;    ``That was the main, single goal, and everything else was chaff
compared to that. And it took a while.''
 &HT;    Now, of course, Hanks is a top movie star, a two-time Oscar
winner, a $20 million man, one of America's favorite personalities.
 &HT;    ``Everything changed,'' he says, laughing. ``Now I just get laid
all the time!''
 &HT;    Hanks, still boyishly handsome at 42, finishes with an aw-shucks
grin. He's kidding, of course.
 &HT;    ``I'm sorry,'' he says. ``We can't talk about that. What about
my nice-guy image?''
 &HT;    That nice-guy image is a key asset of Hanks's latest film, the
romantic comedy ``You've Got Mail.'' Opening nationwide on Dec. 18,
``You've Got Mail'' reteams him with Meg Ryan, his co-star in ``Joe
Vs. the Volcano'' (1990) and ``Sleepless in Seattle'' (1993), as
well as with Nora Ephron, the writer/director of ``Sleepless.''
 &HT;    ``You've Got Mail,'' based on the 1940 James Stewart/Margaret
Sullavan charmer ``The Shop Around the Corner,'' casts Hanks as Joe
Fox, a chain-bookstore executive who is the obvious nemesis of
small, personal-touch bookshops and their owners, such as Kathleen
Kelly (Ryan). The two clash immediately _ not dreaming that they're
simultaneously falling in love online, via the anonymous circuitry
of the Internet.
 &HT;    ``This movie is absolutely rooted in who we are right now,'' the
always-affable Hanks says during a conversation at a Los Angeles
hotel. ``It's about the Wal-Martification of the world, about that
intangible quality human beings have to fall in love with somebody
they don't know
 &HT;    ``On top of that,'' he adds, ``it was Nora, who I know and who I
know will make a good movie. It ended up being with Meg, who always
gets a good game out of me one way or the other.''
 &HT;    In fact, it was Hanks who, after reading the script, called Ryan
and essentially said, ``We should do this together.''
 &HT;    ``Meg is very smart, doesn't lie and she doesn't acquiesce to
somebody's personality just to fold into a conversation,'' he says.
``Meg acts exactly who she is.
 &HT;    ``So without it being competitive in any way, shape or form, the
level of the game is constantly raised with Meg,'' Hanks says
enthusiastically. ``Meg scares you, in the way you want to be
scared by someone you're working with, yet she also intrigues you
the way you want to be intrigued by someone you're working with.''
 &HT;    Hanks is less Web-savvy than his character in the film. He's
simply too busy to spend much time online, he says.
 &HT;    ``All I really do is search for those nude pictures I did 20
years ago,'' he says. ``And, thank God, I have yet to find them!''
 &HT;    Currently, the actor juggles his work on his next film _ an
adaptation of Stephen King's novella ``The Green Mile'' _ and his
commitment to spending time with his wife, actress Rita Wilson, and
their children.
 &HT;    Right now, the movie is winning. Starring Hanks as a brutal
prison guard _ a role for which he has gained about 25 pounds _ the
film is behind schedule and gaining a reputation as what the
sinister Hollywood lexicon calls ``a troubled project.''
 &HT;    ``It is still going on,'' Hanks says. ``It's just one of those
movies that is taking this much time. Some movies you can just
crank out _ this isn't one of them.
 &HT;    ```Green Mile' is a death-row movie,'' he explains. ``We're on
death row for a long time, and you've got to have that look a
little different every time. It was never going to be easy to make,
and it's not _ that's just the way it is.''
 &HT;    Meanwhile, much of Hollywood seems to agree that his previous
film, Stephen Spielberg's summer hit ``Saving Private Ryan,'' will
earn Hanks his third Best Actor Oscar.
 &HT;    The actor himself dismisses such speculation as premature.
 &HT;    ``Oh, are the nominations in already?'' he asks teasingly.
 &HT;    Still, he can't deny the power of Spielberg's World War II
drama. A flood of mail that he's received from veterans has proven
that point.
 &HT;    ``I'm not surprised,'' Hanks says. ``I was blown away by `Saving
Private Ryan,' just like everyone else was.
 &HT;    ``Look, `Private Ryan' was a movie unlike any other,'' he says.
``I don't think any movie like it has been made, and I don't think
any other movie has been embraced by the public the way `Private
Ryan' was.
 &HT;    ``And I'm not surprised at all that veterans are saying, `My
God, they actually made a movie about what it was like.'''
 &HT;    After ``Green Mile,'' Hanks will star in ``Castaway'' for his
``Forrest Gump'' (1994) director, Robert Zemeckis. The film's
unique schedule calls for shooting half the movie in early 1999,
taking a year's break for Hanks to shoot another movie and, under
careful medical supervision, to drop enough weight to give him the
emaciated physical appearance of a man marooned far from
civilization. Then everyone will regroup in 2000 and complete
``Castaway.''
 &HT;    ``It's a risk,'' he concedes. ``There's a lot of money at stake.
Someone could die. But they're trusting us to do it, so we're going
to try.''
 &HT;    Hanks has come a long way from his breakthrough _ but inane _
television sitcom ``Bosom Buddies'' (1980-82) and such early
features as ``Bachelor Party'' (1984), ``Dragnet'' (1987) and
``Turner and Hooch'' (1989). Few people, watching those efforts,
would have predicted that, a decade later, he'd be one of America's
most admired actors, winner of Best Actor Oscars for Jonathan
Demme's ``Philadelphia'' (1993) and for ``Forrest Gump.''
 &HT;    Part of his success, Hanks says, is as simple as growing older,
maturing as a person and gaining experience as an actor.
 &HT;    The rest, he adds, is pure luck _ that, and a willingness to
grab whatever opportunities were offered and make the most of them.
 &HT;    ``Look, I didn't have a lot of choices for the longest time,''
he says. ``I didn't have a real broad horizon as far as things
they'd consider me for. But as soon as they did, I leapt at the
opportunities to do different kinds of stuff.
 &HT;    ``When Jonathan offered me `Philadelphia,' I realized, `This is
a whole new gig.'''
 &HT;    Not that Hanks approached that role as a dying AIDS patient any
differently than he had his parts in ``Bachelor Party,'' ``Turner
and Hooch'' or even ``Bosom Buddies.''
 &HT;    ``My job was still the same _ hit the marks and tell the
truth,'' he says. ``But the nature of what it is was different.
 &HT;    ``Look, you're talking to the luckiest man in the world when it
comes down to having opportunities to go off and do different
brands of movies,'' he says. ``I think you have to put out a mix of
messages _ you have to be that repertory actor in the great
repertory company that's doing something very light and frothy one
night, and the next night is doing `Hamlet.'
 &HT;    ``That's pretty much what I've been going for all along.''
 c.1998 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
