<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5517 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEFFREY-KATZENBERG-ON     11-30 1494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEFFREY-KATZENBERG-ON-PRINCE-OF-EGYPT-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEFFREY KATZENBERG: A REBORN CROWN PRINCE HEADS FOR `EGYPT' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Jeffrey Katzenberg with Steven Spielberg
and David Geffen. 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    He remembers sitting in the back row at a matinee. Unemployed,
angry and underfoot, he'd been banished from the house by his wife.
 &HT;    Naturally, Jeffrey Katzenberg went to the movies.
 &HT;    After all, he'd been a fixture at Walt Disney Pictures, head of
the animation division and the man behind such hits as ``Aladdin''
(1992) and ``The Lion King'' (1993) until only a few months before.
Movies were his life.
 &HT;    That had ended one August morning when his boss, Disney chairman
Michael Eisner, handed him a press release that was about to be
distributed. It reported that Katzenberg _ who initially thought it
hailed a promotion _ instead would be leaving the company.
 &HT;    Consumed with anger, Katzenberg launched several legal suits
against Disney and otherwise didn't work at all, running over in
his mind again and again the apparent ruin of his career.
 &HT;    Then William Shatner saved him.
 &HT;    ``It's so embarrassing, but Captain James T. Kirk and my rabbi
helped me get over my anger,'' Katzenberg says.
 &HT;    The film was ``Star Trek: Generations'' (1994), a natural choice
for Katzenberg, a ``Star Trek'' fan who'd help supervise the first
``Trek'' film in 1979 as a Paramount executive.
 &HT;    Katzenberg remembers the exact moment that turned things around
for him.
 &HT;    ``Kirk dies in `Generations,' and he lies in the arms of Picard
moaning, `What was it all for?''' Katzenberg recalls. ``Picard says
to him, `Captain, it's not the monuments that we build, nor the
legacies that we leave behind that matters. What matters is the
journey. And who, captain, has had a richer or fuller journey in
his life than you?''
 &HT;    At least one man in that dark theater sat up straight.
 &HT;    ``So Captain Kirk croaks,'' Katzenberg says. ``And a light bulb
goes off in my head. I'm going, `I get it! I get it!'''
 &HT;    What he got was that he couldn't be mad at Eisner or Disney
forever.
 &HT;    ``I said to myself in that theater, `Forget it. It doesn't
matter,''' he says. ```You can't take this with you. Live your life
and do good work. Oh, and have a good time.'''
 &HT;    Four years and change later, Katzenberg is having a good time.
As he sips a Diet Coke at 8 a.m. in a Chicago hotel room, he looks
happy, fit and anything but angry. Which comes easily to a man who,
as co-founder of the studio Dreamworks SKG, has a much-touted
animated film, ``The Prince of Egypt,'' opening on Dec. 18.
 &HT;    And to one who was up for a 5 a.m. workout at the hotel gym.
 &HT;    ``People always say to me, `Jeffrey, what is the secret of your
success?''' the 47-year-old, New York-born executive says. ``It's
very simple: I sleep five hours a day, which means I've got three
hours more on every normal human being.''
 &HT;    Those extra hours must have come in handy in making ``The Prince
of Egypt,'' a dazzling, epic retelling of the Moses story, complete
with the celebrity voices of Val Kilmer, Ralph Fiennes, Michelle
Pfeiffer, Sandra Bullock and Jeff Goldblum, not to mention a
much-hyped duet between pop divas Whitney Houston and Mariah Carey.
 &HT;    The early word is good, but Katzenberg admits to being nervous.
An animated, feature-length Biblical story is no sure thing by any
measure.
 &HT;    But when he and partners Steven Spielberg and David Geffen first
conceived Dreamworks SKG, Katzenberg says, the whole idea was to
try new things, and that included animation.
 &HT;    ``For 60 years, since Walt Disney made `Snow White' (1937),
animation has been mostly used to tell fairy tales,'' Katzenberg
says. ``I love the fairy tales and I loved making them. It didn't
make sense to me why we couldn't make completely different kinds of
stories.''
 &HT;    Katzenberg thought of an animated ``Raiders of the Lost Ark.''
An animated ``Terminator''-style science-fiction story. Even an
animated ``Lawrence of Arabia.''
 &HT;    It was Spielberg who suggested revisiting the Cecil B. DeMille
classic, ``The Ten Commandments'' (1956).
 &HT;    ``What I remembered the most about Moses is that he was this
innocent everyman,'' Katzenberg says. ``He was imperfect, flawed,
unsure of himself and reluctant to accept this extraordinary
mission. It's a story any of us can identify with, because we're
all flawed _ especially me. But we all wish that within us is the
ability to do something great.''
 &HT;    Katzenberg spent the next three years with 500 artists, learning
about ancient Egypt and Biblical stories. But the resulting film is
widely seen as a personal statement from him to Disney, a
validation of his contribution to the studio's immense success.
 &HT;    Katzenberg won't hear of it.
 &HT;    ``This film was not about proving myself,'' he says, visibly
annoyed. ``It drives me crazy when I hear it's just me behind this
movie _ it really offends me. This demeans a group of 500 artists
who sat in Glendale, Calif., and devoted themselves to every moment
of this movie.
 &HT;    ``I'm just the quarterback.''
 &HT;    But even the quarterback knows a smart play when he hears one.
 &HT;    Take the parting of the Red Sea. A 7-year-old son of one of his
animators told Katzenberg that when the water parts, ``It better
rock.''
 &HT;    ``That was my goal,'' he says. ``I would walk around going, `You
better make the chariot race and the Red Sea rock.'''
 &HT;    Dreamworks's 1998 has certainly rocked, with $100 million-plus
hits such as ``Deep Impact,'' ``Antz'' and, of course, ``Saving
Private Ryan,'' which to date has grossed more than $190 million
and is Oscar bound.
 &HT;    ``Antz'' sparked its own, appropriately small-scale controversy
when it was unexpectedly released early, ``scooping'' the similar
Disney-Pixar film, ``A Bug's Life.''
 &HT;    ```Antz' was finished early,'' Katzenberg says dismissively. ``I
showed it to Steven and David, who were blown away. Steven said,
`If you can get it out sooner, you should.'
 &HT;    ``The whole thing has been so autopsied by the press _ who did
what to whom? None of it is true. Our movie was just ready first.''
 &HT;    He swears that he doesn't carry any particular grudge against
Disney.
 &HT;    ``I have no rear-view mirror in my life,'' he says. ``I don't
look back. I'm too excited about what's in front of me, and I'm
driving too fast. If I took my eye off of what's in front of me, I
would crash.''
 &HT;    His troubles began in 1994 when Frank Wells, Eisner's No. 2 man,
died tragically in a helicopter crash. Katzenberg expected to
inherit the job. After all, his animation unit had revived the
studio and earned it billions of dollars.
 &HT;    Eisner didn't agree, which led to Katzenberg's departure and a
lawsuit which was subsequently settled out of court.
 &HT;    ``I loved my years at Disney,'' Katzenberg says. ``I loved
working for Michael. I really, genuinely don't have any anger or
hostility or animosity or anything. I let go of it all a long time
ago.
 &HT;    ``I've been very lucky,'' he adds. ``I've had some great mentors
in my career. People took me under their wings _ they trained me,
they taught me.''
 &HT;    Spielberg and Geffen both included.
 &HT;    ``Let's be clear,'' Katzenberg says. ``This is not an equal
partnership. These two guys are trillionares, and much more
accomplished, much more successful and much smarter than I am.
 &HT;    ``They're like two older brothers who are taking care of me,
helping me and teaching me.''
 &HT;    Meanwhile, all three are doing their best to make film history.
 &HT;    ``We're having fun,'' Katzenberg says. ``The spirit of
Dreamworks is, `Let's do something better, bigger, different.'
That's all it is for us.
 &HT;    ``I want the adventure,'' he adds. ``Of course, along the way
there are some misadventures. That's just part of it. But that's
the pioneer, take-a-risk spirit.''
 &HT;    Capt. Kirk would understand.
 c.1998 Cindy Pearlman  
