<HEADER>
A5518 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BURT-REYNOLDS-IN-HARD     11-30 1431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURT-REYNOLDS-IN-HARD-TIME-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURT BEHIND BARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Burt Reynolds in a scene from ``Hard
Time.'' 
 By JEAN OPPENHEIMER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    There was a time in the early 1990s when Burt Reynolds seemed to
be single-handedly keeping the tabloid press in business.
 &HT;    The man who had reigned as Hollywood's No. 1 box-office star
from 1978 to 1982 found his marital and financial woes played out
in the headlines and on tabloid television. There were even rumors
that he was dying.
 &HT;    For a while, Reynolds fought back as best he could. Today,
however, he manages to laugh at it all _ fortified as he is by a
renewed career including an Oscar nomination for ``Boogie Nights''
(1997), several upcoming movies and a three-picture
acting/directing deal with TNT.
 &HT;    The actor recently wrapped Disney's ``Mystery Alaska,'' and on
Dec. 13 will be seen in the first of his three TNT productions,
``Hard Time.'' He plays a veteran police officer who is framed for
murder and sent to prison. Two follow-up films _ one due in
February, the other later next year _ will follow the character as
he is released from prison and sets out to clear his name.
 &HT;    It's a part he can relate to, a character who's been up, been
down and knows about coming back for more.
 &HT;    ``This guy's a survivor,'' Reynolds says.
 &HT;    Not that the actor will admit to being in the middle of a
comeback.
 &HT;    ``I'm not coming back,'' he insists. ``I have been sitting on
the bench, just waiting for them to put me back in the game. Nobody
ever carried me out of the stadium. I was taken out of the game,
but not out of the stadium.''
 &HT;    Sports metaphors come naturally to Reynolds, a former athlete.
In fact, during his high-school and college days, he'd planned to
be a professional football player. But a car accident during his
sophomore year at Florida State University injured his knee, ending
any hopes of a professional career.
 &HT;    Having noticed a lot of pretty girls hanging around the theater
department, he recalls, he limped across campus to investigate. But
it wasn't until he transferred to a small junior college that he
really got serious about acting, thanks to a literature professor
named Watson Duncan.
 &HT;    ``Like all athletes, I sat in the back row of class,'' Reynolds
recalls. ``But he was a brilliant teacher, and slowly I moved down
to the front row. One day he said to me _ I didn't even know he
knew my name _ `You'll be in the play.'
 &HT;    ``I said, `I won't be in any play.'
 &HT;    ``And he said, `Yes, you will. You are going to be an actor.'
 &HT;    ``I said, `You're out of your mind.'
 &HT;    ``And he said, `The reading is at 3.'''
 &HT;    Reynolds got the part, to his own surprise.
 &HT;    ``I have no idea what he saw in me,'' he says with a shrug.
``The first time I got on stage in front of an audience, though, I
felt like I was on the field. I wasn't nervous _ I thought, `I can
play. I'm home.'''
 &HT;    That summer Reynolds was accepted into an apprentice program at
a summer-stock theater in Hyde Park, N.Y., which featured a rising
young actress named Joanne Woodward.
 &HT;    As an apprentice, Reynolds was largely relegated to painting
flats and sweeping floors, but one day Woodward called him over.
Back then Reynolds still went by his nickname, ``Buddy.''
 &HT;    ``She said, `Buddy, you're from the South, aren't you?'''
Reynolds says, slipping into Woodward's languorous Southern accent.
```Yes, ma'am,' I replied.
 &HT;    ```Are you an actor?' she said.
 &HT;    ``I said, `Well, I'm an apprentice.'
 &HT;    ``And she said, `I bet you can act. The next play is `Tea and
Sympathy,' and you'd be wonderful as the athlete.'''
 &HT;    Reynolds, who had never heard of the play, raced off to read it.
The following day Woodward took him to see the director.
 &HT;    ``Buddy is going to read for the part of Al,'' she announced.
 &HT;    The director tried to explain that the role already had been
cast, but Woodward remained steadfast.
 &HT;    ``Let Buddy play the part,'' she said sweetly. ``And pay him.''
 &HT;    Reynolds got the role, his first paycheck and excellent reviews.
 &HT;    Woodward's largesse didn't stop there. She persuaded her agent
to see the play. He signed Reynolds, and the actor _ veteran of
only one play _ was headed for New York, where he got the first
role he tried out for, a part in the road company of ``Mr.
Roberts.''
 &HT;    ``I thought, `This acting thing is good,''' Reynolds recalls,
laughing.
 &HT;    It was the Golden Age of Television, and Reynolds began doing
live television, aided by a friendship with the established actor
Rip Torn. Whenever Torn was doing a show and the producers needed
an actor they could rough up _ toss down a stairway, say, or set on
fire _ Torn would suggest his pal, Burt Reynolds.
 &HT;    ``This was live TV, so you couldn't use a stunt man,'' Reynolds
says. ``Now, where are you going to get a guy you can set on fire?
There aren't a lot of actors who will do that. But I said, `Hey,
that's great. How much money do I get?'''
 &HT;    After a couple of years Reynolds headed to Hollywood, where he
guest-starred on several television series and appeared in a couple
of forgettable films.
 &HT;    The movie that finally made people sit up and take notice was
``Deliverance'' (1972), the harrowing tale of four men on a
canoeing trip down a raging Appalachian river. The actors did all
their own stunt work, including crashing their canoes into rocks
and being swept down dangerous rapids.
 &HT;    ``You couldn't get four actors to do that today,'' Reynolds
says. ``Nobody's that crazy.''
 &HT;    Reynolds was widely touted for an Oscar nomination, but
``Deliverance'' was released only a month after Reynolds's
controversial nude centerfold in Cosmopolitan magazine. While it
may have cost him a shot at the gold statuette, the Cosmo
photographs made him a major sex symbol.
 &HT;    A succession of good-old-boy action films followed, including
the wildly popular ``Smokey and the Bandit'' (1977). But despite
his box-office pull, Reynolds never got the kind of roles that
would help him fulfil the promise of ``Deliverance.''
 &HT;    His most substantive role during those years was an atypical one
in ``Starting Over'' (1979), a story of a man recovering from a
messy divorce. The film was directed by the late Alan Pakula.
 &HT;    ``Everybody told him I shouldn't get the role,'' Reynolds says.
```Burt can't play that part. Nobody will ever believe he's a shy
person who is lost in a singles bar.'
 &HT;    ``But I knew that I was playing a guy who was just acting
cocky,'' he says. ``The guy in ``Starting Over' was closer to me
than anything I have ever played in my life. Pakula knew that.''
 &HT;    Over the years, Reynolds admits, he made a lot of movies he
shouldn't have made and passed on a lot of pictures he should have
made. But he refuses to take time for regrets.
 &HT;    ``That took place in the second round,'' he says. ``This is a
12-round fight, and I'm in the 11th round. You have to forget them
or you won't do well. And you have to make other people forget
them, too.
 &HT;    ``This is a business that is based totally on rejection, and if
you take it personally you will die,'' he says, shaking his head.
 &HT;    When his career faltered, he recalls, a lot of friends and
associates vanished. But he found solace in his work itself.
 &HT;    ``The ship doesn't sink to the bottom when everybody leaps
off,'' he says. ``It keeps going _ thupp, thupp, thupp.
 &HT;    ``If somebody said to me, `You can't act, you can't direct, you
can't produce,' what would I be? Well, I just couldn't do anything
else.''
 c.1998 Jean Oppenheimer  
