<HEADER>
A5519 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAVID-SPADE-IN-JUST-S     11-30 1318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVID-SPADE-IN-JUST-SHOOT-ME-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEAN STREAK: THE HARDLY WARM AND NOT AT ALL FUZZY WORLD OF `JUST
SHOOT ME'S' DAVID SPADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of David Spade in a scene from ``Just Shoot
Me.'' 
 By CHRISTOPHER LOUDON  
 c.1998 Canadian TV Guide  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mother knows best.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, comedian David Spade appeared on Howard
Stern's no-holds-barred radio show and let loose with a scathing
barb about JonBenet Ramsey, the murdered child beauty queen.
Minutes after the broadcast, Spade's mom was on the phone,
reprimanding him for his tastelessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a terrible thing to say,'' she scolded him. ``I hated
myself for laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   With those five words, she unintentionally provided a perfect
encapsulation of her son's comic style.
</P>
<P>
   Laughing at Spade's vitriolic antics is like slowing to check
out a roadside car wreck. You know you shouldn't, but it's
virtually impossible to avert your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Week after week, as ``Just Shoot Me's'' acerbic office lackey,
Dennis Finch, Spade shakes up the traditional conservatism of
prime-time sitcoms. His noxious territory has long been mined
overseas by Brits such as John Cleese in ``Fawlty Towers'' and
Joanna Lumley in ``Absolutely Fabulous,'' but in America it was
previously limited to safer zones such as late night _ ``Saturday
Night Live'' _ and cable _ ``Larry Sanders'' and ``South Park.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Finch, for example, could get away with responding to a
co-worker's adoption of a kitten with the catty comment, ``Poor
little tabby, moments away from a humane death,'' or rattle off
every slang term he can think of for women's breasts and then tell
an insulted Laura San Giacomo, ``I do bottoms, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Spade's envelope-pushing depiction of Finch is the latest result
of 10 years of methodical career planning. Unlike so many fellow
``Saturday Night Live'' alumni who tried to rise too high too fast,
the comedian has opted for a steady series of base hits instead of
one grand-slam home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's true,'' he says, nodding. ``I think it's the best way
to keep your sanity. You have to avoid that sudden, white-heat
attention, where there's nowhere to go afterward. Eventually it
fades, and you're almost in a worse spot, because it's like having
it all and then having it all go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather just keep making money and keep being funny, and
pretty soon a few years have gone by and you haven't disappeared.''
</P>
<P>
   Scanning Spade's early credits, one line that jumps out is a
1989 appearance on ``Baywatch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah,'' Spade says. ``Hey, why don't you hand me some Wite
Out and we can take care of that right now?
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually,'' he says, ``I love it when people say things like,
`I can't believe you were on `Baywatch' or `I can't believe George
Clooney was on `The Facts of Life.' I can. Because you get out here
and you're nobody. You're not going to be offered anything good, no
matter how good you are. And, of course, you'll do anything to make
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played a bad guy on `Baywatch.''' he recalls. ``That was
before I had a persona of my own, something that people could
relate to me. I was just another dipsh-t trying to find an angle.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first three years on `SNL' I couldn't find it
either,'' he adds. ``I didn't do much heavy character work, and any
that I did, Dana Carvey could do better. That's what kept me back.
I watched all the guys I started with _ Chris Farley, Chris Rock,
Rob Schneider _ all kind of pass me. I was the last one to do any
real damage out there. It was definitely frustrating and hard to
keep my head together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I did `Hollywood Minute,' and the boss said, `That's you.
Why don't you keep writing stuff like that?' And I was loving it,
because I was getting a persona.''
</P>
<P>
   Spade quickly parlayed his ``Hollywood Minute'' bitchiness into
several of ``SNL's'' most popular characters, including the
obnoxious flight attendant from Totally Bastard Airlines who
dismisses each departing passenger with a condescending
``buh-bye,'' and Dick Clark's office receptionist who screens even
the most famous callers with a patronizing, ``And you are ... ?''
</P>
<P>
   Then, tiring of ``SNL's'' overheated competitiveness _ an
atmosphere he says ages performers ``in dog years'' _ Spade traded
up to the big screen, playing a snide Stanley to pal Chris Farley's
jolly Oliver in the back-to-back hits ``Tommy Boy'' (1995) and
``Black Sheep'' (1996).
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, after coming within inches of a co-starring role
on the short-lived Tea Leoni sitcom ``The Naked Truth,'' Spade
hesitantly accepted producer Rod Grey's invitation to join the
``Just Shoot Me'' ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was already a show without me,'' Spade says. ``Rod Grey
showed me a tape and said, `Do you think you could fit into this
thing?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't want to play another assistant,'' he recalls,
``since I'd already done that like 10 times. I didn't want all the
stories to revolve around me being the secretary. Also, they wanted
him to be kind of gay, and that's really the only thing I can't do
_ I can't play it fruity.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there was no one like me on the show,'' the comedian says,
``so I thought it might be a good mix. All I asked is that they
give me some kind of vague office-manager role so that I'd have a
reason to stand outside Jack's (George Segal) office and observe
everything that's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Finch may be best known for his waspish ways, but he's more than
just a smarmy smart aleck. Scratch the surface of Finch's slick,
slacker veneer and you find the quintessential little boy lost, a
guy whose desperation to be part of the in crowd is constantly
thwarted by his own nerdiness.
</P>
<P>
   It's a side of Finch that closely parallels Spade's own
less-than-idyllic youth in the Phoenix suburb of Casa Grande, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it seems like a blip on the radar,'' he says, ``but back
then it was a rough ride. It was fun being a kid, but it was also a
time of living in fear. I remember being beaten up a lot. I was a
bit of a brainiac, really good in math and reading, because I
really didn't want to have to do anything outside of school.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Finch recently explained to his office mates, ``I have an
acute sense of when someone is threatening me. I get it from my
mother, along with my fear of owls.''
</P>
<P>
   With ``Just Shoot Me'' an established hit, Spade is content to
be the Krazy Glue that holds the show together and to ``appreciate
a good job with good writing and decent hours and talented people
who really want to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Are there, however, any specific improvements he'd like to see
made in the show?
</P>
<P>
   Spade takes a long pause to consider the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' he says at last. ``There is one thing: I'm trying to
organize make-out parties with the female cast members. It's still
in the early stages.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Christopher Loudon is the editor-in-chief of Canadian TV
Guide, based in North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 1922EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
