<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5535 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIV-PREGNANT-BOS &LR;      11-30 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIV-PREGNANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
S. AFRICA HALTS PLAN TO TREAT HIV-INFECTED MOTHERS  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Acting on new evidence that a short course of the drug AZT
sharply lowers an infected mother's risk of transmitting the human
immunodeficiency virus (HIV) to her unborn child, Dr. Glenda Gray
and her colleagues in Johannesburg, South Africa, have been lining
up women eager to receive the treatment.
</P>
<P>
   At a cost of about $50 per treated woman, Gray figured, the drug
could cut mother-to-child HIV transmission by half _ a payoff
comparable to proven public health measures such as measles
vaccination or prenatal care.
</P>
<P>
   But in October Gray picked up the newspaper and read that South
Africa's health minister, Dr. Nkosazana Zuma, had canceled the
pilot project, which was to test the feasibility of delivering AZT
to 2,500 HIV-infected pregnant women.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said she doesn't understand. ``It doesn't make sense on a
human rights level, on an economic level, or on a moral level,''
she said in a telephone interview. ``I'm still not sure why the
government decided not to go ahead with this intervention in the
face of an epidemic that is unchecked.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was primarily for cost reasons,'' Dr. Glaudine Mtshali, a
top aide to Zuma, said Monday in between appearances to mark World
AIDS Day, which is today.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not an easy decision because every single life is
important,'' Mtshali said. The government wants to spend the money
instead on safer-sex education and condom distribution, she added,
``so we don't have to be faced with this very difficult decision
about a baby due to be born with positive HIV status.''
</P>
<P>
   Mtshali said the government would revisit the decision when
``more information becomes available that is pertinent to the South
African context.''
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's decision threatens to overshadow other recent
steps taken by the government to mobilize the nation against what
many believe is the world's most explosive AIDS epidemic. ``We face
the danger that half of our youth will not reach adulthood,''
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki said in a dramatic October 9 broadcast
address to the nation on AIDS, the first by a leading political
figure. ``Our dreams as a people will be shattered.''
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki, who is viewed as President Nelson Mandela's probable
successor, appealed to South Africans to change ``the way we live
and how we love'' and pledged ``to continue our search for a
medical solution.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mbeki's ``declaration of a Partnership Against AIDS'' was
soon followed by what some call ``Zuma's bombshell'' about the AZT
program. Morna Cornell of the AIDS Consortium, an alliance of 90
South African AIDS groups, said the atmosphere at a recent workshop
of 50 HIV-infected pregnant women was one of ``the most appalling
disbelief and loss of hope.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To learn you're HIV-positive and then to learn that something
can be done to give you a 50 percent better chance you won't
transmit it to your child _ and then to be told by the government
that it is not affordable _ it is just sickening, quite frankly,''
Cornell said. ``And we've just committed ourselves to a $5.3
billion arms purchase. What does that say about the values of the
new South Africa?''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is HIV spreading more rapidly than in sub-Saharan
Africa, and more than half the region's new infections are
occurring in South Africa, according to a report issued Monday by
UNAIDS, the United Nations AIDS agency.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, one pregnant South African woman in every seven is
already infected with HIV, according to a 1997 survey. In the
coastal province of Kwazulu-Natal, the proportion is close to one
in three.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's decision to cancel the AZT pilot project, at
least for now, represents a clash between ``soft'' public health
interventions that promise future payoffs for entire populations
and a ``hard'' technology that can rescue individual infants from
certain death in the here-and-now.
</P>
<P>
   Public health authorities around the globe are watching the
South African debate closely as a harbinger of how the most
AIDS-beleaguered nations may deal with the first medical
intervention shown to have potential impact in stemming a virus
that will infect six million people this year worldwide _ 11 every
minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``My deep concern about South Africa concerns the balance
between prevention and care,'' said David E. Bloom of Harvard
University's Institute for International Development. ``They're
going completely in the direction of prevention and they're writing
off the millions who are already infected.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter Piot, executive director of UNAIDS, said Monday in an
interview from Johannesburg that implementing AZT programs for
pregnant HIV-infected women, even on a limited pilot basis, is
proving more difficult than he imagined. Last spring, in announcing
the positive results from AZT studies in Thailand, Piot said wider
implementation of such programs was no longer a question of ``when
or if we should act, but simply how.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The more I deal with this, the more I see it as a very complex
issue,'' Piot said Monday. ``But it's my understanding that the
door is still open.''
</P>
<P>
   By many measures, South Africa is in a better position to test
the feasibility of prenatal AZT treatment than other, poorer
nations that are proceeding with plans to deliver the treatment to
30,000 pregnant women in 11 sites in Africa and Asia. More than
half of South Africa's population lives in urban areas, its per
capita income is more than $3,000, and its adult literacy rate is
82 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Shepard of Brandeis University, who recently completed an
analysis of prenatal AZT treatment for the government of
neighboring Botswana, said that nation is considering a pilot
project like the one South Africa recently rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard's analysis indicated that AZT treatment of HIV-infected
women would pay for itself by averting about 5,000 pediatric
hospitalizations for every 50,000 women screened for infection and
treatment. ``In the cost-effectiveness literature there are few
interventions that are such good deals,'' Shepard said.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's reluctance appears to stem from its apartheid
history and the current government's determination to redress its
historical inequities in health care, in which 20 percent of the
population got world-class care and the other 80 percent got
virtually nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of equity is very important in South Africa now,''
said Dr. Joseph Saba of UNAIDS, who has coordinated the agency's
activities on prenatal AZT treatment. ``This situation emphasizes
that we need to be as rational as possible, but the political
decision to move forward is more complex than the rational
parameters suggest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
