<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5537 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENSUS-SAMPLING-BOS &LR;      11-30 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-SAMPLING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT ASKED TO REFEREE CENSUS DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court Monday got between the warring
White House and GOP House on the hot topic of how to count the 2000
Census, and it was notably uncomfortable being there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like injecting us into a battle between the two
political branches,'' Justice Antonin Scalia said, echoing the
sentiments of several of his colleagues who heard two highly
charged census cases Monday. ``They will survive, but I don't know
if we would.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue before the court sounds technical: Whether the Census
Bureau, in conducting the 2000 count, can legally supplement its
usual head-by-head enumeration with a statistical estimation, or
sampling, to get a more accurate population figure.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration vehemently argues yes. Its solicitor
general, Seth Waxman, told the nine justices that sampling would
``best achieve the Constitution's goal of determining the number of
persons in each state.'' He called sampling an effective tool to
reduce the census's chronic undercount, which the Census Bureau
estimated at 1.6 percent of the US population in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Census numbers determine how the 435 House seats will be divided
up among the 50 states, and most Democrats think that correcting
the undercount, which disproportionately misses minorities and
urban dwellers, would benefit them politically.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say the stakes in the 2000 Census are high. Maureen
Mahoney, the lawyer representing House Republicans before the high
court Monday, argued that census law and the Constitution forbid
anything but an ``actual enumeration'' for apportionment. ``No
guessing games,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Two lower courts have agreed. In August, a three-judge federal
panel in Washington ruled in favor of the House Republicans,
finding that federal law bars the use of sampling for
apportionment. In September, three federal judges in Richmond, Va.,
made a similar ruling in a lawsuit brought against the
administration by a group of 16 individuals who anticipate their
six states would lose seats in the 2000 count.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Carvin, representing that group, told the justices
Monday that census accuracy was not the most important issue.
``Regardless of accuracy, (sampling) is illegal and
unconstitutional,'' Carvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Waxman argued that the Founding Fathers meant actual enumeration
to be ``a good-faith, empirical effort'' on the part of census
takers to count people every decade with the best available
techniques.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people would think an actual enumeration means a count,''
Justice Sandra Day O'Connor noted.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia sounded skeptical. ``If estimation by statistical
sampling isn't excluded (under actual enumeration), then what is?''
he asked. ``Rolling the dice?''
</P>
<P>
   Scalia also suggested that if estimating the population was what
the Founders had in mind, the young nation would have embraced it.
``The difficulty of finding people in the early frontier days was
much greater than today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The justices also questioned Waxman about the Census Bureau's
plan for counting just 90 percent of the population, beginning
April 1, 2000, and sampling the remaining 10 percent. If
statisticians could produce accurate estimates, Chief Justice
William Rehnquist suggested, ``why do we need a census?''
</P>
<P>
   Census officials and sampling proponents say that in a mobile
nation of private citizens, getting a 100 percent accurate
headcount is impossible. It's a critical issue, particularly for
cities that depend on census numbers for a fair distribution of
billions of dollars in federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been there and done that,'' said Barbara Everitt
Bryant, who was the Census Bureau director during the 1990 count.
``I know you can't get it by going out and ringing doorbells.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice John Paul Stevens suggested sampling might be the only
way to reach some parts of the population. He asked Mahoney, the
GOP's lawyer, what census enumerators would do if a family refused
to answer the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't guess,'' Mahoney said. ``They would have to put
down `zero.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``But what if the lights go on and off inside'' the house?
Justice Stephen Breyer wondered.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the justices sounded exasperated at being asked to
referee what, in the last 18 months, has been an escalating war of
words and threats between the White House and House GOP leaders
over the census. They indicated Monday they could simply dismiss
the census case on the grounds that no parties have been injured
yet and the House has no ``standing'' to sue the president.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia suggested the House play political hardball and cut off
funds to the administration. ``There are about 900 ways the House
can stymie the president if it has the political will,'' Scalia
said.
</P>
<P>
   Parties to the suit hope the high court will rule quickly so the
Census Bureau can get on with its work. ``The sooner we have a
decision, the better,'' Kenneth Prewitt, the Census Bureau
director, said after the arguments.
</P>
<P>
   The court will issue its ruling by the end of June. The cases
are Department of Commerce vs. House of Representatives, 98-404,
and Clinton vs. Glavin, 98-564.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
