<HEADLINE>
TEXAS DEATH ROW ESCAPEE'S GRANDMOTHER PRAYS FOR HIS PEACEFUL
SURRENDER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The grandmother of Texas death row escapee Martin E. Gurule said
Monday if she could get word to her grandson, it would be to
surrender immediately and peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he was to surrender, let it be in peace in God's will,''
said Amalia Marez, Gurule's maternal grandmother who lives in
Corpus Christi. ``I'm hoping for the love of God that he does
surrender and does not let it go any further.''
</P>
<P>
   But Marez also said it is ``to be expected'' that her grandson,
who escaped from the Huntsville prison late Thanksgiving night,
would be shot if he resists capture. She also said she has thought
about the possibility that he may already be dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope not,'' Marez said. ``My prayers are with him.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Gurule, who last week became the first condemned
murderer to escape death row since it was moved to the Ellis Unit
in Huntsville, Texas, has been depressed for some time. Marez added
that it was not unusual for him, or other family members, to get
depressed in November, because that is the month in which Gurule's
mother died, shortly after his birth. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Every letter he writes, he says, `Grandma, I'm sorry for not
writing. I've been very depressed,' '' Marez said. She said he has
continually asked over the years why God took his mother away.
</P>
<P>
   She said he never discussed escape plans with her, adding that
she knows none of the facts surrounding his murder of Mike Piperis
and Anthony Staton during a 1992 robbery at a Corpus Christi,
Texas, restaurant, the crime that sent him to death row.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't question him,'' she said. ``I am very, very proper. I
respect others as well as I wish to be respected. I don't ask
questions. I'm not an inquisitive person. I don't interrogate
nobody, and to this date, as God is my witness, I don't know
nothing, nothing, nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Marez said she was shocked to learn of Gurule's escape but has
not heard from him, nor did he give any hint to the family of his
escape plans.
</P>
<P>
   The family was contacted by authorities right after the escape
and they are still under surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I baby-sit and I'm losing my babies just because of this,''
Marez said. ``I'm not baby-sitting because they (are in) fear, and
I don't blame them. But then again this is the way we make ends
meet, and right now I'm not working. I'm out of a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I ask is for God to give me courage ... more strength to
bear with this problem,'' Marez added.
</P>
<P>
   She said Gurule's father, Eugence Gurule, has been in and out of
the hospital with a virus, and that her husband and Gurule's
paternal grandmother, Lora Gurule, also are depressed over the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying I'm the most courageous here at home, but the
Lord is with me and the Lord is with my husband and my husband
comes from a very religious family,'' Marez said.
</P>
<P>
   She said her brother-in-law, a minister in Mathis, Texas, and
members of his congregation are praying for the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're praying for my grandson everywhere,'' she said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
