<SLUG> BC-MA-CUTOFF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTERS URGE POSTPONEMENT OF WELFARE CUTOFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDITH GAINES   AND HILARY SARGENT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ About 30 people were arrested Monday night after
crowding into Governor Paul Cellucci's office to urge postponement
of Tuesday's welfare benefits cutoff for more than 5,000 families.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters, mostly women, held a day-long sit-in on couches
and on the floor in the lobby outside the governor's third-floor
State House office while six uniformed state troopers guarded the
office entrance. The guards made no efforts to move the protesters
until late in the day when they asked the demonstrators to leave.
When they refused, the protesters were carried by state police
officers to the elevators and booked at an undisclosed location. A
police spokesman said the protesters would be charged with
disorderly conduct and trespassing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the last day,'' said Ann Withorn, a professor at
UMass-Boston said before her arrest. ``We don't know what else we
can do.'' Withorn said she wanted Secretary of State William
Galvin, who is the acting governor while Cellucci is in Israel, to
issue an order extending the time limit for welfare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly would be the right thing to do,'' said Withorn.
</P>
<P>
   But officials said Monday there would be no automatic extensions
or postponment of the cutoff date. However, because of the
mechanics involved in processing the cases, all the families will
receive at least half of their monthly welfare allotment this month
and many will continue getting assistance throughout the holiday
period, said Dick Powers, spokesman for the Department of
Transitional Assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find that the time limit has been an invaluable tool in
prodding people off welfare,'' Powers said.
</P>
<P>
   He explained that when the state law was enacted on Dec. 1,
1996, about 41,000 people fell into the first cutoff group:
able-bodied individuals whose youngest child was age 2 or older. By
this past October, 35,000 of them had left the welfare rolls
because they had gotten a job, gotten enough unearned income to
make them ineligible, or moved to another state.
</P>
<P>
   Officials believe that since October, roughly 800 people have
left the welfare rolls, Powers said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that 2,374 of the remaining 5,000 also have managed to
get jobs but are not earning enough to eliminate their need for
welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 2,800 recipients will receive notice during the week of
Dec. 14 that their benefits are being terminated. In keeping with
standard welfare department policy, these people will be given a
10-day grace period before their benefits actually are cut, Powers
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said 2,195 more have applied for individual exemptions from
the Dec. 1 cutoff. Their checks will not be stopped until their
cases can be reviewed _ which may take up to 45 days.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the policy worry that too few individual exemptions
will be granted, and only for the most extreme cases.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for Working Massachusetts, a coalition of more than 60
welfare, labor, religious, academic and low-income groups, Jeb Mays
said nearly 6,000 individuals have signed petitions urging the
state to extend the cutoff by 3 more years, as federal law allows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Massachusetts law is one of the harshest in the country,''
Mays said. ``Our concern is that in one or two or three months, a
large number of women and children will be facing poverty and
hunger and homelessness. And we know the shelters are already
full.''
</P>
<P>
   Marie Kennedy, another professor at UMass-Boston who joined the
sit-in at Cellucci's office, said she could not remember being this
angry about and issue since the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may be a professor now, but I was on welfare once as a
single mother,'' said Kennedy. ``We call this state the
Commonwealth, but I'd like to know when this wealth is going to be
common.''
</P>
<P>
   Also protesting Monday was Kip Tiernan, the founder of Rosie's
Place, a local women's shelter, and the Boston Food Bank. Tiernan
said already there has been a 25 to 50 percent increase in demand
at Rosie's Place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The increase in need has been phenomenal, he said. ``After
(Tuesday), it will be catastrophic. This will determine whether
these people will live or die.''
</P>
</TEXT>
