<SLUG> BC-GAS-ADDITIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US TO STUDY HAZARDS OF GASOLINE ADDITIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid mounting concern that a new ingredient in gasoline is
contaminating water supplies across the country, US Environmental
Protection Agency Administrator Carol Browner created a panel
Monday to study the hazard posed by the additive and to look into
possible replacements.
</P>
<P>
   MTBE, short for methyl tertiary butyl ether, has been added in
large quantities to ``reformulated gas'' sold in many parts of the
country since 1995, as part of a national campaign to reduce
smog-causing emissions from vehicle tailpipes.
</P>
<P>
   But while MTBE has cleaned the air, it has polluted water,
forcing the closure of wells from Maine to California, including
several in Massachusetts. The US Geological Survey has detected
MTBE, which the EPA considers a possible human carcinogen, in 20
percent of the wells it monitors where reformulated gas is sold.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the governors of Maine and California have asked the
EPA for permission to stop using MTBE, known as an ``oxygenate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``While MTBE and other oxygenates in gasoline have improved air
quality for millions of Americans, I am convening a blue-ribbon
panel of experts to better understand public health concerns that
have been raised by the discovery of MTBE in some water bodies,''
said Browner.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-member panel will be chaired by Daniel Greenbaum, former
commissioner of the Massachusetts Department of Environmental
Protection who now runs the Health Effects Institute, a Cambridge,
Mass. research firm. The panel also includes environmentalists and
fuel industry representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists, who have chided the EPA for not taking strong
action on MTBE, see the panel as a positive step, but they said
studies of MTBE pollution done for Maine and California already
show the additive is too dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``What needs to be done here is a no-brainer. MTBE is too big a
threat to water and it must be banned,'' said John Meinhold of the
Sierra Club in New Hampshire, which is pushing the state to stop
using MTBE in southern New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   However, Browner stressed that the panel's creation does not
mean MTBE is automatically on its way out. Over the next six
months, the panel will look at the environmental and financial
costs and benefits of MTBE as well as other oxygenates that could
be used as an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's purpose, according to an EPA statement, is simply
``to gain a better understanding of the public health concerns
raised by the discovery of MTBE in some water supplies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
