<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TITANIC-RIVETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFECTIVE RIVETS MAY HAVE CAUSED TITANIC TRAGEDY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i cooding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pieces of metal retrieved from the hulk of the Titanic on an
expedition last August have provided strong confirmation of a
recent theory about what really caused the ``unsinkable'' ship to
sink 86 years ago. In a word: rivets.
</P>
<P>
   The rivets used to hold together the massive steel plates of
Titanic's hull, it turns out, were made of improperly annealed
iron. As a result, defects in the metal itself made the rivets
weakest at just the place where their strength was most needed in
an impact: where the rounded heads connect to the shaft.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 rivets recovered from the wreck have now been
analyzed, and 14 of them ``have some kind of problem,'' according
to metallurgist Timothy Foecke of the National Institute of
Standards and Technology in Gaithersburg, Md. Foecke said that as
soon as the impact with the iceberg occurred, the heads simply
popped off many of the rivets, causing long, narrow seams to open
up in the hull.
</P>
<P>
   Microscopic analysis of rivets that were recovered and sliced
open show the reason starkly: Slag in the iron, a glassy material
that is strong but brittle, should account for 2 to 3 percent of
the material, but instead is 8 to 9 percent in the bad rivets.
Whereas the smaller amount actually adds strength, the larger
amount makes the iron too brittle and subject to breakage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a lot of things,'' said Foecke, ``a little bit is a good
thing, but too much is bad.''
</P>
<P>
   But the problem rivets were not really anybody's fault,
explained William Garzke, a naval architect with Gibbs and Cox Inc.
of Virginia, who is in charge of analyzing the Titanic material.
The techniques used today to analyze the defects in the metal did
not exist back in 1910 when the ship was being built, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Titanic's hull was held together by 3 million rivets, Garzke
said. The failure of just a few dozen of them from the tremendous
force of the ship's impact with an iceberg may have caused
Titanic's sinking.
</P>
<P>
   With today's analytical methods, it is now clear that the larger
amount of slag in some rivets formed larger tubes or sheets inside
the iron, instead of the tiny filaments slag forms in smaller
quantities. These caused weak areas in the metal, and when the
rivets were flattened out to form the outside rivet head, the weak
areas ended up lined up with the hull plates, instead of running
along the length of the rivets. Like the grain in a piece of wood,
these defects make it easier for the metal to break in one
direction than another, and in this case it was the worst possible
direction, making it easy for the rivet heads to pop right off.
</P>
<P>
   Titanic's sister ship, the Olympic, was built in the same
shipyard at about the same time and was damaged by a collision in
1911. Photographs of its hull show many missing rivets and a gaping
opening between hull plates, adding further evidence to the
case &UR;  &LR; today that it was bad rivets that caused the large openings
in the hulls of both ships.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier theory that it was bad steel in the hull plates
themselves that caused the great ship's sinking does not stand up
under the new evidence, Foecke said. While some earlier tests had
suggested that the steel became as brittle as glass in the cold
water of the North Atlantic, more recent tests on a section of the
hull recovered from the wreck do not support that view.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found some values of the fracture resistance'' of steel
from Titanic's hull ``that are not terribly different from modern
steels,'' Foecke said. ``We feel this is enough to put to bed the
brittle steel theory.''
</P>
<P>
   But the rivets tell another story. The theory was first
suggested last year, based on an analysis of just two recovered
rivets, leaving open the possibility that these were simply an
anomaly. Now that 40 rivets have been analyzed, recovered from 11
different places on the ship, Foecke said, ``the rivet theory seems
to be holding up. There seems to be a fundamental problem with the
rivets.''
</P>
<P>
   Foecke presented his latest findings Monday at a meeting in
Boston of the Materials Research Society. The research on the
Titanic parts is continuing, Foecke and Garzke said.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the surprising revelations to come from the recent
analysis of the wreck is that the amount of damage to the ship was
actually much less than people thought at the time. Contrary to a
longstanding claim that the ship had suffered a huge 300-foot-long
gash, it turns out that the total opening caused by the impact
amounted to only about 12.5 square feet, Garzke said. Most of this
was in the form of gaps less than an inch wide.
</P>
<P>
   If the Titanic's captain had known that, Garzke said, it is
quite possible that simple countermeasures, such as stuffing
clothing or mattresses into the narrow, leaking seams could have
slowed the inrushing water enough to keep the ship afloat until the
Carpathia arrived to rescue survivors, possibly saving all aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Garzke said that during last August's expedition he was able to
see a section of this open seam firsthand for the first time. Most
of this crack is below the mud line, he said, but it is exposed in
at least one place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
