<HEADER>
A5553 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-UNINSURED-COX     11-30 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-UNINSURED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia begins enrollment for uninsured children
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Patricia Lane of Roswell recently landed her dream
job, as a social worker at an Atlanta senior citizens center.
</P>
<P>
   That break came after Lane struggled for years with health and
financial problems. A single parent, Lane, 48, has raised her two
children without getting child support from her former husband.
</P>
<P>
   Her new job pays about $21,000 annually. That income is too high
for her family to qualify for Medicaid, the federal-state health
insurance program for the poor. And it's not high enough, she says,
to afford private coverage for her two teenage children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really losing sleep over this,'' Lane says.
</P>
<P>
   The worry evaporated after Lane heard about a new insurance
program for Georgia children. Now, she says, her children will be
able to join the PeachCare for Kids program, which targets
thousands of uninsured children in the state, up to age 19. ``It's
a life-saver,'' Lane says.
</P>
<P>
   After a pilot program this fall in the Macon area, PeachCare's
statewide enrollment begins today, with medical servicesavailable
in January. PeachCare is part of a $24 billion federal initiative
to help meet the coverage needs of an estimated 10 million U.S.
children without insurance.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, about 380,000 children, or 17 percent, lack health
insurance. About 168,000 of these children are eligible for
PeachCare, says Georgia State University economist Bill Custer.
</P>
<P>
   Another 155,000 are eligible for Medicaid but aren't enrolled,
he says. Officials with the Department of Medical Assistance, which
runs both PeachCare and Medicaid, hope to ride the visibility of
PeachCare to sign up these Medicaid children.
</P>
<P>
   The children's program can make a significant dent in the
seemingly intractable problem of the uninsured, Custer adds. More
than 43 million Americans lacked coverage last year, up from 41.7
million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Children with health insurance own a major medical edge over
those without coverage, notes Gregg Haifley of the Children's
Defense Fund. ``A child who has an ear infection is more likely to
see a physician and not have a recurrence if that child has
insurance,'' Haifley says.
</P>
<P>
   In crafting their children's program, some states opted for a
private insurance plan. Others, like Georgia, chose to run their
children's program through Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   PeachCare's biggest challenge is to get the word out, says Jana
Key, PeachCare coordinator for the state.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, 1,300 applications have been received. The one-page
forms, which can be mailed in, can be obtained through a toll-free
number, and will also be available at hospitals, doctors offices,
libraries, churches and possibly schools.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Chansky of Roswell says two of his children will join
PeachCare. ``This is a Godsend,'' says Chansky, 63, a retired
salesperson on a fixed income. His wife, who has health problems,
doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot program led to the signup of about 127 children in
Macon and surrounding areas. Among those who've received services
is Chris Woodard, 12, of Perry.
</P>
<P>
   The family has been uninsured for years. But through PeachCare,
Chris, 12, received eyeglasses. Having PeachCare ``took a load off
our minds,'' says Cindy Woodard, his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Laurie Iscaro of Georgians for Children, an advocacy group,
says the pilot's enrollment numbers were lower than anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Besides a minimal effort in marketing, Iscaro cited the monthly
premium of $7.50 per person as a deterrent, especially for those at
the lower end of the PeachCare range. ``These people have marginal
disposable incomes,'' Iscaro says.
</P>
<P>
   The program has other potential pitfalls, Custer says. Some
employers, for example, may drop private coverage for workers'
dependents, believing the state plan could pick up the slack.
</P>
<P>
   But Custer also notes that more parents on Medicaid may be able
to move to higher-paying jobs, and not lose coverage for their
children. That income vs. benefits trade-off is a constant
frustration for the working poor.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Belcher, 19, of Byron says her husband's job didn't offer
a group plan and individual coverage ``is way too expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just over the (Medicaid) limit,'' she adds.
</P>
<P>
   So the PeachCare pilot proved the perfect fit for daughter
Hannah, who will be 2 this month. Says Belcher: ``This is the best
thing Georgia's ever come up with.''
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT THE PROGRAM
</P>
<P>
   _ Funding: $72 million the first year, of which about $20
million is from state funds.
</P>
<P>
   _ Benefits: Include preventive care, dental care, eyeglasses,
prescription drugs, emergency and hospital services.
</P>
<P>
   _ Premium: $7.50 per child per month. For two or more children,
it's $15 per month. For children under age 6, there's no premium.
</P>
<P>
   _ Co-payment for services: None.
</P>
<P>
   _ Income limit: Families earning up to 200 percent of the
federal poverty level. In 1998, that income limit equals $32,900
for a family of four.
</P>
<P>
   _ Estimated eligible population: 103,000 children.
</P>
<P>
   _ Information: 1-877-GAPEACH (427-3224).
</P>
<P>
   Andy Miller writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
