r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LB     11-30 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SCENARIO THAT'S NOT FULL OF BCS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITAL) We take you now to a parallel sports universe,
where people are logical and those wearing pastel, eye-numbing bowl
jackets are not in charge.(END ITAL)
</P>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Nov. 30 _ The first round of the first-ever NCAA
Division I college football playoffs has been set, and fans across
the country are already excited about the intriguing matchups.
</P>
<P>
   After playing superbly all season and being top seed in the
16-team tournament, No. 1 Tennessee is faced with a problematic
opponent, WAC champ Air Force. The Falcons won the WAC title and
received one of the last bids to the tourney, knocking out
16th-ranked Notre Dame, a 10-0 loser to USC in its season finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``At another time in college football,'' said Air Force coach
Fisher DeBerry, ``it wouldn't have mattered if we won the WAC or
Notre Dame lost. They would have gotten the better bowl opportunity
simply because they're Notre Dame.''
</P>
<P>
   So instead, the Vols face a wishbone. ``We've faced some options
teams,'' said Vols coach Phil Fulmer, ``but it's been awhile since
we saw any wishbone, or whatever they call it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State, the No.2 seed, also drew a difficult first game,
against mercurial Big East champs, Syracuse. The Orangemen closed
the season with a 66-13 rout of Miami and easily are the best 8-3
team in the nation. K-State coach Bill Snyder declined to answer
questions about the draw.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse flip-flopped spots in the original draw with Air Force
since the Orangemen and Vols already met this season, Tennessee
winning by a point.
</P>
<P>
   The other big first-round game will pit fourth-seeded Florida
State against longtime nemesis Nebraska. ``Dang it,'' said Bobby
Bowden. ``You play all season hoping for an easy first-round game,
and then you wake up and have to play Nebraska.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest culture clash will be the match between
eighth-seeded Wisconsin and Conference USA champ Tulane, which just
finished its first unbeaten regular season. Badger fans in Madison
plan to build a mock Bourbon Street outside Camp Randall Stadium in
honor of Tulane's first-ever game against a Big Ten team.
</P>
<P>
   Other first-round games include Virginia at Pac-10 champ UCLA;
Georgia Tech at No. 5 Ohio State; Arkansas at Arizona; and Texas
A&AMP;M at Florida. The top eight seeds in the tourney host first round
games on Dec. 11 and 12. The eight winners will then be reseeded
for quarterfinal games on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   (subhd) `Results' from Week 1
</P>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Dec. 12 _ The first weekend of Division I-A playoffs
produced exactly what long-time advocates expected, a couple of
thrilling endings and two major upsets.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse beat No. 2 ranked Kansas State, 29-28, when Donovan
McNabb scrambled for a touchdown on a fourth-and-goal play with 18
seconds left in the game. And unheralded Tulane, playing in snow
flurries, upset Wisconsin, 33-31. Green Wave quarterback Shaun King
threw four touchdown passes. Wisconsin back Ron Dayne ran for 201
yards but also had two key fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State held off Georgia Tech, 31-25. The Engineers and
quarterback Joe Hamilton scored 15 points in the last 4:08 and had
the ball at the Buckeye 11 as time expired. And Florida State
needed a touchdown pass with 1:09 left to beat Nebraska, 30-23.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee outlasted a game Air Force, 29-20; UCLA held on to
beat Virginia, 40-27, after blowing part of a 33-7 lead; Arizona
had no trouble with Arkansas, 38-11; and Florida edged Texas A&AMP;M,
22-16.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterfinals are now set for New Year's Day. After the
reseeding to take advantage of traditional bowl tie-ins, No.1
Tennessee will face Tulane in the Sugar Bowl; UCLA will face Ohio
State in the Rose Bowl; Florida State and Syracuse will face off in
the Orange Bowl; and Arizona meets Florida in the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sugar Bowl has been good to us,'' said Vols coach Phil
Fulmer, ``but then we've never had to face Tulane there.'' Wave
coach Tommy Bowden said it may turn out to be a home field
distraction. ``I'm sure we'll be a lot more nervous on our own
field than we were in Madison.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA coach Bob Toledo welcomes the chance to play a traditional
Big Ten opponent, Ohio State. Buckeye players are ecstatic to get
to the Rose Bowl after a mid-season loss to Michigan State appeared
to derail those hopes. ``In the old system, one loss usually knocks
you out of the national title hunt,'' said Andy Katzenmoyer. ``Now,
we're still alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida State and Syracuse will meet in the Orange Bowl.
Arizona, fast becoming the sleeper choice as national champ, will
face Florida in Tempe, a two-hour drive from Tucson. ``Not only do
we have a shot at the title,`` said Dick Tomey, ``but this will
help our recruiting against Arizona State.''
</P>
<P>
   (subhd) More the merrier?
</P>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Dec. 30 A group of college coaches and athletic
directors, led by Penn State's Joe Paterno and Notre Dame's Bob
Davie, say they will ask the NCAA to expand the NCAA playoff field
to 32 in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Paterno spoke after the Nittany Lions' 28-23 Outback Bowl win
over Georgia, and Davie after the Irish were crushed by Texas and
Heisman winner Ricky Williams in the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've needed a playoff format for many years,'' said Paterno.
``It obviously has been a huge success. The response by bowl people
here and elsewhere is that they'd like to be a part of it. And the
way you do that is by extending the field.''
</P>
<P>
   (subhd) Fictitious Final Four
</P>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Jan. 2 The first Final Four in college football has
been set. On Jan. 16, the New Orleans Superdome will host a
day-night doubleheader, with Tennessee facing Arizona and UCLA
clashing against Florida State
</P>
<P>
   Those four teams advanced with wins on New Year's Day that
supported the argument for playing games on the field, not in polls
and computer rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee ended Tulane's cinderella run, 38-22, in the Sugar
Bowl, but not before the Green Wave won a few fans by taking a
14-13 halftime lead. Meanwhile, UCLA shot down Ohio State, 47-36,
in one of the most exciting Rose Bowls ever. Cade McNown and Joe
Germaine combined for 10 touchdowns passes, and McNown also ran one
in.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State ran past Syracuse in the Orange Bowl, 29-20, and
Arizona, in a battle of teams with rotating quarterbacks, toppled
Florida in the Fiesta Bowl, 26-21. All four games were sellouts.
</P>
<P>
   The title game is set for the Rose Bowl on Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the old bowl system had its merits,'' said the
Bruins' McNown after beating the Buckeyes. ``But I think every
college player in America would like the chance to be where we are
right now. For some, the bowls and polls may be important. But all
the players want to do is play.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITAL) We now return you to your BCS-infested universe and
the tedium of the Liberty, Micron and Humanitarian Bowls.(END ITAL)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
