<HEADLINE>
BIG-LEAGUE LESSONS FOR YOUNG CENTER THORNTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He has bounced up and down in the Bruins' lineup for 22
games, playing on the second line some nights, the fourth line on
others. Some nights, he has been benched for a shift at a time;
other nights, he's been benched for an entire period.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the very public education of Boston center Joe Thornton.
At 19, he's learning all the lessons for free. Besides having to
earn his stripes, Thornton is finding out that in this league, if
you don't play well, you won't play at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``What disappoints me is I have to stop playing him to win the
game,'' said coach Pat Burns, who has been reluctant to use
Thornton in tie games or with a one-goal lead. ``If I get to the
second period and nothing is happening on the second line, I've got
to pull him out and put somebody else there. He's got to figure
those things out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a big deal, we'll have to see. When the game gets
tight or the game gets tough, I've got to go with the more
experienced guys. He's been around for a while so he knows what's
going on. Right now the focal point is the team, it's not Joe
Thornton.''
</P>
<P>
   As tough as some outings have been for Thornton, he is head and
shoulders above where he was a year ago. Burns said there is no
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's miles, miles better,'' said Burns. ``He still has a long
way to go, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the season, after a particularly tough game in which
Thornton played precious little, he said he didn't have a clue as
to the message the coach was trying to send him. Monday, however,
Thornton said he gets it much more now than he did then. Though he
didn't necessarily buy Burns's theory that he can't be trusted in a
tight game, Thornton knows he needs to be more consistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to earn his trust, and when I do that, I'll be
playing a lot more,'' he said. ``I have to work harder, maybe. And
be a better defensive player, maybe. So in those close games, I'll
be able to play more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm improved since last year, big-time. Some games I
feel great and then others, I don't have it going. It's part of
learning consistency. If I can stay at a high level every game,
I'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it a function of maturity or experience, but finding that
measure of consistency isn't nearly as easy as it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go on streaks,'' said Thornton, who has two goals and seven
assists. ``I play good for four games and then I'll have two off.
Then I'll go back. Hopefully I'll have more games up at the high
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I play well, I feel like I can do anything. My (off)
days, I feel like crap. Some games I won't have a great first
period but then in my second, I've picked it up. I don't know what
it is, but I have to get better in the all-around game.''
</P>
<P>
   He went to great lengths during the offseason to beef up his
6-foot-4-inch frame. The key to his game is utilizing that extra
bulk.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I just got a couple hits early, I'll be OK, but if the hits
aren't there, I don't play as well as I should,'' said Thornton.
``I think if I get involved early, I have more success during the
game. It's mental, I know that. I know if I want to play, I've got
to hit and I've got to make things happen. He told me I've got to
get more physical. I try to do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
