<HEADLINE>
FINGER INJURY UNDER CONTROL, BLEDSOE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The most famous finger in New England was
resting comfortably Monday, in a softer splint designed for
everyday living rather than the stronger one designed for the
violence of NFL life.
</P>
<P>
   The index finger on Drew Bledsoe's right hand came out of
Sunday's 25-21 ``Angels in the End Zone'' win over the Buffalo
Bills a little sore, still broken in two places, but battle-tested
and apparently ready for the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little sore,'' said the Patriots quarterback, who will
use the splint for another 4-6 weeks, which means the rest of the
regular season and into the playoffs if they should make it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little more sore than it was on Saturday before the
game, but I think it withstood quite a test and I'm pretty happy
with the way it came out of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he is ``out of the woods'' concerning future starts,
Bledsoe said, ``I would say pretty much, unless something strange
happens. I'll keep it in the splint so that it heals up.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe was picked off once, but he managed to throw 43 passes
and absorb four sacks. The interception had nothing to do with his
finger, he said, but there were some passes that went slightly off
the mark that he would normally drill in much better.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a couple of them where I wasn't as accurate as I
wanted to be, but for the most part they were going the right
way,'' said Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   There was much suspense all week about whether Bledsoe would
play, but he seemed to know by the end of the week that he would be
able to throw the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots took it easy on him in practice; he didn't really
participate until Saturday, when he took snaps and handed the ball
off with no problems. He didn't even have to alter the way he put
his hands under center, after talk of him flip-flopping his hands
to protect the finger.
</P>
<P>
   Now the question facing Bledsoe and the coaching staff is what
path to take in preparation for the Pittsburgh game.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said he's ready to go in what will be one of the tougher
road games on the schedule, and a crucial one for AFC playoff
positioning, as the Patriots and Steelers are both 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers beat the Patriots, 7-6, in the playoffs last year,
a game Bledsoe called the toughest loss of his career and the one
that took him the longest to get over.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe was attempting to drive the Patriots to a game-winning
score when he was sacked on a blind-side tackle by defensive end
Mike Vrabel and fumbled. Pittsburgh's Jason Gildon recovered on the
Patriots' 34 with 1:44 left to seal the victory.
</P>
<P>
   It also was the day that Bledsoe took heat for inviting his
agent, Leigh Steinberg, and quarterback client Ryan Leaf into the
locker room. Though devastated by the loss, Bledsoe shared a moment
of jocularity with the two; Bledsoe said it was just a lighter
moment when Steinberg tried to get him to loosen up.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone wants to make up for the pain of that loss, it would
be Bledsoe. So he will heed the advice of his trainers and Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about it today with the trainers on how we're going
to practice him, and I guess we'll just take it a day at a time,''
said Carroll. ``He can perform in the game and get the job done,
but the fact that you wear on it all week if he's throwing, we'd
have no idea of what it would be like on game day. We haven't quite
figured it all out, but it might make sense not to throw him all
week. I don't want to concede that right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach said Bledsoe's absence from the practice field never
altered the game plan, though it appeared the routes got shorter
after the first-quarter interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really didn't alter the game plan we went in with,'' said
Carroll. ``That didn't have anything to do with it. You could see
right off the bat during warmups that he could throw the ball. So I
waited to see him take his first couple of snaps with Dave
Wohlabaugh, and Dave pounded the ball to him and he had no
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said he savored Sunday's game because ``winning in the
NFL is so tough, and winning games like that are so few and far
between.'' But he and his teammates know that can't keep counting
on miracles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really up to us to correct what mistakes we are making
and start playing like we can on both sides of the ball,'' said
Bledsoe. ``We've been fortunate to have the chance to still be in
the running here. Now we have to take our game to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, and his famous finger, already have.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 1952EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
