<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RENO-ICKES (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno seeks
another 60 days to decide if an independent counsel should be named
to investigate whether former presidential aide Harold Ickes
committed perjury when he testified before a Senate committee
looking into alleged fund-raising abuses. By JOHN HENRY. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCANDAL (Washington) _ The White House says it is ``not
very likely'' that President Clinton will accept an invitation to
testify next week before the House Judiciary Committee. Meanwhile,
a Maryland developer refuses to testify about what he knows of
efforts to conceal an encounter between Kathleen Willey and the
president. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-CENSUS (Washington) _ The Clinton administration, in an
oral argument, asks the Supreme Court to allow it to change the way
the government counts people for the 2000 census _ a move that
could alter America's political landscape and redirect billions of
federal dollars. Critics insist any change would violate the
Constitution. By MARK HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ARAFAT (Washington) _ President Clinton, meeting with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, says the United States may give
$400 million in new aid to the Palestinians as part of
international economic assistance. Meanwhile, Arafat accuses Israel
of hampering economic development in Palestinian areas. By NANCY
MATHIS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-REPORTCARD (Washington) _ The federal government gets high
marks for funding promising AIDS research but rates poorly in
promoting prevention programs and helping developing nations battle
the deadly disease, according to a report released by the advocacy
group AIDS Action. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DOMINIQUE-THREAT (Houston) _ Olympic gold medalist Dominique
Moceanu returns to court seeking a protective order against her
father. The young skater says her father has hired a private
investigator to follow her and, allegedly, has promised the
investigator $10,000 to kill either his daughter's current coach or
the man who hid Dominique during her escape from her family last
month. By RON NISSIMOV.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-TAX-STAMPS (Laredo, Texas) _ The U.S. Customs Service says
agents recovered 86,000 counterfeit New Jersey cigarette tax stamps
that a woman tried to smuggle into the country from Mexico. The
thumb-nail size stickers were hidden in gift-wrapped packages
carried by the woman as she crossed into the country in a taxi. By
DANE SCHILLER. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SHUTTLE-COUNTDOWN (Undated) _ The countdown begins for the
Thursday launch of the shuttle Endeavour, which will ferry into
orbit an important chunk of the international space station. The
shuttle crew will attach a U.S. module to a Russian unit that is
already in orbit. By MARK CARREAU. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-TEENS (Austin, Texas) _ A survey showing that nearly
one-third of Texas middle school students and 43 percent of high
school students use tobacco suggests the enormity of the state's
teen smoking problem, which is worse than health officials
expected. The figures include roughly 1 in every 4 sixth-graders.
By CLAY ROBISON. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-ESCAPE (Huntsville, Texas) _ Allan Polunsky, chairman of
the Texas prison board, says he wants to do away with all
work-release programs for death row inmates after the escape of
Martin Gurule. Meanwhile, the search for the convicted killer
continued with few leads. By KATHY WALT and ALLAN TURNER.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LEBANON (Jerusalem) _ Prime Minister Netanyahu reiterates
that Israel will not unilaterally withdraw from Lebanon. But he
voices readiness to reopen peace talks with Syria so long as there
are no conditions. By DEBORAH HORAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-BUSH (Jerusalem) _ Sounding more like a presidential
candidate than he's willing to admit, Texas Gov. George W. Bush
praises Israel as a ``country of genius'' and avoids a brewing
controversy by canceling a planned trip to a West Bank Jewish
settlement. By DEBORAH HORAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-GERMANY (Paris) _ German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's
recent visit to Moscow underscored the special relationship _
sometimes friendly, often bitterly antagonistic _ that has bound
together Russia and Germany for three centuries. By BERNARD D.
KAPLAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ As the impeachment follies lurch
ahead, political reality is at war with panicky partisanship. The
Republicans are in danger of doing in their own party if they force
the Senate to cope with an impeachment trial. The Democrats are
prepared to settle for censure but can't agree on how tough to get.
By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-SNYDER-KANSAS-STATE (Manhattan, Kansas) _ Bill Snyder has
led Kansas State from the program with the most losses in college
football history to the verge of a perfect season. In doing so, he
has installed a rigid, authoritarian system that has alienated many
but has won him a legion of fans on the Kansas prairie. By TERRY
BLOUNT.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-SLOCUM-A&AMP;M (College Station, Texas) _ His team has won 10
games already this season and is playing in the Big 12 Championship
Game for the second consecutive season. Yet coach R.C. Slocum
remains a target of much criticism among Texas A&AMP;M fans, who
believe he is too conservative on offense. By W.H. STICKNEY.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-RANDY-JOHNSON (Houston) _ Fans of the Houston Astros will
get to see Randy Johnson pitch in the Astrodome next season after
all. But they most likely won't be cheering for Johnson next summer
when he returns to the Dome. Johnson, who helped the Astros to the
most successful season in franchise history in 1998, agrees to a
four-year deal to play for the Diamondbacks. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
</TEXT>
