<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5585 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOTEL-AD-COLUMN-NYT     11-30 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOTEL-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: STARWOOD'S BOUTIQUE HOTEL TO MAKE BROADWAY PREMIERE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The letter ``W'' is getting quite a workout these
days as a result of the growing popularity of the World Wide Web.
Not since Elmer Fudd began fulminating about that wascally wabbit
have so many W's been tossed about so, um, wildly.
</P>
<P>
   Now Starwood Hotels and Resorts Worldwide, the giant owner of
lodging brands like Sheraton, Westin and Caesars World, is staking
a claim to the 23d letter of the alphabet by using W as the name
for a planned chain of boutique business hotels. An unconventional
campaign carrying the theme ``Come to your senses'' is promoting
the initial venture, W New York, which formally opens Tuesday night
in midtown Manhattan with the type of party usually thrown for the
premiere of a Broadway show.
</P>
<P>
   That similarity is no accident because the campaign is being
created by an agency that specializes in entertainment and
lifestyle marketing: Grey Entertainment in New York, a unit of Grey
Advertising, which lists among its clients Broadway and Off
Broadway plays and musicals, In Style magazine, Time Warner Cable
and the promotion company SFX Entertainment. The campaign for W New
York ranges widely from the party to print advertisements to
interactive marketing (CD-ROM's and a Web site).
</P>
<P>
   And there was a series of ``teaser'' mailings aimed at piquing
the curiosity of _ and generating buzz from _ influential New
Yorkers like restaurant owners and hair stylists. They were sent
such offbeat items as boxes of Stress Mints (``Relax in a New York
minute'') and scented soap embossed with the words ``pure'' and
``fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to market what we thought would be a unique property,
the goal was to find an agency that could interest a consumer in
the experience of the hotel as opposed to simply selling a
product,'' said Diane Briskin, director for sales and marketing at
W New York, which was created after an $80 million makeover of the
old Doral Inn at Lexington Avenue and 50th Street.
</P>
<P>
   So the campaign is meant to depart from traditional sales spiels
in the lodging field that focus on the proverbial room with a bed.
The goal is to convey an image for the W chain as a hip haven for
nontraditional customers who are patronizing the new wave of
stylish city hotels typified by the Ian Schrager properties like
the Royalton.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the campaign features some of the participants in W
New York: the architect David Rockwell, who designed the hotel; the
restaurateur Drew Nieporent, who is creating the hotel restaurant,
called Heartbeat, and the night life impresario Rande Gerber, who
is overseeing the Whisky Blue lounge.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many companies are calling themselves `entertainment
experiences,''' said Gerry Logue, president at Grey Entertainment,
``whether it's Starbucks or Barnes &AMP; Noble or the sneaker
marketers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than a place to spend the night,'' he added, ``W New
York is meant to be more of an `experiential destination.' We want
to get across the idea that it's a warm place for you personally
but will also serve your business needs.''
</P>
<P>
   One ad, showing a man reading a newspaper in a chair situated
deep in a forest, carries the headline ``A place of magic, mystery
and meetings ...''; another ad, depicting a woman asleep in a bed
floating in the sky, declares, ``It's a whim, a wish come true.''
</P>
<P>
   Some aspects of the campaign, which has a budget of $1 million,
seem somewhat precious or touchy-feely. W New York is billed as a
``sanctuary'' and ``a place where even sleep itself is inspired.''
Descriptions of the spa and fitness center assert: ``Your body is a
temple. This is your place to worship.'' (Though in the
mixed-message department, some ads suggest that ``if you're in the
mood for something hot, hit the lockers and escape into the sauna
or steam room.'') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the campaign is too ethereal, Logue replied: ``We
have never lost sight of the fact the hotel is there to deliver
service. We're putting out a message so the consumer will say,
`That is the place for me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Briskin said that she was pleased with the tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really important we created some form of provocative
image that would catch your eye and get across the experience of
the hotel,'' Ms. Briskin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starwood is launching a brand of business class hotels with
extreme comfort for the traveler seeking an `urban oasis,''' she
added. ``We recognize we will not appeal to people who make a
standard choice.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the name W, which is also to appear on hotels in such
cities as Atlanta, Chicago, Los Angeles, San Francisco and Seattle,
``it stands for `warm' and `welcoming,''' Ms. Briskin said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
