<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEAKER KEEPS DOOR OPEN TO FUTURE TALKS WITH PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran, under fire for
blocking a stadium bill that could have kept the New England
Patriots in Foxborough, said Monday there may still be ways to
prevent the team's departure if a deal with Connecticut falls
apart.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran, in a wide-ranging discussion with reporters in which
he also shot back at BankBoston Chairman Charles Gifford for
criticizing the Legislature's inaction, said a House bill offering
the Patriots $57 million in infrastructure improvements around a
new Foxborough stadium would stay on the table.
</P>
<P>
   That was a remarkable concession for the Mattapan Democrat who
as recently as this fall said the amount of public financing in the
bill would likely be reduced if it came up again for debate.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday Finneran appeared to back off that harsh stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never said take it or leave it,'' he added. ``The door
is always open. It's never been closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would also soften his position on the Senate bill
which calls for Massachusetts to buy $20 million in land from team
owner Robert Kraft, who would lease it back to the state, Finneran
said it was possible, but for a price.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something to be considered,'' Finneran said. ``Again, it
gets the Commonwealth into a position where we're then acting as a
partner with whoever comes forward. The question might be better
asked of the team. I think they've expressed and exhibited a
preference for having no partner in any of their business
endeavors. They like to go it alone. I understand that preference
because partners can be sometimes difficult. It can be a trying
circumstance.''
</P>
<P>
   Finneran said if the state agrees to purchase the land _ the
very reason why he rejected the Senate bill _ it might require
Massachusetts having a direct interest in the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a possibility,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, shrugging off a lighthearted suggestion that he may want
to call the plays, Finneran said, ``Oh gosh no, although I would
have kept (former coach) Bill Parcells, however.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to elaborate on other ``creative'' measures that
could get a stadium deal done in Massachusetts if the Connecticut
legislature does not pass before the year's end the $350
million-plus plan for a new facility in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some (creative ideas) have already been expressed in private
correspondence,'' he added. Finneran would not say when he talked
to Kraft about other possibilities or what they might be.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials said privately Monday they have not heard from
Finneran since early last summer and pointed out they are
prohibited from negotiating with another state under the terms of a
memorandum of understanding Kraft signed Nov. 19 with Connecticut
Governor John Rowland.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran Monday also responded to BankBoston Chairman Charles
Gifford, who wrote an opinion article in Sunday's Globe in which he
lamented how tough it is in Boston to get things done. ``Rivalries
run deep and convictions are firmly held,'' Gifford wrote, without
mentioning Finneran by name. ``Some say our three favorite pastimes
are politics, sports, and revenge. The decision on a new stadium
for the Patriots provided all that and more.''
</P>
<P>
   Finneran, however, said Gifford's critique was off the mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fairly uninformed position,'' Finneran said. ``This is
not boosterville and it should never be boosterville if
boosterville means you go along with any proposal that comes
forward from anyone who describes himself as having a business
plan. It is not inappropriate on behalf of the taxpayers to
question, and to question very closely, the assertions that are
made with regard to tax revenue and the precedent that would be
established by going along with the proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Finneran also said ``there's hardly a businessman who's been
conscious over the past five years that could do anything but
applaud the performance of the Massachusetts House, with the way
we've transformed the reputation and the atmosphere and environment
of the state as a place to do business.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited tax breaks for the banking and mutual fund industries,
along with the deregulation of utilities, for making the state more
attractive for companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``So when somebody says that the incident of the stadium is
indicative of a parochialism or some type of tribal clashes or
warfare that inhibits progress, I think on that issue they're sadly
misinformed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
