u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RANGERS-LEETCH-NY     11-30 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-LEETCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING BIG PLAYS AGAIN, LEETCH IS SEEKING BIG MONEY
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Rangers have had a few unpleasant experiences
with unrestricted free agency for elite veterans since the era
began with the collective bargaining agreement of 1995. Right wing
Pat Verbeek left for Dallas in 1996, a move that depleted the
team's attack. Center Mark Messier went to Vancouver in 1997, a
departure that hurt many feelings, created a leadership void and
led to a disastrous season. Goalie Mike Richter qualified in 1998
and returned to New York only after negotiations with several teams
resulted in allegations of bad faith.
</P>
<P>
   The next candidate for this market is Brian Leetch, the captain
and star defenseman, who could be free on July 1 because he will be
31 and might be without a contract. Should he reach that point,
Leetch could sell his services to any team. Now earning $3,372,500
in the final season of a seven-year deal, Leetch works cheaply for
an established veteran of his skills and status. ``It's worked out
good for the Rangers the last few years,'' Leetch said. In his next
pact, he may command between $6 million and $10 million a season on
a long-term deal and become one of hockey's highest-paid players.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations, which were postponed earlier this year, began in
earnest Monday at Madison Square Garden, involving Neil Smith,
president and general manager of the Rangers; Dave Checketts,
president of the Garden, and Jay Grossman, the business agent for
Leetch. Both sides have said they would not discuss developments.
</P>
<P>
   The timing seems good for Leetch, who twice has won the Norris
trophy as the NHL's best defenseman. Leetch scored a goal in each
of the last two games, a 2-2 tie in Pittsburgh on Friday and a 5-1
victory at home over Nashville, doubling his season total to four.
He and the Rangers will play again Tuesday night against Florida at
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   After struggling last season while disillusioned over Messier's
departure, Leetch seems more settled. In 1997-98, his plus-minus
ratio of minus 36 was the worst on the team. This season, it is
zero, among the Rangers' best. His 14 assists give him 18 points,
among league leaders for defensemen and second on the team behind
Wayne Gretzky's 21. Although the Rangers remain three games below
.500, Leetch and his teammates exude cautious optimism.
</P>
<P>
   Leetch, more comfortable in his captain's role, and his fiancee
celebrated Thanksgiving by serving as hosts for dinner at a local
restaurant for six teammates who had nowhere else to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very good,'' Leetch said of the event. ``All the trimmings.''
The restaurant is owned by the father of his fiancee, Mary Beth
O'Neal. They are to be married next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rangers know I want to be here,'' Leetch said. ``This is
the only organization I've known. I love it here. I'm happy here.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't seem so happy last season, when he inherited the
captain's ``C'' from Messier. When asked whether it was easier to
be captain this season, Leetch said this might be true because the
turnover on the roster means that fewer Rangers remember the
Messier era. As for those veterans who remain, Leetch was asked
whether they are over the hurt. ``Oh, yeah,'' Leetch said. ``We
talked about that.'' The loss of Messier ``was something that a lot
of us disagreed with,'' Leetch said, ``but it didn't affect the way
we went about our business on the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   As for business off the ice, Leetch said he had some anxiety
after Richter's free-agency episode, but that it had since
dissipated. ``I know the situation,'' Leetch said. ``Each day that
passes, my position gets stronger _ the more pressure on the
Rangers to get something done.''
</P>
<P>
   Leetch and Richter are members of the franchise's senior class.
Both were members of the United States Olympic teams of 1988 and
1998. Leetch first wore the blue shirt on Feb. 29, 1988, and has
played in 747 regular-season games, compiling 168 goals and 550
assists. He won the Norris trophy in 1992 and 1997. Leetch finished
last season with 50 points in 76 games, the worst production, on
average, of his career. But he said he did not feel a need to
redeem himself with a strong start this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here long enough, they know my game, and what I can
bring to a team,'' Leetch said. ``That should not be an issue at
all.'' This may not be a point of view that is shared throughout
the Garden administration, which is filled with executives who have
worked elsewhere for much of Leetch's career. But Leetch's solid
start, and the appearance of a happier mood, could prove
reassuring. Leetch lately has been using the word ``fun'' more
often, in various contexts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, they are happy with the direction it is going,'' he
said of his employers, ``and they want me to be a part of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
