</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TENN-MSTATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Martin no Manning, but Vols on the verge of national
championship
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ If Tee Martin ever forgets whose inescapable
shadow he still lives in, he need only stop in the lobby of the
Neyland-Thompson Sports Center on his way to practice. There, in a
corner of the Tennessee Football Hall of Fame Exhibit that includes
national championship trophies and the original manuscript of
``Rocky Top,'' is the newest display. There, behind an orange
railing, is Peyton Mannequin.
</P>
<P>
   It's a life-sized, life-like replica of Peyton Manning, the most
beloved Vol of all. It looks like one of those audio-animatronic
figures at Disney World. No, Peyton's not walking on water; he's
standing casually, ankles crossed, hands stuck in his blue jeans
pockets, wearing an orange-and-white Tennessee letter jacket. He is
Tee Martin's predecessor. Has anyone ever had a tougher act to
follow? ``I don't know of one,'' Tennessee head coach Phillip
Fulmer said. ``It'd be like. . . .'' he paused. ``I can't even
think of an actor's name. 'Gone With The Wind,' maybe, and trying
to be Rhett Butler. But Tee's done it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tee Martin never will approach the passing records Manning
established here. Even with the burgeoning support Martin's
garnered, no one's calling this place UTee. Not yet. But Taumaurice
Nigel Martin has accomplished what no UT quarterback had been able
to do. He has led the Vols to an 11-0 regular season. Now,
top-ranked Tennessee is one game away _ Saturday night's SEC
Championship Game in the Georgia Dome, against Mississippi State _
from playing for the national championship in the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised,'' Martin said. ``This is all we've been
working hard for since the offseason. We knew we had some big shoes
to fill and prove a lot of people wrong _ even our coaches, who had
some questions.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest question? Martin. In four seasons, Manning threw for
11,201 yards, was the Heisman Trophy runner-up and won the Sullivan
Award as the nation's top amateur athlete last year, was picked No.
1 in the NFL draft and inspired dozens, maybe hundreds, of couples
to christen their newborn sons ``Peyton.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter Tee Martin, a junior and one-time Parade high school
All-American from Mobile, Ala., who had thrown all of 16 passes as
a collegian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peyton got us over the hump, brought a lot of recognition to
the program,'' Fulmer said. ``Peyton followed Heath (Shuler), but
this is an even harder act to follow. Peyton is Tennessee's most
decorated player of all time.''
</P>
<P>
   That the job was clearly Martin's entering spring practice
helped. So did the 6-foot-3, 215-pounder's attributes: a strong
arm, speed and durability. And the ability to shrug off the
inevitable comparisons with Manning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play any attention,'' said Martin, who spoke Monday
while wearing ice bags on his left knee and right ankle. ``The guys
accepted me. We didn't dwell on the past or look into the future.
We dealt with the present.''
</P>
<P>
   And Martin dealt deftly with life in Manning's shadow. ``It
wasn't really hard, because of myself,'' he said. ``I understood
people were going to accept me for who I am, not for trying to be
somebody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer and his offensive coordinator, David Cutcliffe, still had
to adjust to a Tee formation quarterback. Early in the season,
Martin _ who's far more mobile than Manning _ was asked to do more
throwing on the run. That was out of character for a kid who worked
out of the shotgun in high school in a run-and-shoot offense.
Martin directed an end-of-the-game drive in the opener at Syracuse
that led to a last-second field goal and a 34-33 victory. In an
epic 20-17 overtime win over Florida, though, he was just 7-for-20
for 64 yards, with a touchdown and an interception. It was after a
17-9 win at Auburn, when tailback Jamal Lewis suffered a
season-ending knee injury, that Martin began to lift his game _ and
his team _ against Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a coach, you say, 'Who's your next best player? Who gives
you the best chance to win?' `` Fulmer said. ``He played OK (in the
first half at Georgia) but had a couple of bad decisions. Since
then, he's been phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin threw two third-quarter TD passes at Georgia to give UT a
22-3 win. After a tidy performance against Alabama, Martin was
indeed phenomenal at South Carolina. He established an NCAA record
by completing his first 23 passes before finishing 23-for-24 for
315 yards and four TDs. In the last six games, Martin has hit 66.9
percent of his passes, 87 of 130 for 1,291 yards, eight TDs and one
interception. He hasn't thrown an interception in 59 attempts and
has just one in the last 147.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the switch from Peyton Manning to Tee Martin has made
them tougher, because they've had to build up their offensive line
and running game,'' Vanderbilt coach Woody Widenhofer said Saturday
after the best ground game in the SEC rushed for 189 yards in a
41-0 rout of Vandy.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that this kid is 11-0,'' Fulmer said. ``He has
had a great year and has been a phenomenal leader for our football
team in a very quiet way. We wouldn't be here if it wasn't for Tee
Martin.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Wilkinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
