</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maxim knows value of happy returns
 &HT;    By Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   All these holiday magazine stories about Christmas, the season,
the shopping, the gift guides ... the eye cruises the newsstand for
something fresh.
</P>
<P>
   Something, as it turns out, exceedingly fresh.
</P>
<P>
   There it is. The December issue of Maxim ($3.50). Page 72. The
title we can't repeat. But the subject ``bares'' summarizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the holiday season, we consciously toss logic onto the
fire with the yule log,'' author Nancy Miller reports in a story
that offers single men and women tips on how to usher in the New
Year with a fling that would make less sense in another season with
less spiked punch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that what the holidays are about?'' Miller writes.
``Giving, receiving, checking out what you got, and if it's not
what you wanted, exchanging it for something else within 30 days.''
</P>
<P>
   REALITY BITES: So you need a bummer to steady yourself after
that headlong advice for the holidays? The cover story of E, The
Environmental Magazine ($3.95) _ ``Baby Boom: Rampant Population
Growth Is Already Straining the Planet's Limited Resources'' _
should do it.
</P>
<P>
   Writer Stephen Sawicki argues that, in the United States,
political activists who link abortion to family planning are
undermining this country's attempt to control population and
therefore planting the seeds for a frightening scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ``Experts expect the world's (populace) to breach 6 billion by
mid-1999. One worst-case projection is that 27 billion people will
be vying for space _ and much more _ by 2150. If so, the lack of
resources will be unmatched by anything short of our scariest
disaster movies.''
</P>
<P>
   TITANS ALL: Time ($2.95) continues its series on 100 people
``who shaped the past 100 years'' with this week's cover story,
``Builders &AMP; Titans: The Most Influential Business Geniuses of the
Century.'' The piece reaches beyond the usual robber-baron suspects
_ no Rockefeller, no Carnegie _ to focus on a few titans you've
probably never heard of (Willis Carrier, for instance, who invented
air conditioning) and a few you wouldn't expect to be revered (mob
boss Lucky Luciano). Only one woman makes the list (cosmetics
magnate Estee Lauder), and no minority makes the top 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``The diversity of America's population and the entry of women
into the work force gives an important competitive advantage over
other countries,'' Norman Pearlstine, editor in chief of Time Inc.,
writes in an introductory essay.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that advantage will be squandered if our largest
corporations don't figure out how to use these resources more
fully.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta cable mogul Ted Turner gets a brief mention as one of
the ``other powers behind the screen'' in a piece on broadcast
pioneer David Sarnoff.
</P>
<P>
   A BIGGER ROLE: In Rolling Stone ($3), actor/musician Will Smith
talks about possible political aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what my calling is, but my performing career is a
pit stop on the way to whatever the next level of greatness is.
And, again, I'm in the middle of this movie thing and loving it,
but Malcolm X, Muhammad Ali achieved a higher level of personal
greatness.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine also profiles ``the biggest new rock band in
America,'' Barenaked Ladies, including this quip from accordionist
Ed Robertson on what he and guitarist Steven Page were like as
kids: ``We were the geekiest of geeks.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE GOOD THINGS: The woman who is as indefatigable as her
publicists, Martha Stewart, is featured on the cover of Newsweek
($2.95) attached to the title story, ``Christmas Goes on Line.''
America's ubiquitous homemaking know-it-all explains that since
launching her Web page last year (http://www.marthastewart.com),
she's seen the future and it's in cyberspace: ``This Christmas
e-commerce is exploding. Why am I betting the future on it?''
</P>
<P>
   VERY FUNNY: The double ``Cartoon Issue'' of The New Yorker
($3.95) includes an interview with actor Tom Hanks, who says he
regrets giving the Clinton legal defense fund $10,000 in light of
the president's admission that he had a relationship with White
House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all honesty, in the light of events since, it would be
awfully hard to say now, `Oh, here, let me help you out with this
problem,''' says Hanks.
</P>
<P>
   And comedian and actor Steve Martin picks up where Woody Allen
has waxed whimsically for decades in film and print, asking the
question: ``Does God Exist?''
</P>
<P>
   You'll laugh, but you won't get an answer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
