<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Violent TV impedes viewer's memory
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Networks that show too much violent programming may wind up
shortchanging themselves. Researchers say violent TV impedes a
viewer's memory of the commercial messages that run during a
program.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Brad Bushman, a psychologist at Iowa State University, found
in a study that most people can't remember ads they watched while
viewing violence in various programs. Two experiments involving 400
people found that those who watched violent shows couldn't remember
brand names of products that were advertised during the programs.
But others who watched nonviolent shows could remember the brand
names.
</P>
<P>
   In another experiment, 320 men reported their moods after
watching four videotapes to determine whether anger obstructed
their ability to remember the content of commercials. As it turned
out, anger did impair memory, says Bushman, in addition to brand
name memory recall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say that the negative effects of television violence on
memory for commercial messages can be partly due to the anger
induced by the violent content,'' Bushman says. ``This is not good
for advertisers because in the time they hope viewers are absorbing
their commercial messages, viewers may actually be trying to calm
their anger brought on by what they just watched.''
</P>
<P>
   His study didn't cover televangelists who preach fire and
brimstone or sporting events in which violence is the norm.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
