<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5601 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOOTED-ART-BOS &LR;      11-30 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOOTED-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM SEEKS ANSWERS ABOUT MONET'S HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE   AND WALTER V. ROBINSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Museum of Fine Arts moved Monday to confirm
revelations that a Monet waterlily displayed in a major Boston
exhibition of the Impressionist's work was probably confiscated by
the Nazis from a prominent French Jewish art collector.
</P>
<P>
   If verified by the Art Loss Register in London and the French
national museum system, which loaned the painting, ``Water Lilies
1904'' to the MFA, the artwork could soon be returned to the
descendants of Paul Rosenberg, the Paris collector who fled the
Nazis and whose heirs live in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The revelations were reported Saturday and Monday in the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   The French national museum system has held the painting since
1950, only a few years after the artwork was repatriated from the
wartime collection of Adolph Hitler's foreign minister, Joachim von
Ribbentrop, who was hanged for war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference Monday, MFA Director Malcolm Rogers
maintained that the museum cannot be held responsible for not
discovering that the painting, which has been held at the Musee des
Beaux-Arts in Caen, may have been plundered from its owners by the
Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a question that should be directed to the French,''
Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the MFA has said it examines the background of its
artwork, whether in permanent exhibit or on loan, Rogers said that
searching for the owner of paintings with ``troubled histories,''
such as the waterlilies work, is often akin to finding a needle in
a haystack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should people be blamed for responsible guardianship?'' he
said. ``That's absolute nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition is scheduled to go next to the Royal Academy of
Arts in London. MFA officials said it is too early to tell whether
that exhibition will proceed as planned.
</P>
<P>
   However, art law specialists widely expect that once the Boston
exhibition is over, the painting will go back to France and the
Rosenbergs will make their claim.
</P>
<P>
   Once the revelations have been confirmed, Rogers said, the MFA
is prepared to add text beside the painting that will discuss the
Nazis' seizure of art during World War II. Now, a title card beside
the work simply states that ``Water Lilies 1904'' was ``recovered
after World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   The painting is one of 1,955 artworks now in French custody that
were recovered from Germany after the war. &UR;  &LR; Ownership of the works
has not been determined by the French, who nevertheless acknowledge
they made no serious effort to find the rightful owners.
</P>
<P>
   Ownership of the waterlily painting between 1933 and 1950 had
been unknown, according to Paul Tucker, guest curator for the Monet
exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how it got into and out of the Rosenberg
collection,'' said Tucker, who teaches at the University of
Massachusetts at Boston. Tucker added that it is unknown how Von
Ribbentrop obtained the painting.
</P>
<P>
   The artwork has been displayed in eight major exhibitions in 10
cities around the world since 1980, Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, the World Jewish Congress said it will demand at a
45-nation meeting on plundered possessions of Holocaust victims,
beginning Tuesday Washington, that France sell the 1,955 artworks
and donate the revenue to Holocaust survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Though the MFA said it fulfilled its obligation, Jonathan
Petropoulos, the Nazi art-looting expert who helped the Globe pin
down the painting's ownership, expressed disappointment Monday that
museums like the MFA do not devote more resources to ensuring that
their art collections do not contain war loot.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the ease with which the Monet's ownership was identified
by the Art Loss Register _ and how quickly he himself matched it to
a photo of the looted work in his own book _ Petropoulos said the
MFA should have been able to do the same thing with its resources.
</P>
<P>
   Had any of the show's curators simply leafed through his book,
``Politics as Art in the Third Reich,'' they would have had
evidence that the painting was plundered, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Petropoulos said the principal failure lies with the French. But
all major museums, he said, ``have wonderful libraries and files
and expertise, and the ability to enlist the cooperation of other
museums and art dealers in search of verifying information. They
need to use those resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Philippe Lefart, a spokesman for the French Embassy in
Washington, said his government is examining the issue. But he said
he expects that the appropriate course will be for the MFA ``to
repatriate the painting to Paris, and to have the claim analyzed
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, the MFA director, said the painting will remain on
display for the duration of the exhibition, ``Monet in the 20th
Century,'' which ends Dec. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg's American descendants, who have backgrounds in
dealing and collecting art, said they have no wish to disrupt the
MFA exhibition, and approve of the museum's decision to keep the
painting on exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Though the family is weighing its legal options, an official at
the US Information Agency said the USIA gave the MFA standard
protection from seizure for all of the loaned works from abroad,
including the Monet waterlily at issue. The protection is granted
to facilitate the international sharing of art.
</P>
<P>
   It was the New York Museum of Modern Art's failure to seek such
protection almost a year ago that opened the door for Manhattan
District Attorney Robert Morgenthau to subpoena two Austrian
paintings on loan to MoMA after two Americans claimed the paintings
were looted from their family during World War II. Those paintings,
by Egon Schiele, remain mired in litigation in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The MFA, in its application to the USIA, notified the agency
that the Monet waterlily from the Caen museum had an incomplete
history and had been recovered after the war. A USIA official said
the MFA's notice that the painting lacked an identifiable owner was
the appropriate step for the MFA to take.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
