<SLUG> BC-VOLVO-CUTBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLVO TO CUT INTERNATIONAL WORK FORCE BY 5,300 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Ky.)  (rl) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Volvo AB, the Swedish maker of cars, buses, trucks and
construction equipment, said Monday that it would lay off more than
7 percent of its work force, or 5,300 workers, by the middle of
next year.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts will be divided between Europe, where Volvo is the last
of the small, high-volume independent automakers, and the rest of
the world, including 1,000 jobs in the United States. Volvo hopes
to save $367 million a year with the cuts, which are the latest in
the European automobile industry as it braces for slower sales in
emerging markets and reduced growth in Europe and the United
States. Volvo, which backed out of a merger with the French
carmaker Renault in 1994, faces tough conditions as it seeks to
expand its international reach, particularly by moving into
developing markets abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite aggressive,'' said John Lawson, an auto industry
analyst at Salomon Smith Barney in London.
</P>
<P>
   He said the cuts were intended to insure growth in operating
profits as Volvo completes an overhaul of global operations it
began in 1997. About 1,900 job cuts are foreseen in Volvo's car
division, and 900 to 1,000 in each of the truck, bus and
construction-equipment divisions. The remaining jobs will be cut at
small units, like marine engines.
</P>
<P>
   Stefan Lorentson, Volvo's spokesman, said management in the
United States would have to decide ``how, when and where'' to make
cuts here. Volvo operates several plants in the United States,
including a truck factory in New River Valley, Va., and one for
marine engines in Lexington, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo has had to act aggressively to resist growing pressures
from reshuffling in the global industry, exemplified by
Daimler-Benz's recent takeover of Chrysler, forming
DaimlerChrylser. Earlier, Germany's BMW swallowed Britain's Rover,
Volkswagen assembled a stable of brands, including Italy's
Lamborghini, and Fiat now controls the sports car brands Alfa
Romeo, Ferrari and Maserati.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo has decided to close three bus factories in Western Europe
and concentrate production at a new plant in Poland. In October,
Volvo said it would close a car assembly plant in Halifax, Nova
Scotia, eliminating 195 jobs. The cuts announced Monday are in
addition to the job losses in Canada. Last month, Volvo paid $150
million to buy Mexico's second-largest bus maker, Mexicana de
Autobuses, and equip it to build buses and cars for the North
American market.
</P>
<P>
   With a 1.7 percent market share, Volvo is Europe's
seventh-largest producer, not including the European units of Ford
and General Motors, and is dwarfed by market leaders like
Volkswagen, the leader, which has an 18 percent market share.
</P>
<P>
   This year, European car sales are expected to rise by 4.6
percent, to 14 million cars, then decline next year, to 13.7
million, as European economies slow, according to the latest car
industry forecast by Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI. In November, BMW said
it would cut 2,500 jobs at a Rover factory in Britain, and Ford
announced it would cut 2,300 jobs in Belgium. Fiat has said it will
slow production for several weeks in the holiday season to reduce
inventories.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Volvo's recent efforts at reorganization, results have
been disappointing. In the first nine months of this year, net
profit dropped to $679.9 million from $1.1 billion in the period a
year earlier, despite a 15 percent increase in sales, to $18.3
billion. At the start of reorganization, Volvo set a goal of 5
percent operating margin, or operating profit as a percentage of
revenue. At the end of nine months, the margin had slipped to 4.2
percent from 4.4 percent in the period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still much work remaining in order for us to be able
to attain our profitability goal,'' said Leif Johansson, Volvo's
president and chief executive. He said Volvo would determine in
December how large a reserve to set aside for the reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo attributes the weakness in profitability to the cost of
introducing models like the S80, a new flagship sedan that entered
the market this fall, and to the slowness of cost-cutting to offset
the drag of an aging product line.
</P>
<P>
   Announcing the disappointing nine-month results, Johansson said
that sales this year had increased ``according to plan'' and that
turmoil in Asia, where Volvo sells 6 percent of its cars, was
offset by increased sales elsewhere. But he acknowledged that the
emerging-market turbulence of recent months had not figured into
Volvo's original strategy. If it continued, he said, Volvo would be
forced to take measures to adjust cost levels to smaller volume
growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
