<HEADER>
A5611 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-LEWIS-C     11-30 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-LEWIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holyfield-Lewis bout set for March 13
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fourteen years ago, a skinny 22-year-old from Atlanta
made his pro boxing debut in Madison Square Garden, winning a
six-round preliminary bout. In ensuing years, Evander Holyfield's
career would take turns and reach levels few would expect from
someone taken the distance by one Lionel Byarm.
</P>
<P>
   On March 13, Holyfield will return to the Garden for only the
third time in his career to meet Lennox Lewis in a
heavyweight-title unification that became official Monday amid
indoor pyrotechnics and the long-winded, pay-per-view verbal
pumpings of promoter Don King. But Holyfield, who for two years has
spoken of unifying the belts as his only tangible goal, made it
clear Monday that the Lewis fight probably will not be his last.
</P>
<P>
   ``No _ it ain't time to retire, yet,'' said Holyfield, 36.
</P>
<P>
   He then softened that only slightly, adding, ``Every time
somebody says they're going to retire and that this is their last
hurrah _ you know, people don't do great on their last hurrah
because they feel sorry for themselves. When I figure it out, I'll
be laying in bed thinking, 'I don't want to fight any more.'''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield's attorney, Jim Thomas, said he expected the fighter
to continue his career. The winner of the the Holyfield-Lewis fight
is contractually obligated to fight Henry Akinwande or the
next-highest WBA contender. There also will be attempts by some to
put together a third fight against Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield said he probably would stick to his recent desire of
fighting until 2000, even though that projection was based in part
on the idea that the Lewis fight would not be put together until at
least late 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield predicted a knockout over Lewis _ ``This will be an
easy fight'' _ and went so far as to say, ``I've already won. The
date and the belt just haven't arrived yet.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked what tangible goal he would have left after fighting
Lewis, Holyfield said, ``It thrills me to know that I'm at a point
in my life I can win because I want to win. . . . I can retire when
I want to retire. I know sometimes people think I'm a gimmick _
like, 'You're just like every other fighter (who delays
retirement).' But I'm not like every other fighter. I have a
purpose. I'm trying to prove it's how a person thinks that
determines whether he wins, not how big he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Age, size and strength will be Lewis' edges in March. The WBC
champion is three years younger, five inches taller at 6 feet 7 and
20 to 25 pounds heavier at 243, pending the weigh-in. But Lewis has
opened as a slight underdog and has been criticized for the lack of
star quality among his previous opponents. The Brit has lost only
once in 35 fights but he has not fought any of the top boxers of
his era _ Holyfield, Tyson, Riddick Bowe, Michael Moorer, George
Foreman, Larry Holmes. His stature also is reflected in his purse _
$10 million, minus promotional fees. That dwarfs Holyfield's $20
million.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' contention is that others have ducked him. He includes
Holyfield in that group, saying Monday that the WBA-IBF champion
``finally was pressured to fight me.'' When a deal fell apart last
year, Lewis' camp said Holyfield was too greedy in asking for $20
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe when Evander wanted to go another route, he went
another route,'' Lewis' manager, Frank Maloney, said. ``He was
running around in a room, and eventually there were no more corners
he could run to.''
</P>
<P>
   But Holyfield took exception to the remarks and pointed out that
Lewis declined to fight him in 1996 before Holyfield fought Bobby
Czyz, which preceded the shot at Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, when you cry for something enough, you finally
get it,'' Holyfield said about Lewis' public demands for the fight.
``The question is: What will you do when you get it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I could never figure out why nobody would fight him. He's a
lot easier than everybody else. I mean, he's a big guy. But you
don't judge a businessman by what his size is. Why would you judge
an athlete that way? It's the smart guy who prevails, and I believe
I'm the smartest guy in the bunch.''
</P>
<P>
   HOLYFIELD VS. LEWIS
</P>
<P>
   _ When: March 13, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Madison Square Garden, New York City.
</P>
<P>
   _ At stake: Holyfield's WBA and IBF heavyweight titles, Lewis'
WBC title.
</P>
<P>
   _ Purses: Holyfield $20 million, Lewis $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Holyfield 36-3 (25 KOs), Lewis 34-1 (27 KOs).
</P>
<P>
   _ Age: Holyfield 36, Lewis 33.
</P>
<P>
   _ Height, weight: Holyfield 6-feet-2, 220 pounds, Lewis 6-7,
243.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tickets: $1,500, $1,000, $750, $500, $250, $100.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV: Pay-per-view; price to be announced.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
