<HEADER>
A5612 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS01-COX     11-30 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chandler status no better in a week
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Falcons coach Dan Reeves didn't appear any
more optimistic Monday than he did a week ago that starting
quarterback Chris Chandler will be able to play in the next game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking at (Chandler's sprained ankle) before the game
(Sunday), he had not made any progress from when he (was helped)
off the field (Nov. 22),'' Reeves said. ''He's going to have to
make a lot of progress (to play Sunday against Indianapolis).''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves chose to start Tony Graziani at quarterback last Sunday
in St. Louis, but replaced him the the second half with Steve
DeBerg. The resulting 21-10 win clinched a playoff spot for the
Falcons (10-2).
</P>
<P>
   For a change, maybe Chandler's uncertain status isn't cause for
despair.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has won three of four games this season in which
Chandler has been missing or injured, beating the Rams (3-9), New
Orleans (5-7) and Chicago (3-9) _ the latter two when Chandler left
with the Falcons holding a lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts (2-10) are another of the NFL's downtrodden.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Chandler doesn't play, the Falcons can break out a
defense that has climbed to a No. 9 ranking in the NFL,
leapfrogging from No. 17 in one week by holding St. Louis to a
season-low 174 yards.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't hurt to have running back Jamal Anderson, whose
career-best 188 yards rushing moved him to No. 2 in the NFL with
1,326 yards, trailing only Denver's Terrell Davis (1,566).
</P>
<P>
   ``To (win) the way we did makes it extra special,'' Reeves said.
``Winning when you don't have your starting quarterback shows that
it could be done, and also we won when we were negative (one) in
turnovers and gave up a kickoff for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things will usually get you beat. But our defense is
playing great ... and Jamal is running great. I had no idea he had
188 yards.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons defense gave up 304 yards two weeks ago in a 31-19
win over San Francisco, but the Bears managed just 210 yards total
offense two games ago.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis had just 40 rushing yards Sunday, the eighth-best
defensive effort in the Falcons' 33-year franchise history, and the
third top-nine effort in team history this season. Overall, they
are ranked No. 2 in the NFL against the run, allowing just 75.9
yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the time you want to start peaking,'' said weakside
linebacker Cornelius Bennett. ``We're getting plays in quicker. And
when you're rushing the ball well (on offense), everything is
easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
