<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECHOSTAR-NEWSCORP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS CORP. MAKES $840 MILLION SALE TO ECHOSTAR
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Still searching for a way out of the direct-broadcast satellite
business in the United States, the News Corp. said Monday it had
agreed to sell two satellites and their orbital license over the
United States to the Echostar Communications Corp. for about $840
million in stock.
</P>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom Inc., which as the MCI Communications Corp. was in
a partnership with the News Corp. to buy the license in 1996, would
receive about $209 million in Echostar stock. If the deal is
approved by regulators, MCI Worldcom and the News Corp.together
will own about 37 percent of Echostar.
</P>
<P>
   For Echostar, the No. 4 direct-broadcast satellite operation,
and the News Corp., Monday's announcement could be seen as a
triumph of pragmatism. The two companies have been locked in
litigation, with Echostar suing the News Corp. for $5 billion,
since their first major deal unraveled last year.
</P>
<P>
   Under the previous agreement, the News Corp. was to acquire 50
percent of Echostar for $1 billion. But that deal fell apart amid
bickering over technical standards and harsh condemnation from the
cable television industry.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath, the News Corp. turned to one of Echostar's
main rivals, Primestar Partners, a satellite broadcasting service
headed by the big cable television operators Time Warner Inc. and
Tele-Communications Inc. Under that pact, valued at $1.1 billion,
MCI and the News Corp. were to sell the satellites and license in
exchange for 31 percent of Primestar.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not happen either. In May, the Justice Department
sued to stop that deal, contending it would help the cable
television industry stifle a potential competitor. The pressure
forced the two companies to drop the agreement in October.
</P>
<P>
   That left the News Corp. back where it started: with
underutilized satellite assets and little motivation to go it alone
(even with MCI) in investing the billions needed to build a
direct-broadcast business. The two satellites it agreed to sell to
Echostar have not even been launched yet.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Echostar was beginning to feel perhaps a bit nervous
about its larger satellite competitors, which in addition to
Primestar include DirecTV, a unit of the General Motors Corp. In a
conference call with reporters Monday, Echostar executives also
repeatedly mentioned the looming combination of
Tele-Communications, the No. 2 cable television operator, with the
AT&AMP;T Corp., the No. 1 telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   So the News Corp. and Echostar agreed to make peace. The
companies said they would drop their litigation upon completion of
their deal. The News Corp. also agreed to buy 500,000 set-top
converter boxes from Echostar and to allow Echostar to distribute
the Fox News television channel.
</P>
<P>
   Investors cheered the agreement Monday, sending Echostar's
shares to a 52-week high of $38.8125, up $3.8125, in Nasdaq
trading. The News Corp.'s American depository receipts closed at
$28, down 37.5 cents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 2014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
