</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-605&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS FALL 2.3 PERCENT IN WAVE OF PROFIT-TAKING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks had their worst trading session in two months
on Monday, as waves of profit-taking swept through the market.
</P>
<P>
   The declines were broad-based, from computer and drug makers to
banks and financial-service companies and highly speculative
Internet-related stocks.
</P>
<P>
   And it occurred on a day when a sharp drop in commodity prices
sent bond prices soaring and interest rates sharply lower. By late
in the day, yields on the government's benchmark 30-year bond stood
at 5.07 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By the close of trading, the Dow Jones industrial average was
down 216.53 points, or 2.3 percent, to 9,116.55. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index dropped 28.70 points, or 2.4 percent, to
1,163.63.
</P>
<P>
   And the Nasdaq Composite index, which is loaded with
computer-related shares, including a number of Internet companies,
fell 66.90 points, or 3.3 percent, to 1,949.54. Twice as many
shares fell as rose on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had been expecting a correction in the market averages,
which had risen almost without pause since early October.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a wonderful run and prices have risen a lot,'' said
Jack Shaughnessy, the chief investment strategist at Advest Inc. in
Boston. ``For people who have made a lot of money in the last few
weeks, it's time to take some profits. But in my judgment the bull
market still has very powerful legs.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts at ISI Group, a New York research and consulting firm,
put the case for a continued run in stocks into historical
perspective Monday. In a weekly letter to clients, ISI noted that
the Dow's 23 percent gain since early October, to a record 9,374.27
on Nov. 23, has been matched just four times in the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Following those four prior surges _ which occurred in 1975,
1982, 1986 and 1991 _ the Dow continued to rally over the next
three months by an average of 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is most striking is that the prior surges were all in
economic environments similar to today's,'' the analysts wrote.
``Namely, all were financial crisis environments with weakening
global activity, declining profits, Fed easings, accelerating money
growth and slowing inflation. Judging by the four prior rallies,
the current rally will continue until the Fed tightens'' monetary
policy.
</P>
<P>
   But computer manufacturers, whose stocks have been among the
year's biggest gainers, were smacked lower. Dell Computer, which is
up more than 175 percent this year, fell 3, to 60 13/16. Apple
Computer, which has gained more than 150 percent since the start of
January, slumped 3 1/8, to 31 15/16. And IBM, which is up more than
50 percent, fell 4 7/8, to 165 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Drug companies, another group that has enjoyed good gains in the
last two months, also suffered. Merck fell 3}, to 155 1/8. Pfizer
dropped 2 1/16, to 111 15/16. And Bristol Myers Squibb lost 1 3/8
to 122.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks, big gainers since early October, also lost
ground. J.P. Morgan, a Dow component, fell 4 9/16, to 106 7/8.
Chase Manhattan lost 2, to 63 7/16. And Merrill Lynch dropped 5, to
75.
</P>
<P>
   Among financial stocks, Bankers Trust, which is being acquired
by Deutsche Bank for $93 a share, was an exception, with its shares
rising 1 7/16, to 87, after boards from both companies approved the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the sharp drop in Internet-related stocks that was
perhaps the session's most eye-catching development.
</P>
<P>
   Among analysts and traders, these stocks have been a source of
wonder _ and fear _ in recent weeks, because their rapid ascent has
been based on little more than hope. According to many, a sharp
correction among these stocks has been long overdue.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Profit-taking doubtless caused some selling of these stocks
Monday. But reports and rumors that a number of brokerage houses
and clearing agents were raising their margin requirements on some
of the hottest Internet stocks may also have played a role.
</P>
<P>
   Salomon Smith Barney told clients Monday that it had raised its
margin requirements on a number of Internet stocks, including Ebay,
Books-A-Million and Audio Book Club. And DLJ Direct, the online
stock brokerage owned by Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, also
increased margin requirements on a number of Internet issues.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of trading in these issues is done by retail investors.
Any change in margin requirements would make it more expensive for
individuals seeking to speculate in these issues from doing so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raising the margin requirements is a prudent thing to do,''
said one trader who specializes in Nasdaq stocks and asked not to
be identified. ``If you were running a casino, you would be doing
the same thing. And I think it was an aggravating factor in the Net
stocks. This was overdue, but it was anyone's guess when it would
happen or what the catalyst for it would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the Internet stocks, Egghead.com, which operates three
retail Web sites, and had more than doubled in the last three
trading sessions, fell 6 1/8, to 25 1/2. Amazon.com, the biggest
seller of books and music over the Internet, fell 24 5/8, to 192.
America Online dropped 7 5/16, to 87 9/16. Onsale Inc., a Web
auctioneer, fell 36 1/8, to 61 1/2. And Yahoo slumped 24 15/16, to
192.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
