<HEADER>
A5618 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     11-30 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 y LEAH GARCHIK  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; SO NICE TO SEE YOU &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If, upon making your acquaintance,  &UR; President Clinton &LR;  looks at
you and says, ``Nice tie,'' he's really saying, ``Screw you,''
writes  &UR; Jeannette Walls &LR;  of MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; George Stephanopoulos &LR;  decoded the statement for  &UR; David &LR; 
 &UR; Maraniss &LR; , who wrote the Clinton bio ``First in His Class, &LR; '' and
happened to mention to the former White House aide that the
president had given him that compliment.
</P>
<P>
   Many wearers of ``nice ties'' turn out to be journalists.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A ROSY LOOK AT HILLARY CLINTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hillary Clinton &LR;  agreed months ago to pose for the cover of
Vogue months ago &LR; , writes editor  &UR; Anna Wintour &LR;  in the December
issue, and be interviewed to promote her Save America's Treasures
project. Despite the eruption of presidential scandal, the posing
took place and the story went forward.
</P>
<P>
   When  &UR; Annie Leibovitz &LR;  suggested that the first lady might be
pictured reading a newspaper, she was informed by a White House
aide: ``The first lady does not read newspapers.'' Instead, she
posed in evening clothes and ``at work on the Truman balcony'' in
 &UR; Ralph Lauren &LR;  shirt and carefully applied eyeshadow. The story
itself is gushingly reminiscent of  &UR; Tina Brown &LR; 's effusions after
attending a White House party. Some sample observations from  &UR; Ann &LR; 
 &UR; Douglas &LR; ' essay:
</P>
<P>
   _``When you talk to her, there is no rind, no crust of official
pretense barring the quick of the person from access. She's right
there, alive from the start _ the first spadeful comes up gold.''
</P>
<P>
   _``I was struck by her height, the level quality of her
blue-eyed gaze, her erect, head-held-high carriage. ... She's in
that small select group of women who are far more beautiful at 50
than they were at 30.''
</P>
<P>
   _``She is simply smarter than any press person she talks to.''
</P>
<P>
   _``She has charisma, an inescapable aura magically altering the
atmosphere she occupies.''
</P>
<P>
   But Vogue is fickle. While the story heaps praise on this
month's cover girl, it takes a sideswipe (see below re swipe) at
the object of last month's affection, November cover girl  &UR; Oprah &LR; 
 &UR; Winfrey &LR; . Mrs. Clinton is an icon of dignity, says the magazine,
even in this ``tell-all post-modern age of Oprah Winfrey and
 &UR; Jerry Springer &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NAZARETHLAND IN THE WORKS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ground has been broken for a biblical theme park on a 20-acre
site in Nazareth, reports the Times of London. This facility will
feature people working on the land, pruning olive trees and
pressing the oil and doing other things people did in the time of
Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors may have the option of dressing in robes and sandals
and joining in the fun.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jimmy Carter &LR;  and  &UR; Pat Boone &LR;  are among those helping to raise
money for this reproduction of life in biblical times, which will
include a study center, an interactive museum and a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Cover lines on the latest issue of Glamour: ``Your Most
Intimate Info,'' ``Holiday Wow! ... Sexy Dresses Under $100,''
``Drinking and Your Love Life,'' ``12 Rules for Happier Love.''
Inside, a poll for readers: ``Are we too sex obsessed?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Sandy Schaaf &LR; 's bumper sticker brainstorm: ``Eat a Horse _ Go
to Jail!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Johnny Carson &LR;  wears his hair in a ponytail now, reports the
New York Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   - Well, the place Personals didn't look in preparing yesterday's
item about ATM cards was the dictionary.  &UR; William &LR; 
 &UR; Quick &LR;  points out that to swipe means ``to hit with a swinging
motion''; its use as a synonym for steal is strictly informal.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; HOLIDAY GIFT GUIDE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If ``The Nutcracker'' ballet seems begging for verisimilitude,
 &UR; Jean Wauxell &LR;  suggests the holiday gift that makes it all real:
taxidermied mice, from Paxton Gate in San Francisco. Single mice,
stuffed versions of the creatures one pays exterminators to
vanquish, cost $38 to $45.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Meanwhile, Bloomingdale's is selling Moi, ``the delightful
new perfume of Miss Piggy.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``I saw myself playing next to Willie Mays. ... I couldn't &LR; 
 &UR; believe it when the coach, Leo Durocher, came over to me and &LR; 
 &UR; told me there was no point coming back for the second day of &LR; 
 &UR; tryouts. ... I had to settle for being a writer.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; - &LR;  Novelist &UR; Tom Wolfe  &LR; tells New York gallery curator  &UR; Baird &LR; 
 &UR; Jones  &LR; about the time he tried out to be a pitcher for the New York
Giants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
