<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-FREEAGENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIOLES STAND BETWEEN METS AND FREE-AGENT HELP
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Baltimore Orioles' sudden interest in Albert
Belle last week compelled the Yankees to sign Bernie Williams. Now
the Orioles' machinations are having a major impact on New York's
other team, the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   B.J. Surhoff, the free-agent outfielder, will meet with Mets
officials Tuesday, but the sense of several baseball executives is
that the Orioles will lure Surhoff back into their lineup by week's
end. If Surhoff is the priority for the Mets, then Robin Ventura is
second in line _ and the Orioles are bidding heavily for Ventura,
as well. And the Boston Red Sox are also interested in Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   It is believed the Orioles have increased their three-year,
$13.5 million offer to Surhoff to $14.5 million _ an annual salary
of $4.5 million for each of three years, plus an option for a
fourth year with a $1 million buyout. Surhoff, who also has a
three-year offer from the Mets, could qualify automatically for a
fourth year with the Orioles if he plays in a predetermined number
of games (perhaps 140) in the contract's third year. He also has a
four-year offer for about $17 million from the Pittsburgh Pirates.
Last year, the 34-year-old Surhoff hit .279 with career highs of 22
home runs and 92 runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were hosts to Brian Jordan two weeks ago, eventually
made him an offer and seemed to accomplish little more than
increase his negotiating leverage before the outfielder signed with
Atlanta. Steve Phillips, the Mets' general manager, said he felt
there were similarities in this meeting with Surhoff, ``but I also
see some differences, too.''
</P>
<P>
   If not Surhoff, the Mets could sign Ventura. But the Orioles are
believed to be offering Ventura a four-year, $32 million contract,
or $1 million a season more than the Mets. The Orioles, expected to
announce the signing of Belle Tuesday, could use Belle in left
field, Surhoff in right and Ventura at third base and move Cal
Ripken to first base.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips is preparing for the possibility that he will not sign
either Surhoff or Ventura. He expects to meet with left fielder
Rickey Henderson this week and has had constant talks with the
Milwaukee Brewers about second baseman Fernando Vina, who would
fill the need for a leadoff hitter.
</P>
<P>
   If the Mets sign Ventura, Edgardo Alfonzo will move from third
base to second. Phillips said that he had spoken with Alfonzo and
that he would readily agree to change positions. Alfonzo, Phillips
said, asked that the Mets tell him as quickly as possible what
position he will be playing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
