<HEADLINE>
INS TO TEMPORARILY RELEASE 3,000 CENTRAL AMERICAN IMMIGRANTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JO ANN ZUNIGA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ About 400 Honduran and other Central American
immigrants locally, and up to 3,000 nationally, will be temporarily
released by the Immigration and Naturalization Service starting
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   INS officials said the Central American governments cannot
receive any deportations at this time because of the ravaged
conditions in the aftermath of Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   Only those immigrants with nonviolent backgrounds will be
released to supervision of next of kin or nonprofit agencies until
the United States can deport them to their country of origin, said
local INS spokeswoman Luisa Aquino.
</P>
<P>
   ``This does not include temporary protected status or work
authorization,'' she said. ``But we do want to make sure they are
linked with family or an organization that can provide shelter.''
</P>
<P>
   A main reason for the release was to give the immigrants a
better chance of learning whether their families in their countries
survived the storm.
</P>
<P>
   But practically, Aquino said, space would have become a problem
if INS would have simply continued storing the immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are not a threat to society, it is unfair to keep them
behind bars until they can be sent home,'' Aquino said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 Central Americans, mostly Hondurans, held a brief
hunger strike in November in the Bayview Detention Center in South
Texas. They wanted to be deported to their damaged homelands so
they could find out about their families.
</P>
<P>
   Aquino said those protesters will also be considered for
release.
</P>
<P>
   ``The detainees will be released on a case-by-case basis,'' she
said. ``They will remain under the authorization of the INS and
under proceedings for removal.''
</P>
<P>
   INS Commissioner Doris Meissner said in Washington that the
agency has been working with non-governmental organizations active
in the immigrant community to seek their assistance in this
program.
</P>
<P>
   INS earlier extended the temporary suspension of deportations of
illegal immigrants from the Mitch-devastated countries of El
Salvador, Guatemala, Honduras and Nicaragua through Jan. 7.
</P>
<P>
   But some immigrant advocates want the government to allow the
immigrants temporary protected status.
</P>
<P>
   This status, which can be granted up to 18 months and would
allow the immigrants to work, could be given to them because it
applies to citizens of countries affected by ``environmental
disaster resulting in a substantial, but temporary, disruption of
living conditions,'' advocates said.
</P>
<P>
   Benito Juarez, spokesman for the Houston Immigration and Refugee
Coalition, said, ``We believe the releases will help a little bit,
especially for those detained to find out about their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they need to be able to work to help those families.''
</P>
<P>
   Immigrant advocates are encouraging congressional
representatives and Attorney General Janet Reno to support
temporary protected status, Juarez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will probably be reviewed again once the Jan. 7 extension
is ending,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
