A5633 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-STEEL-PA     11-30 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-STEEL-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;       LOCAL STEEL WORKERS PRESS LAWMAKERS TO STOP ILLEGAL TRADE
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Nov. 30 -- When Darren Morgan checked his weekly
work schedule at the Fairless Works Steel Mill the day before
Thanksgiving, all it said was, ``report to personnel.'' He knew
what it meant. He had been laid off.
</P>
<P>
   The Bucks County steel worker didn't testify at a hearing of the
U.S. Senate Steel Caucus focusing on a surge of foreign steel
imports that domestic officials believe has caused the layoffs. But
industry officials who did, blamed foreign steel companies for
selling their product so cheap, that domestic companies can't
compete and are having to cut back production.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign steel industry officials say they are not to blame.
Instead they blame an over-supply of domestic steel caused by last
year's General Motors strike, and other economic conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign steel producers sent 3.9 million net tons to the U.S. in
September -- approximately a 49 percent increase in imports from
the same month last year, according to the American Iron and Steel
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pennsylvania's Republican Senators Arlen Specter and
Rick Santorum are crafting legislation to stem the tide, they
called on President Clinton to enforce trade laws, possibly through
sanctions, to offer more immediate help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a consensus here that U.S. trade laws are
being violated,'' Specter said. ``Dumping is unfair, illegal and it
has to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Specter, said when Congress reconvenes, the
senator would immediately propose a bill that would allow a steel
company to get a temporary restraining order from a federal court
to stop ``unfair trade practices'' if they can prove they might be
damaged by them. He proposed similar legislation in 1993. ``That
way a steel worker can get immediate help if he feels his job is in
danger,'' said Specter spokesman John Ullyot. ``It is a fast legal
recourse while we wait for other legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Commerce Department is expected to issue a preliminary
decision in mid-February on whether Japan, Russia and Brazil are
engaged in steel ``dumping'' -- selling their product for below
production cost, or below what it sells for in its home market.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials told the panel they are working to
speed consideration of the steel industry's case against those
countries. They said the White House is also calling for other
countries to trade fairly.
</P>
<P>
   But Washington can't help steel workers soon enough, Morgan, the
laid-off from Fairless Works, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if something isn't done soon, more people will lose
their jobs.'' said Morgan, who traveled to Washington to watch the
hearing. ``It is a crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Steel announced recently it would cut production by 70
percent at its Fairless Works site, in Bucks County, outside
Philadelphia. About half of the plant's 850 workers could lose
their jobs, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Bethlehem Steel mills in Steelton, where there are 600
employees, are operating on reduced schedules because of lower
order entry and shipments, said Curtis Barnette, Chairman and CEO
of Bethlehem Steel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
