<DOCNO> NYT19981130.0427 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5652 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      11-30 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROBLEM'S CLEAR IF YOU DO THE MATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ I know how you are. You heard about the $53 million,
four-year contract the Arizona Diamondbacks gave baseball pitcher
Randy Johnson and you want to do the math. How much does that
figure per game? Per win? Per strikeout?
</P>
<P>
   You know it's not good for you. You know that fiddling with the
numbers will only make you frustrated, angry and even more
convinced our priorities are completely out of whack.
</P>
<P>
   Please, don't give in to the temptation. Don't submit to the
abuse. Don't torture yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Let me do it for you.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's average yearly salary will be $13.25 million, the
second-highest in baseball behind Mo Vaughn's $13.33 million. The
difference between a first baseman and a pitcher, however, is that
an infielder could appear in most of the season's 162 games while a
pitcher will start, at most, 40.
</P>
<P>
   So, every time he takes the mound Johnson will earn $331,250.
</P>
<P>
   More or less.
</P>
<P>
   He won 19 games last year. If he gets 20 victories during the
1999 season, they'll be worth $662,500 per win.
</P>
<P>
   It goes on.
</P>
<P>
   He had 329 strikeouts in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   If he matches that number next season, each strikeout would earn
him $40,273.55.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans don't earn a strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   An individual with a two-strikeout income is living very well. &QL; 
Enough for tickets? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three strikeouts for a salary and you might be able to afford
tickets to a Diamondbacks game _ provided you don't want a beer and
a hot dog.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau says the average middle-income, married family
takes home about $55,000 a year. And that's with two paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   Even those people, I'd guess, try occasionally to get to a
ballgame. You might be one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you were at Bank One Ballpark during ``Fan Appreciation
Weekend'' last season, when the team announced a 12.1 percent
ticket price increase.
</P>
<P>
   You might know the Diamondbacks already signed pitcher Todd
Stottlemyre to a $32 million, four-year contract, and that the team
will pay third baseman Matt Williams $8 million next season, and
shortstop-second baseman Jay Bell $6 million, and pitcher Andy
Benes $6 million, and outfielder Bernard Gilkey $5 million. And so
on.
</P>
<P>
   You may even know that season ticket holders are being required
to pay regular season prices for two ``exhibition'' baseball games
next year.
</P>
<P>
   You don't like it, but you feel powerless to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   So, when a player like Randy Johnson is signed to a fat
contract, you do the math and complain about our priorities,
accepting it as ``the way things are.'' &QL; 
Some alternatives &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As if that's the way things must be.
</P>
<P>
   There's an organization in California called Alternative Gifts
International (www.altgifts.org), which, like many other charitable
organizations, puts price tags on human behavior other than tossing
a 90 mph fastball.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the cost of keeping one homeless person in a
shelter for one night is $11.
</P>
<P>
   Caring for a Romanian child with AIDS, for a week, is $6.
</P>
<P>
   Donating a couple of chickens to a starving Laotian family is $3
_ a buck less than the cost of a hot dog at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   These things aren't unconnected. They're joined by money.
</P>
<P>
   That's why every time a marquee player is signed to an
unheard-of contract, you want to do the math.
</P>
<P>
   You know that fiddling with the numbers will only make you
frustrated and angry.
</P>
<P>
   You might even believe it's unfair to compare professional
baseball salaries with the price of running a homeless shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as unfair _ but not quite _ as the fact that one Randy
Johnson strikeout earns enough to provide a night's sleep in a warm
bed, under a roof, for about 3,500 people.
</P>
<P>
   E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at
ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 2044EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981130.0428 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
