<SLUG> BC-JUVENILE01-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA'S JUVENILE JUSTICE SYSTEM ACTUALLY AMONG AMONG BEST, FIRM
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By HAL MATTERN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Arizona's much maligned juvenile justice system
actually is ``one of the best in the country,'' a consulting firm
hired to audit the system said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Deloitte Consulting said that although the various state
agencies that deal with juvenile offenders need to better
coordinate their efforts and encourage more family involvement, the
system overall is more effective than most.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is not the best, it is one of the best in the country,''
Bobbie Wilbur, a Deloitte partner, told members of the Joint
Legislative Committee on Juvenile Justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could it be better? Yes,'' Wilbur said. ``But you have a very
sound system.''
</P>
<P>
   The state is paying Deloitte $750,000 to conduct the audit with
an eye toward improving the juvenile justice system, which has come
under heavy criticism in recent years. A draft of the audit was
released to the committee Monday, with the final version due in the
next week or two.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the committee members and officials of the juvenile
justice system praised the audit. Some of the Legislature's
harshest critics of the state's juvenile corrections program said
they hadn't read the report Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But one committee member, Sen. Tom Patterson, R-east Phoenix,
said he was concerned that the audit focused on the Legislature's
role in managing the system, not on the actual programs provided.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is precious little in (the audit) about what works,''
Patterson said. &QL; 
Much of the criticism of the juvenile justice system has been aimed
at the state Department of Juvenile Corrections, which has had
three different directors since it was formed in 1990 and currently
is being run by an interim director.
</P>
<P>
   The agency was forced to operate under a federal court order
from 1993-97 over allegations of civil rights violations. The
department spent nearly $35 million to ease overcrowding and
improve conditions at the state's juvenile facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last December, Eugene Moore was forced out as director of
juvenile corrections after a Maricopa County grand jury report
accused the agency of putting the public at risk by releasing
violent offenders before their sentences were completed.
</P>
<P>
   David Gaspar, who was the department's assistant director, has
been acting director since Moore left. Gov. Jane Hull has been
criticized for not naming a permanent director.
</P>
<P>
   But the audit notes that the Department of Juvenile Corrections
is only one piece of the state's juvenile justice system. Also
playing important roles are county juvenile justice programs,
juvenile courts, and the state departments of Economic Security,
Behavioral Health Services and Education, which provide a number of
prevention and intervention programs.
</P>
<P>
   All those programs are operating successfully, keeping costs
down and the recidivism rate low, the audit said. But the lack of
coordination, collaboration and communication between those
agencies is one of the main problems facing the system, the audit
said.
</P>
<P>
   The report recommended that a systemwide computer information
system be created to provide accurate and consistent data to all of
the agencies involved.
</P>
<P>
   Wilbur also emphasized the need for more involvement by the
families of juvenile offenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are not going to solve this problem until you get families
involved throughout the juvenile justice system,'' she said,
acknowledging that ``that's a tough parent group to go after.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take substantial work to bring them in,'' Wilbur
said. ``But I think it is imminently critical if you are going to
keep kids out of the system. The focus has to be more on youth and
family, not just youth.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 2053EST &QL; 
