<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES HEAR ARGUMENTS OVER CENSUS METHODS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIANNE FLYNN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Is a statistical sample as good as a head count? Is
estimating population legal? Is the argument over methods a
political tussle or a legitimate legal conundrum?
</P>
<P>
   With time running out before the counting is to begin, the U.S.
Supreme Court on Monday started to sort out the controversies
surrounding the taking of the 2000 census, particularly whether a
statistical sampling method can be used to determine population.
</P>
<P>
   The justices heard arguments from two groups opposing
statistical sampling, a group of citizens in six states whose
congressional delegations are likely to change with new census
figures and the GOP-controlled House of Representatives, which
compromised with the president in a census funding impasse by
letting the Supreme Court decide the issue.
</P>
<P>
   That approach wouldn't get any further if it were up to Justice
Antonin Scalia. He indicated he'd let the Clinton administration's
Census Bureau and the Congress battle it out on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like injecting us into a battle between two political
branches,'' the conservative justice said from the bench during
Monday's argument. ``I think they will survive, but I'm not sure we
will.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, though, he and Chief Justice William Rehnquist zeroed
in on the crux of the case: the Constitution's call for an ``actual
enumeration'' of the population every 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist wondered whether that meant finding ``a true number.''
And if a true number could be found using modern scientific
methods, as Solicitor General Seth Waxman said, ``Why do I need a
census, then?''
</P>
<P>
   Actual enumeration, argued Maureen Mahoney for the House, was
what the framers of the Constitution `'intended from the outset.''
Even in 1790, when the Census Act was passed, estimating practices
were common, though not as sophisticated as the one the Census
Bureau would employ in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney was so insistent on a nose-by-nose count, that when
asked by Justice John Paul Stevens what census-takers should do
when faced with an apartment filled with uncooperative people of
ill-repute whose neighbors refused to discuss them, she said they
should not be counted at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your honor, they (census-takers) can't guess,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Carvin, arguing on behalf of the citizens, told the
court that the accuracy of the statistical method, while certainly
in dispute, really doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of its relative accuracy, it's illegal and
unconstitutional,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The justices will try to decide the issue by March, but said in
court Monday they will be lucky to rule by June. That could have a
significant effect on the Census Bureau, which is well into
planning and implementation of the census and is counting on using
sampling. Actual counting would not begin until after April 1,
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Glavin, president of the Southeastern Legal Foundation
and one of the citizen plaintiffs, said after the argument that the
integrity of the census must be ensured and statistical sampling
will not do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will create 27 million mythical people and they will
decide what those 27 million mythical people look like and they
will decide where those 27 million mythical people live,'' Glavin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Miller, chairman of the House oversight subcommittee on
the census, said everyone wants an accurate count, but because the
level of trust in the Clinton administration has been eroded by
various scandals, it is even more imperative to use tried-and-true
counting methods to determine population and restore trust in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990 census missed about 1.6 percent of the population or
about 4 million people, most of them minorities, according to the
Census Bureau. In Arizona, the net undercount was 89,438. Of those,
32,223 were Hispanic and 40,374 were children.
</P>
<P>
   The argument is not mere legal and political hairsplitting. At
stake are money _ the federal government gives states more than
$180 billion each year based on population _ and political power,
both in Congress and in shifting political boundaries within
states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
