u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-TV-KING     11-30 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TV-KING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING PUMPS UP THE VOLUME ON HOLYFIELD-LEWIS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Don King was selling the Evander Holyfield-Lennox
Lewis heavyweight unification fight on March 13, selling Madison
Square Garden as the ``temple in the mecca of boxing,'' but mostly
selling himself as a bejeweled Job set upon by evil forces who had
kicked him around but didn't finish him off.
</P>
<P>
   This is King's post-Mike Tyson period, so he must sell the
Holyfield-Lewis fight with ferocity. He is not guaranteed a profit
from the promotion, so he must cajole pay-per-view purchases above
reasonable expectations to cash in.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are you going to sell two million buys? I predict for you
two million buys,'' he bellowed Monday from a dais on the Garden's
arena floor. ``You say: `What is this crazy guy saying? Is he out
of his mind?'''
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, no fight has ever rung up 2 million pay-per-view
purchases _ the closest was 1.89 million for the second
Holyfield-Tyson bout _ and Holyfield's pay-per-view appeal has
faltered when he has not faced Tyson, Riddick Bowe or George
Foreman. Lewis' pay-per-view appeal is unproven, at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``You say this man can't sell, you say that man can't sell,''
King said, noting criticism that Holyfield and Lewis need foes who
are more charismatic to set pay-per-view records. ``Don't take my
right to have my own opinion away from me.''
</P>
<P>
   But King, well, he can sell. It's no surprise that his slogan
for the fight is ``Kings' Crowning Glory.'' He doesn't mind making
you think he's one of the kings, but the threesome is actually
Holyfield and Lewis, the heavyweight title holders, and Budweiser,
which calls itself the king of beers and is the fight's major
sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   A more realistic assessment of the Holyfield-Lewis pay-per-view
comes from Seth Abraham, the president of Time Warner Sports and
HBO Sports, which will carry the fight on its TVKO unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``One million,'' he said, up from his 700,000 estimate a year
ago. Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``A dearth of big fights, no interim fights for Lennox and
Evander, and Don is engaged because his profit comes from working
the pay-per-view,'' he said. ``Over 850,000, he's in profit.''
</P>
<P>
   For King and Abraham, the fight is detente after eight years of
war. King nixed a multifight extension of a Tyson deal at HBO in
1990 and fled for Showtime, because of Tyson's animosity toward
Larry Merchant, an HBO/TVKO analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, King and Abraham have existed at boxing's equivalent
of Defcon 1, the highest state of readiness for nuclear war.
Renewing their relationship was, Abraham said, ``like dating your
ex-wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Said King: ``We've never argued, never had cross words. We
fought over a broadcaster, not business. This is a great reunion
with Seth.''
</P>
<P>
   One executive of the King-Abraham talks, said: ``It wasn't a
lovefest. There were moments of genuine anger and frustration. Don
had to temper his autocracy. He's ruled the roost at Showtime. He
knows he can't do that at HBO.''
</P>
<P>
   Abraham said that during a dinner over shrimp in garlic sauce
and tangerine beef in October at his apartment with King and Jim
Thomas, Holyfield's lawyer, Abraham became convinced that the final
pieces of the fight puzzle were fitting in. Late that night, Milt
Chwasky, Lewis' lawyer, joined them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all business, no theatrics,'' said Abraham, who
admitted that he was a mite rusty in his King-handling skills. ``My
Kingology degree had lapsed.''
</P>
<P>
   Chwasky recalled an incident several weeks ago when he worried
that the deal would fold. ``Don wanted to pay Lennox the last $2
million in a check, not with a letter of credit,'' Chwasky said.
``I'd have the L.C. two weeks before the fight, but the check
after. I didn't want to chase Don down for the money.`
</P>
<P>
   Another key part of making the fight was King's deal with the
Garden, which is paying a site fee of $8.3 million, part of a pot
that includes $20 million from Time Warner and $1 million from
Budweiser. Holyfield will get $20 million, Lewis about $9.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   King and Charles F. Dolan, the chairman of Cablevision, which
owns the Garden, hail from Cleveland. But as young go-getters, they
hardly inhabited complementary worlds. ``I was in the numbers
business and Chuck wasn't putting his numbers in,'' King said with
a cackle.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Dolan said, ``I've enjoyed many hours with Don across
the negotiating table.''
</P>
<P>
   King made his friendship with Dolan sound like a relationship
between courtly lords of the manor. ``Chuck's word is his bond,''
King said. ``He once gave me $3 million on a handshake. He knows
me. He respects me as a man of honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Or at least as a man who can bring Holyfield to the Garden for
what Dolan hopes will be an arena-jamming event with seats priced
from $100 to $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of months ago, I told Chuck we were interested in the
fight and Chuck said, `I have Don in my office,''' said Dave
Checketts, the Garden's president. ``I went in, Chuck left and we
got the deal done in 12 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Checketts said his goal was to make King forget Las Vegas or any
other site willing to pay a fee of more than $10 million. Time
Warner lobbied for the Garden because of the media attention
emanating from New York that can spur pay-per-view sales.
Cablevision can push the fight at Garden events, on the MSG Network
and Fox Sports New York and in its Nobody Beats the Wiz stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be the mecca of boxing if you're not in the game for
something like this,'' Checketts said. ``Chuck knows that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
