<HEADER>
A5679 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARSONS-COX     11-30 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARSONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former USC coach to testify on perjury conviction resulting from
affair By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Atlanta resident Pam Parsons is scheduled to
testify today before the House Judiciary Committee about her 1984
conviction for perjury in a high-profile civil suit.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons, a former coach of the University of South Carolina's
women's basketball team, spent four months in jail for lying under
oath in a suit arising from her sexual affair with a member of the
team, Tina Buck, a graduate of the former Briarcliff High in DeKalb
County.
</P>
<P>
   Buck also was sentenced to four months for perjury.
</P>
<P>
   As a witness called by the Republican side of the bitterly
partisan committee, Parsons will be queried in detail about why she
made a false statement in a $75 million libel lawsuit she filed
against Time Inc. for an article Sports Illustrated published about
her lesbian relationship with a team player.
</P>
<P>
   But her testimony may elicit a few questions from Republicans
themselves, particularly when they find out that she thinks Clinton
is ``one of the greatest presidents we've ever had'' and that she
had trouble recollecting the details of her own lawsuit during an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   So why did they call her?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea,'' said Parsons, who now lives in Atlanta.
``Maybe they liked my red hair. ``
</P>
<P>
   More likely, Republicans called her to counter assertions from
Clinton supporters that those convicted of perjury in civil suits
are seldom prosecuted and even less frequently jailed. Clinton is
accused of lying under oath in the civil suit brought by Paula
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding a bit like she had found a new religion in the truth,
Parsons said that she would share her personal odyssey with the
committee's members. Remaining mum about what she would say in
particular, she said her only goal was to share truth (and) love
with everyone that I come in contact with for the rest of my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Parsons, who would say nothing about her life in Atlanta, said
she came into contact with truth through a long process of
self-examination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shined the light where the darkness was and I brought it
together within me so I could be who I really wanted to be in this
lifetime _ A woman who is full of peace of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the truth has set Parsons free.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who I am now is a person who has recovered from everything
that I could not face,'' Parsons said. As a person who has
recovered from a damaging past, she said she had words of strength
to deliver the message to others.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the particulars of her case against the parent
company of Sports Illustrated magazine, Parsons said she could not
remember them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not relate to things from good or bad, right or wrong.
What is, is,'' she said. When asked what is, is, she said, ``I'll
talk about it tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Carr writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
