<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5683 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLLIN-AZR &LR;      11-30 1919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUN IS DEADLY ENEMY FOR 10-YEAR-OLD ARIZONA BOY  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ALSO MOVED IN `A' CATEGORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `` '' GILBERT, Arizona _
</P>
<P>
   `Between the dark and the daylight,
</P>
<P>
   When the night is beginning to lower,
</P>
<P>
   Comes a pause in the day's occupations,
</P>
<P>
   That is known as the children's hour.'' &QL; 
Henry Wadsworth Longfellow &QL; 
When night falls, the Collin Cassinat hour begins.
</P>
<P>
   As other children take cover from the darkness, Collin's
playtime is just beginning. Under the moonlight, he races his bike,
catches frogs, hunts bugs and exhilarates in his freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine is no friend to Collin. Exposures of just minutes would
cause his skin to redden, burn and blister. An overdose would kill
him.
</P>
<P>
   Collin, 9, is a child of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Born with a genetic disorder called xeroderma pigmentosum, in
which the cells of the body lack the ability to repair DNA damage
from ultraviolet rays, Collin's best chance for survival is to
avoid all sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   Windows in his family's Gilbert home near Phoenix are tinted and
covered with blinds. The family van is outfitted with blackout
curtains. When Collin goes outside during the day, he is swaddled
head to toe in long sleeves, long pants and a cap with a flap in
the back that makes him look like the youngest soldier in the
French Foreign Legion. He huddles under a blanket.
</P>
<P>
   His parents, Cindy and Tony Cassinat, estimate their son is
exposed to no more than five minutes of sunshine a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad'' is how Collin describes his sheltered life. Yet he's a
bright, chipper youngster with an impish personality and no lack of
friends. Two little girls have appointed themselves his escorts
between school buildings when he is wrapped so tightly against the
sun he can't see through his protective garb.
</P>
<P>
   At recess, classmates vie for the chance to stay indoors with
Collin and play field hockey in the halls.
</P>
<P>
   He admits there are advantages to having XP.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get spoiled,'' he said with a grin, ``by my teacher, then my
mama, then my dad, then my principal.''
</P>
<P>
   Collin was once invited to a sleep-over at the Phoenix Zoo. Last
summer he went to Camp Sundown in Poughkeepsie, N.Y., where young
campers with XP enjoyed indoor activities during the day and played
outside long into the night.
</P>
<P>
   But sitting alone in a darkened van parked where he can watch
his sister's soccer practice, his eyes get a bit teary as he counts
down the minutes until sunset when he can break out of the van and
run free.
</P>
<P>
   At 5:34 p.m., the Collin hour begins.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Cassinat first noticed something alarming about her third
son in February 1989. Six weeks old, Collin had been sitting
outside in his stroller, bundled against the chill. The next day he
appeared to have eczema on his cheeks _ crusty, scabby, oozing
patches.
</P>
<P>
   With a little research, Cindy learned that sunlight could help
dry up eczema, so she took Collin outside again. When the
``eczema'' spread to his arms, her pediatrician prescribed a
cortisone salve.
</P>
<P>
   Diagnosis: Fair Irish skin. Treatment: Keep that boy out of the
sun.
</P>
<P>
   Collin spent his toddler years covered in sunscreen, playing
indoors or in the shade. He wore hats and long-sleeved shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``His skin was always dry and cracky a little bit,'' Tony
Cassinat said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Cindy read a newspaper article about Julian Nieves
Armenta, a 4-year-old Mexican boy being treated for XP at Maricopa
Medical Center and introduced at a University of Arizona medical
symposium. Multiple skin cancers covered his head and dotted his
eyeballs.
</P>
<P>
   Julian's condition, minus the numerous malignancies, sounded
remarkably like Collin's, Cindy thought.
</P>
<P>
   A UA dermatologist confirmed her suspicions. In 20 years of
practice in pediatric dermatology, Dr. Ron Hansen had seen just two
cases of XP. Julian was one. Collin was the other. Most doctors
don't see any.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 130 cases exist in the country, with an estimated
1,000 worldwide. Collin's is the only known case in Arizona, the
Cassinats say.
</P>
<P>
   Extreme freckling and photophobia _ severe discomfort in the sun
_ are the earliest symptoms. Those signs should be detected by age
1 or 2; then protection can begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking a nocturnal person,'' Hansen said. ``Even a
minute or two of sun is enough DNA damage to have skin cancers.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunscreen is a puny weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a diagnosis, the Cassinats devoted themselves to
shielding Collin and instilled in him a sense of self-protection.
If someone opens a window or raises a shade, he'll cry out,
``You're killing me!'' Cindy said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, his cries are all too true.
</P>
<P>
   Undiagnosed and unprotected, children with XP usually die by the
age of 10. Protected, they can enjoy a life expectancy of about 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to his parents, Collin should have nearly a normal life
span, Hansen said: ``Collin will do much better. They were very
careful.''
</P>
<P>
   `NOT ONE TO MOPE'
</P>
<P>
   At Greenfield Elementary School, third-grader Collin blends in
with the other pupils. Only his UV-protective jacket gives him
away.
</P>
<P>
   Classroom windows are shaded, doors to the outside kept shut.
Collin spends his day inside, except for a weekly dash to the
building next door where art classes are held. That's when Diana
Hancock and Amanda Schreck guide their friend across campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``They help me so I don't run into stuff,'' Collin said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he does run into stuff _ the school, a tree. Sometimes
he trips. But he picks himself up and forges on.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not one to mope,'' said his teacher, Sue Villa. ``He
doesn't feel sorry for himself. . . . He's a great little kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Villa takes Collin's special needs in stride. When the school
had its fall festival, she arranged indoor events. When the class
was mandated to clean up school grounds for a lesson in ecology,
she sent them to the cafeteria to pick up trash. She creates indoor
science projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always other ways to do it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Collin's future in school is uncertain. When he graduates to
Greenfield Junior High School in three years, his parents will have
to evaluate the facility for safety. Are windows tinted? Will all
classes be in one building?
</P>
<P>
   The Cassinats pray the next school will be as accessible as this
one. Cindy pulls her van as close as possible to the front door at
Greenfield Elementary, and Collin races in. Once, when the driveway
was blocked by a van collision, she commandeered the delivery
entrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope we can continue in a normal school,'' Tony said.
``That's very important.''
</P>
<P>
   If the junior high proves unacceptable, the Cassinats won't
hesitate to ask for modifications to protect their son. If the
building can't meet their needs, they'll be forced to home school
him, further isolating a boy who already lives a life apart.
</P>
<P>
   A CALCULATED SCHEDULE
</P>
<P>
   The odds that Collin would be born with XP are phenomenal. To
produce the condition, both parents must be carriers of an aberrant
recessive gene. The chances of one partner being a carrier are one
in 250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, fate determined that Cindy, who grew up in California,
and Tony, a native of Wyoming, should meet, marry and have four
children. And one of those children would inherit a pair of XP
genes.
</P>
<P>
   News of that genetic fluke came as a blow, Tony says.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look at you and say your son can not go outside any more.
The next day we told the kids. That was hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Tony insists Collin's needs don't control their lives,
they live on a calculated schedule.
</P>
<P>
   On any given day, Cindy knows exactly when the sun sets. Collin
heads outside 10 minutes later. In the summer, that can be as late
at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   There have been just two family vacations _ to Lake Tahoe in
1996 and to Camp Sundown last year.
</P>
<P>
   While his two brothers, Chris, 16, and Craig, 12, and sister
Courtney, 8, are hooked on sports, Collin shines in the chess club.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting a restaurant before sunset means wrapping Collin ``like
a soft taco,'' Cindy said, and ignoring the stares of patrons. The
explanation, when asked for, is that the boy is allergic to the
sun.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Collin's diagnosis, the family moved from a
1,100-square foot house into a new 4,000-square-foot house,
quadrupling Collin's indoor world. With living room furniture kept
sparse, he was allowed to roller skate inside until the wheels
became too dirty. Tracks in the carpeting were a small price to pay
to let a boy burn off energy.
</P>
<P>
   But Collin still lives life upside down. When other children are
playing outside, he's peering at them from his front window. When
he's outside, his friends are already in for the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sunshine world out there,'' Tony said. ``People open
their windows and let the sun shine in. This goes against what
society is brought up with.''
</P>
<P>
   Because XP is so rare, little scientific research is being done.
For the time being, treatment means vigilence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word is `no sun.' We make judgment calls on what is
worthwhile,'' Tony said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cassinats are scrupulous about checking Collin's skin for
suspicious spots. So far, he's had more than 30 removed; 20 were
cancerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're used to it,'' Cindy said, ``but we wish they wouldn't
keep popping up.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Collin is lucky. Some children with XP suffer blindness,
hearing loss, neurological impairment and mental retardation,
although the connection is unclear. Despite some minor learning
disabilities, Collin is smart and healthy.
</P>
<P>
   For a boy whose enemy is the sun, Arizona would seem the evil
empire. In truth, the Valley of the Sun is Collin's best friend.
Phoenix has no more ultraviolet rays than cloudy Seattle. Clouds do
not block UV rays.
</P>
<P>
   And where else could a boy play outside after dark all year
round? Not Minnesota. Not North Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   SUPPORT GROUP OF 1
</P>
<P>
   Because Collin is the only child with XP in Arizona, there is no
one with whom to commiserate. He is a support group of one.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy said, ``You're looking at XP-AZ right here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet (www.xps.org/) is the Cassinats' link to XP parents
across the country. At Camp Sundown, they learned families cope as
best they can with the rare illness, keeping abreast of the few
developments in the field.
</P>
<P>
   A UV monitor, which detects ultraviolet rays, can alert parents
to dangerous levels of sunlight. But it is an expensive tool the
Cassinats can't afford.
</P>
<P>
   Another promising innovation is a pint-size space suit developed
by NASA. When perfected, it will shield children from UV light
outdoors. Although several models have been constructed, however,
the XP Society has not yet endorsed any design, believing current
suits offer only a false sense of security.
</P>
<P>
   Collin tries to be patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants one,'' Cindy said. ``He asks for one all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing outside during daylight hours is still only a dream for
Collin.
</P>
<P>
   The reality can break a mother's heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get down,'' Cindy said, ``but I can just start
thinking about him and start crying.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never ask, `Why us?' '' she said, with a smile she's been
practicing for a decade, sustained by the words of a friend who
told her, `` `He's here for a very important reason. He has this
disease for a very important reason.' ''
</P>
<P>
   After sunset, those reasons mean little to a boy at play. Collin
has captured a toad, and in his victory, the child of the night
comes alive. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
