<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-TURNER-ALLSTAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta first city to host to All-Stars, Super Bowl in same year
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Braves have won one in extra innings. The
club will entertain the 2000 All-Star game after being informed
three years ago the game was headed elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Worries about the future venue of the Florida Marlins prompted
Major League Baseball to withdraw the 2000 game from south Florida
and redesignate it to Turner Field. An official announcement will
be made today in a press conference at the Ted.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta will also have Super Bowl XXXIV in 2000, the first time
a city will be host to both an NFL championship and baseball's
All-Star game in the same year. In addition, Atlanta has been
awarded NCAA basketball's Final Four championships in both 2002 and
2007.
</P>
<P>
   ''Atlanta is an outstanding choice for Major League Baseball's
first All-Star game of the new millennium,'' baseball Commissioner
Bud Selig said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins were awarded the game at midseason in 1995, the
club's third season under owner Wayne Huizenga. But Huizenga has
had the franchise for sale for the past 17 months.
</P>
<P>
   While a $150 million purchase by south Florida bonds broker John
Henry has been in negotiation since mid-summer, league management
has become concerned about Henry's pledge to build a new stadium
and whether the facility would be completed in time to host the
mid-summer classic.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves had been hopeful of getting the 2002 game, though
that year's game could revert to Florida or the Milwaukee Brewers,
who will move into a new Miller Stadium in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has been the site of just one All-Star game since the
Braves moved to Atlanta in 1966. That game was July 25, 1972, a 4-3
victory by the National League that included a two-run homer by the
Braves' Hank Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
