<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE JUDICIARY REPUBLICANS ACCUSE CLINTON OF EVADING QUESTIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans on the House Judiciary Committee
prepared to broaden their impeachment inquiry to include President
Clinton's 1996 campaign fund-raising as the panel chairman Monday
accused the president of evading questions about Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Committee sources said Republicans, who hold a 21-16 majority on
the panel, will vote Tuesday to subpoena Clinton, Attorney General
Janet Reno and independent counsel Kenneth Starr to produce
documents related to campaign fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Republicans want to question FBI Director Louis
Freeh and Justice Department prosecutor Charles LaBella, both of
whom have recommended independent investigations of fund-raising
irregularities by the Clinton campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP move to expand the committee's inquiry beyond the
Lewinsky affair comes as panel Chairman Henry Hyde is pushing to
complete work in time for a vote on articles of impeachment as
early as next week. Hyde had hoped to have the issue resolved by
the full House before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Hyde said the committee was not getting the
president's full cooperation and accused him of sticking to
``bizarre technical definitions and legalistic defenses'' of his
efforts to hide his affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's criticism was aimed at Clinton's responses to 81
questions drafted by committee investigators after pouring through
Starr's report alleging that Clinton lied under oath, tampered with
witnesses, obstructed justice and abused his presidential
authority.
</P>
<P>
   In his responses, submitted to the committee on Friday, Clinton
broke no new ground. He denied the central impeachment allegations
of perjury, obstruction of justice and abuse of power in the
Lewinsky affair, but he acknowledged misleading the public and top
aides.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, an Illinois Republican, again invited Clinton to testify
before the committee, then warned that ``if the president leaves
undisputed the record of where he has given evasive responses, we
will be forced to assume that the corroborated evidence is
accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart brushed off Hyde's invitation
to appear before the panel whose hearings so far have been marked
by partisan rancor. ``I don't think it's very likely you'll see the
president appear before that committee,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the process to date, there has been very little
comfort for those who were looking for something fair and
nonpartisan,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday, committee sources said the subpoenas Republicans
want to serve on Clinton and Reno are not for testimony, but to
secure a memo produced by LaBella when he was head of the Justice
Department's campaign finance task force. The House Government
Reform and Oversight Committee earlier this year tried
unsuccessfully to secure the memo from Reno, who fought the GOP-led
efforts even in the face of contempt charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The committee is in receipt of information that indicates the
LaBella memo may contain evidence of criminal wrongdoing by the
president,'' said a Republican staff member assigned to the
committee. ``Given this information, we are duty bound to act.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton subpoena will direct him to order Reno to turn over
the LaBella memo, said the staffer, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans also want Starr _ whose 453-page report on the
Lewinsky affair triggered the House impeachment inquiry _ to turn
over evidence obtained from John Huang, a key Democratic
fund-raiser who has cooperated with Starr's investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP move to broaden the inquiry beyond the alleged cover-up
of the president's acknowledged sexual misbehavior drew sharp
criticism from Democrats, who characterized the GOP plan as
``weirdness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said before, and this is confirmation, that this is an
impeachment in search of a crime,'' said Jim Jordan, a Democratic
committee spokesman. ``This says quite a bit, I suspect, about the
confidence Republicans have in the strength of the case they've
assembled at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans' bid to broaden the investigation was leaked to
reporters shortly after Maryland developer and Democratic
fund-raiser Nathan Landow invoked his Fifth Amendment right against
self-incrimination during a closed-door interview with committee
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   During the hourlong session, investigators and committee members
asked about Landow's discussions with Kathleen Willey and whether
he was aware of any effort to cover-up her White House encounter
with Clinton in 1993. Willey has accused Clinton of fondling her
during a private meeting near the Oval Office. Clinton has
acknowledge meeting with Willey but denied any improper behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Committee sources said the investigators hope later this week
for a closed-door interview with Bruce Lindsey, a longtime Clinton
confidant who currently works as deputy White House counsel. At the
same time, Republicans on the panel have decided against
questioning one of Clinton's private attorneys, Robert S. Bennett,
who represented the president in the Paula Jones sexual harassment
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is scheduled Tuesday to hear testimony from 11
witnesses about perjury, one of the offenses Clinton allegedly
committed in his effort to keep his affair with Lewinsky secret.
</P>
<P>
   Among the witnesses are two women convicted of perjury for
making false statements about sex in civil cases. They are:
</P>
<P>
   Pam Parsons, a former women's basketball coach at the University
of South Carolina. Parsons spent four months in jail after she was
convicted of lying about an affair with one of her players in a
libel lawsuit she filed against Sports Illustrated, which published
an article that mentioned the sexual relationship. In her
pleadings, Parsons denied the affair.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Battalino, a former Veterans Affairs psychiatrist who is
serving a six-month sentence of home detention. Battalino also lost
her medical license and was fined $3,500 after she was convicted of
lying in a civil lawsuit filed by a former patient who said she
performed oral sex on him. Those charges were brought by Justice
Department officials in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   During his daily White House briefing, Lockhart derided the
Judiciary Committee's plan to call convicted perjurers to testify
on Tuesday as a ``stunt'' and said its work had been partisan and
unfair from the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this has been about is trying to score political
points,'' Lockhart said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
