<HEADER>
A5708 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUEBEC-ELECT-543&AMP;ADD(     11-30 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUEBEC-ELECT-543&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEPARATISTS RETAIN HOLD ON QUEBEC ASSEMBLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (htv) 
 By ANTHONY DEPALMA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUEBEC _ Premier Lucien Bouchard and the separatist Parti
Quebecois have retained control of Canada's largest province,
according to early projections by Canadian television.
</P>
<P>
   The victory sets the stage for a bitter confrontation with the
rest of the country, and possibly another referendum on
independence, even though most Quebecers say that at this time they
do not want to separate from Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Bouchard appears to have easily defeated the leader of the
provincial Liberal Party, Jean Charest, on whom many people in
English Canada had pinned their hopes for an end to the
French-speaking province's 30 years of threats to separate.
</P>
<P>
   Radio Canada, the French language service of the Canadian
Broadcasting Service, called the election at 8:35 p.m., little more
than half an hour after the polls closed.
</P>
<P>
   With strong support among Francophone voters, Bouchard had the
chance to increase the Parti Quebecois majority in the provincial
assembly, as well as to expand the party's share of the popular
vote. This could provide the conditions he says he needs to win a
third referendum on creating an independent nation in Quebec, a
province of roughly 7 million people on the northern border of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls indicate, however, that only 43 percent of
Quebecers support separation, a drop of four percentage points
during the course of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   What appears to be taking place, analysts say, is that Quebecers
see this election as a vote on government, not on independence, so
separatist emotions are in check. But voters want Bouchard to keep
alive the possibility of another referendum on separation as a way
of increasing the province's leverage with Ottawa in upcoming
discussions about changes in the shape of Canadian federalism.
</P>
<P>
   Even without a referendum, Bouchard's re-election will increase
tensions and uncertainty in Canada. During the campaign he said he
would demand substantial changes in the Canadian federation,
forcing Ottawa to give back more powers over social programs not
just to Quebec but to all ten provinces.
</P>
<P>
   In one stroke that silenced the critics in his own party who
suspected his commitment to changing relations with the central
government and undercut the position of Charest, who equated a vote
for the Parti Quebecois with a vote for separation.
</P>
<P>
   When Charest announced last spring that he would challenge
Bouchard in the election, analysts gave the Parti Quebecois little
chance of retaining power. Many in English Canada believed that if
Charest, a popular federal politician, could win and impose a
moratorium on referendum for the next four to five years, he could
end or severely limit the separatist movement because immigration
and demographics are diluting separatist strength in the province.
</P>
<P>
   But Charest's campaign never caught on. It is expected that
there will now be calls for his resignation, and the resignation of
Prime Minister Jean Chretien, who opposes changes to the Canadian
federation.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of Charest to win support in his home province was
just one surprise among many in this election that seemed to settle
very little except Bouchard's reputation as one of Quebec's most
popular and adept political leaders.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It's been the strangest election I have ever seen in my
life,'' said Pierre Roy, 61, a retired businessman from Lac
Beauport, near Quebec City. ``Bouchard's posters said `Have
confidence,' but people are afraid about what's going to happen.''
Roy voted just after polls opened at 10 a.m. on a gray day with
freezing rain and snow falling in many parts of the province.
</P>
<P>
   While Quebec's future is still uncertain, the outcome of the
election was predicted by public opinion polls weeks ago. Unlike
past developments on Quebec separation, which sent financial
markets into a slump, the results of Monday's election appeared to
have been discounted already.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian dollar actually strengthened slightly, closing at a
value of 65 United States cents. The Toronto Stock Exchange
declined just under 2 percent on a day when most markets around the
world were also down for reasons that had nothing to do with the
election here.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Cooper, chief economist with Nesbitt Burns, a Toronto
financial services company, said that the impact of the Quebec
election could be greater on Tuesday, after all the votes are
counted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bigger the numbers _ in terms of seats in the assembly and
the percentage of the popular vote _ the bigger the impact will be
on Canadian currency and the market,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe that if Bouchard wins more than 50 percent
of the popular vote, he will call another referendum on separation
within a few months. If his party wins many more seats than the 77
it now holds in the provincial assembly, Bouchard is also likely to
interpret that as a mandate for a speedy resumption of the fight
for independence.
</P>
<P>
   In the 33-day campaign _ the shortest in Quebec history _
speeches and rallies proceeded at a frantic pace. The one debate on
Nov. 17 was seen by many viewers as a virtual tie between Bouchard
and Charest. A third candidate, Mario Dumont, of the Democratic
Action Party, also appeared in the debate, and his strong
performance was believed to have hurt Charest.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the campaign generated little real emotion, despite
expectations that it would be a clash of titans. However, the
results indicate that Quebec voters drew a sharp distinction
between Bouchard's ability to govern and his party's commitment to
holding a third referendum on separation.
</P>
<P>
   Polls indicate that most Quebecers do not want to be put through
another referendum, but that they believe the threat of separation
is useful to bringing about changes in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no people yelling slogans in the street or things
like that,'' said Gilles Paquet, director of the Center on
Governance at the University of Ottawa. ``Instead, what you saw
today is the rational vote by a group that feels it can do better
in the Canadian federation by electing a separatist government.''
</P>
<P>
   What appears certain is that the results of the election Monday
will set all of Canada on another painful round of introspection
about the identity and nature of the country.
</P>
<P>
   This period could be different, however, because Bouchard _ an
experienced negotiator _ has introduced a new element that
substantially changes the picture. In one of his many major shifts
in position during the campaign, he hinted that before calling a
referendum on independence, he would push Ottawa for a freer hand
in spending on social issues, especially health.
</P>
<P>
   Under Canada's national medical system, delivering health care
is the responsibility of each of the 10 provinces. But the federal
government provides about 70 percent of the money that the
provinces spend on health care and imposes many standards and
restrictions on how the money can be spent.
</P>
<P>
   Bouchard and the premiers of the other nine provinces signed an
agreement at a meeting last summer to explore a new arrangement
that would give the provinces more flexibility, including the
chance to get money from Ottawa without participating in the
federal system.
</P>
<P>
   For Bouchard, it appears to be a strategy that cannot lose. If
Ottawa gives in to the demands, Bouchard can tell the people of
Quebec that he wrested an important concession from Prime Minister
Jean Chretien, who has strongly opposed giving any more powers to
the provinces.
</P>
<P>
   If Ottawa refuses, Bouchard can say that he had tried to
negotiate in good faith but was rejected. That could represent one
of the ``winning conditions'' that he said must be apparent before
he calls for another referendum on separation.
</P>
<P>
   What is uncertain, analysts say, is how much resentment would be
generated by Ottawa's rebuff of the new federalism, and how that
resentment would affect a vote on separation. Since Bouchard signed
the agreement with the other premiers last summer, little attention
has been paid to the issue in Quebec. But polls indicate that a
majority of Quebecers want Bouchard to negotiate a new federal
union.
</P>
<P>
   For Bouchard, this was the first election in which he could take
his ideas to the entire province. In 1995, he was named by the
party to finish out the term of the former premier, Jacques
Parizeau, who resigned after the separatists' narrow defeat in the
October 1995 referendum.
</P>
<P>
   During this campaign, Parizeau _ a separatist hard-liner _ drew
the ire of English-speaking Canada when he told a group of students
that the Parti Quebecois strategy was really to use the threat of
separation to milk the rest of Canada for all the concessions it
could get, and then to go ahead with separation.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we're in Canada we'll go get our booty,'' he was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Bouchard, who once served in the federal Cabinet of former Prime
Minister Brian Mulroney and was Canada's ambassador to France,
takes a much less strident position on separation. By imposing the
requirement of ``winning conditions'' on another referendum, and by
raising the question of negotiating changes in Canadian federalism
with Ottawa, Bouchard has left himself so many options that there
is no way to know exactly what his plans are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although many people in the rest of Canada saw what Bouchard
was doing as being like holding a knife at the throat of Canada,
it's not like that here in Quebec,'' said Alain Dubuc, chief
editorial writer of La Presse, a leading French-language Montreal
newspaper that is against separation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people here like about Bouchard is not his use of scare
tactics but his energy and strength. He has restraint, but he is
also strong enough to resist the dictates of Ottawa.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
