<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IINTERNET ISSUES TAKE A DIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Led by a nose dive in Internet and technology shares, the US
stock market fell sharply Monday, a week after hitting record
highs. nasdaq down 66.90, 1949.54, 3.32 percent
</P>
<P>
   The 216.53-point drop, or 2.32 percent, in the Dow Jones
industrial average came on a wave of profit-taking that wiped out
last week's 173-point gain and dampened some of the first hefty
gains in stock prices since July.
</P>
<P>
   But the most dramatic drops occurred in stocks of companies that
sell products and services on line. Such electronic commerce shares
had soared last week on anticipation of robust holiday sales.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow closed at 9116.55 _ more than 250 points below its
record close of 9374.27 set last Monday and 216 points lower than
Friday's close.
</P>
<P>
   Investors last week went on a buying spree sparked by a wave of
megamerger announcements and anticipation of brisk holiday sales
that would boost Net-related stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But profit-takers had second thoughts. ``It's just a mixed bag
with no reasons you can point to at this point,'' said Joseph
Barthel, chief investment officer at Fahnestock &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, declining issues outnumbered advancers by 2-to-1 on the
New York Stock Exchange, where IBM Corp. was the Dow's biggest
decliner. It closed at 165 1/8, down 4 7/8 while United
Technologies fell 4 9/16 to 107 3/16. Despite the fall, the Dow was
still more than 15 percent higher than at the start of 1998 and
some 1700 points above the Aug. 31 low of 7400.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's rout was most pronounced in the technology-heavy Nasdaq
market, where major Internet-related stocks were swept up in record
trading volumes. The Nasdaq lost 66.90 points, down to 1949.54, or
3.32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; cl10.5 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Decliners led 3-to-2 with Yahoo Inc. plunging 24 15/16 to 192,
while Microsoft Corp. shares dropped 6 1/16 to 122. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The sell-off sharply affected some electronic commerce retailers
like Amazon.com, the big bookseller, and Open Market Inc., the
Burlington developer of electronic commerce software, whose stock
price dropped 3 1/2 points to close at 17 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations that shoppers would skip crowded malls for the
comfort of buying holiday gifts on-line from home had fueled last
week's runup in Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The downturn, said Wall Street analysts, came after some
investors began to question their infatuation with companies doing
business on line. Although electronic commerce revenue could double
to $2.3 billion this year, according to some industry estimates,
that's still only 1 percent of total holiday retail sales.
Moreover, many on-line companies that increase their fourth-quarter
business are still unlikely to generate significant profits,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see a &UR;  &LR; lot of small investors selling their shares _
people looking to close out the year, some of whom invested early
on and made some money,'' said Matthew J. Luckett, a software
research analyst at SoundView Technology Group.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most stunning drops came in shares of &UR;  &LR; on-line
auction companies whose stocks had soared last week even
though &UR;  &LR; many won't have profits for at least two years.
</P>
<P>
   Onsale Inc., a Internet auctioneer based in Menlo Park Calif.
saw its stock price plunge more than 36 to close at 61 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   The yo-yo effect also took its toll on newcomers to electronic
commerce. Books-A-Million Inc., a Southeastern chain with 172
bookstores that recently began selling books over the Internet, saw
its stock skyrocket 26 points Friday to close at 38 15/16. Monday
the stock fell 9 7/16 to close at 29 1/2 on volume of 22.8 million
shares.Seattle-based Amazon.com stock fell 24 5/8 to 192.
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
