<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5712 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEATH-ROW-ESCAPE-COX     11-30 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-ROW-ESCAPE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Death row inmate on the loose
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Martin Gurule is still out there someplace,
outside the concrete walls and the razor wire and the ticking clock
of his death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   His extraordinary escape Friday _ he is the first to break out
of Texas' death row since 1934 and the first to escape from the
Ellis Unit since it opened in 1965 _ has set off one of the biggest
manhunts the Texas prison system has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials hit the alarm button shortly after midnight
Friday, just after Gurule, condemned for the 1992 murder of Corpus
Christi restaurant owner, clambered up the double outer fences,
wriggled through the coiled razor wire, and vanished into the
night. Six other would-be death row escapees with Gurule
surrendered in the prison compound when guards opened fire.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, correctional officers _ many who live in houses
next to the prison _ were racing to pre-arranged positions,
following a plan they routinely practice in escape drills.
Telephones quickly rang in houses near the prison, notifying
residents that a prisoner was loose.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an extensive and comprehensive battle plan that
swings into effect immediately'' after an escape, said Glen
Castlebury, a spokesman for the Texas Department of Criminal
Justice.
</P>
<P>
   In the minutes and hours after the first shots rang out hundreds
of corrections officers were deployed in a containment plan that
they hope has trapped Gurule within a 17,000-acre expanse of woods,
bogs, and farmland bordered by three roads and an arching bend of
the Trinity River.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't search like you would for a lost child, where you
lock arms in arm and search every square inch,'' Castlebury said.
Instead, they have created a spider's web of trails throughout
their search zone, and they are waiting for their missing killer to
cross one of its strands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose becomes containment. As long as he's on that land
and stays there, we will outwait him. We have more patience, we
have more food.''
</P>
<P>
   The battle plan has been battle-tested, Castlebury said. The
prison system has a perfect record in capturing escaped prisoners,
he said, and the inside joke at the prisons is that escapees are
always caught within three hours or three miles.
</P>
<P>
   But Gurule, on death row for shooting Minas ``Mike'' Piperis
while robbing Piperis' U&AMP;I Restaurant in Corpus Christi, has been
missing for four days, and nobody knows how far he has gone. Maybe
he raced to the nearest road and jumped into a car before the swarm
of correctional officers could seal off the area.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials say they are exploring that possibility, but
they believe he's laying low nearby, playing the needle in the
17,000-acre haystack surrounding the Ellis Unit, 12 miles north of
Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   Dogs pulling long hours
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Ellis Unit, at the command center set up to lead the
search effort, prison officials coordinate the roughly 500 officers
and 70 dogs who form the bulk of their force.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 500 officers involved in the hunt at any one time
are kept out of the search area, so that their scent will not
confuse those doing the actual hunting: the dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven ``tracks,'' or trails have been set up within the
perimeter, along with others skirting the riverbanks, Castlebury
said. Dog teams _ 10 tracking hounds loping ahead of two officers _
have been tracing those tracks up to four times a day. Four teams
at a time are out in the search area around the clock, Castlebury
said, waiting for the dogs to sniff out evidence that the inmate
has moved across one of the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``These dogs are not scent-specific, meaning you don't have them
smell the inmate's pillow case,'' Castlebury said. ``They will
follow any scent.''
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Tommy Freeman, who manages the dog teams at the prison,
said his dogs tracked Gurule's scent to a highway about a
quarter-mile east of the prison, where it abruptly stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike a lot of people think, there are a lot of situations
where we can have a problem (tracking),'' Freeman said.
</P>
<P>
   Prison spokesman Larry Fitzgerald said it was possible the
inmate had stepped into a pile of cow manure, which would throw off
the dogs' ability to track his scent.
</P>
<P>
   Castlebury said they can't be sure it was Gurule's trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a case of 'Who knows?' `` he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, officers are positioned every 25 yards on five or six
miles of farm roads and state highway on the southern and western
sides of the perimeter, keeping an eye on the roads and checking
every passing vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Overhead, two helicopters _ one from the Texas Department of
Public Safety and one from the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization
Service _ have flown intermittently over the area, hoping Gurule's
body heat will trip their infrared sensors.
</P>
<P>
   Those sensors won't work if Gurule is dead, however. Prison
authorities found blood near the razor-wire-topped fence that
Gurule scaled, but they have said they don't think he was shot.
</P>
<P>
   Until they find evidence that the 29-year-old convict somehow
slipped out of the area before they could establish their perimeter
_ or until enough time has passed to convince them he's gone _
prison officials will stick to the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Todd, another prison spokesman, called it a ``combination
of scent and tracks and good old country boy hunches.''
</P>
<P>
   Hacksaw blade discovered
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials have launched an investigation into how the
inmates, who all had greater freedom of movement because they
worked as orderlies on the cellblock, were able to slip into the
exercise yard, cut through the fence around it, and remained
undetected on a rooftop for hours.
</P>
<P>
   After Gurule's escape, guards quickly discovered they'd been
had: the sleeping forms in the inmates bunks were really rolled-up
bedding. On Monday, prison officials announced they found a hacksaw
blade on the roof where the inmates hid before the escape attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not brought in from the outside as far as we can
determine,'' Fitzgerald said. ``It's the kind we have at our
industries. We have a bus barn here, a furniture shop. The fact we
have a saw blade is not unusual. We are concerned, obviously, how
this occurred, but first we have to find him.''
</P>
<P>
   Another part of the search involves detective work. When a
Huntsville resident reported the theft of a blue GMC pickup truck
from the parking lot of a local business, the police passed on the
information to the command center.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are checking ``every contact, every family member,
every friend'' for leads, Castlebury said. The investigation has
also included poring over Gurule's visitor list and correspondence
list, looking for evidence that he had help from the outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, they don't have any leads there,'' Todd said.
</P>
<P>
   So they keep running the dogs, checking motorists' trunks, and
waiting for Gurule _ if he's in there _ to move.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating,'' Gary Johnson, director of the prison
system, said late Monday afternoon after another full day of
searching. ``But we can't quit just because we're frustrated. We
just have to be patient and press on.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson repeated his belief that Gurule remained within the
searchers' perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I knew he was not here, we would pull out,'' he said. ``But
we have no plans now of pulling out. As long as there's a chance
he's here, we'll be here. We're committed for the long haul.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Harmon writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. This article includes material from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
