<DOCNO> NYT19981130.0455 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5713 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUILTLESS-FRITO-LAY-C     11-30 1346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUILTLESS-FRITO-LAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Guiltless Gourmet's plight for space on grocery store shelves
 &HT;    By R. Michelle Breyer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Five years ago, healthy chip maker Guiltless
Gourmet was fat and happy.
</P>
<P>
   The company had pioneered the baked tortilla chip and had
outlasted competitors like Fit Foods and Smart Temptations. It went
from peddling chips in a few retailers in Austin to selling them in
stores in all 50 states. It opened a sleek headquarters with office
suites, and its workforce ballooned to more than 100 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Goliath.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1994, Plano-based Frito-Lay Co., the Microsoft Corp. of
the chip industry (tortilla chips, that is) decided it wanted a
piece of the burgeoning low-fat chip business.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Frito-Lay owned the rest of the snack chip business,
with products like Doritos and Tostitos sold around the globe. When
it introduced Baked Tostitos and Baked Lays, it used its formidable
brand-name appeal and burgeoning budget to gobble up market share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life as we knew it changed,'' said Robert Greenberg, the
company's vice president of advertising and marketing. Guiltless
Gourmet nearly crumbled.
</P>
<P>
   But instead, it regrouped, reformulated and redesigned. Gone
were plans to start selling other low-fat products, like potato
chips, replaced by plans to make its core product better. It also
cut its workforce, tweaked its manufacturing and distribution
systems, and did whatever it could to remain a contender.
</P>
<P>
   It has.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without these changes, we would have shrunk to a point where
our business could have disappeared,'' Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the chip company has $8 million in revenues _ not
including sales to natural foods stores _ and is among the Top 10
tortilla chip brands nationally, according to the Snack Food
Association, an Alexandria, Va.-based tradegroup. It is second
among low-fat tortilla chip makers _ albeit a distant second _
behind Baked Tostitos, according to the tradegroup.
</P>
<P>
   But Guiltless Gourmet's story goes deeper than its nine types of
chips and seven dips.
</P>
<P>
   It is a tale any small company with a big idea can relate to,
one of a modern-day David which _ at least for now _ is holding its
own in a battle against Goliath by making some quick and decisive
moves. ``There's definitely a niche for them,'' said Ann Wilkes,
spokeswoman for the Snack Food Association.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Foreman, a former restaurateur, started Guiltless Gourmet
out of his Austin home with an investment of $200 and a desire to
lose weight. His personal trainer told him he needed to cut down on
his fat intake, but he was unable to give up one vice _ chips and
salsa.
</P>
<P>
   So he began to experiment with low-fat options. By August 1989,
he had developed a low-fat, no-oil, baked tortilla chip as an
alternative to fried chips. Encouraged by the result, he had labels
made and brought two bags to Whole Foods Markets Inc.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1990, Foreman sold his restaurant so he spend all his
time on Guiltless Gourmet. Sales grew from $35,000 in 1989 to
$200,000 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Foreman solicited investors to help fund
expansion. John Oudt and John Koerner, the former owners of Barq's
Rootbeer Inc. of New Orleans, invested an estimated $350,000 for 35
percent of Guiltless Gourmet.
</P>
<P>
   With the infusion of capital, Guiltless Gourmet in 1991 was able
to move into a new $1 million automated 20,000-square-foot plant in
Southeast Austin. In 1992, it bought an additional $1 million in
production equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The company rapidly grew, tapping into a growing appetite for
low-fat foods. Sales hit $20 million in 1993, a year before Foreman
sold the company to Oudt and Koerner.
</P>
<P>
   Guiltless Gourmet's success did not go unnoticed. It captured
the attention of Frito-Lay _ which unsuccessfully attempted to buy
the Austin-based company. Instead, Frito-Lay entered the low-fat
market on its own.
</P>
<P>
   With a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   Alongside its Doritos, Fritos and Cheetos, Frito-Lay added its
Baked Tostitos and Baked Lay's low-fat and non-fat snack foods.
Although Guiltless Gourmet had a four-year head start, the company
watched as it went from the market leader to a minor player. Sales
plunged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went from having a dominant share of a small category to
having a small share of a large category,'' Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Guiltless Gourmet President and Chief Executive Mike Schall, who
joined the company the same week Baked Tostitos went national, who
in a magazine interview once likened competing with Frito-Lay to
``dancing between the elephants toes.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 1995, with its sales declining at a precipitous
rate, the executives at Guiltless Gourmet decided to launch an
aggressive campaign to fight back _ an effort that cost the company
more than $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   It meant cutting out fat, so to speak, in the company. Gone were
the office suites. The 7,500-square-foot corporate headquarters was
reduced to 1,100 cramped square feet in the company's warehouse.
The company's workforce, once as high as 120 employees, was trimmed
to 55.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg, a veteran of the food industry, was brought in to
boost the company's sales and marketing efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had only one real shot to make the change,'' Greenberg
said. ``If we didn't make the most of it, it was all for not.''
</P>
<P>
   First, Guiltless Gourmet embarked on extensive consumer testing
_ a first for the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to make it taste better,'' Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   In February, 1997, the company decided to add a little canola
oil to the chips to improve the flavor. That change _ which gave
each serving a modest 2 grams of fat _ was met with rising sales.
</P>
<P>
   At roughly the same time, the company unveiled new packaging to
reflect the change in the product.
</P>
<P>
   The colorful bags, which use a special film designed to improve
shelf life, focus on the product's improved taste rather than its
low number of fat grams.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in more than two years, we saw sales start
to grow again,'' Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Guiltless Gourmet sought to improve quality
control. That meant buying higher-quality corn and retooling the
manufacturing process.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the toasted smell of baked corn fills the company's plant
in Southeast Austin, which processes more than 1,500 pounds of corn
an hour. Within 12 hours, red, white, yellow and blue corn kernels
are cooked, steeped, ground, cut into triangles, baked, seasoned
and packaged. The 7-ounce bags of chips are packed into cases,
which are stacked into pallets, which are shipped to stores around
the country.
</P>
<P>
   But changing the look and taste of the products won't do
anything if the customers can't find them.
</P>
<P>
   During 1993 and 1994, Guiltless Gourmet chips were distributed
nationally by companies who focused on specialty, gourmet and
natural food items, from salad dressings to energy bars. Often
Guiltless Gourmet products were relegated to the ``healthy living''
section, far from the other snack foods, Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   This worked for a while because of the double-digit growth of
low-fat snack foods. But with Frito-Lay chomping away at market
share Guiltless Gourmet had to find a better way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers had dozens of other opportunities to buy chips
before they ever saw our chips, if they ever saw our chips,''
Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   So Guiltless Gourmet decided to sell to snack-food distributors.
The distributors are responsible for maintaining the mix of
products and fighting for more shelf space. The result of this
increased exposure has been a significant sales increase, Greenberg
said. At Austin's Central Market this week, a large display of
Guiltless Gourmet products are showcased in the middle of the snack
food aisle. ``You have to work for the product and fight for shelf
position,'' he said. ``These are the type of things that Frito-Lay
does in its sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   R. Michelle Breyer writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
