<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5722 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOBIL-BEAUMONT-HNS &LR;      11-30 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOBIL-BEAUMONT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKERS AT BEAUMONT, TEXAS, MOBIL REFINERY AWAIT ANNOUNCEMENT OF
EXXON MERGER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEAUMONT, Texas _ When workers file through the front gate of
the sprawling Mobil refinery in a part of Beaumont, Texas, once
known as the ``Lower Woods,'' they march under the familiar red
winged horse, Pegasus, that has been a symbol at the refinery since
1931.
</P>
<P>
   But Beaumont's refinery was already mature by then. The refinery
at the end of Burt Street has been at work since 1903 when Col.
George Burt built his Security Oil Co. and sold it to investors who
were also stockholders in Standard Oil.
</P>
<P>
   Since then generations of Beaumont residents have spent their
working lives at the refinery. Many hope that tradition will
continue now that it appears Mobil Oil and Exxon will combine to
reform a big part of what was once Standard Oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a big uncertainty,'' said Richard Hidalgo, who has
worked at the plant for 26 years. His grandfather, Felix Hidalgo,
worked at the refinery, as did his uncle and cousins. His son, also
called Richard Hidalgo, is part of the fourth generation of the
family to work there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows what to expect,'' he said. Rumors of mergers with
other companies have gone around the refinery in years past, as
have rumors of massive layoffs or even of the refinery being shut
down.
</P>
<P>
   But through good economic conditions and bad, the old refinery
has kept on, going through periodic expansions and modernizations.
Today, it is the country's fourth-largest refinery and Mobil's
largest.
</P>
<P>
   It has a workforce of 1,250 and can process more than 13.6
million gallons of crude oil a day into a long list of products.
</P>
<P>
   Its birth came hard on the heels of the big Spindletop oil boom
just south of Beaumont in 1901. That strike was followed by other
oil discoveries all along the Texas coast. Refineries in Port
Arthur became flagships of Texaco and Gulf. Today they are Motiva
and Clark Refining.
</P>
<P>
   Texas anti-trust laws didn't allow Standard Oil to build a
refinery in Texas, said Beaumont historian Judy Linsley, but it was
common knowledge that the owners of the Security refinery were the
same as the owners of Standard Oil. ``It was like the rhinoceros in
the living room,'' she said. ``Nobody talked about it.'' Most
locals called the plant the Burt Refinery although Col. Burt sold
it before it started operation, she said.
</P>
<P>
   By 1909 the state forced Standard Oil to sell the refinery and
it was sold to a group of Texas investors headed by Galveston
financier, John Sealy. The refinery operated under the name of John
Sealy, Refiner of Oil.
</P>
<P>
   In 1911 it was reorganized under the Magnolia name and many
oldtime Beaumont residents still refer to the plant as the Magnolia
Refinery. Socony _ a big part of the old Standard Oil trust that
had been dissolved earlier _ bought a large part of Magnolia in
1918 and took complete control in 1925. That was the same year a
second round of oil discoveries were being made at Spindletop.
</P>
<P>
   In 1931 Socony and Vacuum combined, Linsley said, bringing the
familiar flying red horse symbol to Beaumont. In 1959 it became
Mobil. The refinery gave birth to two Mobil chemical plants and
several other petrochemical plants using products from the
refinery.
</P>
<P>
   By 1920 the refinery was the biggest single employer in Beaumont
and is still the biggest industrial employer. ``It kept us afloat
during the Depression,'' she said, ``because it kept going.''
</P>
<P>
   In the earlier part of the century, Linsley said, the old
refinery gave the city much of its identity.
</P>
<P>
   A Magnolia band might entertain city folks from a park bandstand
on Sunday afternoons. Company baseball and basketball teams had
loyal fans. A company newsletter called ``Magpetco'' was regular
reading in many homes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1924 the refinery started Beaumont's first radio station with
the call letters KFDM standing for ``Kall For Dependable
Magnolene,'' referring to a popular lube oil made in Beaumont.
Today the station is KLVI and it's still in Beaumont.
</P>
<P>
   Today's workers say they no longer have that feeling of family
that workers once had, but they say their refinery is as modern as
any in the country. ``It's a competitive refinery,'' said Jimmy
Herrington, an employee since 1971 and president of Oil, Chemical
and Atomic Workers Union Local 4-243.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, he said the refinery workforce has been cut
by at least 250 as many maintenance and repair jobs that were once
done by Mobil employees are now performed by contract workers
employed by outside companies. The contract workers never earn the
job security and benefits accrued by employees of the refinery, he
said. It's a trend that bothers many union members.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not trained as well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Workers also fear that a merger of Mobil and Exxon may give the
combined company far too much refining capacity. ``Exxon has a big
refinery in Baytown and another one in Baton Rouge,'' he said. ``We
worry about what's going to happen to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Refinery managers haven't told workers what to expect from a
merger, Herrington and other union leaders say. ``Probably because
they don't know anything yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Dawson, who has worked at the refinery 18 years and is the
union local's secretary-treasurer, said she is upbeat about the
possibilities. ``We've already made this a good operation. We know
they're making money.''
</P>
<P>
   Many workers are joking about what the combined company might be
called, she said. Several years ago, when a Mobil-Chevron merger
was being talked about, the joke was it would be called ``Moron.''
Now names like Exxil, Ex-Mobil'' and ``Moxxon,'' are being bandied
about.
</P>
<P>
   Mobil workers also are worried about what will happen to their
benefits, such as retirement packages, after a buyout, Hidalgo
said. After Chevron bought the big Gulf refinery in Port Arthur in
the 1980's, Gulf retirees ended up taking Chevron to court over
retirement benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo, 52, said he hopes the old refinery will continue to
provide employment for his son and other relatives.
</P>
<P>
   As for himself, he's not too worried.
</P>
<P>
   He's retiring Tuesday, and taking his retirement benefit in a
lump-sum payment. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
