<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5724 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENSUS-SAMPLING-COX     11-30 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-SAMPLING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Supreme Court asked to intervene in census controversy
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman and Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Opponents of the Clinton administration's plan to
use estimates in the 2000 census on Monday asked the Supreme Court
to prohibit estimations even if they prove more accurate than a
traditional head count.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau is proposing to employ scientific sampling to
get a better count of minorities and other hard-to-reach
populations, which could boost the population totals for urban
areas, including Dayton, that may have been shortchanged in the
1990 census.
</P>
<P>
   The once-a-decade census helps determine each state's
representation in Congress, the drawing of electoral boundaries and
the distribution of more than $175 billion in federal funds. And
with so much at stake, the debate has become divisively partisan
with Democrats supporting the use of estimates, and Republicans
opposing it.
</P>
<P>
   Solicitor General Seth Waxman, arguing on behalf of the
administration, told the justices that every census since 1790 has
been an estimate of the population since no census has physically
reached every person in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Sampling, the use of a randomly selected cross-section of the
population to estimate the entire population, would be a ``quality
check'' on the accuracy of the Census Bureau's more traditional
methods of trying to count every American household through mail
and follow-up visits, Waxman said.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing the Census Bureau to use sampling ``will best achieve
the Constitution's goal of determining the number of persons in
each state,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the House of Representatives and a group of
individuals that includes Matthew Glavin, president of the
Atlanta-based Southeastern Legal Foundation and Rep. Bob Barr, a
Georgia Republican leading the fight against sampling, agreed that
no census is likely to count everyone.
</P>
<P>
   But, they argued, the Court should uphold two lower court
rulings that blocked the sampling plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of accuracy, it is both illegal and
unconstitutional,'' said Michael Carvin, who represents Glavin and
Barr in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 100 percent head count is the only permissible means of
apportioning the population,'' Carvin said.
</P>
<P>
   In town for the case was Ohio's Secretary of State-elect Kenneth
Blackwell, who also is co-chairman of the U.S. Census Monitoring
Board. Blackwell, a Cincinnati Republican, opposes the use of
sampling techniques and held a press conference on the steps of the
Supreme Court after arguments concluded. The Monitoring Board,
which oversees both the planning and execution of the census, has
taken no position on the sampling issue.
</P>
<P>
   But Blackwell wants the Census Bureau to use federal documents
such as Medicaid records to double-check the accuracy of
preliminary census counts rather than estimations to arrive at the
final total. That, Blackwell argued, will meet the Constitutional
requirement of counting existing people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a traditional head count census,
supplemented with administrative records,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau has no plans to use such documents for the
2000 census, but is looking at adding them to the process for the
2010 count. Meanwhile, Blackwell said he's worried that all the
legal jousting could jeopardize the government's ability to conduct
the 2000 census because Census Bureau planners still don't know if
they'll be permitted to use the sampling technique they had
expected to have at their disposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a great chance that if this saga plays out too much
longer,'' Blackwell warned, ``we'll place the census at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Montgomery writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 2137EST &QL; 
