<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 30, 1998 -- RENO-ICKES, 11-30 -- In
1997, Harold Ickes, left, testified for three days before the
Senate Governmental Affairs Committee about his dealings with the
teamsters. Here he is seen conferring his lawyer, Robert Bennett,
on Oct. 8. Attorney General Janet Reno is to decide if an
independent counsel should investigate whether Ickes, a former top
White House aide, committed perjury before a Senate committee.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) SAN FRANCISCO -- Nov. 27, 1998 --CALIF-BROWN-2, 11-27 --
Mayor Willie Brown campaigns with Gray Davis during the primary
election season in May for governor of California. At right is
Dolores Huerta of the United Farmworkers Union. Brown knows how to
make the voters laugh, but they are still unhappy with him. In
fact, a recent poll found that only three of 10 were inclined to
back him for a second term. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) SAN FRANCISCO -- Nov. 30, 1998 -- CALIF-BROWN-1, 11-30
-- San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown during a memorial service for
the late Mayor George Moscone and Supervisor Harvey Milk. Brown
knows how to make the voters laugh, but they are still unhappy with
him. In fact, a recent poll found that only three of 10 were
inclined to back him for a second term. (Monica Almeida/New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 30, 1998 -- CHRISTMAS-FLOATER, 11-30
-- Workers rush to finish decorating the National Christmas Tree on
the Ellipse on the Mall, late Monday afternoon, in preparation for
a ceremony on Tuesday when Tipper Gore places the final ornament on
the top of the tree. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- Nov. 30, 1998 -- BOMBING-MILITANT, 11-30 --
The story of Ali Mohamed's dealings with the United States, based
on interviews with associates, government officials and former Army
officers, suggest that he was inexorably drawn to intrigue and the
shadowy gambits of espionage, and along the way, the U.S.
authorities missed opportunities to grasp the depth of his
allegiance to the cause of Islamic extremism. Mohamed is seen in
photo from videotape. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Nov. 30, 1998 -- NY-DINING, 11-30 -- A
vendor prepares food in New York's Midtown. The New York Historical
Society is holding an exhibit titled ``From Pushcarts to
Restaurants Deluxe: Dining in New York at the Turn of the
Century.'' The rituals of eating have always spoken volumes about a
place, particularly about New York. (William Lopez/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) PRINCETON, N.J. -- Nov. 30, 1998 -- SCI-EMBRYOS-COMPETE,
11-30 -- Dr. Shirley Tilghman of Princeton University in her lab.
Tilghman got some unexpected results in a study of genetic
imprinting involving two species of mice. (Dith Pran/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13)NEW YORK -- Nov. 30, 1998 -- HILFIGER-FASHION-2, 11-30 --
Tommy Hilfiger, left, hopes to keep his core trendy teenage
audience and capture a new customer with more sophisticated styles,
like these two cashmere dresses introduced for the fall. (Chester
Higgins Jr. /New York Times Photo)*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Nov. 30, 1998 -- HILFIGER-FASHION-1, 11-30
-- Tommy Hilfiger hopes to keep his core trendy teen-age audience
and capture a new customer with more sophisticated styles. From
top: Logo-free $2,950 crocodile handbag and open-toe sling-backs.
(Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) PRINCETON, Mass. -- Nov. 30, 1998 -- SCI-OLDFOREST-BOS,
11-30 -- John O'Keefe sits on an old beech tree along with David
Orwig, a forest ecologist. Behind them is a section of old forest
growth that has been virtually untouched. These trees are part of
the largest known old-growth forest in Massachusetts, about 200
acres of woodland that was never cut because no one thought the
timber was worth the trouble. (Justine Ellement /New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) ENGLEWOOD, N.J. -- Nov. 30, 1998 -- OIL-MERGER, 11-30 --
A Mobil and Exxon gasoline station in Englewood. A source close to
the merger talks between the two major oil companies says that they
are still working to complete a deal which could be announced as
early as Tuesday. (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Nov. 30, 1998 -- BERLIND-BROADWAY, 11-30 --
Producer Roger Berlind stands outside a New York theater. In just
over a week, Berlind will put on a tuxedo for the opening of ``The
Blue Room,'' starring Nicole Kidman, his 33rd opening night in the
22 years since leaving investment banking to produce plays. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Nov. 30, 1998 -- BALLET-HISPANICO, 11-30
--Ramon Oller, a choreographer with Ballet Hispanico, during a
rehearsal of ``Bury Me Standing,'' his new work that is based on a
book about Gypsies. The brooding psychic landscapes created by
history and personal experience are the terrain inhabited by three
of the new and recent dances that will be performed by Ballet
Hispanico in a two-week season opening Tuesday at the Joyce
Theater. (Nancy Siesel/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- Nov. 30, 1998 -- AMSTERDAM-BOOK-REVIEW, 11-30
-- Ian McEwan's new novel, ``Amsterdam,'' which won Britain's
prestigious Booker Prize this autumn, is a dark tour de force, a
morality fable, disguised as a psychological thriller. (Naum
Kazhdan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) MOUNTAINVIEW, Calif. -- Nov. 30, 1998 --
SCI-SAGAN-LEGACY, 11-30 -- Christopher Chyba, Ph.D., chairman of
the Carl Sagan Study of Life in the Universe, stands in front of an
artists rendering of the orgin and evolution of life, at the Seti
Institute in Mountain View. Chyba leads a 12-person panel drafting
plans for a spacecraft that the agency in 2003 wants to fire toward
Europa, a large moon of Jupiter whose icy, cracked surface hints
strongly of an interior ocean. (Susan Spann/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ALLENTOWN, Pa. -- Nov. 30, 1998 -- SCI-FITNESS-TREADMILL,
11-30 -- More gyms are using exercise equipment for group programs
like this Trekking class at the Conditioning Center in Allentown,
Pa. Group classes are moving out of the aerobics studio and on to
the cardiovascular machines found on the gym floor. Treadmill
classes in particular are beginning to appear on aerobics schedules
all across the country. (Sal DiMarco Jr. /New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) LOS ANGELES -- Nov. 30, 1998 -- SCI-SCIENTISTS-FILM,
11-30 -- The biologist James Watson, left, and Carolyn Porco, an
astronomer at right, discussed movies and science with David Milch,
a producer. Efforts are being mounted to get Hollywood to portray
scientists in a more realistic light, as people with more complex
drives and emotions. (Michael Tweed/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Nov. 30, 1998 -- SCI-ALZHEIMERS, 11-30 --
Using images obtained through magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), Dr.
Mony de Leon points to the Hippocampus, the area in the brain that
shrinks over the years in patients with Alzheimer's Disease.
Scientists at New York University Medical Center spent three days
exploring the brain of a woman in the search for clues about what
destroyed the brain of her mother at a very early age. (Barbara
Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 30, 1998 -- MIDEAST-ARAFAT-2, 11-30 --
President Clinton, flanked by Vice President Al Gore, foregruond,
and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, pose for photographers prior
to a closed-door meeting at the White House. Arafat, in Washington
for a donors' conference of potential financial donors, met with
Clinton and pressed for Palestinian statehood. (Stephen Crowley/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 30, 1998 -- MIDEAST-ARAFAT, 11-30 --
President Clinton calls for increased aid to Palestinians as
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, foreground second from
right, and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, right, confer on
Monday. Seated in the background right is National Security Advisor
Sandy Berger. Clinton, calling for increased aid to secure peace in
the region, announced his request to Congress for 400 million
dollars in additional US aid to the Palestinians. (Stephen Crowley
/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
