u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     11-30 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: OFFICIATING ERRORS ARE PART OF THE GAME
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ The defensive back, naturally, could not
believe the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go back and get all the Hail Marys on tape, and I'll bet
you my next paycheck that you would be hard pressed to find two
with no shoving on it,'' said the Jets' nickel back Corwin Brown.
``There's shoving on every one of them. Give me a break, man.''
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback, not surprisingly, argued that a pass into the
end zone from the 26-yard line is no Hail Mary, and it was about
time the man on offense got a last-second break.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's pass interference, it's pass interference,'' Vinny
Testaverde said. ``There's always a lot of bumping, and I always
thought the refs ought to make that call.''
</P>
<P>
   Get the picture? It is always a tossup as to which side of the
official's judgment we are going to wind up on. Heads, we win.
Tails, we whine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me into that one,'' Bill Parcells said, with no one
around to call the Jets' coach for delay of opinion. ``I have never
filed an official's report since 1983, and that's all I'm going to
say about it. When I'm retired from the league, I'll have something
to say about the officials.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the country was not about to wait, after a long,
contentious holiday weekend that produced several episodes of
referee rage, and Monday's historic rule change that will now
require the umpire to raise the existential question _ heads or
tails? _ and receive an answer before he tosses his coin.
</P>
<P>
   The comically botched pre-overtime toss in Detroit last Thursday
was the prelude to stunning end-game calls missed and made Sunday
in New England, which helped keep the soon-to-be Foxboro ex-Pats in
their divisional chase. While no one yet knows if this was good for
the Jets, Keith Byars, the veteran fullback, said he couldn't
remember a last-second call that bad. ``I would hope,'' he said,
``for instant replay.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the replay, the Patriots' Shawn Jefferson was out
of bounds for the 10-yard pass he caught at the Bills' 26 from Drew
Bledsoe on fourth-and-9, with six seconds left and the Patriots
trailing by 4 points. Bledsoe then somehow hit Terry Glenn in the
chest, in the end zone, in a crowd. Glenn dropped the ball, but an
official dropped a flag. The interference call against the Bills'
Henry Jones set up Bledsoe's 1-yard touchdown pass to Ben Coates,
and produced renewed calls for impeachment hearings against those
enterprising souls who depart the conventional work force each
weekend to become the National Football League's adjunct officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys do a good job, mainly, but they're not involved,
they're not there every day,'' Byars said. ``I said a few years ago
I would like for us to have full-time officials. We're the only
sport that doesn't have them.''
</P>
<P>
   An excellent point, except for this: Did we not just finish a
major league baseball season in which the unionized, full-salaried
umpires were vilified as the worst plague on the pastime since the
Black Sox scandal? And please tell me when anyone stood up recently
and applauded the work of those abused arbiters of basketball,
hockey, tennis, figure skating and any other sport whose winners
and losers are often determined by educated guesswork.
</P>
<P>
   Brutal, gut-wrenching calls have always been part of sports,
which have become more difficult than ever to officiate, with X-Ray
Cam waiting to freeze-frame every painful miscall. Granted, some of
these grandfatherly gents hanging on as NFL officials can't dodge
their own flipped coin, much less a snorting nose tackle. But then,
a reasonable man in his prime can see that half the job is making
the calls; the other half is avoiding one's death.
</P>
<P>
   In the era of performance enhancement, these players are
increasingly pumped up by weights and dietary supplements and who
knows what else? They hit harder, move faster and, as Parcells
said, an entire season could come down to inches, split seconds,
millions of dollars potentially risked on a single play. The
intolerance for those who officiate is going beyond the point of
being unfair. It is beginning to sound absurd.
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't the Bills could have stopped the Patriots from the
1-yard line Sunday? Couldn't Pittsburgh could have kicked off to
Detroit and held its ground? The NFL can go ahead and bring back
instant replay, stretch out a game already too long. There will
still be human error, which the best teams will continue to find
ways to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone sees one thing and someone sees another,'' a shrugging
Keyshawn Johnson said. ``There's good plays and bad, good calls and
bad. Everyone's human.''
</P>
<P>
   Amen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 2142EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981130.0473 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5738 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAYCARE01-AZR &LR;      11-30 1644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAYCARE01-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA TRAGEDY UNDERSCORES DANGERS OF UNREGULATED CHILD CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KARINA BLAND  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The cops knew Nancy Musser was operating a child-care
center in Phoenix even though she had been suspected of fracturing
the skull of a newborn baby four years earlier. So did state Child
Protective Services.
</P>
<P>
   But Inez Heath and Kim Gray had no way of knowing about Musser's
background when they left their newborn twins in her care.
</P>
<P>
   Now one of the twins is dead. And the surviving twin, 2-year-old
Emily, points to pictures of her dead brother and asks for her
``bubba.''
</P>
<P>
   Their story is an example of what can happen in states like
Arizona where anyone can get paid for watching as many as four
children in their own homes with no government regulation or
interference.
</P>
<P>
   And because there is no central agency or registry where parents
can file complaints or check out potential caretakers for previous
offenses, someone like Musser can hurt a child and still stay in
business.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 87,000 Arizona children are cared for by as many as
6,000 unlicensed, unregulated child-care providers.
</P>
<P>
   But a bill being proposed for the 1999 legislative session by
child advocates would require criminal background checks as well as
clearance by CPS for such providers. It also would create a central
registry where parents could file complaints. &UR; The proposal would
not apply to all small providers but to anyone who cares for two or
more children from more than one family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to extend this protection to your next-door
neighbor who watches your children or relatives,'' Bruce Liggett of
Children's Action Alliance, a non-profit advocacy group, says.
``We're trying to identify people who are in the business of child
care.''
</P>
<P>
   People like Nancy Musser.
</P>
<P>
   She is now at the Arizona State Prison Complex-Perryville,
serving a 10-year term for child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until after Musser was arrested for shaking their
son, Matthew, did Heath and Gray learn that she been investigated
by police and CPS over allegations she fractured the skull of a
3-month-old baby in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The child was in Musser's care when the mother arrived to find
the baby limp and listless. At the hospital, doctors discovered a
skull fracture.
</P>
<P>
   Musser was never prosecuted, though, because of a lack of
evidence. But had the proposed legislation been in effect, a
criminal background check and CPS clearance would have turned up
the 1992 incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had known, the children never would have been there,''
Heath, 43, the twin's birth mother, says. She and Gray are a
lesbian couple. &QL; 
RESISTANCE TO BILL LIKELY
</P>
<P>
   Although the women say the proposed legislation could have saved
their son's life, it is sure to come up against resistance in the
state Legislature where lawmakers have turned down similar bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I want kids protected,'' says House Majority Leader
Lori Daniels, R-Chandler. ``But parents also have the
responsibility to protect their children and check out the places
where they leave them.''
</P>
<P>
   Other lawmakers worry that the cost of background checks and the
like would put too big of a financial burden on small providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing you'll do is drive a lot of these people out
of business,'' says Rep. Bob Burns, R-Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   And that could make child care harder to find and more
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, logically speaking, if it is minimum health and safety
that we are trying to guarantee through rules and regulation, then
it makes sense that those rules and regulations ought to follow the
child,'' Burns says.
</P>
<P>
   Liggett, a former child-care project manager for the state
Department of Economic Security, wrote the proposal after hearing
the horror stories of parents like Gray and Heath.
</P>
<P>
   FILE OF COMPLAINTS
</P>
<P>
   He has a file of names of parents whose kids have been neglected
or abused by the people paid to care for them. They are cases,
Liggett says, that may have been prevented by the proposed
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   On Memorial Day in 1997, Tania Brindley left her youngest
daughter, 18-month-old Kasia, with her neighbor, a woman who had
been baby sitting Kasia and her sister, Monique, 4, for more than a
year.
</P>
<P>
   That night, when Brindley came to pick up Kasia, she found her
on the living room floor, covered with bruises. She was having a
seizure.
</P>
<P>
   The baby sitter said she got caught under a trundle bed. But at
the hospital, doctors said Kasia had a subdural hematoma the size
of the surgeon's fist in her brain. Her little skull was
fractured. &UR; The baby sitter was charged with child abuse and
sentenced in December 1997 to 20 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Now 3, Kasia walks with a limp and has a speech impediment. She
is epileptic and goes to speech, occupational and physical therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Monique was hit, too, Brindley found later, and once made to eat
her own vomit. She goes to counseling.
</P>
<P>
   `YOU COULD BE A MURDERER'
</P>
<P>
   Without the proposed legislation, the baby sitter can easily set
up shop again when she gets out of jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could be a murderer, fresh out of prison, and you could
care for four or fewer children in your home for pay,'' Liggett
says. ``There would be no one looking over your shoulder. No one
would have to know.''
</P>
<P>
   State law allows child-care providers to operate free of
regulation as long as they care for four or fewer children _ like
the women who cared for Kasia and Matthew.
</P>
<P>
   DES offers certification for such providers but it is voluntary,
not mandated. There are no background checks; it is simply a
registry. That can be revoked, but the provider can care for kids
without it.
</P>
<P>
   Only providers who want to care for children whose care is
subsidized by DES _ an estimated 1,300 _ must be certified by DES,
and that certification mandates inspections and health and staffing
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Only child-care providers who watch more than four children must
be certified by the state Department of Health and subject to its
regulations, including inspections and health standards, says
Lourdes Ochoa, program manager with DHS' Office of Child Care and
Licensure. She estimates DHS has about 250 licensed child-care
homes. &QL; 
6,000 NOT COVERED
</P>
<P>
   That leaves as many as 6,000 child-care homes not covered by
either agency's certification.
</P>
<P>
   DES funds the Child Care Resource and Referral, a free registry
for child-care providers and parents looking for child care. It,
too, is a voluntary listing for providers, and the agency offers
parents no guarantees about quality of care.
</P>
<P>
   At first, anyone caring for four or fewer children could list
themselves with the agency.
</P>
<P>
   But starting three years ago, the agency required providers sign
a notarized statement saying they had never been investigated for
child abuse or neglect, denied a license for child care in any
state or convicted of a criminal offense.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than sign it, 900 providers dropped from the agency's
rolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We let parents know that when you are using an unregulated
provider, there is nobody who is going into that home and
regulating what is going on there,'' executive director Susan
Wilkins says. ``No one is monitoring. No one is doing background
checks.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, her agency gives parents a place to file complaints, and
parents can read those files before choosing a provider. The agency
takes complaints only on its own providers.
</P>
<P>
   RANGE OF COMPLAINTS
</P>
<P>
   Complaints range from providers watching more than four children
and not changing diapers often enough to not feeding children and
upping fees with no notice.
</P>
<P>
   Some complaints are more harrowing. Had they happened in
child-care homes not listed with the agency, no one ever would
know.
</P>
<P>
   In January of 1996, a child was molested by an 11-year-old boy
while in the provider's care. In October 1993, a parent complained
that an infant was covered in bruises and bite marks. And in
January of 1993, a parent reported seeing a provider beating her
own 2-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   ``We suggest that parents check out the provider themselves _
see if the children seem to be happy, if they will let you in at
any hour of operation, that the house is clean,'' Wilkins says.
``And then continue to monitor what goes on inside the home.''
</P>
<P>
   Heath and Gray did just that.
</P>
<P>
   Musser was recommended by another woman who had cared for their
older son, Joey, now 4. They talked to the other parents who left
their kids in Musser's care.
</P>
<P>
   Musser watched Joey for 18 months before the women left the
10-week-old twins in her care. She was an ideal caregiver, the
women say, keeping meticulous notes about what each child ate,
number of diaper changes and how long they slept.
</P>
<P>
   Musser was even a Sunday school teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We trusted her,'' Gray, 41, says.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Sept. 27, 1996, Gray picked up the children. Both she
and Heath are nurses, so Gray knew something was wrong with Matthew
as soon as she saw him. His skin was yellow.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was like a dishrag,'' Gray says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Musser told Gray that Matthew had spit up and choked. But
doctors said Matthew had been shaken. He suffered brain damage and
internal bleeding. His ribs were broken.
</P>
<P>
   When Matthew got out of the hospital a month later, Heath and
Gray worked opposite shifts, so one would always be home with him.
A shunt drained fluid from his brain. He was fed through a tube.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs show Matthew smiling. He could say ``Hi.''
</P>
<P>
   He could move his hands and legs but not control his head. He
liked music and he could see things that were bright, like the
children's television show character Barney.
</P>
<P>
   But despite his apparent recovery, the injuries had been too
much for him. He died on June 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like we lost Matthew twice,'' Gray says, her eyes filling
with tears. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
