<HEADLINE>
NIXON-ERA AG SAYS HOUSE SHOULD CENSURE CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Budgeted as House-Impeach)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A generation after he clashed with President Nixon
in the ``Saturday Night Massacre'' of Watergate, the US attorney
general of that era, Elliot L. Richardson, said Monday that the
House should censure President Clinton and reject the effort to
impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, a Republican who served as attorney general and
lieutenant governor of Massachusetts in the 1960s, before he went
to Washington, made the recommendation in a telephone interview as
he prepared to testify Tuesday before the House Judiciary Committee
in a hearing on ``the consequences of perjury and related crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole case rests on the coverup and the lies about an
affair with a young woman,'' said Richardson, 78, who also served
as defense secretary under Nixon and commerce secretary under
President Gerald R. Ford. ``The matter is absent the elements of
abuse of power that were contingent to the Nixon case.''
</P>
<P>
   In calling for Clinton's censure, Richardson, a Washington
lawyer, has joined several other prominent GOP figures, including
Ford, who have proposed sanctioning Clinton short of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson is scheduled to appear before the Judiciary Committee
with two federal judges, two military officers, several legal
scholars, and two women who were convicted of perjury for lying
about their sexual relationships. The witness list also includes
Alan Dershowitz, a professor at Harvard Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson resigned as US attorney general in 1973 when Nixon
ordered him to fire Archibald Cox, the special prosecutor for
Watergate. The episode became known as the ``Saturday Night
Massacre.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said the House would forfeit any chance of censuring
Clinton if it sends articles of impeachment to the Senate, where
``the only remedy is the president's removal of office.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want something short of removing the president from
office, you cannot support the charge of impeachment,'' Richardson
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 2143EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
