<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5742 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANKERS-NEWMAN-2TAKES     11-30 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKERS-NEWMAN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHIEF EXECUTIVE COMES UP SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BANKERS-TRUST-DEUTSCHE, BANKERS-DEAL, BANKERS-INDUSTRY) 
(lb) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It wasn't supposed to end this way.
</P>
<P>
   When Frank Newman took over Bankers Trust Corp. three years ago
he vowed to rein in the New York bank's vaunted trading operation _
widely viewed as populated by free-wheeling hot shots more
interested in making big bets on the direction of financial markets
than in the well-being of their clients _ and he regularly
proclaimed his determination to maintain Bankers Trust's
independence.
</P>
<P>
   Now, undone by huge trading losses and nasty internal strife at
the eighth-largest bank in the United States, Newman, 56, has been
forced into an act he firmly opposed as recently as five months
ago: the sale of Bankers Trust.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, in a move that has been widely anticipated for more
than a week, Deutsche Bank, the German banking giant, formally
announced plans for a $10.1 billion acquisition of Bankers Trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank will go down in history as the person who sold Bankers
Trust,'' said Raphael Soifer, an analyst with Brown Brothers
Harriman. ``Frank is partially the victim of circumstance, but as
the bank evolved under him, with an emphasis on emerging markets,
trading in Eastern Europe and Asia, junk bonds, and initial public
offerings, he left Bankers Trust particularly vulnerable to the
global financial turmoil of the last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Newman, who declined repeated requests for an interview, is
certainly not the only victim of the upheaval that has ripped
through international banks in an unusually tumultuous year. Some
chief executives, like Mathis Cabiallavetta of UBS in Switzerland,
and Martin Taylor, the chief executive of Barclays, Britain's
biggest bank, lost their jobs after huge trading losses
materialized.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, as in the ousters of James Dimon, Citigroup's
president, and David Coulter, the president of BankAmerica, trading
losses provided a convenient excuse for departures that were the
result of more deep-seated corporate frictions.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of his counterparts in the banking world, Newman was
blind-sided this summer by trading losses that snowballed after
Russia devalued its currency and declared a debt moratorium in
mid-August. Unlike them, he has not lost his job.
</P>
<P>
   But while Newman will join the board of Deutsche Bank and have a
senior position in the investment banking unit created by
Deutsche's purchase of Bankers Trust, he is not expected to wield
significant managerial control in the new entity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the third quarter hadn't happened, I would have
characterized Newman's legacy as having led a significant
turnaround in the company's fortunes,'' said Diane Glossman, an
analyst with Lehman Brothers Holdings. ``He did a remarkable amount
of work in a short period of time, but then his time ran out.''
</P>
<P>
   The clock started ticking for Newman in July.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Newman's position was relatively strong. Wanting to
keep the bank intact, he had recently spurned overtures from Bank
of New York, Mellon Bank and State Street Corp. to sell Bankers
Trust's valuable business as a securities custodian.
</P>
<P>
   And in a June interview, around the same time that Deutsche Bank
first privately floated the idea of a merger, Newman firmly
asserted that Bankers Trust would remain independent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are proponents of the idea that bigger is not necessarily
better,'' he said at the time. ``We're trying to find markets where
we can add value.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Newman accepted an invitation in July from a senior
Deutsche Bank investment banker and board member, Ronaldo Schmitz,
to dine at the St. Regis Hotel in Manhattan. They revisited the
possibility of a merger, according to executives later involved in
the transaction, though people close to Newman said he was
noncommittal at that meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Newman had every reason to believe then that he did not have to
rush into a marriage with Deutsche Bank, a plodding financial
behemoth that had been badly bruised by previous, ill-considered
forays into investment banking _ an arena where Bankers Trust was
making inroads. Newman still enjoyed strong support from his board
and he had managed to steer Bankers Trust away from an overreliance
on trading.
</P>
<P>
   Big banks long ago branched away from the traditional business
of making loans to corporations and began trading stocks, bonds,
currencies and more exotic financial products known as derivatives.
Bankers Trust, founded in 1903 to handle the trust business of
other large banks, had transformed itself in the late 1980s and
1990s into one of the most aggressive and innovative trading shops
on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   But a series of derivatives scandals a few years ago wreaked
financial havoc on the bank and led to the departure of Charles
Sanford as its chairman and the ascent of Newman to that position.
</P>
<P>
   Newman's credentials _ he had been the chief financial officer
of Wells Fargo and BankAmerica before serving as a top official in
the Treasury Department from 1993 to 1995 _ were seen as the balm
needed to restore credibility to Bankers Trust's damaged
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Newman, who had no experience as a trader or an investment
banker, never entirely fit in at Bankers Trust. He is respected for
his analytical abilities and methodical planning, but he was widely
criticized within Bankers Trust for being aloof and awkward in
social settings.
</P>
<P>
   Newman also relied on a small group of advisers from the West
Coast, especially the chief financial officer, Richard Daniel, a
move that alienated some senior executives. And as befalls any
executive seeking to reshape a company, Newman also made enemies
among traders who resented his cutbacks in their business.
</P>
<P>
   Even with these tensions, Newman succeeded in making important
changes at Bankers Trust despite the financial mess he inherited.
``He came into a company that was very beaten down and so focused
on derivatives products that it had lost its competitive edge,''
observed Judah Kraushaar, a Merrill Lynch analyst.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, 72 percent of Bankers Trust's profits came from
trading. Last year, only 16 percent did. And as Newman guided
Bankers Trust more deeply into overseas markets and allowed the
firm's junk-bond business to expand, he also bolstered the
company's presence in investment banking last year by buying Alex.
Brown &AMP; Sons, a small but well-regarded regional brokerage firm
with an important role in underwriting technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an uneven performance earlier this year, Newman was
still well positioned to keep Deutsche Bank at a distance until the
torrent of ill will unleashed by the Alex. Brown acquisition and
substantial trading losses in July and August combined to weaken
his standing. At that point, insiders say, he began to lose the
ability to determine his own fate.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Many Alex. Brown employees grumbled that the sale of their firm
left them in a financial nether world. They were no longer an
independent regional brokerage, yet they were trapped inside a bank
that still lacked the heft to compete with the most powerful Wall
Street investment firms.
</P>
<P>
   Several senior executives left Alex. Brown, and many of those
who stayed were unhappy, bankers said, particularly Mayo Shattuck,
a long-time Alex. Brown employee who became co-head of Bankers
Trust's investment banking unit.
</P>
<P>
   Shattuck, who is scheduled to play a senior role in Deutsche
Bank's new investment banking operation created by the Bankers
Trust acquisition, is said by colleagues to have been among the
most vocal critics of Newman. Shattuck did not return calls seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in newspapers and magazines, reports began to surface
this summer of Newman's fondness for glittering parties and
expensive corporate perks. Newman's supporters attributed them to
disgruntled employees trying to smear his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, it was clear that several members of the bank's
board were not pleased with the publicity surrounding Newman's
spending and fondness for a phalanx of private security guards. One
person close to the board, and a supporter of Newman, said some
board members were ``poisoned'' against Newman by the turmoil at
Alex. Brown and by unwanted public interest in his spending habits.
</P>
<P>
   All this unrest might have been smoothed over had it not been
for hundreds of millions of dollars in trading losses that,
beginning in July, hit Bankers Trust, including an embarrassing
disclosure of a big hedge-fund loss related to Russia. Ultimately,
the bank posted a third-quarter loss of $488 million and, despite
Newman's reputation for risk aversion, disclosed that its
sophisticated models to manage risk-taking had failed to perform
effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank made the promise to reduce the risk profile of Bankers
Trust but look what happened in the third quarter,'' said Soifer,
the analyst at Brown Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   As Bankers Trust's stock price fell, the bank was roiled by
internal accusations that Newman had allowed its risky junk-bond
portfolio to balloon, senior employees said.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank, which had dubbed its takeover campaign ``Osprey''
after the black-and-white bird of prey, stopped considering a
purchase of the San Francisco brokerage firm Hambrecht &AMP; Quist and
began circling Bankers Trust more closely.
</P>
<P>
   With Bankers Trust's financial position severely weakened,
Newman was forced to take the takeover proposal much more
seriously. He held talks with Deutsche Bank's chairman, Rolf
Breuer, at an International Monetary Fund conference in Washington
in September and followed up with a meeting at Breuer's home in
Frankfurt, Germany, in October.
</P>
<P>
   When Bankers Trust reported its big loss for the quarter on Oct.
22, Deutsche Bank made its move. It quickly offered $93 a share for
the beleaguered bank. Details of the transaction were worked out by
investment bankers from Goldman, Sachs, which was advising Deutsche
Bank, and by Jeffery Goldstein, an investment banker with Bankers
Trust. Morgan Stanley Dean Witter was also hired as an outside
adviser to Bankers Trust.
</P>
<P>
   Newman's future is hazy. In a news conference Monday, Breuer
said that Newman's duties would involve overseeing the integration
of the two companies, helping to negotiate regulatory hurdles in
the United States and dealing with claims stemming from Deutsche
Bank's involvement with the Nazis during the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that Frank will just be a transitional figure,''
Soifer said, ``and he'll be there for only a few years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 2145EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
