<DOCNO> NYT19981130.0478 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5746 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILFIGER-FASHION-ART-     11-30 1437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILFIGER-FASHION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILFIGERS FOR MOM, OR AT LEAST FOR BIG SISTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If only daughters wore what their mothers wore, designers' lives
would be easier. But that is not the case, and so Tommy Hilfiger
has set himself a daunting challenge in his bid to dress not only
the hip young teen-ager with whom he has been so successful, but
now, the older, more serious career-minded customer.
</P>
<P>
   Hilfiger is introducing two new women's collections that are so
mature and career-minded as to be unrecognizable beside the
fun-loving, logo-emblazoned sportswear that he's known for.
</P>
<P>
   Can Hilfiger, whose mass-market success has been one of the most
remarkable of the past decade, sell clothes without the tip-off of
his blaring flag iconography and large-wrought signature, which are
almost universally recognized?
</P>
<P>
   He certainly hopes so. He wants to sell a teen-ager a pair of
jeans and her mother a tailored gray and pink wool suit, or a
$2,000-plus crocodile handbag.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more sophisticated, but it still has a youthful look,''
Hilfiger said of the two new lines. ``I don't want to abandon that.
If I have to fail to sell clothes to a 50-year-old woman because of
that, then that's the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   The pricier of the two collections is already in his Beverly
Hills store. A bridge collection, slightly less expensive, arrives
next spring.
</P>
<P>
   History shows that there are difficulties expanding upward into
more expensive and complex fashion. In the 1980s and early '90s,
Guess, which had been wildly successful selling jeans and other
fashions to teen-agers, failed in its efforts to establish a
higher-priced brand.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Liz Claiborne, a label that thought it had
across-the-board cachet, found itself ousted from Saks Fifth Avenue
when its broad distribution made it a liability to the store's
rarefied image. Claiborne went on to make a mark in the bridge area
with the formidable Dana Buchman brand, which has no association
with the Claiborne name and operates as a separate division.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Hilfiger may defy all these precedents. His Midaslike touch
has already extended beyond his original market of polo shirts and
jeans for men to include boys' wear, men's tailored sportswear,
jeans wear, clothes for teen-age girls, fragrance and home
furnishings. In a rare feat, he has remained hot with hip-hoppers
and Wall Streeters alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy has been an amazing phenomenon in so many ways,'' said
Faye I. Landes, a retail analyst and a managing director at Salomon
Smith Barney. ``The brand has been able to transcend what it
started out as. For a long time we heard that Tommy was just the
inner city _ oh, Tommy is just men's and boys. He's done a very
nice job with the women's.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Landes has taken a look at the top-of-the-line collection in
the Hilfiger Beverly Hills store, priced from about $250 for a
jacket to more than $3,000 for a silk jersey gown. She said that
even though the overall market for career clothes and bridge lines
is doing poorly, she is optimistic about the new Hilfiger lines.
``They repeatedly show they can do more with the brand than people
thought they might originally,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While most fashion stocks, including that of Ralph Lauren, whom
Hilfiger is so often accused of imitating, have been hurt this
year, Hilfiger has surged 32 percent. Sales of the label's products
reached $661.7 million for the fiscal year ended in March, and are
expected to exceed that in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Hilfiger, perhaps better than anyone, understands the gamble,
and is proceeding cautiously. ``I think it's a risky business,'' he
said. ``Designers with expensive collections have failed miserably
from a business point of view. Look what happened to the bridge
business. Look what happened to the designer business in department
stores.''
</P>
<P>
   Department stores, most notably the Federated chain, which
includes Macy's, have pulled backed markedly in designer-priced
clothes. And in the last 12 months, sales of bridge clothes, a rung
below designer, have slowed strikingly, retailers said.
</P>
<P>
   Hilfiger expects first-year sales of the collection to be no
more than $5 million and wavers about any sales projections over
$20 million for the line, even at its maturity.
</P>
<P>
   The two collections will be introduced exclusively in the
Hilfiger flagship stores in Beverly Hills, London and Mexico City,
and in two more to open next year in London and Sao Paolo. They are
not being offered to some of Hilfiger's best customers, like
Macy's.
</P>
<P>
   He has his sights on top specialty stores like Bergdorf Goodman,
Saks Fifth Avenue and Nordstrom, which will have a chance to buy
the line for fall 1999, he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn$taf-z &QL; 
u lxxnt26 nt22 nt06 nt11 nt17 nt33 &QL; 
ulxx nypt &QL; 
 &UR; BC-HILFIGER-FASHION-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: he said. &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're offering the new, expensive collection only in places
where people understand it,'' he said. ``We're not going to sell it
to Dillard or in the heartland. I expect my Beverly Hills customer
to understand it. I've been so successful in everything I've done,
I'm afraid to put it out there in department stores and have it not
sell.''
</P>
<P>
   The collections' style is a clean, sophisticated exuberance, an
interpretation of the Hilfiger signature. Now it turns up in
sweater sets or nylon handbags suitable for the office. But the
collections go further with slinky silk jersey evening columns
sprinkled with beads, perforated suede dresses, gray and white
ankle-length windowpane skirts and navy two-button jackets.
Handbags and shoes bear logos that don't suggest traditional
Hilfiger flags. Some are logo-free.
</P>
<P>
   As career-oriented as the clothes are, when designing this line
Hilfiger took celebrities as his muse. His real secret may be, as
Ms. Landes said, the recognition that everyone can dress like a
celebrity, an idea first put forth by the entertainers who populate
hip-hop culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking young, I'm thinking about a lot of the musicians
_ from Lauryn Hill to Sheryl Crow to Gwen Stefani from No Doubt _
who inspire me,'' Hilfiger said.
</P>
<P>
   One potential roadblock to Hilfiger's dream of seeing his new
lines sold widely is the tendency of high-end retailers to guard
their prestige jealously. A fast-selling populist label may quickly
fill coffers, but can also jeopardize a store's image. But in
Hilfiger's favor is his strong association with celebrity and
youth, which almost any fashion store finds attractive. Saks said
it will definitely consider the collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen other designers inspired by the street, so for him,
who started in that, why shouldn't he address his creativity to
this market?'' said Nicole Fischelis, a vice president and fashion
director for Saks. ``Ultimately, it's the product and how it's
marketed. It's more about the product than the image.''
</P>
<P>
   With Hilfiger, of course, it is his image _ fun, youthful, sexy,
informal _ that has helped propel his success. And it is this image
that Estee Lauder is banking on; its Aramis division will introduce
a Hilfiger cosmetics line and a fragrance next fall, both primarily
for an older customer _ anyone over 19, in Hilfiger's world _ for
whom subtlety in design has its appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmetics will include basic colors and trendy shades, for the
core Hilfiger customer as well as the new one being courted, said
Pamela Baxter, senior vice president and general manager for
Aramis. ``We have to address both,'' she said. ``It will work as
long as Tommy stays tied to the world he's tied into _ music and
movieland.''
</P>
<P>
   With no color cosmetics brands on the market from any other
American designers (no less than Ralph Lauren, Diane Von
Furstenburg and Calvin Klein have all tried and failed), Hilfiger,
whose cosmetics will cost $10 to $15, is trying yet another
high-wire act. ``Right now we don't see a competitor,'' Ms. Baxter
said. The new fragrance _ unnamed so far _ will also be skewed
toward women 18 to 35.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hilfiger's attempt to redefine his image upward is a
big challenge, he is entering the new market modestly. ``A $5
million business doesn't even register on my radar screen,'' he
said flippantly.
</P>
<P>
   But here's a thought to give Hilfiger pause: if the young people
who now find his brand so hip turn away once they notice that
adults, too, are wearing it, his core business _ the goose that has
laid golden eggs _ may begin to suffer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
