<HEADLINE>
RED SOX SEEK ALTERNATIVE TO WILLIAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There may be gloom on Yawkey Way because Bernie
Williams refused to surrender his pinstripes, but paralysis has not
set in. The phone lines are still working, and Monday Red Sox
general manager Dan Duquette and his lieutenants were making the
rounds of agents and teams, exploring how they might stitch
together an alternative course of action.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have not entirely abandoned the notion that Rafael
Palmeiro would be an acceptable substitute for Mo Vaughn at first
base. Monday, the Sox called Palmeiro's agent, Jim Bronner, though
no new offers were forthcoming. Palmeiro's incumbent team, the
Orioles, already has offered him a five-year, $45 million deal, and
the Texas Rangers, having failed to achieve their top priority of
signing pitcher Randy Johnson, are expected to turn their
attentions to Palmeiro, who last season hit more home runs (43 to
40) and drove in more runs (121 to 115) than Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox talked more about potential scenarios than the
specifics of an offer, Bronner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're certainly not trying to overwhelm us,'' said the
agent. ``I think they're trying to do some other things, but
they're not willing to let us go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox also have had conversations with Robin Ventura, recently
the recipient of a four-year, $32 million offer from the Orioles
after receiving a lesser bid from the Mets. Ventura gives Baltimore
an option in case Palmeiro heads elsewhere and could be reuniting
with Albert Belle, his White Sox teammate who may be signing with
the Orioles as soon as Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the immediate wake of the Yankees' unexpected decision to
yield to Williams's demand for a seven-year, $87.5 million
contract, Duquette said he intended to turn his attentions to
upgrading the club's pitching staff, which supposedly was the No. 1
offseason priority all along. The best pitcher still available in
free agency is righthander Kevin Brown, who has expressed a
preference to remain in the National League, though his agent,
Scott Boras, said he would not rule out the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   To sign Brown, the Red Sox would have to pay him more than the
six-year, $75 million deal they gave Pedro Martinez last winter,
which is a remote option.
</P>
<P>
   They have talked about Tim Belcher, who was 14-14 with a 4.27
ERA for a lousy Kansas City team last summer, and Monday, they
spoke with Pete Schourek's agent (Bronner) about a two-year deal
that would bring the lefthander back to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek, remember, distinguished himself with a gallant
six-inning stint in Game 4 of the Division Series against the
Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   In 10 days, baseball's winter meetings begin in Nashville, and
Duquette is expected to be active on the trade front at that time.
The Sox almost certainly will renew their pitch for Montreal
outfielder Rondell White, who hit .300 with 17 home runs and 58
RBIs in an injury-disrupted season. The Sox already have spoken to
Montreal about White, but their initial proposals, which included
young prospects such as outfielder Dernell Stenson and pitcher
Robert Ramsay, were rebuffed. The Expos turned down a much richer
package of prospects from the Yankees for White.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
