<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5756 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-IMPEACH-BOS &LR;      11-30 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-IMPEACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL TO PROBE CLINTON FUND-RAISING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican-controlled House Judiciary
Committee, in a sudden shift, is poised to widen the impeachment
case against President Clinton by examining White House
fund-raising practices in the 1996 elections, congressional sources
said Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Republicans decided Monday to subpoena FBI Director
Louis J. Freeh and a former top Justice Department prosecutor,
Charles LaBella, to privately question why they recommended that
Attorney General Janet Reno seek an independent counsel to
investigate Clinton's fund-raising activities, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's GOP majority, in a closed-door meeting tonight, also
plans to send subpoenas for documents to Clinton and Reno, ordering
them to turn over the confidential memos in which Freeh and LaBella
called for an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Reno rebuffed the recommendation, although a Justice Department
investigation of the 1996 campaign finance activities continues.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Judiciary Committee plans to approve a subpoena
for independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr to turn over evidence he
has involving John Huang, a former Democratic fund-raiser and
central figure in the fund-raising investigation. Starr
investigated whether Huang made payments to Clinton's friend,
Webster L. Hubbell, in exchange for Hubbell's secrecy in the
Whitewater inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Additional subpoenas are expected to be sent to the Justice
Department for information on three other former Democratic
fund-raisers who have been linked to fund-raising abuses: Johnny
Chung, Yah Lin ``Charlie'' Trie, and Mark Middleton.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported Monday night that Paul McNulty, a
spokesman for Republicans on the Judiciary Committee, said, ``The
committee has received information which suggests that the campaign
finance abuse memos may contain allegations of criminal wrongdoing
by the president. The committee is duty-bound to investigate that
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources said committee Republicans also plan to make public
portions of the president's videotaped civil deposition in the
recently settled sexual harassment lawsuit that Paula Corbin Jones
filed against him. The panel's chief GOP investigative counsel,
David P. Schippers, wants to show the videotape when he makes a
final presentation to the committee, as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic moves came as Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry J.
Hyde followed many committee Republicans in blasting Clinton for
his responses last week to 81 questions from the GOP majority about
allegations stemming from the president's sexual affair with Monica
S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of shedding new light on the key facts, the president
chose to evade them,'' Hyde said. ``He has made it very clear he is
going to stick with his reliance on bizarre technical definitions
and legalistic defenses.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and FBI had no immediate response to the
GOP plans. However, Reno, Freeh and LaBella previously have refused
to turn over the confidential documents to other congressional
committees. LaBella is the former head of Reno's campaign-finance
task force investigating the 1996 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Democrats lashed out at the new GOP initiative,
describing it as a frantic attempt to revive a moribund inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just left shaking our heads at the weirdness of it
all,'' said Jim Jordan, spokesman for the committee Democrats.
``We've said before, and this is confirmation, that this is an
impeachment in search of a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   With Republicans outnumbering Democrats on the committee, 21-16,
the GOP subpoena plans are expected to be readily approved.
</P>
<P>
   The move to expand the inquiry comes as Reno faces a deadline of
next Monday to decide whether to seek an independent counsel to
investigate Clinton's fund-raising activities. She decided last
week against seeking an independent counsel to examine Vice
President Al Gore's campaign finance activities.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the impeachment inquiry's new direction, sources said
Hyde tentatively set a schedule Monday to complete House action on
the impeachment issue before Christmas week. Under the preliminary
plan, Clinton's lawyer, David E. Kendall, would present the
president's defense before the full committee next Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's chief investigative counsels _ Schippers for the
Republicans and Abbe Lowell for the Democrats _ would make
presentations on Dec. 8 and 9.
</P>
<P>
   Then the 37-member panel would debate and vote on proposed
articles of impeachment against Clinton on Dec. 10, 11, and
possibly Saturday, Dec. 12. The commitee also will consider
Democratic motions for alternative sanctions, such as resolutions
of censure, rebuke or disapproval.
</P>
<P>
   Under Hyde's plan, any measure that passes the committee would
be considered by the full House as soon as Dec. 14 and no later
than Dec. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the president's failure to respond in a helpful
manner, we will move forward based on the established record of
corroborated evidence,'' Hyde said, referring to Starr's 445-report
on the Lewinsky matter. ``If the president leaves undisputed the
record or where he has given evasive responses, we will be forced
to assume that the corroborated evidence is accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Jim Kennedy took issue with Hyde's
characterization of Clinton's responses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president made a good faith effort to respond to
politically motivated questions,'' Kennedy said. ``The chairman
should recognize that the country's interest in a fair and
constitutional process comes ahead of partisan games like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The developments unfolded as the Judiciary Committee prepared to
convene a hearing Tuesday on ``the consequences of perjury and
related crimes.'' The public hearing will be only the third _ and
possibly the last _ before the panel hears the final presentations
next week.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart called the session ``a
stunt.'' He also questioned the fairness of the
Republican-controlled Judiciary Committee, and said he did not
expect Clinton to accept an invitation to defend himself before the
panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's very likely that you'll see the president
appear before that committee,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, Democratic fund-raiser Nathan Landow refused to
testify in a closed-door deposition with the committee, citing his
Fifth Amendment right against self-incrimination. Landow has
acknowledged talking with former White House volunteer Kathleen
Willey about her allegation that Clinton groped her and tried to
kiss her near the Oval Office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Republicans want to know if Clinton played any role in
trying to influence Willey's testimony in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the Willey inquiry, the committee also has subpoenaed
Robert S. Bennett, the president's lawyer in the Jones case, and
Bruce R. Lindsey, a White House deputy counsel and one of Clinton's
most trusted advisers. But sources said the committee may withdraw
Bennett's subpoena and focus on questioning Lindsey in a deposition
on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
