<HEADLINE>
HOTELS AT JFK BUFF THEIR IMAGE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 6) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost everyone who flies has spent at least part of a night at
an airport hotel. Predawn departures, missed connections, canceled
flights, oversold seats: all sorts of things can lead to a
sleepless stay, watching car headlights flicker across the ceiling
and hearing planes taking off and landing.
</P>
<P>
   We stalled travelers are known in airport-hotel jargon as
``distress'' customers. The phrase is usually apt: already pained
by the forces that brought us there, we are still more distressed
by the place we have been deposited. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But hotels at airports are changing. Figures from Smith Travel
Research in Hendersonville, Tenn., show that airport hotels
nationally had a 70.5 percent occupancy rate last year, which
outstripped other sorts of hotels from luxury to budget.
</P>
<P>
   For this year, until September, the figure was 71.3 percent. An
analysis by the magazine Hotel and Motel Management cited as causes
both an improvement in facilities _ business centers, fitness
centers and tennis courts _ and an overflow of guests from downtown
hotels.
</P>
<P>
   These trends are visible in New York around Kennedy
International Airport, where three of the five hotels within about
five minutes' driving time have just completed major overhauls. Two
are shiny new hotels in old shells, one empty for years and the
other a former welfare hotel.
</P>
<P>
   A third completed renovations this year while continuing to
operate. All attract business and vacation guests, in addition to
the usual flow of airline crews and stranded passengers. Unlike
some airports, including Bradley at Hartford and Bangor, Maine,
Kennedy does not have a hotel attached to the main terminal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's five hotels, in a quiet residential part of Jamaica,
Queens, bear familiar names: Ramada Plaza, JFK Airport Hilton, Four
Points by Sheraton, Radisson and Holiday Inn. The Hilton was
renovated at the end of 1996, according to its director of sales,
and the Ramada was converted from a Marriott two and a half years
ago, and is doing some work now, one floor at a time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The three most recent renovations, the Four Points, Radisson and
Holiday Inn, are full-service hotels that provide features for
business travelers, data ports and extra telephone lines, for
example, as well as meeting rooms, some quite large.
</P>
<P>
   They have restaurants and health facilities as well, and the
Holiday Inn has a glassed-in indoor pool, a hot tub and a sauna.
These hotels, nicely landscaped and surrounded by low-rise houses
and highways with grassy banks, seemed bucolic and welcoming after
the unplanned night I recently spent in a budget motel in the midst
of nothingness eight miles from the new Denver International
Airport. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Radisson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ``newest'' of the New York three is the Radisson, a 12-story
cream-colored building with light green trim. This hotel, once the
JFK Plaza, built in the 50s, had been shut for six years before
being taken over by the new owner, French Quarter III. Between
January and September it was gutted and redecorated, and in
mid-November, when I looked it over, the job was ending, with rooms
on the second floor getting finishing touches. A contractor's
``punch list'' of remaining small tasks was taped to a shelf in
each room; mattresses were still wrapped in plastic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the hotel was active. A meeting room on the main
floor was filled with students taking notes on how to become
notaries, and the 24-hour restaurant, called Charles, had laid out
a buffet and was well occupied.
</P>
<P>
   The buffet lunch was set up _ Charles normally has waiter-served
meals at lunch _ for 75 South African Airways passengers. Their
flight was canceled the evening before and they were given dinner,
a hotel night, breakfast and lunch while waiting for the next day's
flight. The hotel has 215 employees, a number affected by the
provision of 24-hour van and food services.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The lobby had a semiformal look _ a lot of glass, marble floors,
dark upholstery and patterned rugs. There were vases of real
flowers, and orchids planted in moss, some in need of pruning.
</P>
<P>
   The cocktail lounge leading to the restaurant was dim at 12:30
p.m. and two people were there reading papers. A couple in the
lobby were eating a deli lunch off a coffee table. Another couple,
knee-deep in shopping bags, were waiting to be picked up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The hotel has 386 rooms, half of them nonsmoking, 18 equipped
for wheelchairs. All have fire sprinklers. In the west wing, the
rooms all have king-sized beds. The larger rooms in the east wing
have two queen-sized beds. All the rooms have two telephone lines.
The bases of the lamps on the desk-tables have both power plugs and
telephone outlets for modems. A shelf pulls out to hold a
keyboard. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The business center is a modest room on the second floor with
two fax machines and a computer with Internet access. There is no
staff here, and the guest uses the service by inserting a credit
card into a device that puts a designated credit on an electronic
card called the Office, which in turn can be used to activate the
machines and pay the fees.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The fitness center is spacious and windowed, with five
treadmills, three step machines, two stationary bicycles and free
weights. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The hotel has a contract with American Airlines and American
Eagle to accommodate crew members, usually from red-eye flights,
said Richard Sarno, head of sales. They are housed on a hall where
quiet is maintained in the daytime: the vacuuming is done at other
times. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The introductory rate, in effect now, is $149 a night, which
works out to $170.74 with New York City's hotel tax of 13.25
percent plus $2 a night. The corporate rate is $169, or $193 with
taxes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Radisson Hotel JFK Airport, 135-30 140th Street, Jamaica, N.Y.
11434; (718) 322-2300, or (800) 333-3333. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Four Points by Sheraton  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This hotel has a spiffy European feel, with the bombe chests and
huge Baccarat vases in the lobby. The ``H.R.'' emblem in the glass
doors in the lobby stands for Hampshire Hotels and Resorts, the New
York company that owns the Four Points.
</P>
<P>
   The emblem of the brand, the four points of a compass, is inlaid
in the marble floor of the lobby. A white baby grand backs up to
the glass wall overlooking a garden and gazebo in the back; in the
early afternoon, the player piano was providing soothing music. The
flowers were fresh. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This hotel, as the Kennedy Inn, housed welfare clients from 1991
to '96, and then underwent a 20-month overhaul. It opened in the
fall with praise from Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who hailed it as the
first new hotel to open near the airport in 20 years and called it
luxurious. All 184 rooms on four floors are now in use. Smoking is
permitted in half of them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Its manager, Barry M. Shatoff, said that the hotel was popular
among business travelers from overseas and people closing
international real estate deals: the participants all fly in to
Kennedy, do their work near the airport and fly home without having
to cope with ground travel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 185 guest rooms and 15 suites have three telephones on two
lines, plus data ports. The desks are big and the rooms are light.
The fitness center is tiny, with two treadmills and two step
machines.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The hotel has a sleek-looking restaurant, Birchwoods, offering
what its menu describes as American food and wine. Sunday brunch
with cappuccino (all of it you can drink) is $15.50. Thanksgiving
dinner, buffet style, was $15.50.
</P>
<P>
   In good weather there is service in the garden, and musicians
play in the gazebo, according to Elie Pariente, the assistant
manager. When I was there, a party of 20 people was being served
lunch. The bar, Fitzgerald's Lounge, would not be out of place in
Manhattan: paneled-looking and well outfitted with glasses and
bottles.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel provides room service until 1 a.m., and the kitchen is
closed from 1 to 6 a.m. Snacks can be provided at all hours,
Pariente said. The airport shuttle operates 24 hours.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rate for a room with a double, king or queen bed, or two
double beds, is $179 a night, or $205 with taxes. A suite with a
living room is $275, or $313 with taxes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Four Points Hotel by Sheraton, 151-20 Baisley Boulevard,
Jamaica, N.Y. 11434; (718) 489-1000. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Holiday Inn  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A monthly calendar of events that includes an ad for weddings
and rehearsal dinners defines the Holiday Inn: it is a place
focused on social activities. Victor Vongs, the general manager,
said that one big goal of the $4 million rehabilitation, which took
15 months and was completed in March, was to have the place ``not
feel like an airport hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   Le Bistro lounge has been designed to let people mingle and help
themselves to the $9.95 lunch buffet. The motel's meeting and
function rooms are large, and the place can accommodate up to 650
people in a reception; 500 sitting theater style. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outside the glass walls of the restaurant is a Japanese garden.
The flowers in vases inside are silk.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vongs pointed to a big alcove off the lobby that he said was
formerly a car-rental counter. It is being converted to a business
center. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Holiday Inn sells stay-and-fly packages, allowing guests who
are taking trips to park their cars in the 360-place motel lot and
retrieve them a week or two later. The fitness club, with swimming
pool, sauna and hot tub as well as a large exercise room, attracts
many reunions and family groups, Vongs said. The motel also sells
memberships to nonguests.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The guest rooms have been redecorated, this time with brass
bedsteads. Smoking is permitted in 40 percent of the rooms. The
busy season is July to October, and prices are somewhat lower the
rest of the year. There are also family bed-and-breakfast packages
in the winter. A room with a king-sized bed is $139 to $179 a
night, or $159 to $205 with taxes. A junior suite starts at $210,
or $240 with taxes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Holiday Inn JFK Airport, 144-02 135th Avenue, Jamaica, N.Y.
11436; (718) 659-0200.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
