<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OIL AND NATURAL GAS LEAD DROP IN COMMODITY PRICES
</P>
<P>
   Commodity prices, led by a plunge in oil and natural gas,
dropped sharply, pushing one key index to the lowest since 1972.
The Goldman, Sachs index of 22 commodities fell 3.97 points, to
133.55, its lowest in 26 years.
</P>
<P>
   The persistent weakness of commodity prices continues to hobble
many emerging-market countries _ from Russia and Indonesia to
Mexico and Chile _ that depend on such exports for economic growth
and government financing.
</P>
<P>
   SHELL AND TEXACO END VENTURE TALKS
</P>
<P>
   Royal Dutch/Shell announced that it had broken off talks with
Texaco about combining their refining and marketing businesses in
Europe, because a joint venture would not produce the savings they
had sought. The breakdown in that negotiation came as a person
close to the merger talks between Exxon and Mobil said that the two
companies were still working to complete a deal, which could be
announced as early as Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   VOLVO TO LAY OFF 5,300 WORKERS
</P>
<P>
   Volvo, the Swedish maker of cars, buses, trucks and construction
equipment, said that it would lay off more than 7 percent of its
work force, or 5,300 workers, by the middle of next year as part of
plans to increase productivity and profits. The cuts will include
1,000 jobs in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   MORE SPARRING IN MICROSOFT TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   In a day of detailed cross-examination at Microsoft's antitrust
trial, Frederick Warren-Boulton, an economist, summed up the
government's case of how the company wields its market power. And
Microsoft attacked its portrayal as a monopolistic bully.
</P>
<P>
   EISNER FRIEND COMES TO LIVENT'S AID
</P>
<P>
   An investment firm run by a friend of Michael Eisner, the
chairman of Walt Disney, agreed to lend more than $23 million to
Livent, the Broadway theater company headed by Michael Ovitz. Ovitz
was forced out by his boss and former friend, Eisner, as president
of Disney in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   MET LIFE EXECUTIVES FACE WINDFALL
</P>
<P>
   As Metropolitan Life Insurance reorganizes so that it can issue
stock, the big winners are likely to be the company's executives.
The 12 million policyholders are to share a one-time payout of $14
billion. But the executives will be perpetually in line for stock
options, bonuses and higher salaries.
</P>
<P>
   CHAIRMAN OF UNIVERSAL IS OUSTED
</P>
<P>
   Casey Silver, the chairman of troubled Universal Pictures, was
ousted after the dismal box-office results of the studio's most
recent big-budget films, ``Meet Joe Black'' and ``Babe: Pig in the
City.'' Silver, a low-key and popular figure at the studio, will be
replaced by his boss, Ron Meyer, who is president and chief
operating officer of Universal.
</P>
<P>
   TWO SATELLITES ARE SOLD
</P>
<P>
   News Corp. said it had agreed to sell two satellites and their
orbital license to Echostar Communications for $840 million in
stock as it seeks to leave the U.S. direct-broadcast satellite
business.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERGY TO SELL BRITISH UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Entergy, the fourth-largest electric-power generator in the
United States, said it would sell its British electricity
distributor to the French national power company for $3.18 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
