<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROAMING AROUND MOBILE  
 ITALIAN POTTERY PAINTING  
 FINDING AIRLINE PARTNERS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 6) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By PAUL FREIREICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. We plan to be in the Mobile, Ala., area during January or
February in the areas of Dauphin Island and Gulf Shores. Can you
tell me about the weather, interesting places to see, special
gardens and the Mobile Mardi Gras? _ Elizabeth Barsky, Uniondale,
N.Y. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. To capture several highlights of the area in a single day,
you might make Bellingrath Gardens your first stop. Sixty-five
acres of the gardens _ which are in Theodore, about 20 miles south
of downtown Mobile _ are cultivated. In January, camellias,
snapdragons and pansies are out and by mid-February you may be able
to see as many as 50,000 tulips, daffodils and hyacinths in bloom.
</P>
<P>
   Admission is $7.50, $5.25 for children. For $13.95 ($9.95 for
children), one can also see the 15-room house completed in the
1930s for Walter Bellingrath, the first bottler of Coca-Cola in
Mobile, and his wife, Bessie.
</P>
<P>
   On display are collections of porcelain (including Meissen and
Sevres) and furniture. The gardens open at 8 a.m. daily and close
at dusk; the house opens at 9 a.m. Information: (800) 247-8420 or
(334) 973-2217. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can lunch at the gardens or en route to Dauphin Island, 15
miles away. Worth a stop on the island, which is on Mobile Bay, are
the Dauphin Island Sea Lab and Fort Gaines.
</P>
<P>
   The Sea Lab, at 101 Bienville Boulevard, is the home of the
Estuarium, where exhibits capture life in the main ecosystems of
the Mobile estuary system, from the swamps of the delta to the
reefs of the Gulf of Mexico. Open daily from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.
Monday through Saturday and 1 to 5 p.m. on Sunday. Summer hours are
longer. Admission: $6, $3 for children. Information: (334)
861-2141.
</P>
<P>
   During the Civil War, Fort Gaines, now a neighbor of the
Estuarium, and Fort Morgan played an important role in defending
Mobile Bay. Undeterred by the forts and by mines, known as
torpedoes, Adm. David Farragut of the Union forces declared in
1864: ``Damn the torpedoes! Full speed ahead!'' The forts fell
shortly thereafter. Today the forts are a 45-minute ferry ride
apart; the fare is $1 and $15 for a car, including passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Gaines is open 9 to 5 daily. Information: (334) 861-6992.
Fort Morgan, in Gulf Shores, is more extensive and one should allow
two hours to see it. Hours: 8 to 5 for the fort, 9 to 5 for the
museum. Information: (334) 540-7125. At both forts, admission is
$3, $1 for children.
</P>
<P>
   The places listed here are more than a day's worth. And if you
want to get to Fort Morgan and Gulf Shores, remember that the ferry
runs only every 90 minutes. Ferry information: (334) 540-7787. The
big drawing cards in Gulf Shores, which is 22 miles from Fort
Morgan, are golf (there are 13 championship courses) and beaches on
the Gulf of Mexico. Information: (800) 982-8562.
</P>
<P>
   No scheduled tours cover the sites mentioned, but you make be
able to arrange something with Gray Line of Mobile, (334) 432-2229,
or Memorable Mobile Tours, (334) 344-8687. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for Mobile's Mardi Gras, it will run from Feb. 3 to 16, with
a total of 20 parades plus other events. Temperatures then should
be between 46 and 60; in January, the average is 44 to 58.
Precipitation is typically 4.7 inches in January (vs. New York's
3.4) and 5.4 in February (vs. 3.2). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I would like to go to Italy next spring to learn pottery
painting. How can I find schools that offer weeklong courses in
English? _ Vivian Wachsberger, New York, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. The pickings are slim. In the area you mention, only the
Centro Internazionale Jacopone gives a course in what is known as
decoration pottery. Depending on student preference, classes are
held in Deruta, the celebrated center of pottery making, or in
Todi, a 15- to 20-minute drive away. Instruction is in Italian, but
an interpreter is provided free.
</P>
<P>
   The program, which includes classes Monday to Friday and full
board in a three-star hotel, costs $115 a day in January, February,
March, November and December and $124 a day in April, May, June,
July, September and October. (The cost is calculated at 1,691 lire
to the dollar.) A minimum stay of seven days is required.
</P>
<P>
   If participants prefer Deruta, sessions run four hours after
which they are driven back to Todi. (Transportation by private car
is $24 a day.) If the choice is Todi, classes run six hours. On
Saturday, there is an educational excursion. Among the
possibilities are a cultural and historical look at Todi; Todi and
its castles; along the ancient Flaminian Way; and the wine country,
which includes Orvieto, Montefalcone, Deruta and Torigiano.
</P>
<P>
   Reservations must be made at least a month in advance, at which
time a 50 percent payment is required. Transfers from and to the
Rome airport for non-Italian students are also covered. The center
is at 46 Vocabolo Castello, 06050 Collevalenza, Todi, Italy;
telephone and fax (39-75) 887445.
</P>
<P>
   For a broader sense of the courses given in Italy, there are
hundreds of brochures available at the Istituto Italiano di
Cultura, 686 Park Avenue (between 68th and 69th Streets), New York,
N.Y. 10021; (212) 879-4242. It is open Monday to Friday, 9 a.m. to
4:30 p.m. The institute's Web site, www.italcultny.org, is also a
useful resource. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Would you help me find foreign airlines that are partners
with domestic airlines for frequent flier mileage? I am deaf and
must go through the Virginia Relay (which links deaf and hearing
people) and try to explain what I want, which can be quite a
hassle. _ Dorothy W. Blackburn, Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   A. Those unfamiliar with how deaf people communicate by
telephone with people who can hear may not be aware that the
process can be quite cumbersome. It is somewhat like a conversation
between two people who do not have a language in common. In this
case, a relay operator, who is sort of a translator, transcribes
what an airline representative says. Those remarks then appear at
the deaf person's end either in typewritten form or on a computer
screen. Thus, a conversation can end up taking much longer than it
otherwise would.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, what you're looking for is available from Inside
Flyer magazine electronically and in print. On the Web, where
access is free, the address is www.webflyer.com. Or for $14.99 plus
$3 for shipping and handling, you can get a copy of the new
Official Frequent Flyer Guidebook, which is to be shipped next
month, from Inside Flyer, 4715-C Town Center Drive, Colorado
Springs, Colo. 80916; (800) 767-8896 or (719) 597-8889, fax (719)
597-6855.
</P>
</TEXT>
