</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESPY-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOSING ARGUMENTS PRESENTED IN CASE OF FORMER CABINET SECRETARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Mike Espy, a former congressman and agriculture
secretary once thought to be a rising political star, spent his
45th birthday Monday in a federal courthouse hearing himself
denounced by prosecutors as a corrupt official and praised by
defense lawyers as a dedicated public servant.
</P>
<P>
   In closing arguments before the case went to the jury, Donald
Smaltz, an independent counsel, sought to portray Espy as
thoroughly insensitive to ethics laws and regulations, someone who
eagerly accepted gifts from companies and lobbyists who had
business before the Department of Agriculture. Espy led the
department in President Clinton's first term until he was forced to
resign in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing two months of testimony, Smaltz told the jury that
Espy was especially fond of major sporting events and thought
nothing of seeking hard-to-get tickets for professional football
and basketball games and tennis matches from companies that had
vital business with the department.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Wells, Espy's attorney, told the jury that Espy had
committed no crimes and that the items he received were gifts from
friends. Such gifts are explicitly allowed under federal law. Wells
said the prosecution did not and could not present any evidence
that Espy made any decisions based on gifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came to work in the morning and he treated everyone
fairly,'' Wells said. ``And he made his decisions on the merits.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells sought to portray Smaltz and the staff of the independent
counsel as a gang of bullies who sought to concoct a case out of
small matters. In fact, much of the trial has dealt with the wisdom
and effectiveness of the law that allows for the appointment of
independent counsels to investigate accusations of wrongdoing by
senior administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   Smaltz's four-year $17 million investigation of Espy's conduct
has been hotly debated by opponents and supporters of the law,
which expires in June but can be renewed. The Espy investigation
has received a level of scrutiny second only to that given the
investigation of Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel who has
reported to Congress that the president may have committed
impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Espy is charged with taking about $35,000 in illegal gifts,
lying about it and trying to get a friend to cover for him. Last
week a federal judge dismissed eight of the 39 counts against him
and part of a ninth. If convicted on the most serious charges,
violating the federal meat inspection law, Espy faces a minimum of
three years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Smaltz's summation was halting and uneven; he jumped around
among many of the 30 remaining counts in the indictment. The
complexity of the case made it difficult to follow which contractor
had offered Espy tickets to which sporting event and which law
might have been broken.
</P>
<P>
   As Smaltz spoke, Espy glanced at a Bible in his lap.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of race has been near the surface from the beginning
of the trial. Espy's lawyers sought to press the idea that he
attached little importance to such secondary matters as game
tickets because he was preoccupied with running the Agriculture
Department. The job was made especially difficult, the lawyers
argued, because his staff resisted new ideas presented by the first
African-American agriculture secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Facing the jury of 10 blacks and two whites, Smaltz, who is
white, implored them to decide the case ``on facts, not politics or
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells, who practices in New Jersey, offered a passionate
oration, adopting a down-home flavor by sprinkling his argument
with ``y'all'' and dropping his `g's' at the ends of words.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case has been a bunch of garbage,'' said Wells, who is
black. ``Just garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells disputed each of the charges, saying, for example, that
when a lobbyist gave Espy $4,400 worth of tickets to the U.S. Open
Tennis Tournament, Espy was told the tickets were free.
</P>
<P>
   When another lobbyist paid $3,200 to Espy's girlfriend so she
could accompany him to Greece, Wells said, the money represented
the winnings of a bet between the girlfriend and the lobbyist.
Espy, he said, had no knowledge of the money paid to the
girlfriend. And when a lobbyist gave Espy a set of new luggage,
Wells said, it was because Espy had come to an event with a
broken-down duffel bag. In none of those instances, Wells said, did
Espy know that the lobbyists had billed the expenses to their
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Many commentators have said that the conduct Espy is accused of
demonstrates that when he became a Cabinet officer in 1993 after
serving six years in the House, he brought with him a notion of
ethical behavior more typical of Congress: that it is customary if
not acceptable to trade a few favors.
</P>
<P>
   That view was reinforced during the trial when Carol Browner,
the head of the Environmental Protection Agency, testified about a
conversation she had with Espy early in the Clinton presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Browner said Espy told her he thought the stringent ethics
code of the executive branch was ``a bunch of junk'' and that he
would continue to behave as he had done in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Espy did not take the stand. In fact, the defense put on no
witnesses. The prosecution presented 70 witnesses over two months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
