<HEADLINE>
NEWS FROM LANA MARKS  
 THE PRINCESS PLAID  
 `THOMAS CROWN COUP' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Colo., Nev., Texas, Ill., Mass., Calif.)  (af) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lana Marks is building a small empire based on her
sumptuous handbags cast in glossy reptile skins or bright, smooth
leathers.
</P>
<P>
   This week she will introduce ready-to-wear and shoe collections
in her two stores, one at 645 Madison Ave. (60th Street) in New
York and the other in Palm Beach, Fla., where she has her offices.
</P>
<P>
   By next year, six new Lana Marks stores will be opened. A
boutique at 211 South Galena Street in Aspen, Colo., is scheduled
to open in mid-December; in January, Ms. Marks plans to open a
store on Rodeo Drive in Beverly Hills, and later in the year, two
stores in Las Vegas, one in Houston and one in Bal Harbour, Fla.
All will carry the ready-to-wear collection except one of the Las
Vegas stores.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Marks' handbags are sold in stores like Saks Fifth Avenue,
but for fall and spring the clothing and shoes will be sold only in
her stores. She will offer them at wholesale beginning with the
fall 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The department stores can give us only 100 or 200 square
feet,'' Ms. Marks said. ``In our own store we can do 2,000 square
feet and present the entire line.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoes and handbags are enjoying a run of popularity in fashion,
and price seems to be of little concern. Ms. Marks' bags are priced
from about $800 to $12,000. ``People want style and fashion,'' she
said, ``but they want beautifully made handbags.''
</P>
<P>
   In the shoe collection, a simple sandal will cost around $400,
but most high-heel pumps and moccasins will be priced at $1,000 to
$2,000. Like her handbags, the shoes will emphasize exotic skins
like ostrich.
</P>
<P>
   In the ready-to-wear collection, ``I'm keeping the prices below
$2,000,'' Ms. Marks said without a trace of irony. Asked if that
was an attractive price for most customers, she said, ``For what
I'm doing, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, her fur-trimmed suits and cocktail dresses will not
be for everyone but for the kind of woman who still wears a suit on
an airplane. Ms. Marks has done well selling exclusivity. ``They're
to wear to lunches, to wear traveling,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Burberrys is selling a special tartan created to memorialize
Diana, Princess of Wales.
</P>
<P>
   The tartan may seem a little less cynical than some of the many
Diana promotions, since the royal family, including the Princess,
Prince Charles and Queen Elizabeth have all worn the traditional
Burberry plaid on several occasions.
</P>
<P>
   The Diana tartan, a blend of pale blue with navy, black and red
stripes, will be in Burberrys stores starting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern, created by LochCarron, a tartan manufacturer based
in Scotland, will be sold in the United States only through
Burberrys.
</P>
<P>
   Prices range from $95 for a mohair stole to $195 for a muffler
to $325 for a cashmere throw. They will be available at Burberrys
stores in New York, Chicago, Boston, Washington, San Francisco and
Honolulu.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the sales will go to the Diana, Princess of Wales
Memorial Fund, a spokeswoman for Burberrys said, though she would
not specify how great a portion.
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Turnbull &AMP; Asser, the venerable men's clothier, will supply
Pierce Brosnan's shirts and ties in the remake of ``The Thomas
Crown Affair.'' And Michael Kors is dressing Rene Russo in Celine
and his own collection.
</P>
<P>
   It's quite a coup for them both. The original movie, starring
Steve McQueen and Faye Dunaway, is one of the most stylish films of
all time, highly rated by designers and stylists.
</P>
<P>
   John Bartlett did two collections recently, one under his own
name and one for Byblos, which he said were inspired by the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Turnbull &AMP; Asser will have a difficult job ahead of it to
compete with McQueen's suave but tough turtlenecks, and smartly
tailored suits and sports jackets, not to mention Ms. Dunaway's
over-the-moon high-fashion insurance investigator.
</P>
</TEXT>
