<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTERIAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Medtronic Buys Arterial for $3.7 Billion  &HT;       
 By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Arterial Vascular Engineering of Santa Rosa said yesterday it has
agreed to be acquired by medical technology giant Medtronic Inc. in
a stock swap valued at $3.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would give Medtronic of Minneapolis, already a leader
in the pacemaker market, AVE's technology for using angioplasty and
stents to treat heart disease without open heart surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Angioplasty is the process of reaming out the plaque that can
restrict blood flow to the heart. Stents are wire-mesh tubes that
are inserted into arteries after angioplasty to keep the blood
vessels from collapsing, as they often do if doctors perform
angioplasty alone.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Kurt Kruger follows the $2 billion worldwide stent
market for NationsBanc Montgomery Securities. He said yesterday's
merger _ Medtronic's fifth acquisition since July _ gives it a
stent product line to rival its two top competitors, Guidant Corp.
of Indianapolis and Boston Scientific.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medtronic had a strong business in the electrical side of
heart treatments with its pacemakers,'' Kruger said. ``But without
AVE, it had a very weak offering in the stent market.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanjiv Arora, who follows the medical devices market for Dain
Rauscher Wessels in Minneapolis, said the deal also made sense for
AVE, which has a 36 percent share of the stent market.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this leading position, Arora said AVE would have had a
harder time as a stand-alone company in the future, competing with
Guidant and Boston Scientific, which have 29 and 22 percent
respectively, of the stent market.
</P>
<P>
   AVE specializes in stents, while its main competitors had
broader product lines. ``The market is starting to move to bundling
of a wide range of products to hospitals,'' Arora said. ``Medtronic
needed stents as part of its mix, and AVE needed the devices
Medtronic sells.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim McCamant, editor of the Medical Technology Stock Letter in
Berkeley, said the deal's $54 per share price tag represented a
``substantial premium'' for AVE, which had been trading in the
mid-30s before the deal was announced.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Assuming the merger receives shareholder and regulatory
approval, it will end a bold solo run by AVE, which was founded in
1991 by medical engineer Brad Jendersee and accountant John Miller.
AVE introduced its first stent in 1994, challenging market pioneer
Johnson &AMP; Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   AVE went public in 1996 at $21 a share and became a hit in
hospitals as well as on Wall Street. In fiscal 1998, it earned
$115.1 million on sales of $387.6 million. It employs about 4,000
people worldwide. About 2,000 work at a new campus in Santa Rosa,
making AVE one of the city's largest employers.
</P>
<P>
   Medtronic chief executive William George said yesterday he
expects only minimal layoffs as a result of merging the two
companies' sales forces. Overall, he expects to add employees in
Santa Rosa as the stent business expands. AVE chief executive Scott
Solano, who used to be a vice president at Medtronic, will run the
stent businesses of the combined companies.
</P>
<P>
   AVE's shares skyrocketed $16.50 yesterday to close at $48.88.
Medtronic lost $2.28 to end the day at $67.63.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, AVE shareholders will get $54 worth
of Medtronic stock for every AVE share they own _ provided
Medtronic stays between $61.20 and $74.80. If Medtronic stock falls
below this range, AVE shareholders would get .88 shares of
Medtronic for every AVE share.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, if Medtronic rises above this range, AVE
shareholders will get .722 shares of Medtronic for each of their
AVE shares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
