<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Will Chevron Join the Other Oil Giants in the Mating Dance?  &HT;       
 By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Will Chevron be a buyer or a seller?
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, it will be one or the other. Because if the second-tier
energy titan were to attempt to go it alone, it would probably take
itself out of the game. The current slide in crude oil prices has
been so relentless that it is forcing the oil industry to slash
costs by combining operations, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   New and more efficient energy exploration technologies and the
flawed policies of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries have caused a massive glut, sending oil prices into a
downward spiral. And while some eternal optimists were hoping that
crude might actually rise to hit $18 a barrel this year (no, I
don't know what they were smoking), the price has plummeted to its
current trough of $11.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, supply is exceeding demand, and the competitive landscape
of big oil is undergoing rapid change. However, so far, San
Francisco's Chevron appears unwilling to attend the industrywide
mating dance while its biggest competitors have already agreed to
go home with each other.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by Exxon's plans to marry Mobil _ the second proposed
merger of this sector behind British Petroleum's acquisition of
Amoco _ Chevron shares soared about $5 on Friday to close at
$85.625. Yesterday, Chevron shares slipped $2 on a dour day for the
Dow, closing at $83.625.
</P>
<P>
   For stockpickers, Chevron's fate is tough to call. Yet for those
investors who are willing to bet that the Northern California oil
giant is ripe for a takeover, the spoils could be huge.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the good fortune of Mobil shareholders, who have seen
their holdings rise 39 percent from the company's low in August.
Meantime, Amoco shares have risen as much as 52 percent from their
52-week low in July.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, being acquired might just provide Chevron with its
best chance of succeeding in the new world order of ``super-major''
oil corporations. The reason: If it acquires smaller companies, it
would still be too small to compete with the big guys.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, senior analyst Fadel Gheit of Fahnestock &AMP; Co. in
New York thinks that the behemoths which have already announced
deals aren't done with their holiday shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the dust settles with these two mergers (led by BP and
Exxon), we'll see yet another one,'' Gheit says.
</P>
<P>
   Consolidation in the energy patch has just begun, he says, and
don't be surprised if British Petroleum and Exxon go out and buy
more companies _ providing, of course, that Uncle Sam gives its
blessings to pending deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exxon isn't done. They do not see (their proposed merger with
Mobil) as the end game,'' Gheit says.
</P>
<P>
   So, who's left?
</P>
<P>
   Texaco and Arco are the next largest U.S. oil companies behind
Chevron that are likely to get devoured by the new breed of
super-majors, Gheit says. (Talks to combine certain European
operations between Royal Dutch/Shell and Texaco broke down
yesterday.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Arco, probably, in a few months will be the next to go,'' he
says. And Chevron?
</P>
<P>
   ``Likely, we are going to see Chevron go to the British
Petroleum (Amoco) camp,'' Gheit suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Chevron could join forces with Texaco or Arco, but a
merger with either second-tier company would not give Chevron
enough bulk to keep pace with BP-Amoco or Exxon-Mobil, Gheit says.
</P>
<P>
   However, a Chevron-Texaco combination would make a nice fit, he
acknowledges, because the two companies are already joint-venture
partners in an exploration company.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the worst course of action for Chevron would be to
take no action at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Arco, Chevron and Texaco prefer to remain independent,
that's fine,'' Gheit says.
</P>
<P>
   ``(But) their stocks will get hammered.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(at sign)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 2204EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981130.0493 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5774 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SFCHRON &LR;      11-30 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Clinton Outlines Internet Growth Strategy  &HT;       
 By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
President Clinton yesterday announced steps to accelerate growth of
the Internet and electronic commerce as vital cogs of the global
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must give consumers the same protection in our virtual mall
they now get at the shopping mall,'' Clinton said at a White House
press conference touting an administration report on Net issues.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The long-awaited paper supports staunch consumer protection,
faster Net connections and privacy rights _ but through
self-policing by industries rather than government-mandated laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Self-regulation in the digital age will require the private
sector to engage in much greater collective action to set and
enforce rules than was characteristic of the Industrial Age,'' the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, Clinton and Vice President Al Gore will direct
the Commerce Department to work with the Federal Communications
Commission to design incentives for private companies to build
high-speed &UR;  &LR; Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   The White House also will direct the Small Business
Administration to help U.S. companies connect to the Web and press
the World Bank and private companies to fund Internet projects in
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clinton called for a crackdown on Internet fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about privacy and fraud have kept millions of customers
from shopping online, and the United States must do more ``to
develop new approaches to protect privacy in cyberspace,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Despite some consumer reticence, the number of online users
worldwide has more than doubled to 140 million in the last 18
months, and technology companies account for a third of the
nation's annual economic growth, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers estimate that Internet-related sales could
surge to $1.5 trillion in 2003 from $10 billion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to keep this momentum going,'' Clinton told a group of
lawmakers and industry executives, including officials from eBay
and Cisco Systems. ``I think the Internet has an enormous role to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Faster Internet connections are considered key to the success of
e-commerce. About 40 percent of U.S. homes with computers will use
the Internet to do part or all of their holiday shopping, up from
10 percent last year, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, ``for many consumers and businesses, the World Wide Web has
become the World Wide Wait,'' said a White House statement. ``The
information superhighway becomes a dirt path before it reaches
America's homes.''
</P>
<P>
   The one-hour White House event amounted to a ``going away''
party for presidential Internet adviser Ira Magaziner, said one
attendee. Magaziner _ who crafted the Internet white paper as well
as the administration's ill-fated health-care reform plan _ is
scheduled to leave his position in January.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, a champion of the administration's high-tech measures,
will oversee future White House Internet programs.
</P>
<P>
   The &UR;  &LR; government document is sketchy on details, prompting the
White House to ask various agencies to develop specific plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The electronic commerce initiative is a work in progress,''
said Jerry Berman, executive director for the Center for Democracy
and Technology in Washington, D.C. ``Ira did a terrific job putting
it together, and judging by the turnout, he has done a good job of
publicizing its importance.''
</P>
<P>
   Some consumer groups, meanwhile, contend that industry
self-regulation does not work and laws are necessary to safeguard
consumer interests and personal data in the fast-paced Internet
market. Without legislation, they warn, the United States will open
itself to a trade war with Europe, where self-regulation has been
declared incompatible with laws guaranteeing strong privacy
protections for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Others accused the government of ``punting'' on the
controversial topic of encryption, which imposes strict export
controls on data-scrambling technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``By ignoring it, the administration leaves future e-commerce in
limbo,'' said Stanton McCandlish, program director at the
Electronic Frontier Foundation in San Francisco. ``You can't
advance technology into the 21st century with Cold War policies
still in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Magaziner's report comes on the heels of a raft of
Internet-friendly legislation in the United States over the past 18
months.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Congress passed and Clinton signed into law a
three-year ban on new Internet taxes and extended copyright
protections to cyberspace. Internationally, the administration
persuaded the World Trade Organization to adopt a one-year ban on
tariffs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Magaziner brokered an agreement with a new
nonprofit organization, the Internet Corporation for Assigned Names
and Numbers, that will oversee the handling of Web addresses such
as .com, .net and .gov. Previously, the government contracted with
Network Solutions, a private Herndon, Va., company, to dispense
domain names.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
