<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 IRS Likely Won't Treat Day Trading As Business  &HT;       
 By Arthur M. Louis  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  Can I get any deductions or write-offs to offset my
capital-gains tax from stock trades? If I have a $1,000 gain on a
stock and paid a total of $100 in commissions to buy and sell it,
can the $100 be deducted from the gain? Also, are day traders
allowed to deduct the costs of home-office space, computers and
telephones from their income?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  The good news is that yes, you can reduce your taxable
capital gains by the amount you pay in commissions.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that you probably can't persuade the Internal
Revenue Service to let you deduct office space and the rest. You
might want to try something easier, like playing hoops one-on-one
against Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   To claim an office deduction, you must surmount two major
hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   First, you must prove that stock trading is your business.
</P>
<P>
   Second, you must demonstrate that your office space, telephone
and computer are used exclusively for that business. If your kid
and his friends occasionally wander into the room to play Riven on
your PC, that could blow it for you.
</P>
<P>
   But don't worry too much about your kid and his friends, because
you probably won't get past the first hurdle. Hardly anyone does.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that there is no law or regulation establishing
the parameters. It is up to the IRS to decide whether trading is
your business. Even if you trade all day, every day and generate
enormous volume, the IRS may rule that you are an addicted
hobbyist, not a businessman, and therefore don't qualify for
special tax treatment.
</P>
<P>
   IRS spokesman Jesse Weller says it might help if you can
demonstrate that trading is your only occupation, that you have
received professional training to operate a trading business and
that your trading has been profitable in at least three of the past
five years.
</P>
<P>
   Day Care Dilemma
</P>
<P>
   Q: I need to decide between putting money in a day care
reimbursement program offered by my employer or using the federal
child care tax credit. I have two children, and if I choose my
employer's program I would set aside $4,000 per year in tax-exempt
dollars to be spent on day care. Which program makes more sense?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: The child care tax credit is ``mainly intended for
low-income wage earners,'' notes Ali Farhat, an accountant with
PricewaterhouseCoopers in San Francisco. It has little if any value
for people in the middle and upper income brackets.
</P>
<P>
   The credit is subtracted directly from your federal taxes, but
not your state taxes. Depending on your income, you can claim a
credit ranging from 20 percent to 30 percent of your child care
expenses _ up to an expense limit of $2,400 for one child and
$4,800 for two or more children.
</P>
<P>
   If your adjusted gross income is less than $10,000, you can
deduct 30 percent. The deduction phases down by one percentage
point for every additional $2,000 of income. If your income is
greater than $28,000, you can claim only a 20 percent credit.
</P>
<P>
   With the day care reimbursement program, federal regulations let
you put up to $5,000 per year into an escrow account and withdraw
the money as you need it to pay for the care. The money you place
in the account is exempt from federal and state taxes. However, any
money you set aside and don't use will be forfeited, so take care
in estimating your day care needs.
</P>
<P>
   Some simple math will help you decide whether the child care tax
credit or the day care reimbursement program works best for you.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say that you and your spouse file a joint tax return and
that your taxable income totals $45,000. Your maximum child care
tax credit for the two kids would be $960 _ 20 percent of $4,800.
Your federal taxes would be reduced by that amount.
</P>
<P>
   Next, calculate the federal and state tax savings you will get
by setting aside $4,000 tax-exempt dollars in a day care
reimbursement program.
</P>
<P>
   Someone in your bracket would be effectively taxed at a combined
32.3 percent federal/ state rate _ allowing for the fact that state
taxes are deductible from federal income. Multiply $4,000 by 0.323
and you get $1,292 _ your tax saving from the day care
reimbursement program. That beats the child care tax credit by a
cool $332.
</P>
<P>
   People in lower tax brackets might find that the child care
credit is better. Everyone should do the math before choosing.
</P>
<P>
   A cautionary note: Before this year, taxpayers could lose all or
part of their child care credit if they were subject to the
alternative minimum tax. Just before adjournment, Congress
eliminated that rule for the 1998 tax year only. In the next
session, it will consider eliminating it permanently.
</P>
<P>
   Name Change
</P>
<P>
   Q: If I add my wife's name to my brokerage account as a joint
owner, does this create a tax event for either of us?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: No. Merely adding a name to an account does not produce a
tax liability. You won't have to pay a gift tax, and she won't have
to pay income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   However, if your wife withdraws more than $10,000 from the
account in a single year, you will have to file a federal gift-tax
report. Even so, you won't have to actually pay the tax if she is a
U.S. citizen. Any gifts you give a citizen spouse, no matter how
large, are tax-exempt. The tax filing is a bureaucratic formality.
</P>
<P>
   If your wife is not a U.S. citizen, you might have to pay a gift
tax, says IRS spokesman Larry Wright. If your noncitizen wife
withdraws more than $100,000 in a single year, the excess is
subtracted from a $625,000 lifetime exclusion. Once that $625,000
exclusion is used up, you will have to pay gift tax on any further
withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you put her name on your account today and she withdraws
$900,000 before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The first $100,000 doesn't create a tax liability, but the
remaining $800,000 does. You have to pay gift tax for the year on
$175,000 ($800,000 minus $625,000). Any further withdrawals in
later years will be fully taxable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to moneybag(at
sign)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
