<SLUG> BC-BOFA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 New BofA Confronts Critics at State Hearing  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The new BankAmerica Corp. faced a parade of critics at a San
Francisco public hearing yesterday who warned the bank to keep its
promises to California communities.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Louis Papan described the meeting of his California
Assembly Banking and Finance Committee as an ``informational''
investigation to determine whether North Carolina's NationsBank
Corp. is following through on its commitments to be a good
corporate citizen two months after buying San Francisco's
BankAmerica and taking its name.
</P>
<P>
   But, with San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown and more than a dozen
other witnesses attacking the new BofA's brief record in the state,
the hearing seemed more an exercise to serve notice on the bank:
Increase your investments in California communities or face the
wrath of activists and political leaders in your biggest market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were concerned this group of strangers would do violence''
to the community programs of the old BofA, Brown said. Now ''we are
more than concerned _ we are becoming alarmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Other witnesses were pointed about what could happen if the new
BofA cuts the flow of funds to California communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we get answers,'' it might be ``time for communities to
be rethinking their investments in BofA,'' said San Francisco
Supervisor Michael Yaki.
</P>
<P>
   Papan described the deposit and contract business of state and
local governments as ``the biggest ax we've got.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brown was skeptical of such moves. ``I don't know of
anything the city can or should do except have its voice heard,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In their statements, BofA officials were quick to take up the
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``In community development lending, no institution even comes
close to the new Bank of America,'' declared Eugene Taylor, the
NationsBank executive tapped to run the western region of the
combined bank.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor noted that the bank promised to earmark $350 million
nationwide for purposes such as affordable housing and economic
development. And he said the bank would raise its charitable giving
in California from about $11 million this year to $18 million next
year, if its income grows according to plan.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing took place against a backdrop of bad blood between
the new bank and the California activist groups that pressure
financial institutions to put money into low-income and minority
communities.
</P>
<P>
   The old BofA was widely regarded as a leader in community
investment. In 1997, following extensive talks with activists, it
set aside $140 billion for local development initiatives over 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   After NationsBank agreed to buy BofA, community groups were
angered when the North Carolina bank refused to commit to specific
California lending goals or negotiate community investment plans
like those signed by Wells Fargo and Washington Mutual.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lack of a specific commitment to California is a very
negative sign,'' said Alan Fisher, executive director of the
California Reinvestment Committee, a coalition of 190 nonprofit
groups and public agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Relations deteriorated further after the new bank booted out
former BofA Chairman and chief executive David Coulter and top
community development officials of the old BofA, putting its own
people in key jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave Coulter's recent departure has lead to concerns that the
new BankAmerica will not honor its other commitments,'' Papan said
in a release.
</P>
<P>
   Heated exchanges at the hearing reflected those tensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's talk about Mr. Taylor's role,'' said Robert Gnaizda, an
official of San Francisco's Greenlining Institute, about BofA's
senior representative at the meeting. ``He was there at the time
they decimated Barnett Bank,'' he said about Taylor's role
absorbing the Florida bank.
</P>
<P>
   Shot Taylor in response to other Gnaizda barbs: ``I can't argue
with a man who has his facts wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 2206EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
