<DOCNO> NYT19981130.0498 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5780 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-10-10-321-SFCHRON &LR;      11-30 1626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-10-10-321-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Get the 411 on 10-10 Calls  &HT;       
 By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The pitches sound so seductive _ win $1 million by dialing
10-10-345, save 50 percent over your regular long-distance carrier
with 10-10-321, call anywhere in the state for 5 cents a minute
using 10-10-811.
</P>
<P>
   But behind the talking dogs and celebrity hucksters peddling
those great deals is a lot of fine print.
</P>
<P>
   Read it and you'll see that the 10-10 phone numbers hawked by
Tony Danza, John Lithgow and Sugar Ray Leonard can actually make
your phone bills go up, not down.
</P>
<P>
   That's because many of these so-called dial-around services have
hidden surcharges, monthly fees and minimum talk times. And many of
the 10-10 numbers compare their rates to the highest rates around,
which most people don't pay.
</P>
<P>
   Many people who use dial-around numbers wind up paying higher
rates than if they had used a discount plan offered by their
regular long-distance carrier.
</P>
<P>
   The concealed costs have surprised many consumers, who expected
to see huge savings on their long-distance bills. Federal and state
regulators say the number of people filing complaints about 10-10
numbers is on the rise and caution consumers not to choose a
long-distance phone company based on glitzy ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some customers out there who dialed 10-10 and got
more than they bargained for,'' said Linda Woods, manager of the
California Public Utilities Commission's consumer affairs branch.
Woods said the CPUC has gotten complaints, mostly from people who
didn't read the fine print before placing a call.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to be misled by the ads, Woods said, because they make
long-distance calls sound so cheap.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Cable &AMP; Wireless says consumers can save big by
paying only 9 cents a minute with 10-10-566. What the company
doesn't tout is the $4.95 monthly fee consumers pay for using the
service _ even if they only make one call.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar Ray Leonard says the DimeLine is a knockout at 10 cents
per minute. But the dial-around has a three-minute minimum, so even
a one-minute call costs 30 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission and the Federal Trade
Commission are both conducting informal investigations into whether
the ads are false or misleading, according to the FCC and a New
York state legislator involved in the issue.
</P>
<P>
   If the regulators find the ads are misleading, they could fine
the companies or order them to change the wording.
</P>
<P>
   There are some cases where 10-10 numbers are a better deal, but
it's not easy to say when.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some dial-arounds out there that offer very
competitive rates, and some don't have hidden fees and talking
minimums,'' said Becky Sachs, a spokeswoman for the
Telecommunications Research and Action Center in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs said Excel's 10-10-297 is one of the better ones because
it has no minimum talk time. Excel charges between 9 cents and 15
cents per minute.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the controversy surrounding dial-arounds, they have
proven extremely popular among the telephoning public. There are
almost a dozen 10-10 numbers out there, and industry watchers say
the dial-around market will be worth $3 billion next year.
</P>
<P>
   Growth of Services
</P>
<P>
   The concept isn't new. The first dial-arounds appeared more than
15 years ago, when consumers who wanted a company other than AT&AMP;T
for their long-distance service had to dial a code to reach another
provider. The past few years have seen an explosion in 10-10
numbers, as consumers have gotten used to competition and become
more price conscious about phone service, according to industry
watchers.
</P>
<P>
   Even having to dial two extra digits hasn't curbed the public's
appetite for dial-arounds. Earlier this year, the FCC began
requiring the companies to add an extra 10 to their codes _ 10-321,
for example, became 10-10-321 _ in order to make sure there are
enough dial-around numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates say one reason the services are so popular is
because people don't realize the rates are high. The ads make the
10-10 numbers sound like great discounts, and many people never
check their phone bill to see how much they were actually charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ads really border on being deceptive,'' said Ken
McEldowney, executive director of Consumer Action in San Francisco.
``The truth is, people could probably get a better deal with their
standard service than with a dial-around.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry calls these services dial-arounds because a
customer dials a special access code, which routes the call around
their long-distance carrier and onto a different phone network. The
name of the dial-around company and the charges are included on the
customer's next phone bill.
</P>
<P>
   Big Names Behind the 10-10s
</P>
<P>
   What's confusing about the dial-arounds, say regulators, is
determining the companies behind them. Most dial-arounds are
actually controlled by the big phone giants.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky Dog, or 10-10-345, for example, is an AT&AMP;T subsidiary, but
even consumers who scour the fine print of a Lucky Dog ad won't see
that. Two of the most popular dial-arounds, 10-10-321 and
10-10-220, are controlled by a company called Telecom USA, a
subsidiary of MCI WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, customers who dial a 10-10 number unwittingly use
their own long-distance carrier _ and pay higher rates to boot.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-10 companies say they cloak their parent companies
because consumers identify with a brand more than the company
behind it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You identify with Skippy or Jif, rather than Procter &AMP; Gamble.
And you identify with Old Navy, but you don't necessarily know
that's the Gap,'' Siegel said. ``We wanted to have something that
would distinguish us.''
</P>
<P>
   The main targets for dial-arounds, according to MCI WorldCom,
are customers who aren't on a calling plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between 10 percent to 40 percent of customers out there are
not on a calling plan,'' said Brad Burns, a spokesman for MCI
WorldCom. ``Either they thought they were on a calling plan or they
just weren't motivated enough to do it. We're looking for a way to
tap into those consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the major long-distance companies offer discount calling
plans to customers who make a lot of long-distance calls. AT&AMP;T, for
example, offers rates of 5 cents and 10 cents per minute for
long-distance calls. And Sprint just recently began offering
unlimited long-distance calls on weekends for just $25 a month.
Some of these plans also have monthly fees.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; A Matter of Timing
</P>
<P>
   Sachs of TRAC said those plans guarantee customers certain rates
at certain times, regardless of the length of the call. With
dial-around numbers, the per-minute rate may depend on the length
of each call.
</P>
<P>
   ``10-10-321 is one of the more misleading ones in that it has a
20-minute talking minimum in order for a customer to get the
discounts that are advertised,'' Sachs said.
</P>
<P>
   If a customer hangs up before the 20 minutes are over, it can
cost as much as 28 cents per minute _ one of the highest rates
charged by any long-distance company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows before you get on the phone how long a call is going
to last?'' Sachs said. ``Unless you know for a fact that you're
going to call someone who's definitely home and can definitely talk
for 20 minutes, you can wind up paying really high rates.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads also boast that customers can save 50 percent over
AT&AMP;T's basic rate by dialing 10-10-321. What they don't tell you is
that AT&AMP;T's basic rate is among the highest in the industry and
that hardly anyone pays that rate, Sachs said. The majority of
people are on a discount calling plan, which has significantly
lower per-minute prices.
</P>
<P>
   Burns of MCI WorldCom said 10-10-321 does save people money if
they talk for more than 20 minutes. A 25-minute daytime call from
San Francisco to New York, for example, would cost $4.20 with
10-10-321.
</P>
<P>
   An AT&AMP;T customer without a calling plan would pay $7 for the
same call. But someone with a calling plan might pay as little as
$2.50.
</P>
<P>
   ``If customers don't realize the savings that we promised them,
they're not going to use the service again,'' Burns said. ``Of the
consumers who use dial-around products, we've found that 88 percent
of them are very satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   Other companies also defend their rates and promotions, saying
dial-arounds wouldn't be so popular if people weren't getting a
good deal.
</P>
<P>
   Something for Everyone
</P>
<P>
   ``It may very well be that for lots of consumers, being on a
calling plan of some sort is the best thing for them,'' said Mark
Siegel, a spokesman for AT&AMP;T's consumer services. But some
consumers might do better with Lucky Dog, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many of these dial-arounds out there, and they
change their plans so frequently. In order to avoid getting ripped
off by one of these, we suggest consumers get on a calling plan,''
Sachs said. ``If they're on a calling plan, chances are they will
save as much if not more money than if they used a dial-around.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, state Assemblyman Scott Stringer plans to propose
legislation that would restrict what dial-arounds can claim in
their ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a famous actress telling you this is the buy of the
century, only then you dial and find out it's not such a great
deal,'' said Stringer, a Democrat. ``People are easily misled and
we need to simplify the way consumers gain information so they're
protected.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Stringer said consumers should ``be careful,
price the services out, ask questions and find out if that's the
package for you. Don't watch a television commercial and then dial
10-10 because you miss your grandmother. You should call your
grandmother, but there's no need to be gouged while doing it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
