<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5787 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIG-FREEZE-FLA-COX     11-30 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIG-FREEZE-FLA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forcasters predict major cold snap for Florida
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A hard frost early next year, prompted
by the La Nina weather phenomenon, may cause ``devastating'' damage
to South Florida crops, weather forecasters said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But agricultural officials in Palm Beach County and the Treasure
Coast said damage would depend on the crop and the timing and
severity of the cold snap.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service's freeze prediction came during an
assessment of the hurricane season, which ended Monday. The season
did not cooperate with the calendar, as Nicole, far out in the east
Atlantic, became the year's 14th hurricane early Monday. But Nicole
was expected to dissipate in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a 75 to 80 percent chance we'll have a freeze'' in
January or February, said Jim Lushine, Warning Coordination
Meteorologist for the National Weather Service's Miami office.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters can't say how deep the mercury will drop or for how
long. But the moderate weather of the last few months, which is
expected to continue through December, will leave crops more
vulnerable than if they'd toughed out cooler weather, Lushine said.
</P>
<P>
   La Nina is a cooling of the tropical waters of the eastern
Pacific Ocean, the opposite of the El Nino effect.
</P>
<P>
   La Nina is expected to leave the Midwest and Northeast colder
and wetter than normal, Lushine said. He said extra snowfall and
resulting wind patterns will draw the jet stream down into Florida,
bringing the cold weather.
</P>
<P>
   A typical freeze brings one or two nights with lows dipping to
the high 20s from Miami-Dade to Palm Beach counties and perhaps to
the mid-20s in the Treasure Coast, Lushine said. The last one
occurred in January 1997 and lasted two days, causing an estimated
$300 million in crop damage in South and Central Florida.
</P>
<P>
   A two-day freeze in 1989 brought an estimated $1 billion damage
statewide.
</P>
<P>
   A hard freeze could also leave a lot of dead vegetation, fuel
for summer fires often sparked by lightning, Lushine said.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture officials tempered Monday's dire crop predictions.
</P>
<P>
   A January freeze would not be as devastating as a December snap
to vegetable crops in Palm Beach County and the Treasure Coast,
said Dr. Thomas Shueneman, a Palm Beach County agriculture agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, there are two seasons for vegetables, and January
falls right in between so if there's going to be a frost we can
plan around it,'' Shueneman said.
</P>
<P>
   Citrus starts to die if the temperature falls below 28 degrees
for more than four hours, said Steve Ebersbach, production
supervisor for the 4,000-acre Callery-Judge Groves in Loxahatchee.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get into trouble when you get a sustained cold,'' he said.
``Then previous weather doesn't make any difference.''
</P>
<P>
   A freeze in late December or early January, which is only
halfway through the sugar cane harvest, would cause more damage
than a later snap, said John Dunckelman, vice president for
agriculture research for the Florida Sugar Cane League in
Clewiston. He said if temperatures are in the mid-20s for up to
eight hours, stalks would freeze and split, sugar juice could be
ruined, and new plantings could die, affecting future crops.
</P>
<P>
   La Nina historically brings almost twice as many landfalling
tropical storms and hurricanes, but most do not strike Florida,
Lushine said, citing a study by Florida State University's Center
for Oceanic-Atmospheric Prediction Studies.
</P>
<P>
   La Nina might also prompt tornadoes in December or January and
again in May or June, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On top of all of this, forecasters predict another El Nino
running from the fall of 1999 to the summer of 2000, Lushine said.
He said forecasters can't explain the quick turnaround; the current
La Nina followed the second-greatest El Nino this century in
1997-1998, which succeeded a La Nina in 1996-1997. El Ninos usually
alternate with La Ninas and occur every two to seven years, but not
always. The last El Nino before 1997-1998 was in 1982-1983, while
the last La Nina before the two most recent was in 1988. Some
years, of course, are neither El Nino or La Nina years.
</P>
<P>
   Max Mayfield, the hurricane center's deputy director, also said
Monday that the 34 hurricanes in the last four years is an all-time
record; the previous four-year record was 32 from 1948 to 1951. He
said the total of seven tropical storms or hurricanes striking the
U.S. mainland this year, causing $6.5 billion in damage, was double
the historical average.
</P>
<P>
   Eliot Kleinberg writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. Seth Mnookin contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
