<SLUG> BC-PIRO-MURDER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Television show may air segment on missing Florida man
 &HT;    By Joe Brogan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. _ Police have asked the television show
America's Most Wanted to run a segment on Singer Island resident
Christopher Benedetto, who has been missing since before his wife's
body was found Nov. 23 in a freezer in the couple's garage.
</P>
<P>
   There is a good chance it will air, but not this week, America's
Most Wanted spokeswoman Cindy Smith said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy was scheduled for today on the body of Benedetto's
wife, Janette Piro, 45. She was found by relatives stuffed in a
fetal position in a freezer under a workbench at 1160 Dolphin Road.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Charles Seibert, associate Palm Beach County medical
examiner, said the autopsy could not be performed last week because
the body was frozen solid and needed ``four to five days'' of
thawing to prevent deterioration.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to go slowly,'' he said. ``You can't just leave it
out at room temperature.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dade County Medical Examiner's Office was performing a
special test Monday on the body at the local medical examiner's
office that required four or five hours, a spokeswoman at the local
office said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Riviera police nor the county medical examiner would say
what the Dade County test involved, or why that agency was called
in.
</P>
<P>
   Benedetto, 42, has been missing since the couple failed to show
for a dinner date with neighbors Nov. 11.
</P>
<P>
   In another development, Riviera Beach Detective Pat Galligan
said Monday that the couple's financial accounts had not been
touched, but he wouldn't elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago Benedetto retired after receiving a seven-figure
insurance settlement for seriously injuring his back in a
construction fall in New York, his attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   Galligan refused to comment on whether credit cards issued to
the couple had been used since Benedetto's disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   He also declined comment on results of Luminol tests done to
detect blood traces in the home or whose fingerprints were found in
the couple's Toyota 4-Runner, which was discovered parked at a
Singer Island hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Brogan writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
