<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia: Lawyer Given Jail Term
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer who is defending former Deputy Prime Minister Anwar
Ibrahim in his trial on sex and corruption charges was sentenced to
three months in jail for contempt of court. The lawyer, Zainur
Zakaria, had refused to apologize for having accused two
prosecutors of trying to have a witness lie.
</P>
<P>
   India: Quick Parliament Session
</P>
<P>
   Parliament convened for the first time since the defeat of the
Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party in state elections last
week. The session adjourned after shouting leaders of regional
parties rushed to demand the resignation of Prime Minister Atal
Behari Vajpayee, who heads the party. The victorious Congress Party
is demanding a parliamentary debate on the failure to control
rising vegetable prices.
</P>
<P>
   Cambodia: Coalition Approved
</P>
<P>
   A new coalition government, with Hun Sen as prime minister, was
approved in the National Assembly, 99-13. Prince Norodom Ranariddh,
who heads the junior party in the coalition, was elected speaker
last week.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   United Nations: Britain Signs Court Treaty
</P>
<P>
   Britain's U.N. representative, Sir Jeremy Greenstock, signed the
treaty that creates an international criminal court, bringing the
number of signatory countries to 61. The United States was among
seven countries, including Iraq and Libya, that opposed the treaty
when it was adopted in July, fearing it could be misused against
American troops and other Americans abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: New Salinas Charges Dismissed
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge has again dismissed charges of illegal
enrichment against Raul Salinas de Gortari, brother of the former
president. Salinas was acquitted of similar accusations this year.
But on Nov. 17, prosecutors filed new charges, arguing that Salinas
had illegally amassed $12 million in his brother's administration,
from 1988 to 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
