<HEADER>
A5811 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-PHILLIPS-COLUMN-L     11-30 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PHILLIPS-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTREAL CITIZENS MOROSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ In Los Angeles, the NHL team struggles and the
populace yawns.
</P>
<P>
   In Montreal, the fabled Canadiens struggle and it's a civic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   And to call these Canadiens a struggling team is to be kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Habs have no backbone,'' a Montreal Gazette headline
proclaimed after Friday's 5-1 loss at Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop the bleeding!'' another begged Sunday after the
Canadiens' 4-3 loss to Pittsburgh the night before.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadiens had lost seven of their previous eight games
before Monday night's meeting with the Kings. It got so bad, they
were even taking hits from one of their own _ the legendary Guy
Lafleur.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only team that would remind me of teams when I played is
Detroit,'' Lafleur told a Canadian newspaper last week. ``As for
Montreal, I just look at them as one of 27 in the league.... The
problem is there is only one good line. The rest are mostly
defensive players. They can score a few goals, but are they guys
you can count on for the big goal in the playoffs?''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to one of the Canadiens' players, Lafleur added:
``Brian Savage gets paid as a 35-40 goal scorer ($3.5 million), but
he's never done that. What's the motivation for making more money?
They don't have any because they're already making millions. When I
was playing, you were told, `Score more and we'll give you more
money.'''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine what Lafleur's comments would be if he weren't working
these days as a goodwill ambassador for the Canadiens.
</P>
<P>
   The players are feeling the tension. Defenseman Eric Weinrich,
recently acquired from the Chicago Blackhawks, has noticed the
increased pressure playing for his new losing team as opposed to
his old one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to compare it is if I'd played on the Bulls last
year,'' he said. ``Here, the people and the media don't leave any
stone unturned. The people here, when they talk about the game, if
we win, they say, `We won.' If we lose, they say, `We lost.' It's
not like the team lost. It's like the city lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The days of dynasties are probably gone. Canadiens fans should
accustom themselves to winning once in awhile, not all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Is it a bad thing? For those who enjoyed the aura of the
Canadiens, it most definitely is. But it's a new era. The NHL will
soon have 30 teams, and prolonged dominance is a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league's been talking about parity for years and years,''
said Kings coach Larry Robinson, a former Canadiens great. ``Well,
they've got it. Nashville comes in, an expansion team, and they're
right in the middle of the pack. That's parity for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's some more parity: Les Habitants can only wish they had as
many victories as those fabled Predators from Music City USA. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One down, two to go
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers won the Petr Nedved sweepstakes, leaving disgruntled
Canuck Pavel Bure and unsigned Islander Zigmund Palffy as the two
best hockey players not playing in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps the Penguins won, ridding themselves of someone who
wouldn't play for them and getting a talented if underachieving
forward, Alexei Kovalev, in exchange.
</P>
<P>
   It does not appear the Nedved acquisition eliminates the Rangers
from making a bid for Bure. Before making the Nedved deal, Rangers
GM Neil Smith reportedly checked with Canucks counterpart Brian
Burke to make sure Burke wouldn't want Kovalev in a deal for Bure.
</P>
<P>
   The cash-strapped Penguins' standoff with Nedved _ who sat out
all last season and the first quarter of this one _ ended as well
as Pittsburgh could have hoped. Not only did the Penguins get
Kovalev in the five-player deal, they saved $2 million in salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'm happy; I don't know what my sentiments
are,'' Penguins general manager Craig Patrick said. ``I guess I'm
pleased to finally be able to get proper value for our asset.''
</P>
<P>
   Kings GM Dave Taylor said he'd had interest in Nedved, but it
cooled when the Penguins insisted on a deal that would have
included 19-year-old center Olli Jokinen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hockey culture 101
</P>
<P>
   A major issue last week in hockey-crazed Canada was a report by
an academician who spent a year studying an unidentified American
Hockey League team. He concluded that the ``hyper-masculine'' world
of hockey has created a social sub-group with unique
``homo-social'' practices.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Robidoux, who recently completed a Ph.D. on hockey
culture at a Canadian university, wrote about such hazing rituals
as players drinking from a punchbowl filled with alcohol, spit and
urine at a party, and stripping on the team bus, then seeing how
many nude players would fit into the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no room for self-development,'' Dr. Robidoux told the
National Post. ``If you don't fit within this one, singular notion
of what it means to be a man, you're not welcomed.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robidoux also found that the single-minded participation in
the sport stunts some players' intellectual growth. One 25-year-old
player could only spell phonetically.
</P>
<P>
   ``He spelled self-esteem `self of steam,''' Robidoux reported. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
