<DOCNO> NYT19981130.0514 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5833 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-ESCAPE-HNS &LR;      11-30 1356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-ESCAPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS DEATH ROW INMATE NOT FIRST TO TRY ESCAPE, BUT FIRST TO MAKE
IT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
and ALLAN TURNER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ Martin E. Gurule may be the first killer to
escape from Texas' death row in 64 years, but two other condemned
prisoners tried to flee just a year and a half ago, taking a
virtually identical roof-top escape route, prison officials
acknowledged Monday. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Prison records reviewed by the Houston Chronicle show that on
June 26, 1997, killers Willie Pondexter and Cedric Ransom cut
through a recreation yard fence at Huntsville's Ellis I Unit with a
hacksaw blade, just as Gurule and six other death row inmates did
Thanksgiving night. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Pondexter and Ransom then climbed onto the roof, ``headed south
to the end of the building and climbed down to the ground between
the chapel and south gym'' and made a dash for the perimeter
fences, records show.
</P>
<P>
   That escape attempt, which Texas Department of Criminal Justice
officials never publicly reported, was thwarted when a tower guard
spotted Ransom climbing the first fence and ordered him to drop to
the ground. Ransom did, and prison guards then found Pondexter
lying on the ground inside the recreation yard compound, according
to an official report filed a day after the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials confirmed Monday that they had found a fragment
of a hacksaw blade on the prison roof, where Gurule and the other
inmates apparently waited for several hours before sliding down the
side of a building and running for the fences before dawn Friday.
Only Gurule succeeded in escaping.
</P>
<P>
   A prison official also confirmed Monday that Panchai Wilkerson,
one of the six murderers who attempted t flee with Gurule, had
tried to escape from death row in 1993. In that incident,
Wilkerson, a 29-year-old killer from Harris County, and death row
inmate Jessy Carlos San Miguel, were caught after they used a
hacksaw blade to cut through a prison recreation yard fence, said
TDCJ spokesman Larry Todd.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that escape attempt, Wilkerson was placed in the ``work
capable'' program, a status that gave him and the others involved
in last week's escape the freedom to move about without constant
monitoring by guards.
</P>
<P>
   In both of the previous escape attempts, the inmates were
disciplined, but it could not be immediately determined how or for
what length of time they were disciplined, Todd said late Monday.
Traditionally, when death row inmates are disciplined, they are
removed from the work program, if they had that status. They also
can be denied visitation and commissary privileges.
</P>
<P>
   As the search for Gurule continued for a fourth day Monday,
Allan Polunsky, chairman of the Texas Board of Criminal Justice,
said that ``it's certainly a possibility'' that the work program,
which since 1986 has allowed death row inmates to work in a garment
factory, will be abolished as a result of the escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's time we examine the policies with respect to the
work capable program,'' said Polunsky, who was in Huntsville to
observe the search. ``I am personally not a proponent of the work
program, but there are other board members and we all need to
assess this in calmer times.''
</P>
<P>
   Polunsky said he has appointed fellow board member Alfred M.
``Max'' Stringfellow of San Antonio to oversee TDCJ's
investigations into the escape and to report back to the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there was a breakdown in procedures and the overall
security,'' Polunsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Monday, a death row guard said that TDCJ has known for
some time that ``it was just a matter of time'' before a condemned
prisoner escaped because inmates routinely cut through recreation
yard fences.
</P>
<P>
   And, despite TDCJ official comment to the contrary, one national
expert in prison gangs said that Sammy Buentello, the prison
system's gang expert, alerted him by e-mail after receiving
information that Gurule was a member or associate of the Mexican
Mafia prison gang.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, prison officials in Huntsville admitted they were
frustrated that their fourth day of searching for the escaped
killer appeared to be ending in failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that doesn't mean we can just quit,'' said Gary Johnson,
director of the Institution Division of the Texas Department of
Criminal Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said as many as 500 officers and 70 search dogs were
engaged in the hunt, and will continue concentrating on the heavily
wooded area in which the Ellis Unit is situated ``until we have
hard proof he is not here.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said they were investigating the weekend theft of a
blue 1989 GMC pickup from the parking lot of a Huntsville auto
parts store, but Johnson said they have no evidence that the stolen
vehicle was connected with the escape.
</P>
<P>
   Infrared sensing devices turned up nothing Monday, and Texas
Parks and Wildlife officials patrolling the nearby Trinity River in
boats, also came up empty. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; But Johnson and other prison officials insisted they believe
Gurule remains within the secured seven-mile perimeter south and
east of the prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no plans of pulling out. We're here for the long
haul,'' Johnson said. ``It is our mission to keep killers locked
up.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; And TDCJ spokesman Glen Castlebury added that the search will
continue 24 hours a day until Gurule is found. ``We never close,''
he said. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Gurule, 29, sentenced to die for the 1992 murder of two men
during the robbery of a Corpus Christi restaurant, was the only
inmate who achieved his goal in the break-out, crossing a pair of
10-foot-tall razor-wire topped fences that ring the prison. The
other killers surrendered after sentries opened fire with AR-15
rifles. None of the inmates was hit.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said it is possible that Gurule and the others had
formulated no plans for their escape other than how to get out of
prison. If that was the case, Gurule might be wandering aimlessly
in the woods, possibly wounded, and likely without food and water.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Herbert L. DuPont, chief of internal medicine at Houston's
St. Luke's Episcopal Hospital, said that with current temperatures
ranging from 70 to 80 degrees, Gurule could survive up to 10 days
with no water at all, and a couple of weeks without food.
</P>
<P>
   ``Water is the limiting factor,'' DuPont said. ``The weather is
OK, and he's hiding so he's going to stay out of the sun. The
temperature is about perfect. He has an advantage in that regard.''
</P>
<P>
   The death row guard, who declined to be identified by name in a
story, said he and other guards have long been concerned about the
freedom their wards have, and that every recreation yard has
``dozens'' of patches in the fence where inmates have tried to saw
their way to freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Monday that the origin of the hacksaw blade the
inmates used to cut the fence is unknown, but the guard confirmed
suspicions that it could have come from a prison workshop. He said
death row inmates routinely obtain the hacksaws from general
population inmates by trading for drugs, cigarettes and other
contraband as well as commissary items.
</P>
<P>
   General population inmates have access to hacksaws in the school
bus repair barn and other work sites to which they are assigned, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Death row prisoners assigned to work in the garment factory also
have far more freedom than other death row inmates, the guard said.
For example, they are allowed to go to indoor recreation areas,
called day rooms, and to outdoor recreation yards unaccompanied by
guards.
</P>
<P>
   A door leading from the day room to the recreation yard _ the
door that Gurule and his accomplices apparently used _ remains
unlocked about 14 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the guard said that cell block doors to work
capable death row prisoners automatically open every hour on the
hour, giving those prisoners the chance to leave their cells if
they choose.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, other death row prisoners remain locked in their
cells 23 hours a day, and are handcuffed, shackled and escorted
everywhere they go inside the prison. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 2244EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
