<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS RESUME QUEST FOR PITCHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Big Unit made a big decision Monday, and
in the process forced the Angels and Dodgers to go to Plan B.
</P>
<P>
   Both local teams were in the hunt for free agent pitcher Randy
Johnson, but Johnson picked the Arizona Diamondbacks, who will pay
him $53 million over four years. His average annual salary of
$13.25 million is second in baseball to Mo Vaughn's $13.33 million
with the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, what the decision came down to was not money. All
four teams in the running -- Dodgers, Angels, Rangers and
Diamondbacks -- made similar offers. But the Diamondbacks' Bank One
Ballpark is in Phoenix, about a half-hour drive from Johnson's
Paradise Valley home.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Diamondbacks convinced Johnson that they are committed
to winning immediately. And with Johnson in their starting
rotation, their chances got significantly better.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Johnson in the Diamondbacks' rotation are recently
signed Todd Stottlemyre and Armando Reynoso. Andy Benes and lefties
Brian Anderson and Omar Daal return from last year's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, obviously there are family issues and he's pleased to
spend his life in the Valley for hopefully the rest of his baseball
life,'' Barry Meister, one of Johnson's agents, told a Phoenix
radio station. ``But also from the top, we have a commitment that
the Diamondbacks are going to do what it takes to get to the World
Series and we believe that. . . . What it came down to was that
Arizona really showed us a blueprint for success.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was always an interest in his part and a tug in
his heart relative to playing at home,'' Diamondbacks owner Jerry
Colangelo said. ``The big question was how soon could we become
competitive as compared to all of these teams because of his fierce
competitiveness and desire to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt confident from the first day I met with Randy and his
agents. And I felt in my heart of hearts that this was the right
place for him. I believe that many of the moves we made since that
first meeting 29 days ago made the difference. All of those moves
were significant in his eyes, in terms of commitment to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone, who said the club will now
go after free agent pitcher Kevin Brown, wasn't surprised at
Johnson's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows you how important his family is to him,'' Malone
said. ``I think you have to compliment and respect a man like that.
You can't be disapppointed knowing what his priorities are.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew this was a longshot because of the commitment to his
family. We knew Arizona probably was the favorite all along because
he just built a home there.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 35, was 19-11 with a major league-leading 329
strikeouts pitching for the Mariners and Astros last season. He
struggled with the Mariners in the first half of the season (9-10,
4.33 ERA) amid bad blood between himself and Mariners management
because of strained contract negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   But after being traded to Houston on July 31, Johnson went 10-1
with a 1.28 ERA while helping the Astros win the N.L. Central.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, believed to be one of the two finalists for Johnson,
are disappointed but will move forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, we made a good, honest effort,'' Angels general manager
Bill Bavasi said. ``We made an effort right out of the chute. We
talked to him the first day we were allowed to. We were up front;
there were good negotiations. But they don't all work out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' top priority remains finding a No. 1 starter, which
is bad news for center fielder Jim Edmonds. Had the Angels signed
Johnson, the Angels likely would have kept Edmonds and possibly
traded Garret Anderson for a No. 3 or 4 starter.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Edmonds can be used as trade bait to get an ace. Roger
Clemens and Pat Hentgen of the Blue Jays, and Francisco Cordova of
the Pirates are reportedly available for the right price.
</P>
<P>
   ``Free agency, trades, you name it -- we've got to find more
pitching,'' Bavasi said.
</P>
<P>
   It is the Angels' policy not to discuss names of players they
have an interest in, but Malone made it clear -- the Dodgers want
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had discussions with (agent) Scott Boras about Kevin
Brown,'' he said. ``And there are other pitchers available. Maybe
not high profile, but guys that fit in for us. I like our pitching.
Sure, Randy Johnson or Kevin Brown would help, but we're in good
shape with (Chan Ho) Park, (Darren) Dreifort, (Ismael) Valdes,
(Carlos) Perez and (Dave) Mlicki.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Associated Press contributed to this story.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
