<SLUG> BC-CITYHALL-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT ALLOWS LIMITED RALLY AT CITY HALL
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal appeals court arrived at a Solomonic
solution Monday in a legal challenge to the Giuliani
administration's virtual shutdown of public access to City Hall,
ruling that hundreds of demonstrators could hold a rally Tuesday in
the parking area in front of City Hall but could not set foot on
the building's 11 steps.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, by a three-judge panel of the 2nd U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in Manhattan, left both sides publicly declaring
partial victory.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said that the panel had largely ruled in their
favor by reversing several aspects of a decision last week by a
District Court judge and by not impinging on their right to assess
the security needs for City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can come in the plaza but not go on the steps,'' Michael
Hess, the city's corporation counsel, said. ``And that's a major
victory for the city.''
</P>
<P>
   But spokesmen for Housing Works, an AIDS service organization
that had sued the city over access to City Hall, said that by
winning the right to step beyond the concrete barriers that
surround the building, they had won. ``Our whole point was to be at
City Hall to make this statement,'' Charles King, the group's
co-director, said. ``If I'm standing one step in front of the
steps, I'm going to consider this a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling, the court left unanswered its reasons for barring
the demonstrators from City Hall's steps. Norman Siegel, the
director of the New York Civil Liberties Union, which had argued
the case for Housing Works, said he was disappointed with that part
of the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel and representatives from Housing Works met Monday with
city and police officials to work out the details for the rally,
which will begin with a parade down Broadway from Houston Street
and end with a news conference in the parking area, which is called
City Hall Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   About 550 people are expected to attend. It marks the first
event staged in front of City Hall by anyone other than the city
since mid-August, when the Police Department launched Operation
Bravo, a plan to tighten security in lower Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 2313EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981130.0526 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5984 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     11-30 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON'S TITLE HOPES WILL SUFFER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It basically came down to a coin flip. The
immediate futures of four franchises were up in the air while star
pitcher Randy Johnson took his sweet ol' time calling out his
preference. Which would it be, the Anaheim Angels or the Arizona
Diamondbacks?
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Johnson's decision finally landed with a thud heard
around Southern California. The Diamondbacks it was.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say the Angels lost.
</P>
<P>
   So Anaheim didn't add the left-hander to its starting rotation.
Neither did its hated neighbor to the north. No matter what spin
they put on it publicly, the Dodgers had to be privately gnashing
their teeth over letting Johnson slip through their fingers for a
second time in less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   First they moved too slowly to consummate a trade for Johnson in
the spring when he was unhappily ensconced in Seattle, and now
they'll have to face him in divisional play. At least the Texas
Rangers, who were the other team reportedly in the final running
for Johnson, won't have to suffer through that ignominy.
</P>
<P>
   One of Johnson's representatives said the former USC standout
was swayed in the end by the fact ``Arizona really showed us a
blueprint for success.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but we seem to recall the Angels led their division
for a lot more days this past season than did the expansion
Diamondbacks. Moreover, Anaheim's signing last week of free-agent
slugger Mo Vaughn would seem to have reinforced its foundation
against late-season collapses.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, a starting rotation of Johnson, Todd Stottlemyre,
Armando Reynoso, Andy Benes and Brian Anderson or Omar Daal is a
significant stride in the right direction for a Diamondbacks team
that went 65-97 in its inaugural season. But the last time we
checked, Arizona's offense was Travis Lee, Matt Williams, Jay Bell
and a pile of rust.
</P>
<P>
   Williams pursued a move to Arizona because he wanted to be near
his children who reside there with his ex-wife. Johnson also has
familial ties to the area; his permanent residence is in Paradise
Valley, a half-hour's drive from the Diamondbacks' ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing inherently wrong with wanting to be a
year-around father and/or husband. The problem arises when a
quality-of-life decision is passed off as being all about the
quality of the offers.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson chose the Diamondbacks because of their blueprint for
success? Yeah, right, and we chose to live in Southern California
because of the traffic. If what Johnson really wants is to win a
World Series title, the Angels would have been his clear-cut
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if it's true what one of his representatives
insinuated, that Johnson was put off by the higher taxes in
California, it says a lot about the price Johnson was willing to
pay to contend for a championship.
</P>
<P>
   You would think baseball's ultimate prize would be an
irresistible lure to someone who already has won a Cy Young and the
respect (and in many cases, fear) of his peers. What else
individually is there left for him to achieve?
</P>
<P>
   But hey, we hope he enjoys pitching for a team that's liable to
trigger more flashbacks to his last few weeks in Seattle than those
few blissful months he spent in Houston. At least his wife will be
there to leave the light on when things on the field turn bleak.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the events of the past few days have made it
abundantly clear the egos driving the Fox Group and the Disney
Company are rubbing up against each other like the tectonic plates
underneath our feet.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever there's Fox and Disney in tight proximity, there's
friction. And the resulting tremors would appear to be a fine thing
for long-suffering Dodgers and Angels fans. Or did it escape your
notice that the Angels couldn't be bothered to go after slugger
Mark McGwire or pitching ace Roger Clemens when the Dodgers were a
family-owned entity.
</P>
<P>
   Then Fox takes over the Dodgers and makes noises about becoming
a major player in the free-agent market. And fast as you can say
about-face, the Angels are reaching for their checkbooks.
</P>
<P>
   On the night the Angels made Vaughn the game's highest-paid
player, the Dodgers reportedly upped their offer to Johnson. Now
they have little choice but to turn their checkbook to San Diego
free agent Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Why, if Fox and Disney aren't careful, their personal grudge
might escalate into the kind of bidding war that makes Southern
California the envy of baseball fans everywhere. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
