</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-KEARL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANLEY B. KEARL, 84, SCULPTOR AND PROFESSOR
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Brandon Kearl, a sculptor, died on Nov. 21 at his home
in Scarsdale, N.Y. He was 84.
</P>
<P>
   Kearl's small bronze figurative sculptures, which he described
as ``metaphysical realism,'' drew on archaic and classical Greek
art, European Surrealism and biblical references to create private
scenarios that some critics compared to science fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Kearl had solo shows at the Institute of Contemporary Art in
Boston (1957), the Hudson River Museum in Yonkers (1969) and the
Guild Hall Museum in East Hampton, N.Y. (1982), as well as at
museums and galleries in Basel, Munich, Rome, Stockholm and
Bangkok, Thailand. His work, which is represented by the Arlene
Bujese Gallery in East Hampton, was included in group exhibitions
at the Whitney Museum of American Art (1962) and the Museum of
Modern Art in New York (1965), and at the Venice Biennale in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   Kearl had a doctorate in sculpture from the University of Iowa
and most recently taught sculpture at the Pratt Institute in
Brooklyn. For nearly a decade, he lived in Rome as a Fulbright
scholar.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Trudie; two stepsons, Richard C.
Holbrooke, President Clinton's special envoy to the Balkans, and
Andrew Holbrooke of Manhattan, and two sisters, Lucille Armati of
Reston, Va., and Roberta Kearl of Connecticut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
