<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME'S BADFELLAS 
ED AND AL
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON WITH BRUCE LAMBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Of the names on Time magazine's list of the 100
``most influential business geniuses of the century,'' some belong
to bosses who dominated American industry: Henry Ford and Bill
Gates, for example. And then, right after Walt Disney, is the name
of a different kind of boss: Charles ``Lucky'' Luciano, the
legendary mafia leader.
</P>
<P>
   In no time, Time had Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani fuming.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much weak thinking about the mafia and so much
romanticizing of it,'' the mayor said at City Hall. ``This idea
that most of these mafia people could have been successful
businessmen if they had only gone into business completely begs the
question. They have a tactic available to them that people can't
use in business, at least not openly, and that is murdering lots of
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``So most of the mafia people that I've met, prosecuted and put
in prison basically have sub-par intelligence, would not have been
successful in business, other than the business of murder,'' he
added. ``And the whole idea of suggesting that creates the further
romanticization of an organization that now is hopefully ending.''
</P>
<P>
   One can only wonder what the mayor would have said if he had
accepted Time's offer to write its article about Luciano (``He
downsized, he restructured and he used Standard &AMP; Poor's as much as
Smith &AMP; Wesson,'' the headline says).
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was, as a former prosecutor, he'd be the perfect
choice to not glorify this guy,'' Bill Saporito, Time's business
editor, said of Giuliani. ``The mayor's people accepted on his
behalf, saying he was excited about it, and two weeks later they
said he'd changed his mind. Didn't say why.'' In place of the
mayor, Time recruited Edna Buchanan, who won a Pulitzer Prize in
1986 as a reporter for the Miami Herald.
</P>
<P>
   An Odd Couple
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not the usual sight at the Four Seasons,'' the Rev. Al
Sharpton said, sounding as if he relished the understatement.
</P>
<P>
   But there he was, having lunch (chicken salad) with former Mayor
Edward Koch, who had the chef's salad and who once had him
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   That was 20 years ago. Monday, they talked about an idea Koch
calls the ``second chance proposal'' to help nonviolent felons
clear their criminal records. Koch said that he and Charles
Ogletree Jr., a professor at Harvard Law School, had been
discussing ways to remove the stigma that mandatory sentences for
drug convictions create.
</P>
<P>
   The idea would be to pardon felons who had served their jail
time if they joined some kind of national service corps and passed
drug tests over several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``My proposal was you serve for a year or two, during which time
you are tested regularly for drugs and you have to get your GED and
you learn a skill,'' Koch said. ``And then you'll be tested again
for another one or two years, and if you don't show drug use and
don't have another altercation with the law, you'd get a
presidential pardon. So, if you are asked, `Have you ever been
convicted of a crime?' you could answer no. So you can get a job,
vote, raise a family.''
</P>
<P>
   Koch and Sharpton said they had agreed to arrange a conference
on the proposal next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unlikely combination of Koch and I coming together might
spur people to push for legislation,'' Sharpton said. ``It's not a
sexy issue, and I think we've got to make it that.''
</P>
<P>
   As if that were not enough for one midday encounter, the lunch
proved that Sharpton is something of a celebrity in Koch's circles.
For there was a third person at the table: James Gill, a managing
partner at the law firm where Koch works when he is not deciding
cases on the syndicated television show ``The People's Court.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lunch was for 12:15,'' Koch said. ``About 10 of 12, he said:
`I just saw your schedule. Can I come to lunch with you? I want to
meet Al Sharpton.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
