<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981130.0534 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6005 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-JOHNSON-DBACKS-HN     11-30 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-JOHNSON-DBACKS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
More than a month after beginning the free-agent process, Randy
Johnson found the answer he was searching for right outside his
front door.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Johnson, who spent the final two months of the 1998 season with
the Astros before becoming one of the most sought-after prizes of
this offseason, elected to stay close to his family and in the
National League by agreeing Monday to a four-year, $52.4 million
contract with the Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The $13.1 million average annual salary makes Johnson the game's
highest-paid pitcher and second-highest-paid player behind Mo
Vaughn, who will average $13.33 million from last week's six-year
agreement with the Anaheim Angels. Johnson's deal also includes a
club option for a fifth year with a buyout provision.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks, a second-year expansion team, had plenty of
leverage in their pursuit of the 6-10 lefthander. Johnson lives in
Paradise Valley, Ariz., a suburb of Phoenix and a 20-minute drive
from Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was always an interest on his part and a tug in
his heart relative to playing at home,'' Diamondbacks owner Jerry
Colangelo said. ``The big question was how soon could we become
competitive as compared to all of these teams, because of his
fierce competitiveness and desire to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson chose Arizona ahead of the Angels, Texas Rangers and Los
Angeles Dodgers, each of whom made the Big Unit a four-year offer
worth at least $12 million a year, his representatives said.
</P>
<P>
   If his agent is to be believed, not everything came down to
dollar signs for Johnson. He also was impressed with the
Diamondbacks' commitment to improve drastically from 1998, when
they went 65-97 _ the third-worst record in baseball _ and finished
their inaugural season 33 games behind the San Diego Padres in the
NL West.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to weigh all the factors _ how competitive the team
would be in the future, where his family would be comfortable,''
said Johnson's agent, Barry Meister. ``Money was a non-factor,
because everything was pretty comparable. He made the decision
late, late, late Sunday night, slept on it, still felt that way in
the morning, and we called the other clubs.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who owns a career record of 143-79 and won the 1995
American League Cy Young Award, was unavailable for comment Monday.
He will be introduced as a Diamondback at a Wednesday news
conference at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Already this winter, the Diamondbacks have opened their
pocketbook to the tune of almost $100 million to upgrade a pitching
staff that tied for 12th in the NL with a 4.63 ERA and was last in
the 16-team league with 908 strikeouts. Arizona recently signed
free-agent pitchers Todd Stottlemyre and Armando Reynoso to
respective four-year and two-year deals worth $32 million and $5.5
million. They also added reliever Greg Swindell and first baseman
Greg Colbrunn to a nucleus that includes third baseman Matt
Williams, infielder Jay Bell and up-and-coming first baseman Travis
Lee.
</P>
<P>
   When the Diamondbacks report to spring training in Tucson,
Ariz., this February, they will have a pitching staff with six
proven starters _ Johnson, Stottlemyre, Reynoso, Andy Benes, Brian
Anderson and Omar Daal. The last two, like Johnson, are
lefthanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Randy, it's possible that we could have the second-best
staff in baseball,'' Colangelo said. ``Our rotation is as
formidable as anybody out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say pitching wins championships. We're going to test that
theory.''
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Johnson by Arizona did not surprise many,
including Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker. The Astros, to
whom Johnson was traded by the Seattle Mariners on July 31, had
hoped to re-sign Johnson and offered $33 million for three years
before dropping out of the bidding early last week by refusing to
commit to a guaranteed fourth year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really felt Arizona was the front-runner all along, given
the importance Randy placed on family and the fact he built a
beautiful new home out there,'' Hunsicker said. ``All signs pointed
toward Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker added that, barring injuries, the Diamondbacks are
shaping into a contender within the NL West.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are putting a rotation together that has the ability to
win every series they go into,'' he said. ``As we saw in the
playoffs, one player doesn't make the difference in winning or
losing. If they keep their rotation healthy, then other clubs will
have their hands full when playing Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 35, spent more than eight seasons with Seattle, helping
the Mariners to AL West titles in 1995 and 1997. His relationship
with the Mariners' front office soured after the club refused to
give him a contract extension following the 1997 season. He went
9-10 through July before being shipped to Houston just minutes
before the trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson became more marketable during his stint with the Astros,
going 10-1 with a 1.28 ERA and 116 strikeouts in 84 innings. In
all, he struck out 329 batters in 1998, the fifth time he has led
the major leagues in strikeouts and the highest total since Nolan
Ryan's 344 with the 1977 Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson will get a $5 million signing bonus, $7.35 million next
year and $12.35 million in each of the following three seasons.
Arizona has a $12 million option for 2003 with a $3 million buyout
clause. The contract also includes bonuses if Johnson is a Cy Young
winner.
</P>
<P>
   In order to lure Johnson, the Diamondbacks were apparently
willing to do anything. During Monday's announcement, manager Buck
Showalter said his rules prohibiting facial hair and long hair will
not apply to Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told Randy right from the get-go we like him just the way
he is,'' Showalter said. ``That rule will be grandfathered for him.
If someone comes to me and says they want to do that, I'll say,
`You match what he does on the mound, and we'll talk about it.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
