<DOCNO> NYT19981130.0535 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6007 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXASA&AMP;M-HNS &LR;      11-30 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXASA&AMP;M-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
COLLEGE STATION _ When Texas kicker Kris Stockton booted a 24-yard
field goal with five seconds left to sink Texas A&AMP;M 26-24 on
Friday, the emotions of the Aggies arched over the crossbar with
the ball and plummeted to earth with a resounding thud.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The biggest game of A&AMP;M's year brought the agony of defeat,
leaving the Aggies with the prospect of wrestling No. 2-ranked
Kansas State for the Big 12 championship while riding their lowest
ebb in an otherwise triumphant season.
</P>
<P>
   But coach R.C. Slocum said Monday there is no reason to believe
No. 10 A&AMP;M will be anything less than confident when it bursts onto
the field Saturday at the Trans World Dome in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team, as I've said all along, has demonstrated great
character throughout the course of the season,'' Slocum said. ``I
thought they did that (Friday) playing on the road in an atmosphere
that was charged with all the Ricky Williams record-breaking, big
crowd and all that. I thought they showed a lot of character in
hanging in there, playing, fighting back and actually taking the
lead late in the ballgame. I think we'll have the same thing this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize how good Kansas State is, that we're getting
ready to play a team that a whole lot of people think is the best
in college football,'' added Slocum, who served as a K-State
assistant coach in 1970 and 1971. ``We're seeing that as a
challenge and looking forward to it. And I think our players will
be ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The day after Thanksgiving, the Aggies were outplayed in
virtually every phase of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Williams ran the Wrecking Crew ragged, gaining 259 yards against
the nation's No. 2 defense to become Division I-A's career rushing
leader.
</P>
<P>
   As for A&AMP;M's offense, running backs Dante Hall and Ja'Mar Toombs
were rendered ineffective as the Aggies netted minus-seven yards on
the ground. And with the exception of a fourth-quarter spurt when
he rallied the troops to a brief lead, quarterback Randy McCown was
kept in a vise.
</P>
<P>
   It was exactly the scenario Slocum had talked about wanting to
avoid at all costs during the preceding week. But the aftershock,
he said, won't be long-lasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried to make a point in visiting with the team (to
remind them) that we're 10-2,'' Slocum said. ``Had we lost our
opening game, then lost a game in the middle of the year, we'd be
sitting here 10-2 as the (Big 12) South Zone champions and ranked
No. 10 in the nation. With this team, I think we'd all be very
happy. I think our team will bounce back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we are 10-2 is that this team has great character.
We lost a two-point game on the road to a team that probably has
the Heisman Trophy winner playing tailback for them. They've got an
experienced offensive line. So I don't think there's any
embarrassment over the fact we lost a road conference game by two
points.''
</P>
<P>
   All-America linebacker Dat Nguyen thinks the Aggies will be over
their emotional trauma come kickoff Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge challenge,'' he said. ``We didn't play as well as
we wanted to do, and Texas had a great game. (Saturday) just gives
us another opportunity to go out there and play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, having the chance to go play what may be the best team
in the country, I think it's a great opportunity to just go out
there and enjoy ourselves, have some fun. And hopefully, we'll
finish on a positive note.''
</P>
<P>
   After starting on a sour note, losing 23-14 to then-No. 2
Florida State in the Kickoff Classic, A&AMP;M reeled off 10 wins in a
row. Included in that string were victories over No. 2 Nebraska
(28-21), No. 25 Texas Tech (17-10) and No. 13 Missouri (17-14).
</P>
<P>
   But after losing to the Longhorns, the Aggies are again hearing
the tired refrain of Slocum's critics, who say the coach has
repeatedly been unable to win ``the big one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what?'' Slocum said. ``I could care less about that.
I think it's something that's been greatly exaggerated. We won a
bunch of big games. This team won 10 straight football games
without a break. Along there were several games that could be
classified as big games. Whether they were winnable or not
winnable, we won 10 in a row. And (Texas) was one where we were on
the road playing a conference game.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this league, Kansas State lost no league games this year.
We lost one. Everybody else lost multiple games. I'll take our
record and put it against anybody else. I think there are about
four teams in the country that would have a better record than we
have (against A&AMP;M's schedule).
</P>
<P>
   ``And to say that you can win 90-something games, average 9.3
wins a year for 10 years, and to say that you don't win big games
somewhere, the logic in that whole statement is missing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-98 2330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
