<DOCNO> NYT19981130.0536 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6008 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-KSTATE-SNYDER-HNS     11-30 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KSTATE-SNYDER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Kansas State coach Bill Snyder is a quiet man who doesn't show much
emotion. He is a man who believes any obstacle can be overcome
through hard work and proper preparation.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's difficult to find something that will upset his resolve.
But it's easy to detect a twinge of disgust when Snyder is asked
about the complicated formula that may leave his Wildcats out of
the national-championship game.
</P>
<P>
   The Bowl Championship Series ranks undefeated Kansas State third
behind Tennessee and UCLA. The Wildcats still have the Big 12
Championship Game against Texas A&AMP;M on Saturday in St. Louis to try
to move up a spot _ but A&AMP;M's loss to Texas didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   A win by the Aggies would have made it possible for Kansas State
to earn more BCS points by defeating A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``A&AMP;M winning would have been better for us as it relates to the
BCS, but I have a hard time understanding all that,'' Snyder said.
``It still depends on whether we win this game, and we can't take
that for granted by any stretch of the imagination. We're just
preparing to try to win the conference championship. That's what's
on our minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe for Snyder. But a few of his players are honest enough to
admit the BCS situation haunts their thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real frustrating,'' All-America punt returner David Allen
said. ``We have worked so hard all year to get to this point. We
are the first Kansas State team in history to go 11-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``To not get a chance to play for the national championship
would be a big disappointment to us. We just have to hope if we win
this game, something good will happen for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder tells his team to focus on the task at hand and not get
wrapped up in the BCS madness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing we have an opportunity to impact is the outcome
of our game,'' Snyder said. ``That's the only thing we have any
control over. We understand the situation, but we don't understand
the (BCS) system itself and all the nuances that go with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State ranks No. 1 in the ESPN/USA Today coaches poll and
No. 2 in the Associated Press poll.
</P>
<P>
   But the BCS ranking _ which is what matters _ has the Wildcats
No. 3 because of a non-conference lineup of Indiana State, Northern
Illinois and Northeast Louisiana (which have a combined 12-21
record, and Indiana State is a Division I-AA member).
</P>
<P>
   If UCLA defeats Miami on Saturday and Tennessee wins against
Mississippi State in the Southeastern Conference Championship Game,
the only chance Kansas State has of moving up in the BCS is to
defeat the Aggies by a big margin.
</P>
<P>
   So will the Wildcats go in trying to run up the score?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you start thinking along those lines, you can create some
big problems for yourself,'' Snyder said. ``A&AMP;M is too good a team
for us to think about winning by a particular margin. We have to do
things the right way just to have a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   If the oddsmakers are correct, winning shouldn't be much of a
problem for the Wildcats, who are 15-point favorites over the
Aggies (10-2). Texas A&AMP;M was in the BCS picture until its 26-24
loss to Texas on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it (the loss) was very disappointing for them,''
Snyder said. ``But I know (A&AMP;M coach) R.C. (Slocum) does a
marvelous job with his players. I think they will respond in a
positive way. I think they will bounce back and use that game as
motivation, more than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies gave up 259 rushing yards to Heisman hopeful Ricky
Williams, the most ever by an individual against an A&AMP;M defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a far better defense than the impression some
people might have gotten against Texas,'' Snyder said. ``It's a
very aggressive defense. They play hard and run extremely well,
which is why they always have a lot of people around the football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their players seem to know their schemes well, and they
respond to it. They are very good at handling their individual
responsibilities. But when you watch the (Texas) game on tape, you
see the field condition was not conducive to real efficient
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The only advantage Snyder believes his team might have over the
Aggies is that Kansas State had Thanksgiving weekend off to spend
with family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came back Sunday, I sensed we were physically
refreshed and mentally refreshed as well,'' Snyder said. ``I think
that's important at this stage of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder wants his players to forget about the BCS rankings and to
try to treat this game like a normal week on the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the way it is treated by the conference helps us,''
Snyder said. ``It's handled like a regular week, with no hoopla or
extra events to be concerned with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there's a lot more riding on it than a regular
game. But in terms of preparation, it has some semblance to a
regular game, and that's what we want.''
</P>
</TEXT>
