<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-30 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6011 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANN-TISCH-PROFILE-NYT     11-30 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANN-TISCH-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALL HER AN ADVOCATE, NOT AN ARISTOCRAT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan.)   (mk) 
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What's a career girl to do when she marries a
millionaire and doesn't have to work anymore?
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of women have answered that question by buying Versace,
training at the Waldorf for the right charities and raising money
for hot political candidates.
</P>
<P>
   For Ann Rubenstein Tisch, the answer was to fight bureaucracy
and establish a school for girls.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tisch is a former television reporter whose first job was
carrying her own camera while covering the county courthouse in
Topeka, Kan. ``I thought that was a really good job,'' she said the
other day, sitting in the office of the school she created.
</P>
<P>
   She scraped her way to New York, subbed for Jane Pauley on ``The
Today Show'' and met Andrew Tisch on a blind date, entering the
lives of the rich and famous, rather than just pressing her face
against the glass, as reporters tend to do. But these days, she is
rarely identified as the second wife of Andrew Tisch, heir to the
Loews Corp. family fortune in hotels, insurance, watches and
tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, touched by the yearnings of poor minority girls to
aspire to more than having babies, she founded the Young Women's
Leadership School, a public middle school for girls in East Harlem,
two years ago. To the consternation of civil libertarians and
old-line feminists _ who have filed a civil rights challenge
against the school _ it has quadrupled in enrollment, to 217
students.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Ms. Tisch is thinking of going national.
</P>
<P>
   When she started the school, she was portrayed in the tabloids
as Lady Bountiful, the dilettante backer of a lace-collar imitation
of Upper East Side prep schools and parochial schools. Ms. Tisch
attends her share of benefits _ breast cancer, Library Lions, the
homeless _ though less so since the births of her two daughters,
now in preschool.
</P>
<P>
   But, she insists, ``I am not a socialite.'' When The New York
Post called her one, she called to complain. The Post reporter
looked it up in Webster's (``a socially prominent person''). ``I
don't go to fashion shows,'' retorted Ms. Tisch, who doesn't even
polish her nails.
</P>
<P>
   She also objects to being called a philanthropist. ``I don't
think I've earned enough of my own money,'' she demurs. What, then,
to call her?
</P>
<P>
   She ponders the question. ``A public-school founder,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The Tisch name is etched on brass plaques around the city, from
the Central Park petting zoo to the Children's Museum in Manhattan,
but it is not on display in the Young Women's Leadership School,
which is tucked away on the ninth and 10th floors of a leased
building at 106th Street and Park Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Private donations to the school, including hers, come to less
than 3 percent of its budget, she said. ``We did not approach this
feeling that money is the school system's biggest problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tisch, 44, who lives on the Upper East Side, functions as
the school's trouble-shooter, fixer and influence peddler.
</P>
<P>
   The school has no gym, so she arranged for the girls to swim at
Asphalt Green, with girls from the Brearley School. When the school
was awaiting books in mid-November because the Board of Education
had not cut a check, Ms. Tisch gave the vendor her American Express
card. ``I'm their mad dog,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Rubenstein grew up in the Country Club district of Kansas
City, Mo., a neighborhood as affluent as the name implies. Her
father, an Annapolis graduate, owned a small finance company. Her
mother volunteered for organizations like the American Jewish
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tisch has looked at both Public School 6, in her
neighborhood, and Nightingale, the single-sex private school, for a
daughter who is entering kindergarten. She thinks that everyone,
not just those who can afford private school, should have the
single-sex option.
</P>
<P>
   The do-good impulse comes naturally. As a child Ann Rubenstein
was stricken with shame when her friends teased a fourth-grade
classmate for doing a project in pencil, instead of Magic Marker,
which the girl could not afford. As a reporter, she hated the
churning of daily journalism, each story as disposable as a wet
tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Working as a national correspondent for ``The NBC Nightly
News,'' she visited a school in Milwaukee that had established a
day care center for teen-age mothers. ``Where do you see yourself
10 years from now?'' she asked the students. Out of the corner of
her eye, she saw a tiny girl start to weep quietly. Ms. Tisch
approached the girl but could not get her to talk to the camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it told me was, the day care center was terrific, but it
was not the answer,'' Ms. Tisch recalled. ``I didn't do anything
with it, but I filed it and I didn't forget about it.''
</P>
<P>
   She met Andrew in 1989. She left her TV job in 1991, after 19
years in the business.
</P>
<P>
   In her mental Rolodex, she looked up the image of the weeping
girl. The answer, she thought, was a school where girls would be
valued for their intelligence, not their sex appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Ms. Tisch created the Young Women's Leadership
Foundation and began consulting with people who wanted to set up
similar public schools across the country. It will happen, she
said, though _ scarred by the pending legal action _ she won't say
exactly where. ``I'm a journalist,'' she said. ``I thought people
would talk about this for a day or so. I've been amazed at the legs
it has.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
