<SLUG> BC-NJ-DEER-HUNT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE REJECTS PLAN FOR CULLING HERD 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New Jersey attorney general's office announced Monday that
plans by Princeton Township to begin eradicating deer with paid
sharpshooters would violate state hunting laws.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement and a seven-page legal opinion, Attorney
General Peter Verniero said the town could put out bait for deer
and then shoot them with shotguns, muzzle loaders or arrows during
the limited hours permitted for conventional hunting.
</P>
<P>
   But the law allows no exceptions for culling deer with
high-powered rifles, using silencers, shooting at night or using
spotlights, Verniero said. All of these were techniques that the
township was prepared to approve if it had been allowed to retain
White Buffalo Inc., a wildlife management organization that
specializes in culling suburban deer herds using sniper technology.
</P>
<P>
   Township officials said they were disappointed with the decision
and planned to explore whether legislation could be drafted
specifically to permit sharpshooting as a wildlife management tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a problem that is not going to go away and we are
going to have to find some way of addressing it,'' said Phyllis
Marchand, the township mayor and one of hundreds of residents who
has been in a car-deer collision in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Bob Shinn, commissioner of the state Department of
Environmental Protection, issued a statement saying that the
department was ``sympathetic to the situation of Princeton'' and
would help the township develop a plan for managing its deer that
did not violate state law.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-square-mile township is estimated to have about 1,300
deer in an area that biologists have calculated is appropriate for
300 of the animals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
