</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-HOV-LANES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASSING OF HOV LANES BRINGS LITTLE SORROW
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARDING TOWNSHIP , N.J. _ Jennifer Heald cannot think of a car
pool that would have anything to do with her.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney, she lives in Bridgewater in central New Jersey,
works in Hackensack up north, and is not sure from day to day
whether or when she is going to her law office or one of three
different courthouses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know a soul that goes from Bridgewater to
Hackensack,'' she said. ``It's not a common destination.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet for a long time she has been forced to bear the indignity of
watching a handful of drivers sail along the special car pool lanes
on Interstates 80 and 287 with the hauteur of members of a snooty
club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was horrible, absolutely horrible,'' she recalled of her
daily commuting. ``Two lanes would be dead stopped and people in
the HOV lane would be going by at 50 to 55 miles an hour. It
clogged things up and made me half an hour late for work.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, though, those 30 miles of special lanes for
high-occupancy vehicles, or HOV lanes, were opened to all comers,
which meant that solitary drivers like Ms. Heald had their choice
of as many as four lanes (instead of three or two).
</P>
<P>
   ``This morning, it was zooming,'' Ms. Heald said. ``Everybody
was going along like a normal highway.''
</P>
<P>
   The special lanes were consigned to the dustbin of noble
governmental failures under an order from Gov. Christine Todd
Whitman, who has even got federal officials to excuse repayment of
the $240 million it took to build the lanes.
</P>
<P>
   By several standards, the HOV lanes on the two interstates were
a failure. Not only did a number of resentful solitary drivers
sneak into the special lanes each day, but even supporters of
reserved lanes concede that they work best on highways carrying
commuters to a single destination, like the devoted bus lane
leading to the Lincoln Tunnel into Manhattan. Where commuters are
bound for an archipelago of scattered office parks, as they are in
northern New Jersey, arranging car pools and bus schedules becomes
the transportation equivalent of a Rubik's Cube.
</P>
<P>
   According to state transportation officials, no more than 452
vehicles and as few as 32 an hour used the HOV lanes on Interstate
287, compared with an average of 1,500 vehicles per regular lane.
Interstate 80's HOV lanes were used more often, but they did not
relieve congestion in the three general-admission lanes. The
experiment proved that the ``Field of Dreams'' philosophy _ ``if
you build it, they will come'' _ may work for baseball stadiums but
not for HOV lanes.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, some car pool adherents were proud of their
contributions to a cleaner environment, of course. At dawn Monday,
Jack Crowley sat in his Toyota pickup in the bleak parking lot of a
Pathmark in Jefferson Township, smiling the smile of the just _ the
last of the just. Crowley had just dropped off his 14-year-old son,
Casey, who was hooking up with three schoolmates and Mike Metalsky,
a biology teacher, to travel in a car pool along Interstate 80 to
Seton Hall Prep.
</P>
<P>
   ``We send four boys from Sparta and a teacher to Seton Hall Prep
in West Orange in a single car,'' said Crowley, with the precision
of a consultant for an engineering firm, which he is. ``That's
pretty energy efficient.'' But Monday, Crowley might just as well
have been a righteous teetotaler helplessly watching the beer flow
like water at the end of Prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   As with Prohibition, the episode of the northern New Jersey
H.O.V. lanes shows that it is hard for government to make people do
what they see no great reason to do. With an initiative like
recycling, most people have gone along because they know that
cities and towns have run out of space for dumping garbage. But the
drivers on I-80 and I-287 could see firsthand that there was no
easing of congestion or increase in car pooling. By sticking their
heads out the window, they could sniff that traffic-stalled cars
were only aggravating pollution.
</P>
<P>
   However, supporters of car pooling like Judith P. Schleicher,
president of Mc Rides Inc., a nonprofit transportation group, worry
that a day of reckoning has been put off for a few years at best.
With houses and condos sprouting prolifically in northern New
Jersey, each one generating a car or two, the interstates are
expected to be congested again. Officials may once again have to
put pressure on businesses to help their employees arrange car
pools. They may even revive some form of specially designated
lanes.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever they do, they will no doubt find ways to claim credit
for the virtues of the outcome. It is interesting to note that
Monday there was only one traffic trouble spot: a three-mile jam on
Interstate 287 North. It was caused by rubbernecking drivers who
wanted to get a glimpse of Governor Whitman, surrounded by
photographers, taking down the last HOV sign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
