<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO HOLIDAY FOR USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Holiday Bowl decided Monday that it will not
invite USC under any circumstances, meaning Oregon or Arizona will
be its Pacific-10 Conference representative for the Dec. 30 game.
</P>
<P>
   In a close vote, the San Diego-based bowl's selection committee
decided it would rather have Oregon than USC, provided UCLA goes to
the Fiesta Bowl. If UCLA ends up in the Rose Bowl, the Holiday Bowl
will select Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have every right to do what they want and I have no
problem with that,'' USC athletic director Mike Garrett said. ``I
knew we were bowl bound. You never know what's going to happen.
We're playing in a bowl game and that's what we're shooting for.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrett said he expects the Sun Bowl to extend an official
invitation to USC perhaps as early as today. The Trojans (8-4) will
probably play Purdue (8-4) in the New Year's Eve game, even though
the Sun Bowl is not happy about a rematch of the Trojans' season
opener, which USC won 27-17.
</P>
<P>
   If Ohio State were given an at-large berth in a BCS bowl game,
then Purdue would probably go elsewhere and the Trojans could
possibly play Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday Bowl executive director John Reid informed the Pac-10
Monday afternoon that the Ducks had been selected over the Trojans
in a narrow vote.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon's deciding factors were the number of fans it would bring
who would require hotel rooms, as opposed to USC fans driving down
the day of the game. Oregon also features quarterback Akili Smith,
a San Diego native. The Ducks will play Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   The news that the Trojans will play in El Paso will not be a
cause for celebration among most of the players, who preferred San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to go to San Diego,'' wide receiver Billy Miller
said. ``It's close and my family can drive down.''
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne honored: Linebacker Chris Claiborne earned two
prestigious honors. He was named Football News' 1998 Defensive
Player of the Year and also named the Pacific-10 Conference's
Defensive Player of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Among the players Claiborne beat out for the Football News Award
were linebackers Dat Nguyen of Texas A&AMP;M and Jevon Kearse of
Florida, his two main competitors for the Butkus Award.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want that Butkus,'' Claiborne said. ``I want to bring it
back here.''
</P>
<P>
   All-Pac-10 team: Five Trojans were first-team selections to the
All-Pac-10 team _ Claiborne, offensive lineman Travis Claridge,
defensive lineman Ennis Davis, cornerback Daylon McCutcheon and
free safety Rashard Cook.
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne and Arizona cornerback Chris McAlister were the only
unanimous selections to the team on offense or defense.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver R. Jay Soward, defensive end Sultan Abdul-Malik
and cornerback Antuan Simmons were named to the second team.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker David Gibson and tailback Chad Morton were named
honorable mention.
</P>
<P>
   Another commitment: Tailback Mike Wagner of Bishop Amat has
orally committed to USC, giving the Trojans their first running
back commitment.
</P>
<P>
   USC has also received commitments from defensive tackles Bernard
Riley and Sagan Atuatasi of Los Alamitos; linebacker Aaron Graham
of Bakersfield; defensive tackle Malcolm Woolridge of Boca Raton,
Fla; wide receiver Kareem Kelly and defensive back Darrell Rideaux
of Long Beach Poly; tight end Jacob Rogers of Oxnard, and
linebacker Markus Steele of Long Beach City College.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
