A6022 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     11-30 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
HE is a powerful, swift, awesome memory now, like one of those
twisters that come roaring out of the sky unexpectedly and leave
the broken litter of overturned trailer parks in their wake.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson and his ferocious fastball spent barely more than
two months in Houston and are now officially part of a brief and
glorious past here with the news that the Arizona Diamondbacks got
their man by putting $52.4 million, cash money, on the barrel head.
</P>
<P>
   For the Astros, it was a marriage that lasted barely longer than
the union of Dennis Rodman and Carmen Electra and, in truth, had
the same chance of enduring. The fact the club never heard back
from either Johnson or his agent after making a three-year, $33
million offer says all you need to know about his intention of
returning to our city.
</P>
<P>
   So the Big Unit becomes the Tall Cactus, certainly an apt
description for one who'll be expected to stand like a giant
saguaro, a desert bloom in the midst of a vast, arid wasteland of
expansion talent. It is a prickly development for National League
hitters, who had hoped Johnson would take his gangly frame and
intimidating heater to the Texas Rangers or Anaheim Angels. That
way, he would line them up between his cross hairs in only the
All-Star Game, the World Series or an infrequent interleague
contest.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it is the AL batters who've been spared, now having to
stare down the barrel of the rifle at Johnson on only those rare
All-Star or interleague occasions. Because with this decision _ to
stay in his offseason home in the Phoenix area, ostensibly to
finish his career _ the Big Unit has all but written the World
Series out of his future, which speaks volumes about him as a
competitor.
</P>
<P>
   By turning down comparable offers from the Rangers and Angels,
Johnson snubbed both the 1998 AL West champs and the runners-up. By
joining the Diamondbacks, he goes from his last two mound
appearances as the ace of the Astros' staff in the NL Division
Series against the Padres to a role as the lead horse on a
last-place club. Arizona compiled a 65-97 record last season,
finishing 33 games behind the Padres, a gap that doesn't figure to
close much unless the Diamondbacks also plan to reel in free agent
Kevin Brown and an in-his-prime version of the ailing Joe DiMaggio.
By hitching himself to the Diamondbacks' wagon, Johnson confirms
what many have suspected all along. At 6-10, he is simply taller
than your run-of-the-mill money-grubber in baseball, interested in
reaching not so much for glory as for the biggest wad of money and
a comfortable place from which to put his feet up and cruise into
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Perplexed Rangers general manager Doug Melvin said he had been
told that the location of spring training was the prime
consideration in Johnson's decision and that Texas and the Los
Angeles Dodgers never stood a chance because they hold their camps
in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Is that nice? Johnson, it seems, wants to spend even the six
weeks of spring training near his loved ones. But while family
values are admirable, such a mindset raises considerable questions
about professionalism and a bid for greatness. It shows a player
who ranks personal comfort over team goals, a tepid competitor with
a low priority on winning.
</P>
<P>
   While Ken Caminiti chose to return to the Astros in part out of
desire to be at home with his family, he gave up an additional
$12.5 million in guaranteed money from the Detroit Tigers to do it.
Johnson, it seems, wanted his cake and a chance to eat it in the
outfield Jacuzzi at Arizona's Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   As strictly a capitalist exercise, it is certainly Johnson's
right to get whatever the market will bear. But it is always
disingenuous to hear players say that money and personal whims
don't matter so much. Remember those comments Johnson made about
wanting to see how committed the Astros were to making offseason
moves toward a championship? Obviously, they were more committed
than the Big Unit.
</P>
<P>
   For all of the stirring evenings and the excitement he brought
to our town, it still nags to think of Johnson's poor first half to
the 1998 season, when he underperformed with a 9-10 record and 4.33
ERA in Seattle while being insulted at the notion of pitching for a
mere $6 million. He touched down in Houston and cranked up his arm
to produce a 10-1 record and a 1.28 ERA and pumped up his value on
the free-agent market.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he is gone to the desert, a fitting place, home to other
cold-blooded lizards.
</P>
</TEXT>
